<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S UNDERSTAFFED COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Feb. 23:
</P>
<P>
   There are many problems in the criminal justice system that
yield no easy answer. But there is a fairly simple solution to the
flood of cases that is overwhelming New York City's criminal
courts. It is to hire enough judges, defense attorneys and
prosecutors to handle the workload created by the steep rise in the
number of arrests for minor offenses made by a Police Department
that has responded energetically to the Giuliani administration's
quality-of-life campaign. Unfortunately, Gov. George Pataki and
Republican and Democratic legislative leaders in Albany are not yet
paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Major crime has fallen. But the city's criminal courts are
swamped with cases involving minor assaults, fare-beating on the
subways, disorderly conduct, shoplifting and other misdemeanors
involving sentences of less than a year. The reasons are plain
enough. Although the number of misdemeanor cases has soared by 85
percent since the early 1990s, the number of judges has remained
roughly the same.
</P>
<P>
   Court administrators have done a good job of making the
arraignment process more efficient to cope with the record number
of arrests. Likewise, district attorneys' offices and the Legal Aid
Society have shifted staff and resources to handle the crush. But
Albany has not seen fit to provide new resources to keep the rest
of the system up to speed. As a result, the disposition of cases is
often delayed, or handled in a cursory manner, thereby eroding
respect for the judicial process while imposing hardships on
defendants, victims and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some offenders are able to escape punishment
altogether because of the shortage of trial capacity and the
limited menu of appropriate sanctions short of incarceration now
available to harried judges.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani could help matters by picking up the pace
in filling criminal court vacancies. But the main bottleneck
remains Albany. For two years running, Pataki and state lawmakers
have ignored Chief Judge Judith Kaye's sensible reorganization plan
that would give court administrators new flexibility to assign
judges to places where they are most needed. She will soon resubmit
her plan. Meanwhile, there is a pressing need for more judges, not
just in New York City but throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   It should be possible for Pataki, along with the Senate majority
leader, Joseph Bruno, and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver to strike
a quick deal to provide the necessary manpower for the courts. The
question, as usual, is whether they can rise above partisan
squabbling over who should control the judicial appointments. A
little statesmanship on both sides could mean a lot more effective
law enforcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
