<HEADLINE>
BOYS RANCH UNLIKELY TO SEE QUICK LICENSE RENEWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona Boys Ranch wants its operating license renewed
immediately based on an overhaul of controversial youth-training
policies, but a key state official says the request won't be
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not feasible for us to issue a license by Friday,''
said James Hart, assistant director of the Arizona Department of
Economic Security.
</P>
<P>
   A formal response to Boys Ranch is expected by midweek, Hart
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement released late Monday, Boys Ranch board
chairman Robert Johnson said the importance of immediate renewal
``cannot be overstated.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys Ranch's population has dwindled to fewer than 40 after the
death of a youth last year, forcing staff layoffs. The program once
had 600 troubled youths from several states placed at its rural
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect the renewal of the license, derailed after the
death, to help them get youths back into the program.
</P>
<P>
   In a Feb. 18 letter to DES, Johnson said the completion of a
consultants' report proposing changes, and a detailed
implementation plan for those changes, should be enough to earn
Boys Ranch a new license. He asked DES to move by Friday for
immediate renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be clear that the Ranch has responded positively,
vigorously and with a cooperative spirit to improving its
operations and ensuring the safety and health of troubled juveniles
in its care,'' Johnson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Important changes cited by Johnson include better communication
with, and closer monitoring by state regulators; new policies and
safeguards emphasizing ``zero tolerance for abuse''; and expanded
board oversight of Boys Ranch activities.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators at DES are reviewing the new policies and Boys
Ranch's plan to put them into effect. Some changes already are
under way, but some will not be made until later this spring or
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said the state will consider a new license only when all
proposed changes have been made and regulators have had time to see
them in action. While the state is mindful of Boys Ranch's
financial concerns, Hart said it has not set a deadline for a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more important to us is the safety of children,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, DES refused to renew Boys Ranch's license, citing a
culture of abuse that led to the March 1998 death of 16-year-old
Nicholaus Contreraz. The California youth died while being punished
at a boot camp in Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   A DES investigation revealed that Contreraz was suffering from a
severe lung ailment that went untreated for days. He died while
being forced to exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Five former Boys Ranch employees, including a Boys Ranch nurse,
were indicted in October in connection with the case.
</P>
<P>
   Though Boys Ranch officials appealed last year's decision not to
renew its license, administrative hearings were postponed under an
October settlement agreement. It calls for changes in Boys Ranch
management and in how the program treats troubled teens referred to
it by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also required independent consultants to pore over Boys
Ranch and its programs, and to recommend changes that would
permanently alter the abusive culture that DES concluded led to
Contreraz's death.
</P>
<P>
   Boys Ranch continues to operate on what amounts to a temporary
extension of its old license.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said respected national consultants produced a thick report
of detailed proposals for change, some of which already have been
put into effect. For example, top administrators were replaced, new
board members with experience in the field have been named, an
ombudsman's office was created and filled, and explicit new
policies have been written to guide interaction between teens and
Boys Ranch staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tenor of the discussions . . . has been very amicable,''
Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   Since some changes are still on the drawing board, however, Hart
said DES must see them at work before considering a new license.
Even if all the conditions were met today, he said, the renewal
process would take more time than Boys Ranch envisions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Pat Flannery can be reached at pat.flannery(at)pni.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
