<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGNITY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM HELPS PROSTITUTES REGAIN DIGNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINA LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ At first, it was exciting.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot of attention for a girl _ cars honked when she
walked by, men whistled at the sight of her and ``boyfriends''
promised her anything and everything.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there was the quick money, and a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   But what Vicki first saw as the glamorous life of prostitution
faded quickly as her body and mind withered under a crack
addiction. Her pursuit of crack cocaine pushed her through the
series of beatings, robbings and rapes known as street life.
</P>
<P>
   Her fast excitement turned into slow pain.
</P>
<P>
   At six months pregnant, the 25-year-old realized her child would
die if she didn't get help.
</P>
<P>
   And here, Vicki got lucky: At the time she was looking for help,
the city of Phoenix was one of the few places in the country
willing to provide a diversion program specifically aimed at
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dignity is a pilot program sponsored by the City of Phoenix
Prosecutor's Office and contracted with Catholic Social Service of
Phoenix to provide support and services to help prostitutes get off
the streets. The end result not only would provide resources for
prostitutes, but would ideally reduce crime and save taxpayers'
money.
</P>
<P>
   It stands for ``Developing Individual Growth and New
Independence Through Yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   And although nobody claims the program is the answer to stopping
the world's oldest profession, its organizers say it could be the
key to helping men and women who are ready to reclaim their lives,
and their dignity.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a few other cities across the nation that have
similar programs, and none are as extensive as Dignity, program
coordinator Kathleen Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women who are arrested for prostitution in the city
are given an option of attending the 36-hour class instead of going
to jail. It's a one-time-only offer that focuses on showing a
prostitute that ``what she does is not who she is,'' said Mitchell,
a former prostitute herself.
</P>
<P>
   The program began when Mitchell sent a newsletter about Dignity
House, another program that offers services to prostitutes, to the
city prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   She was asked to write a proposal for a diversion program, which
the City Council later approved, and the program was born.
</P>
<P>
   Since February 1998, 100 people have graduated. In all, about 65
percent of those who started the program finished it, Mitchell
said. Its organizers are evaluating the cost-effectiveness now.
</P>
<P>
   However, given the scope of the problem and the complex social
aspects involved in prostitution, it's unclear whether a program
such as Dignity can survive.
</P>
<P>
   But its supporters say this is the only program that has worked
for them. Forget rehab. Forget halfway houses.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Vicki has quit prostitution and given up crack.
She takes care of children during the days, and brings home A's in
the courses that will bring her closer to becoming a chemical
dependency counselor.
</P>
<P>
   There's also 31-year-old Lisa Godinez, who worked the streets
for 10 years to support her crack cocaine addiction. She's been
clean and sober for almost a year thanks to the program.
</P>
<P>
   She even has a list of goals hanging in her bedroom: finish her
GED, reunite with her eight children, get off intense probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugs robbed me from myself, my kids and my family,'' she
said. ``I've broken so many promises, my kids don't believe me
anymore. But I take it one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Vicki, who asked that her last name be withheld, and
Godinez said Dignity is the only program they've been through
that's prostitute-specific, unlike the numerous rehabs both have
attended.
</P>
<P>
   They are just two examples of the of the 120 men and women who
are arrested for prostitution-related crimes in Phoenix every
month. It costs about $2,000 to arrest and prosecute each one,
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   And much of that cost is paid for by city dollars.
</P>
<P>
   City laws against prostitution are strict _ mandatory sentencing
requires first-time offenders to serve 15 days in jail, 30 days for
a second offense and 60 days for a third. Those caught four or more
times, which is the majority, serve six months, Phoenix police Lt.
Larry Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   Dignity students must attend seven sessions that range in topic
from health dangers to the criminal aspects to trauma bonding.
They're told how they affect the community, what can happen to them
and how to get out.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the program, they're taught life skills and what
resources are available to help them.
</P>
<P>
   But program supporters know that many of the students who
graduate from the classes will go right back out on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were girls there that were `doing dates' on the
breaks,'' Vicki said, adding that a crack addict doesn't want to
work for eight hours a day, when a trick is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   About 85 percent of women prostitutes are addicted to drugs,
Mitchell said. They have been abused and neglected, and their pimps
won't let them leave. Not to mention the fact that there are always
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These women have absolutely nobody, and when somebody says
`you're pretty' or `you're smart,' they just fall apart,'' social
service supervisor Dana Mercz said. ``They're vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the drugs numb prostitutes' pain and the pimps
keep them there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make these women feel so special,'' she said. `'They're
really smooth. They're cunning. They really hook 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``And before she knows it, she's doing something she never
thought she would do.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems are severe, and even Mitchell admits that these men
and women need more than a 2{-week class. They need affordable
housing, treatment, day care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a chip in the iceberg,'' Jacobs said. `'We don't
have the residential, the educational component.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But who in the community will foot the bill?''
</P>
<P>
   But for people like Renae, who struggled to keep daughter Vicki
off the streets for about seven years, it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic,'' she said. ``A year ago, I didn't think she
could be in my home. I would have the baby, but I wouldn't have
Vicki.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It blows me away.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Christina Leonard can be reached at christina.leonard(at)pni.com
via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
