A5402 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MILLLER_BEARS-AZR     02-23 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MILLLER_BEARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARS ENTER SWEEPSTAKES FOR FREE-AGENT MILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cardinals have their first serious competition in trying to
keep outside linebacker Jamir Miller, considered one of the NFL's
most attractive free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is scheduled to visit the Chicago Bears today and
Wednesday, his first free-agent trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears are looking for an outside pass rusher to replace John
Thierry, who was taken one pick after Miller in the first round of
the 1994 draft. Thierry, a disappointment his entire Chicago
career, also is a free agent and is expected to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's interest in Miller surfaced just as another team, the
Oakland Raiders, dropped out of the picture. The Carolina Panthers
and Cleveland Browns talked to Miller earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's agent, Steve Baker, spoke with Raiders officials during
the weekend at the NFL scouting combine in Indianapolis, but the
Raiders decided they don't have the salary-cap room to bid for him.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials continue to talk almost daily with Baker but
still haven't made an offer for Miller, the team's leading tackler
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another Cardinals free agent, free safety Kwamie
Lassiter, is scheduled to visit the San Diego Chargers today. The
Chargers are looking to replace Devin Bush, who signed with the St.
Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter's agent, Jim Solano, was presented a multiyear deal by
the team last week. He is believed to be looking for between $1.5
million and $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals haven't completed their deal to re-sign offensive
tackle Lomas Brown. His agent, Lamont Smith, met with team
officials Friday in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he expected the two-year contract to be finished by
as early as last weekend. But he has decided to visit the Cleveland
Browns on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns are interested in Brown because they still need a
left tackle to fill out their offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials talked to kicker Chris Jacke's agent, Steve
Weinberg, in Indianapolis and plan further discussions. Jacke, an
unrestricted free agent, handled the place-kicking duties the final
four regular-season games and the two playoff games because of a
knee injury to Joe Nedney, who isn't expected to be at full
strength until at least the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the Cardinals were among the 152 players
allocated to the NFL Europe league for next season. They are
defensive end Jomo Cousins (Berlin) and wide receivers Kevin Drake
(Scotland) and Andy McCullough (Frankfurt, Germany). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
