<SLUG> BC-RODMAN-REAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKER FANS SOUND OFF ON NEWS OF RODMAN'S ARRIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Scornful of his contract offer and the team's
superstar mentality, basketball's bad boy Dennis Rodman declared he
wants to worm his way into a Los Angeles Lakers uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed to the teeth in body-piercing jewelry and topped with a
foppish hat, Rodman hissed, quipped and cried as he told a crowded
news conference Monday at Planet Hollywood in Beverly Hills that
he's ready to sign and will be ready to play by Thursday against
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will make me happy is if I can bring this city a ring
just like I did in Chicago,'' he said. ``I'm here just because I
want to make people happy. I miss entertaining. I miss entertaining
for the people. I play for the people, I give the people what they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for a championship after 12 inglorious seasons, the
Lakers were mum beyond saying that ``sometime very soon'' Rodman
would be signed to a contract.
</P>
<P>
   The ``people'' were more outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   The predominant lament of sports fans all across town was that
the untarnished image and championship tradition of Baylor, West,
Kareem and Magic were in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good act. He belongs on Hollywood (Boulvard) or maybe
over there on Sunset with the other freak shows and people like
him,'' said Trey Smith, sitting in the crowded TGI Friday's in
suburban Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   But like others, he was open to the possibility Rodman could
help the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Rodman's never pretended to be pure of heart or out to
help humanity,'' Smith said. ``He's got to be the most self-serving
man out there, but the Lakers think he'll help them win.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fan, Clive Lee, 17, added: ``The Lakers need help,
especially at the forward position. They need someone to grab
rebounds and do the dirty work so he'd be a good addition. Everyone
knows how he is off the court, but he's a player on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans wish Rodman would play it straight as a Laker, shut
his mouth, hang up his dresses and help the Lakers win a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got enough pretty `women' wearing dresses in L.A. We
need someone who wants to play basketball,'' said 37-year-old Bob
O'Donoghue.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting alongside O'Donoghue and a few other conservatively clad
business consultants at Yankee Doodle's Sports Bar and Restaurant,
Steve Johnson, 38, implored Rodman to ``close his mouth or just
stay wherever the hell he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Miner, 30, had a terse message for Rodman: ``Shut up and
sign the contract or leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Miner, a Lakers fan his ``entire life'' who sports bleached
blond hair that would make Rodman proud, stressed he doesn't have a
problem with the five-time NBA champion's tattoos or body piercings
_ only the contract dilly-dallying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ridiculous,'' Miner said. ``But the way they're
playing now, he can't hurt. He knows how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans also took offense at Rodman's news conference remarks that
``all the guys want to be superstars'' instead of being team
players, a pointed reference to Lakers stars Kobe Bryant and
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bad thing to say,'' Oscar Lazo said as he cooked for
a lunchtime crowd at Weber's Place in blue-collar Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the experience he has, he should show some guidance
and help out Kobe and Shaq,'' the 28-year-old said. ``I still think
he'll help the team if he ever starts playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
