<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPATHY FOR TYSON'S TV ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Residents at the county jail in Rockville, Md., were in a group
area, doing time, a popular activity among members of the prison
population.
</P>
<P>
   A new inmate suddenly went berserk.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson pitched a fit, and then a television. The set crashed
to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether other inmates were watching the TV at the
time, but if they were, they couldn't have been pleased that their
entertainment hour had been interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The set was dead. No picture. No sound.
</P>
<P>
   Manslaughter: ``Aww, (at)$%! . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Grand theft auto: ``What did you do ``that'' for?!''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson: ``I'm sorry . . .''
</P>
<P>
   While inmates took turns aiming the remote at the broken set,
with no response, guards placed the perpetrator in solitary
confinement, perhaps for his own protection.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's lawyers argue that their client shouldn't be disciplined
for destroying county property because the jail deprived the former
heavyweight champ of his antidepressant medication.
</P>
<P>
   Defending Mike Tyson is a full-time job. When he's not biting an
ear in the ring, he is jumping out of his car after a minor traffic
accident and assaulting elderly motorists. That incident, a parole
violation, landed Tyson back in jail.
</P>
<P>
   But this latest aggression is understandable. Maybe even
forgivable. When Tyson threw a TV, he gave in to a very powerful
human urge.
</P>
<P>
   Medicated or not, many of us at some time have experienced the
same impulse. Have you ever felt like picking up your TV set and
throwing it?
</P>
<P>
   Be honest.
</P>
<P>
   We've all seen those TV commercials for discounted long-distance
telephone rates (dial 10-10-whatever). After watching and listening
to the same ad 20, 30, 40 times, do you start talking back to the
set?
</P>
<P>
   Don't you want to scream?
</P>
<P>
   In one TV spot, a businessman lifts an outdated computer from
his desk and tosses it out of a 10-story office window.
</P>
<P>
   Ever want to do that with your TV?
</P>
<P>
   I do, whenever I see . . .
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vitale. The college basketball guru is a nice man. He loves
the game so much that ``for a cheap rush, (he) takes hits of air
from old basketballs'' according to David Letterman's Top 10
reasons Vitale is nuts. But his loud, ranting shtick is almost as
irritating as a TV set with a horizontal-hold problem.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Musburger. The most melodramatic announcer in TV sports.
Every event is extra special because ``he'' is on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any NBA game. The league can do all the ``I Still Love
This Game'' promos it wants. NBA players hugging kids. Signing
autographs, mending fences with disgruntled fans. But the
post-lockout level of play isn't good. Some nights it's dreadful.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Utah scored 56 points. After beating the Suns, Detroit
lost to San Antonio. The Pistons shot only 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Billiards. Thumb wrestling. Strongest-man competitions. Almost
anything on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Venturi. ``So and so has ``no'' shot,'' the veteran golf
announcer whispers. Of course, so and so invariably proves
otherwise, hitting his 170-yard approach out of the hay and landing
the ball four feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman. Is there any network he is not on? Any talk show
he won't do?
</P>
<P>
   There he was again Monday, the biggest self-promoting
cross-dresser in sports, holding court at a news conference at
Planet Hollywood in Beverly Hills, where the 37-year-old forward
announced that he has decided to play for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   If you missed Dennis on the network news, don't worry. Look for
him soon on a cable channel, pushing one of the world's five
shortest books:
</P>
<P>
   ``My Plans To Find The Real Killers,'' by O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wild Years,'' by Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   `` Mike Tyson's Guide to Dating Etiquette''.``''
</P>
<P>
   `` The Amish Phone Directory''.``''
</P>
<P>
   `` Things I Would Not Do For Money,'' by Dennis Rodman. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
