<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5405 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RODMAN-LADN     02-23 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN SAYS HE'S READY TO SIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Dennis Rodman had much to say _ too much
for live television _ at a typically bizarre press conference
Monday but the question on the lips of Los Angeles Lakers fans
remained unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Will the NBA's king of rebounding and self-indulgence join the
Lakers as speculated throughout the month?
</P>
<P>
   Rodman said yes, indicating at one point that he would sign a
contract later in the day, his most tantalizing such statement to
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, my first game will be Thursday,'' he said. The
Lakers will play their 13th game of the 50-game season Thursday
night against the Clippers at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers executives, who didn't attend Rodman's long-hyped
announcement, issued a brief statement indicating a contract
agreement was not imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying for the past couple of weeks that we would
like to have Dennis Rodman on our team,'' said Mitch Kupchak, the
Lakers' general manager. ``Now that he's announced his desire and
intention to play for us, we hope to sign a deal and see him in a
Lakers uniform sometime very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very soon'' could mean a contract as early as today, according
to some reports.
</P>
<P>
   But keep the purple and gold hair dye in the cupboard for now.
Given Rodman's impulsiveness and the division in the Lakers' front
office over his value, nothing will be certain until the ink in his
signature is dry.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, 37, has pulled down the most rebounds in the NBA for a
record seven straight seasons, and earned two championship rings
with the Detroit Pistons and three with the Michael Jordan-led
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``what will make me happy'' now is helping the talented
but inexperienced Lakers to a title. He said he's ``bored'' since
officially retiring last summer.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned, though, that he doesn't want to join the Lakers in
the role of teacher for young teammates.
</P>
<P>
   And Rodman, who would receive less than $500,000 from the Lakers
this season because of the NBA salary cap and the lockout-shortened
schedule, said he would like a two- or three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like a stumbling block. Part of Rodman's appeal to
Lakers owner Jerry Buss is the thought the team could dump the
unpredictable power forward at the end of the short 1999 season if
he proves to be the distraction many predict, but a two-year
compromise might be agreed upon if today's negotiations go
according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman said he doesn't believe reports that Lakers vice
president Jerry West is opposed to signing him. But he conceded
Lakers players might ``resent me'' for keeping them guessing all
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the people of L.A. and California will accept me
for who I am,'' said Rodman, who has head-butted a referee, argued
publicly with a coach, kicked a courtside photographer and missed
team practices during his 12-year NBA career. ``I miss entertaining
for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   But fans who think he's a perverted self-promoter couldn't have
been dissuaded by Rodman's performance Monday at an
entertainment-themed restaurant, where his press conference drew a
volatile mix of impatient sportswriters and fawning Hollywood
reporters and paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up 30 minutes late, wearing a huge, multicolored hat,
nose rings and orange shoes, which went nicely with a black suede
jacket and gray slacks. His wife, actress Carmen Electra, was at
his side, a rarity that put photographers in a dither.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman began by saying he was there to ``make up my mind if I
want to play'' _ as if he intended to decide on the spot. Only when
pressed did he say definitively, ``I have made up my mind I want to
play for the Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to tease you guys (reporters) or anything like
that,'' Rodman said. He added: ``I must be very interesting and
important for you guys to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the question-and-answer session, Rodman broke down while
arguing that his charity contributions prove he isn't ``selfish.''
Tears leaked from beneath his dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   His 25 minutes at the microphone included frequent four-letter
words, notably a scatological description of the Lakers' half-court
offense. And when someone asked what role Electra played in
Rodman's career decisions, they volunteered a detail of married
life that must have caused noontime TV viewers to clamp their hands
over the kiddies' ears.
</P>
<P>
   The press conference was carried live on three broadcast
channels, a regional cable sports network and at least one sports
radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The radio station was represented by two men in feather boas,
one sporting a lavender wig and white wedding dress to emulate an
old Rodman publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classic media circus, which is why Rodman should have
expected the big laugh he got by explaining why Lakers
representatives weren't invited to the press conference: ``We
didn't want to make it a big spectacle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
