r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_PENGUINS-     02-23 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_PENGUINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENGUINS TRIP UP COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Was he rafting on the Volga? Perhaps he was rock
climbing in the Urals? A moonlight stroll in Gorky Park, maybe?
</P>
<P>
   Pick any locale. But wherever the concentration of Coyotes
goalie Nikolai Khabibulin was Monday night, it wasn't in
Pittsburgh's Civic Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin did the best impression of Billy Buckner since
Buckner cost the Boston Red Sox the World Series by allowing a slow
roller to beat his five-hole, as the Coyotes fell for the fifth
straight time, 4-1, to the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have come at a worse time because the Coyotes,
playing six men recalled within two weeks from Springfield and
using defensemen Oleg Tverdovsky and Deron Quint as wingers,
executed a tight game plan well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say, it was just one of those nights,''
said Khabibulin, who started for the 16th time in 18 games. ``I was
stopping the good shots and missing the bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the guys played very good in front of me. They
played with a lot of intensity and a lot smarter. I lost the game
tonight. They told me not to worry about it . . . it's hard to say
anything right now.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad were the Penguins' goals? Not one would have
statistically been recorded as a prime scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   The first, by Ian Moran at 6:03 of the first period, came when
Moran was dumping a lazy three-hopper to set up a line change that
slowly scooted through his five-hole from the behind the red line.
It would have been ruled icing had it not been on net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I played good after that _ well, before the second
goal,'' Khabibulin said with a wry smile.
</P>
<P>
   The second, by Stu Barnes at 7:25 of the second period, bounced
off the back of Khabibulin's left foot after Barnes shot it from
behind the goal line on the goalie's right, 1:10 into a power play.
</P>
<P>
   The third, which ended Khabibulin's night early for the second
straight game and put rookie Robert Esche in net, came at 9:15 of
the second period when a falling Aleksey Morozov reached out and
hook-slung an off-speed shot through the five-hole.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the Coyotes' recent collapse has come full cycle.
While forwards have been lost to injury by the bushel, the
forecheck disappeared and defensemen wandered, Khabibulin was the
one constant who has been reliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a stingy game plan,'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``With
the lineup we had, we wanted to make sure we played it close to the
vest and not give up any odd-man rushes and hopefully get out of
here with a 1-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players executed the game play pretty damn well.
Unfortunately, Niki had a pretty bad night. It goes without saying
for the larger portions of the season, he has been sensational for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than than the fact the Coyotes played their most solid
game of the trip, another bright spot was that captain Keith
Tkachuk finally broke his eight-game streak without a goal on a
solid defensive-related play.
</P>
<P>
   Teppo Numminen stole the puck away from Barnes and fed Tkachuk
on a breakaway. Tkachuk beat goalie Tom Barrasso with a back-hander
crossing the net at 18:28 of the second period to make the score
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith has been coming and I think he's pretty much back,''
Schoenfeld said. ``He had four good scoring chances at Tampa and
was coming at Florida. A rib injury is not easy to come back from
because of all the torque the middle takes. It eliminates the
ability to forecheck and finish checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Tkachuk nor leader Rick Tocchet were about to point
fingers at Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played better but we still lost,'' Tkachuk said. ``Niki is
our Number 1 guy. He has been our best player all year. He was
winning games for us when we had no business winning. We can't
blame him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet, whose three goals had represented all of the Coyotes'
scoring in the first two games of the seven-game trip, concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple fluky goals; what can you do?'' Tocchet said. ``The
worst thing you can do is start blaming anyone. It's the biggest
cliche in sport, but it's true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to be a winner, but it's tough to be a loser. You
can't be a quitter when you're losing. When we get through this, it
can make us stronger for the playoffs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 0027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
