<SLUG> BC-BBN-GOMEZ-COLUMN-D-BACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUBHOUSE BANTER GOOD OMEN FOR D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Take just two steps into the Diamondbacks clubhouse
down here and it immediately hits you how different the 1999
Diamondbacks are from the inaugural version.
</P>
<P>
   This, baseball fans, is what a big league clubhouse is supposed
to be like: Half animal house, half serious. It's a combination
shared by almost every winning club, and it exists only when
veterans dominate the roster.
</P>
<P>
   You know you're in a major league clubhouse when you hear one
player yelling across the room at another and giving him a hard
time about his golf game, his expanded biceps or just about
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Through little fault of their own, this type of banter was
practically non-existent last year. It is, however, a necessary
ingredient in the big leagues if you want to win.
</P>
<P>
   It's a given that most people will never step into an occupied
big league clubhouse. But if you could, you would notice a common
thread among winning clubs _ a friendly but spirited camaraderie
that spares no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to look at chemistry and putting a little
more importance on it,'' said Pete Incaviglia, a veteran who is in
camp with a minor league contract and trying to win one of the
backup outfield jobs. ``It's not always the best teams that win,
but the teams that play best together.''
</P>
<P>
   Incaviglia, who has 206 career home runs, is exactly the type of
player the Diamondbacks were missing last season. He's loud and
boisterous, and if you didn't know him, you might even think he's
obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   But sift below the coarse exterior and you find as respected a
player as there is in baseball, one who knows what it takes to win
games.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget what a well-schooled player Incaviglia is
when you see him taunting Todd Stottlemyre every day. But when
Stottlemyre gives it right back to Incaviglia or Luis Gonzalez, you
are instantly reminded of what was missing last season.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation for last year's basic silence was not the fault
of the players on the roster. Except for a handful of veterans, the
clubhouse was filled with kids who hadn't accomplished much in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   Part of baseball's unwritten code states that you keep your trap
shut until you have done something. Using that as a barometer, it's
no wonder the majority of the players didn't act like nuts
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   The few veterans that were around last year _ players such as
Andy Benes, Matt Williams, Jay Bell and Devon White _ didn't have
the kind of personality to dominate a clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And that's OK. You don't want too many wackos in the same room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, we got a different group of guys when it
comes to getting on guys,'' Manager Buck Showalter said. ``It's a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer Gregg Olson, who did not have a secured job last spring
and therefore was hamstrung from taking control, has flexed his
veteran muscle this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are taking vans back and forth between Tucson
Electric Park and their minor league complex across a busy avenue.
After the first day of workouts, Olson noticed the minor league
pitchers taking up the front seats of the vans while guys like
himself and Stottlemyre had to clumsily climb into the back.
</P>
<P>
   Olson listed the criteria that must be met for sitting in the
seats nearest the driver. They include: Having played against
coaches Dwayne Murphy or Jim Presley or having been a bona fide
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   While he was at it, Olson stipulated that the same rules apply
for sitting in the first four rows or the last four rows on bus
trips to other ballparks this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's real special when you step in and see a glow in
the clubhouse,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Before camp started, I thought this club was capable of winning
about 84 games, mostly because of all the new pieces being fitted
together. After watching the first week of workouts, I can say this
club is capable of anything, including winning the National League
West. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 0032EST &QL; 
