<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-RODMAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN MELODRAMA BRINGS MIXED REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 REAX-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman's personal soap opera is apparently moving to Los
Angeles, based on his news conference and a statement released by
the Lakers Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Will he make the Lakers a championship team? Or will he become a
distraction that leads to disaster?
</P>
<P>
   Forgive the Suns if they haven't been watching As the Worm Turns
with rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can all sleep at night,'' forward Tom Gugliotta cracked
when told of Rodman's announcement. ``Between that and Kosovo, who
knew what was going to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Center Luc Longley, a former teammate of Rodman in Chicago,
smiled when told that Rodman had played up his decision, strung out
the process and made a big splash with his news conference,
alternately crying and cracking jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis playing it up?'' Longley said. ``Fancy that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Suns agree that Rodman, if healthy, in condition and
focused on his job and not Hollywood, could make the Lakers even
more lethal than they already are.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely adds a big rebounder and a guy who is going to
play defense,'' Clifford Robinson said. ``You know what he's going
to bring on the court. But you know what he's going to bring off
the court as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of whether the team is strong enough not to
let that affect what they do on the floor. But there's no question
he can help them on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kleine, another former Rodman teammate, figures the story
could play out one of two ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen what he did for Chicago,'' Kleine said. ``But
you've seen what he did in San Antonio. ''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman tore the Spurs apart before leaving there. With the
Bulls, with the strong personalities of Michael Jordan and Scottie
Pippen, he won championships despite generating a whirlwind of
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the type of player he is,'' Gugliotta said.
``If he can be what he's been for the Bulls, he can probably help
that team. But it's risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good organization. Hopefully, there are enough good
guys there to control him. They've got a veteran leader in Derek
Harper, and there are some guys in the organization, like Magic
(Johnson), who can do that, I assume.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Shaq's team, and there's a lot of pressure on (Shaquille
O'Neal) to win a championship. I don't think he'd allow anybody to
come in there and take away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley said Rodman wasn't a bad guy to have on a team, at least
when a game was being played.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a great teammate as far as I was concerned _
when game time comes,'' Longley said. ``He can do a lot of things
on the floor. He can help that team a lot if he's focused.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Longley have any advice for the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not prepared to give advice,'' he said. ``Stay tuned. I
think they'll figure it out for themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
