<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SUNS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S KIDD'S PLAY:SUNS HAVE FUN  
 EVEN COLD, FLU CAN'T STOP GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jason Kidd was feeling so dizzy and sick Monday night against
the Dallas Mavericks, he was practically seeing double. In fact, he
was seeing triple-double.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the effects of a cold and flu that caused Kidd to leave
the game for a few minutes early in the first quarter, the Suns
point guard recorded his third triple-double in five games in a
101-83 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's line: 17 points, 12 assists, 10 rebounds and his seventh
victory in eight games against his old team since the Mavericks
traded him to Phoenix. Three of his 22 career triple doubles have
now come against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say it's a vendetta,'' Kidd said. ``But
everytime I go out and play against them, I'm going to give
110-percent, sick, hurt, it doesn't matter. That was my thought
process when I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd said his chest was burning in the opening minutes of the
game, he was dizzy and not sure he could continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I hit my second shot there at the beginning and fell on
the court, I just wanted to stay there,'' Kidd said. ``Rex
(Chapman) was funny. He told me he knew something was wrong when he
ran past me''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the ball,'' Chapman interjected.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when Kidd probably didn't need to produce such an
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman rediscovered his shooting touch and scored 18 points on
7 of 12 shooting while doing a solid defensive job on Dallas guard
Michael Finley, who had 17 points but made 6 of 16 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd got him some easy shots early, and that got Chapman going.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first layup, Jason got me the ball where I could
probably have dunked it,'' Chapman said. ``But I just wanted to
make sure I got it in the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit five of his first six, including a three-pointer and a
tough baseline runner that took him almost behind the backboard.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Manning came off the bench to scored 17 points in 22
minutes, hitting seven of eight shots on postup moves the Mavericks
couldn't solve. He added seven rebounds and four assists in what
was probably his best game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny looked really active,'' said Suns Coach Danny Ainge.
``He gave us a little of everything out there, he defended,
rebounded, boxed out, made shots, gave us leadership. He was every
bit as good as he was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   And Clifford Robinson came off the bench to lead a defensive
effort tha limited the Mavericks to 39-percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   It was far more than the road-weary Mavericks could handle, and
their point guard, former Sun Steve Nash, also was suffering from
the flu. He failed to score a field goal in 23 minutes in the face
of Kidd's defense, missing three shots and getting only four
assists and one free throw.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were playing their seventh straight game on the
road, all within a span of 11 days, and the fatigue showed in the
fourth quarter, when the Suns turned a 10-point lead into 16 in
less than four minutes. Manning scored eight of the club's first 10
points in the quarter to lead the rush.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns wanted to jump out quickly on the Mavericks, knowing
that they would be tired. And they did, grabbing a 12-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Suns failed to put the Mavericks out of their misery.
Trailing by 18 with 6:45 to go in the first half, Dallas closed the
half on a 21-11 run to get within eight.
</P>
<P>
   At least it was a lead. In their previous four games, the Suns
had faced deficits of 17, 15, 22 and 19 points. They came back to
win two of those games , and regained the lead against Detroit only
to lose that one.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they never trailed and blew it open in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Kidd, a towel wrapped around his head, sounded
like a guy who needs a day off. He attended an open scrimmage
Sunday, and said he probably should have stayed in bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't tell Coach Ainge I was sick,'' Kidd said. ``I know
how much the fans mean to the Suns and the league, so I wanted to
be there.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much doubt he'd be there for the Mavericks, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
