<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-GILKEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILKEY UPBEAT AS DEAL DRAGS  
 D-BACKS, PIRATES CONTINUE TO WORK ON TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Will Bernard Gilkey be a Diamondback or a Pittsburgh
Pirate?
</P>
<P>
   The answer remained up in the air late Monday night as officials
from both clubs and in the commissioner's office waited for the
outfielder to decide whether to accept changes in his contract as
part of a trade that would send him from Arizona to the Pirates in
exchange for infielder-outfielder Tony Womack and outfielder Al
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which has been widely reported for the past week,
could be completed today, might need more fine-tuning or could be
scuttled altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Its completion hinges upon issues regarding an annuity that will
pay Gilkey $1 million a year for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what's going on for sure. I watch ESPN
like everybody else and wait to see what happens,'' Gilkey said
after arriving at Tucson Electric Park late Monday afternoon.
``Whether I'm in Arizona or in Pittsburgh, I'm going to contribute
to either ballclub one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really worried. I'm confident that Jim (Bronner,
agent) can take care of the business part of it. The most difficult
thing was figuring out what kind of clothes to pack, for cold
(Pittsburgh) or warm (Arizona).''
</P>
<P>
   Said Diamondbacks General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr., who spent
most of the day on the phone with Pirates GM Cam Bonifay and
Bronner, ``We'll just have to wait to see what happens tomorrow
(today).''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gilkey remains a Diamondback. As of Monday
afternoon, he planned to be on the field today as the club begins
full-squad workouts. When he arrived, he shook hands with the
clubhouse crew headed by Chris Guth and was expected to speak with
Manager Buck Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming here, Gilkey was in Phoenix undergoing a physical
performed by Diamondbacks team physician David Zeman. The Pirates
were concerned about a slight injury to his right knee when it
locked up while he was playing recently with his 3-year-old son at
their home in the St. Louis area.
</P>
<P>
   The exam included a magnetic resonance imaging test, which
revealed no damage. The information was sent to the Pirates'
medical staff in Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Gilkey, who was acquired in a trade from the New
York Mets on July 31, said he wants to remain a Diamondback, ``but
I know that baseball is a tough sport and this (trades) is the
nature of the beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey knew his name was being tossed about in trade talks, but
his attention was focused on his wife, Patrice, who on Feb. 16 gave
birth to the couple's second son.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .227 with four homers and 28 RBIs in 82 games for the
Mets, and .248 with one homer and five RBIs in 29 games for
Arizona. But he had only nine at-bats in September, when he was
affected by vision difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   During the final week of the regular season, Gilkey traveled to
Calgary, Alberta, to undergo elective corrective laser surgery on
both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He has not hit against live pitching, only off pitching machines
in a cage, but does not anticipate any problems as the spring
progresses.
</P>
<P>
   While he is focusing on his hitting, Gilkey also will be faced
with the adjustment of a position switch, from left field to right
field. Luis Gonzalez, acquired by the Diamondbacks in a trade with
Detroit, is expected to start in left field, with free-agent signee
Steve Finley in center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buck has talked to me about it over the winter. I'm a good
enough athlete where I can adjust pretty well,'' Gilkey said.
</P>
<P>
   He has always received strong support from his family, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about whether he can rejuvenate his career to a level that
approaches the .317, 30-homer, 117-RBI season he had with the Mets
in 1996, whether he has anything to prove, Gilkey said, ``I can
make believers out of non-believers if I stay positive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
