<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOKINEN SKATES THIN LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It may not be saying much given the current state of
the Kings, but in recent games, rookie Olli Jokinen has been one of
the team's best players.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday night's 5-1 loss to the St. Louis Blues, Jokinen -
the third player chosen in the 1997 NHL draft - had collected three
points in his previous three games.
</P>
<P>
   And a big reason may be that Jokinen recently has become
smaller. The 20-year-old Finn said he has been on a low-fat diet
and dropped eight pounds in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started riding the bike, doing extra work and eating
different food,'' said Jokinen, who has been following the
nutritional advice of a Finnish friend. ``Some guys are joking that
I don't eat anymore. I just eat normal food. That's how I lost
weight, eating normal food and working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson said, ``A couple of weeks ago, we felt he
was carrying too much weight. He came to training camp at 210, 211
(pounds on a 6-foot-3 frame). He was up to 218. Now, he's back to
211, 212. He's got his jump back and he's much more of a physical
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   In a slump: The Kings' offense has been in a season-long,
team-wide slump. No one, it seems, is immune.
</P>
<P>
   Including Monday's loss, Russ Courtnall has no goals in 14
games, Luc Robitaille has one in seven, Craig Johnson has one in
14, Ray Ferraro has one in nine, Yanic Perreault has none in nine,
Sandy Moger has one in 16 and Pavel Rosa has one in 11. Johnson and
Rosa were healthy scratches Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jozef Stumpel's meaningless goal with 3:51 left Monday gives him
two goals in his last 13 games. Before suffering a knee injury last
week that is expected to sideline him for about three weeks, right
wing Vladimir Tsyplakov had not scored a goal in 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War: Center Craig Conroy and defenseman Chris McAlpine
downplayed it later, but the teammates engaged in a wrestling match
during the Blues' practice Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get the puck, McAlpine slashed Conroy, who swung his
stick and clipped McAlpine on the head. McAlpine then responded
with his ``game slash'' - harder than the practice slash. This
raised Conroy's ire, and the two dropped their gloves and
eventually wrestled each other to the ice before teammates stepped
in.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the two had an animated discussion, but eventually were
laughing about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff happens, but it doesn't last more than the time it
takes for it to happen,'' Conroy said. ``It's over and you can joke
about it afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the bout was ``just frustration. If you're
winning, none of that stuff happens. It's a lot more fun. When
you're losing, everybody's a little testy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
