<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5435 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-LEWIS-HNS &LR;      02-23 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-LEWIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The last memory most Houstonians have of Rashard Lewis was his
tearful draft-day mini-news conference.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lewis, the 6-10 product of Elsik High School, desperately wanted
the Rockets to select him with one of their three first-round
picks. He sat on the edge of his seat each time Houston's turn came
around, television cameras beaming Lewis' reaction all over the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets' selections came and went, and Lewis was still
sitting. In fact, the entire first round swept by without his name
being called.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was crestfallen.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going to the Rockets, Lewis, who had been projected
by some to go as high as the 12th pick, dropped into the second
round, where the Seattle SuperSonics snapped him up with the 32nd
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to contain his disappointment, Lewis broke down, as one
might expect from a teen-ager who felt he had been jilted by a
longtime love. And like most every other teen-ager, Lewis no doubt
made up his mind to make sure that former love would come to regret
that decision.
</P>
<P>
   It might be working, because the next time local fans see him,
Lewis is more likely to have a broad smile stretching across his
face. He's happy with his new love, and it's obvious.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those everything-happens-for-a-reason stories, Lewis
is expected to be in the starting lineup tonight when the Sonics
take the floor at Compaq Center to play the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing,'' Lewis said during the lockout of his
draft-day ordeal. ``I wasn't going to let it get me down for long,
though. I figured I should start working on my game so I could go
up to Seattle and show them something.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has shown plenty.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of size, athleticism and shooting ability made
Lewis a standout during coach Paul Westphal's practices. Still, he
was a second-round pick on a team loaded with veterans.
</P>
<P>
   All Lewis needed was a break.
</P>
<P>
   And he got just that when Billy Owens broke his left pinky in
the Sonics' third practice. Westphal made a surprising decision,
opting to put Lewis, a forward, into the starting lineup at
shooting guard in the Sonics' Feb. 13 game against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have circumstances, he certainly wouldn't be
starting,'' Westphal said of Lewis. ``Billy would be. But I don't
want to artificially hold him back, either. I think this is the
best move.''
</P>
<P>
   With that move, Lewis became the youngest player in franchise
history to start a game, and the fourth-youngest starter in league
history. Lewis, who finished with eight points and five rebounds in
the Sonics' 105-92 victory, was 19 years, 189 days old when he
started his first game, trailing only the Lakers' Kobe Bryant (18
years, 159 days), Toronto's Tracy McGrady (18, 222) and Portland's
Jermaine O'Neal (19, 125).
</P>
<P>
   To say the Sonics have been surprised would be an
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much time and money and resources as we spend on the
draft,'' Seattle general manager Wally Walker said, ``I always like
to stand up and say, `Hey, this is the guy we had targeted all
along.' But that's not even close to the truth. We didn't spend
much more than cursory time with him as we prepared for the
draft.''
</P>
<P>
   But just scant months later, here's Lewis, starting in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he made the decision to start Lewis based on two
factors: He wanted to keep last year's starter, Hersey Hawkins, as
a weapon off the bench; and the youngster had proved he deserved to
get some meaningful minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get him some experience under his belt, if possible,
and I think this is the opportunity to do that,'' Westphal said.
``I think he has a real feel for the ball, a feel for rebounding.
He's not a player out there to put on a show; he's out there to be
efficient. He's a player that makes plays. It's rare for a kid that
young. He handles himself with a lot of maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gathering experience. This is a really nice luxury for us
to be able to use him, get him some experience and still win
games.''
</P>
<P>
   A big part of his maturity came from an offseason of intensive
workouts at Westside Tennis Club, where Lewis played in regular
pickup games against Moses Malone, Hakeem Olajuwon, Shaquille
O'Neal, Otis Thorpe, Rodney McCray, Mark Bryant, Othella Harrington
and Antonio McDyess. Shy and timid at first, Lewis blossomed under
the tutelage of the assembled veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he was surprised to find that veterans were willing
to show him the ropes and teach him some of the tricks of the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you hear all that about pros, but when I made
mistakes, they pulled me aside and told me what I needed to do to
make me better,'' he said. ``They told me things like to keep
playing and keep shooting. I was just waiting for the ball to come
my way, but they told me to be more aggressive and shoot the ball
more. They wanted me to get into the game more, and I guess I
needed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the lockout hurt many players and fans on various
levels, it actually benefited Lewis, who is averaging 3.7 points
and 2.8 rebounds in 12.3 minutes per game for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helped me a whole lot,'' Lewis said. ``The season
could have started a long time ago, and I'm not sure I would have
been ready then. Playing (at Westside during the lockout), I think
I learned a little bit more than I would have just going straight
in and playing with Seattle. Right now, I think I'm a better player
than I would have been if there hadn't been a lockout.''
</P>
<P>
   He's apparently a much better player than the Sonics
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to comprehend how advanced he is,'' Westphal said.
``I had all kinds of high school credentials and went on to a nice
career in the NBA. But I wasn't ready to play an NBA game when I
was 19. It's ridiculous to even think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know 18- and 19-year-olds. I think Rashard is
exceptionally mature in the way he handles himself. He restores my
faith in the youth of America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
