<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5436 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     02-23 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN Kim Perrot spoke about her illness Monday, she first said she
had breast cancer. She made such an odd mistake for two reasons:
one, because she is more frightened than she has ever been 10 times
over, and two, because her closest friend and fellow Comet, Cynthia
Cooper, lost her mother 11 days ago to breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Cobbs died Feb. 12, one week before Perrot found herself
numbly sitting in a doctor's office at the Medical Center being
told about her own cancer. It had taken root in her lungs and
spread to her brain, where a tumor the size of a golf ball now
threatens her motor skills.
</P>
<P>
   The stuff in her chest is worse, though. It may threaten her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, perhaps the biggest little woman on the face of this
cruel planet, came to Westside Tennis Club to break the bad news to
us herself. So women are the weaker sex? The Braves' Andres
Galarraga sent a spokesman in his stead last week when it was
revealed he would miss the 1999 baseball season because of a tumor
on his spine.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to fault Galarraga. This is, however, to applaud the
fortitude inside Perrot, who will spend four hours under the knife
Wednesday morning while the top of her skull is temporarily removed
and the odious lump below is cut out.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery is not uncommon. Barring some terrible complication,
it won't kill her. But the procedure is merely the start of a
difficult ordeal. Radiation therapy on several other, smaller
tumors in the brain must follow. Then, chemotherapy will begin to
deal with the alveolar adenocarcinoma in her chest. That cancer is
an aggressive one, and it tends to respond poorly to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Why Kim?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just random bad luck,'' Comets physician Walt Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   But Perrot insists she will play in the WNBA again. While she
was speaking, albeit haltingly and tearfully, her coach, Van
Chancellor, sat to her right, his head slumped way forward. He
rubbed his eyes hard. If you looked closely, you could see tears
dripping from his cheeks into his lap.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't crying for an athlete. He was crying for a young woman
who might as well be his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot was never supposed to play for Chancellor. She wasn't
supposed to play for anybody in this newfangled American pro league
for women because, well, because she just wasn't good enough.
Cripes, look at her. A runt! She was fortunate she didn't get cut,
sight unseen, before she ever tugged on a pair of Comets practice
shorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim has won every battle she's been in,'' the coach said.
``She can win this one, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot didn't reveal her fear when she fought long odds as a
wannabe Comet. If there were tears, we didn't see them. She simply
set her jaw, bowed her skinny back and won Chancellor's heart _
with hers.
</P>
<P>
   While Kim ran the show, the Comets won the first WNBA title,
then another. Her story _ I'd call it rags to riches, but she has
hardly gotten rich _ made her a much-coveted inspirational speaker.
She addressed a group at Rice on Sunday, never once intimating to
the enthusiastic crowd that she had black clouds over her head in
the form of black smudges on her MRIs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Raymond Sawaya, chairman of the department of neurosurgery
at M.D. Anderson and the man in whose skilled hands Perrot's future
initially rests, estimates his hospital annually performs some 200
of the operations Perrot will undergo. Many are complete successes;
some fail altogether. Most results are somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's cancer is unpredictable. There's no reason for it, nor any
rhyme to its pattern once inside the body. Perrot has yet to feel
any discomfort in her lungs. Every manifestation of the disease _
headaches, slight numbness on her right side and a slurring of
speech after a recent workout _ is the result of what Sawaya
concedes is a ``relatively large'' node inside her skull.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot is perhaps the last person in pro sports who would seem
disposed to such an interloper. She neither drinks nor smokes. Her
worst vice is a heated dominoes rivalry with Chancellor. She pretty
much lives to play ball, and she has played it amazingly well for
someone seemingly so ordinary. Possibly, she will play again.
Perrot, it seems, is not someone to carelessly bet against. But you
can't favor her chances. This is deadly stuff she's up against.
</P>
<P>
   Random bad luck. It can't be explained or understood, as with
the other unfair things that happen in the world every minute of
every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
