<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS &LR;      02-23 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The road to a third straight National League
Central championship just got a little tougher for the Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a day when position players began reporting for spring
training, the Astros learned Monday that All-Star outfielder Moises
Alou will miss most, if not all, of the 1999 season with a torn
anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee. Alou, 32, hurt himself
last week when he fell off a treadmill while training at his home
in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a devastating blow,'' said Astros general manager
Gerry Hunsicker, whose best-case scenario has Alou missing no fewer
than five months. ``This is one of the fears you live with in this
business and hope you never have to address. This was the worst
possible scenario for this injury. For all intents and purposes,
he's out for the year. I think the best we could hope for is that
he returns sometime in late August or early September.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were holding out hope the injury was not serious. But
their worst fears were confirmed when an MRI in Houston by team
physician Dr. David Litner revealed a torn ACL.
</P>
<P>
   Alou was ushered through the back door at Methodist Hospital on
Monday afternoon and was unavailable for comment. He immediately
boarded a plane for Miami, where he may seek a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Alou finished third in the NL Most Valuable Player voting last
season behind Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire. In his first season with
the Astros, Alou hit .312 with a team-leading 38 home runs and 124
RBIs in helping the club win a second consecutive NL Central
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said Alou was hurt Thursday when he tried to adjust
the controls on a treadmill that was going too fast, lost his
balance and caught his knee in the crevice between the treadmill
belt and frame. He also hurt his left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery has not been scheduled, but Hunsicker expects it to
happen sometime next week.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Astros did not believe the injury was severe.
Hunsicker thought it could be a cartilage problem that would
sideline Alou for three to four weeks. Alou flew to Houston on
Sunday night and walked unassisted and without a noticeable limp
upon arrival at Bush Intercontinental Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was shocked by this diagnosis,'' Hunsicker said. ``I
think he was really stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou's agent, Bob Gilhooly, said his client was taking the news
hard after suffering what may well be his third season-ending
injury in the past eight-plus years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never had injuries that have been just nagging,''
Gilhooly said. ``It's always something catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   In November 1990, Alou suffered a torn rotator cuff in his right
shoulder while diving back to first base on a pickoff attempt in
the Dominican Winter League, forcing him to have surgery and miss
the Montreal Expos' entire 1991 season. In 1993, he suffered a
dislocated left ankle and fractured leg when his spikes got caught
in AstroTurf as he made a quick stop after rounding first base. He
missed the final three weeks of that season.
</P>
<P>
   Alou has been on the disabled list seven times since being
drafted in the first round by Pittsburgh in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Minus Alou, a member of the Florida Marlins' World Series
championship team in 1997, the Astros will likely start the season
with an outfield alignment of 23-year-old Richard Hidalgo in left
field, Carl Everett in center and Derek Bell in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to replace him,'' Hunsicker said. ``Just like
(Jeff) Bagwell, (Craig) Biggio and Bell, you don't replace those
All-Star-caliber players. When you have a contending club, depth is
just vital. It's what separates a contending club from the rest of
the pack. It's like an insurance policy. If you don't buy one, then
need it and don't have it, you're in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Astros avoided any prolonged injuries to their
front-line players. Bagwell, Billy Wagner and Mike Hampton spent
time on the disabled list but were out for no more than three
weeks. Hidalgo separated his right shoulder after colliding with
the center-field wall at Denver's Coors Field and was sidelined for
two months.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, who was traded by the Marlins to the Astros in 1997,
played in all but three of the Astros' 162 games last season and
set career highs in almost every offensive category, including
homers, RBIs, hits (182), runs (104) and doubles (34).
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said the focus now shifts toward solidifying the
fourth and fifth outfield spots. Dave Clark most likely will get
one of the spots, and the Astros have a pool of players, including
Glen Barker, Ryan Thompson, Alex Diaz and Brent Bowers, to choose
from for the other. All except Barker have major-league experience.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said the club would not explore acquiring an
experienced outfielder outside the organization at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time that would become an alternative is if we don't
have the talent in camp to fill those spots,'' he said. ``I think
that would be premature to suggest that we would be focusing
outside. I'd like to see what we have in camp first and give those
players an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will also use spring training to learn to live
without Alou. Manager Larry Dierker admitted the loss of Alou
weakens his club and said its task becomes significantly tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a body blow but not a knockout,'' Dierker said. ``I think
we're still a good club but not as good as yesterday (before the
news). I would have projected us as probably a playoff team. I take
that word probably now to possibly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 0127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5439 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-23 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The ironic coincidence is how it happened.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moises Alou was running in place _ making good time but getting
nowhere. He was spinning his feet on a treadmill, working hard but
not moving forward even an inch.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly and strangely, something happened that left Alou caught
in a point of no return, tangled in the tread and tripping
backward. It ended with Alou sprawled on the ground, his entire
season torn apart like the ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours earlier, the Astros had broken off the Roger Clemens
trade negotiations because of a worry that ultimately they, too,
might be running in place had they pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   The Clemens trade surely would have sold tickets, brought home a
hero and given the pitching staff a boost as broad as Clemens'
shoulders and overwhelming as his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   But what if? Would a single twist of fate ultimately leave the
Astros making good time but not moving forward even if they had
Clemens?
</P>
<P>
   It was a worry that constantly ran through the minds of skipper
Larry Dierker and general manager Gerry Hunsicker. At what cost
Clemens?
</P>
<P>
   The Clemens deal likely would have cost the Astros at least one
outfielder, maybe two. Derek Bell and his 600-plus at-bats, his
.314 average and 108 RBIs probably would have gone to Toronto along
with his experience.
</P>
<P>
   What if something were to happen to Alou? The Astros wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Carl Everett would have gone in the deal. Maybe Richard
Hidalgo. Maybe Dave Clark would have been a throw-in. While none of
those outfielders is an established every-day player, all are
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   And with the outfielder would have gone a pitcher _ not Scott
Elarton but maybe a proven starter like Mike Hampton, the only
lefty on the starting staff. The minor-league prospects would have
been culled, too.
</P>
<P>
   What if? The Astros wondered.
</P>
<P>
   What if something strange, unexpected and fateful happened to
Alou, the only time-tested outfielder who would have remained?
</P>
<P>
   Clemens could do a lot for this team, but what he couldn't do
was hit .312 with 38 home runs and 124 RBIs like Alou. He could
throw 95 mph, but he could not offer the outfield depth or key hits
of a Hidalgo or Everett.
</P>
<P>
   And how would taking such a risk in the outfield jibe with the
risk already taken behind the plate, with Brad Ausmus traded to
Detroit and the reins to the catching duties handed over to the
young and unproven Mitch Meluskey?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have left us basically with two positions where we
were unproven,'' Hunsicker said, referring to catcher and the
full-time outfield duties either Everett or Hidalgo would have
taken had Bell been traded. ``The more unproven every-day players
you have, the bigger the risk. The more inexperience, the more
unpredictable it becomes. We kept thinking we might be more
vulnerable to injury and have less flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the snap in Alou's left knee was a devastating blow to the
Astros' hopes, but it didn't crush them. There is flexibility in
the outfield, if not a player who can replace Alou's 1998 numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And while the trade of the veteran Ausmus was a risky move, in a
twist as ironic as the one that will leave Alou out of action
through at least most of 1999, it was a major factor in the Astros'
passing on Clemens and feeling better today about Alou's injury.
</P>
<P>
   Had Ausmus not been traded, Hunsicker and the Astros would have
been more inclined to let go of Bell and get Clemens. With Ausmus
still around, it would have meant only one unproven regular player
would have to enter the lineup instead of two.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros might have been more willing to deal for Clemens. But
in the wake of Alou's injury, the Astros would have been in quite a
pickle today.
</P>
<P>
   The outfield would have consisted entirely of players who have
never played every day in the big leagues _ Hidalgo, Everett and
Clark. How many teams have won a division with a rookie catcher and
essentially an entirely new every-day outfield?
</P>
<P>
   ``Depth is everything,'' Hunsicker said. ``Too many people
underestimate its importance. (During the Clemens trade talks), we
kept asking ourselves, `If something happens, could we handle
it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Something very bad happened. But while it remains to be seen how
the Astros will respond without Alou, the prospects in the outfield
are much more solid. Bell will be in right field, Everett likely
will start in center, and Hidalgo will be in left.
</P>
<P>
   Clark should come off the bench, and the speedy Glen Barker, who
came from Detroit in the Ausmus deal and offers more depth, figures
to make the big club. And certainly somewhere, the much-heralded
Lance Berkman is wondering when the call will come.
</P>
<P>
   Has a GM ever earned Executive of the Year votes for the trade
he did not make? Has a trade widely considered ``minor,'' like the
one of Ausmus, ever proved to be bigger in the big picture?
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of questions to be answered without Alou, but
one that should not be asked about the pass on Clemens is, ``What
if?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
