<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAMES DEFEAT RANGERS, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ It is difficult enough for a veteran team to
play 7 games in 11 days with the last two ending on consecutive
nights in a time zone two hours west of home. It is even more of a
problem when a top defenseman for that team leaves with an injury
early in the game. And it makes things worse when the best player
on the opposition is motivated by what amounts to a pre-game
farewell ceremony before fans who admire him.
</P>
<P>
   This unfortunate team on Monday night was the New York Rangers,
who fell by 6-2 to the Calgary Flames in the Saddledome, a result
that ended their two-game winning streak and prevented then from
moving within 2 points of a playoff berth. The injured defenseman
is Ulf Samuelsson, a rough customer who doesn't usually stay hurt
long. And the burning Flame was Theo Fleury, who scored on
Calgary's first shot of the game and then set up a power-play goal
to put his team up by two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Any chance of a Ranger comeback ended at the five-minute mark of
the third period when Cory Stillman scored a short-handed goal,
giving the Flames a 5-1 lead, after a turnover by Brian Leetch on a
long pass in his own zone. Leetch, who played almost 23 minutes in
the first two periods, looked fatigued. He has been playing around
30 minutes a game. A major part of the Rangers' attack, the captain
has three goals in his last 32 games. For Calgary, Stillman had two
goals and so did Phil Housley. Kevin Stevens and Manny Malhotra
scored for the Rangers. The Flames are undefeated in five games and
are 6-1-5 in their last 12.
</P>
<P>
   The early minutes of the game ruined the goalie-rotation plans
of Coach John Muckler. Although Mike Richter stopped 39 of 40
Edmonton shots in a 2-1 victory over the Oilers in overtime on
Sunday night, Muckler started the rookie Dan Cloutier on Monday
night. It was part of a plan to establish a rotation that would
still give Richter the majority of games while exposing Cloutier to
more competition. But Cloutier, who had won his previous two
starts, failed to finish the first six minutes and Richter replaced
him after the Flames had a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cloutier said he was screened on the first goal but that he did
see the second goal. He said he would not be discouraged. ``No
point in sitting on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other piece of early bad news concerned Samuelsson, who left
the game early in the first period with a groin strain. Samuelsson
will have four days to recover. The team does not play again until
Friday night, when Phoenix visits Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelsson said he was injured in a 6-1 victory over Pittsburgh
last Friday when a puck hit him high on the right thigh. ``Really
weak,'' he said, referring to the muscle in the injured area. ``I
tweaked it a couple of times in warm-ups tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelsson said that doctors told him he needs about a week to
recover but that he might be back before then.
</P>
<P>
   The Ranger news got worse after the game when Muckler said that
Todd Harvey would probably miss the next four weeks to recover from
a broken thumb on his right hand. Harvey, who has been an
inspirational player despite injuries, has missed the last three
games because he has problems gripping his stick. Harvey said he
expected his right hand to be placed in a hard cast and that he
hoped to return in less than one month.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's game began with a ceremony honoring Fleury, the
veteran Flames right wing who will probably leave the team soon as
an unrestricted free agent. Making $2.4 million this season, Fleury
recently killed a proposed trade to the Los Angeles Kings, who were
willing to sign him for $25 million over four seasons. Fleury
turned it down and said he did not want to leave the Flames this
season, preferring to stay for the struggle to make the playoffs.
Calgary is not expected to re-sign him in the summer for budget
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony marked Fleury's 823rd point as a Flame, breaking
the team record of 822 set by Al MacInnis, who now plays for St.
Louis. Among the gifts Fleury got was a silver stick. He used a
more traditional tool to open the scoring at 2 minutes 47 seconds,
beating Cloutier on the glove side off the rush on the first Flames
shot of the game. It was Fleury's 30th goal of the season. Then
Fleury set up Valery Bure on the power play at 5:09 to give the
Flames a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the Flames went up by 3-0 on Housley's goal, the Rangers
got one back on a power play when Wayne Gretkzy set up Stevens, who
beat goalie Fred Brathwaite from short range. But the Flames got it
back 13 seconds later when Richter misplayed the puck to the
corner, stumbled, stopped a shot while sprawling but lay helplessly
while Stillman backhanded the rebound into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler winced when someone suggested that the busy schedule may
have accounted for fatigue and a defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' Muckler said. ``I hate using excuses. we don't have
any space for feeling sorry for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The game marked another day in Gretzky's quest to break Gordie
Howe's record of 1,071 goals accumulated in the National Hockey
League and World Hockey Association in both the regular season and
the playoffs. Although the record is not officially recognized by
the NHL, it is real and it is significant. Gretzky has one goal in
his last 18 games, two in his last 28 and eight for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's name was chanted heartily by the Calgary fans during
his final shifts. He finished the game with no shots on goal but
had a scoring chance late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have done it last night in Edmonton,'' said
Gretzky, 38, who has not said whether his 20th NHL season will be
his last. ``I wish I could have done it tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
