r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RODMAN-REACTION-L     02-23 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-REACTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GET READY FOR THE CIRCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Dennis Rodman is coming, and Kobe Bryant knows this
much about the imminent arrival of his new Los Angeles Lakers
teammate: ``It's gonna be bananas.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-week build-up to Rodman's signing will soon give way
to the three-ring circus only he can create. And it's already
starting.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds of the locker room being opened before tipoff
Monday, three TV cameras and six reporters were staring Bryant in
the face, armed with questions about the multi-tattooed,
cross-dressing rebounding specialist.
</P>
<P>
   And this is just the prelude. Are they ready for the crush?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody can prepare for it,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers will take it, if it means Rodman providing 15
rebounds a game and defense against Karl Malone, Vin Baker and
Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing for us to focus on is Dennis adds rebounds
to this team,'' said Bryant, who is happy with the acquisition.
``It can take a lot of pressure off of Shaquille (O'Neal).''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman is likely to sign a two-year deal for the veterans
minimum salary _ $1 million per season as a player with 10-plus
years _ sometime today. He could be in uniform as early as Thursday
night's game at Anaheim against the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, nothing's certain with Rodman, who reportedly was
ready to sign several times in the past few weeks, only to drag the
process out longer.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Del Harris wasn't making any immediate plans for Rodman's
arrival, or even making any statements about his presumptive new
starting power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until he's actually put the ink on the paper, it really is too
early for me to say anything,'' Harris said. ``I've learned that in
my 20-plus years in the league that nothing is final until it's
final.''
</P>
<P>
   And once it's official, the true test of the Lakers' focus will
commence. Though Rodman has been talked about as the missing piece
to the Lakers' championship aspirations, the talk among the Lakers
was not about titles, but about balancing Rodman's potential
negatives with his contributions.
</P>
<P>
   As Bryant put it, ``I think it's gonna be even more of a
challenge for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And someone who knows the Lakers well thinks they may not be up
to that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dennis wants to be Dennis the rebounder that he is, they
could be fine,'' said ex-Laker Nick Van Exel, ``but if he wants to
come in with all the gimmicks and antics, that's when they're gonna
run into all the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Without veteran leaders with championship rings, such as Michael
Jordan and Scottie Pippen, the Lakers might not be equipped to
handle Rodman, Van Exel said. ``I don't know if he really respects
Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Harris couldn't get along with a strong personality like
Van Exel, does he stand a chance with Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny. Comical. I would love to see it,'' Van Exel said.
</P>
<P>
   He also thinks it's a bad move. ``I can't see anything good out
of it, really. I think they have a championship team right now,
with all the pieces in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Those pieces are easily scrambled by Rodman's personality, as
the San Antonio Spurs once learned. Derek Harper, the 15-year
veteran now in command of this young team, believes, or at least
hopes, Rodman's antics will not be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it couldn't,'' he said, ``because I don't want it to be a
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that anything in the world can sidetrack me or
break my concentration,'' Harper said. ``We can ill-afford to be
side-tracked at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jones said he wasn't thinking about Rodman's arrival and
responded with a combination of disinterest and apparent
trepidation. But he said Rodman could bring ``some laughter, some
fun'' and some entertainment to a team in need of it. And he
believes Rodman's knack for distraction could be an asset when
turned on the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets up under (Karl) Malone's skin,'' Jones said of the
Jazz forward, who has killed the Lakers in two straight
postseasons. ``That's gonna be a great distraction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
