<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5450 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-23 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHINING SHAQ WARRANTS NO SPECIAL SLACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Late in the first half of Sunday's Sonics-Lakers game
at KeyArena, Shaquille O'Neal took a pass on the right side of the
key, turned and started to thunder his way hoopward.
</P>
<P>
   Olden Polynice moved into his way _ believed to be a first for a
Sonic center since O'Neal became a Laker.
</P>
<P>
   The bump of upper torsos wasn't enough to make a foul, but it
was just enough to disturb O'Neal's footwork. He lost his dribble
out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a dramatic turnover, nor was it the first time
O'Neal has been denied. But it marked a shrewd, vital maneuver at
the heart of the Sonic success _ and the point of O'Neal's
obscenity-festooned laments after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you about it, man,'' Polynice said, grinning. ``I
can't give away the scouting report.''
</P>
<P>
   He later acknowledged what could be seen by close observation _
the Sonic plan was to keep O'Neal from planting both feet for his
power move. Once O'Neal is set, a defender might have more luck
pushing over a grain silo.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as O'Neal is striding, he has a chance to be nudged
off-balance. Considering the numerous close-in shots that rimmed
out, the nudge worked just often enough to deny him a handful of
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, O'Neal uses terms other than nudge, and his
colorfulness will require you to use your imagination. Based on the
fine issued by the NBA Monday, they were $10,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   But were some tactics by Polynice illegal, as O'Neal claimed? Is
there a double standard of rules application, as he charged?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and yes. And since O'Neal benefits from both at least as
much as he is hindered, here's some intimate advice for the NBA's
leading scorer:
</P>
<P>
   Shut up.
</P>
<P>
   A frame-by-frame video breakdown of the contact between Polynice
and O'Neal probably would reveal enough specific violations both
ways to draw criminal charges, never mind six fouls each.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't happen, because NBC doesn't want to televise
free-throw contests. The network already has Ahmad Rashad to fill
its boredom quota.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Polynice was guilty of the two-hand push to the back,
O'Neal was guilty of the off-arm hook as he powers to the hoop. But
O'Neal almost always skates by on that offensive foul. Just as he
gets by with the big man's hippity-hop.
</P>
<P>
   That was a maneuver mastered by former Houston great Moses
Malone, who was always shuffling his feet under the boards while in
possession of the ball. But he was so quick and active under the
boards that it became a trademark that almost never generated a
call of traveling.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, the NBA allows a sort of liberal
interpretation of its laws once a good player establishes a
trademark move or style.
</P>
<P>
   If NBA officials were strict constructionists, Michael Jordan
might have been just another pretty good jump shooter, since his
frequent violations of rules concerning traveling and palming the
ball would have retired his method of driving to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, it's instructive to watch Gary Payton during his
money move in the low post. With his back to the basket and the
defender, Payton wiggles backward, fakes one way and then whirls
his lead shoulder the other way, nearly lunging past his helpless
foe. The trailing hand carries the ball almost above his plunging
head, and he seems to run the length of Rhode Island between
dribbles.
</P>
<P>
   Never gets called.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure where the line should be drawn. What I am sure
about is that every sport has similar latitudes toward rules
interpretation. From football's permission for offensive linemen to
hold, to baseball's OK for double-play makers to be merely in the
neighborhood of second base when they catch the ball for the pivot,
the pro sports attitude is to allow the game to be played, and
players to star, short of egregious abuse of the rules.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's rage against the uncalled foul is understandable,
because defense against him typically is not so much a style or a
move as it is a counterpunch. But O'Neal is the initiator of much
contact because his bullrushes provoke it.
</P>
<P>
   If he were a jump-shooter or a high-post slasher, I could
understand the martyrdom. But Shaq is a runaway truck, and the
floor slopes downhill wherever he's standing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Lakers led the NBA in free throws attempted, and
O'Neal had more per game than anyone in the league except for Karl
Malone. Think of it this way: A running back is going to get
tackled more often than a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   So, big fella, save your wounded soul for the rap CDs. Keep the
martyrdom act for the director of your next movie. If you need a
public psyche-flushing, call Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   Just spare the rest of us your view of your tortured existence.
I mean, it's not as if going to the free-throw line is a positive
experience for you.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
