<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5503 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANDS-LEGISLATION-SFC     02-23 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDS-LEGISLATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA LAWMAKERS OFFER $2.3 BILLION CONSERVATION BILL  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Framed by stunning views of San Francisco Bay
and the Golden Gate Bridge, California Sen. Barbara Boxer and Rep.
George Miller unveiled ambitious legislation Monday at the Presidio
that would earmark $2.3 billion annually for everything from
renovating decaying urban parks to purchasing thousands of acres of
land for public recreation and endangered species protection.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed Resources 2000, the proposal drew enthusiastic plaudits
from attending Bay Area politicians, particularly San Francisco
Supervisor Michael Yaki, who sees it as an opportunity to restore
Golden Gate Park's sagging infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said some of the money could also be used to provide a
long-overdue renovation for the U.S. Mint in San Francisco, which
was closed in 1994 because of earthquake safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill probably won't pass in the precise form Boxer
and Miller presented, insiders say the chances of passing a major
federal land and water conservation bill this year are good, given
unusual bipartisan support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Miller and Boxer, both Democrats, would fully fund
the Land and Water Conservation Fund, which was established in 1965
to use revenues from offshore oil development to purchase land for
conservation and recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Congress allowed $900 million annually for the fund. But with
the exception of one or two years in the 1970s, only a small
fraction of that figure has ever made it into the program's yearly
budget.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the past 30 years, the lion's share of revenue from
offshore oil development has been diverted to the federal general
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Resources 2000 would do two things: It would fully pay for the
Land and Water Conservation Fund and it would establish new funds
for urban and regional parks, fisheries conservation, endangered
species protection and farm and rangeland preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would provide the full $900 million for the Land and
Water Conservation Fund and $1.4 billion for seven ancillary
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to restore the commitment made to the American
people 30 years ago,'' said Miller, of Martinez. ``This will
provide states, local communities, farmers and others the resources
they need'' for environmental restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, for her part, invoked conservationist President Theodore
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a comprehensive long-term strategy so our children's
children can herald our actions as we do T.R.'s today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was something of a love-fest between Boxer and
Miller, as she presented him with a pair of pince-nez similar to
the ones Roosevelt wore.
</P>
<P>
   ``With George's mustache, I think he looks like T.R.,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yaki was ebullient at the prospect of securing federal funds for
renovating Golden Gate Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``All cities and counties have a chart they don't like to show
the public,'' he said, ``and that's the one for deferred
maintenance and infrastructure for urban parks. Finally, we have a
bill that can address that. It's a godsend.''
</P>
<P>
   Richmond, Calif., Mayor Rosemary Corbin said the bill could help
establish a large city park, benefiting many city residents who
spend their lives surrounded by concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a linear park that will cut through some of
our poorest neighborhoods,'' she said. ``(To us), that's what this
bill is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Resources 2000 is competing with bills offered by other federal
legislators, including one by Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, that would
fully fund the Land and Water Conservation Fund, but would also
provide incentives for increased offshore oil development.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., will probably introduce
legislation of her own to provide enhanced revenues for the Land
and Water Conservation Fund, said Jay Watson, the California and
Nevada Regional Director for the Wilderness Society. Watson noted
that President Clinton has also called for pumping money into the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Kapolczynski, Boxer's California director, said Resources
2000 is superior to the other proposals ``because it is off-budget.
It guarantees full funding in perpetuity, and it doesn't provide
drilling incentives, like Young's bill does.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the president's proposal goes, said Kapolczynski, ``it
would subject the money to the full appropriation process. It could
be diverted in any given year.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said the Boxer-Miller bill is ``the high water mark, the
thing to aim for.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill may not pass intact, said Watson, he expects
that significant land and water conservation legislation will come
out of the current Congress and be signed into law by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important and exciting here is that bipartisan momentum
is building to make the funding permanent and secure,'' Watson
said. ``Both sides want it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
