r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSHA-BLOOD-SFCHRON &LR;      02-23 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSHA-BLOOD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MEDICAL WORKERS AT RISK IN BLOOD COLLECTION, U.S. WARNS  &HT;     By APRIL LYNCH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of health care workers risk exposure to deadly
blood-borne diseases each year because of accidents caused by
broken blood collection tubes, federal health and safety
investigators warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2,800 health care workers are injured by broken
glass blood collection tubes every year, according to the
Occupational Health and Safety Administration. One doctor in
Maryland died from an HIV infection contracted in a blood
collection tube accident.
</P>
<P>
   Health care workers can also contract diseases such as hepatitis
B or hepatitis C from exposure to infected blood.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the injuries could be prevented by changing the way
blood is collected or examined, OSHA officials said in a warning
issued in conjunction with the National Institute for Occupational
Safety and Health and the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The glass tubes in question are familiar to almost anyone who
has ever had a blood test. The tubes are used for blood collection
everywhere from hospitals to blood donation centers and doctors'
offices. Collected blood is drawn into the tubes and sent to
laboratories for testing.
</P>
<P>
   Most accidents occur when the tubes are being sealed or placed
in centrifuge machines to start some testing procedures. Pressure
on the tubes sometimes causes them to shatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood can spatter, potentially exposing (health care)
personnel to blood-borne pathogens,'' the OSHA warning said. ``The
broken glass fragments can also injure the user, resulting in
exposure to blood.''
</P>
<P>
   OSHA and the other federal agencies said other types of
collection devices and methods should be used to reduce the risk of
accidents from broken glass tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Among those recommended are tubes made of materials other than
glass or those wrapped in puncture-resistant film, tubes that are
safer to seal and blood testing that does not require putting blood
samples  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
