<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRREPAIR-ACCIDENTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA HAS FAILED TO INCREASE NUMBER OF INSPECTORS AT AIRCRAFT REPAIR
STATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE, Wash. _ Safety problems at aviation repair stations are
well known to government investigators nationwide. Over the years,
sloppy repairs and slipshod equipment installation have been
identified as a factor in or the cause of several aircraft
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board reported that several
people were injured on June 8, 1995, when the engine of a ValuJet
plane exploded on takeoff from Atlanta. Investigators said the
engine failed because repair station workers failed to do a proper
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, according to the safety board, a fatigue
fracture ``undetected or improperly repaired'' at a repair station
caused a propeller to rip off a Southeast Airlines plane cruising
18,000 feet above western Georgia. Eight people were killed and 21
injured as the pilot fought to land the disabled aircraft in a
hayfield.
</P>
<P>
   On May 11, 1996, 110 passengers died in the flaming crash of
another ValuJet DC-9 in the alligator-infested Florida Everglades.
The fire began in the cargo hold, caused by oxygen generators
improperly packaged and identified at a repair station.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were still waist-deep in swamp water at the crash
site as members of Congress were demanding immediate changes in the
way the Federal Aviation Administration monitors the nation's 2,800
third-party repair stations. With great flourish that FAA announced
it was going to increase the number and intensity of inspections.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA first promised to improve regulation of repair stations
and the qualifications and abilities of station workers in 1989.
But according to the General Accounting Office, the improvements
have been repeatedly delayed, as has the FAA's pledge to increase
the number of inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the FAA had about 600 inspectors responsible for the
intricate examinations. No new inspectors are expected to be added
in the near future. With the FAA having to find money for air
traffic control's pay raises, a wide hiring freeze has been
ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, third-party repair stations are gaining popularity:
The FAA estimates that repairs, maintenance and mandatory
inspections of nearly half the nation's 6,900 passenger and cargo
planes are contracted out to privately operated repair stations in
the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Having work done at the FAA-certified stations can be a
money-saver for airlines that want to avoid the enormous cost of
huge hangars, specialized tools and mechanics with special skills.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stations are little more than mom-and-pop operations
that fix specific cockpit instruments. Others tackle complex jobs
such as engine repair. A few, such as Everett's Tramco, offer
nose-to-tail services with FAA certification to rebuild an entire
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   While FAA inspectors have found problems at Tramco, no crashes
or accidents have been attributed to work done there.
</P>
<P>
   Regulating aircraft repair shops is never easy. While everyone
shares the same FAA Bible, interpreting the regulatory scripture
can lead to problems.
</P>
<P>
   There are tens of thousands of precisely worded Federal Air
Regulations _ or FARs _ guiding every possible aspect of flying.
There are FARs governing the design, construction and installation
every screw, bolt, cable, engine, electrical item, control device,
seat and piece of metal on an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations also control who is authorized to maintain these
items, the manuals they use and how and when the maintenance is to
be done.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes can boil over, with FAA lawyers and repair plant
operators dickering on penalties when violations are found. Options
include suspension or revocation of the station's FAA license to
operate, a letter of correction, a letter of reprimand or a cash
fine that could range into the millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   FAA field inspectors lament that the fines often have no
relation to the severity of the violation _ with companies that
count profits in millions of dollars ordered to pay just $800 or
$1,000 for a violation that could endanger an aircraft and the
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   That sends a mixed message to the inspector and the company,
according to a General Accounting Office report to Congress in
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 0402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
