<HEADER>
A5726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN24-COX     02-23 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What teen-age boys talk about on the way to school
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two chief topics of conversation the other day among the
three teen-age boys I cart to school were:
</P>
<P>
   The snippet of a porno film that somehow made its way into an
episode of ``The Simpsons'' aired locally last week; and a fellow
student who had his tongue pierced.
</P>
<P>
   None of the boys saw the four seconds of hardcore that for
still-unexplained reasons made it onto the Fox show, but news of it
has doubtless sent ratings soaring among the adolescent set. The
station manager has apologized more times than Bill Clinton, fired
somebody who was supposed to check the tape, and is probably
enduring massive amounts of ribbing.
</P>
<P>
   He has my sympathy. As for me, I am happy that I was not
required to explain exactly what the four seconds of porn
contained. They already knew, the teen-age boy information network
being quicker than any high-dollar computer line, especially when
it comes to hormonal matters.
</P>
<P>
   As for the boy who had his tongue pierced, the general consensus
among my passengers is that placing a sharp object through one's
tongue is a lousy idea. I was heartened to hear this. For a moment,
I was fearful that the next big fight at the house would be over my
stepson's wish to also get his tongue pierced.
</P>
<P>
   These teen-agers run in packs, you know, like wild dogs. Each
day they tumble into my car dressed identically: wide-legged jeans,
Doc Martens, a T-shirt from the Puking Rats or some other rock
group whose lyrics cannot be reprised in a family newspaper, and
their hair parted in the middle and always in their eyes. If it's
cold, they bring Adidas jackets with white stripes up each sleeve,
but they rarely wear them. Usually, the jackets end up crumpled in
the back seat of my car to be picked up later. Wearing a jacket
apparently is not cool.
</P>
<P>
   This is the grunge look, I'm told. There are cliques in high
school, which is no surprise. There have always been cliques. My
passengers are grungers, devotees of heavy-metal music like Korn,
Tool and other Bands With Only One Name. Other cliques include the
preps and the kickers. Female preps are OK among these teen boys,
being female and all, but male preps are disdained. As for kickers,
well. Let's not go there.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried on occasion to explain with the benefit of
middle-aged wisdom that dividing people into groups based on how
they dress is dumb. I may as well be speaking Esperanto for all the
good it does me.
</P>
<P>
   I torture the teens by forcing them to listen to National Public
Radio on the 15-minute drive to school. Likely this is the only
news they are exposed to that isn't on MTV. After some initial
grumbling, they have resigned themselves to their cultural fate and
at times actually become interested in a story. Of greatest appeal
are news items having to do with anything gross, such as a recent
piece about the millions of rats in Washington, D.C. No, not
Congress. Real rats, which outnumber people in our capital by about
four-to-one, if memory serves me correctly. This story had their
full attention, being high on the teen gross-out scale.
</P>
<P>
   Stories about Alan Greenspan, Kosovo or impeachment put them
into a daze, and they start talking about what music video they
watched the night before, what so-and-so said on the phone, or how
they're going to talk their parents into springing for a new pair
of Docs.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are a constant topic of conversation on the ride to
school. They are divided into two categories: cool and mean. A cool
teacher does not assign much homework, allows the occasional
playing of CDs in class, and doesn't care if one catches a little
shut-eye while the lecture drones on. A mean teacher expects
students to do their work and whops them upside the head if they're
caught sleeping. Luckily for the nation's future, most teachers are
considered mean.
</P>
<P>
   While tongue piercing is considered highly gross, tattoos are
considered cool. My stock answer is that my stepson can pierce any
part of his body he wishes once he is paying his own rent. I also
point out that a tattoo is a painful process consisting of many
hundreds of needles inserted into the skin. I'm counting on his low
pain threshold to keep him from doing something dumb.
</P>
<P>
   News of the Impeachment Trial That We Thought Would Never End
dominates NPR today. The vote is unanimous in my car. We're all
glad that the trial is finally over so NPR can get back to doing
cool stories about dog-eating alligators and other stuff that teen
boys find fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
