</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONMMENTARY: Many sleppless nights
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My inner clock is suffering from premature
Y2K syndrome. It's never been much of a timepiece, but now it has
quit working altogether. My son assures me it's just a phase. I
tell him I'm too old to be phasing.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, my days and nights have become indistinguishable, except
for one being darker than the other, and now I find myself roaming
the house at 3 a.m. looking for something to iron. For a while I
tried calling friends for catch-up chats, but that didn't work out.
Even the polite ones kept falling asleep mid-conversation.
</P>
<P>
   What I think about mostly during the owl hours is how everybody
else is asleep and I'm not. Why them? Why not me? Maybe what my
ex-husband used to say is true. When I'd marvel at his ability to
sleep through tornadoes and 3 a.m. feedings, he'd attribute his
uninterrupted slumber to a clear conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Just about the time I decide to give in and look for a job
teaching night school at a community college, my built-in Big Ben
resets itself and I have to start all over. No more bean tostadas
at 6 a.m. just because it feels like lunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Often, as I lie awake trying to locate the Big Dipper through my
bedroom windows, I ponder the meaning of time. We're told it's
relative. My question is: To what?
</P>
<P>
   When I was a kid, time was taken care of by my parents: Get up!
(OK.) You'll be late for school! (I'm up.) Are you up? (Almost.)
And don't try getting dressed under the covers again. (Rats!)
</P>
<P>
   And my teachers. ... Mrs. Fecser, second grade: It's time for
arithmetic. (Double rats!) Elizabeth, it's your turn to answer the
first problem. (I didn't have time to do my homework; I fell
asleep.) You're lazy. (I'm just a little kid who hasn't learned to
tell time yet.) So I've noticed.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hours into the school day she'd announce: All right,
everyone. It's time for us to visit the restrooms. (I don't have to
go now.) It's TIME! (Are you sure?) Just, GO! (OK, I'll try.) Maybe
my confusion is genetic.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother Parker always had bad luck with clocks. One day I
asked Granddaddy why Grandmother took afternoon naps. I thought
that was just for little kids. He told me it was because her inner
clock was broken and he wished she'd get it fixed because the
household found it a little irritating to be awakened at 2 a.m. to
the strains of Grandmother banging out her own fractured version of
Tchaikovsky's 1812 Overture complete with cannon fire. Granddaddy
suggested she find a quieter way to celebrate the Russian defeat of
the Napoleonic invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime during WW2, daylight savings time came to Jacksonville
(Fla.), and while the rest of the city moved their clocks ahead one
hour, Grandmother refused. Said it wasn't natural and she'd have no
part in it. Singularly, she trod her familiar though untimely path.
</P>
<P>
   Being a chip off Mrs. Parker's old block, I've come to realize
that clocks just don't work for me either _ like the morning I woke
my 8-year-old son, hustled him off to the shower, and fed him
breakfast. I was shoving him out the door to catch the bus when he
pointed out the obvious. It was still dark outside. We were three
hours early for the bus, so we settled down to a poker game in his
bottom bunk. Of course, we fell asleep and missed the rest of the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   And now I find that instead of getting better at this relativity
of time stuff, I'm getting worse. My only hope is that come the
year 2000, the world will slow down and catch up with me.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
