<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mazda keeps LXP Protege within range of entry level
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Auto buyers are always on the lookout for deals,
especially ones that happen to include great value. It is always a
bonus to the buyer if the vehicle's brand carries a certain amount
of prestige. Nowhere is this search more intense than in the
entry-level segment.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is common for a brand to grow upscale. Car brand X
might start off at a price of $12,000, but two years down the road,
the asking price has risen to $18,000. That's not just inflation at
work. Some of the increase may come from government-mandated
changes for safety or environmental reasons, but many times, the
cars are just getting fancier or including more equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for many consumers this kind of upward growth
takes them out of that brand's price range.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda, however, has kept its eye on the entry-level buyer while
not cutting the quality of its cars or lessening its image, which
includes producing a full range of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   With the 1999 LXP Protege, Mazda has a brand-name vehicle that
isn't beyond too many buyers' financial capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Protege gets a new, more European body style this year. But
for many, the real news is that the base price begins at $13,130, a
number that puts it on the edge of the entry-level segment.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a stripped-down model. The new Protege has real
seating for five, and its structure has been enhanced with a triple
H-body construction, adding to the vehicle's safety. Window posts
and metal rails in the roof and on the side of the car are designed
to protect occupants in the event of a side impact or rollover.
</P>
<P>
   Dual front air bags are standard, and the rear doors are
enhanced with a safety catch pin. Powered by a peppy 1.6-liter
four-cylinder engine, the Protege offers 29 mpg city and 34 mpg
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the basics. There is a full complement of standard
features most entry-level consumers want, including AM/FM radio
with a CD player, power windows and door locks, cruise control,
three-point seat belts, 60/40 rear fold-down seat, rear window
defogger, tilt steering column, dual power mirrors, intermittent
wipers and tinted glass.
</P>
<P>
   Air conditioning will run an additional $1,145. But even then,
consumers are looking at a fully dressed out Protege with a sticker
under $15,000 in a name-recognizable package.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written exclusively for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
