<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLACK-QBS24-COX     02-23 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLACK-QBS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Race is not an issue in quarterback bonanza of '99
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The National Football League, which has done as
miserable a job developing black quarterbacks as it has hiring
minority head coaches, is poised to take an important step on the
former.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the league, it could be a dawning of a new era,'' Kansas
City offensive coordinator Jimmy Raye said before the quarterbacks
worked out Sunday at the NFL combine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a year we're going to bring a lot of young blood to
the (quarterback) position,'' Raye said, ``and it's significant
that much of it is going to be young black blood. It appears that
we are not as color-blind about quarterbacks as we once were.''
</P>
<P>
   A talent pool that might rival the legendary quarterback class
of 1983 has helped the NFL's collective vision. Not since 1987,
when four quarterbacks were taken in the first round, have more
than two been chosen in the opening round. Five or six quarterbacks
might go in the first round of the 1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Of the consensus top four quarterbacks this year, three
prospects _ Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida, Syracuse's Donovan
McNabb and Akili Smith of Oregon _ are African-Americans. All three
are expected to join in the opening round Kentucky star Tim Couch,
the probable first pick. Some personnel directors say they think
that all four might be taken by the middle of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the 23 quarterbacks invited to the combine are
minorities, the highest number for the annual predraft workouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles, who pick second, told Culpepper on
Saturday that their plan now is to take a quarterback, even if
Heisman trophy tailback Ricky Williams still is on the board. A
fourth black quarterback, Shaun King of Tulane, quietly is being
considered as a potential first-round pick by at least three clubs.
Ted White of Howard is likely to be drafted in the middle rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Even Aaron Brooks of Virginia apparently improved his stock some
on Sunday by demonstrating good arm strength and running the
40-yard dash in a sub-4.6 time. McNabb and Smith apparently threw
the ball very well during workouts. Culpepper chose not to work out
but will throw during an on-campus session in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worried about the race thing at my position, but
I'd be naive to say it hasn't been something you notice about the
NFL,'' McNabb said. ``I guess there's been sort of an unspoken
feeling that we had to be clearly better than the (white)
quarterbacks for the league to consider us. But there's no hint of
that here, really. I guess that's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970 draft, the first combining the NFL and old AFL,
49 quarterbacks have been selected in the first round. Three _ Doug
Williams of Tampa Bay (1978), Andre Ware of Detroit ('90) and Steve
McNair of Tennessee ('95) _ were black. Nearly as many Mannings _
Archie in 1971 and Peyton last year _ have been selected in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy noted that when he left the
University of Minnesota in 1977, he was the most celebrated
quarterback in the school's history and held virtually all of the
Gophers' career passing records. But when he signed as an undrafted
free agent with the Pittsburgh Steelers, he never got the
opportunity to compete at the position. He was switched to free
safety in his first minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, Dungy says he still feels slighted, but he
emphasized that none of this year's prospects will have a similar
fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely we're seeing progress,'' said Dungy, who is
interested in McNabb and King. ``People are being evaluated on
their arm strength, size and mobility on an even playing field. You
don't hear scouts saying, `Can we afford to take this guy? Will he
be able to pick up our system?' The issue of race is not an issue
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who led Tulane to its first undefeated season, pointed out
that all of the prospects have played quarterback most of their
football careers. None ever was asked to change positions.
Culpepper, McNabb and Smith all said that they have not been
scrutinized more closely because of race.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers director of operations Tom Donahue, who
could take a quarterback in the second round, said the stereotypes
that once dogged black passers no longer are a factor in evaluating
prospects. ``There was this subconscious temptation to describe a
black quarterback as `more athletic` or `more mobile,' those kinds
of euphemisms,'' Donahue said. ``You simply don't hear that
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more opportunities now,'' King said, ``because
there's a need for younger quarterbacks in the NFL and because
we're the best ones. If you can play, you can play, and it doesn't
matter if you're purple.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
