<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Feb. 23, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-KIDNAP (Modesto, Calif.) _ The FBI is treating the
disappearance of Carole Sund, 42, her daughter Julie, 15, and
Silvina Pelosso, 16, a family friend from Cordoba, Argentina, as a
possible kidnapping. They have not been seen since they left their
motel on the edge of Yosemite National Park a week ago. By ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   TOWN-REBOUND (Donna, Texas) _ This small South Texas city has
frequently been in the news, but for all the wrong reasons. The
headlines have detailed growing gang influence, satanic worship,
crooked cops, a ghoulish murder, political in-fighting and a water
system that almost went dry. Despite these ordeals, there is a
growing sense the dirt-poor town of Donna can rebound. By JAMES
PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   DIRTY-DOZEN-TEXAS (Houston) _ Africanized honeybees and red fire
ants are on the hit list of 12 exotic plants and animals that lack
natural predators in Texas but ravage wildlife across the state. A
look at these renegades, and the federal effort to fight back and
save threatened and endangered species. By ALLAN TURNER. (Graphic
available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-HIRING (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ A decision by Union
College to restrict its next four faculty hires to minority
candidates and loosen the purse strings to pay them has angered
some professors and prompted a debate over affirmative action on
campus. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   PILOTS-SUIT (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco lawyer is suing
American Airlines pilots on behalf of passengers whose flights were
delayed or canceled during the recent labor dispute. Attorney
Patrick Catalano wants the lawsuit to be declared a class action so
that perhaps thousands of plaintiffs may join the original six in
seeking damages. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-TOMATOES (Houston) _ Any way you slice it, the
best-tasting tomatoes are home-grown. For best results in the home
garden, plant early. For many, March is tomato time, but a February
head start is hard to pass up when the weather is as mild as it has
been this winter. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader who has wanted a hydrangea in
her yard since she first saw Donna Reed hiding from James Stewart
in the movie ``It's a Wonderful Life'' wants information on the
bush and whether it will do well in the South. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   MISCHKA'S-GOWNS (New York) _ At the height of the dress-down
grunge explosion five or six years ago, two clean-cut prep-style
guys, Mark Badgley and James Mischka, went in the opposite
direction. They perfected the now-iconic slip-dress and embellished
it with the most extravagant but subtle beading, charged a small
fortune for their creations and made fashion history. By CYNTHIA
ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION-COACH (Albany, N.Y. ) _ Four hours before a football
game, Denver Broncos' quarterback John Elway would eat eggs,
potatoes and ketchup. ``He just likes it,'' team nutritionist
Jackie Berning said. Although Berning won't take credit for Elway's
performance during last month's Super Bowl, she made sure he and
his teammates ate well. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Just a week and a constitutional
crisis ago, I took vacation vowing never to write about politics
again. So then what happens? There's an outbreak of all the great
political sins and emotions _ fear, loathing, envy, hate, gluttony
_ and all in true San Francisco style. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
