<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC24-COX     02-23 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Size matters when it comes to batteries
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What determines the usefulness of a ``12 volt'' automotive
battery? How do I know if my battery really needs to be replaced or
if it just needs to be recharged? When it comes time to replace a
battery, what do I need to buy? Is the most expensive the best, or
can I get by with a cheap one?
</P>
<P>
   Those are a lot of questions about such a simple box.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive batteries are manufactured and rated according to
specific criteria. First, the battery must fit into the space
provided for it and connect to the existing battery cables. This
external physical characteristic is defined as the BCI (Battery
Council International) group number. A group number is assigned to
a battery according to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Its maximum dimensions of length, width and height.
</P>
<P>
   While this might seem like a no-brainer, it is actually very
important. Besides the obvious ``well, it looks like it will fit''
and then doesn't, installation of the wrong size battery can lead
to the battery strap not fitting or working properly.
</P>
<P>
   If the battery is not secured correctly and is allowed to jiggle
or bounce around, all kinds of problems can occur. Acid spills and
broken plates inside the battery are only a couple. These two items
alone have the potential of turning a perfectly good electricity
generating device into a battery-bomb.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen far too many batteries held down with bungee cords,
slats of wood jammed around them and/or old coat hangers. The size
of the battery matters! Make sure the battery tray and strap are in
good shape and doing their jobs. If they are eaten away with
corrosion, get them repaired or replaced.
</P>
<P>
   -- Voltage: 6 or 12 volts.
</P>
<P>
   Six-volt electrical systems were replaced by 12 volts many years
ago. However, 42-volt automotive electrical systems are on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   -- Post configuration.
</P>
<P>
   Which side are the ``+'' and ``-'' mounted on the battery? It's
another seemingly simple situation until you get home and the
cables don't reach, or worse yet, get hooked up backward.
</P>
<P>
   -- The type of terminals.
</P>
<P>
   Top-mount or side-mount terminals are the most common automotive
application. Some batteries are equipped with both types to fit a
broader selection of vehicles. If you get one of these batteries,
be sure to leave the little plastic caps in place on the terminals
you don't use. This reduces the risk of electrical shorting.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have a battery that fits in place, you need to
determine its electrical capacity before you go ahead and connect
it correctly.
</P>
<P>
   A battery is rated on its ability to pass ``working
electricity'' tests. Typically, there are three major ratings _
reserve capacity (RC), ampere hour (A/H) and Cold Cranking Amps
(CCA) _ that determine what a battery is suppose to do under
certain conditions. All of the tests are related to time,
temperature, the amount of electricity (called amperage) needed for
the work to be done, and the minimal amount of voltage required to
keep the electrical system functioning.
</P>
<P>
   You may find all, some or none of these ratings printed on the
top of a battery. If they are not visible, you will need to ask for
the battery documentation. Remember, all of these tests pertain to
a fully charged battery at 12.66 volts. A partially charged battery
will not perform to specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Next week: Details on battery ratings and two other ``looks
good'' ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an ASE master automobile technician/L-1. Write her in
care of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to
nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
