 PageExpress budget for the week of Feb. 22, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
Feb. 23. To be delivered Friday, Feb. 26, by 2 pm.
 &UR; FOCUS: BEIRUT (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., Feb. 26) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The joke told is that spy satellites must click away when they
pass over this spot. From the top, the rusty trap doors in the
middle of this circular pavement look like they must cover a
missile site or underground bunker. But, when weather permits, the
doors open and a large blurry mirror flips up, displaying to
passing cars what's going on inside _ dancing and drinking at one
of Beirut's new night spots. Even during the war, Beirutis found
ways to keep the night life going. Now that the war is over and the
city is literally being rebuilt, the choices abound.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BAALBEK: Intricate stone carving and gigantic architecture
make Baalbek, the ``City of the Sun,'' one of the most extensive
and spectacular Roman ruins in the Middle East. Since November, the
experience has been heightened by a unique museum opened underneath
the ruins, in the tunnels that used to house animals for sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT: SUCCESS OF THE WB NETWORK (Available by 2 p.m.,
Thu., Feb. 25) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling TV network WB is the biggest success story in
television right now. While the major networks _ NBC, ABC, CBS and
Fox _ are all losing viewers, the WB is gaining them: 13 percent
from 1997 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' Grade: A-;
``Pecker,'' Grade: C; ``Permanent Midnight,'' Grade: D; ``Urban
Legend,'' Grade: C+.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: Blondie's ``No Exit,'' JMocean Worker's
``Mixed Emotional Landscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR: CREATING SPEED MACHINES(Available by 5 p.m., Thu., Feb.
26) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like parents fussing over a newborn, race teams agonize over
every inch of a new car, hoping they've created the machine that
will win races like today's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NASCAR NOTES
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD: AFRICAN CUISINE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   African cuisine remains a mystery to most Americans, says
Jessica Harris, who is touring the country promoting her latest
effort, ``The Africa Cookbook: Tastes of a Continent.'' African
dishes are, at once, familiar and exotic.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: African dishes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE: New technology and cutting-edge nutritional
research have led many medical and scientific experts to conclude
what everybody and their great-grandmother have known forever _
that real and substantial relief can come from over the counter _
the kitchen counter, that is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS: AUDI A6 AVANT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North American buyers may not immediately think of Audi when
station wagons are mentioned, but the European manufacturer
actually has commonality with those vehicles traditionally regarded
as family haulers _ primarily, change. With the new-for-'99 A6
Avant, Audi is burying the past.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Facts about the A6 Avant.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING: The most common perception of the term
``platform'' is it means the vehicles share the same floor plan or
metal stamping that constitutes the ``floor'' of the car. That may
be the case on a shared-platform vehicle, but not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY: TAX RETURNS AT THE PC &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Dark Ages before home computers, anyone preparing
his income-tax returns had to sit down with pencil, paper and a
calculator and shuffle through a box of records for hours to get
the job done. Now that person can sit down in front of his computer
screen and accomplish the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH TOOLS: A talking parrot on your PC? Every so often an
idea of such surpassing brilliance arrives via e-mail that I cannot
but share it with you.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: FamilyPC magazine, in its March 1999 edition,
takes a look at the issue of brand names as related to technology
products. It attempts to answer this question: When it comes to
computers, is label-consciousness anything more than simple vanity?
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: If you have plenty of money and want a new
computer, there are good reasons for buying one. But if you are one
of those people who have to count pennies and make decisions
between buying a new computer and paying the mortgage, don't feel
compelled to buy just because you have this vague notion that you
need more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: CUBA CALLS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The surreal sense of entering the Cuba of the 1950s has given
way to an awkward commercialism and an all-out wooing of foreign
tourists and investors. And while I still see the roadside
billboards praising the benefits of Castro's socialist revolution,
they are flanked by advertisements for Samsung electronics and
Pepsodent toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL TIPS: Some helpful tips and what to see and what to
avoid while in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS: The refectory of Santa Maria delle Grazie housing
Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last Supper'' in Milan will close for three
months for completion of a restoration that began two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS: POLITICAL HUMOR _ AL FRANKEN-STYLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the current political climate, it's become almost impossible
to write satire that outstrips reality. Political gadfly Al Franken
has wisely pretty much ignored the current Washington shenanigans
in his latest book of political humor, going straight for
unvarnished fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: Jo Ann Beard's memoir, ``The Boys of My Youth,''
has boys in it, but the central characters are all women and the
supporting characters are dogs.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: The publication of ``November 1916,'' the second
volume of Solzhenitsyn's three-book cycle, ``The Red Wheel,'' could
help alter his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Translation is not a matter of searching
out exact equivalents. Its a matter of ear and voice.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: There are no happy families in ``Werewolves in
Their Youth'' _ just different varieties of marital distress,
filial rage, paternal disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH: DANGERS OF INHALANTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dizzying buzz from inhalants lasts only a minute or so, but
the side effects can be lasting and extremely severe _ even for
first-time users. Youngsters sometimes suffer permanent damage to
their brain, bone marrow, liver and kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VITAMIN A: By failing to invest a few million dollars to
add vitamin A to food supplies in developing countries, the world
is missing a simple, cost-effective opportunity to prevent the
deaths of at least 1 million children a year.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MONITOR: A wristwatch-style blood pressure and pulse
monitor can help keep track of your physical conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: Taking samples of newborns' DNA can be a
useful tool, some parents find.
</P>
