Feb. 23. To be delivered Friday, Feb. 26, by 2 pm.
 &UR; FOCUS: BEIRUT (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., Feb. 26) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The joke told is that spy satellites must click away when they
pass over this spot. From the top, the rusty trap doors in the
middle of this circular pavement look like they must cover a
missile site or underground bunker. But, when weather permits, the
doors open and a large blurry mirror flips up, displaying to
passing cars what's going on inside _ dancing and drinking at one
of Beirut's new night spots. Even during the war, Beirutis found
ways to keep the night life going. Now that the war is over and the
city is literally being rebuilt, the choices abound.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BAALBEK: Intricate stone carving and gigantic architecture
make Baalbek, the ``City of the Sun,'' one of the most extensive
and spectacular Roman ruins in the Middle East. Since November, the
experience has been heightened by a unique museum opened underneath
the ruins, in the tunnels that used to house animals for sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT: SUCCESS OF THE WB NETWORK (Available by 2 p.m.,
Thu., Feb. 25) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling TV network WB is the biggest success story in
television right now. While the major networks _ NBC, ABC, CBS and
Fox _ are all losing viewers, the WB is gaining them: 13 percent
from 1997 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' Grade: A-;
``Pecker,'' Grade: C; ``Permanent Midnight,'' Grade: D; ``Urban
Legend,'' Grade: C+.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: Blondie's ``No Exit,'' JMocean Worker's
``Mixed Emotional Landscapes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR: CREATING SPEED MACHINES(Available by 5 p.m., Thu., Feb.
26) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like parents fussing over a newborn, race teams agonize over
every inch of a new car, hoping they've created the machine that
will win races like today's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NASCAR NOTES
