   &UR; TRAVEL: CUBA CALLS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The surreal sense of entering the Cuba of the 1950s has given
way to an awkward commercialism and an all-out wooing of foreign
tourists and investors. And while I still see the roadside
billboards praising the benefits of Castro's socialist revolution,
they are flanked by advertisements for Samsung electronics and
Pepsodent toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL TIPS: Some helpful tips and what to see and what to
avoid while in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS: The refectory of Santa Maria delle Grazie housing
Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last Supper'' in Milan will close for three
months for completion of a restoration that began two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS: POLITICAL HUMOR _ AL FRANKEN-STYLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the current political climate, it's become almost impossible
to write satire that outstrips reality. Political gadfly Al Franken
has wisely pretty much ignored the current Washington shenanigans
in his latest book of political humor, going straight for
unvarnished fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: Jo Ann Beard's memoir, ``The Boys of My Youth,''
has boys in it, but the central characters are all women and the
supporting characters are dogs.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: The publication of ``November 1916,'' the second
volume of Solzhenitsyn's three-book cycle, ``The Red Wheel,'' could
help alter his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Translation is not a matter of searching
out exact equivalents. Its a matter of ear and voice.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: There are no happy families in ``Werewolves in
Their Youth'' _ just different varieties of marital distress,
filial rage, paternal disappointment.
