<HEADLINE>
JEWELS INSPIRE TWO DESIGNERS' GOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the height of the dress-down grunge explosion five
or six years ago, two clean-cut prep-style guys, Mark Badgley and
James Mischka, went in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   They perfected the now-iconic slip-dress and embellished it with
the most extravagant but subtle beading, charged a small fortune
for their creations and made fashion history.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes are timeless and collectible. Each of them is a
scintillating work of art.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the designers had planned to show their extensive
fall/winter '99 line in their new and unfinished 11th-floor
showroom. But due to insurance problems that had more to do with
safety than anything else, the show was canceled, so the Bead Boys
saw guests and buyers in their current Seventh Avenue showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Seated on black chairs at chic metal tables between pipe racks
displaying yard after yard of beaded and non-beaded evening
dresses, skirts, sweater sets and a limited amount of fur-trimmed
daywear _ each creation given a name, not a style number _ the men
discussed the clothes. As a young model paraded out in a
wasp-waisted strapless black ball gown with a massive skirt and
train, Badgley, the dark-haired partner with the studious black
glasses, called the dress a ``she.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably one-fourth of the winter selection are full-skirted
ball gowns, a welcome change for the hip-and-thigh endowed who
could never get their little toe into one of Badgley Mischka's
slips. Not that the clothes were ``body-ist'' or anything, but,
Mischka said, ``We listen to what people tell us on the road at
trunk shows, and we wanted to add a silhouette for more bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The slip dress is still a classic,'' added Badgley. ``It
always works, it's always young and modern.''
</P>
<P>
   The new gowns have bodices with beaded straps, some that are
strapless, some coming off cap-sleeved, low-cut beaded chiffon
illusion tops; skirts are in iridescent satins in grayed-down,
dusty jewel tones. It is a collection that has taken its
inspiration from antique jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Portia'' dress, the full-on strapless black taffeta
ball gown, for instance, the decoration looked like an Edwardian
pearl. A rose-cut diamond necklace was suspended on the front of
the dress under the bust.
</P>
<P>
   Badgley Mischka created an entire series of low-cut black
dresses designed to enhance their customers' fabulous jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Color choices for fall and winter also include what Badgley
calls ``a memory of color,'' or hues that change in the light and
that defy description. What I thought was a toast and platinum
velvet gown was actually green over nude that had been washed and
faded. The top of the gown was a waterfall of clear beading,
splashing down from the shoulders on chiffon net. ``We have upped
the luxury quotient,'' laughed Badgley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
