<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR THROWS HIS HAIR IN THE RING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just a week and a constitutional crisis ago, I
took vacation vowing never to write about politics again.
</P>
<P>
   So then what happens? There's an outbreak of all the great
political sins and emotions _ fear, loathing, envy, hate, gluttony
_ and all in true San Francisco style.
</P>
<P>
   Political consultant Clint Reilly announced his candidacy for
mayor last week, and Mayor Willie Brown upstaged him with the two
words mayors are never supposed to utter during political
campaigns: ``fare increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, we'll pay more for bad service on the municipal transit
system, and as we know from restaurants, paying more for bad
service makes you like it more.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, while I was away the mayor got a new hair cut. He
got all of them cut. He had his head shaved. I don't know if this
is the youth look, the Jesse Ventura look or he's giving out
flowers to tourists arriving at the airport. But it doesn't look
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, now there's a tad more room in the hat for the ego.
</P>
<P>
   Let me know when he gets pierced.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that I hate Willie Brown. On Monday, Brown
went on a local television program and failed to deny there would
be a fare increase. Instead he attacked the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost,'' he told television host Ross McGowan,
``you've got to know that the San Francisco Examiner is a wholly
owned subsidiary of the Hate Willie Brown Club of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, he inflated his importance. The world doesn't hate
Willie Brown. The world knows him only from sycophantic reports in
magazines and on ``60 Minutes.'' All the people who hate Willie
Brown are in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't all of the people. But it's most of the people part of
the time _ that part of each day when they're trying to find a
parking space or waiting for a bus. Of course, that can be a long,
hate-filled time.
</P>
<P>
   As the first columnist to stick it to Brown, rather than suck up
to him, I resent him saying my newspaper is a ``wholly owned
subsidiary'' of the Hate Willie Brown Club. The way he usually
talks about us, you'd think he'd at least call us the world
headquarters of the Hate Willie Brown Club.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be wrong anyway. No, we in the press don't hate
politicians. We love them the way San Franciscans love sourdough.
We have them for lunch, sliced or torn, and we love them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we dunk them in a stew of their own juices.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Brown made the uncharacteristic mistake of getting
tripped up by a tongue other than his own.
</P>
<P>
   A member of his hand-picked Muni task force told the public that
the transit system needs a more stable funding base, and thus fare
increases may be necessary. And Brown agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   It may be true that Muni needs a fare increase, but the last
thing Brown needed was mention of the words just 90 minutes before
Clint Reilly announced his candidacy for mayor. Some suspect the
mayor scheduled the official release of his Muni plan to upstage
Reilly's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   That it did, the way setting your own garage on fire upstages
the new house next door.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Reilly interesting, besides the fact that he's
interesting, is that he's a political consultant gone on to the
hard stuff _ trying to get elected himself.
</P>
<P>
   This takes guts, as well as money, and he has both. Surely he
knows that people hate political consultants more than politicians.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no one to blame and no one to bill if the real
politician wins _ you know, the bald one.
</P>
<P>
   I mean the follicly challenged one.
</P>
<P>
   This is San Francisco, after all, where the overweight can be
protected from ridicule. Not politicians, though. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
