<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-NONFAT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of 
 professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets. This week's choice is nonfat milk.  
   
   
   
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Clover Has the Skinny on Nonfat-Milk Flavor  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Last week we brought you the tasting panel's top
choices for whole milk. But what about the nonfat variety?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panelists tasted eight brands of nonfat milk, and were
surprised at how much they liked the milks, agreeing that many
brands have improved vastly since the days when nonfat milk's
watery appearance and taste often earned it the label ``blue
milk.'' Panelists also concurred that nonfat milk is best served
very cold.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors went to  &UR; Clover Stornetta  &LR; (1/2 gallon, $1.69-$1.99
at many supermarkets), which came in second place in the panel's
previous whole-milk tasting. And panelists scored Clover's nonfat
milk higher than Lucerne, their top choice for whole milk. Three
panelists particularly liked the mouthfeel, and all the panelists
commented on the exceptional taste. All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Lucerne  &LR; (1/2 gallon, $2.11 at Safeway),
winner of the whole-milk tasting. While one panelist described the
flavor as ``clean and honest,'' two others did not like the watery
appearance. Three would buy it; two might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Berkeley Farms  &LR; (1/2 gallon, $1.99-$2.15 at many supermarkets)
came in a close third, three points lower than Lucerne. Two
panelists called it nondescript, but another thought it had too
much flavor. Three would buy it, one might buy it and one would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to one of the more expensive brands,  &UR; Straus &LR; 
(1/2 gallon, $3.19-$3.39 at many supermarkets). Three panelists
liked the distinctive grassy flavors of this organic milk, but two
others thought it had an off taste. Two would buy it, one might buy
it and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Castle Creamery &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $2.79 at Andronico's) and
 &UR; Horizon &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $2.69-$3.11 at many supermarkets) tied for
fifth place. One panelist thought Castle Creamery tasted sweet,
while another described the flavor as sour. Two panelists thought
it had a richer mouthfeel. Three would buy it, one might buy it,
and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were more divided on Horizon. One thought the organic
milk had almost no milk flavor, and another described it as thin
and watery. But the remaining panelists liked the clean, mild
flavors. Three would buy it; two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Two brands scored too low to rate: Michael's Organic and
Sunnyside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robin Davis is a Chronicle staff writer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia Hart,
dietitian and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San
Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1322EST &QL; 
