<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5854 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICKCOOK-SFCHRON &LR;      02-23 2405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKCOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with 
 enough leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes 
 plus suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus 
 suggestions in optional trim.  
   
   
 THE WEEKEND COOK: Persian Rice Weaves an Exotic Spell  
   
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Among the most popular of Iran's legendary rice
dishes is chello, aromatic, long-grain rice that is washed, soaked
and steamed in a traditional, almost ritualistic process that
renders each grain dry, separate and astonishingly firm-tender.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it steams, the rice forms a prized crust _ tah dig _ on the
bottom of the pot. Chello is served mounded like a pyramid, with
the deep golden tah dig as a garnish. A thin layer of butter,
yogurt, egg, potato or lahvosh helps create the crust. Our recipe
uses butter, yogurt and egg.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, basmati rice _ similar to Persian rice _ is
used to make chello. It is traditional to soak the rice in salted
water before steaming it, which produces a grain that is tender but
resilient, a texture difficult to duplicate without a saltwater
soak.
</P>
<P>
   When chello is served with grilled meat, the dish is called
chello kebab. Chello kebab is easy to make but takes time. The meat
must be marinated and the rice soaked and steamed _ both of which
can be done without much attention. An organized cook can start in
the morning and have a feast for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Chello kebab is a great company dish, and the leftovers can be
used many ways during the week. The two accompanying weeknight
recipes are inspired by another Persian rice dish called pollo,
where steamed rice is layered with meat, fruit, nuts and seasonings
and resteamed. Although these recipes are adaptations, they are in
the spirit of pollo-style rices where flavors and textures are as
intricately woven as a Persian rug.
</P>
<P>
   The herb sauce is also inspired by the Persian kitchen. Dill,
scallions and mint are readily used in Persian salads, but we whir
them into a pestolike condiment to accompany the kebabs. The sauce
keeps up to four days refrigerated, and you'll find many uses for
it during the week, too.
</P>
<P>
   Chello kebab is a dish for both gourmet and novice cook. It's a
wonderful project for anyone who appreciates good rice, regards
cooking as a pleasure and enjoys delving into underexplored
culinary territory. Yet, because it doesn't require special
equipment or cooking skills, chello kebab is easy enough for the
less adventurous cook to make with good results.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MASTER RECIPE: CHELLO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sumac is a red berry with a citrusy flavor. This spice,
traditionally sprinkled on chello, is available in Middle Eastern
markets. If you can't find it, omit it.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 cups basmati rice (preferably from India), cleaned
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon saffron threads, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plain yogurt (not nonfat)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Ground sumac (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the rice in a large bowl. Pour in lukewarm water to cover
by 2 inches. Swish the rice with your fingertips, let it settle,
then pour off the cloudy water. Repeat 4 or 5 times, until the
water runs clear. Drain. Return the rice to the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve 3 tablespoons of the salt in 12 cups cool water. Pour
over the rice, swish it briefly and set aside to soak for 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Place the crumbled saffron in a bowl and pour 11/4 cups boiling
water over it. Cover and steep for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg and yogurt in a small bowl until well combined. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 4 quarts water into a large, heavy pot with a tight-fitting
lid. Add the remaining 2 tablespoons salt. Cover and bring to a
boil over high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the soaked rice well, then stir into the boiling water,
cover, and return to a boil. As soon as the water boils, uncover
the pot and boil hard until the rice is cooked but still firm (not
brittle) in the center, in 3 to 4 minutes. Check the rice after 3
minutes by biting into a few grains. Try not to under- or over-cook
it. Drain the rice well.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse out and dry the pot. Return it to medium heat. Pour all
but 3 tablespoons of the melted butter into the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Stir 11/4 cups of the cooked rice into the egg mixture. Spread
it evenly over the bottom of the pot. Increase heat to high. Add
the remaining rice, mounding it into a neat pyramid with a spatula.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the remaining 3 tablespoons butter with 2 tablespoons
water. Drizzle the mixture over the rice. Place a kitchen towel
over the pot, then cover tightly with the lid. Steam for 5 minutes.
Reduce heat to low and steam for 45 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the sink with an inch of cold water. Stand the
still-covered pot in the water for 5 minutes to help loosen the
crust.
</P>
<P>
   Submerge 2 cups of the cooked rice in the reserved saffron
water; let stand for 1 minute. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, mound about 5 cups of the remaining rice into a
pyramid on a serving platter. Sprinkle a scant cup of the
saffron-tinted rice over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Using a spatula, remove the rice crust from the pot, in pieces
if necessary. Arrange the pieces around the pyramid of rice.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with the sumac on the side, letting each diner sprinkle it
on to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate the remaining saffron rice for use in
Basmati Rice with Dried Cranberries and Chicken. Let the remaining
plain rice cool to room temperature, then cover and refrigerate for
use throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 15 cups of rice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP: &LR;   &LR; 285 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 50 g carbohydrate, 7 &LR; 
 &LR; g fat (4 g saturated), 31 mg cholesterol, 486 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKEND RECIPE: CHELLO KEBAB &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a salad of chopped tomatoes, cucumbers and scallions
dressed with olive oil and lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 6 good-sized limes
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   8 boneless, skinless chicken thighs, halved
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds boneless leg of lamb, cut into 11/2- to 2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Chello (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup Herb Sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Evenly divide the juice, onion and salt between 2 medium-sized,
nonreactive bowls. Add the chicken to one bowl, the lamb to the
other. Toss the meats to coat with the marinade. Cover and
refrigerate for 5 hours, tossing once or twice. Remove from the
refrigerator and let stand at room temperature for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the broiler or grill. Remove the meats from the marinade
and dry well with paper towels. Thread the meats on skewers. If
using the grill, lightly brush it with a little of the oil. Brush
the kebabs with the remaining oil.
</P>
<P>
   If using the broiler, lightly brush a large, shallow-sided
baking tray with a little of the oil. Brush the kebabs with the
remaining oil.
</P>
<P>
   Grill or broil the kebabs until the lamb is slightly pink in the
center, 7 to 9 minutes, turning once after 5 minutes, and until the
chicken is cooked through, 10 to 12 minutes, turning once after 7
to 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange half of the chicken and about a dozen pieces of lamb
around the rice. Serve with the Herb Sauce as a condiment.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, cover and refrigerate the remaining chicken and lamb for
use throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4, with leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 450 calories, &LR;   &LR; 37 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 32 g fat (7 g saturated), 125 mg cholesterol, 405 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKEND RECIPE: HERB SAUCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Use very fresh herbs. Refrigerated, the sauce will keep for 4
days.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch cilantro, most of the thick stems discarded
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch scallions
</P>
<P>
   6 large dill sprigs, thickest stems discarded
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 scant cup mild olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon + 1 teaspoon dried mint, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cilantro, scallions, dill and salt in a food
processor; process, scraping down the sides of the bowl as
necessary, until the herbs are pulpy.
</P>
<P>
   With the motor running, drizzle in the oil, processing until the
herbs are finely chopped and an emulsion forms.
</P>
<P>
   Pour and scrape the sauce into a bowl. Stir in the mint and
enough lemon juice to give the sauce a slight edge.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 60 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 g protein, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 6 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 101 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: CURRIED LENTILS, LAMB &AMP; BASMATI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lentils mixed with rice are traditional in Persian cooking,
sometimes with the addition of meat or dried fruit. A handful of
currants or raisins in this easy dish would be a welcome
counterpoint to the spices. Add either when you add the peas.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups lentils, picked over for pebbles, rinsed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion (10 ounces), cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons good quality curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon (scant) ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon (scant) cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   8 pieces of lamb (from Weekend Recipe), finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cups basmati rice (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen peas, defrosted
</P>
<P>
   Instructions
</P>
<P>
   Bring 31/2 cups salted water to a boil in a small saucepan. Add
the lentils, cover, reduce heat to medium and simmer until just
tender, about 15 minutes. Drain, reserving the cooking liquid. Set
the lentils aside.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large heavy saucepan over medium-high heat.
Add the onion and saute, stirring frequently, until golden, about 7
minutes. Reduce heat, if necessary, toward the end of the cooking
time so the onion doesn't burn.
</P>
<P>
   Add the curry powder, 1/2 teaspoon salt, the black pepper,
cumin, cayenne and cinnamon. Saute, stirring, for 30 seconds. Add
the reserved lentil cooking liquid and boil for 30 seconds. Add the
lamb and simmer for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly stir in the rice, reserved lentils and the peas,
tossing until the rice mixture is completely coated with the
seasoned liquid. Using a spatula, mound the rice into a pyramid.
Cover tightly, reduce heat to low and steam for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mound into a pyramid on a platter and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 or 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 550 calories, &LR;   &LR; 34 g protein, 81 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 10 g fat (5 g saturated), 54 mg cholesterol, 185 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 9 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: BASMATI RICE WITH DRIED CRANBERRIES &AMP; CHICKEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The classic version of this dish calls for preserved sour
cherries. You may use dried sour cherries if you find them, but
dried cranberries are similar and readily available. The
combination of sweet-tart fruit, black pepper and a hint of
bitterness from saffron is exotic and lovely. The lengthiest step
of this easy dish is caramelizing the onions.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups dried cranberries or dried sour cherries
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 very large onion (12 ounces), minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   8 pieces of chicken (from Weekend Recipe), finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 cups basmati rice (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup saffron-tinted basmati rice (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sliced almonds, toasted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped walnuts, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the dried cranberries in a bowl. Pour 1 cup of boiling
water over them and let steep for 10 minutes. Drain, reserving the
soaking liquid. Set the cranberries aside.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, melt the butter in a large, heavy pan over medium
heat. Add the onion and salt. Saute, stirring frequently, until the
onion is deeply caramelized but not burned, 35 to 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Increase the heat to high. Deglaze the pan with 1/2 cup water.
Boil for 1 minute. Add the reserved cranberry liquid, the chicken,
lemon juice and pepper. Simmer for 1 minute. Add the cranberries,
rice, almonds and walnuts. Toss gently but thoroughly to combine.
Using a spatula, mound the rice into a pyramid. Cover the pan,
reduce heat to low and steam for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mound the rice into a pyramid on a platter and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 705 calories, &LR;   &LR; 26 g protein, 96 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 25 g fat (7 g saturated), 71 mg cholesterol, 469 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 5 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM: &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MORE IDEAS FOR LEFTOVERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In combination or separately, any leftover chicken, lamb and
Herb Sauce from Chello Kebab, and leftover basmati rice make good
weekday dishes, including:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chicken-Lemongrass Soup. &LR;  Mince the bulbous part of a large
stalk of lemongrass. Simmer, covered, in chicken broth for 5
minutes; strain. Combine the broth, some finely chopped Chello
Kebab chicken and leftover basmati rice; simmer for 2 minutes. Add
a seeded, thinly sliced jalapeno pepper and a handful of coarsely
chopped cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lamb Salad with Herb Yogurt. &LR;  Thinly slice leftover Chello
Kebab lamb. Toss with chopped hearts of romaine, sliced cherry
tomatoes, cucumbers, scallions and radishes, lemon juice, olive oil
and salt and pepper to taste. Top with a dollop of plain yogurt
seasoned with salt, pepper and some Herb Sauce. Accompany with
toasted pita bread.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Green Rice. &LR;  Thoroughly combine leftover basmati rice and Herb
Sauce to taste. Using a spatula, mound the rice into a pyramid in a
heavy-bottomed pan. Sprinkle with a little water. Cover tightly and
steam over low heat for 10 minutes. Serve as a side dish for meats,
poultry, fish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stuffed Peppers. &LR;  Halve lengthwise and devein red bell peppers.
Fill with a mixture of cooked basmati rice, Herb Sauce, finely
chopped Chello Kebab chicken or lamb and chopped scallions. Place
the peppers in a baking dish. Pour 1/4 cup water in the dish, then
drizzle peppers with a tablespoon of olive oil. Cover with foil and
bake in a 375-degree oven until the peppers are tender, 30 to 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; White Bean-Basmati Soup with Herb Sauce. &LR;  Drain and rinse
canned white beans. Simmer them in chicken broth for 5 minutes. Add
leftover basmati rice and a thinly sliced carrot. Simmer for a
minute. The mixture should be soupy. Serve topped with a small
spoonful of Herb Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Basmati Breakfast. &LR;  Combine leftover saffron-tinted basmati
rice with chopped nuts, dates and dried apricots, and dried
cherries or cranberries. Top with milk, half-and-half or cream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
