<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but 
 the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is 
 enlightening. Starting today, with Food in the News, The 
 Chronicle's Food staff aims to change that. This regular 
 round-up column will make practical sense of the latest 
 nutrition-related studies _ as well as offering offbeat but 
 tantalizing snippets of other food news to put on your plate. 
 &HT;       
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: A Tomato a Day Keeps the Doctor Away  
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ The tomato is the media star of the moment after a
study published last week in the Journal of the National Cancer
Institute confirmed its cancer-fighting ability.
<P>
   Unlike the parade of other foods researchers suspect might have
anti-oxidant properties, the tomato is the real deal. The latest
report, out of Harvard Medical School, analyzes 72 past studies
linking tomatoes and cancer rates and concludes that eating a large
amount of tomato products may help reduce cancer risk _
particularly cancers of the prostate, stomach and lung.
</P>
<P>
   The tomato's secret is its high concentration of lycopene, the
carotenoid that makes the fruit red. But simply eating lots of raw
tomatoes won't do the trick. To fully release the lycopene,
tomatoes must be heat-processed. And to properly distribute the
cancer-fighting properties throughout the body, tomatoes should be
eaten with a little fat.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 12 ounces of tomato juice a day offers enough
lycopene to have some impact, the Harvard report shows. But without
oil to help the body absorb it, much of the advantage can be lost.
So eat some buttered toast with your morning tomato juice, says Dr.
Clare Hasler, head of the Functional Food program at the University
of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you eat a raw tomato on an empty stomach, you're not going
to get the lycopene,'' she says. ``That's why lasagne and pizza are
good sources _ you get that bit of fat, and the sauce provides a
high concentration of lycopene. But be reasonable. It doesn't mean
you can layer your pizza with tons of Italian sausage.''
</P>
<P>
   So exactly how much marinara is beneficial? Scientists are still
trying to figure that out, but one of the studies showed men who
ate 10 servings of cooked tomato products a week had lycopene
levels elevated enough to fight the cellular changes that precede
cancer. Other nutritionists say a serving a day is a good
guideline.
</P>
<P>
   And a serving is much less than you think.
</P>
<P>
   ``A slice of pizza is probably a serving and I would think a
typical plate of spaghetti is several servings,'' says professor
John Eurdman, director of nutritional sciences at the University of
Illinois. He heads up a National Cancer Institute study of lycopene
and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, tomato processors are ecstatic about the NCI report.
In ads, Heinz is touting ketchup as a cancer-fighter. And the
California Tomato Growers Association expects a boost in business.
About half of the world's processed tomatoes come from the state,
where about 3.2 million tons of paste are made each year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Eat Out, But Carefully &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Americans are eating out twice as often as they did 20 years
ago, according to a recent U.S. Department of Agriculture report.
That's good news for the restaurant business, but bad news for
diners' health.
</P>
<P>
   The new study based on food consumption surveys from 1977-95
shows the proportion of food we eat away from home has nearly
doubled. But food eaten at restaurants, fast-food joints and
take-out places is often much less healthy than what we eat at
home.
</P>
<P>
   For example, respondents reported that fat makes up about 31
percent of the calories of their home-cooked food. But it jumps to
almost 38 percent in the food they eat out.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, researchers says, is psychological.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers may believe that it is less important to consider
the nutritional quality of food away from home or (they are) less
willing to sacrifice taste when eating out,'' the report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Safer Sandwiches &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Government researchers have come up with another reason to eat
lots of horseradish with your roast beef. The root can knock out e
coli, listeria and a host of other disease-causing agents in food.
</P>
<P>
   The magic little microbe inhibitor is something called allyl
isothicoyanate, which shows up in high levels in horseradish and
mustard oil.
</P>
<P>
   The study comes from a food chemist from Oklahoma Sate
University who worked with USDA researchers in a search for
alternatives to chemical preservatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
