<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Recipes follow in optional trim.  
   
   
   
 Bay Area Pastry Chefs Trade Cookie Secrets  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Pastry chefs are unique among cooks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They head to the kitchen before dawn to supervise a quiet riot
of tiny chemical explosions and alchemy.
</P>
<P>
   They are precise people obsessed with their craft. News about
changes in the water content of butter can stop conversations.
Baking is, above else, chemistry. And chemistry is precise.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the nature of baking helps explain why about 80
Bay Area pastry chefs spent an entire morning earlier this month
debating the finer points of measuring brown sugar and the
attributes of a good cookie.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs who gathered in a Financial District hotel were part
of the Bakers Dozen, a loose-knit group that meets quarterly to
swap tips, troll for new recipes and look for new talent. Each
meeting features a different subject. This time, it was the cookie.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies are close to the perfect dessert: portable, personal and
full of possibility. With just a few bites, a cookie conveys a lot
of information about the amalgam that comprises the dough. In the
hands of a good cook, imagination and technique can elevate what
is, at its essence, a homey and simple culinary concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like cookies to be comfort food. I don't want them to
be too complex,'' said Carolyn Weil, pastry chef and cooking
teacher from Berkeley and a founder of the Bakers Dozen. Her
favorites are cookies that feature the flavors of brown sugar and
oatmeal.
</P>
<P>
   Oatmeal is a key ingredient in the chunky chocolate oatmeal
cookies made by Black Cat chef David Chesarek _ just one of about
50 offerings chefs brought for an informal tasting. Rows of
delicate meringues, chocolate crisps, rum creme-filled vanilla
discs and lots in between snaked across a table at the back of the
hotel meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of home cooks who attended hoped to glean tips from
the experts and improve their own techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Knauer, a home cook from San Francisco, figured out why
her chocolate chip cookies sometimes turn out flat: too much brown
sugar. Although she uses the same-size measuring cup, she realized
she doesn't always pack it the same. She left vowing to weight the
brown sugar after she packs it.
</P>
<P>
   Knauer was brave enough to bring a batch of her family's
favorite cookie: apricot half moons. They held up well against the
professionals' offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Here is her recipe, plus four others created by professionals
and presented at the cookie showdown. Although there was no
official winner, these are among the cookies that won praise from
Bakers Dozen organizers or created a buzz among cookie tasters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM: &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GINGERSPICE COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You'll need a kitchen scale to make this recipe from Barbara
Mooradian, who is a former pastry chef.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons hot coffee
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces softened butter
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   Granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Line a baking sheet with baker's parchment. Cut a 12x16-inch
length of parchment and place nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, soda and salt. Set aside. Combine the
molasses and coffee; set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer on medium speed, cream the butter for 1
minute. Add the sugar and cream for 30 seconds, scraping the sides
of the bowl. Add the minced ginger and spices; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the flour mixture alternately with the molasses/coffee and
mix well, scraping the sides of the bowl from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Using a spatula, scrape the dough onto the length of parchment,
then with the help of the parchment, roll the dough into a
2-inch-diameter log. Place in the freezer until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to bake, unwrap the log and slice into 1/4-inch-thick
rounds for thin, crisp cookies; or into 3/4-inch rounds for soft,
chewy cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Coat the cookies with granulated sugar, then place on the baking
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for about 14 minutes, reversing the pan at the halfway
point. Cool on rack.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 48 thin or 16 thick cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER THIN COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 70 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 9 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 3 g fat (2 g saturated), 9 mg cholesterol, 57 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PISTACHIO PRALINE COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Galen Warner of Rose Pistola restaurant in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Praline:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shelled unsalted pistachios, skinned
</P>
<P>
   Cookie Dough:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   21/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; For the praline:  &LR; Lightly grease a baking sheet, or use a
silt mat. Put the sugar in a small saucepan. Stir in just enough
water to make a paste. Boil over high heat until the sugar turns a
rich caramel color. Remove from heat and quickly stir in the
pistachios with a heatproof spatula. Pour onto the baking sheet or
silt mat. Cool to room temperature, then finely chop in a food
processor. Cover with plastic wrap and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the cookie dough:  &LR; Sift together the flour, baking powder,
baking soda and salt. Using an electric mixer on low speed, cream
the butter and sugars. Add the eggs, vanilla and sifted dry
ingredients; blend well. By hand, fold in the crushed praline.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the dough onto lengths of baker's parchment and roll
into 2-inch-diameter logs. Refrigerate at least 4 hours, or until
well chilled and firm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; When ready to bake:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 325 degrees. Line 2
baking sheets with baker's parchment. Unwrap the logs of dough and
cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices. Place the cookies 2 inches apart on
the prepared baking sheets. Bake about 15 minutes, or until just
golden.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 60 to 70 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 105 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 17 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 4 g fat (2 g saturated), 13 mg cholesterol, 60 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; OATMEAL WALNUT CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From David Chesarek of The Black Cat restaurant in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces softened butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whole milk
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups instant oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces semi-sweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, baking powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, cream the butter and sugars on low
speed. Blend in the egg, vanilla and milk. Add the sifted dry
ingredients and the oatmeal; mix on medium speed until just
incorporated. Fold in the chocolate chips and walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap the dough in plastic wrap and refrigerate for 4 hours,
until chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees. Line 2 baking sheets with
parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Drop generously rounded tablespoonfuls of dough onto the
prepared baking sheets, spacing the cookies about 2 inches apart.
</P>
<P>
   Bake about 15 minutes, or until lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 60 to 70 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 105 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 10 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 7 g fat (4 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 53 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; APRICOT HALF MOONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These may be filled with raspberry, fig or other thick preserves
of choice. From Linda Knauer, home baker.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound butter
</P>
<P>
   1 pound creamed cottage cheese, sieved
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   About 11/4 cups thick apricot preserves
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chopped walnuts or pecans
</P>
<P>
   4 egg whites, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the butter, cottage cheese and flour; stir until a soft
dough forms. If dough is too soft, add a little more flour. Shape
into 1-inch balls and place on a baking sheet. Cover with plastic
wrap and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to bake, preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Line baking
sheets with baker's parchment.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out the dough balls into 3-inch-diameter circles. Place
about 1 scant teaspoon jam in the center of each and fold the dough
over into a half-moon shape. Make sure the edges are well sealed to
contain the jam.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the sugar and nuts. Using a pastry brush, lightly
brush each cookie with beaten egg whites, then sprinkle with the
nut mixture. Place cookies on the baking sheets and bake for about
20 minutes, depending on crispness desired. Remove from baking
sheets and let cool to room temperature. Dust with powdered sugar
just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 56 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 150 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 16 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 9 g fat (4 g saturated), 19 mg cholesterol, 93 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
