<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Recipes and roundups of restaurants, suppliers and 
 cookbooks follow in optional trim.  
   
 A Taste of Paradise: The Bay Area offers a culinary voyage 
 across the South Pacific  
 Hawaii _ Fiji _ Tonga _ Samoa  
   
   
 By M.M. Pack  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ One Friday night last spring, after the last class
of the week, a procession of cars pulled away from the California
Culinary Academy in San Francisco heading for a clifftop back yard
overlooking San Pablo Bay. Some of the cars carried food and beer;
others sagged under loads of firewood and stones; still others were
stuffed with burlap bags, chicken wire, and bales of ti and taro
and banana leaves.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proudly leading the parade was a tiny blue Honda Civic
containing two large men and _ lolling in the back seat _ a very
recently slaughtered, disconcertingly intact 150-pound pig.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the pig, we were a pretty diverse crew. From Tokyo
to Tucson to Texas, from Manila to Maine, some of us were not long
out of high school, others were changing from careers as varied as
truck driving, professional dancing and technical writing. We
seemingly had nothing in common except our passionate love for food
and cooking. And this night we were going to have a luau.
</P>
<P>
   Class member David Vera, from Fiji, led us in digging the
roasting pit, building the bonfire, heating the rocks, burying the
pig in a shroud of burlap and aromatic leaves and then
not-so-patiently waiting until the next afternoon for the feast.
And feast we did, not only on the succulent, smoky, fork-tender
kalua pig, but also on poi and yams and poke, tropical fruit salad
and coconut haupia.
</P>
<P>
   This taste of the Pacific Islands only left me hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   The cuisines of the Pacific Islands may be the original fusion
food. The history of the Pacific is one long story of peripatetic
voyaging and settling, warfare and colonization, cultures colliding
and morphing, all of which affected the food.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian cuisine, most familiar to mainlanders, is a blend of
foods from distinct eras of migration, according to Rachel Laudan,
author of ``The Food of Paradise'' (University of Hawaii Press,
1996).
</P>
<P>
   The first wave was the Micronesian voyagers of the third century
who brought pigs, chickens, taro, sweet potatoes, bananas, sugar
cane and coconuts to add to the ocean's wealth of seafood.
Americans and Europeans _ many from Portugal _ began arriving in
the late 18th century, introducing new fruits and vegetables, salt
meat and salmon. Asians and Filipinos landed in the 1880s, bringing
rice, noodles, tofu, soy, Asian vegetables, herbs and spices.
</P>
<P>
   This heady larder all started to come together in 1920s with the
comfort fare called Local Food _ raw fish poke, teriyaki, Spam
musubi, saimen noodle soup with fishcake, the salted dried fruits
called crack seed, Portuguese sausages and malasadas, and
fruit-flavored Hawaiian shave ice. In the early 1980s, Local Food
jumped another notch when restaurant and hotel chefs began turning
the ingredients into sophisticated fare, launching what they called
Hawaiian Regional Cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The food of Fiji also reflected the cultures that settled there
_ originally Melanesians and Polynesians, then Western traders and
missionaries. Chinese immigrants brought rice, soy and ginger, and
Indians added the panoply of spices, peppers and curries that are
such an integral part of Fijian food today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fijian cuisine is the only one I know that includes a
variety of native green vegetables,'' Vera says. Some of these are
taro leaves; bele, ``slimy but tastes good,'' Vera says; tightly
curled fern shoots called ota; spinach; moca (pronouned ``motha'');
duruka, buds of a plant resembling sugar cane that's like fibrous
asparagus; and nama, which is a reef seaweed with a crunchy
texture.
</P>
<P>
   Tonga and Samoa weren't as heavily settled by Westerners so the
food in those countries remains closer to the original island
cooking. Samoan and Tongan cooking tends not to be highly spiced;
it features cooked breadfruit, taro root, taro leaves and green
bananas served with coconut milk and onions.
</P>
<P>
   Suckling pig roasted on a spit is well-loved in Tonga and
barbecued turkey tails are popular in Samoa, says Levi Lelea, who
serves plate lunches at Levi's Market in Daly City. ``So is a dish
called luau pilikaki, which is made from taro leaves, coconut and
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   While each of these island cultures is unique, they still share
some cooking methods and ingredients, such as earth ovens (called
imu in Hawaii, lovo in Fiji, umu in Samoa), dug in a pit, to
slow-cook food; staples such as taro root and leaves, bananas,
coconut milk, yams, pork; and prepared dishes made from fresh raw
fish.
</P>
<P>
   But the migration to the Pacific Islands has not been one-way.
Many Islanders have settled in Northern California, too. The
Association of Bay Area Governments counted more than 21,000
Hawaiians in the nine-county Bay Area in 1990, and that number has
increased in the last decade. Robert Uhrle, executive director of
the Samoan Community Development Center, speculates there are as
many as 30,000 Samoans in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Several cultural groups sponsor events and serve as
clearinghouses, including the Pacific Islander Cultural
Organization in San Francisco and the Polynesia Polynesia
cq &LR; Cultural Organization in San Jose, whose members have compiled a
cookbook (see cookbook list).
</P>
<P>
   Island food at Bay Area restaurants ranges from
California-Hawaiian fusion at Aloha Junction in Mill Valley to
straight-up plate lunches at Hawaiian Drive-In No. 28 in the
Mission and Tita's Hale Aina in the Castro. If you time it right,
you can catch some music with your food at the Templebar in
Berkeley or the Punahele Grill in San Francisco. Levi's Market in
Daly City serves take-out Samoan plate lunches and desserts six
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   But you can also cook Island food yourself, helped by
ingredients from across the Pacific. Poi, taro leaves, frozen
prepared food and all manner of Island snacks can be found in
specialty stores (see Supplies listing), and fresh Island fish
varieties are often available from fishmongers. And fresh tropical
produce can often be found in well-stocked supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   All of this can easily be turned into Island food at home, a
comfort food that personifies the word multicultural. The more I
learned about Pacific Island food, the more I appreciated that in
our months together my classmates had taught one another their home
cooking from Japan, the Philippines, Fiji and all over the States.
That's why, on that evening by the water before we scattered to our
corners of the planet, it seemed so fitting to celebrate our
diversity through the rich culinary mosaic of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
M.M. Pack is a recent graduate of the California Culinary Academy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM: &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HAUPIA WITH TROPICAL FRUIT COMPOTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While this simple coconut pudding often is made with cornstarch,
the more traditional method is to thicken it with arrowroot.
Arrowroot produces a creamier, lighter pudding with a more
pronounced coconut flavor. The classic Hawaiian presentation is to
cut the pudding into squares and serve on pieces of green ti leaf.
Alternatively, chill the pudding in molds, then turn out onto
dessert plates. Accompany with fruit compote. Adapted from ``The
Food of Paradise: Exploring Hawaii's Culinary Heritage,'' by Rachel
Laudan (University of Hawaii Press, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons arrowroot
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Fruit Compote (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mix the arrowroot and sugar in a saucepan; gradually whisk in
the coconut milk until there are no lumps. Place over low heat and
cook, whisking constantly, until the mixture just simmers and has
thickened. Remove from heat and stir in the vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into an 8-inch square cake pan or 6 individual molds,
cover, and refrigerate for at least 2 hours, until the pudding
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Cut into 6 squares (or turn out of molds) and garnish with fruit
compote.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 345 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 34 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 24 g fat (21 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 18 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TROPICAL FRUIT COMPOTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This also is good made with pineapple, passion fruit, bananas
and strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 mango
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 papaya
</P>
<P>
   2 kiwi fruits
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon thinly sliced mint leaves (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Peel and seed the mango and papaya and peel the kiwis. Cut the
fruit into 1/2-inch cubes and mix together gently.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle with mint leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 50 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 12 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 0 g fat (0 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 3 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; KOKODA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Variations of marinated raw fish are found throughout the
Pacific Islands; kokoda in Fiji, oku in Samoa and poke in Hawaii.
This Fijian version, from David Vera, traditionally is made with
walu, but any very fresh, firm, white-fleshed fish, such as sea
bass or swordfish, may be used. Make this one day in advance; the
fish should marinate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound walu, ono, or other firm white-fleshed fish fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh lemon or lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   To Finish:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated carrot
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup diced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup diced green onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced peeled and seeded tomato
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced seeded fresh Thai pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely minced lime zest
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   The day before serving, cut the fish into 1/2-inch cubes. Place
in a bowl with the vinegar, lemon juice and salt. Cover and
refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 45 minutes before serving, drain the fish and
rinse it briefly in cold water. Drain the fish again. Place in a
bowl and add the carrot, red onion, green onion, tomato, cilantro,
pepper, lime zest and juice, and the coconut milk. Mix gently.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate for 30 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 265 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 6 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 17 g fat (12 g saturated), 44 mg cholesterol, 118 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LAULAU &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Laulau is a traditional Hawaiian dish that can be made with fish
and pork, beef and/or chicken. The key to its great flavor is fat.
If you use very lean meat or fish, the laulau may be dry and the
flavor disappointing. The traditional outer wrapping of aromatic ti
leaves is beautiful and contributes much to the taste of the dish,
but if ti leaves are not available, you can use foil instead. This
recipe comes from David Vera.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 two-inch cube pork butt
</P>
<P>
   1 two-inch cube beef chuck steak
</P>
<P>
   1 two-inch cube butterfish, or other rich fish such as salmon
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 fresh taro leaves, or 1 to 2 large collard green leaves (see
note)
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh ti leaves
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cut a 4-inch length of kitchen string. Season the meat and fish
with a generous amount of salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   If using fresh taro leaves, cut off and discard the tough stems,
then simmer the leaves in water to cover for at least 45 minutes.
This destroys the calcium oxalate crystals in the leaves. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Pass the ti leaves back and forth over a flame (such as a gas
burner) for 10 to 15 seconds. This enhances the flavor and makes
the leaves a little more pliable.
</P>
<P>
   Place a taro leaf in the palm of your hand. Place the meat and
fish in the center of the leaf and wrap the ends of the leaf around
the filling. Wrap 2 or more taro leaves around the bundle so it is
completely enclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 ti leaf shiny side down on a work surface. Place the
other ti leaf shiny side down across the first one at right angles
(forming a giant ``X''). Place the meat/fish bundle in the center.
Bring the 4 ends of the leaves up around the bundle, then tie the
bundle with string.
</P>
<P>
   Place the bundle in a steamer over simmering water, cover, and
steam for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, remove the string and ti leaves. Accompany the laulau
with steamed rice or poi.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Fresh taro and ti leaves are available in stores that
stock Pacific Island specialties.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 175 calories, &LR;   &LR; 19 g protein, 0 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 11 g fat (4 g saturated), 66 mg cholesterol, 69 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PALUSAMI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Variations of this dish, with and without meat, are prepared in
Samoa, Fiji and Tonga. In this version from David Vera, canned corn
beef is the traditional filling, but well-marbled beef brisket also
works. Wrapping the contents in taro and banana leaves may take a
little practice, but the end result is so delicious, it's worth the
effort. Having two pair of hands for the task makes it easier. The
slow baking enhances the nutty flavors of the taro and coconut in
combination with the beef.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   7 fresh taro leaves, or one package frozen taro leaves (see
note)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound beef brisket, well-marbled, cut into 1-inch cubes; or 16
ounces canned corned beef, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tomato, cored, seeded and cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   2 chile peppers, deveined and minced (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons cilantro, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 banana leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 limes, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If using fresh taro and banana leaves:  &LR; Cut off and discard the
taro leaf stems, then simmer the leaves in water to cover for at
least 45 minutes. Drain. Select a medium-sized bowl to act as a
mold. Line the bowl with the 2 largest taro leaves, forming a sort
of leaf container. Arrange 3 more leaves inside to strengthen the
bottom of the leaf container.
</P>
<P>
   Place the beef in the center, then add the onion, tomato,
peppers and garlic. Top with the cilantro. Pour the coconut milk
over the filling and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Tear the remaining 2 taro leaves into small pieces and place on
top of the mixture. Carefully fold the large taro leaves up and
over to form a bundle. Cut the banana leaf in half lengthwise.
Place the halves at right angles to each other (forming an ``X'')
on a flat surface. Transfer the taro leaf bundle to the center of
the ``X'' and fold the banana leaves up and around the bundle. Wrap
the entire packet in foil.
</P>
<P>
   Place the bundle in an oven-proof dish and bake for 11/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If using frozen taro leaves:  &LR; Thaw and drain the package of
leaves. Line a medium-sized bowl with a large piece of foil. Inside
the foil, form a lining using half of the taro leaves. Following
instructions above, fill the leaf container. Spread the remaining
taro leaves over the filling. Wrap the foil over all, forming a
sealed bundle.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, open the bundle while it is still piping hot. Squeeze
lime juice over the filling and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 415 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 32 g fat (24 g saturated), 69 mg cholesterol, 109 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PRAWNS WITH SWEET POTATOES IN COCONUT CURRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This dish, from David Vera, is a good example of the strong
Indian influence prevalent in Fijian cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 large sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   6 fenugreek seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   2 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 hot chiles, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   3 cups coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium prawns, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 limes, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Boil the cubed sweet potatoes in water to cover until they are
just tender, not soft. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the
onions, garlic and ginger and saute until the onions are
translucent. Stirring constantly, add the mustard, cumin and
fenugreek seeds, the cinnamon, cloves, chiles and curry powder. Be
careful the mixture doesn't burn.
</P>
<P>
   Add the coconut milk and bring to a boil. Reduce heat and simmer
for 10 minutes. Add the sweet potatoes and simmer for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the prawns and bring to a boil, then remove from heat.
Discard the cinnamon stick. Season with salt and pepper and garnish
with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with steamed white rice and the lime wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 600 calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 25 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 45 g fat (33 g saturated), 172 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 201
mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
