<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SALAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe 
 for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow 
 in optional trim.  
   
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Black Cat's Salad Is Whisker-Lickin' Good  
   
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ When we ordered the artichoke and potato salad with
poached lemons at Black Cat, my friend couldn't quite accept the
fact that some one would actually eat a whole lemon _ peel, pith
and all.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But that's one of the highlights of this simply delicious salad
at the San Francisco restaurant celebrating the cuisines of four
cultures that come together on Broadway: Chinese, Italian, seafood
and the old-time Barbary Coast.
</P>
<P>
   For the salad, chef Reed Hearon cooks small fingerling potatoes
and sets them aside. Then he cooks artichokes and lemons together,
adding potatoes during the last minute to reheat. The ingredients
are drained, then lightly coated with a simple vinaigrette made
from olive oil and the warm juices from one of the poached lemons.
It's simple yet delicious.
</P>
<P>
   The most time-consuming task is preparing the artichokes. They
must be trimmed and stored in lemon water so they won't discolor
before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Hearon, who also owns Rose Pistola, opened the Black Cat in
1998, but it looks as if it has been there for years. At no other
restaurant in the city can you find a delicious tea-smoked duck, a
raw seafood bar, steaming chowders, a thick steak for four and a
veal chop Milanese all on the same menu. It's a smorgasbord of
flavors, but the simplicity of the warm salad celebrates the best
of California freshness.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Black Cat, 501 Broadway (at Kearny), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 981-2233. Lunch and dinner daily.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bauer is The Chronicle's food editor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM: &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
THE SECRETS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The ingredients. &LR;  The combination of creamy potatoes, artichoke
hearts and lemons is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Poaching the lemon.  &LR; Cooking takes away much of the bitterness
from the skin and pith, so you can eat the whole fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BLACK CAT'S WARM ARTICHOKE, POTATO &AMP; POACHED LEMON SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
4 lemons
</P>
<P>
   4 medium artichokes
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 small fingerling potatoes
</P>
<P>
   8 parsley sprigs, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large mixing bowl with cold tap water and add the juice
of 1 lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Working with 1 artichoke at a time, remove the leaves and pare
the woody stem with a vegetable peeler. Cut the heart (with stem)
in half lengthwise and scoop out the fuzzy choke. Immediately place
the artichoke heart halves in the bowl of acidulated water. This
keeps them from discoloring.
</P>
<P>
   Bring large pot of generously salted water to a boil. Drain the
artichoke hearts and add them, along with the remaining 3 lemons to
the boiling water. Simmer until the artichokes are tender, about 20
minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, simmer the potatoes in a generous amount of salted
water until they are tender. Drain, peel if desired, and cut in
half lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the warm potatoes, artichoke hearts and the parsley in a
serving bowl. Cut each lemon in half. Add 4 of the halves to the
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze the juice from the remaining 2 halves into the olive
oil. Season with salt and pepper and stir to emulsify. Pour this
vinaigrette over the vegetables and toss gently to coat. Add more
salt and pepper, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the component parts equally among salad plates.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 265 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 35 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 14 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 83 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 6 g fiber. &LR;  2mn!ZHZfE3{
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
