<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU LIGHT UP MY LIFE _ OR JUST MY SHOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What makes the lights in tennis shoes light up _ batteries or
chemicals?
</P>
<P>
   _ T.N.
</P>
<P>
   A: The light comes from a watch-type battery, said David Gatto,
chief executive officer of L.A. Gear.
</P>
<P>
   The battery is encased in a temperature-resistant epoxy that is
activated with motion. ``Picture a can with a wire inside,'' Gatto
said. ``The wire vibrates and touches the inside of the can,
completing the circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   The shoe's batteries normally last about four to six months.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Gear introduced the first lighted shoe in 1992. ``It was an
instant success,'' Gatto said. First popular with older children
and teen-agers, the customers are now ``decidedly below age 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many others died in the Audie Murphy plane crash of May
28, 1971?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.D., North Richland Hills, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Murphy, 46, was traveling in a twin-engine plane with four
business associates when it crashed into a mountain near Roanoke,
Va. All five were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The war hero and actor was flying from Atlanta to Martinsville,
Va., to visit a manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, several groups have led efforts to commemorate
Murphy, the most decorated combat soldier of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   A fan club was begun in 1995 by Stan Smith. For more
information, write to Audie Murphy National Fan Club, 8313 Snug
Hill Lane, Potomac, MD 20854-4057. There's also a World Wide Web
site about his accomplishments at www.audiemurphy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get the music from ``Star Trek Voyager''?
</P>
<P>
   _ V.P., Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A: GNP/Crescendo Records has released soundtracks for ``Star
Trek Voyager'' and many other science-fiction TV shows and films.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 ``Voyager'' CD sells for $12.95 on CD and $6.95 on
cassette.
</P>
<P>
   To request a catalog, write to GNP/Crescendo Records, 8480-A
Sunset Blvd., Hollywood, CA 90069; or call (323) 656-2614.
</P>
<P>
   You can order the ``Voyager'' CD over the World Wide Web by
visiting www.gnpcrescendo.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
