<HEADLINE>
RUDYARD KIPLING'S ROUSING STORIES DESERVE REVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A capricious editor suggested that I deliver a regular column on
books that are acknowledged as classics or ought to be. Almost 10
years and 500 entries later, I've begun repeating myself.
</P>
<P>
   Very soon after the advent of this series, readers assumed I
have read every truly notable book and am keen on every
distinguished author. Far from it, and I'm often at a loss for
responding to requests for producing essays on authors whose works
I've never investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Zweig, for example. I've obtained an English translation
of ``Beware of Pity,'' and when I get around to reading it, I may
be able to say something about Zweig, who to me has been only
another foreign name.
</P>
<P>
   Or George Sand. Have I even ``seen'' any of her books?
</P>
<P>
   Or Rex Beach. I've read none of his chest-pounding bestsellers
of yore but probably could fake an essay on the strength of having
watched three of the five (!) movie versions of ``The Spoilers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still they ask, and often I comply _ with a consideration of
Stephen Vincent Benet, for example, or a valentine to Rebecca West.
Frequently I'm asked to write about an author or book that was
covered before the reader in question caught up with the series. Do
Faulkner, they say, or Poe or Mark Twain or Edith Wharton.
</P>
<P>
   The champion, though, is Rudyard Kipling.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no longer surprised when someone asks me to commit a Kipling
tribute, because it happens so often. Some years back, I devoted a
column to ``Kim'' and supposed that took care of Kipling, with
whose work _ poetry, fiction, tales for children _ I was familiar
partially but not comprehensively. In recent years I've read more
of his good stuff, reacting to all those requests.
</P>
<P>
   Rudyard Kipling (1865-1936), an India-bred Briton, certainly is
popular with American readers, although I haven't figured if he's
popular ``still'' or popular ``again.''
</P>
<P>
   In his writing prime he was the most beloved writer throughout
the world since Dickens, and in 1907 he became the first British
author awarded the Nobel Prize in literature. But his reputation
plummeted in his own lifetime, then continued its descent
posthumously. Anti-Kipling sentiment may have been political
primarily, when it became fashionable to scorn Kipling as apologist
for English imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   That Kipling has staged a comeback isn't argued. Recent critical
revaluation is positive, but lay readers are the constituency that
has brought all of his writings back into print.
</P>
<P>
   He's a man's writer. Men are captivated by the rough
colloquialism of the ``Barrack-Room Ballads'' (''Danny Deever,''
``Gunga Din'' et al.), although Kipling is on occasion a competent
lyric poet to please women.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a writer for boys, rather than generally a writer for
children. The ``Just So'' stories for younger children may not
favor a gender, but the ``Jungle Books'' and ``Captains
Courageous'' and ``Kim'' were consciously crafted for the male
adolescent reader. Because they are not ``written down'' to their
intended audience, adults also enjoy these rousing adventures.
</P>
<P>
   A charge against Kipling was that he couldn't, and therefore
didn't, write ``adult'' fiction; and his biographers generally
agree that he wrote ``The Light That Failed'' as a rebuttal. It's a
good enough novel with a valid tragic hero, but it misses greatness
for seeming padded. One could believe it might have been one of
Kipling's marvelous stories, which tend to be longer than most
short stories and contain enough elements to stock a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Kipling's genius for economical storytelling has never been
questioned. He is an absolute master of the long short story,
exemplified by ``The Man Who Would Be King.'' In a Kipling tale
something is always happening or is about to. He's a writer to stir
real heart-thumping excitement in the reader.
</P>
<P>
   One might suppose he was a happy man. He wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor emitus for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
