<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-MOVIE-BOS &LR;      02-23 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MOVIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE FILM'S BATTLE FOR THE FRENCH CINEMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The French may be eternally grateful to the US soldiers
who took part in the invasion of Normandy, but some are less
enthusiastic about the Hollywood invasion.
</P>
<P>
   For years, some French, especially cultural purists, have
bemoaned the pervasiveness of American culture, and have reserved
particular scorn for Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural commentators complain that the steady rise of the
number of Hollywood films is not only dumbing down French audiences
but is also endangering an indigenous film industry regarded as the
last vibrant and independent one in Europe. Despite those warnings,
French moviegoers are voting with their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Paris, where the cinematograph was invented a century ago, is
more than the birthplace of the cinema. It is widely considered the
capital of film appreciation. But the type of film the French
appreciate is changing. Movie attendance in France rose last year
dramatically, from 150 million to 175 million, but the audience for
French films shrunk from 51 million to 44 million.
</P>
<P>
   A French film, ``Le Diner de Cons'' (loosely translated as the
Dinner of Idiots'') was the second highest-grossing film last year;
selling 8 million tickets. But the gap between it and the American
blockbuster, ``Titanic,'' which sold 20 million tickets, seemed to
capture the fortunes of the competing film industries.
</P>
<P>
   All of this explains why this month's release of a film called
``Asterix and Obelix versus Caesar'' has taken on David and Goliath
proportions. With a budget of about $45 million, it is the most
expensive French film ever made.
</P>
<P>
   It stars the French icon, Gerard Depardieu, and includes cameo
appearances by many contemporary French stars. The hype surrounding
the film, meanwhile, seems to underscore French anxiety over the
erosion of their culture.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on the exploits of French cartoon characters
that were created in the 1950s in response to an invasion of
American and British imports, which, at the time, were accused of
diluting the cultural distinction of French cartoons. The cartoon
series is wildly popular, having sold some 280 million comic books
in 77 countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the live-action film, Obelix and Asterix and their friends in
a tiny French village fend off Roman invaders by drinking a magic
potion that gives them superhuman powers.
</P>
<P>
   Some cultural purists have suggested it is patriotic duty not
only to see the film, but to like it. Albert Uderzo, who with
collaborator Rene Goscinny created the cartoon characters on which
the film is based, was blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new film has to sink the Titanic,'' he said. ``French
pride is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   But others suggest intellecutal honesty is a French virtue that
trumps pride, and French critics have displayed ample quantities,
dismissing the film as much ado about nothing. The consensus among
critics is that the movie, unlike the cartoon strip, is not funny,
and that the best performance comes not from the hulking Depardieu,
who plays Obelix, but from the scrawny Italian actor Roberto
Benigni as the devious Detritus, who steals the potion and the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Bercoff, film critic for France-Soir, explained the
ambivalence that tinged many honest assessments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like high treason to say it, an attack against the
very heart of the nation, a crime worthy of court martial and
execution by firing squad, but I have to confess: after a few
minutes, I was royally bored by this film,'' he said. ``Nobody
applauded and a few people whistled because it was so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Parisien, which gave the film two out of five stars, was even
more blunt: ``It isn't funny. The actors play themselves. The
special effects are old hat. Big stars don't necessarily make for a
good film.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Figaro, which is among the most nationalistic of newspapers,
still had to ask: ``With all this sumptuousness, this respect for
detail, this stunning cast, these extraordinary settings, with this
whole marvellous spectacle that three generations have waited
impatiently to see, one question remains: why doesn't it work
better?''
</P>
<P>
   While the critics hate it, the French public is more
enthusiastic. In its first week, the film broke the French weekly
attendance record, selling 2.7 million tickets. By the end of last
week it had sold a total of 4.3 million. Claude Berri, the film's
producer, said the film needs to sell 5 million tickets to break
even, and hopes to sell 10 million, a goal that seems easily
reachable. Whether it can eclipse the record set last year by
``Titanic'' is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing the critics, Depardieu defends the movie as being
rooted in the tradition of distinctive French filmmaking. But even
he agrees the French film industry is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' he said, ``is most producers are stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
