<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN24-CO     02-23 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Flooded with memories of summer
storms
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share, via Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray,
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Leslie Ann Clark
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   When you've grown up in Oklahoma's Tornado Alley, you're
accustomed to dangerous weather, and if you are forced to go
without it, you really miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Like the plants in my yard in the D.C. suburb where I now live,
I, too, begin to wither and dry up.
</P>
<P>
   I call my parents when I see on the Weather Channel that it's
raining back home, and they stand on the back patio, holding the
phone up to the aluminum awning for me to hear the pitter-patter of
the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes if I'm real lucky, I even get to hear a long roll of
thunder in the background. I sit listening to the crackle of the
cordless phone and I'm transported back in time ...
</P>
<P>
   I can remember stepping off the faded yellow school bus into the
hot Oklahoma sun. As I crossed the street and headed home, the wind
started to pick up, blowing my hair into my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Dead leaves scurried across the street, like the other kids
hurrying for home. Sometimes the wind would be so strong that bits
of sand would sting my bare legs.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the corner onto my street and facing west, I could see
the most glorious sight there is to see in the springtime: Huge,
white cumulus clouds billowing up into the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   I stood dumbstruck staring at the swirling concoction. The tops
boiled and bubbled, reaching higher and higher into the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Just when I thought it couldn't grow any bigger, I'd hear a low
rumble in the distance and see a flash of light from deep within
the cloud.
</P>
<P>
   The wind turned sharply cooler and, taking a deep breath, I
could smell the sweet, clean rain before it fell.
</P>
<P>
   Running home, I witnessed the sky quickly turning a deep
black-blue. Soon the darkness was illuminated with lightning
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   I watched as the strikes made a path to the ground, uniting
heaven and earth for one brief moment and then releasing. Thunder
soon followed, and the process repeated more quickly each time.
</P>
<P>
   I'd count the seconds between the lightning and thunder to
compute the distance of the storm. Kid meteorology 101.
</P>
<P>
   The willow tree in my front yard swayed to and fro like an old
lady stretching in the morning, bending and twisting on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   As I threw my books onto the front porch, I felt the first bit
of rain, big drops that hit so hard they splattered a good 2 inches
across your bare leg.
</P>
<P>
   I stood in the driveway with my eyes closed, head tilted back
and mouth open, letting the rain wet my lips, teeth and tongue. The
drops hit with a thud on my head, harder and harder, until I
couldn't stand it any longer.
</P>
<P>
   I ran to the safety of the indoors and, with my wet face pressed
against the picture window in our living room, stood and watched
the miracle take place.
</P>
<P>
   First the flower beds filled. Puddles formed around the trees.
Soon a river was sweeping down the edges of the street, taking
twigs and leaves and everything in its path down the gutters.
</P>
<P>
   When rain began to let up, that was my signal to grab the
umbrella and rush outside for an afternoon of play.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting to no one in particular, I ran barefoot to the tiny
river in the street. The rain chilled my toes. Pebbles and sand,
rushed along by the current, swept over the tops of my feet.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm ceased, the sky would turn the most ominous
color, a greenish-yellow, as the sun struggled to make its way
through the clouds -- and then, so gold it almost hurt your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   As the world returned to normal, I'd see it, a beautiful rainbow
forming over the western sky -- red, orange, yellow, green, blue
and purple arching above the rooftops of my neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly kids and dogs would make their way outside into the
street for the last hour of play for the day ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear that one, Leslie?'' my mom yelled into the phone
as the rain pounded the roof and nearly drowned out her voice.
``That was a good one! I just wish you were here to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm already there, Mom. And I can see it all.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Ann Clark lives in Olney, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
