<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5878 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUTRITION-COACH-HNS &LR;      02-23 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTRITION-COACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIET IS PART OF WINNING STRATEGY FOR DENVER BRONCOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in sports, ``s,'' and lifestyle, ``l,'' category)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Four hours before a football game, Denver
Broncos' quarterback John Elway would eat eggs, potatoes and
ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just likes it,'' team nutritionist Jackie Berning said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Berning won't take credit for Elway's performance
during last month's Super Bowl, when the Broncos beat the Atlanta
Falcons 34-19, she made sure he and his teammates ate well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two Super Bowl wins came when we started feeding the
Broncos breakfast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Berning, like many mothers, is a big believer in the power of
food.
</P>
<P>
   As nutrition coach for several professional teams, including the
Broncos, the Denver Nuggets, the Cleveland Indians and the Colorado
Rockies, she credits a balanced diet for laying the foundation for
good health, fitness and peak athletic performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing to me is people fuel their cars better than
they fuel their bodies,'' said Berning, who has been working with
the Broncos for 15 years and is a spokeswoman for the American
Dietetic Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people show up at the office with no fuel in the
tank?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And having no energy or feeling too tired are two of the biggest
excuses people give for not exercising, according to a recent
national survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't always think of their diet as a reason they lack
energy,'' said Dr. Kristine Clark, director of sports nutrition at
Pennsylvania State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right foods, such as eggs, whole grains, fruits,
vegetables and dairy products, can help fuel energy and give that
extra push needed to get up and exercise, whether you are a serious
athlete or just trying to stay in shape,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Essman of Guilderland, N.Y., makes her living, in part,
through exercise, and can't afford to run out of energy. Some days,
she teaches three exercise classes with appointments in between as
a personal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find I have to have a lot of energy,'' said Essman, who owns
Janet's Personal Workout, a fitness training company. ``I don't
think there's any magic formula. I don't drink any potions or eat
special bars. I eat food.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's a good menu for energy? According to the American
Dietetic Association, carbohydrates are the main source of fuel for
working muscles. That's why foods high in carbohydrates should
comprise at least 60 percent of the calories in an athlete's menu.
</P>
<P>
   Good food choices include breads, grains, fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   But when you eat is just as important as what you eat.
</P>
<P>
   If you work out in the morning, Clark recommends eating a
scrambled egg with vegetables and whole wheat toast, one to two
hours before.
</P>
<P>
   If you exercise after work, she suggests taking a 4 p.m. break
to eat chicken salad on whole wheat bread, a hard boiled egg,
low-fat sports bar or yogurt with fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Back to breakfast, Berning believes most people will do better
even if they just grab a banana before heading out the door.
</P>
<P>
   People who are running on empty are easy to spot. ``Their head
is bobbing at their desk and they have trouble staying awake,''
Berning said.
</P>
<P>
   Other snacks for energy include: 12 ounces of orange juice, one
cup of grapes and one bagel, low-fat vegetable soup with a pita
pocket, and a low-fat muffin with a cup of skim milk.
</P>
<P>
   Essman likes to munch on fruit and pretzels during an especially
busy day. She also makes a point of washing down her meals and
snacks with plenty of water: ``A lot of people are fatigued because
they don't drink enough water,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to Berning, the Broncos don't hit the field until
they have eaten breakfast at team headquarters. ``It's a
continental breakfast, low-fat muffins, fruit juice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative _ running on an empty stomach and no fuel _
feels like slamming into a brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Broncos say, `I'm going to be a hurtin' unit,'''
Berning said.
</P>
</TEXT>
