<HEADER>
A5879 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-23 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE IN ANGER THAN IN SORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a year well supplied with deplorable behavior, Dan
Caccavaro wondered if the word _ at least in its verb form _ hadn't
expanded beyond its statutory limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, the word suggests an emotion that is
ongoing, like hate or love, as in `I deplore bigotry,' he wrote.
``But politicians use the word as a synonym for denounce, a verb
that denotes an action'' _ deploring the actions of Saddam Hussein,
for example. ``Is this a correct use?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   I hoped it was, since I too have used deplore to mean
``denounce.'' And as it turns out, Caccavaro was on to something:
Deplore has changed its tune to suit 20th-century tastes, but so
gradually and stealthily that few have noticed, much less objected.
</P>
<P>
   Deplore originates with the Latin deplorare, to bewail, weep
bitterly, mourn, and its English connotation, for centuries, was
primarily regret, not anger. A 1642 reference to ``our deplorable
brethren and neighbours'' describes people in a wretched condition,
the sinned against rather than the sinners. But it's not hard to
lament and condemn in the same breath, and Samuel Johnson, author
of the famous 1775 dictionary, noted that deplorable was
``sometimes, in a more lax and jocular sense, used for
contemptible; despicable: as, deplorable nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   The denunciatory flavor seems to have stayed in the background,
though, till our century. In the '50s and '60s, a few usage
arbiters noticed the waning of the primary meaning: Theodore
Bernstein, for example, notes in 1965 the growing ``undertone of
disapproval'' in deplore. ``To say that `The President deplored the
tactics of Congress' is to say not only that he regretted them but
also that he frowned upon them.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently we live in a time more fond of denunciation than
lamentation, though deplore still often conveys both senses. And
neither meaning of the word is restricted to an ongoing condition:
You can't deplore a person, but you can deplore either a single
event or a permanent situation _ or both, on a really bad day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Captive audience
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing many local readers have deplored is the former wording
of donor credits on WBUR-FM in Boston _ ``Listeners support us,
along with (company name),'' they used to say, as if the listeners
were paying the sponsors. The revised version should please critics
_ ``We're funded by you, our listeners, and by (increasingly long
list of company names),'' is the new formulation. But the
transition wasn't entirely smooth: One January morning we woke to
hear ``We're funded by you, our prisoners'' _ an apt description,
some spouses might say, of us morning-to-midnight public radio
junkies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the shocking language news came from Tyco, whose
Sing and Snore Ernie, the talking Muppet, was programmed to say
``It feels good to lay down.'' This year, it's Ty Inc., creator of
the Beanie menagerie, that goofed, giving birth on Jan. 1 to
Millenium the misspelled bear. Ernie's grammar was corrected in
subsequent production runs, and given the depth of Beanie madness,
a similar fix in Ty's Millenium bug could make the single-n version
one hot teddy. Get him now, Beanie believers, before the fatal
correction comes. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Ann Landers also blundered in a recent column, printing a letter
that demanded a ban on the phrase rule of thumb, claiming it
derived from an English ruling allowing a man to beat his wife with
a stick no thicker than his thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Word writers have worked hard over the past few years to correct
this language legend, and you'd think Ann's staff might have
checked it before serving it up to millions of readers. The true
story isn't simple, but rule of thumb was being used to mean
``rough guide'' a century before Judge Francis Buller, in 1782,
issued his controversial guideline for wife-beating. And it wasn't
called a rule of thumb: Neither the judge nor the outraged public
used the phrase in connection with the case. It was only in the
1970s that the (erroneous) link between spousal abuse and rule of
thumb was embraced. (For a more complete history, and other verbal
entertainments, see Jesse Sheidlower's Web site at
www.randomhouse.com/jesse/.)
</P>
<P>
   As for Ann Landers, she gets nine lashes with a wet ziti _ no
bigger than her thumb, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
