<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      02-23 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX PROSPECT CHO HAS A MAJOR LEAGUE MSSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ He wore the uniform at Fenway Park on the
Fourth of July, when he became the first from his country to pitch
for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was Christmas in Korea, the day of Jin Ho Cho's
homecoming, and he put on the uniform again. This time, he was
standing at the grave of the father who had died seven months
earlier, when his son was on the other side of the world. Promise
me, the father had told his family as he lay dying of cancer, that
you won't tell my son until he comes back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I win my first game in the big leagues,'' Jin Ho Cho
whispered at his father's grave, ``I will dedicate it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Heartbreak requires no translation. Between Cho's halting
English, and the hollow expression in his eyes, there was no
mistaking the sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe my dream, to be a major league baseball player,'' Cho
said here  &UR; Monday &LR;   &UR; afternoon &LR; , sitting on a folding chair in an
empty clubhouse where only memories echoed off the walls. ``My
father say, `Cho, don't tell him.' Me? Not happy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was about to board a plane for home in Los Angeles, where he
had been enrolled in intensive English classes, when a Korean
reporter approached and asked about his father's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `He's still living, what are you talking
about?' '' said Sangyeol Moon, the LA-based correspondent for The
Daily Sports Seoul, who was here  &UR; Monday &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   When he landed in Korea, Cho said, an older brother was there to
meet him, and confirmed that his father was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father died in May, on May 31,'' Cho said.
</P>
<P>
   He died just several days after Cho had been summoned to Trenton
from Single A Sarasota to pitch for the Red Sox in an exhibition
against their Double A farm club. Cho pitched well that night, and
when the Sox were short a starting pitcher in July, general manager
Dan Duquette called up Cho, who became one of the few pitchers ever
to reach the big leagues in his first season of professional
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, he had been pitching for Korea University. Now
he was facing Frank Thomas and Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Korea University, I saw Frank Thomas on TV,'' Cho said.
``Good hitter. Albert Belle, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Cho spoke so little English that pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan bought an English-Korean dictionary and communicated with
him by pulling out a Daffy Duck sketch pad and drawing pictures.
Cho distinguished himself, allowing just one run in six innings,
but he wound up taking the loss in a 3-0 Red Sox defeat.
</P>
<P>
   He would make three more starts for the Red Sox, with
diminishing results each time, before being sent back to Trenton.
He went 0-3 with a no-decision and an 8.20 ERA in four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came back to Trenton,'' said Ralph Treuel, who was the
Thunder's pitching coach and now is Boston's minor league pitching
coordinator, ``you could see he was emotionally worn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like he'd lost a little bit of his edge. He'd been
humbled a little bit at the major league level, and I think he'd
gotten a little tired. His stuff wasn't there like it was before.
We shut him down to give him time to recoup. You could see he was
exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Cho began last season in extended spring training and changed
teams faster than some teammates changed undershirts, advancing to
Sarasota and Trenton before receiving the summons from Boston and
the subsequent return ticket to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost like being traded four times,'' Treuel said.
``New towns, new teammates. Physically and emotionally, that's a
whirlwind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Cho if he was scared or nervous when he arrived in the big
leagues, and you cannot be certain he understands the question,
even while pantomiming wiping your brow. His answer? ``No,'' he
said. ``Not scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning to Trenton, Cho finally had a chance to settle
into the business of learning America. He lived with teammates John
Barnes and Jim Chamblee, and the other pitchers in the Thunder
rotation _ guys like Paxton Crawford and Jack Cressend and Robert
Ramsey _ made it a point to befriend him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a likable guy,'' Treuel said. ``The guys took him in
with open arms. They told me stories about taking him to Denny's,
and how much he would eat. He had a huge appetite.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Cho about Trenton and he says, ``Everybody my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   His agents, Steve Schneider and Gus Dominguez, had a
Korean-American law student, Kenneth Yoo, working as an intern. Yoo
stayed in regular contact with Cho, sending him the latest Korean
CDs from LA, where they're much easier to find than in Boston or
Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very frugal,'' Yoo said. ``Most of his money, he sends
home to his family in Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   Cho has discovered some native pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch American TV,'' Cho said. ``ESPN, baseball games. I
like action movies. `Braveheart.' Mel Gibson. `Lethal Weapon.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He has a friend in fellow Korean pitcher Sun Woo Kim, who spent
last season in Sarasota. They attended instructional league
together, and also studied English together in a school in LA.
</P>
<P>
   Where once it was rare to see a smile, Cho's face now will light
up in recognition. When a minor league coach called out ``Cho!'' in
passing, Cho responded, ``What's up?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the quicker he can become adapted to the culture here,
the quicker he'll make it back to the major leagues,'' Treuel said.
</P>
<P>
   Few in the Sox organization have questions about his ability,
although he'll almost certainly start this season in Triple A
Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's definitely got major league stuff,'' said Treuel,
citing a fastball that Cho throws in the low 90s, as well as a
slider and a changeup that remains a work in progress. ``It's just
a matter of time, and a matter of need on the major league club.''
</P>
<P>
   Cho expects to return. ``I want to go back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has a promise to keep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
