<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JILTED BY DEMOCRATS, AFTER ALL BOSTON HAS DONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So Hollywood, not history, is expected to provide the backdrop
for the 2000 Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   That choice _ which should become official after contract
details are finalized _ says something about Al Gore. The reaction
here says something even more about Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The convention city was viewed locally as Gore's to choose. Last
week, the vice president called Mayor Menino to tell him the big
party would be in LA, not Beantown. The mayor was mad and let Gore
know it. Hell hath no fury like a Menino scorned.
</P>
<P>
   After all we've done, Menino fumed, what does Boston get? The
cold shoulder from Gore _ and charges of systemic discrimination in
the city's public housing from Andy Cuomo, as Menino likes to call
the secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   This city worked hard to pitch itself, and for once the public
and private sectors worked well as a team.
</P>
<P>
   But is that really so surprising, given the stakes? What city
could possibly be more willing than Boston to open its arms, its
wallets, and its prime vacation spots to the Oval Office?
</P>
<P>
   We have opened all of that and more to Bill Clinton. Throughout
his presidency, we have been his enablers _ a city filled with
Hillarys. When he lies, we forgive him. When others shun him, we
race to pose for photographs with him. Degraded, disgraced, it
doesn't matter. He scurries to the Kennedy Library, gives us that
misty squint, and we swoon. When he leaves, he takes our money with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential power is not just an aphrodisiac for sloe-eyed
White House interns or long-suffering White House wives. It seduces
the men and women of this city over and over again. Trying to
replicate a moment in history, still golden in our minds _ remember
Jack! _ we clutch at one candidate after another.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton Boston found a winner and a soul mate. In victory we
could celebrate the triumph of our great cause and the influence
and access that comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Here, you pay to play, a game well understood and skillfully
executed by Clinton, Gore, and the Democratic National Committee.
This city cheerfully poured millions into the party coffers. Just
this month, at a post-impeachment event to ``honor'' Newton
resident and retiring DNC chairman Steven Grossman, die-hard donors
raised $700,000 for the Democratic party. About 80 people paid
$10,000 each for a lunch of sea bass, mixed green salad, and
marscapone pastry with strawberries. Another 500 guests settled for
a reception with chicken Caesar salad and assorted cookies for $250
per person.
</P>
<P>
   The president raised Menino's hopes when he supposedly mused
during their ride from the airport, ``It all began here . . .
Bunker Hill, the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a foolish older woman who refuses to see the truth in the
mirror, we believed the lines thrown our way. Boston was in the
running. Los Angeles was making mistakes. Clinton and Gore knew who
their friends were and where they lived. The vice president could
forget about the Big Dig, the new convention center still in the
fantasizing stage, the dearth of hotel rooms, and, most of all, the
big political prize in California _ 54 electoral votes. He would go
with history and grit, not Hollywood and glitz.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he didn't. Gore went with the convention city choice
backed by conventional wisdom. And that makes sense, because he is,
according to conventional wisdom, the Democratic Party nominee and,
quite possibly, the next president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is the man to beat, at least as long as the economy holds.
Like Walter Mondale, he is the establishment candidate. On paper he
has every every advantage, every benefit, and he is nailing down
every bit of money. But sometimes you can become captive to all the
strengths you bring to the table. Money can buy consultants and
advertising; it cannot buy hearts. And heart still counts for
something even in a political world that is mostly about handing
over bags of campaign contributions _ doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, like everywhere else, politics is now an affair of
the pocketbook. But here it also still remains an affair of the
heart. So the risk-averse Gore takes a risk in ignoring his New
England romance. We thought we had a relationship!
</P>
<P>
   There is still a long way to go before he wears the crown of
party nominee. Those he crosses may not be able to knock the crown
off, but they can surely dent it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Menino says he is not just disappointed that Gore
overlooked Boston for the 2000 Democratic National Convention. He
is also distressed that the vice president decided to pick a locale
associated with Monica Lewinsky _ the woman with whom Clinton
didn't have ``sexual relations,'' just sex _ and the Buddhist
temple, where Gore attended a fund-raiser he didn't know was a
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
