</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK HAS ROGER...AND SO WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm trying to picture the Rocket waltzing into Manhattan's
Lespinasse and paying $35 for a foie gras appetizer that's half the
size of a flattened Slim Jim at Bayou Mama's. Or having some
snot-nosed 28-year-old investment banker from Goldman Sachs tell
him at the communal table at Asia de Cuba that he made twice as
much money in his year-end bonus than Roger Clemens made all of
last year, and he never had to break a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The point here is that this city's angst, its hand-wringing, its
collective tantrum over the Clemens-Yankees marriage is much ado
about hardly anything at all. We have descended into despair, but
the real reason is simple: Boston has become a city of
Manhattanphiles, a people constantly wrestling with our own obvious
sense of inferiority.
</P>
<P>
   You'll recall what comedian Fred Allen once said. ``I just
returned from Boston. It's the only thing to do if you find
yourself up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny guy, that Mr. Allen, and a Bostonian to boot. Funniest
part is, he speaks to the fears of a city that regards itself as
the backward little cousin of our suave and sophisticated relative
down the street, New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bostonian-turned-New Yorker Bill Bratton explains it another
way. The former police commissioner of both cities, Bratton comes
along Monday to make a declaration anathema to most men: Size does
matter. In New York, you can influence national change, garner
national publicity, become a national figure. In Boston, he leaves
unstated, the people of southern New Hampshire might see you on the
local news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is more questioning of itself than New York,'' Bratton
added. ``Boston is much more of an introspective place. New York
never questions itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Question ourselves? Us? What was it that happened when the
Toronto Blue Jays made a trade with the New York Yankees last week
that had absolutely nothing to do with the Boston Red Sox? We just
about drowned in our own inferiority. The Yankees got our goat once
again, they did. They stole the Babe. Bucky Dent hit one into the
net. And now they've got our Roger, even if he wasn't really ours
anymore. What a pathetic little province we've become when the
Yankees can lord Roger Clemens. Right?
</P>
<P>
   But what's wrong with this picture? As sports sage Will
McDonough points out, the trade is meaningless to the Red Sox. The
Yankees will win the AL East with or without Roger Clemens. It's
the wild card we're playing for now. So this isn't about baseball,
but perceptions, our own fears. We are frightened that we've become
nothing more than a silly little outpost, a place where whispy
Brahmin men wear brown loafers with blue suits as they call
corporate headquarters in Manhattan twice a day to find out how
much more of the budget has been cut.
</P>
<P>
   Does Charlotte feel this way about Atlanta? San Francisco about
Los Angeles? Portland, Oregon, about Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   Take a hard look at Bosotn and New York. Both have
Italian-American mayors. Well, theirs speaks English as if it's his
native tongue. So forget that.
</P>
<P>
   And true, New York has Fortune 500 companies. It dominates the
worlds of art and music. It has eclipsed Boston as a publishing
center. Hell, The New York Times even bought this newspaper, and a
shopping conglomerate changed the name of Jordan Marsh to Macy's.
What's left for us?
</P>
<P>
   Well, try livability. As Boston financier and author John
Spooner points out, ``Your worst day in six months in Boston is
like every day in New York. You just have to laugh in terms of who
you have to duke. You can't walk a block without someone's hand
out.''
</P>
<P>
   People pay more to garage their car on the Upper East Side than
most Bostonians pay for rent. Commuters from Connecticut ride the
train 90 minutes each way and regard themselves as lucky. An
exquisitely mediocre steak at Smith &AMP; Wollensky's runs upwards of
$30 per cut.
</P>
<P>
   And try compassion. New York is the largest, loneliest city in
the country. They have Howard Stern. We're blessed, in comparison,
with the likes of Howie Carr. Yes, they have Dan Rather and Tom
Brokaw, but we have Chet and Nat, and for good and for bad, isn't
that really what it's all about?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they have Roger Clemens and we are left with our
nagging sense of inferiority, which is, in effect, our sense of
self. Boston is not New York. It doesn't want to be New York. But
it hesitates at being too different. Perhaps it's better that Roger
is there. There will come a day soon when he wishes he was back
here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
