<HEADER>
A5891 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURER-BOS &LR;      02-23 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST TREASURER ACCUSTOMED TO BODY BLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While former Massachusetts state treasurer Joseph
Malone was all too willing to tout his days as a football player at
Harvard, few voters know that his successor was an Ivy League
football player, too.
</P>
<P>
   Only she played without a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon O'Brien, who took over as treasurer last month, played
on the Yale women's rugby team, and was captain of the women's
soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents never imposed gender roles on me or my siblings,''
O'Brien said. ``I never thought about not doing sports, though I
have to admit rugby was a challenge. As a halfback, I was chased a
lot. But I ran fast because I was very scared. I think I was the
only member of the team who didn't get bloodied.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien also appears unlikely to get bloodied in a scandal in
the treasurer's office revealed just last week: Investigators
arrested a 20-year employee and an associate for allegedly trying
to steal $6.5 million from the Unclaimed Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The new treasurer, in office a little more than a month, hopes
the purported embezzlement will help her persuade lawmakers to let
her go forward with one of her major goals: a full-blown audit of
the treasury and lottery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, 39, is the first woman to be elected to statewide
office without being part of a ticket or a special election. The
distinction is reflected even in her nonpolitical life.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien and her husband, former lawmaker Emmet Hayes, receive
cards addressed to ``Treasurer and Mrs. O'Brien.'' Recently, Hayes
was shopping in a local grocery store when another shopper pointed
him out as he piled food into his cart. ``Oh, look,'' she said to
her companion. ``It's Shannon O'Brien's husband. I guess he does
all the home work now.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Boston University Law School, O'Brien was part of
an increasing chorus of women's voices on Beacon Hill when she
served in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as a member of former Senate president William M. Bulger's
leadership team, she was tagged with the ``old boy'' label in her
run for treasurer. After all, O'Brien comes from a long line of
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   As a lawmaker, O'Brien lived in Easthampton in Hampden County
and represented the western part of the state. When she married in
1996, she moved to Whitman with her husband and stepdaughter, Jill,
adding the South Shore to her political base.
</P>
<P>
   She has barely taken office, but already some are saying that in
four or eight years, O'Brien could be a strong gubernatorial
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could be a consensus candidate,'' said political
consultant Michael Goldman. ``Just look at who was with her on
stage the night she won the treasurer's race: Ted Kennedy was
there. Joe Moakley, too. For Democrats, it was the safest place to
be that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Goldman, that kind of talk is particularly
flattering. Five years ago, when he was the key strategist behind
former senator William Keating's ill-fated attempt to dethrone
Bulger, O'Brien criticized Goldman as a ``schmuck.'' Today, Goldman
shrugs off the insult as part of the normal rough and tumble of
state politics. ``Voting for O'Brien was the easiest vote I cast
this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of five children, O'Brien attended
Williston-Northampton high school, a private day school in
Easthampton, before heading to Yale University like her father
before her.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, of Irish and Polish heritage, seemed destined for a
career in politics. With her father, Edward O'Brien, on the
Governor's Council, her grandfather an aide to the late Governor
Paul Dever, and her great-grandfather Michael a state
representative, the O'Brien family has been called ``the Kennedys
of Western Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The family name is so well known that it's almost a brand name
in the western part of the state,'' said high school classmate
Paula Monopoli, a law professor in California. ``But she never
coasted on her name. She literally knocked on doors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen her intimidated by anything,'' marveled
Wendy Hill, who met O'Brien when the two were captains of opposing
soccer teams. ``She was an incredibly versatile player. And she's
like that off the field, too.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien spent eight years on Beacon Hill, serving three terms in
the House and one in the Senate from 1987 to 1994. Unlike some
other women before her, such as former Ways and Means chairwoman
Patricia McGovern and Senator Linda J. Melconian, O'Brien never
headed a major legislative committee. Appointed chairwoman of the
Senate's obscure steering and policy committee, which determines
when bills are taken up, she also served on the banking, labor,
insurance, and human services committees.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien sponsored several bills that became law, including one
that made child abuse a felony rather than a misdemeanor, a
whistleblower law that protects state employees who report fraud
and abuse in state government, and a measure that decreased
employee health care costs for cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   She supports abortion rights and opposes the death penalty _ the
opposite of her husband, whom she met when both were state
representatives. ``She used to call me a Neanderthal,'' Hayes
joked.
</P>
<P>
   After losing his reelection bid in 1990, Hayes became a
lobbyist. His clients include construction, environmental, and
transportation concerns, incuding the Boston Water and Sewer
Department. Since O'Brien's election as treasurer, Hayes has told
his clients he will not represent anyone with business before the
treasurer's office or lottery. ``We've gone further than the law
specifies because we don't even want the perception of any
conflict,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien first ran for treasurer in 1994, when Democratic leaders
recruited her to take on Malone, the popular Republican incumbent.
She was outspent nearly 4 to 1, and Malone walked to victory,
winning 63 percent of the vote. Still, O'Brien gained valuable
statewide contacts and name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   She worked as a health care executive for the next four years;
by night, she gathered political IOUs by running US Senator John F.
Kerry's record-breaking signature drive in his 1996 reelection
battle against then-Governor William F. Weld.
</P>
<P>
   Before she announced her second campaign for the treasurer's
office in 1997, O'Brien made a critical move: She convinced other
Democrats eyeing the race that she was the best candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearing the primary field was a really tough challenge, but
she did it,'' said former lieutenant governor Evelyn Murphy. ``It
let her focus all her energies on the final election. By being
willing to run once and lose, she was able to position herself as
the incumbent in the primary the second time around.''
</P>
<P>
   In the general election, O'Brien beat GOP businessman Robert
Maginn with 62 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   As treasurer, she plans to redirect the state's investment
strategy away from international equities and help establish
priorities for the state's long-term capital needs _ one of which
she believes should be upgrading public school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her reputation as a classic Beacon Hill insider, she
claims she will ``change the culture'' at the lottery, long viewed
as a hideaway for political hacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it, I have my work cut out for me,''
O'Brien said. And the job doesn't come with a helmet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
