<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-ESTRICH-ART-BO     02-23 1587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ESTRICH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTRICH ON ESTRICH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Estrich writes to understand her life.
</P>
<P>
   After she was raped at 21, she wrote a book about the legal
system. When she lost 50 pounds, she wrote a diet book. Now, the
smartest girl in class, the first female president of the Harvard
Law Review, the first woman to run a presidential campaign (for
Michael Dukakis) and the youngest woman to get tenure at Harvard
Law School, is writing about why women do not have more power.
</P>
<P>
   She is writing about herself. Estrich teaches law and has a
syndicated newspaper column. But she isalso a 46-year-old mother of
two. She is not a first anymore. She is just like countless other
women who edged out of the fast lane and into the car-pool line.
She makes peanut butter sandwiches and parses ce-real box text. She
counts calories.
</P>
<P>
   And on a recent afternoon she is arching her size-6 body proudly
in front of a hotel mirror, running her hands along her skin-tight
white jersey top and tiny pleated black skirt for a newspaper
photographer. She is doing this because she is on tour for the
paperback version of her diet book, ``Making the Case for Yourself:
A Diet Book for Smart Women.'' But what she is really doing, it
seems, is making a case for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am grappling with right now is seeing the men of my
generation assuming power in America and the women of my
generation, the women I went to law school with, the women I did
politics with, not. In a word,'' declares Estrich, in an interview
at a Boston hotel. ``You can't say any of the women are wrong. On
the contrary. I'm the one who told many of the women who worked for
me, `Whatever you do, don't miss children. Don't wait.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Estrich complaining about her lot. The woman who once
brandished political polls with pride now eagerly displays
photographs of her children, ages 5 and 8, and her husband, Marty
Kaplan, a communications professor. She works in her Los Angeles
home three days a week and teaches law at the University of
Southern California the other two days. At night, after the
children have gone to bed, she flips on some music and logs on to
the computer she used to write two books in the past year and a
half, the diet book and one about politics and criminal justice
called ``Getting Away With Murder,'' published last spring. They're
fine books, in their way. But they do not put her on the evening
news, where she used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her if she wants to work on a political campaign again, and
Estrich erupts in the hoarse boomlet of laughter that is her
trademark. She does not, not now, not even if it's a woman
candidate. What she wants is for women to have more flexibility.
She wants, in short, to alter the course of Western civilization so
that women can have productive, even first-string careers, and have
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all the justifications for why it is that the men who
used to work for me now run the world and I don't,'' declares
Estrich, throwing her hands in the air. ``Look, I'm happy. I'd
rather get up at 2 in the morning with a baby crying than (for) a
candidate in need of my assistance any day of the week. But we've
got to figure out the chapters of our lives. How are we gonna
change a system that gives us these either-or choices? How are we
going to get power on our terms?''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Estrich, a Lynn native, doesn't still
hang around some pretty powerful people. Just last week she spent
an hour talking to President Clinton in his office. (``I just
called up and said I'm going to be in town and can I come by?'')
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is a good friend. (``We used
to get excluded from all the same meetings together.'') And there
was that dance not long ago ``at Ben and Sally's'' with some of the
old political gang. She is talking, of course, about those famous
partygivers, former Washington Post editor Ben Bradlee and his
wife, writer Sally Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it mean that she does not travel, although she doesn't
do much. Last week she was completing a rare five-city promotional
tour for her diet book, which has already gone back to press two
times.
</P>
<P>
   Although Estrich has the look of a large person squeezed into a
thin person's body, and concedes that staying slender requires
constant vigilance, she looks trim and fit. Sitting in a plush
armchair at the Westin Copley Hotel in Boston, she talks
enthusiastically about a range of topics including her fertility
doctors, her three-day-a-week exercise program, and, of course,
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Monica Lewinsky had gone on my diet, maybe she wouldn't
have been on her knees so much,'' hoots Estrich.
</P>
<P>
   So, what is it with the diet book? Why is Susan Estrich, pioneer
thinker and firebrand feminist, pushing a list of ways to stay out
of the kitchen? (Do your nails. Seduce someone. Have sex repeatedly
and frequently, says the list distributed by her publisher.) Why is
Estrich, a frequent TV news commentator, talking about her thighs
and preening for a publicity photos in black mesh hose and a brief
black cocktail dress?
</P>
<P>
   Because for most of her adult life she could not. Because when
she went to the closet to get something to wear to the Democratic
National Convention in 1988, even her largest size 14s with elastic
waists did not fit. Because when several years and two babies later
she looked in the mirror and saw 170 pounds packed on her
five-foot-six-inch frame. Because she did not want to die of a
heart attack at 54 as her father did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it was vanity,'' says Estrich. ``But part of it was I
had these babies. Nothing, nothing grabbed my heart and held it so
strongly as looking at my babies. I needed to live.''
</P>
<P>
   And so at last, Estrich lost weight, about 50 pounds in all. And
then she wrote a book about it. Published last year, the book
offers no dieting miracle, but basically advises women to throw
away the excuses along with the Danish and commit themselves to the
job at hand: losing weight. And if feminists complain that Estrich
has sold out, that she's buying into male cliches of womanhood, let
`em.
</P>
<P>
   ``I notice the people who say that kind of thing are usually
naturally thin,'' Estrich notes archly. ``Dieting for me is an act
of feminism. It is an act of taking responsibility and taking
charge of my life. I was fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason she was fat, was because she was working so
hard. During the Dukakis campaign, Estrich traveled for months at a
time and routinely worked 100-hour weeks. Every night, she and
whoever else was still in the office near midnight would call out
for Chinese food so that, ``by the time of the convention I had
gained 25 pounds and we were ahead at that time,'' Estrich moans.
``Imagine what falling 20 points in the polls can do to your
weight. When the going gets tough, the tough start eating.''
</P>
<P>
   It is more than a decade since Estrich was plucked from her
professor's post at Harvard to become manager of Dukakis's troubled
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Estrich says she's smarter now than she was then, but ask what
is her newfound wisdom about Dukakis and a very long, very
uncharacteristic silence follows. She gazes out the window, eyes
her white-tipped fingernails. Although Estrich says she and Dukakis
remain friends and see one another occasionally, the failed
campaign is difficult for her to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was who I was. We all did our best. It was an awkward and
difficult situation,'' she says finally. ``I didn't have
(Dukakis's) confidence in the way I needed to have it. In politics,
you fight with somebody for a long time and you win some and you
lose some and by the end it's time for someone else to come in and
do battle.''
</P>
<P>
   If Estrich remains loyal to her former employer, she is also
loyal to another fellow Democrat who has come upon hard times.
Recalling that Bill Clinton used to call her nearly every night of
the 1988 campaign to get the poll numbers and offer his help,
Estrich said she supports the president because, ``He's my friend.
He's also the leader of my team, which stands for choice for women
and the things I believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrich doesn't just mean the choice to have an abortion. She
means the choice of having a real career as well as a family, and
the freedom to elect to do one without sacrificing the other. To
achieve that, Estrich argues that the rules of work need to be
restructured to provide greater flexibility, so that women have
more opportunities in their 40s, and that women in their 20s need
not be afraid of their own ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to live our lives like men. But that isn't the
only alternative,'' said Estrich. ``There is a third way and we've
got to chart it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Estrich, however, now is not the time. The phone in
Estrich's hotel room is ringing furiously. A black sedan is purring
outside the hotel, waiting to take her to the airport. And Susan
Estrich pulls on her sunglasses and starts to head back home toward
the job at which she will always be first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not such an egomaniac to think that no one can do what I
can do on a political campaign,'' calls Estrich, hurrying down the
corridor. ``But I'm 100 percent certain that when it comes to my
children, no one can do what I do. I have an irreplaceable role and
it's at home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
