<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHILDHOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING THE LIFE OF LORD BERNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FIRST CHILDHOOD 
A DISTANT PROSPECT 
By Lord Berners 
Turtle Point Press/Helen Marx Books; 243 pp. and 186 pp.; $14.95
and $12.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America has not forgotten Lord Berners, because he was never
known here.
</P>
<P>
   In England, Gerald Tyrwhitt, Lord Berners (1883-1950), was
prized as a composer, novelist, wit, and incomparable host. On more
than one occasion, Stravinsky proclaimed him the finest composer in
England. He composed scores for Diaghilev's Russian ballet and for
the young company that grew into the Royal Ballet; his
collaborators included Gertrude Stein, Satcheverell Sitwell, and
Frederick Ashton, and his friends included most of the notable
literary, musical and political figures of his time and place. He
provides occasion for whimsical or outrageous anecdotes in numerous
memoirs. Nancy Mitford, who might have invented him, didn't need to
when she put him into her novel ``The Pursuit of Love'' as Lord
Merlin, whose whippets wear diamond chokers and whose parti-dyed
pigeons spread across the sky like ``a cloud of confetti.''
</P>
<P>
   Musicians have always been interested in Berners, who was dubbed
the ``English Satie,'' though Satie dismissed Berners as ``a
professional amateur.'' There are several CDs devoted to Berners's
work (a delightful one features Dame Felicity Lott and Graham
Johnson in the complete songs). Last year, belatedly, a first
biography appeared in England, Mark Amory's ``Lord Berners: The
Last Eccentric.''
</P>
<P>
   Berners was certainly not the last eccentric, but he certainly
belongs in the great tradition. The composer Constant Lambert
recalled how Berners could achieve solitude even on a crowded
railway train. ``He would put on dark glasses and slyly beckon in
the passers-by. Those isolated figures who stood the risk of
entering the carriage became so perturbed by his habit of reading a
newspaper upside-down and taking his temperature every few minutes
that they invariably changed carriages at the next station.'' One
of his novels, ``The Girls of Radcliff Hall,'' privately printed,
transparently disguised his circle of homosexual friends as
students in a girls' school whose headmistress, Miss Carfax, is
clearly Berners himself. Cecil Beaton was so horrified that he
destroyed every copy he could find. Berners is supposed to have
presented the volume to Queen Mary, who complimented him on his
accurate picture of school life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Eccentric'' has awakened interest in Berners's
literary work. Turtle Point Press has reissued the two slender
volumes of autobiography that Berners wrote, ``First Childhood'' in
1934 and ``A Distant Prospect,'' a sequel published in 1945, and in
May will bring out an omnibus volume of six of his Firbankian
novels, (but not including ``The Girls of Radcliff Hall'').
</P>
<P>
   The autobiographies carry Berners up to his departure from Eton
at 16. In some respects the story they tell is all too familiar _ a
childhood cosseted but emotionally isolated, the roughing up in a
boy's school, romantic friendships, the awakening of aesthetic
impulses, and the conflict of those impulses with a materialistic
family and society. What makes the books memorable is the clarity
of Berners's unforgiving memory, his sense of character and eye for
detail, his judgment, his wit, his voice, his slant. The familiar
story is economically told from a point of view that still sounds
fresh and modern more than 60 years later _ and it is bracingly
free of self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   Consider his portrait of his grandmother, the ``violently
low-church'' Lady Bourchier, who ``went so far to have herself
described in `Who's Who' as `distinctly low,' an epithet which must
have caused some surprise to those who were unaware of its
sectarian significance.'' Berners recalls the ordeal of twice-daily
family prayers, for which the domestic staff were summoned. ``They
were obliged to quit whatever work they were engaged upon, dress
themselves up in tidy clothes and troop into the dining-room in
order to sit upon hard benches for 20 minutes or more, listening to
my grandmother declaiming scriptural exhortations in a voice that
seemed to hold out very little hope of salvation for the lower
classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Musical readers will enjoy Berners's accounts of his youthful
infatuations with Chopin (``the subtle changes of harmony that were
like the iridescent hues on the plumage of the Himalayan
pheasant'') and with Wagner, who obsessed him even though Berners
had been told that Wagner couldn't write a decent fugue. Music puts
Berners at odds with his fox-hunting family; paradoxically, his
ability to play musical comedy tunes earns him the favor of
sporting boys at school.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting that while Berners is never sexually
explicit, the books carry a considerable erotic charge for that
very reason; the romantic yearnings are without defined objects,
but they are also never unclear. Berners's autobiographies are
amusing period pieces, like his music, and like his music, they
have lasting value. What makes these two books unnerving is
Berners's sensibility, which is not escapist at all; he creates
entertaining artifice by facing down uncomfortable facts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
