<HEADER>
A5901 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-ART-BOS &LR;      02-23 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEEP WRANGLER BETTER THAN EXPECTED, BUT OFFERS LITTLE TO LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not love at first sight . . . even though we were
introduced on Valentine's Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   There it sat, a 1999 Jeep Wrangler Sport _ the selfsame car I'd
begged my son not to buy two years ago. This was fate at its most
perverse.
</P>
<P>
   Get behind the wheel? Me? Drive one? I don't even like to follow
these things on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2 a.m., the end of a long shift, and driving did beat the
option of putting on running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Would that I could say it was an enjoyable trip.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't particularly smooth with the clutch _ this Jeep had a
close-ratio five-speed manual tied to the 4.0-liter in-line six
engine that seemed to want you to move briskly through the gears.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the well-grooved ruts on the northbound Central Artery
brought back fantasies to trying to ride the famed Gilley's
mechanical bull. We bucked and yawed and threatened to make some
unplanned lane changes.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the curving road by the local cemetery (an appropriate
location) was negotiated with care. I wasn't tipsy, but I was
paranoid that my ride might be.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning the Wrangler was sitting in the driveway,
waiting _ I'd like to say it had a defiant look in its plastic
foglights.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. G tried to play peacemaker and offered a Significant Other
Opinion: ``At least it's new.''
</P>
<P>
   That was true.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orange Line is only a mile-and-a-half away. Even though
I hadn't fallen for this first cousin of the Jeeps I once drove in
Uncle Sam's National Guard, I voted with my feet. Off to the T it
was. I didn't want to take this set of wheels _ out to play in
Boston's Friday traffic _ even if the tires were aptly named
Goodyear ``Wranglers.''
</P>
<P>
   How could it be that bad, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, simply climbing in one of these vehicles requires
being limber (Significant Other Opinion No. 2: ``Don't wear tight
slacks.''). If you have trouble getting into the front seat, don't
even think about getting in back. I managed only because the
passenger's seat slides up to the dashboard to create a tad of room
to execute this maneuver, which has a degree of difficulty of 8.2
on a scale of 10. In summertime, with the softtop down, it would be
just as easy to climb in over the side.
</P>
<P>
   Best to fold the back seat down and use it for storage. The
tailgate (with full-sized spare attached) swings open to provide
space for a row of grocery bags _ everyone has to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Once aboard, there's no room for the driver, either. Even with
the seat all the way back, the driving position is nuclear-sub
tight (``You can't even see the pedals,'' said
son-who-would-have-bought-one) with no place at all to rest your
arms.
</P>
<P>
   More annoyances? An irritating little orange arrow regularly
pops up on the dashboard display urging the driver to shift to a
higher gear even though the tachometer indicates a bare 2,000 rpms.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it's almost too easy bashing this beastie in print,
but two night's of sleep and the knowledge that 12 miles doesn't an
auto review make mandated a new beginning, starting with the
premise that this isn't your father's Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   We started with the owner's manual, knowing there's always a
nugget of knowledge to be shared. We learned:
</P>
<P>
   1. Be wary of abrupt maneuvers that could lead to rollovers
(wow!);
</P>
<P>
   2. If you ever want to use the soft top (not supplied with our
test car), find someone who has one of these vehicles and have them
show you the routine.
</P>
<P>
   So we hit the roads, hitting the highways, sitting in shopping
mall traffic and just driving both city and country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Significant Other Opinion No. 3: ``It's got a great heater.''
</P>
<P>
   True.
</P>
<P>
   A little Sunday snow on a dirt road wasn't a full
four-wheel-drive test, but the Wrangler loved it.
</P>
<P>
   But how much of that driving can one find in this area?
</P>
<P>
   On paved roads the steering and gearbox weren't so bad once we'd
adapted to them. Road noise _ long a bugaboo of Jeeps _ was
tolerable, too. This version is clearly more docile on macadam than
its predecessors, but it still yearns to go off roading.
</P>
<P>
   So, who does buy a Wrangler? I always figured the drivers were
irresponsible kids (``Couldn't you say `young and carefree'?'' asks
my aforementioned offspring.).
</P>
<P>
   A purchaser of this Sport model _ the midrange between the SE
and Sahara _ would have to go past the base price of $17,810.
Add-ons (air conditioning, ABS, hard top, fog lamps and the like)
brought the sticker to $21,560.
</P>
<P>
   And they'd have to buy some gas, too. Our test tank of gas
produced 17.2 mpg (right in the predicted range of 16-19).
</P>
<P>
   But Jeeps have been selling for years, and they've got a
personality you at least have to grudgingly respect.
</P>
<P>
   So, even if this isn't my father's Jeep, I'm still glad it isn't
my son's, either.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll share this secret: I'd love to try driving in
summertime on beach sand and in salt air instead of on road sand
with salt everywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
