<HEADLINE>
IS YOUR NEXT DESTINATION SAFE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   International travel is not without its dangers.
</P>
<P>
   A global travel warning was issued this week by the State
Department immediately after the killing of three Kurds who stormed
the Israeli consulate in Berlin. The warning urged Americans to
take special security precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Even without this incident, travelers should be aware that
danger lurks in many parts of the world. With Americans exploring
more and more remote parts of the world, the wise traveler should
check out information on unknown destinations for safety's sake.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department regularly issues travel advisories on just
about every land in the world. To obtain an advisory call the State
Department (Citizens Emergency Center, Bureau of Consular Affairs,
2201 C St. NW, Room 4811, US Department of State, Washington, DC
20520) at 202-647-5225 or on the Internet at
http://travel.state.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware, though, many have critized these advisories for either
not providing enough information on the dangers of a destination or
for exaggerating the risks.
</P>
<P>
   Another risk of international travel is your health. The federal
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's International
Travelers Hotline provides information on health risks and medical
needs for places around the world. Call 404-639-2572 or on the
Internet www.cdc.gov
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus on the world
</P>
<P>
   The Camden Conference is a weekend program that opens the world
to those attending. Held annually in the picturesque Maine coastal
village of Camden, Maine (about four hours from Boston), this
year's conference Feb. 26-28 will focus on sub-Saharan Africa. For
12 years the conference has focused on some global region, culture,
or foreign policy issue.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers from Africa and American academic institutions will
discuss the region from colonial to modern times. Featured speaker
will be Margaret Dongo, who in 1995 challenged Zimbabwe's Zanu
party and the leadership of Robert Mugabe. The conference is held
at the Camden Opera House. For more information, call 207-236-1034
or on the Web at www.camdenconference.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Culinary weekends
</P>
<P>
   Culinary vacations with celebrity chefs are again on the menu at
the New England Culinary Institute just outside Burlington, Vt. The
Whisk Away Weekends will be at the Inn at Essex, home to the
institute. The weekends will be held March 19-21, March 26-28,
April 23-25 and June 18-20. Topics include pastry, chocolate, the
Mediterranean, and exploring the world of fresh ingredients. March
programs are $535 a person and include accommodations, the other
weekends are $395 plus accommodations. For information, call
802-764-1490.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tours of interest
</P>
<P>
   Five night packages to catch the America's Cup Challenger races
and the America's Cup finals are being offered by Air New Zealand
October through March. Packages beginning at $1,799 a person
include air fare from Los Angeles, accommodations, a racing cruise
and more.
</P>
<P>
   Changing China is the topic of a tour April 27-May 18. The tour
is designed to see not only well-known attractions but also to meet
the Chinese in cities and villages. The tour is being led by Robert
L. Nichols, a former foreign service officer who was stationed in
China. The tour is $4,989 a person from Boston and includes air
fare, accommodations, meals and tours. For information, call Katlin
Travel Group (15 Depot Square, Lexington, MA 02420) at
800-552-8546.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Name the bird
</P>
<P>
   How would you like to name a new bird? It's just one of the
events on the Audubon Society's calendar this spring. March and
April bring one of the world's most spectacular wildlife pageants
to a short stretch of Nebraska's Platte River. About 500,000
sandhill cranes (almost 80 percent of the world's population),
along with millions of other migratory birds will be flocking to
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Platte will also be able to experience the
society's 29th annual Rivers and Wildlife Celebration in Kearney,
Neb., March 11-14. And on March 5 in Fort Worth, Tex., the society
will hold an auction to name a bird so rare it doesn't have a name.
The bird, an antshrike, was recorded for the first time in a remote
corner of the Amazon basin. The lucky bidder will have the honor of
creating the scientific name of this living creature.
</P>
<P>
   For information on these events, call the National Audubon
Society in New York at 212-979-3000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbados festival
</P>
<P>
   The sixth annual Holders Season, a festival of music and
theater, will be held in Barbados March 3-20. A highlight of this
year's season will be a Caribbean adaptation of Shakespeare's ``The
Tempest'' with a cast of Bajan and British artists. For information
on Barbados, call 800-221-9831.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weekend getaways
</P>
<P>
   Hyatt Touch Weekends offer an easy and inexpensive getaway.
Rates for the weekend at Hyatt hotels across the county begin at
$69 a night. When guests arrive they receive a ``Things to Do''
card filled with information about local attractions from shopping
to cultural activities. All weekend guests also receive a bonus.
From now through April 25, guests receive a $25 dining certificate
to sample the hotel's dishes. For more information, call
800-233-1234 and ask for the offer code ``touch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Flowering ideas
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will have the rare opportunity to view the interiors
and gardens of some of America's most beautiful private residences
during the 52d annual Festival of Houses and Gardens, March
18-April 17, in Charleston, S.C. More than 150 homes and gardens
are included, and there will be 11 neighborhood tours (each offered
twice). Since tickets are limited and many tours sell out before
the day of the event, advance reservations are encouraged. Tickets
are $35 per event and can be obtained by calling 843-722-3405.
</P>
<P>
   New Bern, N.C., will have its annual Historic Homes and Gardens
Tour on April 9-10. The Hats Off to Spring tour includes 14 homes,
two gardens, and 11 churches.
</P>
<P>
   A Friday evening walking tour with architectural specialists
will point out landmarks such as the 1895 City Hall and the
birthplace of Pepsi-Cola. Tickets for the homes tour are $13.50 in
advance, $15 on the days of the tours. For tickets, write to
Historic Homes Tour, PO Box 207, New Bern, NC 28563. For
information, call 252-638-8558.
</P>
<P>
   Knoxville, Tenn., will hold its annual Dogwood Arts Festival,
April 9-25. The festival, which draws some 350,000 people to East
Tennessee each spring, features more than 100 public and private
gardens open for viewing and 60 miles of blooming Dogwood Trails.
For information on the festival, call 800-DOGWOOD or 423-637-4561.
For package tours, call 888-400-8955.
</P>
<P>
   Another dazzling display of flowers can be seen during the
annual Daffodil Festival on Nantucket. This year's festival is
April 23-25 and features more than 3 million yellow, orange, white,
and pale pink daffodils along the roadsides, in gardens, and in
window boxes.
</P>
<P>
   An annual feature is the antique- and classic-car parade that
features blossom-bedecked vehicles. Since rooms are limited on the
island, advance reservations are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Visitors Service for information at 508-228-0925. For
an official guide to Nantucket, call 508-228-1700. Nantucket is now
served by two high-speed ferries, cutting the trip from Hyannis to
Nantucket to about an hour (call the Hy-Line at 508-778-2600 or the
Steamship Authority at 508-771-4000).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Garden ideas
</P>
<P>
   Old Sturbridge Village, the 1830s New England village, will hold
a Garden Planning Symposium on March 6, focusing on heirloom
varieties and 19th-century garden styles. Garden Planning Workshops
are set for March 7. For information, call 508-347-3362.
</P>
</TEXT>
