<HEADLINE>
OODLES OF NOODLES AT A MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've lost your noodle, perhaps you can find it at our
Museum of the Month: the four-year-old Ramen Museum in Yokohama.
</P>
<P>
   The museum attracts even more visitors than Japan's National Art
Museum, according to the JAL Newsletter. On display are dozens of
types of ramen _ a tasty noodle _ from around the world, including
an instant version with Arnold Schwarzenegger on the cup.
Three-hundred Japanese noodle bowls are also exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   The lower floor reproduces a Japanese street at dusk, with 88
miniature buildings. And there are nine on-site ramen restaurants
that draw so many diners that the lines stretch for blocks. At the
gift shop, you can buy ramen jewelry, key chains, and even
``emergency ramen,'' lasting up to three years.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can't make it to Yokohama, don't despair: The man
behind it all, Yoji Iwaoka, hopes to bring a similar museum to Las
Vegas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of ramen: The Japanese really do love the stuff. They
consume 5.3 billion servings a year, in about 600 varieties. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What country has a map on its flag? (Answer at end
of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: In Spain, Donald Duck's nephews Huey, Louie, and Dewey
are known as Jorgito, Juanito, and Jaimito. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Big Mac beat: McDonald's has opened its first kosher restaurant
outside of Israel _ in Buenos Aires. It's also opened its first
restaurant in Sri Lanka. Meanwhile, Burger King has opened a
``fly-through'' restaurant at a helicopter landing pad in London. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The long and short of it: The longest nonstop commercial flight in
the world is reported to be the Capetown, South Africa-Miami run on
South African Airways. It spans 7,650 miles in 14 hours and 30
minutes. The shortest commercial airline flight in the world is
said to be the Westray-Papa run in Scotland's Orkney Islands on
Loganair. It takes two minutes and there's no meal service. What is
believed to be the shortest commercial flight in the United States
is a mere 20 miles, from Appleton to Oshkosh, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cake contest: At the Shilla Hotel in Seoul, you can have your cake
and possibly a hotel stay. The hotel's master pastry chef has
created a millennium cake, shaped like a half-globe. The elaborate
cake costs about $25 US a slice, but the ninth customer gets a
complimentary cake and the 99th gets a hotel accommodation coupon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thai taboo: Do not pat children on the head in Thailand. Such
action is said to interfere with the upward flow of the spirits. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Puff, puff: The Chinese smoke 150 billion cigarettes a year _ 30
percent of the world's total. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Brrrrr: Nearly 99 percent of all the ice on Earth is found on or
near Antarctica and Greenland. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: Readers have added to our recent list of names of
Massachusetts' communities that are the same as men's first names.
Allen Barron of Easton, cites a friend named Easton. Dorothy Ekberg
of Cromwell, Conn., mentions Milton, which happens to be her
husband's name. And Ray and Doreen Gondola of Tewksbury contribute
a very common man's name: Marblehead! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Cyprus. (With thanks to uselessfacts.net, via
frequent contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
