<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SET YOUR SIGHTS ON FAR HORIZONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asia, Arabia, Australia, New Zealand, China, India, Africa,
Europe, and Antarctica are places to discover by ship. And, if you
can't decide which ports of call to make, choose the world. A world
cruise is not only possible, but becoming affordable.
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean may be the most popular cruising waters in the
world, but more and more travelers are discovering they can cruise
just about anywhere as easily as booking a Caribbean cruise.
</P>
<P>
   In summer 1999, a small armarda of ships _ many that cruise the
Caribbean in winter _ sail the waters of Europe. Cruise companies
are finding passengers are looking for new destinations, and the
popularity of Europe is evident by the number of ships that are
being home ported along the continent from spring through fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last year both Princess and Royal Caribbean scheduled the maiden
voyages of their newest and largest vessels in European waters. And
this year are adding more ships to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Just as European cruising is becoming more popular, cruise lines
are also extending their horizons to ports throughout the world.
While some lines such as Seabourn, Crystal, and Silversea regularly
roam the world, and others such as Cunard and Holland America have
annual world cruises, other familiar names like Princess, Royal
Caribbean and Norwegian are placing ships in distant ports.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is twofold, there are more new ships and cruise lines
are looking for new ports of call for them, and there are growing
numbers of cruise veterans who are eager to explore new regions of
the world on lines they enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Among some of the international cruises:
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean International's Legend of the Seas will set sail
in November on a program called Royal Journeys, a series of 10
globe-trotting cruise itineraries. The 160-day program will visit
four continents, reaching 41 ports in 19 countries. Passengers will
be offered the opportunity to disembark the ship in a designated
port of call, travel to an alternative destination, then rejoin the
vessel in another port of call. Pre- and post-cruise packages will
also be available at land-based resort accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line now has its Norwegian Star stationed in
Australia for year round cruises. The ship has been renamed the
Norwegian Capricorn and is sailing on seven- and 14-day cruises.
The ship, the former Royal Viking Sea, is ideally suited for
Pacific waters as unlike newer ships which have shallow drafts for
Caribbean cruises, the Capricorn was designed for world cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Cruises has expanded its African and Holy Land cruises.
The line claims it is the first and only cruise line to offer an
in-depth exploration West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Cunard, which has been cruising the world for years, is
featuring Awesome Arabia this year. Featured will be calls to the
port of Dubai, which has emerged as a tourist destination for
travelers seeking a taste of Arabia while still enjoying all the
comforts and facilities of a world-class destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers on Cunard ships enjoy the exploration of exotic
destinations and the opportunity to witness firsthand the
combination of historic cultures and breathtaking surroundings.
That's why an Arabian program is such an asset to our cruise
offerings,'' said Peter Bates, executive vice president of Cunard.
Cunard ships heading for Dubai are the Queen Elizabeth 2, Royal
Viking Sun and Sea Goddess II.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pacific, Clipper Cruise Line is adding a fourth vessel to
its small ship fleet. The Clipper Odyssey will sail on three and
four day cruises from Bali, and in December sail for Australia's
Great Barrier Reef and New Zealand for a series of 10-day cruises.
</P>
<P>
   In the Caribbean many lines offer a private isle experience for
their passengers. Now Radisson Seven Seas Cruises is doing the same
in French Polynesia. Guests on the Paul Gauguin, which sails weekly
out of Tahiti, will now have a private motu of their own for a
secluded beach day of water sports, relaxation, and gourmet dining.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly three of the more luxurious ways to explore the world
by ship are offered on Silversea, Seabourn and Crystal cruise
lines. These lines are noted for their luxurious surroundings, fine
food, and world-class itineraries that range from Europe to the Far
East.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you want the world, a new cruise line, World Cruises,
begins sailing that call on all the continents including
Antarctica. What makes this line all the more interesting is its
pricing. Cruises will range from about $10,000 to around $15,000 a
person _ most world cruises have prices beginning above the $15,000
mark, and don't include all the continents. World Cruises is part
of the Toronto-based Marine Expeditions, which has been offering
cruises to Antarctica and other exotic destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Antarctica may seem an unusual destination, but its a regular
port of call for Orient Lines' Marco Polo. While every cruise line
has a special program planned for the new millennium, the Marco
Polo will be again heading there Dec. 23 for a New Year's Eve gala
on the southernmost continent. ``Most people who visit Antarctica
come back feeling totally exhilarated and renewed,'' said Deborah
Natansohn, president of the line. ``We couldn't think of a better
place to start a new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   For new ports of call far beyond the Caribbean, check out the
itineraries of these lines: American Canadian Caribbean Line,
Classical Cruises, Costa, Crystal, Cunard, EuroCruises, Holland
America, Ivarian Lines (a freighter with superb passenger
facilities), Marine Expeditions, Norwegian Cruise Line,
OdessAmerica Cruise, Orient Lines, Princess cruises, Quark
Expeditions, Radisson Seven Seas Cruises, Regal Cruises, Royal
Caribbean, Royal Olympic, Seabourn, Silversea, Special Expeditions,
Star Clippers, Temptress Adventure Cruises, Windjammer Barefoot
Cruises, or Windstar Cruises.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Royal music
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Music Festivals are back again aboard the Radisson Diamond
in June and August. Three 11-night cruises will feature some of
Europe's finest musicians, virtuosos and singers. The performances
will be held in settings such as the Hermitage Theater in St.
Petersburg, th Hall of State inside the Stockhyolm Royual Palace,
the Ajuda Palace in Lisbon, and France's Palais du Grand Large.
Each of the twin-hulled Radisson Diamond voyages will feature up to
four countries. For those making early bookings, savings of up to
$900 a person plus a $500 per stateroom bonus amenities package are
available. The bonus can be applied to shore excursions, spa,
boutique or the onboard Golf Academy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Big band cruises &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four of the country's most popular big bands will bring the
nostalgic sounds of swing to sea aboard Norwegian Cruise Line's
popular Big Band theme cruise aboard the legendary Norway Nov.
27-Dec. 4. The lineup includes the Artie Shaw Orchestra, Guy
Lombardo's Royal Canadians, Tex Beneke and His Orchestra and the
Terry Myers Orchestra. Special events on the sailing include
autograph signings, contests, a free-of-charge jukebox with old
favorites, period movies, and on days at sea, almost continuous Big
Band performances from 2 p.m. to 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Alaska for Jews
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the 6 million Jews who live in North America, about 38
percent are either orthodox or conservative Jews who observe strict
dietary laws and who do not travel on Saturdays. To take an Alaskan
cruise has meant traveling on a Saturday and, probably having to
bring along one's own kosher food. A cruise, Alaska Through Jewish
Eyes answers these and other travel problems. A kosher Alaska
adventure is set for June 1-15 aboard the Universe Explorer. Lotus
Tours and Rabbi Marvin Tokayer of New York, who have operated
kosher tours and cruises since 1982 say the cruise will feature
freshly prepared kosher foods, talks on Alaska as well as on Jewish
history. For information, call Lotus Tours at 800-267-5415.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
