<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DEBATE ON NIXON'S JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ First, let's get the age thing out of the
way. Trot Nixon is not 30 years old. He has not been in the Red Sox
organization for 15 years. It just seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   All of the 1999 Red Sox were due in camp Tuesday (Feb. 23) and,
for the first time in his professional baseball career, Trot Nixon
has a job. Red Sox manager Jimy Williams is counting on Nixon to be
his starting right fielder Opening Day in Kansas City April 5.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is still only 24 years old (he'll be 25 April 11), which
seems impossible for Sox fans who remember hearing about him back
in 1993 when Daddy Butch Hobson was Boston's manager.
</P>
<P>
   How long has Trot been around? He was drafted by Lou Gorman.
This is the Red Sox equivalent of being one of Bill Parcells's
secretaries with the Patriots. Boston's Machiavellian general
manager Dan Duquette has purged the organization of almost all
Gorman nominees (John Valentin and Scott Hatteberg are the only
other Gorman draft picks still playing for the Sox).
</P>
<P>
   A multisport high school star in Wilmington, N.C., Nixon had a
scholarship to play quarterback at North Carolina State, but the
Sox made him the No. 7 pick in the draft and lured him to baseball
with an $890,000 signing bonus. They also set aside No. 7 _ the
number worn by Mickey Mantle, the favorite player of Trot's
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   There was small talk about Hall of Fame after Trot was drafted.
The Sox shipped him to Fenway for a round of public batting
practice, and Trot wowed the crowd with homers into the bullpen and
shots off the wall. Then he disappeared into the quagmire of the
minor leagues, and he's been almost invisible since that initial
showcase at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Lynchburg. Sarasota. Trenton. Pawtucket. Winter ball. Counting
time in the Florida Instructional League, Nixon has been playing
minor league ball for six seasons. Along the way he suffered a
chipped bone in his lower back and the discouragement of hitting
only .244 at Triple A in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon got it together last summer, hitting .310 with 23 homers
and stealing 26 bases for Pawtucket. He got called up to the bigs
Sept. 6 and hit .259 in 13 games. He started in right field in the
third game of the playoffs against the Indians and hit a single off
Charles Nagy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Darren Bragg gone and the Sox desperate for
outfielders with any power, Nixon's the one to play right field
unless he flops in Florida. This is his time. The job is his to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it that way,'' he said. ``I look at it that I
have to make this team. I need to go out and play well in spring
training. It's been a long time. I've had a lot of ups and downs,
but I've learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said the low point for him came in 1997 when he struggled
at Pawtucket. But he never thought about giving up and never
regretted choosing baseball over football. His family and friends
understood that the road to the big leaques is littered with
landmines (Nixon's wife, Kathryn Fisher, is a NASCAR reporter for
ESPN2). Some Sox fans have been less patient, wondering, ``Whatever
happened to Trot Nixon?''
</P>
<P>
   Casual fans of big league baseball have no idea how difficult it
is to make it to the majors. For every big leaguer you see riding
the bench with the Pirates, there are 15 kids who signed
professional contracts, kissed their families goodbye, and wasted
their youth kicking around the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not take long for certain players, but it is true _
there's so many baseball players in the minor leagues,'' said
Nixon. ``I don't think people quite understand it at all, just how
many players there are. Even in one organization, there's a lot of
players.''
</P>
<P>
   This winter he worked out in Bradenton with Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great four weeks at the `military academy' in
Bradenton with Nomar,'' he said. ``I worked on speed, agility,
lateral movement. I did a lot of weightlifting and spent 2-3 hours
a day in the cages and taking ground balls and fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's father, William, is a renowned kidney specialist in
Wilmington. He was an active participant in Trot's original
contract discussions and has been labeled a ``stage dad'' by some
folks in Sox camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that says that just doesn't know squat,'' said Trot.
``I push myself. You work out with me and you realize that. My
father pushed me when I needed to be pushed and that was in high
school and a lot of other fathers have done that same thing. It's
not like I answer to him and he pushes me. I push myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he gets to play where Dwight Evans, Tony Conigliaro, Ken
Harrelson and so many other sluggers patrolled. It has been 10
years since any Sox outfielder hit 20 homers (Evans in '89).
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've got a lot to prove to the fans and the
ownership,'' Nixon acknowledged. ``But I can't really give you
numbers. I've never even played half a major league season. But I'm
going to play hard, and hopefully I'l have a chance to put up
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can hit the ball, give 'em some speed. I don't have
the strongest arm in the world, but it's somewhat accurate. And I
play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
