<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FUTURE IS ALL MINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGTSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the good news arrived from the US Patent Office, I let out
a whoop of joy that I have no doubt will be heard until the end of
time. I had been awarded US Patent 89764392307921. I now own rights
to all knowledge of the future.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't seeking protection of any new invention. I had not come
up with a novel contraption for mopping Schnaunzer poop off your
shoes. I hadn't devised a unique applicator for zit cream. Nothing
as concrete as that. My goal was to guarantee that I alone would
benefit professionally, personally, and financially from my own
special intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   I do not intend to reveal here the unique concept I've created
and implemented in my prognostications that lifts my efforts above
those of everyone else. It's my secret, after all. Suffice it to
say that my special knowledge, acquired after years of dedication
and expense, met the Patent Office's criteria and merited broad
protection. Indeed, in the split second it took to thump the
bureaucratic stamp of approval on my application, the Patent Office
revolutionized the world of prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Now anyone who wishes to venture a prediction on anything: the
weather, the horses, the stock market, the likelihood of another
sexual dalliance by President Clinton will have to pay me first _
or risk serious legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the patent office delivered its wise decision, I did
what I do best: I peered into my future. And there I saw a crisp
image of mountains and mountains of dollars, bills of the highest
denomination piled as high as Mountr McKinley and there I was
jumping and sliding and frolicking all over the place. It was all
mine _ all mine!
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone object to my good fortune, allow me to point out
that what I requested and what the patent office endorsed is now
pretty much standard operating procedure. As Seth Shulman describes
in his telling, just-released book, ``Owning the Future: Inside the
Battles to Control the New Assets _ Genes, Software, Databases, and
Technological Know-how _ That Make Up the Lifeblood of the New
Economy,'' the patent office routinely grants exclusive rights to
broad notions.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier days, the patent office granted protection only to
tangible innovations. But now it deeds blanket rights to ideas,
concepts, and techniques that cut across wide swaths of the
high-tech, medical, and agricultural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Shulman explains, doctors now own medical
procedures, preventing other physicians from freely using them.
Software companies now gain monopolies on the building blocks for
writing new computer programs, freezing out competition and
possible innovation. Biotech researchers are even buying up the
rights to our own genes.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has become so outrageous, Shulman reports, that
lawyers are now arguing that professional athletes should be able
to patent or copyright their unique moves on the basketball court
or football field.
</P>
<P>
   Now as I use my exclusive rights to peer into the future, I can
see the outcome. Medicine will revert to the stone age as rights to
treatments will send costs soaring and leave us all dying without
care. Food production will dry up and we'll all starve as
agribusiness uses its patents to squeeze farmers. And we'll no
longer have rights to our own bodies as companies will have
patented every biological and genetic inch of us.
</P>
<P>
   But am I worried? Nah, I've got my patent. The future belongs to
me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston's e-mail address is levingston(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
