<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     02-23 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE-COLLAR WORKERS SHARE GILLETTE'S GOOD FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Alfred Zeien leaves Gillette Co. in April, he will not go
empty-handed. The departing chief executive, who announced his
retirement last week, will walk away with Gillette stock and
options worth roughly $160 million, based on last year's proxy
statement. But part of the Zeien legacy will be the millions he
made for other people, including Gillette employees.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as anyone can remember, most Gillette employees have
put their spare cash into Gillette stock, aided by generous
matching contributions from the company. The practice violates the
basic rule of investing _ namely that you don't put all your eggs
in one basket _ but hardly anyone at Gillette is complaining. Who
complains, after all, when he achieves the American dream and
becomes a millionaire?
</P>
<P>
   According to John O'Connell, a benefits executive at Gillette,
roughly 300 of the 7,500 participants in the company's savings plan
have accounts worth more than $1 million. The list doesn't include
retirees or people who have bought stock through other vehicles.
Even more impressive than the number of millionaires is who they
are. About 20 percent of the group, or 60 people, are Gillette
employees who have never earned more than $50,000 a year. ``Some of
them are blue-collar people who work in the factory,'' said
O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   How did they amass such big nest eggs? Simple: They socked away
a fair amount of money in a stock that has performed spectacularly.
Under the rules of the savings plan, employees can put away up to
15 percent of their pay per year. In fact, the average contribution
is about 10 percent of pay, far above the US corporate average.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette matches 50 percent of the employee contribution up to
10 percent, or a maximum of 5 percent of pay. The Gillette
contribution is always made in company stock, and a big chunk of
the employee money goes toward the stock as well, even though
workers can invest in other things. About two-thirds of the plan's
$2.1 billion in assets is parked in company stock.
</P>
<P>
   And what a stock it has been. Since 1981 the stock has climbed
60-fold. Between the end of 1987 and the end of 1997 its value
increased 17 times, an annual rate of appreciation of 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a different story. Fears that the hard times in
Asia and Russia would slash Gillette sales _ a good assumption as
it turned out _ sent the stock on a steep slide. Between July and
September, the stock lost 40 percent of its value. ``People didn't
run away,'' said O'Connell, who saw very little change in employee
investment patterns. So far that faith has been rewarded. Gillette
stock, which dipped as low as 36, has recovered to 54, still below
its high of 62.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to employee investing habits, the company takes a
hands-off attitude. Gillette offers investment education and plenty
of opportunities to diversify. But if employees choose to stick
with the stock, so be it. In fact, Gillette executives, including
Zeien, have long endorsed the idea that employee stock ownership is
a good way to build loyalty to the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is proud of the fact that you can go up to anyone in the
company and that person can tell you what the stock price is,''
said Danielle Frizzi, a Gillette spokesman. There are kiosks and
message boards sprinkled throughout Gillette facilities, said
Frizzi, where employees can check to see how the stock is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Investment experts get nervous when they hear about so much
money concentrated in one stock, even a great stock like Gillette.
``If you've got more than 25 percent of your money in one asset
that can be dangerous,'' said Dee Lee, a financial planner with
Harvard Financial Educators.
</P>
<P>
   Lee points out that even great companies sometimes have a way of
falling off a cliff. Remember Digital Equipment Corp.? Its stock
price fell from 200 to 20 over a period of years, a process that
wiped out billions, a chunk of which belonged to employees.
Employees may think they know their companies well, say planners,
but turning points are notoriously difficult to spot, even for
insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette employees are not the only ones in love with their own
stock. At some of America's best companies _ Coca-Cola, General
Electric, Pfizer _ the bulk of the assets in the 401(k) plan are in
the firm's own stock. ``Can you blame these people?'' asks Lee.
``They've done so well. How do you tell them to diversify? They've
got an ingrained loyalty to the company.''
</P>
<P>
   So far that loyalty has been well-placed. Under both Zeien and
his predecessor, Colman Mockler, Gillette employees have had their
eggs in the right basket. Come April, those eggs become the
responsibility of Michael Hawley, the new chief executive. Can he
keep them from cracking? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
