<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVID-OSCAR-BOS &LR;      02-23 1622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVID-OSCAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OSCAR FOR A PARI OF AVID INNOVATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEWKSBURY, Mass. _ Tom Ohanian and Michael Phillips are days
away from receiving an Oscar for technological achievement, one of
the pinnacles of their careers. Yet here they sit, in a dark room
whirring with computers, trying to make sense of Scene 43 in an
indie film called ``Dweller in the Dark.''
</P>
<P>
   It's basic horror-film stuff, and Phillips and Ohanian have
taken on the job of making several messy shots meld together in one
coherent, hopefully terrifying, scene. But as it stands now,
according to both men, it ain't melding.
</P>
<P>
   Ohanian's skill as a film editor will help make order of things,
and Phillips will use his talents as a director to fine-tune. But
the real help will come from Avid Film Composer, a souped-up
$80,000 bundle of hardware and software that both men helped
develop for their employer, Avid Technology of Tewksbury. Film
Composer is a digital film-editing system that starting in 1992
quickly began replacing the bulky flatbed, the traditional
film-editing machine used over the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   It's this computer and what it's done for film and television
that helped garner Avid, Ohanian, and Phillips their Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the company won a scientific and engineering award from
the Academy for Film Composer, a bronze tablet that denotes any
achievement that ``had a definite influence on the advancement of
the film industry,'' according to the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, while dozens of other technological innovators
receive certificates and similar tablets, Avid will be the only
recipient of the coveted gold statue, a hard-won and carefully
orchestrated Hollywood nod acknowledging that Avid's technology has
arrived and that editing film will never be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Ohanian and Phillips, two film guys with no
computer background, got together with Avid's engineers to help
create Film Composer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we were driving oxcarts for years and this guy comes
by and says, `Here's a Jaguar. Do you think you'd like it?' '' said
Joe Hutshing, an Oscar-winning film editor who last edited ``Meet
Joe Black'' and who is currently editing ``Being John Malkovich''
on an Avid system.
</P>
<P>
   The system allows film to be digitized, edited, and manipulated
on a high-end computer system at 24 frames per second, then
transferred back to film without a breakdown in quality or timing.
</P>
<P>
   Although many other companies make similar systems, Avid's
success in filmmaking and television is in its numbers. An
estimated 85 percent of the prime-time television shows are edited
on Avids, 70 of the 114 films at this year's Sundance Film Festival
were edited on Avids, and 10 films nominated for Oscars this year
were edited using an Avid product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very similar to what happened when somebody invented the
word processor,'' Hutshings added. ``You might have had a great IBM
Selectric, but after the word processor came along, who cares.''
</P>
<P>
   On a flatbed, when a director or film editor wanted a scene to
dissolve into black, the editor would first have to lug that reel
of film to the machine. Such reels, which hold about 10 minutes of
film, weigh about 4 pounds each. If it wasn't the right reel, there
was more lugging to do, and more linear-based searching, a task
akin to finding a particular scene using the forward and reverse
buttons on a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   After finding the shot he wanted to dissolve, the editor would
take a china marker and run it across 24 frames of film. That, for
all intents and purposes, was the dissolve. A film would then be
sent out to be processed. Until it came back, editors and directors
never really knew what they had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watched it, you would see this line go through and
you'd say, OK, I think I know what that dissolve would look like,''
said Phillips. ``Slow motion or skipping motions were all leaps of
faith. If you talk to editors, you hear all these horror stories
about how many times they had to go back to the (film) labs because
it just wasn't what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   On a digital editing system, those 10-minute reels fit on
portable hard drives. If you want a dissolve, you see it right
there and then. Slower? No problem. Click a button. Done.
</P>
<P>
   If someone muffs the pronunciation of a word, an editor can
search the entire movie, find the same word, and transfer it to
that scene. No need to fly an actor back to dub the soundtrack. No
need to reshoot anything.
</P>
<P>
   In one demonstration, Ohanian and Phillips had a copy of the
screenplay for ``Mouse Hunt'' on one monitor and a scene from the
movie on another. Phillips clicked on a scene on the screenplay
monitor, and it appeared on the second monitor instantaneously. On
a flatbed, this would have taken several minutes, maybe a half
hour. On an Avid, it took less than a second.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene from the same movie in which a mouse runs across a
floor packed with mousetraps, the director wanted to fill one gap
with another trap. Using an Avid, editors cloned one of the traps
in the scene, turned it sideways, and digitally moved it into the
open space.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the technology became available for the first time,
editors saw it from a very creative side. They said, `Give me the
same eight months to edit a feature on this and I can explore it 25
times more ways than I ever could on film,' '' said Phillips.
``There is never a reason for saying `why not' anymore. You just do
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   After the changes are made on an Avid, the computer system then
prints out a precise ``cut list'' of all the editor's desired
special effects and manipulations. Those instructions are sent to a
film house, which will make the changes happen on celluloid,
something that computers have yet to replace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negative cutters will be around for a long time,'' Phillips
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Avid's technology allows filmmakers to experiment with
editing techniques, some say it has also accelerated the pace of
filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   From the time the film ``Lethal Weapon 4'' shot its first scene
to the time it opened in theaters, a scant seven months passed. It
was a Hollywood record. But with hundreds of millions of dollars in
loans hanging over the production, mega-actors facing mega-demands
for their time, and studios clamoring to save money, seven months
was a godsend. It wouldn't have been possible without a digital
film-editing system.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the postproduction time is shrinking,'' said Ohanian,
``because if you're floating $100 million out on a loan, it's big
money here, and you can make a lot more money in terms of getting
that product into the theater faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohanian and Phillips are far from Hollywood types _ two men who
prefer to be behind the scenes rather than out front.
</P>
<P>
   Ohanian is a 38-year-old Rhode Island native who became
fascinated with film after his father gave him a Super 8 camera.
Although he started college as a dentistry major, he quickly
changed his mind. ``The moment I put two pieces of film together
and faked somebody out, I wanted to be an editor,'' he said. When
he came to Avid 10 years ago, he was the fledgling company's eighth
hire.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, 38, was raised in France and schooled in Montana,
where he taught himself classical guitar and became interested in
studying music for film. After making a movie for some music he had
written, and creating rolling titles on a class project using slide
projectors and a roll of butcher paper, he was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, being a control freak, I thought, if I can do
the music and the movie, I can do it all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two came together when Phillips took an Avid class and saw
an early prototype of the system. When he realized this newfangled
system was similar to straight-cut editing on a flatbed, he spoke
up. Phillips told the instructor that what Avid was doing on the
computer was no different from what he and other directors were
doing on traditional film-editing equipment. ``I wasn't overly
impressed,'' he said, telling the instructor that the system
wouldn't sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Well, how should it work?' I said, `Hire me and
I'll tell you.' And I've been here ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Their work is now focused on bringing this expensive technology
to independent films, where time and money are of the essence.
Ohanian and Phillips said that such filmmakers can save $100,000
using a digital film-editing system, making up for lost time,
reshoots, and the cost of processing film. Which is why they're
helping out with ``Dweller in the Dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the system, Ohanian puts Scene 43 in some order, and the
story begins to show.
</P>
<P>
   A girl clad in a towel stands transfixed by a boarded-up window,
and a monster's hand reaches through, grabs her head, and drags her
into the blackness. A guy comes into the room and screams; more
people come into the room, scream, and run to the window.
</P>
<P>
   Then Phillips and the computer take over, tightening cuts,
fixing a continuity problem in which the monster's hand is on the
girl's head and then later on her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, after they've experimented with some of Film
Composer's many special effects, a scream is moved under another
scene, the monster's hand looks almost real thanks to a timing
delay, and the scene's movement is suddenly fluid.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times artists won't think of paths to go down because
they know the technology is too hard to use or the technology
doesn't allow them to do it,'' said Ohanian. ``Here, you can do
that stuff. And what we're doing here has taken less than five
minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
