<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S PEOPLE MUST BE HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world events. To publish it as a ``separate buy''
article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    As Russia is approaching the time of new elections, it faces a
truly unique alternative. At the crossroads of two eras it must
decide to get off the ground and forge ahead or be resigned to
ultimate decline.
 &HT;    This is a time, after all, when the Russian authorities have
lost touch with the needs of the nation. The real will of the
people must be known. And so it is necessary to be sure the next
elections are truly free and fair.
 &HT;    The voting could help Russia recover that bond between the
government and the people. If the elections are again corrupted by
intrigue, conspiracy, under-the-carpet maneuvers and the charade of
``campaign techniques,'' as happened so outrageously in 1996, when
President Yeltsin was re-elected, expect the worse to happen.
 &HT;    The fact is that since 1991, there has not been a clean election
in Russia. The will of the people has been frustrated at all levels
_ federal, regional and in the republics. In recent years, Russian
voters have learned a great deal and must no longer be taken for
granted. New campaign deceptions are bound to fail.
 &HT;    There is one danger not to ignore: Of late, many people have
become so disenchanted that they might not vote at all. Some
politicians and academics have therefore suggested that, for a
limited time, voting should be made mandatory. This may seem rather
undemocratic, but I support the idea.
 &HT;    It may not work in other countries, but it could become a big
plus for Russian democracy, where the people must take hold. It
could help bring younger voters to the polls; they tend to stay
away. It would also minimize the possibility of manipulating
election returns.
 &HT;    Incidentally, voting in elections was for many decades mandatory
in Italy, with no harm done to Italian democracy. In Austria, this
rule is still in effect. In the United States, of course, this
might sound like heresy, but why should we always emulate America?
 &HT;    The media could play an important role. It is true that most of
our media is in the hands of those who pay, but freedom of the
press still exists in Russia. The test of a journalist's
responsibility is whether he or she pays heed to conscience and a
sense of professional duty. Many of them, I know, are thinking
about what's best for the nation.
 &HT;    The goal should be clear _ consolidating all those who are
capable of defending the interests of the majority and the
interests of Russia as a sovereign state. Is there a party that
could do it?
 &HT;    Let's look at the situation without bias. Opinion polls give the
lead to the communists, but they cannot win. They do not have a
realistic program for pulling the country out of crisis; they
represent only a part of the populace. The right-wing coalition of
the so-called radical democrats does not have a prayer _ the people
are likely to hold them responsible for Russia's chaos and
disastrous situation and punish them at the polls.
 &HT;    Thus, something new should be devised. And the possibility is
there, because what the Primakov government is doing is similar to
the program put forth by Yuri Luzhkov, the current mayor of Moscow
who aspires to national office. Both men emphasize the need to
protect Russia's national interests and to provide for the needs of
ordinary people.
 &HT;    This duo could work well, all the more so because their goals
have much in common with the positions taken by Grigori Yavlinski
and his Yabloko party. Many governors too appear ready to support
Primakov and his policy course. To sum up, conditions are in place
to create a broad-based alliance that would guarantee stability and
progress.
 &HT;    This is also a time for the West to take unconventional, wise
and courageous decisions. The West must demonstrate that it can
take a new look at Russia, and that it understands how dangerous
would be the temptation to take advantage of Russia's current
weakness to try to marginalize it in world affairs. This may well
be the time for the West to take an unprecedented step in
cooperation with Russia.
 &HT;    All responsible forces within and outside Russia should realize
that the fall of the Primakov government would plunge Russia into
chaos. Elections _ presidential or parliamentary _ could then
become impossible. There are some good reasons to be critical of
this government, but remember that Primakov was called in to manage
a disastrous political situation and a ruined economy.
 &HT;    What is more, Russia is going through a multiple crisis _
economic, psychological and political-institutional. Without
stability, it is hard to combat such a crisis. Too hard, in fact _
so I would venture to suggest that the presidential elections be
held first, not after the elections to parliament. This would
clarify the future direction of the country and make it possible to
start working quietly and in concert on amendments to the Russian
constitution.
 &HT;    Of course, to implement this scenario without violating the
constitution we need the consent of the president. It is up to him
to decide. Yeltsin should evaluate the need to do it so as to give
the country a chance to choose its future in a proper environment.
Today, he could still decide how history will look upon him.
Tomorrow, it may be too late.
 &HT;     c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow. He travels
and lectures widely; and will be touring the U.S. in March.
President Gorbachev is a principal figure in the acclaimed CNN
series ``Cold War,'' now being broadcast around the world.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1413EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5951 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-VOICE-PEOPLE-N     02-23 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VOICE-PEOPLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S PEOPLE MUST BE HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world events. To publish it as a ``separate buy''
article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
