u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     02-23 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Feb. 23, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.    (Adds: COURT-NCAA and
INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL)    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ President Clinton and
congressional leaders from both parties, meeting for the first time
in 19 months, vow post-impeachment cooperation to rescue Social
Security, cut taxes and boost education. But signs of trouble loom.
By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICAN-DISUNITY (Washington) _ With peace officially
breaking out between President Clinton and congressional
Republicans, GOP leaders find time to squabble among themselves.
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson has harsh words for GOP leaders in
Congress. Then, right in front of reporters on the White House
driveway, House Speaker Dennis Hastert and Senate Republican leader
Trent Lott voice drastically different views of tax cuts. By DAN
FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI-BUSH (Washington) _ New York Gov. George Pataki says at a
news conference he will not join some of his Republican
gubernatorial colleagues in urging Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to
run for president. He also announces a $5.2 million federal grant
to upstate New York communities to protect water quality. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-NCAA (Washington) _ The Supreme Court makes it harder to
sue the National Collegiate Athletic Association under a law
banning sex bias in educational programs receiving federal aid. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   FEINSTEIN-MEXICO (Washington) _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
charges that the Mexican government isn't doing enough to root out
corruption and money laundering by drug cartels. But President
Clinton is expected to certify to Congress later this month that
the Mexican government is making good faith efforts in the war on
drugs. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL (Washington) _ Sens. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.,
and Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., discuss the future of the
independent counsel law at a news conference on the eve of a Senate
hearing into whether Congress should renew the statute. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ What are we to make of recently
surfaced allegations that Bill Clinton raped a woman 21 years ago?
The statute of limitations for rape prosecution has run, the charge
has not been proved, there is no evidence of obstruction of
justice, and violence has never been a Clinton characteristic. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
