   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ After 17 days of
negotiations, the ethnic Albanians agree to sign a Kosovo peace
agreement within two weeks, the State Department spokesman says. He
says ethnic Albanians said they would sign after ``technical
consultations'' with the people in Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REACT (Belgrade) _ Reaction of the Serbs in Belgrade. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FIGHTING (Bukos, Yugoslavia) _ Developments in Kosovo:
more fighting, etc. By Carlotta Gall. With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Beijing) _ With a newfound political drive, the
U.S. and China have resumed intense negotiations over China's entry
into the World Trade Organization, hoping against the odds to be
able to announce a breakthrough when Prime Minister Zhu Rongji
visits Washington in April. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RITTER (Washington) _ U.N. officials denounce Ritter, the
former arms inspector, and the conclusions of his book on the
misuse of arms inspections by the U.S. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Lebanese guerrillas firing machine
guns ambush Israeli commandos in southern Lebanon, killing three
officers and wounding five other soldiers. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURD (Istanbul) _ The Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah
Ocalan, who was captured in Kenya last week, is formally charged
with treason, a crime that can carry the death penalty. By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-PLOT (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ The federal judge in Puerto
Rico handling the case of seven Cuban exiles charged in connection
with a plot to assassinate Castro has reversed himself, ruling that
the trial will take place in Puerto Rico and not in Miami. By Karl
Ross.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional leaders of both
parties meet with Clinton for the first time in 19 months and also
talk to the nation's governors. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SOCSEC (Washington) _ A House Ways and Means Committee
hearing is expected to underscore the differences between the
parties on saving Social Security. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-COUNSEL (Washington) _ On eve of congressional
hearings, more on the independent counsel act. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DRAGGING-DEATH (Jasper, Texas) _ Closing arguments in the Jasper
dragging death trial. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-MAYORAL (Chicago) _ Results of the mayoral election,
with Mayor Daley heavily favored. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS (New York) _ Looking at the legal basis for
Mayor Giuliani's policy to seize cars even after a driver accused
of drunk driving is acquitted. By Alan Finder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Greenspan, delivering his
semiannual testimony to the Senate Banking Committee, says the
economy retains considerable momentum with no evidence of
inflationary problems. But he adds that dangers remain, ranging
from a potential stock market crash to the possible development of
inflationary pressures. The Fed stands ready to quickly raise or
lower interest rates if the economy grows too fast or too slowly,
he says. He again issues a warning about the level of stock prices,
but he does not appear to be as worried as in the past. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-EURO (Zurich, Switzerland) _ It isn't one of the 11 euro
nations _ it isn't even a member of the European Union _ but that
hasn't stopped Switzerland from embracing the continent's new
common currency with an enthusiasm that eclipses even the euro
euphoria of some of its large neighbors. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EURO (London) _ The British prime minister, Tony Blair,
announces his government's plans for adopting the euro. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was down
22 points, or 0.2 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 15 points,
or 0.6 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 1.7 percent in Tokyo and 2.2
percent in Hong Kong. They rose 2.5 percent in Frankfurt, 1 percent
in London and 0.3 percent in Brazil. They were flat in Mexico. On
the American debt market, the long bond was down 23/32 point, with
the yield at 5.40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BSKYB-CANALPLUS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Folo on reports that
British Sky Broadcasting, which is controlled by Rupert Murdoch, is
in talks with Canal Plus of France about a merger that would create
a European television power. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments at the Microsoft
antitrust trial. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-Y2K (Washington) _ Bipartisan House sponsors announce
legislation regarding the Year 2000 computing problem that is
expected to incorporate provisions to limit businesses' liability.
</P>
<P>
   NEXTEL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Nextel Communications' loss narrowed
more than expected in the fourth quarter as it signed up more
customers and revenue doubled. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly business travel column.
By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
