<HEADER>
A6010 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLA-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF     02-23 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLA-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLA'S WORLD (WHY KIDS TALK TO IMAGINARY FRIENDS)
</HEADLINE>
  By LAURA HILGERS 
 c.1999 Child 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday, August 21: Our daughter, Willa, began talking to herself
when she was 1. She would sit in her crib, before falling asleep or
just after awakening, and practice new words. ``Mine. Bear. Mine.
Bear,'' she would say, trying the words on for size.
</P>
<P>
   Now 4 1/2, Willa still talks to herself, before falling asleep
at night and during her (so-called) quiet time. She talks nonstop.
She sings. She invites pretend friends over. She re-creates fairy
tales. She takes the events of her day and turns them into
something her 4-year-old mind finds easier to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is delightfully odd, occasionally alarming, often
reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, August 26: Today, during quiet time, Willa and an
imaginary friend are ``babysitting'' an infant. No surprise: My
sister gave birth to a girl 17 days ago, and Willa and her
2-year-old brother, Devin, have spoken of little else. ``We're
babysitters, and we're taking care of a little girl,'' Willa
announces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, her old babysitter died,'' replies her friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got really sick, and she died,'' Willa confirms.
</P>
<P>
   Then her friend says to Willa, ``My mommy died.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to one-up her, Willa replies, ``My daddy died. It was a
long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   As Willa launches into talk of angels, I worry outside her door
that she either harbors murderous thoughts toward our babysitter or
would like to knock off both of her parents. Then I remember that
we recently saw ``Madeline,'' a movie that left Willa perplexed.
``Where were Madeline's parents?'' Willa has been asking me. ``Why
did they die?''
</P>
<P>
   After quiet time, I talk with Willa about death and tell her
that, even though everyone dies eventually, she doesn't need to
worry now: Mommy and Daddy are going to live a long time so we can
take care of her. As I say this, I cross my fingers and pray that
guardian angels, of which Willa is so enamored, really do exist.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, August 27: Willa, who is about as strong-willed a
child as you're likely to meet, does not take very kindly to
discipline. At every attempt, she fights me like an ornery bull. So
I am stunned when, on occasion, she repeats my rules, nearly
verbatim, to her stuffed animals_as if they were reasonable after
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to set the timer, and if you're not quiet in 10
minutes, you are all going straight to the barnyard,'' Willa tells
a lineup of dolls today. ``One, two, three...'' she says, counting
to 10. ``OK, everybody back in the barnyard,'' she says, sighing
like a veteran mom. ``Except you, Raggedy Ann.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, August 31: Today was Willa's first day of
prekindergarten, and we made a huge fuss about it. This emboldened
Willa to consider staying at school for a nap, as some of her
classmates planned to do. ``Could I please stay?'' she begged us.
When we told her no, perhaps another day, Willa took the matter
into her own hands. Now, during quiet time at home, Willa has
transformed her room into a classroom. But she's not a kid; she's
the teacher. ``Guys? What are you doing?'' Willa demands of her
pupils, Max, Patrick, Melissa, Lucy and LaKeisha, a seedy
assortment of dogs and dolls. ``Stop! What are you doing? Are you
listening to the teacher?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of you has to go to sleep. If you say that you're
not going to sleep, then you are not going to be allowed to play
outside,'' she says, then pauses for a moment. ``OK, goodnight,
boys and girls. I hope you all have a good sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   I am amused by Willa's insistence on playing the teacher_or,
more often, the mom_but I also feel a pang. Last year, Willa never
napped at school because she was afraid to. When I hear her, I
think, yes, this is a good way to tackle fears, by playing out what
it would be like to nap at school.
</P>
<P>
   But then the mom in me takes over, it pains me that she is
afraid of anything, and I want to rush in, wrap my arms around her
and make everything OK. I stop myself. She'll need these skills to
navigate the sometimes scary terrain of life.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Sept. 3: Willa has invited her Barbie, a frequent
guest, to quiet time today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to make a Lego bridge,'' Willa tells Barbie.
``Actually, it's going to be a dock. It's going to be the longest
dock ever, ever built. No one's ever seen one as long as this.''
</P>
<P>
   On seeing the finished result, Barbie is quick to agree.
``Thatt's a h-u-g-e dock, Willa,'' she marvels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, Barble,'' Willa replies. ``I'm very good at building
stuff.'' As Barbie heads down the dock, however, Willa warns her,
``Watch out. There are crabs down there!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's pretend there aren't crabs,'' Barbie suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. Watch out!'' Willa revises, ``There are all toys down
there!''
</P>
<P>
   Of everything I've heard so far, I enjoy this conversation the
most. It makes me feel as though, amid the chaos and frustration of
raising children, we're doing something right. We've told Willa
that she's good at making things; that she'd be a good architect
(the word means nothing to her) because she's good at drawing.
We've even held her hand when, to her delight and horror, she
caught two crabs with a makeshift fishing pole this summer.
</P>
<P>
   As I listen outside her door, I delight in the way Willas mind
rearranges the pieces of her fife into something more interesting.
From the mundane she creates something magical.
</P>
<P>
   But I also feel wistful. I know my eavesdropping days are
numbered. In a few short months, Willa will no longer have her
quiet time. Even now, I can hardly keep her in her room at night.
</P>
<P>
   And as she grows older, her thoughts will retreat to her mind, a
place I can only hope she'll want to share.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it may just be time to switch channels. As Willa
ventures from her room, her little brother is sitting on his bed
next door, practicing words. ``Devin, like it. Devin, like it,''
he's saying, trying the sentence on for size. It's music to my
ears.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laura Hilgers is a free-lance writer who lives in San Anselmo,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
