<HEADER>
A6011 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-LIFEBEAT-ART-N     02-23 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING KIDS CREDIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color vertical illustration of a skateboarding
teen-ager holding credit cards. The color illustration in JPEG
format is available in minutes by calling Joe Applegate at
212-499-3342 or graphics assistant William Gonzalez at 499-3355.) 
 (Eds: Zakk is cq.) 
 By AMY SCHLEIN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many Americans, Andy Amundsen bought his Christmas presents
this year with his MasterCard _ he likes to rack up the bonus
frequent flyer miles.
</P>
<P>
   A responsible card user, Amundsen does not buy more than he can
afford and keeps track of what he's spending. When the bill comes
in, he matches his receipts to his statement and writes a check for
the full amount. To his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Amundsen, 16, and a high school junior, is one of many college
and high school students rapidly joining the legions of
plastic-carriers. It's a trend that can give them a good lesson in
money management and a jump on a good credit history, or plunge
them into a serious world of debt. It all hinges on how well they
manage the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Teenage Research Unlimited survey, 39 percent of
America's 18 and 19-year-olds have credit cards in their own names,
and 10 percent have access to a parent's card. And a recent study
by Phoenix Home Life Insurance showed that 60 percent of college
students have a credit card, but 20 percent of those surveyed can't
define the term ``buying on credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Before signing a contract for a credit card - or taking a card
on their parent's account - young people should know all the facts
about credit, said Paul Lauterjung of Financial Freedom, a
Petaluma, Calif., money management agency that helps people conquer
the basics of cash flow, set up a livable budget and pay off debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we've worked in the high schools and asked for a show of
hands of those with credit cards, about a third of the kids raised
their hands. And of those, some of them had up to three cards,''
Lauterjung said.
</P>
<P>
   Teens are perfect card-company targets, because they're good
consumers, and they want to be independent of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the 25.2 million Americans aged 13 to 19 spent $96.3
billion, according to the Rand Youth Poll, which anticipates at
least 4 percent annual growth in teen spending in the years ahead.
Because of the abundance of after-school jobs and increasingly
generous allowances, teens have plenty of money to spend. In 1997,
older teens, aged 16-19, had an average income of just over $5,100
a year, according to Rand research. And credit card companies have
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit card issuers are reaching them in high school at the
sophomore and junior level,'' Lauterjung said.
</P>
<P>
   Two main dangers put teens at risk with credit, he said. These
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Overextending themselves by buying more than they can pay
back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting into the ``minimum payment syndrome,'' where card
users pay only $5 or $10 a month, which just covers the finance
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things don't help kids to plan ahead, and they lead to
impulse buying,'' he said. ``It's very easy to get things on credit
that you can't afford.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, there are benefits to teens using
credit cards properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they track where they spend and use credit responsibly,
they'll be more in control of their money, instead of the other way
around,'' Lauterjung said. ``If it increases their money awareness,
that in itself will lead to better decisions down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Amundsen has had his own card on his dad's MasterCard account
for a little over a year. He's allowed to use it at his
convenience, as long as he pays his full balance each month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it for as much as I possibly can,'' said Amundsen, who
has worked at a copy center for four hours a day, three days a week
since the eighth grade. ``I pay for everything with it. Christmas
presents, gas, food, errands for my parents - basically whenever I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule has always been, if he wants to use the card, he has to
pay the balance. It's not an option to put it off until the next
month and pay the finance charge. When the bill comes, he matches
his receipts with the bill and pays his parents with a check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never thought of our credit limit as a chunk of change
that I can go out and blow,'' he said. ``My parents have taught me
a lot about finances. Some of it I became interested in and learned
more about on my own, like CDs and the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``For as long as I can remember my parents have paid the entire
balance for their cards each month. It has definitely helped me see
this as the only way to use a credit card. Besides, why would you
want to pay $40 for a pizza that cost $20? That's an exaggeration,
but it will happen sooner or later if you don't pay your balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Amundsen has considered getting his own card to establish a
credit history, but he's found that many require a minimum income
level of $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   Zakk Murphy, an 18-year-old high school senior in Sonoma County,
Calif., applied for and received credit cards for Target and
Mervyn's stores shortly before he turned 18. He said he got the
cards so he wouldn't have to wait for pay day from his job to buy
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only have money from your paycheck when you get paid every
month, or whatever. So it's easier if you don't have cash, but
you've got the card right there, you can still get what you need,''
he said. ``And you also get discounts for having the card, like 10
percent or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he mostly buys clothes on his accounts, and he pays
the minimum payment amount for the cards each month. ``I've been on
top of it. When I get my checks from work, I divide out what I owe
and pay the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he learned money management on his own - it wasn't
something his family taught him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are learning a lot in economics class,'' he said. ``Since
it's senior year, we're getting some more mature,
stepping-into-life stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hast teaches a high school economics course in Petaluma,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely cover good debt and bad debt, which applies to
credit cards,'' he said. ``Good debt would be something that would
accrue you benefits in the future; bad debt is consumable items,
items that don't retain value, that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't think teens are ready for credit cards,''
he said. ``But they should remember that credit cards are only good
if you follow the guidelines for good credit. Get the low-interest
rate, don't have too many cards, and pay your bills off every
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Hast said, don't assume that all cards are the same: ``You
can obtain a Visa card from anywhere from 9.5 to 24 percent ...
It's easy to pick the brochures up, just shop around for a while
before you fill out the application.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Amy Schlein writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
