<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILOTS-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISGRUNTLED PASSENGERS SUE AMERICAN PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Six American Airlines passengers are suing the
carrier's pilots over flights that were delayed or canceled during
a recent labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on behalf of six Illinois residents whose flights from
Chicago to San Francisco were delayed or canceled Feb. 10, San
Francisco lawyer Patrick Catalano filed a complaint in San
Francisco Superior Court Feb. 18. In it he asks that the lawsuit be
declared a class action so that perhaps thousands of plaintiffs may
join the original six in seeking damages.
</P>
<P>
   Catalano said that while he believed it would be difficult for
individual passengers to prove they had suffered significant
damages, he believed they could collectively describe delay-related
emotional distress and inconvenience that was allegedly a result of
pilots' disobeying a federal court judge's order to end a
``sick-out.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots began returning to work over the Presidents Day
weekend after calling in sick to protest the recent acquisition of
Reno Air by the AMR Corp., the parent of American. The disgruntled
pilots fear the acquisition of the discount carrier will allow
American to parcel out more flights to the lower-paid Reno pilots.
</P>
<P>
   If the San Francisco lawsuit is declared a class action, damages
per person would be limited to $200, Catalano said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300,000 to 400,000 American passengers were inconvenienced
during the labor action. On Feb. 10, the same day the
Chicago-to-San Francisco flights were delayed, U.S. District Court
Judge Joe Kendall in Dallas ordered the pilots back to work. Three
days later, he cited the union, the Allied Pilots Association, in
contempt and fined it $10 million for ignoring the order.
</P>
<P>
   The inconvenience continued for several days after Kendall
issued his order as pilots did not promptly return to work.
</P>
<P>
   The six Illinois residents went to Catalano when they arrived in
San Francisco, on separate American flights, to attend a business
meeting. Their delays were from six hours to three days, Catalano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Pilots Association spokesman Drew Engelke said from the
union's offices in Fort Worth, Texas, that the lawsuit was without
merit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1459EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0133 </DOCNO>
