<HEADLINE>
OLIVE OYL, POPEYE TAKE THE PLUNGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Comic books have always played out the fantasies
of young men, so it should come as no surprise that their male
characters are almost always single and open to playing the field.
Mickey never wed Minnie ``and never will,'' according to a Disney
representative. It took 60 years for Superman to marry Lois Lane,
after which a plot line was promptly introduced where the Man of
Steel split into two separate people. Was the timing coincidental?
(BEGIN ITALICS) No, we don't think so. (END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope better things are in store for Popeye and Olive
Oyl, who tie the knot in a comic released by Ocean Comics this
week. But early signs don't bode well. Popeye once again tells his
decades-long gal, ``I yam what I yam,'' and has only a cigar band
to give her as a ring. He doesn't even take the corncob pipe from
his mouth when he kisses the bride. Ewwww!
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the proceedings are pretty tame until the final page.
After they kiss, Popeye tells Olive, ``So we're finally hitched!
Well, blow me down!''
</P>
<P>
   Olive replies, ``Later, Popeye, later.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1501EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0135 </DOCNO>
