<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POST-MITCH-FARMS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDURAS AND NICARAGUA: FARMING AFTER HURRICANE MITCH  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: 125-word optional trim at 800; total uncut 1,125)   (This excellent 1,125-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 20 Feb. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 800; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS
1,125 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA AND MANAGUA _ Edgardo Serrato points to the river, a
docile trickle of water in the distance. ``That...'' he says, then
swings around and points to the top of his field, ``got up to
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He turns back and indicates the barren, stony landscape on
either side of the river. ``And that,'' he says, ``used to look
like those,'' pointing to a thick patch of trees downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he sweeps his hand across his field, the soil newly
sown with beans, now covered with sand up to half a meter (nearly
two feet) deep. ``And this is what it left us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It,'' of course, was Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   It is nearly four months since Mitch swept through Honduras,
while its wide skirts of rain soaked Nicaragua (and, to a lesser
extent, parts of Guatemala, El Salvador and southeastern Mexico).
</P>
<P>
   The most urgent disaster relief has been done, and the clouds of
rain and rescue workers have cleared. Now for reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Among their many tasks, governments, aid agencies and farmers
like Serrato are assessing the damage to agriculture _ a vital
industry and big export earner _ and the time and money it will
need to recover.
</P>
<P>
   At least the destruction was not as great as was at first
feared. Early estimates put Honduras's crop losses at 70 percent
and the number of its homeless at 2 million (out of 6.3 million).
</P>
<P>
   There was talk of the country being set back 50 years. For the
first few days, with bridges down, cities cut off and water
everywhere, that sounded possible.
</P>
<P>
   Better estimates are now emerging. Central American farming
divides roughly into (a) staples, such as beans, maize and rice,
grown mostly by small farmers, many with only a hectare (2 acres)
or two, who live off their crops and sell any surplus; and (b)
export goods, such as bananas, coffee, cane sugar, sesame (in
Nicaragua) and shrimps.
</P>
<P>
   Beans, ready to be picked, were badly hit: both countries, it is
thought, indeed lost some 70 percent of this crop. But there is
more than one bean harvest a year.
</P>
<P>
   Maize too took a battering, but governments bought seeds for
emergency post-Mitch planting.
</P>
<P>
   Distribution was not brilliant: the mayor of Puerto Cortes, on
Honduras's Caribbean coast, says that promised seeds never arrived
and he had to drum up help from local businesses. But overall both
countries lost only 20 percent or so of the maize they could expect
in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   In commercial crops, Honduras lost nearly half of its bananas
and 20-25 percent of its coffee _ which means, between them, about
one-eighth of its exports.
</P>
<P>
   Nicaragua lost only 6 percent or so of either, but two-thirds of
its sesame.
</P>
<P>
   As for shrimps, for all the flooding of their salty lagoons,
there are even reports that Honduras's shrimp farmers will do
better in the year after Mitch than before.
</P>
<P>
   Crop losses, however, are only the simplest part of the story. A
harder question is what Mitch did to the land.
</P>
<P>
   When rivers that had burst their banks receded, they left sand
up to two meters (six-and-a-half feet) deep. Some small farmers
with fields next to rivers have lost them for good.
</P>
<P>
   Where there is less sand they, like Serrato, can mix it into the
soil, but the mixture does not hold water so well. In the hills,
torrents of water washed soil away, or left it but rinsed the
nutrients out of it.
</P>
<P>
   No one can yet quantify the effects, but at least for a time the
land will be less fertile.
</P>
<P>
   That is bad news for countries whose food output was already
rising less quickly than their populations: according to the World
Food Program, Honduras grew 27 percent less food per person in 1996
than in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But it is much worse news for some individual farmers, since so
many were only just scratching a living anyway. The same goes for
workers on the big banana plantations.
</P>
<P>
   In Honduras, Standard Fruit (a subsidiary of Dole, an American
fruit giant) says it will in time produce as much as before; but
not necessarily in the same spots, and it will take two years just
to replant everything that was washed away.
</P>
<P>
   Overall in the plantations, the result will be temporary or
permanent unemployment for thousands of workers.
</P>
<P>
   At least Standard can afford the $70 million-75 million it
reckons it will need to put its Honduran plantations back in order.
For many subsistence farmers there, the problem is how to replant
at all, and what. Normally, they save enough seed from one harvest
to plant the next. Not this time. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 800) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government bought rice and maize seed abroad, but Hondurans
are choosy about beans: they like a local red variety. ``Seeds of
Hope,'' a scheme sponsored by the United States Agency for
International Development, is supporting farmers _ Serrato is one _
to grow seeds for distribution to others. So are a couple of local
schemes.
</P>
<P>
   But this year such efforts will supply only a fraction of what
is needed for the main planting. Most farmers will have to sow
alien beans for a season at least, and they may get lower prices
for the result. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, recovery involves much more than just replanting and
waiting for the harvest. ``People see a hurricane as a one-off
blow,'' says one American development worker, ``but this is an
ongoing crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Freak rains during January dumped more water on some parts of
Honduras than the hurricane had, and farmers who had tried a late,
post-Mitch planting lost their crops again.
</P>
<P>
   Pests and fungi have flourished in the swampy conditions;
special chemicals and equipment are needed to get rid of them.
Dykes, bridges and roads have to be rebuilt; a lot of the lost
bananas and coffee were not washed away but went bad because they
could not be got to market in time.
</P>
<P>
   Most heavy-duty machinery is still out repairing the main roads,
so local roads are often being restored by hand. Silted-up rivers
must be expensively dredged before the dry season ends in May, or
they will flood again with the first rains.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture officials in both Honduras and Nicaragua reckon
their farms could recover in about five years. Nicaragua's
government plans to spend $1 billion during that time to achieve
it. But neither country has that kind of money, and local banks are
reluctant to lend except short-term.
</P>
<P>
   The governments of the Mitch-hit countries will present their
plans for reconstruction to prospective foreign aid donors, in
Stockholm, in May. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,125-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
