<SLUG> BC-A-LAID-BACK-VOYAGE-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER  
 LUXURY FREIGHTER: LAID-BACK VOYAGE OF THE AMERICANA 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;  wtg882 tac-z
</P>
<P>
   If there's such a thing as a schizophrenic ship, it's the
container ship Americana, says veteran traveler Jim Leveque, now
retired in Mexico. As he puts it, ``Forward, it's sweating,
shirt-sleeved, braying John Wayne, while aft it's immaculate Gene
Kelly relaxing in a cashmere sweater and penny loafers.''
</P>
<P>
   We talked to Leveque about his recent cruise on Americana, the
only vessel afloat designed to haul big, bulky cargo containers and
to cuddle up to 88 passengers in cruise ship comfort at the same
time. The proof of the latter is in the numbers: Out of a crew of
just over 50, fully 30 of those people are aboard solely to pamper
the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Early last summer, the Norwegian-owned Americana _ after
spending its first decade doing 50-day round trips between New York
or New Orleans and South America _ began three-week runs from
Houston to nine ports on the Gulf of Mexico and in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   An appealing aspect of Americana, Leveque says, is that she
never seems, and never is, crowded. Except over the winter
holidays, the ship rarely carries its maximum passenger capacity.
The rest of the year, half to two-thirds full is considered a good
load.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it is relatively full, more often than not fewer than
a dozen people might be found daytime in the lounge or the card
room-cum-library, and not all that many more topside on the
spacious sun deck by the swimming pool. Americana people spend a
good deal of their time in their quarters _ and for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Even the standard double would be considered a suite on any
other ship. It has a parlor area with sofa, coffee table and
windows seemingly large enough to admit Moby Dick. The bathroom
includes a tub and bidet. The deluxe doubles are 25 percent larger
and the suites are twice as big.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers can read from the multitude of books in the library,
or watch a movie chosen from the ship's 400-plus videos. Or they
can venture onto the bridge, which is open round-the-clock except
when entering or leaving port. The officer on watch will help
understand the maps, explain navigation and talk about the cargo,
which could include a 5,000-gallon tank of Barbados rum headed for
the United States, enormous pieces of John Deere farm equipment
destined for Costa Rica or a container of foam food trays and
fabric just picked up in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Americana gets more socialable at mealtimes, during afternoon
tea, at the pre-dinner cocktail hour and for cordials and coffee
afterward, Leveque found. During the latter two periods Shirley
King plays piano, and before bedtime there may be bingo, blackjack
or bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Purser Bill Gable, a veteran of two decades at sea, likened
Americana people to those who went cruising a generation ago: of
adequate age to be affluent _ few are under 60 _ well traveled and
sufficiently cosmopolitan to have nothing to prove to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   They are not, he stresses, at all like those aboard the
1,000-plus passenger ships who pay $700 for a riotous week afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, rarely did Leveque see a T-shirt and only occasionally
jeans. One passenger was shunned for wearing a sleeveless tank top
to breakfast and lunch, Leveque said, until he realized his fellow
passengers considered such attire underwear. Shorts are forbidden
in public areas after 6 p.m., and ``informal'' dinner attire for
men means a nice sport shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional drill and announcements to get ready
for shore excursions, the public address system was rarely used.
There was no encouragement to do this or that at a particular time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like not having to make choices,'' asserted one passenger to
Leveque. ``I like that there aren't any.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Americana travelers are inactive dullards. To the
contrary, most have quite interesting backgrounds, Leveque said,
citing these examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Houston geophysicist who, with his wife, survived
revolutions in a trio of Third World nations, and whose four
children were born in different countries.
</P>
<P>
   _ A former dean of communications and social sciences at the
University of Southern California who was a reliable guide to the
wine list, for before retiring to Mexico he had 600 bottles in his
cellar.
</P>
<P>
   _ An entrepreneur who had lived in France, India, the Virgin
Islands, Hong Kong and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   _ A former music librarian who had done the long South American
voyage on Americana 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   Such addiction isn't all that unusual. One other woman, probably
the recordholder, has taken 14 cruises, and it's rare that at least
a quarter of the passengers on any given trip aren't repeaters.
</P>
<P>
   Fares are seasonal, with the highest roughly from mid-November
through the end of April. A standard double is $4,914 per person
high season, $4,368 the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And you can kiss the hated single supplement good-bye: Singles
pay no more for an outside single cabin than either party in a
standard double _ and windowless, inside quarters are less, $3,780
in high season, $3,360 at other times. All tips are included in the
basic fare. Medical staff members are on board.
</P>
<P>
   Port stops include Cartagena, Colombia; LaGuaira, Venezuela; San
Juan, Puerto Rico; Rio Haina, Dominican Republic; Puerto Limon,
Costa Rica; and Veracruz, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For further information on Americana, call toll-free (800)
451-1639 or (201) 798-5656, or fax (201) 798-7304. The mailing
address is Ivaran Lines, Newport Financial Center, 111 Pavonia
Ave., Jersey City, N.J. 07310-1755.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
