<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6155 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TREND-NYTSF &LR;      02-23 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TREND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTIGENERATIONAL CRUISES 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EVERETT POTTER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It might be a conventional island-hopping cruise in the
Caribbean or an adventure ship off the coast of Costa Rica, a
10-day trip to Riviera ports or a week in the misty waters of
Alaska's Inside Passage. But whether it's parents taking their
children, their own parents or a hybrid group of all three
generations to sail off into the sunset together, multigenerational
cruising is a growing trend.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise ships provide a safe, controlled environment for
children. They can be educational for kids and broaden their
horizons. But if a cruise is chosen with all family members in
mind, it can provide an array of activities for cruise-goers of all
ages as well as ample time for adventure, education and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   These multigenerational cruises can be a way for adults and
their parents to come together, to share the excitement of foreign
travel and enjoy the luxury of a floating vacation. It's a family
reunion joined with the inherent sociability of a cruise ship. On
today's large ships, that means space for private time as well.
</P>
<P>
   For multigenerational cruising, look for cruise lines that offer
a consistently high level of service and a well-planned mix of
activities for various age groups.
</P>
<P>
   Holland America (300 Elliott Avenue W., Seattle, Wash. 98119;
800-426-0327; www.hollandamerica.com) has ships such as the
Statendam, the Maasdam, the Ryndam and the Veendam, all good
choices.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1,613-passenger ship like the Maasdam, even the least
expensive outside double cabins contain twin beds that can be
easily converted to queen-sized and have sitting areas with sofa
and chair.
</P>
<P>
   There are usually two nights out of seven where formal wear is
called for, and white-gloved stewards live up to Holland America's
reputation for pampering. But don't be put off by some of the
formality. Those with teenage children in tow can expect youth
counselors to have organized discos and other activities. While
Holland America excels in general, a ship like the Maasdam is
especially well-suited for classic cruising in Alaskan waters.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean International (1050 Caribbean Way, Miami, Fla.
33132; 800-327-6700; www.royalcaribbean.com) and its megaships such
as Legend of the Seas, Splendour of the Seas and Sovereign of the
Seas are 2,000-plus passenger vessels offering a vast array of
entertainment and dining possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Splendour of the Seas, for example, is a very spacious
2,076-passenger ship that spends its winters in the Caribbean and
its summers in Europe. Play golf on an 18-hole seagoing course,
catch performances in the high-tech theater or stargaze using the
ship's starwheels to point out where each constellation is.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean has a four-tiered kids program, for sailors ages
3 to 17. There are separate kids' playrooms, a Captain Sealy's Kids
Galley Menu tailored to children's appetites and daily ``compass''
itineraries that give kids an hour-by-hour account of daily
activities.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who like true togetherness, Royal Caribbean has
suites that can sleep up to six family members.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity Cruise Line (1050 Caribbean Way, Miami, Fla. 33132;
800-327-6700; www.celebrity-cruises.com) has ships like the
Century, Galaxy, Mercury, Zenith and Horizon, which offer some of
the classiest cruise-going afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging in size from about 1,100 to 1,800 passengers,
Celebrity's ships are a sybarite's delight with stellar
entertainment, good dining and wonderful design.
</P>
<P>
   The price is another factor. Celebrity isn't inexpensive, but it
does provide extraordinary bang for a buck. Priced like Holland
America, its food and service can approach that of a higher-end
cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Galaxy, which has 2,056 passengers. The standard
cabins, with queen-size bed, a large window, two armchairs and a
spacious bathroom by cruise ship standards, is an elegant affair.
</P>
<P>
   As for kids, Celebrity has a notable four-tiered, age-ranked
kids program for children ages 3 to 17, with separate kids-only
clubhouses, teen centers and separate pools.
</P>
<P>
   There are also innovative programs like Summer Stock Theater, in
which kids of all ages first rehearse and then perform before their
parents later in the cruise. The Young Mariners Club offers a
behind-the-scenes look at shipboard life, and there's a Junior
Olympics to make sure that active kids stay active.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy sails in the Caribbean in winter, in Alaska during
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The new 2,400-passenger Disney Magic is the first ship from the
new Disney Cruise Company (210 Celebration Place, Suite 400,
Celebration, Fla. 34747; 800-951-3532; www.disneycruise.com). The
Disney Wonder will join her later in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On a one-week Disney cruise, the itinerary is typically three
days at sea followed by four days at Walt Disney World, or vice
versa. Family cabins that boast a revolutionary one-and-a-half
baths are star attractions in the accommodations area.
</P>
<P>
   As for entertainment, this is Disney, so expect Broadway-style
shows at the Walt Disney Theater and a dizzying array of shipboard
attractions for kids, like Studio Sea for family cabaret acts, ESPN
Skybox for sports nuts and Oceaneer's Adventure for kids ages three
to 12.
</P>
<P>
   At the full-screen Buena Vista Theater are Disney classics and
first-run releases. And there are three themed nightclubs for
adults only.
</P>
<P>
   This ships sails in the waters off Florida and the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance travel
writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
