<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6157 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      02-23 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SURVIVAL OF THE PRETTIEST: The Science of Beauty &QL; 
 &UR; Nancy Etcoff (Doubleday, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   As Mae West said, too much of a good thing can be wonderful.
When do we acquire our appreciation of beauty? Consider the
research of psychologist Judith Langlois. She collected hundreds of
slides of people's faces and asked adults to rate them for
attractiveness. She then showed the slides to 3-month-old babies.
The infants stared significantly longer at faces the adults had
found attractive, and they seemed to appreciate attractiveness
regardless of the subject's sex, race or age. This suggests, Etcoff
writes, that even babies have beauty detectors, and that human
faces might share universal elements of beauty even though their
features are varied. Babies are not immune to the standard; other
studies have shown that parents tend to be more affectionate and
playful with attractive babies. The message of this enlightening
book is that love of beauty is not a cultural lesson but a basic
instinct, a biological explanation for the fact that we cannot
withstand appearances. We can't explain it (when Etcoff asked
people at a modeling agency to define beauty, they described the
experience of (begin itals) seeing (end itals) beauty, and not what
beauty actually looks like), but it has us in its clutches for a
host of ancestral and biological reasons. Although Etcoff allows
that beauty is ``howlingly unfair,'' a genetic given that does not
reflect a person's intelligence or character, she also insists that
it has merit and purpose in the human equation. That, she says, is
why we should remember these measured words from George Eliot, whom
Henry James called ``magnificently ugly'': ``All honour and
reverence to the divine beauty of form! Let us cultivate it to the
utmost in men, women and children, in our gardens and in our
houses. But let us love that other beauty too, which lies in no
secret of proportion but in the secret of deep human sympathy.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MYTHS, LEGENDS &AMP; FOLKTALES OF AMERICA &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by David Leeming and Jake Page (Oxford, $25)
</P>
<P>
   It's said that when the legendary blues singer Bessie Smith was
11, she was kidnapped and taken in a burlap bag to Ma Rainey, who
gave her singing lessons. ``Johnny Appleseed'' was really an
eccentric, homeless man called Jonathan Chapman, who walked
barefoot in the coldest weather and devoted his life to planting
apple seeds in the remote places of the American frontier. Paul
Bunyan never existed at all _ stories about him are called
``faketales'' by folklorists who believe Bunyan was the creation of
lumber companies and chambers of commerce. This anthology also
includes the myths, legends and folktales of Bigfoot, Uncle Sam,
Billy the Kid, George (`I cannot tell a lie'') Washington and
Hiawatha, as well as the mythologies of indigenous peoples and of
the Europeans, Africans and Asians who came later. The tales are
tall, and peculiarly American. ``They serve as mirrors in which a
group of people can see themselves,'' the editors write. ``More
specifically and more often, they are like those mirrors in which
we apply makeup or even disguises, designing images of who we think
we are, how we believe we should appear to the world, and how we
think we should perform in it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WALKING ON WATER: Black American Lives at the Turn of the
Twenty-First Century &QL; 
 &UR; Randall Kenan (Knopf, $30)
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean to be Black? Is there a cohesive answer to
such a sprawling question? Kenan acknowledges from the outset the
arrogance of his original purpose in writing this book _ ``to
chronicle, chart, eviscerate, enumerate, analyze and explain the
nature of Blackness.'' But the question _ what does it mean to be
Black? _ so resounded throughout his life that he decided to travel
the country, talk with ordinary Black people in unheralded jobs and
places, and discover through them what it meant to be Black. He
started in 1991 and planned to spend up to a year on the road,
traveling from place to place in a Jeep he named Bucephalus (``for
though I am not an egomaniac,'' he says, ``I am not unambitious'').
In the end, it took six years, and he came back with no answer
other than that he, like the rest of Black America, is a work in
progress. This book is his response to the people and places he
met. It is, he admits, ``a very bookish book,'' full of long
conversations and his newfound sense of peace even without the
answer to his question. To paraphrase Whitman, he says, ``I contain
multitudes.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FOOTBALL'S BEST SHORT STORIES &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Paul D. Staudohar (Chicago Review, $22)
</P>
<P>
   In Peter Gent's ``Waiting for the Turk,'' a 30-year-old
professional football player faces the end of his career. In
``Sooper Dooper,'' a story composed entirely of dialogue, Frank
Deford writes about the commercial madness surrounding the Super
Bowl (``This ain't no Super Bowl,'' says a small-town reporter.
``It's a supermarket.''). It's a strange alliance, football and
literature, but it works if the names are big enough. Here are
stories by Irwin Shaw, Michael Chabon, Don DeLillo, T. Coraghessan
Boyle, Damon Runyon, John Updike, Grantland Rice and others.
Staudohar edited the previous ``Baseball's Best Short Stories'' and
``Golf's Best Short Stories.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(You can reach Anne Stephenson at
amste.wphenson(at)worldnet.att.net,via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
