<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRTY-DOZEN-TEXAS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC SPECIES PROMPT FEDERAL EFFORT TO FIGHT BACK IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Graphic available on NYT database) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The ``Dirty Dozen's'' siege of Texas may lack the
edge-of-your-seat suspense of ``Jurassic Park.'' When it comes to
generating sheer terror, grass carp, wild pigs, water hyacinths and
the other exotic species that make up the Dozen can't compare to
rampaging raptors.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind both, though, is much the same: Man arrogantly
manipulates nature. Nature bites back.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, exotic species deliberately or accidentally
introduced into Texas have devastated thousands of acres, say
officials of the San Antonio-based Texas Nature Conservancy, which
compiled the list of the 12 worst offenders.
</P>
<P>
   That list, identical to one put together by the organization two
years ago, was released earlier this month as President Clinton
signed an executive order creating the Invasive Species Council.
The multiagency panel has 18 months to develop a comprehensive plan
to battle the unwanted exotics. Nationwide, renegade species are
blamed for declines in population of at least 42 percent of
designated endangered or threatened species.
</P>
<P>
   While Africanized honeybees and imported red fire ants have
grabbed headlines in Texas, Nature Conservancy officials say other
species on the Dirty Dozen list have gone about their destruction
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Grass carp have stripped lakes and bayous of all vegetation;
Chinese tallow trees have overwhelmed coastal prairies; water
hyacinths have clogged waterways; salt cedars have sucked springs
dry; and nutria have destroyed valuable wetlands with their
tunnels. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Rounding out the list are feral cats and dogs, European
starlings, turf grasses and Johnson grass.
</P>
<P>
   All these species, said the Nature Conservancy's David Wolfe,
share two significant traits: They have no natural predators in
Texas, and they are extraordinarily adaptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good number of species on this list,'' he said, ``are good
at reproduction anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THEY JUST KEPT EATING AND EATING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Houston fishing guide Mark Marmon, the grass carp is a thing
of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing an average 6 to 10 pounds, the carp _ a non-native
species imported to clear out the weeds in Texas waterways _ is a
better fighter than redfish, more aggressive than mullet. And, best
of all, it thrives in polluted urban waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who live in Montana,'' Marmon said, ``can go to the
edge of town and have a nice trout stream. What we do is the same
thing, but we don't need to leave town. We just go down to the
bayou. There are some big Mamous in there.''
</P>
<P>
   For state conservationists, though, the grass carp is an
omnivorous horror _ a prime example of the peril of bringing
foreign species into a new setting.
</P>
<P>
   State biologists introduced many of the fish into East Texas
waterways to eat weeds, said Larry McKinney, Texas Department of
Parks and Wildlife's senior aquatics director. But those fish were
sterile. Other carp, introduced by individuals were not sterile _
and the result was alarming.
</P>
<P>
   Once the carp ate the noxious weeds, experts said, they just
kept eating and eating. All lake life fell victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are voracious eaters,'' McKinney said. ``Some years ago
at Lake Conroe, there were so many grass carp that they cleared all
the vegetation out. I couldn't believe it until I saw it myself,
but they then ate the grass from lawns at the water's edge and
leaves from the low-hanging branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a browse line along the lake shore two to three
inches from the water.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`IT'S A HORRIBLE PLANT' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Root by root, tendril by tendril, plants are the stealthy
predators on the Dirty Dozen list.
</P>
<P>
   Countless East Texas streams are clogged with the
purple-blossomed water hyacinth, which began spreading through
Louisiana bayous after it was exhibited at a New Orleans
agriculture exhibition in the 1880s.
</P>
<P>
   In West Texas, the tamarisk or salt cedar _ commonly used as
windbreaks in the desert Southwest _ fill riverbeds and suck
springs dry.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the Chinese tallow _ loved for its brilliant
crimson fall foliage _ is rampaging across the once-pristine
grasslands that surround Galveston Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salt cedar is an arid land plant that has adapted by
robbing water,'' said Fort Davis-based Nature Conservancy biologist
John Karges. ``They extend a deep, deep tap root at the expense of
other things with shallow roots. They're like pine trees in that
they are covered with needles. So they have a huge evaporative
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sterilize the soil, or shade it, so other plants can't
grow. And another thing the little bugger does _ it reproduces and
moves around by wind. You can cut down a tree, but if it's flowered
and produced seed, there will be billions of seeds carried on the
wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Karges said a 1961 survey found the salt cedar infested at least
14,000 square miles of the desert Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying that salt cedars have stolen more water from
the Pecos River than the states of Texas and New Mexico ever have
fought over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in Galveston County, the Chinese tallow is running
amok over thousands of acres.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, the fast-growing tree's seeds were used in the
manufacture of vegetable tallow for candles and soap; the tree was
introduced to the United States in the 1700s by Benjamin Franklin.
As late as the 1950s, government agencies distributed free tallow
seeds to Gulf Coast farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Park and Wildlife's McKinney lamented, ``It's a
horrible plant. Not many things can eat it. It doesn't have much
structure. And it can displace an entire, diverse fauna.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dumesnil, who manages a Nature Conservancy marsh preserve
in Matagorda County, said tallows, like salt cedars, may poison the
ground around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When tallows come into an area,'' he said, ``they basically
out-compete everything else. It's been said that tallow don't
support invertebrates _ beetles, worms _ that benefit warblers and
other insect-feeding birds. That's to say their wildlife value is
minimal to zero.'' Conservationists battle the trees with
herbicides, selective burning and &UR;  &LR; digging up seedlings. Still the
tallows continue to spread.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, roughly 2 percent of Galveston County was infested by
the trees. By 1990, that area had grown to 16 percent, and by next
year, the infestations likely will have increased to 31 percent of
the county, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
YES, THERE'S A PIG PROBLEM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're the hogs from hell _ a classic case of Jurassic pork.
</P>
<P>
   Night after night, marauding through West Texas' scenic Davis
Mountains, the wild pigs plow up acre upon acre in a grunting,
squealing feeding frenzy. Nothing stops them. When the pigs are on
the prowl, even mountain lions stand aside.
</P>
<P>
   The pigs _ some thought to be the descendants of hogs brought to
America by Spanish explorer Hernando De Soto in the 1500s _ long
have been a fixture in the East Texas piney woods and the South
Texas chaparral. Now, though, they have spread to the state's most
remote regions. Wildlife experts at Texas A&AMP;M University estimate
the wild hogs are present in more than 200 of the state's 254
counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are becoming quite a problem,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very large feral hogs,'' said Karges. ``They go to wet
areas and wallow. Rocks the size of bread boxes are flipped up. The
ground looks like it's been churned up with bulldozers.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney said he has found acre upon acre turned up to a depth
of 2 feet by rooting hogs. ``It looked just like a plowed field,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   After examining the markings of captured hogs, Karges said he
believes many are the offspring of domestic porkers that have
escaped captivity. ``In just a few generations, they will revert to
a thin-wasted feral type,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The animals are prodigious breeders, birthing several litters a
year, and formidable fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a mountain lion comes upon a straggler, it's bacon,''
Karges said. ``But mother sows can be quite fierce. Lions normally
won't tangle with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The hogs' threat to endangered species comes from their
willingness to eat anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very wide spectrum of foods they will eat,'' said
Dumesnil in Matagorda County. ``There's predation on small
ground-nesting birds; they'll eat the eggs. They'll eat snakes.
They'll eat dead animals if they're relatively fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
