<HEADLINE>
COURT MAKES IT MORE DIFFICULT TO SUE NCAA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday made it harder to sue
the National Collegiate Athletic Association under a law banning
sex bias in educational programs receiving federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling unanimously, the court said that while the NCAA receives
dues from federally financed colleges and universities, that does
not open it to lawsuits under the anti-bias law known as Title IX
of the Education Acts of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   However, the justices left open the possibility that such
lawsuits still may be allowed. The justices told a lower appellate
court to consider other arguments raised by Renee Smith, an Ohio
woman who says she was illegally declared ineligible to play
intercollegiate volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had argued the NCAA can be sued because the dues it
receives from member schools makes it an indirect recipient of
federal funds. But the high court disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At most, the association's receipt of dues demonstrates that
it indirectly benefits from the federal assistance afforded its
members,'' Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg wrote for the court. ``This
showing, without more, is insufficient to trigger Title IX
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawyer, Carter G. Phillips of Washington, D.C., said he
was not concerned about today's ruling, adding that Smith has a
good chance of convincing the lower court she still should be
allowed to sue the NCAA because schools have given it control of
athletic programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly live to fight another day,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   During arguments in January, the NCAA's lawyers told the court
that the association was not a federal aid recipient and that
athletes should take up discrimination complaints with the
individual schools.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who lives in Wintersville, Ohio, played volleyball for
St. Bonaventure University in the 1991-92 and 1992-93 seasons. She
chose not to participate in the next season, and she graduated in
two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Smith later pursued a graduate degree at Hofstra University and
a law degree at the University of Pittsburgh. At each, her attempts
to play two more seasons of volleyball were blocked by an NCAA rule
that bars graduate students from competing in intercollegiate
athletics at a school other than the one from which they earned
their undergraduate degree.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawsuit said the NCAA grants men a disproportionate number
of waivers from that eligibility rule. The NCAA said more men seek
such waivers and added that a higher percentage of women are
granted them.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court judge threw out Smith's lawsuit, but the
3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated her Title IX claim
last year, saying the NCAA was not ``merely an incidental
beneficiary of federal funds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision overturned that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entities that receive federal assistance, whether directly or
through an intermediary, are recipients within the meaning of Title
IX; entities that only benefit economically from federal assistance
are not,'' Ginsburg wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The justices returned the case to the 3d Circuit appeals court
to hear Smith's arguments that she should be allowed to sue the
NCAA under Title IX because it receives federal funds through the
National Youth Sports Program and on grounds that schools have
handed controlling authority over athletic programs to the NCAA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1612EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
