<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     02-23 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL ROBESON: BELITTLED, OSTRACIZED _ BUT UNBOWED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year would have marked the 100th birthday of Paul Robeson,
actor, singer, linguist, athlete, scholar, author, political
activist and perceived threat, whose human rights achievements have
been all but belittled in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrations and retrospectives have been held across the nation
in honor of the man who adhered to his convictions and paid the
heaviest of prices. An attempt to correct a terrible mishandling of
history? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But also consider this: The controversial Malcolm X has been
honored with a U.S. postage stamp, but there has been no such
recognition for Robeson. Apparently, in mainstream America,
Robeson's achievements are still tainted by the perception _
accurate or not _ that he clothed himself in communism and was
nothing less than a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesdaty night, PBS airs one of the more fairly reported
examinations of Robeson's life. Two hours in length, ``Paul
Robeson: Here I Stand'' uses interviews with friends and family
(including his son, Paul Robeson Jr.), personal papers, letters,
private films, confidential political documents, medical records
and Robeson's wife's diaries.
</P>
<P>
   To thoroughly understand Robeson is to understand the struggles
in which he was engaged and the times in which he engaged in them.
He refused to let success blind him to racism. He refused to sing
before segregated audiences, campaigned against lynching, urged
Congress to outlaw racial barriers in baseball. He spoke on behalf
of aborigine civil rights. As the Cold War intensified, his
political views made him an increasingly controversial figure.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, Robeson refused to accept racial servility in
exchange for a position as a privileged black man.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government and its security agencies, such as the FBI,
which kept tabs on Robeson from the 1940s almost until his death in
1976, would have overlooked his support of the Soviet Union, the
American trade union movement, and even his championing of Africa
and African-Americans, if he'd shown the slightest willingness to
accept racial deference and his ``place.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Robeson's pro-Soviet positions remain controversial, we
should recall that his so-called crimes were merely unpopular
ideas, not necessarily active disloyalty to this country. Wednesday
night's documentary shows how, at the height of Robeson's
popularity, he was a national symbol and cultural leader in the war
against fascism abroad and racism at home. ``Here I Stand'' also
documents in detail his downfall. During the McCarthy era, he was
discredited because of his political views and dedication to the
cause of civil rights. The persecution reached a climax in 1950
when Robeson's passport was revoked; he fought for eight years to
get it back.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, the FBI and State Department killed his career. There
were no more concerts, recordings, theater, radio broadcasts,
publications.
</P>
<P>
   As writer Lloyd Brown puts it, ``Paul Robeson was the most
persecuted, the most ostracized, the most condemned black man in
America, then or ever.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``Here I Stand'' makes clear is that Robeson's politics
left too large a moral stain on his achievements.
</P>
<P>
   All most history books offer on Robeson is this story: He was
the son of a runaway slave and became the third black man to attend
Rutgers University. An all-American football player, he graduated
from Columbia Law School (he left the profession because no one
would work with a black lawyer) and was the first black man to play
Othello.
</P>
<P>
   Was he a communist? His son, Paul Robeson Jr., says he was not.
The elder Robeson would never answer the question because he
thought it unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But Robeson's support of the Soviet Union had less to do with
communism than with his support of freedom, of labor, ]of people of
color, and of working people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
