<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-MAGAZINES-NYT &LR;      02-23 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MAGAZINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD 'ZINES RAISE COVER PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food lovers grumble about higher prices, real or perceived, for
bottled water, California wines and a dish of risotto. Now another
of their indulgences undeniably costs more.
</P>
<P>
   Even though consumer prices are holding steady on average,
nearly all the major food magazines have raised their cover prices
recently, from a few pennies to a couple of dollars: on the
newsstand, food costs more than fashion these days. But subscribers
are not affected yet, and those who buy retail seem not to have
reacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even notice that the price of Saveur went up,'' said
Paige Watson, the vice president of Broadway Panhandler, a cookware
store in New York. ``I haven't heard any comments from my customers
about it. The food magazines just fly off the shelves here. And
people have been paying $5.95 for Fine Cooking all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Saveur, published by Meigher Communications, has raised its
cover price to $6 from $5. ``We wish to continue to be the
premium-price magazine,'' said publisher David Kahn. ``Across the
board, affluent consumers are paying more for better quality,
whether it's microbrews from the Anderson Valley or single-malt
scotch from Islay.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saveur's approach to its subscription price is quite the
opposite: it has started offering eight issues, a year's worth, for
$19.95, down from $29.95, and says the lower price will be in
effect nationwide by the end of the year. ``Our advertisers
demanded it,'' Kahn said. ``Advertising correlates directly with
subscriptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Saveur's single copy sales, accounting for about 13 percent of
total sales, fell 3 percent over the past year, while subscriptions
rose 11 percent, according to a preliminary report by the Audit
Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   At Cook's Illustrated, which went to $4.95 from $3.95, the
publisher and editor, Christopher Kimball, said that a test on
newsstands last year ``found we sold more copies at the higher
price.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With our subscription price of $24.95 for six issues, what we
have done is make an adjustment so people no longer pay less for a
single copy than subscribers,'' he said, adding that his magazine,
which has no ads and is supported by newsstand sales and
subscriptions, isn't especially price sensitive. ``Ours is a
dedicated reader,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Shanken, the editor and publisher of Wine Spectator,
which went to $3.95 a copy in January from $2.95, said ``the new
price is a fair price that recognizes the usefulness and quality of
the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Charging less,'' he said, ``was actually demeaning to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Food Arts, which he also publishes, he said the new $6
price, up from $4, was ``fair.'' The glossy magazine is a trade
publication, with 92 percent of copies given to professionals free
and few sold retail.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Walker, the chairman of Walker Communications, a
consulting company, said that prices for all magazines, not just
those specializing in food, are rising, in part because wholesale
distributors are consolidating. ``There used to be hundreds of
local companies and it was easier for publishers to make deals,''
he said. ``Now there are less than 50 across the country. The
magazines used to be able to count on 45 percent of the price. Now
they're getting less.'' He said publishers also want to increase
revenues from circulation, not just advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Food &AMP; Wine led the pack, going to $3.95 from $3.50 in
September. In January, Cooking Light raised its price to $3.50 from
$2.95.
</P>
<P>
   But the price of Bon Appetit and Gourmet, both published by
Conde Nast, has crept up this year only to $2.99, from $2.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some testing and found that consumers did not react to
the increase, but it has real implications for us in terms of
revenue,'' said Susan Blattman, consumer marketing director for Bon
Appetit, whose total circulation is about 1 million. ``It's become
an industry-wide phenomenon, and we think there's room for us to
increase the price further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
