<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTIPAGE-TEX     02-23 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTIPAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR REPORTER HOPES THIS PAGE IN MUSIC HISTORY GETS TOP BILLING AT
GRAMMYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four or five of us were sitting in my dorm room in 1987, bored
and broke, discussing what we'd do after college besides owe money.
Someone said he planned to be a famous singer, proving that even in
Claremore, Okla., hope could spring within the soon-to-be
disillusioned hearts of freshmen at Will Rogers State Junior
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' I said, ``my great aunt is Patti Page.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patti Page. Like the street.'' Claremore, her birthplace, had
named a street after her: Patti Page Boulevard. ``She says talent
isn't enough. She says you need luck more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The singer-to-be _ I forget his name _ stared at me, puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean to tell me,'' he said, incredulous, ``that they named
your aunt after a street sign?''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was, as it has always been. My contemporaries are
unimpressed with my claim to relative fame: Aunt Patti, 71, who
charted an incredible 111 singles from 1948 to 1982, Billboard's
greatest female pop star ever, a k a my granny's sister. When I was
7, the strangers I accosted at airports (''My great aunt is Patti
Page!'') had no idea whom I was talking about. Now, thanks to my
generation's appropriation of the cocktail culture, there is a hint
of recognition. Still, ask them to name the person whose sobriquet
was ``the singing rage,'' and they're likely to answer, ``Courtney
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm hopeful that Wednesday night's Grammy Awards will change her
Q-rating, if only slightly. (She's up for her wonderful performance
on ``Live at Carnegie Hall _ the 50th Anniversary Concert.'')
Although it's questionable whether Aunt Patti's category, Best
Traditional Pop Vocal Performance, will be televised, she may at
least be able to claim the title ``Grammy winner,'' a designation
that means more to my generation than it should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited, but I'm realistic,'' Aunt Patti says from her
home in Del Mar, Calif. (She's already picked out a new dress for
the show, one that ``hides what I've put on over the years.'') ``If
I don't win, that's fine. But I think the idea of this Grammy is to
honor what I've done in the business. If that brings new fans,
that's great. But it's not like I'm going to be on MTV soon.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone need not worry about her place in the pop-music
pantheon, it's Patti Page. Born Clara Ann Fowler in 1927, the
second-youngest of 11 children, Aunt Patti performed as Ann Fowler
until she took over a radio spot called ``Meet Patti Page,'' a
fictitious corporate spokeswoman for Tulsa's Page Milk Co. She was
discovered and went to Chicago to sign with the fledgling Mercury
Records. In 1948, with a song written for Vic Damone, ``Confess,''
Aunt Patti had her first hit. It also marked a trademark studio
trick of hers that she repeated on several songs, using multi-track
recordings of herself to provide the background vocals instead of
using an orchestra. (She still makes sure to tell youngsters that
she used the technique before Les Paul.) By 1950, she had her first
No. 1 hit, ``All My Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, she made history with a B-side single to the
Christmas tune ``Boogie Woogie Santa Claus.'' She was finishing up
a show at the Copacabana in New York when people started yelling at
her to ``sing the waltz!'' She didn't realize it, but the fans were
referring to the Christmas tune's B-side, ``Tennessee Waltz,''
which soon topped the pop charts. ``We called up the Mercury
distributor and said, what waltz are they talking about?'' she
says. ``He said, `You must have your head in the sand. We've had to
order more records three times already.''' ``Waltz'' became the
third-bestselling single in history (after Bing Crosby's ``White
Christmas'' and the new champ, Elton John's ``Candle in the Wind
1997'').
</P>
<P>
   She was a huge star throughout the decade, hosting her own TV
variety show _ she received much flak from outraged racists when
she kissed Nat King Cole on the cheek after he performed on her
show _ and cutting more hit records. Her last pop hit, in 1965, was
the title track to the film ``Hush ... Hush, Sweet Charlotte.'' All
told, she sold more than 100 million records.
</P>
<P>
   Many were country songs. In fact, Aunt Patti is widely seen as
the first ``crossover'' artist. Although many C&AMP;W traditionalists
despise Aunt Patti's simple, sweet ballads, her success helped pave
the way for Nashville's boom. As Bob Allen and Pete Loesch wrote in
``The Blackwell Guide to Country Music'':
</P>
<P>
   ``At the outset of the '50s, country music was still very much a
rural cult music in terms of its ... `demographic appeal.' Even in
the late '50s, sales of 25,000 on a country hit were deemed
respectable. Yet at the same time, artists like Patti Page and
Rosemary Clooney were having million-sellers with country songs ...
recorded in a pop style. Thus the sound of ringing cash registers
and the allure of the more lucrative pop-crossover market became
the inspiration for the `Nashville sound' ... (which) shaped the
course of country music ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   So here's hoping that the Grammys, which are supposed to honor
the best in pop and country, give something back to Aunt Patti, who
meant so much to both genres. The awards themselves look pretty
hefty, so if she does win, the next time someone asks if she was
named after a street sign, maybe she'll let me use it to knock the
fool upside his head.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Celeste writes for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can
call him at (817) 390-7701. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1623EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
