<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAMPS-80SSYMBOLS-TEX     02-23 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAMPS-80SSYMBOLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'80S SYMBOLS WE WANNA SEE ON OFFICIAL U.S. POSTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who'd've thought that the decade that brought us MTV and
Reaganomics would turn into a philatelist's dream? Here's the deal:
The good people of the neither-rain-snow-nor-sleet mind-set are
honoring the '80s as part of their ``Celebrate the Century''
program. They've picked images for potential stamps from five
categories and are asking we-the-people to vote for up to three of
our favorites in each category. Balloting, which continues until
the end of this month, is set up on a Web site, stampvote.msn.com.
</P>
<P>
   We can't help but love the people who gave us the handy phrase
``going postal,'' but we think they missed some of the '80s icons
of popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Here, respectfully submitted, are our write-in votes.
</P>
<P>
   Category: Lifestyle
</P>
<P>
   Their picks: Video games, aerobics, minivans, mountain biking,
Cabbage Patch Kids, camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   Our choice: Cup holders.
</P>
<P>
   Those wacky postal workers were close, but any soccer mom can
tell you that minivans are OK, but cup holders rock. These nifty
little devices were the real selling points of the minivans. To
each kid, his own juice receptacle, we say. And to each
kid-chauffeur, a sense of peace.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Category: Science &AMP; Technology
</P>
<P>
   Their picks: Personal computers, AIDS awareness, space shuttle
program, compact discs, cable TV, gene mapping
</P>
<P>
   Our choice: Atari's Donkey Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Cable TV? Wasn't that a '70s thing? We suggest replacing it with
the Atari series of video games, specifically Donkey Kong, because
who didn't spend endless zombified hours getting joystick cramp
while trying to reach the next level in this cleverly animated
video game? Sure, it was the same two levels, repeated ad nauseam.
But who could grow tired of battling a giant ape that hurls
fireballs and beer barrels at an Italian plumber? Most importantly,
it introduced the world to Nintendo's future cash cow, Mario. And
by the way, where's the Mario Brothers stamp?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Category: People &AMP; Events
</P>
<P>
   Their picks: Vladimir Horowitz's first Soviet Union concert in
61 years, the fall of the Berlin Wall, the Strategic Arms Reduction
Treaty, the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, the freeing of the American
hostages in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Our choice: ``We Are the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Lighten up, mailmen and -women. Why not choose an event that was
historically and politically important but also involves lots of
easily mocked egos? This was the epitome of rock-star self-impor
... er, charity, in which Michael Jackson and Lionel Ritchie wrote
a song about starving people in Africa, invited several of their
well-fed friends along to sing the song in a video that played
endlessly, and then dropped the subject for most of what remained
of the rest of their careers. We dare the Postal Service to fit all
those big heads on one stamp.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Category: Sports
</P>
<P>
   Their picks: NCAA March Madness, figure skating, Senior PGA
Tour, the Lakers vs. the Celtics, San Francisco 49ers, beach
volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Our choice: William ``The Refrigerator'' Perry doing ``The Super
Bowl Shuffle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the 49ers had the dynasty, winning three Super Bowls in
the '80s. But the Chicago Bears better exemplified that decade of
excess. In Jim McMahon, they had a bad-boy quarterback with an MTV
haircut (he even appeared on the cover of ``Rolling Stone),'' and
they did a ``music video,'' for crying out loud, featuring all
300-pounds-plus of behemoth lineman ``The Refrigerator,'' shakin'
his booty and rappin' (to be charitable) to ``The Super Bowl
Shuffle.'' Seemed like a real act of hubris till da Bears won that
year. Then it just seemed like an act of cheesiness, and cheesiness
must be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Category: Arts &AMP; Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   Their picks: ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial,'' hip-hop culture,
country music, ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' (the book, not the
movie), ``Cats,'' ``The Cosby Show''
</P>
<P>
   Our choice: A dazzling collage of Michael Jackson's glove,
Madonna's bangles and Mr. T's gold chains.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, nothing said entertainment like bizarre fashion
accessories (besides, why would the Postal Service want to feature
``E.T.'' when the alien communicated by phone?). Heck, why stop at
just three things? There's ZZ Top's beards, Prince's purple
vestments, Bruce Springsteen's denim-clad rear end in front of an
American flag, Spandau Ballet's skinny ties, Cyndi Lauper's
multicolored ... everything, and, of course, hair bands, parachute
pants and spandex.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot writes on films and pop culture for the
FortWorth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or
e-mail: robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
