<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRLS FINALLY GET TO STEP UP TO THE PLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am glad that women's sports are thriving and attracting fans
of all ages, races and sexes. For many women, baby boomers and
beyond, that success is a small bit of retribution for all those
years when we were told that girls are not good at sports. With
time has come enlightenment and more opportunities for young ladies
to pursue their interest in sports. Hooray for time.
</P>
<P>
   It's too late for me, though. No one ever tossed the baseball
around with me in the front yard. No one demonstrated the proper
method to soften up a new catcher's mitt with that oily, creamy
stuff. See? I still don't know what it's called. No one put a ball
on a stick and stood by patiently while I took swing after swing
and somehow managed to miss the large stationary sphere. By the
way, that's pretty funny if you haven't seen it. To this day, I
can't play a position in the outfield because I can throw a ball
only about 20 yards without pulling a muscle. No one ever really
taught me how to throw a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Given my background, I understood why little 6-year-old Bruce
didn't pick his best friend, Holly, to be on his baseball team on
that merciless, hot July day at the park. Bruce and Fuji were the
team captains. One by one, they selected players from the group of
kids assembled there. Holly was sure that Bruce would select her,
maybe not first, but eventually, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Nope. He left her standing there. In fact, she was the last one
standing. She went to Fuji's team by default.
</P>
<P>
   Holly passed Bruce on her way to the catcher's position, which
is where they always put the worst player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you pick me?'' she asked him, her eyes filled to
the rim with tears. ``I'm your best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still my friend,'' he said. ``But you stink at
baseball. I want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That made no sense to Holly, but Bruce wasn't trying to hurt her
feelings; he just wanted to win.
</P>
<P>
   The game didn't get off to a good start. Bruce's mostly-boy team
hit three home runs in a row. The girls in the outfield dropped the
balls or let them roll right by. They did manage to fire one ball
toward home plate just as Bruce's pitcher came blasting off of
third base like a cannon. Holly, at catcher, ducked and screamed as
ball and boy approached. The boys laughed at her, even the ones on
her team.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, somehow her team managed to tie the game going
into the last inning. Bruce was up to bat with two outs and a full
count. He hit a pop-up and much to Holly's dismay, she realized
that she would have to catch it. She spun around like a top trying
to follow the ball, then stuck out her hand and closed her eyes. To
our collective delight, some angel put the ball in her glove! But
that's as good as it gets, Holly struck out when her turn came to
bat and the game ended in a tie.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Holly asked Bruce, ``Are you still my best
friend?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he said. ``And I'm gonna teach you how to bat, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So next time I can be on your team?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' he said with a big grin.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's a start.
</P>
<P>
   You go, girls.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
