<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLOGIST-RAINFOREST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ON A MISSION: ECOLOGIST BUILDS RESPECT FOR THE RAIN FOREST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Wayne Takeuchi first went into the vast rain
forest of Papua New Guinea 11 years ago searching for medicinal
plants that could be used by the National Cancer Institute in the
fight against cancer and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Today, under private grants, the Hawaii native works with the
indigenous clans of the largest island nation in the South Pacific,
teaching them to value the plants for their own sake _ whether they
are ever developed into wonder drugs or not _ and showing them how
to use their natural resources without depleting them over the long
haul.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 95 percent of the plant specimens growing in New
Guinea are found nowhere else in the world, Takeuchi says, and
although most of the people of New Guinea live in palm-leaf and
bamboo huts and get their food, fuel, medicine and virtually all of
life's raw materials from the forest, they take their natural
treasures for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Takeuchi, who has worked for the Botanical Research Institute of
Texas the past three years, made his first visit to Fort Worth last
week to meet with his associates at BRIT, which is headquartered
here.
</P>
<P>
   In what is known as an Integrated Conservation and Development
Program, Takeuchi is helping a group of 50 clans collect and index
their plants and develop ecotourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for them to believe people will pay just to see the
rain forest,'' Takeuchi says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I help them assess the value of nontimber products, such as
nuts and ecotourism. Things they can do on their own to improve
their economy without sacrificing any of their natural resources,''
says Takeuchi, 46. ``The developing world is very protective of
their biological wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bioprospecting _ finding and developing plants for their
economic value _ has become a political hot potato, and the Papua
New Guinea government has called a temporary halt to that form of
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing now is pure research, not economic
development,'' says Sy Sohmer, BRIT's director, who worked with the
forest service in New Guinea 20 years ago. ``We teach them to
evaluate the resources they have by international protocols.''
</P>
<P>
   Those resources appear to be vast.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1979, every time I went out into the forest, half the
specimens I would bring back would be brand new,'' Sohmer says. ``I
cataloged 127 specimens of trees and shrubs, and half were new
discoveries.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 90 percent of the large South Pacific island was covered
with primary rain forest then.
</P>
<P>
   No one has any idea how many new specimens are still to be
discovered in New Guinea. Thousands of square miles of primary rain
forest _ about 65 percent to 70 percent of the island _ remain with
trees taller than 20-story buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 20 completely unknown areas remaining,'' says John
Pipoly, head of BRIT's floras program. ``We have only satellite
images of them. No biological scientist has ever set foot there.''
</P>
<P>
   By helping the people of New Guinea preserve their own
biological wealth, BRIT also hopes to help, in part, to protect the
world against disasters associated with El Nino's wide-ranging
climatic impact such as last summer's fires in Mexico, greenhouse
gases and global warming, Sohmer says.
</P>
<P>
   Fires destroyed more natural resources around the world in the
last two years than at any other time in recorded history. Many of
the fires were started by people but quickly blazed out of control
due to high temperatures and lack of rain. Thousands of acres of
grassland and rain forests in New Guinea burned, including
protected areas.
</P>
<P>
   When you destroy the forests, you destroy insurance against
future natural disasters, Sohmer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not finding out what the plants are good for, but we are
training the people who live there and own them to be the best
possible stewards of them so they won't just disappear,'' Pipoly
says. ``The stewards of the world are the people living in the
forests and savannas and grasslands.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
