<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOTEL-BARS-3TAKES-     02-23 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOTEL-BARS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL BARS: SOME OF THE CITY'S MOST SECLUDED OASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City is filled with unappreciated treasures.
But in the world of food and drink, none are so neglected as hotel
bars.
</P>
<P>
   They have been here for ages, planted like pillars around the
city. Many are elegantly decorated, like miniatures of the grand
hotels that engulf them. And perhaps it is for that reason that
they tend to be overlooked by New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the barrier of the hotel lobbies lay some of the
city's most secluded oases, where you can relax over a well-mixed
drink, be treated like a king, or simply be as anonymous as the
bars themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Spending time in one, in fact, can be as much of an escape as a
walk in Central Park _ a brush with seclusion and quiet, a moment
to step out of your citified soul and collect your thoughts. But
unlike Central Park, a hotel bar offers you comfortable sofas,
tinkly music, a great selection of wine and liquor, and, often,
tasty _ and free _ salty snacks.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as you inquire about the protocol for getting a
table _ whether it's giving your name to the host at the King Cole
Bar at the St. Regis or calling ahead to the bar at Morgans Hotel
for a reservation _ you're likely to take to it as naturally as a
splash of vermouth to a jigger of gin.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel bar is indeed an unusual social confluence. From
morning to night, the clientele can vary from delicate women
sipping on rum to portly businessmen lighting up cigars. Some may
be hiding, hovering over a scotch, others may be waiting nervously
for a date to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers drift in and out. Regulars cling to their corners.
Women feel comfortable walking in alone.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel bars have long been a part of city life. When elegant
hotels began cropping up around the city in the last century, said
Michael Batterberry, a co-author with Ariane Batterberry of ``On
the Town in New York'' (Routledge, 1999), hoteliers depended on
their bars to make up for financial losses in their restaurants.
They pushed bar life, which was then customarily only for men.
</P>
<P>
   ``They served as the public version of private men's clubs,''
Batterberry said. New York was a boom town then and so the bars
were open from early in the morning until late at night. Men went
there to socialize, to do business, to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Bartenders became creative salesmen. ``A first-rate bartender of
one of the great hotels of the last century was expected to
maintain a working repertory of at least 150 cocktails, shrubs,
slings, punches, cobblers, juleps, smashes, flips and nogs,'' the
Batterberrys write. ``These were consumed at all hours of the day
and night; `cocktails,' however, were first ordered only as
eye-openers.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the drinks may be less flashy, the hours shorter and
the drinkers perhaps less zealous, but that special something that
a hotel bar can capture is no less palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Many of city's hotel bars evoke another age. They have
wood-paneled walls, worn leather banquettes, and bartenders who
still consider drink mixing and casual conversation to be art
forms. Watching Jose Ortiz at the Bemelmans Bar in the Carlyle
Hotel is like watching a dancer. Every motion, from plucking a
napkin off of the stack to placing a skewer of olives over your
martini, is fluid and graceful.
</P>
<P>
   A hotel bartender's pace is generally slower than those in the
outside world, but they pay attention to you. Go a few times and
they will learn your name. You will learn theirs, too.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Winters, a money manager at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
has known Ortiz for 25 years. Other nights, when Winters arrives at
the King Cole Bar, he does not even feign a motion to order. As
soon as Wolfgang Hauck, one of the bartenders, sees him
approaching, he begins pouring him a glass of chardonnay and asks
him how he's been.
</P>
<P>
   If not for skillful bartending, then the snacks at some of the
hotel bars are reason enough to go. At the Bemelmans, for instance,
there are crisp little potato chips, made at the hotel, and pewter
bowls of fat, buttery cashews. Some hotel bars offer full menus.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oak Bar at the Plaza you can order oysters with a
martini, or depending on the strength of your stomach, a Reuben.
And if you manage to get a seat at the Fifty-Seven, Fifty-Seven bar
in the Four Seasons Hotel, don't pass up the food. The salmon
croquettes with caviar, the tuna sashimi, even the salad are all
exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   Snacks and a friendly bartender can do wonders, too, to allay
the shock of the bill, which, without a drink, might be difficult
to take. Hotel bars are not cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, no price can be placed on the ambiance, or that
brief feeling of seclusion in a city where escape is the only
antidote to the daily chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The Classics
</P>
<P>
   From the marble tea room in the St. Regis Hotel, the King Cole
Bar may look like an opening to a dark cave, but inside it feels
more like a theater. All attention is drawn to the stage-like bar
and the fabulous Maxfield Parrish mural of King Cole on his throne,
which glows like a warm fire across the back of the room.
</P>
<P>
   In the early evenings, the bar is dotted with clusters of men in
suits, huddling in small groups and chewing on cigar ends. There
are often a couple or two who look as though they've been there for
years. The corners of the room are dark and the banquette seating
is low. It is a good place to disappear from the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But you are never completely unnoticed. Hauck, 43, the
bartender, keeps a close eye on the level of everyone's drink. On a
recent evening, a customer asked him how long he'd been there.
``Since the beginning of time,'' he said, then roared with
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't happen to be on your way to Lespinasse next
door, there is plenty to nibble on. In fact, bar snacks don't get
much better. A regular said you need a fork and knife to eat the
macadamia nuts in the mixed nuts, which are served in a silver
dish. That's about right.
</P>
<P>
   You can also order a sumptuous feast. That is, if you live on a
trust fund. Prosciutto and melon would be perfect with a martini
there; an order is $19.
</P>
<P>
   The Bemelmans Bar at the Carlyle is just as dark and secluded,
but less boisterous. Piano sets twice a night temper the noise
level, and it is often quiet, especially on weeknights. It is a
place for a tete-a-tete, not a business deal.
</P>
<P>
   You can sit alone at the bar, mesmerized by Ortiz, a master of
the martini. On a recent evening, two well-dressed men sat a few
stools apart in silence. Both had been coming for decades. But they
had never met.
</P>
<P>
   The Hideaways
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hotel bars in the city are cloistered within their
hotels. They are small, intimate and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The bar in the Mark hotel, on the Upper East Side, for instance,
never really roars. The noise that rises from the people sitting in
the small hidden chamber is barely audible, more like a purr.
</P>
<P>
   A server in a tuxedo and a woman behind a small bar discreetly
look after their customers as if they were guests in their home. A
bucket of chilled Champagne is near the door and drinks are served
in small, delicate glasses.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of lit cigarettes and perfect manicures but as
in many of the best hotel bars around the city, the crowd is
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place is filled with fashion people,'' said Harriet
Jagger, an editor at Tatler magazine in London in town for Fashion
Week. ``They're from Harvey Nichols,'' she pointed, ``My friend
here's from French Vogue.'' Another night it was full of Asian
businessmen drinking Budweisers from bottles. You never know.
</P>
<P>
   There are even groups of young people settled into the forest
green sofas and miniature floral slipper chairs. ``I don't want to
go to bars that smell like my fraternity house,'' said Robert
Goner, a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   He does not go to make friends or to eat _ the hors d'oeuvres
are about as good as wedding food _ but to pause before going out
for the night. He has a martini and rounds up friends on his cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cafe Pierre, in the Pierre Hotel, is similar. Swathed in
floral patterns you would expect in a Fifth Avenue apartment, it is
a place you could take your grandmother for a Manhattan, or meet a
date.
</P>
<P>
   Journeys at the Essex House, though, with its masculine
wood-paneled walls and fireplace like a university club, might be
better for your grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   The Lounges
</P>
<P>
   Boutique hotels like Morgans, the Mercer and W New York are
redefining hotel life with settings that feel more like downtown
clubs than corporate lobbies. And if you can actually find the
hotels _ few seem to have signs out front _ you will see that they
have also changed the concept of the hotel bar. They have become
more like lounges.
</P>
<P>
   At W New York, the lobby bar is furnished all in natural colors
with shared ottomans divided by triangular pillows and butcher
block tables with checkerboards burned into the top. It is a place
for sprawling and socializing; and the loungers are young.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgans bar feels more like a cave. You descend a dark
staircase and enter through velvet curtains. The walls are brick
and hung with candles. A long underlit marble table that stretches
through the center of the room encourages mingling. It is loud and
dark, and you soon forget you are in a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But many of these boutique hotel bars teeter on the edge of
obnoxiousness. The long hall of 44 at the Royalton, for instance,
is austere and attracts a publishing crowd. It's the kind of place,
said Adam Peck, a television producer and regular, ``where you sit
there looking fabulous and aggravated.'' Perhaps it is the $13
drinks that are so ``aggravating,'' or the cement steps you must
sit on because all the sofas are taken.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Mercer, though, that exemplifies the kinks that these
new hipper-than-thou hotels need to work out. It feels like the
Calvin Klein store on Madison Avenue, and the hospitality can be
just as minimal. On a recent evening, an experience at the hotel
went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   I entered alone and sat down in a chair that looked comfortable.
All around me were knots of people, some of whom looked barely out
of their teens, dressed like they just walked out of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   After many minutes, a server finally approached. Instead of
taking my order, she and asked me to move into the bar area: the
comfortable chairs were for hotel guests. So I did and I approached
an empty table. Then, a different server came over to tell me the
empty table was taken.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   I scanned the room and suggested a few places where I could
easily fit. She refused and then directed me to the bar downstairs.
There I stood for 10 minutes. No one approached this time. Not even
to take my order. It was a corner of neglect in one of New York's
most convivial arenas.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a choice of some of the best hotel bars in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   BEMELMENS BAR The Carlyle, 35 East 76th Street, (212) 744-1600.
Hours: Tuesday to Saturday, 11 a.m. to 2 a.m.; Sunday, noon to 1
a.m.; Monday, 11 a.m. to 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: Dark and sedate, with lots of corners to tuck in to.
Pianists at 5:30 p.m. and 9:30 p.m. Both the daytime and nighttime
bartenders have been there for 40 years, so they know how to mix a
martini.
</P>
<P>
   CAFE PIERRE The Pierre, 2 East 61st Street; (212) 838-8000, ext.
6499. Hours: Daily, noon to 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: It could be a French Embassy tearoom. The bar is dark
and empty and the cheese puff snacks depressing; the beautifully
covered chairs that line the long, narrow room are the places to
settle in. A pianist begins playing at 8:30 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   FIFTY-SEVEN, FIFTY-SEVEN The Four Seasons, 57 East 57th Street;
(212) 758-5757. Hours: Monday to Saturday, 3 p.m. to 1 a.m.;
Sunday, 3 p.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: The drinks are as big and beefy as the pin-striped
clientele. It is a beautiful space paved with silky wood panels,
but not beautiful enough to make it worth battling the crowds at
cocktail time. Later, when tables are open, you can order off the
smart bar or restaurant menu: tuna sashimi, steak, even
strawberries with lemon sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   44 The Royalton, 44 West 44th Street; (212) 944-8844. Hours:
Tuesday to Saturday, 3 p.m. to 1:45 a.m.; Sunday to Monday, 3 p.m.
to 12:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: A sleek, austere corridor lobby filled with chic
women. At lunch and after work it has the volume of a college
cafeteria. Station your party in different spots to scout a free
table; or, if you're really ambitious, try to snag a seat in the
tiny, round vodka room. For $13 you can get a good Kir royale, a
hard cement step to sit on and a lot of attitude.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNEYS Essex House, 160 Central Park South (Avenue of the
Americas); (212) 484-5159. Hours: Sunday to Saturday, noon to 12:30
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: An old-style men's club with a lot of women filling up
the leather sofas. There is a fireplace with gas logs and a small
room with a fountain that's worth a peek.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wildly unpredicatable crowd. In a single evening you
could witness people making business deals, a failing blind date
and a group of 20-somethings whooping it up.
</P>
<P>
   KING COLE BAR The St. Regis, 2 East 55th Street; (212) 350-6998.
Hours: Monday to Thursday, 11:30 a.m. to 1 a.m.; Friday and
Saturday, 11:30 a.m. to 2 a.m.; Sunday, noon to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: A theater-like setting with hosts who control the
seating like ushers. Go early or after 7 p.m., and dress well. The
many regulars do business on their cell phones or sit in silence.
If the bar nuts _ the best in town _ are not filling enough, there
is a menu with everything from chicken consomme to caviar. Make
friends with someone who will pay.
</P>
<P>
   MARK'S BAR The Mark, 25 East 77th Street, (212) 744-4300. Hours:
Daily, noon to 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: A cozy tea room that feels like a luxury train car.
The furniture is small and tall men in the Biedermeier chairs look
as though they are sitting on tricycles. But it hasn't kept them
away. It is an older, European crowd. And it never seems to be
busy. Try the bloody Mary, made with a maceration of peppercorns
and vodka.
</P>
<P>
   MERCER KITCHEN The Mercer, 147 Mercer Street (Prince Street);
(212) 966-6060. Hours: Daily, 8 a.m. to 10:45 a.m., noon to 2:45
p.m., 6 p.m. to 1:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: Cool lighting and clean lines make it feel like the
set for a fashion shoot. Identification is probably not necessary,
but something with a Prada tag may be. There are no off-hours.
</P>
<P>
   MORGANS BAR, Morgans, 237 Madison Avenue (37th Street), (212)
686-0300. Hours: Monday and Tuesday, 5 p.m. to 2 a.m.; Wednesday to
Friday, 5 p.m. to 4 a.m.; Saturday, 6 p.m. to 4 a.m., Sunday, 6
p.m. to 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: A gypsy's den lit with candles. It gets busy after 8
p.m., filling up with a young crowd whose voices bounce off the
brick walls. Small, low tables are best for a tete-a-tete; the long
marble communal table guarantees mingling.
</P>
<P>
   OAK BAR The Plaza, Fifth Avenue at Central Park South; (212)
546-5330. Hours: Monday to Saturday, 11:30 a.m. to 1:30 a.m.;
Sunday, noon to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: A beer hall filled with men in suits. A television set
lowers the tone. To get a seat before 8 p.m., you can ask to sit in
the Oak Room next door. There you can relax in a worn leather
chair, sip on a drink, nibble on the world's largest raisins and
watch the table after table of gray-haired men muttering to one
another.
</P>
<P>
   OASIS BAR W New York, 541 Lexington Avenue (49th Street); (212)
755-1200. Hours: Sunday to Thursday 11:30 a.m. to midnight; Friday
and Saturday, 11:30 a.m. to 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ambiance: California and casual. One day it is calm and
Zen-like, the next it is filled with ``Friends'' cast lookalikes.
The menu is also very California: flatbread and hummus, chicken
satay with curry yogurt sauce, carrot ginger lemongrass soup, power
protein wraps and smoothies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
