<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      02-23 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TWO-DAY MARINADE GIVES ZEST TO SEA BASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 This is the fourth of eight columns by Rick Moonen, the executive
chef and an owner of Oceana in Manhattan. His collaborator on these
columns is Dorie Greenspan.  
 By RICK MOONEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If cooking is as much alchemy as chemistry, here is the dish to
prove it: Chilean sea bass metamorphosed by a two-day submersion in
a miso marinade, then broiled until it is as brown and shiny as a
perfectly barbecued rib.
</P>
<P>
   Two days is a long time to marinate anything, particularly fish,
but it takes that long for the marinade to work its magic. It is a
blend of orange juice and zest, brown sugar, sake, a light miso
paste and the pungent chili paste called sambal oelek.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean sea bass, which is actually Patagonian tooth fish,
starts out as what I call a Jell-O fish: its flesh is soft, wet and
oily. Steam it and its texture will remind you of soft-boiled eggs.
But cover it with the marinade and all that changes, strikingly.
</P>
<P>
   The marinade's salts and sugars act as a cure and turn the soft
fish into one that flakes in large, firm shards. Marinated, the
Chilean sea bass comes to resemble cod, but creamier and richer.
</P>
<P>
   And after two days, it is not just the texture that changes. The
fish is imbued with the salty, sweet, bitter, acidic flavors,
complexity and exotic richness of the marinade's ingredients, many
of them rooted in the traditional cooking of Japan, and all of them
intensified when the fish is cooked.
</P>
<P>
   I top the glazed fillets with cilantro leaves and surround them
with a salad of mango and scallion greens splashed with a citrusy
dressing, an integral part of the dish.
</P>
<P>
   The fish calls for the coolness and sharpness of the salad and
its dressing, whose flavors are haunting but immediately appealing.
The crisp citrus taste in the dressing comes from the
citrus-flavored soy sauce called ajipon, and from yuzu kosho, a
chili paste that includes yuzu, a Japanese citrus fruit prized for
the oils in its skin. To pull the flavors into balance, I add
mirin, a sweet Japanese rice wine, and rice wine vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   You may have to make a few shopping trips to collect the
ingredients for this dish, but I promise you they will be worth
it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MISO-GLAZED CHILEAN SEA BASS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes, plus 2 days for marinating the fillets &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 oranges
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   { cup light-brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   } cup sake
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups light miso paste (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sambal oelek chili paste (see note)
</P>
<P>
   6 skinless fillets of Chilean sea bass, each about 7 ounces
</P>
<P>
   \ cup ajipon (see note)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup mirin (see note)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup seasoned rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup soybean oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon yuzu kosho (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, peeled and finely shredded
</P>
<P>
   { daikon, peeled and finely shredded
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe mango, peeled, pitted and cut into short, thin strips
</P>
<P>
   3 scallions, green parts only, thinly sliced diagonally
</P>
<P>
   6 sprigs cilantro, leaves only. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare marinade: Using a vegetable peeler, remove zest
(avoid the white pith) of 1 orange in about 6 wide slices. In a
small saucepan, combine slices of zest, orange juice and brown
sugar. Bring to a boil, then lower heat and simmer until reduced to
one-third. Turn heat to its lowest setting, and stir in the sake,
miso paste and chili paste. Stir for 10 minutes, then remove pan
from heat. Transfer to a bowl, and cool quickly by placing over
ice.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place fish and marinade in a large zipper-lock plastic bag,
making sure fish is coated with marinade. Press out the air, and
seal securely. Refrigerate for 2 days.
</P>
<P>
   3. To prepare yuzu dressing: Finely grate the zest of remaining
orange. In container of a blender, combine grated zest, ajipon,
mirin, rice vinegar, soybean oil and yuzu kosho. Puree until
smooth. Set aside at room temperature, or refrigerate up to 4 days.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat a broiler with a rack 8 inches from source of heat.
Remove fillets from marinade, and place on a metal baking pan. Add
a few spoonfuls of water, and brush fillets with just enough
marinade to glaze them. Broil until deeply browned and cooked
through, about 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   5. While fish is broiling, heat a medium skillet over high heat.
Add vegetable oil, carrots, daikon and 1 tablespoon of water. Saute
until heated through, about 1 minute. Season with soy sauce. Remove
from heat.
</P>
<P>
   6. Place a portion of sauteed vegetables in center of plate. Top
with a fillet and a sprig of cilantro. Surround with mango and
scallion slices. Drizzle yuzu dressing over mango. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Miso paste may be found in health food stores. Sambal
oelek, ajipon and mirin may be found in Asian food stores. Yuzu
kosho may be ordered from Young Land Trading, (718) 229-5535.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1633EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     02-23 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, Feb. 24. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ After 17 days of
negotiations, the ethnic Albanians agree to sign a Kosovo peace
agreement within two weeks, the State Department spokesman says. He
says ethnic Albanians said they would sign after ``technical
consultations'' with the people in Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RITTER (Washington) _ U.N. officials denounce Ritter, the
former arms inspector, and the conclusions of his book on the
misuse of arms inspections by the U.S. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Lebanese guerrillas firing machine
guns ambush Israeli commandos in southern Lebanon, killing three
officers and wounding five other soldiers. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   ALPS-AVALANCHE (Rome) _ An avalanche crashed through a small
Austrian resort and left at least seven people dead and dozens
missing, in one of the worst Alpine snow disasters in years. Snow
and deadly winds prevented emergency helicopters from flying into
the ski village of Galtuer, near the Swiss border. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional leaders of both
parties meet with Clinton for the first time in 19 months and also
talk to the nation's governors. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-COUNSEL (Washington) _ On eve of congressional
hearings, more on the independent counsel act. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DRAGGING-DEATH (Jasper, Texas) _ A white supremacist, John
William King, was convicted in the dragging death of James Byrd
Jr., a black man. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS (New York) _ Looking at the legal basis for
Mayor Giuliani's policy to seize cars even after a driver accused
of drunk driving is acquitted. By Alan Finder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FED-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Greenspan, delivering his
semiannual testimony to the Senate Banking Committee, says the
economy retains considerable momentum with no evidence of
inflationary problems. But he adds that dangers remain, ranging
from a potential stock market crash to the possible development of
inflationary pressures. The Fed stands ready to quickly raise or
lower interest rates if the economy grows too fast or too slowly,
he says. He again issues a warning about the level of stock prices,
but he does not appear to be as worried as in the past. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-EURO (Zurich, Switzerland) _ It isn't one of the 11 euro
nations _ it isn't even a member of the European Union _ but that
hasn't stopped Switzerland from embracing the continent's new
common currency with an enthusiasm that eclipses even the euro
euphoria of some of its large neighbors. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EURO (London) _ The British prime minister, Tony Blair,
announces his government's plans for adopting the euro. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS  &LR;  (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-POUND (Undated) _ A profile of Dick Pound, the American who
has emerged as the IOC's internal investigator. By Richard
Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
