<HEADLINE>
GOP GOVERNORS STEP TOWARD BUSH ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michigan Gov. John Engler said Tuesday that many of
his Republican colleagues are ready to endorse Texas Gov. George W.
Bush ``with an eye toward winning'' the 2000 presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   An endorsement from the governors is important, Engler said, to
galvanize support and create a network ``to get our candidate
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``National campaigns are hard. It's not too early to start
thinking about what we need,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Engler said he canvassed the 31 GOP governors over the weekend
to gauge support for Bush and found about two-thirds would support
the Texas governor, who has not yet announced that he is a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Marc Racicot of Montana said the endorsement would be
released when 15 or more signatures are collected. That could come
within days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of my colleagues looked at 2000 with an eye toward
winning, and we feel George W. is a candidate who can run strong,
coast to coast,'' Engler said on the final day of the National
Governors' Association meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was honored by the support he has received from
fellow Republicans during the gathering of governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of friends who, I guess, want to stand up and
say, `I'm for George W.,''' Bush said after a closed-door meeting
with Texas lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, though, reiterated that he would continue to work on state
business in the Texas Legislature before making a presidential
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to announce an exploratory committee within weeks
that will allow him to test the waters and begin raising money for
a national campaign once the state's legislative session ends in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a job to do. I'll be in my state, doing my job, doing
the job I was elected to do,'' said Bush, 52, the son of former
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bush said he was undecided about running for the
presidency, lawmakers from his state are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he look undecided to you?'' said Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is the clear, dominant front-runner in this
race, and the odds are he is going to win the election,'' said
Gramm, who ended his failed presidential bid in 1996 after the Iowa
Republican Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's stature as a candidate who can bridge gaps
between the party's moderate and right-wing factions, and his
powerful allure among Hispanics in Texas, not all 31 of the
nation's Republican governors are prepared to endorse the Texan.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, the New York Republican who is often
mentioned as a presidential candidate, praised his colleagues for
``taking an active role and stepping out in front'' by supporting a
candidate early in the presidential nomination process.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki said he would not join just yet in supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to sign the letter,'' he said of the
endorsement driver among GOP governors. ``I am not going to endorse
a candidate who hasn't declared. I am not endorsing any candidate.
It's too early in the process for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters said his landslide re-election in November _
with 49 percent of the Hispanic vote and strong support from other
minorities and women _ is an electoral blueprint that can help the
GOP reclaim the White House after eight years of the Democratic
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Connecticut Republicans want to attract more
African-Americans, more Hispanics,'' Gov. John Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said a letter from Republican governors endorsing a Bush
candidacy would be ``more for his encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said an endorsement would advance a message of inclusion
that some Republicans fear will be overshadowed by rhetoric coming
from the religious right-wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tenure and experience as a state executive also attract
the support from many of the governors.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating has joked that Bush is the
``governor of a country down there in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some governors, meanwhile, have voiced their support for other
potential candidates who may seek the GOP nomination, like former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, former Vice President Dan Quayle,
and Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, the former Red Cross president and wife of 1996
GOP nominee Bob Dole, has launched an exploratory committee and has
high ratings in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But governors have been cool to her potential candidacy because
she has not held an elective office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are serious about winning, then I don't think we are
going to nominate somebody who has never run for an office
before,'' Engler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
