<SLUG> BC-NUN-CD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUN'S MEDIEVAL MUSIC RE-ENGINEERED FOR MODERN TIMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By   DAVID BLOOM 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES &UR; _  &LR; Hildegard of Bingen is an unlikely figure for
20th-century pop veneration, yet here at the end of the millennium
the 12th-century German mystical nun, herbalist and composer is
building quite a fan base, bolstered recently with an atmospheric
CD by Jocelyn Montgomery, produced by David Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish-born, classically trained Montgomery first learned
Hildegard's music in London, with a vocal group that focused on
early medieval music.
</P>
<P>
   After years of singing Hildegard's music in churches, busking
with madrigal singers on London streets and working in other
classical music settings, she landed her first record deal, to sing
Hildegard. Then she had to find a producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man who suggested going ahead and doing a solo recording
felt that it needed a contemporary context,'' Montgomery said. ``We
threw out several names and David's came up. He was in the process
of building an amazing studio in his (Hollywood Hills) home. He
heard me sing a little bit of it and was immediately interested in
going in the studio after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch had long collaborated with Montgomery's husband, film
producer Monty Montgomery, on film and TV projects, and had some
background producing soundtracks related to his work. But his
offbeat reputation (he created the TV series ``Twin Peaks'' and
films ```Blue Velvet'' and ``Eraserhead'') still made Lynch an
unusual choice to update 800-year-old sacred music, Montgomery
concedes.
</P>
<P>
   Even odder was her choice for co-producer: German documentary
maker and Hildegard aficionado Heidrun Reshoeft, with whom
Montgomery spent a week in the Rhine River Valley convent where the
nun lived.
</P>
<P>
   But the odd combination of talents, nonetheless, paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting ``Lux Vivens'' (on Mammoth Records) is an
ethereal, almost cinematic album of monkish mood music for the
post-medieval. It's just that getting there was, perhaps
unsurprisingly, more like making a movie than an album.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, as recording began on each song, someone would
read translated versions of Hildegard's surreal Latin lyrics to
Lynch, so he could visualize the song's meaning and imagery,
Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely was directing the process in a great way, and
encouraging and insightful about what would set up a mood and bring
things out vocally,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With those images in his mind, Lynch had Montgomery sing each
piece in virtually unbroken takes ``to not interrupt the flow of
the chants,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she, Lynch and other musicians would record instrumental
tracks (she plays violin and accordion) that then were radically
modified _ the pitch altered as much as three octaves _ and turned
into washes of background sound that lapped around the edges of her
crystalline voice.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Lynch worked in sound effects, such as the repeated
unsheathing of a sword in ``Battle and Aftermath'' and pastoral
nature sounds behind several other songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt like he was transported back to the time of the
Crusades; he had this ongoing theme,'' Montgomery said. ``He was
seeing things as he heard me sing, and maybe that's the difference.
He's seeing visions as he directs.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a sometimes-otherworldly sound that feels far
different from the often gorgeous but respectfully authentic
re-creations of Hildegard's music by other artists.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery said she felt ``completely OK'' with modernizing
medieval church music in that way. The result, she said, may be
more viscerally true to the passionate and evocative mysticism that
inspired Hildegard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having had the experience of doing (Hildegard performances in
churches), I may have felt _ maybe not consciously _ that doing it
that other way was frustrating, that something wasn't coming
through, wasn't being expressed,'' Montgomery said. Taking the
music out of its sacred setting freed her to get to the music's
center, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just interesting how it still came together as a piece
and still did something for the music,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   She now plans to leave Hildegard's music alone for a time, while
she explores more contemporary recordings with more conventional
music producers. But Montgomery said she had no regrets about the
unusual path that led to ``Lux Vivens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have done it this way because I could have
become an unchallenged classical musician,'' Montgomery said. ``And
I've been given an opportunity to go a different way. It really was
quite an experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
