<HEADER>
A6306 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV02-     02-23 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV02-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A LITTLE ENDORSEMENT FROM FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, March 2)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She pulled a small capsule from her pocket, flicked her eyes
over to the next table, leaned in close and whispered ``gingko.''
Gulping it down with coffee, she explained she'd first been
introduced to gingko in Hawaii. It made her feel sharper, she said.
She doesn't get stuck putting the right face with the wrong name
like she used to.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote down gingko in big letters on my list.
</P>
<P>
   Before gingko, there were others, including St. John's Wort, the
lightweight's alternative to Prozac. I once found myself in the
parking lot at the grocery store, ripping into a new bottle of St.
John's Wort, like some serenity addict, seeking the calm my friend
had found with this herb. Of course, there was Echinacea, the
herbal way to get through cold and flu season, right up there next
to chicken soup and Vitamin C.
</P>
<P>
   I can look at just about everything in my bathroom shelf as
first endorsed by a friend. Kay's gingko, Terry's St. John's Wort,
Sandie's garlic pills for cholesterol, Barbara's valerian root for
insomnia, Emily's aromatherapy soap for tired muscles, somebody's
small vial of lavender oil for headaches.
</P>
<P>
   I trust my doctor to give me good medical advice but to keep up
on the latest trend in supplements, I rely on my friends. Everyone
has a favorite wonder herb, a vitamin that helped their mood,
improved their sex life, got them through the flu, saved their
marriage. And they're so willing to share.
</P>
<P>
   I was an early proselytizer for a natural progesterone cream
made from yams that some say balances your estrogen, others say
relieves stress and many more think prevents their skin from
looking like an avocado.
</P>
<P>
   You may scoff about treating yourself with leaves and twigs, but
perhaps you have an aloe vera plant in your bathroom for small
burns and mosquito bites. And didn't Grandmother's beloved castor
oil come from a bean?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that one person's miracle plant can be another's waste
of money. This stuff doesn't work for everyone, but then neither
does ibuprofen. When I pushed the hormone cream on a friend she
broke out in hives. Another tried St. John's Wort and got real
cranky, mostly because it didn't produce the desired effects.
</P>
<P>
   When I brewed my sister a pot of ginger tea she took a whiff and
asked for Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   Herbal remedies are not just for leftover hippies. They're big
enough that the major drug chains now sell them and medical
journals debate the merits of gingko and garlic. They're pretty
seductive. One can be pretty good at saying no to drugs and still
succumb to peer pressure when it comes to vitamins, herbs and
fantastic balms.
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe celebrity endorsements, but I'll try just about
anything I can get in the health food department if a friend swears
it delivers extra energy, lessens anxiety and moves you naturally
into that state once known as mellow.
</P>
<P>
   These are the people who tell you when to cut your hair and
change your glass frames. If they say ginseng works for the 4 p.m.
slump, you try it.
</P>
<P>
   There are skeptics. We were discussing some new energy booster,
one of those with three letters instead of a name, and Mary
wondered, ``People brag that it gives them such a lift but how come
when you call them up they're always taking a nap?''
</P>
<P>
   Mary's lucky, though. She can improve her day with a new
lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   I heard about one woman who takes a Chinese herb to keep her
hair from going gray and while it does remain an honest dark brown,
so does her mother's at 75, which could mean either mom's on the
herb too or they just have good hair genes.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Jane, usually so conventional you'd expect her to call
911 before an herbalist, now is hooked on primrose oil for both PMS
and easing the pain from an old tennis injury.
</P>
<P>
   It can go beyond vitamins and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a bottle of orange-flavored baby aspirin I bought after
meeting a woman on a rafting trip who says she pops one every
morning to keep from ever having a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico I heard about a face cream coveted by visiting
Americans. I finally tracked it down, smeared it on and waited for
the results. It put a nice gloss on a sun tan but no miracles
occurred, even though I began to notice that a number of my country
women did indeed have remarkable skin for their vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, my friend had to go and point out that they were the
Americans who came to San Miguel de Allende for face lifts.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it's a baby boomer conceit, a belief that there is
something magical and likely found in nature that will allow us to
do it better, to play longer, work smarter, sleep sounder and age
tautly.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gail Sheehy said, today 50 is 40, 40 is 30.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone know much about kava?
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
