<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EGGS ARE THE SAME, BUT THE NAMES ARE CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Egg drop soup, a cliche of American Chinese restaurants, has a
less-well-known Italian counterpart, stracciatella. These soups
demonstrate how easy it is to transform a basic dish in spirit,
moving from one cuisine to another almost as quickly as you can
change your mind about which you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Both are based on a simple principle: eggs curdle when dropped
into boiling stock or water. When they are used to thicken a sauce
or stew, the heat is kept low, for a smooth, creamy result.
</P>
<P>
   In egg drop soup, whether Chinese or Italian, you do just the
opposite: keep the heat relatively high so that the eggs cook in
shreds, or curds. The result is a lightning-fast soup of substance.
</P>
<P>
   Egg drop soup is best flavored with soy sauce, chopped scallions
and a bit of sesame oil. Stracciatella is flavored with freshly
grated Parmesan cheese (Parmigiano Reggiano is essential for best
flavor) and a suspicion of garlic; some chopped parsley is a
radically untraditional but acceptable addition, at least for
heretical Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Both rely on stock _ don't make these soups out of water and
expect them to taste like anything _ and are pretty good even with
canned stock. I find either variation quite filling, but to make
them into a real one-pot meal I add some chopped greens _ spinach
or watercress is especially good _ and finely chopped boneless
chicken or shrimp, all of which will cook in about the same time as
the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   (My daughter persuaded me to add cooked thin egg noodles to the
Chinese soup, and we both liked that version.) To accommodate the
added solids, however, increase the amount of stock by about half
(six cups instead of four).
</P>
<P>
   EGG DROP SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt, if necessary, and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped scallions, both white and green parts
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil, or to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring 3 cups stock to a boil over medium-high heat in a 6- to
8-cup saucepan. Beat remaining stock with eggs and soy sauce until
well blended.
</P>
<P>
   2. When stock is boiling, adjust heat so it bubbles frequently
but not furiously. Add the egg mixture in a steady stream, stirring
occasionally until eggs gather together in small curds, 2 or 3
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Taste, and add salt if necessary (or more soy sauce). Then
add plenty of pepper, the scallions and the sesame oil. Taste
again, adjust seasonings and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 to 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
