A6325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL24-COX     02-23 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIPARTISAN PUSH TO WEAKEN OR ABANDON INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After more than a year of bitter partisanship over
the investigation of President Clinton, Democrats and Republicans
may have found an issue where they agree: Neither party likes the
independent counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute as it exists today should not be reauthorized,''
Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said Tuesday. His Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee will begin Wednesday to consider the fate of the
law, which has triggered 21 executive branch investigations over
two decades. The law is scheduled to expire in June unless Congress
renews it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden is on those who want to keep it alive in its
current form,'' Thompson said, holding out the possibility of a
dramatically scaled-down version.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have long objected to the law, which they have seen
as a weapon wielded against Republican presidents during the
Iran-Contra probe of the Reagan administration. Now many Democrats,
angered at Kenneth Starr's investigation of Clinton, also oppose
it.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, the ranking Democrat
on the governmental affairs panel, argued for revamping the
independent counsel system, which was originally passed after the
Watergate scandal to restore public trust in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything will be gained by abandoning this
law,'' Lieberman said. He also urged that the debate over the law
``not be allowed to be a referendum on Judge Starr's performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the witnesses scheduled to testify at Wednesday's
kick-off hearing have favored either scrapping the law altogether,
or narrowing its scope.
</P>
<P>
   Former attorney general Griffin B. Bell and former Senate
Republican leader Howard H. Baker Jr. are slated to tell why they
found the statute ``seriously flawed'' in a recent joint study.
Bell, a Democrat who is now an Atlanta lawyer, has long held that
independent counsel investigations run the risk of becoming a
``search for a crime to fit the publicly identified suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   The current statute calls for an independent counsel whenever
the attorney general finds ``credible evidence'' of wrongdoing by
the president, vice president or by a cabinet member or other high
administrative official. The aim was to give investigations more
credibility. Independent counsel probes have resulted in more than
50 criminal convictions, including 13 under Starr.
</P>
<P>
   However, even some of the former independent counsels are
joining in the criticism of the statute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law can't be saved and it shouldn't be,'' said Joseph
diGenova (cq), a former independent counsel whose investigation
exonerated the Bush administration of improperly examining the
passport files of then-candidate Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make federal law enforcement, with its vast powers,
able to focus on one person, you create a very dangerous
situation,'' said diGenova, a Republican who also will be
testifying at Wednesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   DiGenova said the problem does not lie with Starr or any
particular independent counsel but with the establishment of the
position itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every tactic that Ken Starr used is exactly the tactic that
the Clinton Justice Department uses every day in courthouses all
over this country,'' diGenova said. ``They subpoena family members,
mothers, fathers, psychiatrists, priests _ you name it.''
</P>
<P>
   DiGenova said he would have used those same tools, but he said
he opposes concentrating all those powers in an independent probe
aimed at a single official. ``There are all sorts of remedies'' for
investigating high government officials, diGenova said, citing the
decision to appoint a special investigator of President Nixon
during Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the attorney general use the regulatory authority she has
had since the Teapot Dome scandal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that would not be enough, warn those who still champion the
independent counsel law .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very important act,'' said Arthur Christy, a
special prosecutor during the Carter presidency, who is scheduled
to be one of the few proponents of the unpopular statute to speak
at the Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without it, we could have all sorts of trouble. It's very
simple: Suppose you have a cabinet member accused of a felony, and
you've got the attorney general investigating his fellow cabinet
member?'' Christy said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers keeping the current law, but he suggests reducing the
number of officials covered to about 20, instead of the
approximately 70 officials who are now potential targets.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson suggested that he might consider keeping independent
counsels but limiting their jurisdiction to just three officials:
the president, vice president and attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman held out the possibility of a pool of independent
counsels, selected in advance, to be called on when needed. And
another participant in the debate, former appeals court judge
Robert Bork, has proposed that Congress set up a permanent panel of
investigators to oversee the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   A few members of Congress are seeking to change the law instead
of eliminate it. Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark., has proposed a measure to
rework the statute and add more financial oversight. He has won one
Democratic co-sponsor, Rep. Cynthia McKinney of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   However, any effort to salvage the independent counsel statute
faces an uphill struggle, now that its past defenders have joined
its longtime foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a post-Watergate liberal notion and it was a
disaster,'' Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., a one-time
advocate said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, an opponent whose committee has jurisdiction over the
law, said, ``I am not convinced that it has not outlived its
uselessness.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
