<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL HYDRANGEAS DO WELL IN THE SOUTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have wanted a hydrangea in my yard since I first saw Donna
Reed hiding from James Stewart in the movie ``It's a Wonderful
Life.'' They had just left her high school dance. I love the sound
of that hydrangea and the way it moved.
</P>
<P>
   Will you please provide any information you have on this bush?
Will it do well in the South?
</P>
<P>
   A: What a great memory. Yes, hydrangeas do well in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There is more than one hydrangea to consider for your garden.
``Hydrangea macrophylla,'' the large-leafed shrub with the large,
rounded clusters of pink or blue blooms, flowers in late spring.
Soil acidity can alter flower color. For bluer blooms, sprinkle 2
tablespoons of aluminum sulfate or sulphur around the plant in
early fall. This will promote a more acidic soil. To encourage pink
blooms, sprinkle a cup of dolomitic lime around the shrub. This
boosts alkalinity. Water well after any application.
</P>
<P>
   This hydrangea, also known as French or garden hydrangea, has
large, coarsely toothed leaves and large, domelike clusters of
flowers. Some love this plant for what they see as old-fashioned
blooms. Others see the blooms as gaudy. These hydrangeas vary in
height according to variety, but many of these garden types are in
the 3- to 5-foot height range. The blooms, like them or not, dry
well.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in this big-leaf species are those hydrangeas with
blooms that resemble lacy caps. The blooms are made up of fertile
and sterile flowers. ``H. macrophylla'' `Mariesii Variegata,' for
example, produces delicate pink or blue lacecaps and variegated
foliage. This does well in our garden and matures to 4 or 5 feet in
height.
</P>
<P>
   Oakleaf hydrangea, ``Hydrangea quercifolia,'' is a woodsy
deciduous shrub that can reach 6 feet in height and has large
oaklike foliage that turns a reddish-purple in fall. Large clusters
of creamy-white blooms appear in late spring or early summer. Bark
may exfoliate on mature branches. This is a great addition to any
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangeas are deciduous and lose their leaves during winter.
You may be tempted to prune at this time, but do not prune until
after the shrub flowers in late spring or you'll remove the buds.
(I understand there is one variety, `All Summer Beauty,' that is
the exception to this rule. This variety flowers on current year's
growth. I have not seen this plant locally.)
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangeas like morning sun and afternoon shade, and they grow
well here in bright shade. A well-draining, organically enriched
soil is best. Use an organic mulch, too. Shrubs that are healthy
and growing well in an organically enriched soil will require
little or no supplemental fertilization, but if needed, a
slow-release, balanced fertilizer can be applied in early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangeas, like azaleas, need adequate water, especially during
the hot, dry summer months. Keep the soil moist but not soggy.
Mulch will help preserve soil moisture and help moderate soil
temperature in summer and winter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; The leaves on my snapdragons are looking sickly. The top
sides have yellowish areas. There are brownish, raised ringlike
areas on the undersides of the foliage. What is this?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; That is rust, a fungal disease. If the plants are severely
infected, I often just remove and destroy them rather than try to
stop the pustules from spreading. But the disease can be
controlled, if caught early, by dusting the foliage _ making sure
to get the undersides _ with sulfur. There are other fungicides as
well, but make sure the one you use targets rust.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the garden area clean. Remove any fallen, infected leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Note: Remember to remove spent flower stalks on snapdragons,
as well. This encourages the plant to regrow and produce more
stalks, and in turn gives you more blooms. Apply a liquid, balanced
fertilizer to encourage more bloom cycles until the hot weather
gets the best of these cool-season annuals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many years ago I saw garlic being grown as a houseplant. It
was beautiful, with long wooden tendrils. Can you help me learn how
to do this?
</P>
<P>
   A: How unusual. I've seen garlic grown in containers, but have
never seen it grown as a houseplant. Garlic is a member of the
onion or allium family. I'm afraid I don't know of any that produce
wooden tendrils. Perhaps with age, those with twisting stems get
woody. (Or perhaps I'm misunderstanding your letter.) Serpent
garlic, ``Allium sativum var. ophioscorodon,'' for example,
resembles common garlic but is larger and has stems that coil,
straighten, then continue upward growth. Does this sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   We plant garlic in the garden in Houston in late September and
October for May/June harvests. Some gardeners start individual
cloves in small containers of potting soil prior to setting the
plants in the vegetable bed. The small pots are placed where they
receive morning sun and afternoon shade to encourage good growth.
</P>
<P>
   You could try this and just continue growing the garlic in
containers. Simply buy a good head of garlic from the grocery. Peel
the papery skin and divide the cloves. Start the individual cloves
in plain clay pots (with drainage holes) filled with a good soil
mix. Plant the individual cloves, tip up, an inch or so deep and
about 4 inches apart if planting more than one in a (larger)
container. Keep the soil evenly moist.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pots in a window where the plants will get a half-day
of sun, and apply a liquid fertilizer regularly once the plants are
growing. Grow the garlic on a patio or balcony, if possible, and
bring the plant indoors for short visits. Fresh air is always best.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic bulb formation occurs in response to lengthening days in
the spring; however, this has to be preceded by a relatively long,
cool growing period that makes fall planting ideal. Providing this
cool condition indoors would be tricky. But perhaps you only want
the plant(s) as ornamentals. If so, you could start cloves now and
see what happens. I would like to know how your garlic progresses.
</P>
<P>
   The garlic plant is cold-hardy, able to withstand freezing
temperatures. As the days become longer in the spring, bulbs form
rapidly. Garlic will also bolt, or produce seed stalks, but this
doesn't seem to inhibit the production of good-sized bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   For those who wish to plant garlic in the garden this fall,
boost the soil with an abundance of organic matter. Good drainage
is essential. To ensure good drainage, create ridges in the bed and
plant on top of these. Garlic is a relatively heavy feeder, and
side dressing with a nitrogen fertilizer is beneficial. Water.
</P>
<P>
   To harvest in late spring/early summer, pull the garlic, shake
off excess dirt and hang it in a shaded, dry area for several
months. Use as needed. Or, break into individual cloves and freeze
in freezer jars to avoid flavoring ice.
</P>
<P>
   Note: I'm wondering if you possibly saw the climbing onion,
``Bowiea volubilis,'' a novelty houseplant with a large, green bulb
(planted with half its girth above the soil line) that sends up
nearly leafless, branched stems that will twine around a support.
These plants can be 3 or more feet long. The small flowers are
greenish-white. This plant prefers partial sun, average room
temperature, a well-draining soil that is kept moist during the
growing season and on the dry side otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
