<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS AND NOTES ON FOOD AND DINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three Americans Win Bread-Baking Championship
</P>
<P>
   Any doubts that bread in American shops and restaurants has
vastly improved should be erased by the news from Paris, where last
week the United States won bread-baking's world cup, the Coupe du
Monde de la Boulangerie.
</P>
<P>
   The contest, pitting teams from 12 countries, began in 1992; an
American team qualified in 1994 and came in sixth. Two years later,
Americans won in the specialty bread and baguette category.
</P>
<P>
   On the winning team were two instructors from the Greystone
campus of the Culinary Institute of America in St. Helena, Calif.:
Thomas Gumpel, who won in the artistic design category, and Robert
Jorin, who baked sweet breads and pastries. Jan Schat, the third
team member, responsible for baguettes and specialty breads,
teaches bakers at Il Fornaio, a chain of bakeries in California.
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese Cheeses
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese cheeses are so new to American markets that the
traditional, artisanal varieties are not even mentioned in the
encyclopedic ``Cheese Primer'' by Steven Jenkins (Workman, 1996).
But a few kinds are now being imported and are well worth
discovering.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a blend of cow's, sheep's and goat's milk, has a mildly
acid tang with added spiciness from its rich paprika rub. It's a
relative bargain: $6.99 for eight ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Evora, a semihard sheep's milk cheese, is crumbly, yellowish and
pleasantly sharp ($10.99 for six ounces).
</P>
<P>
   Queijo Azeitao is a mild-tasting sheep's milk cheese that
develops a soft, satiny interior when ripe, not unlike Torta del
Casar from Spain. But such sumptuousness comes at a price: $16.99
for a nine-ounce round. Like Evora and, increasingly, cheeses from
other countries, it is made with a vegetable coagulant derived from
thistles, not with animal rennet.
</P>
<P>
   Ribafria, a mellow, buttery goat cheese ($7.99 for seven
ounces), puts the appetite on edge with the heat of the crushed
black peppercorns that crust it.
</P>
<P>
   All four are available at Murray's Cheese, 257 Bleecker Street
(Cornelia Street), in Manhattan, at the prices above. Some are also
sold by Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Avenue (79th Street);
Zabar's, Broadway and 80th Street, and Fairway, 2127 Broadway (74th
Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132d Street). Prices vary.
</P>
<P>
   Not Mom's Hamantaschen
</P>
<P>
   Tradition usually prevails when it comes to hamantaschen, the
triangular pastries that symbolize Purim, which begins Monday
evening. Prune, poppy-seed and apricot fillings sum it up. But
Black Hound, 170 Second Avenue (11th Street) and at the Mall at
Short Hills, fashions the most delicious little hamantaschen around
and fills the flaky glazed pastry with the likes of chocolate and
pecan-honey in addition to poppy seeds and first-rate apricot
preserves.
</P>
<P>
   And no prune, because Amiram Dror, the owner, said, ``I had a
bad experience with prunes as a child.'' Available through March 3
at $20 a pound; with a day's notice they can be delivered in
Manhattan for an extra charge: (800) 344-4417. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
