<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6341 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MTV-INTERNET-515&AMP;ADD-     02-23 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-INTERNET-515&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV BRANCHING OUT BEYOND THE TUBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``f'' business news file)  
 By LAURA EVENSON  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MATEO, Calif. _ If MTV Networks Chairman Tom Freston gets
his way, generations of couch (set ital)and(end ital) mouse
potatoes will soon be howling, ``I want my MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable network giant, whose channels include MTV, VH1,
Nickelodeon, Nick at Nite and TV Land, announced a major online
expansion Tuesday, including new music and children's World Wide
Web sites to further extend its reach ``from cradle to, well,
near-grave,'' says Freston.
</P>
<P>
   The online expansion will give MTV Networks' fans of all ages
more of what they want when they want it, including music, music
news and information, children's activities and a chance to
purchase a piece of American pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   The new Web sites and services also will extend the global reach
of MTV Networks, which already reaches a quarter of the world's
television households in 85 countries and territories ranging from
China to South Africa with shows geared to local languages and
customs. MTV plans to run both sites from new offices in San Mateo,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we can count on is that entertainment and media will
become ever more individualized for people around the globe,'' says
Freston, 53, who worked as a bartender in the Caribbean and a
clothing merchant in New Delhi before helping to launch New
York-based MTV in 1981. ``That's the point of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV Networks will launch its eclectic music site, tentatively
called the Buggles Project, in June, and its large secure site for
children, tentatively called Project Nozzle, in September.
</P>
<P>
   Fans also will soon be able to shop on all MTV's Web sites,
including its more TV-focused MTV.com and nick.com, thanks to the
networks' recent purchase of Red Rocket, an online toy retailer.
</P>
<P>
   The Buggles Project will provide a huge network of online radio
stations from which Web surfers can pick and choose to create a
station that suits their tastes and can flow, or ``stream,'' into
their computers around the clock. The new site is named for the
Buggles, a band whose music video, ``Video Killed the Radio Star,''
was the first to appear on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The network, which MTV acquired with Imagine Radio in Brisbane,
Calif., ``already is streaming 100 radio stations,'' says Freston.
``So if I like West African guitarists, hip-hop and classical
music, I could create a personalized radio station that reflects
those preferences.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Rugrats'' set can turn to Project Nozzle, which will
feature online activities and games created by and for kids. MTV
purchased Nvolve, a Web development company in San Mateo, Calif.,
to create a safe site for kids by requiring parents to register
them online for access to bulletin boards, chat and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   MTV Networks' new online sites will enhance its cradle-to-grave
appeal it started with its TV channels, where kiddies watch such
shows as ``Blue's Clues'' on Nickelodeon, teens and young adults
tune into MTV, Baby Boomers view rock documentaries on VH1 and
grandparents tune into ``I Love Lucy'' on Nick at Nite or ``The
Lone Ranger'' on TV Land.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To hold on to its wide range of viewers, MTV Networks has
already retooled at least two channels and changed the way it
reaches its core teen and young adult fans.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of appealing to teens solely via the MTV channel, MTV
Films, with Paramount Pictures (both are owned by Viacom), is going
after them at the cinema. New movies include ``Varsity Blues,''
about high school football in small-town Texas. Released last
month, it already has taken in more than $48 million at the box
office. On Friday, Paramount and MTV Networks will release ``200
Cigarettes,'' a comedy set in New York's East Village on New Year's
Eve 1981. Its cast reads like a Who's Who of young Hollywood,
including Ben Affleck, Courtney Love and Christina Ricci.
</P>
<P>
   The MTV cable channel also underwent a makeover. ``It veered off
its mark in the mid-1990s,'' says Freston, as it moved away from
music and toward vapid veejays and game shows. To get back on
track, he says, MTV hired hosts who care more about the music they
present than what they look like. ``Carson Daly is not a glamour
boy, and that's the point,'' Freston says of the host who's dating
Jennifer Love Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   To better understand its viewers, the channel sent researchers
into the closets and record collections of 100 young adults last
summer to study their pop culture tastes. It also has set up a
studio overlooking Times Square that raised its profile with both
artists and audiences.
</P>
<P>
   MTV Networks turned Nickelodeon into a must-see channel for
children when it spent about $30 million in the early 1990s to
develop animated hits like ``Rugrats'' and ``Blue's Clues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed Nickelodeon to be more about entertainment, because
when it was `educational' kids didn't like it,'' Freston says.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Blue's Clues,'' live-action host Steven Burns never talks
down to his young audience. Instead, he and his animated dog, Blue,
enlist young viewers to help to look for clues and solve problems.
``Rugrats'' revolves around cartoon babies, but it is closer in
spirit to ``The Simpsons'' than ``Barney'' as it mocks the yuppie
behavior of parents Stu and Didi Pickles.
</P>
<P>
   The goal behind such programming, says Freston, ``is to develop
shows that kids like and will stay with until they know it's time
to move on to MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV Networks' toughest task may be to figure out how to reach
Boomers past age 50. ``I don't know that a music video network is
an approach that will work for them,'' says Freston. ``In our
cradle-to-grave coverage, we're sort of missing the grave part. For
now, internally at MTV we're calling it VH2.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, MTV Networks will offer increasingly customized
entertainment for ever-larger audiences. ``The one thing we can
count on as we move into the next millennium,'' Freston says, ``is
the continued de-massification of the media worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
