<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-TOMATOES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMATOES RIPE FOR PLANTING IN EARLY SPRING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Any way you slice it, the best-tasting tomatoes are
home-grown.
</P>
<P>
   For best results in the home garden, plant early.
</P>
<P>
   Diehards have already seeded tomatoes indoors. Daredevils may
have already transplanted outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us will find tomato transplants in local nurseries,
ready to go into a sunny, organically enriched, well-draining bed.
Several garden centers are already stocked.
</P>
<P>
   For many, March is tomato time, but a February head start is
hard to pass up when the weather is as mild as it has been this
winter. Whatever your planting date, keep an eye on the weather to
avoid being caught off guard by frost.
</P>
<P>
   While tomatoes don't like cold weather, it's important to plant
them in early spring, as many varieties won't set if night
temperatures climb above 72 degrees. For those of you new to the
area, it warms quickly here. An early start gives you a better shot
at a good harvest before the summer heat shuts down production.
</P>
<P>
   When you visit your nursery you'll see small, plastic tabs in
each tomato pot. Read these, as they not only give the variety name
but other useful information _ whether the tomato is determinate or
indeterminate and to what extent it is disease-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Determinate tomatoes have vines that put on little growth once
fruit is set, so you get a short harvest time. Indeterminate vines
keep growing after fruit sets, and tomatoes in various stages of
development may be on the vine at one time. The harvest may last
months.
</P>
<P>
   Buy stocky transplants and only disease-resistant varieties.
These will hold up best in our warm, humid climate. Disease
resistance for a particular variety is indicated by V for
resistance to verticillium wilt and F for resistance to fusarium
wilt. N means a tomato is resistant to nematodes, T that it is
resistant to tobacco mosaic virus and A for resistance to
alternaria.
</P>
<P>
   Methods vary among tomato gardeners, but all agree that tomatoes
are most productive in full sun. An organically enriched,
well-draining soil is important, too. Prior to planting, work in 40
to 60 pounds of compost per 100 square feet, some cottonseed meal
as a nitrogen source and bone meal as a phosphorus source that will
encourage root growth, which in turns promotes better flowering.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the bottom leaves from each tomato transplant, then plant
deeper than it grew in the small pot. New roots will grow along the
buried portion of the stem, and since tomato plants are heavy
feeders and can become so large here, a heavy-duty root system is
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Mulch around the plants to help retain soil moisture, reduce
weeds, discourage soil-borne diseases and keep future fruits clean.
The mulch will keep soil temperatures down during warm weather and
enrich the soil as it breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Place a heavy-duty tomato cage around each young plant. It is
too difficult to cage a large plant. You'll break the stems. Wrap
the cage with fiber row cover. This keeps bugs and diseases at bay
and gives the plants a good, healthy start. The cover also will
provide protection should we have a late frost. Don't worry: Light
and water penetrate these covers.
</P>
<P>
   Good air circulation is vital to tomato health, and caging helps
improve air movement within a plant.
</P>
<P>
   Again, fertilization schedules differ among tomato growers. Some
use fertilizers created especially for tomatoes. One successful
gardener begins biweekly applications of fish emulsion when
transplants have been in the ground a week. Others apply this
monthly. Some advocate side-dressing with a nitrogen source
(21-0-0) every three weeks when the first tiny fruit appears. The
goal is to supply nutrients, but keep in mind that while tomatoes
like nitrogen, too much may trigger brown spots on the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Even soil moisture will prevent fruit from cracking, discourage
blossom drop and blossom-end rot. To help ensure a harvest for
Memorial Day picnics, beat the birds. Harvest tomatoes when they
show a first blush on the bottom of the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
