   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Developments at the Microsoft trial,
with the final witnesses facing cross-examination on their direct
testimony as a weekend deadline looms to begin a six-week recess.
(Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TBS-NEWCHANNEL _ Turner Broadcasting will announced Wednesday a
new cable TV channel, its first in years and the first new one
since its purchase by Time Warner. The channel will be called
Turner South and will be a regional (Southeast) entertainment
channel. will have new logo as art. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) Financial and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   COCACOLA-PERU _ Coca Cola agreed to buy half of Peru's Inca Kola
Peru SA, a stubborn rival, the second move in the past month to
expand in South America. Coke also agreed to buy a 24 percent stake
in Jose R. Lindley e Hijos SA, the Inca Kola bottler. The
transaction represents another step in its relentless global
expansion. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT-EARNINGS _ Home Depot said fiscal fourth-quarter
profit rose 36 percent as home sales fueled demand for kitchen,
flooring and other remodeling products. Net income rose to $418
million, or 27 cents a share, from $307 million, or 20 cents, a
year earlier. Home Depot was expected to earn 26 cents.
Unemployment at almost 30-year lows, high consumer confidence and
low interest rates are sparking homne sales, which creates new
customers for paint, lights and other supplies. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WEB-CARTOONS _ Cartoon Network debuted today two original
cartoons online. It hopes to do the same with five by year's end as
a new way to test pilots. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-TRADESHOW _ Health Information Management Society brings
17,000 people to town. With photo essay of 2 or 3 shots from
carnival-like trade show that belies stuffy acronyms. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-VERTICAL _ Vertical markets are the Web's new untapped
revenue/partner/alliance scheme. WebMD, by positioning itself as a
vertical portal, makes is very attractive to companies like
CompuServe and CNN who are looking for depth of content in a
specific market. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAS-SWITCH _ Georgia natural gas deregulation advances with the
expected release today of the latest count of Atlanta Gas Light Co.
customers who have switched to marketing companies. Legislation is
also being introduced in the state legislature and put on a fast
track to ensure that all Atlanta Gas Light customers are assigned
to marketers by Sept. 30. with all that in mind, we canvass current
rates being offered by marketers. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ A look at the Mazda Protege. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-COLUMN _ Weekly column on how organizations are handling
their Y2K-bug issues, focusing on companies and governments in
Atlanta and the Southeast. (Chambers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-RATINGS _ ATLANTA _Atlanta-based Media Matrix releases its
list of the most popular Web destinations. The top destination
remains AOL. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
