<HEADER>
A6361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-VOTERS24-COX     02-23 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-VOTERS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELIS ABROAD EXPECTED TO FLY HOME FOR ELECTIONS
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM During elections in other countries, activists try to
``get out the vote.'' In Israel, they try to fly the vote in.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand Israelis, in a series of competing and
hush-hush political airlifts, are expected to come from America and
Europe to cast their ballots in elections this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The influx is apparently a result of Israelis' dedication to
politics, their penchant for traveling and living abroad, and a
system that allows absentee ballots to only a select few.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are individual Israelis headed back, but the country's
national airline, El Al, is offering election discounts for those
wishing to return. And, reportedly, several competing groups are
arranging charter flights for voters leaning their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be kind of a race between (airlift) efforts,'' said
Israeli political analyst Daniel Elazar, of the Jerusalem Center
for Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Elections for prime minister are May 17, with an almost certain
run-off on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Yedioth Aharanot, Israel's largest daily newspaper, reported
recently that five unnamed organizations, ranging from the left
wing to the ultra-Orthodox right wing, were organizing subsidized
flights back for the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming the report is difficult because some of the groups do
not want to tip off their rivals. Ultra-Orthodox groups deny that
they are involved, as the left wing activists allege.
</P>
<P>
   But, it is widely believed that ultra-Orthodox Israeli citizens
from New York returned on subsidized flights in 1996 to vote for
election winner Benjamin Netanyahu. Accounts may be exaggerated,
but they have prompted protests in the Israeli parliament and now
opponents want to use the same tactic to counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli voters are ready to oblige. The small, tense, country,
still faces a war in Lebanon and occasional terrorism on its
streets _ factors that motivate citizens to want to vote. And
people living overseas who take politics personally are willing to
pay hundreds of dollars, missing school or work, to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli law allows them to stay on the voting rolls even if they
are out of the country for years and have not voted in the previous
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 elections showed why activists think it's worthwhile to
fly in their allies.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu defeated Shimon Peres by a mere 29,457 votes out of
about 3.1 million cast. Considering that voter turnout was 79
percent typical here, but mammoth by American standards there is
not much slack within the country for picking up new votes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, absentee ballots are available only to Israelis in
special services, such as the diplomatic corps. Israel, a country
that used waves of immigrants to strengthen its claim to the land,
never wanted its citizens to leave.
</P>
<P>
   But many do leave, to study or work for a few years, or to live
permanently under dual citizenship in another country. Gavri
Bargil, an organizer of the New York-based group Kesher, estimates
that there are 300,000 Israelis living in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kesher, formed in the last few months, seeks to maintain
connections between Israelis overseas and back home. But Bargil
said the elections provided the urgency for starting the group,
which is organizing flights for voters at discounted rates.
</P>
<P>
   He said the goal is to fly a few thousand people to Israel for
the run-off election at a cost around $450 each, half of the
typical price.
</P>
<P>
   Bargil said the group does not ask how people will vote, which
would be illegal. But, he concedes that the offer might be of most
interest to people who are dissatisfied with Netanyahu's current
right-wing government.
</P>
<P>
   Bargil himself used to head the left wing Peace Now, Israel's
largest political group.
</P>
<P>
   A European effort, apparently loosely aimed at left wing voters,
is attempting to fly Israelis home for just a $50 contribution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the widely rumored ultra-Orthodox efforts in 1996
may be small this time.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the ultra-Orthodox efforts are hazy. The Chabad,
or Lubavitch Jewish movement, was accused of flying in voters in
1996. A spokesman in Israel said the group did not then and will
not this time.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rabbi Tzvi Berkowitz, director of the Chabad youth
organization in Miami, said that he had heard rumors ``that
something is going on . . . if it is a rumor or an actual act they
are talking about, I cannot tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Liebman, an Israeli professor in politics and religion
at Tel Aviv's Bar-Ilan University, said the Lubavitch Jews will try
to keep a ``low profile.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, they have been disillusioned with Netanyahu, who
they have accused of breaking promises by turning over land to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were severely burned,'' Liebman said. ``I don't think the
ultra-religious parties, at this point, are that worked up.''
</P>
<P>
   (Palm Beach Post staff writer Steve Gushee contributed to this
story).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
