<HEADER>
A6364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ERITREAN-RESTAURANT-A     02-23 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERITREAN-RESTAURANT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CULINARY JOURNEY OUT OF AFRICA INTO NEW HAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food was not exactly the highlight of my year in Africa. It was
1969. The Biafran war was on.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember much about Biafran cuisine, frankly, but I know
it involved a lot of stockfish. Stockfish is dried cod, stiff as a
board, and mercenary cowboys flew tons of it into the rebellious
little enclave from an island called Fernando Poo.
</P>
<P>
   I went along once, sitting on top of the cargo in the back of a
wheezing DC-3, where I had a better view of the pilot than I
wanted. He had only one hand on the controls, since he needed the
other to hold a bottle of Scotch. He was as stiff as the stockfish.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nigerian side of the lines, I usually ate groundnut stew.
Groundnuts are peanuts, sort of. The stew was just about as awful
as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry as usual on a visit to Sierra Leone, I plowed into
something listed as ``pepper steak'' on a hotel menu. The dining
room was dark, and I admit I didn't examine my plate closely. It
was a steak, sort of, but the thing had been saturated with
incendiary chilies, not the benign black peppercorns I expected. I
was on a liquid diet for a week.
</P>
<P>
   A prudent man takes evasive action, so I ate a lot of the time
in the agreeable little Lebanese restaurants that you used to find
in African cities.
</P>
<P>
   I also rejoiced when the news took me to former French colonies,
which were still pretty French. I jumped at things like a $20
Cavaillon melon in Cameroon (that's 20 1969 dollars, remember) and
a lovely Mediterranean loup, or bass, fresh off the plane from
Marseilles, perfectly grilled over fennel twigs in a desert hotel
in Niamey, Niger.
</P>
<P>
   Eating spiny lobster in Dakar, Senegal, you could almost imagine
yourself in Nice. Monomaniacs, the French, but they do eat well.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Africans I met had more important things on their
minds. They were too busy either fighting for their lives or
scraping a living to pay much attention to food, as long as there
was enough of it. The privileged elites were too busy aping the
Europeans who had just given them their freedom to pay much
attention to local food traditions.
</P>
<P>
   I spent a week or so in 1969 with guerrillas fighting to gain
independence for Eritrea, then a province of Ethiopia. Neither they
nor I had much to eat. It seemed highly unlikely then that the
rebels would win, but they finally did, after a devastating 30-year
war. It seems almost unbelievable that the fighting has resumed in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   It never occurred to me, of course, that one day I would sit
down to sophisticated meals in an Eritrean restaurant worlds away
in New Haven, but that happened, too.
</P>
<P>
   Caffe Adulis, a block from the Yale University campus, is a
byproduct of the war that created modern Eritrea, an East African
country of 3.5 million along the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   I guess you would call it an ethnic restaurant. Invited for
lunch, I went along expecting ``ethnic'' decor: you know, two weary
travel posters and a half-dead philodendron. Instead, I found a
clean-lined, two-level space, airy and immaculate, with handsome
chairs, butcher paper covering the linen on the tables and lively
semiabstract pictures on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   That was one surprise. Another was the food. My wife, Betsey,
who doesn't have much time for Birkenstocks or Lonely Planet
cuisine, loved it, and so did I. It made up for a lot of culinary
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant was created by three refugee brothers named
Ghebreyesus _ Ficre, 36, Gideon, 38, and Sahle, 28, the sons of a
judge _ who escaped in the 1970s from the chaos in Asmara, the
Eritrean capital, and came to New Haven at the suggestion of their
sister, who was working with a church group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She chose it, Gideon said, ``so we wouldn't get involved in all
the big-city craziness but we'd be close enough so she could keep
an eye on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ficre is the cook (and the painter of the pictures on the
restaurant's walls). Before opening the cafe in October 1992, he
toiled in other people's restaurants in New Haven for a dozen
years, which may account for the consistency of his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't excellent one day and awful the next, the way some
are,'' said his brother Gideon, who works in the dining room with
Sahle.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the subtlety and complexity of Eritrea's cooking,
which Ficre Ghebreyesus interprets as the spirit moves him, that
makes Caffe Adulis so distinctive. If geography has cost Eritrea
dear, politically, in the form of long years of foreign domination,
it has conferred great benefits, gastronomically, by opening it to
the influences of three continents.
</P>
<P>
   Indian spices, the collard greens of sub-Saharan Africa, the
hummus of the Middle East and the couscous of North Africa mingle
with Greece's feta cheese and the pasta of Italy, once Eritrea's
colonial master.
</P>
<P>
   Two staples define Eritrean cuisine. One is injera, a moist,
spongy sourdough crepe made from teff, a kind of millet grown in
the East African highlands. Its slightly sour taste offsets the
sweetness of some of the food that it accompanies, either in a kind
of Eritrean burrito, with lentils, salads and seasonings rolled
into it, or as a scoop for picking up other foods.
</P>
<P>
   The second is berbere, a blend of spices and sun-dried peppers,
about the size of banana peppers, grown in the East African
highlands. The hot yet mellow flavor cannot be duplicated, Ficre
Ghebreyesus insists, with anything grown in Mexico or Louisiana. He
imports berbere and other spices from his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   One of the regulars at Caffe Adulis is Robert Ferris Thompson, a
charismatic Yale professor, who explores the links between the
painting, sculpture, music and dance of Africa and those of the
United States and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   He drops by one evening and orders ``Master T's Favorite'' _
jalapenos stuffed with tomatoes, onions, garlic and scallions and
moistened with olive oil. Taking in the scene, he makes notes on a
corner of the paper tablecloth; when he is finished, he rips it off
and takes it home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   A's favorites _ not, alas, so listed on the menu _ were
menchetabish, a dry beef curry with a surprising hint of rosemary;
a wonderfully balanced salad of seared tuna cubes, fava beans,
onions and bitter greens (arugala, collards, spinach), and a killer
coconut sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Alexander, Ficre's wife, who directs the poetry center
at Smith College in Northampton, Mass., called the sorbet ``an
ideal ending, with one perfectly clean note.'' Quite so.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. A's favorite? She was thrilled by a vegetarian dish, one of
several offered, called two-tomato gig, a creamy, hearty
combination of oven-roasted whole tomatoes that collapse and
caramelize as they cook, with mozzarella cheese, bermuda onion and
arugula.
</P>
<P>
   A house specialty is shrimp barka, whose list of ingredients
vividly underlines the multicultural origins of Eritrean cooking.
Pan-seared jumbo shrimp are served in a quickly cooked tomato
sauce, flavored with basil and red onions and topped with Parmesan
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Italian, right? Not exactly. Unsweetened coconut and dates, from
Africa, also figure in the mixture, and the whole is served over
basmati rice from India.
</P>
<P>
   Another shrimp dish uses an equally unlikely combination of
ingredients: tomatoes, onions, garlic, hot peppers, scallions ...
and ultracrisp strips of cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   A third shrimp creation is served on fettuccine, strictly al
dente.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is all this authentic?'' I asked Ficre, a little dubiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tricky word, authentic,'' he replied. ``Tricky idea. Food
ideas move around the world very quickly today, and if you went to
Eritrea, you'd find American touches here and there. There are tens
of thousands of Eritreans living in the United States, and when
they go home, they take new food ideas with them. For us, that's no
more foreign than pasta once was.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Haven, salsas and portobello mushrooms have found a place
in Ficre's kitchen, as has guacamole. In New Haven, the drinks list
is longer. There are African beers, like Mamba from the Ivory Coast
and Xingu, a dark brew from Brazil, but also first-class wines from
a half-dozen countries, including Domaine Drouhin, a standout pinot
noir from Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   This is no cheap and cheerful student hangout; some main courses
cost as much as $16 to $19. But it has been a success from the
start, attracting students, professors, theatergoers and
townspeople, to say nothing of businessmen and lawyers, who often
book the cafe for office parties. On weekends, there is a wait of
up to 90 minutes for tables.
</P>
<P>
   Brought to America by slaves, African ingredients and dishes
have long since entered the culinary mainstream here; Southern
standbys like okra, gumbo and black-eyed peas, among others, all
have their origins in Africa. But they have never achieved the
cachet of some Moroccan dishes, like b'stilla, a sweet-savory
pigeon pie, or Algerian couscous.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Ghebreyesus brothers is one small sign that
African food, cooked and served with flair, can have broad appeal.
Another is a new book, ``The Africa Cookbook: Taste of a
Continent,'' by Jessica B. Harris, a professor at Queens College
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I stumbled across yet another, in an unlikely setting:
Arizona. There on the wide-ranging, almost recklessly eclectic menu
of Roxsand, a Phoenix restaurant, I spotted piri piri shrimp among
the appetizers. A vibrant saute of shrimp in olive oil with garlic
and chopped peanuts, it was taught to Roxsand Scocos by a waiter,
whose family had fled South Africa years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She confessed with some embarrassment that she used Tabasco
sauce instead of peppers from Africa, but the dish tasted terrific,
anyway _ every bit as good as the piri piri shrimp I ate a couple
of years ago in a waterfront dive in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP BARKA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Ficre Ghebreyesus, Caffe Adulis, New Haven &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 medium red onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   5 very ripe and juicy tomatoes, chopped coarsely
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   { cup finely chopped fresh basil (1 bunch)
</P>
<P>
   15 pitted dates ({ cup), cut crosswise in thirds
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsweetened shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   { cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium shrimp (16 to 20), shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups cooked basmati rice.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large, heavy pot, heat olive oil over medium heat. Add
onions, and saute until wilted, about 10 minutes. Add garlic, and
continue sauteing, stirring frequently to prevent sticking, for 2
minutes longer. Stir in the tomatoes, salt, and pepper. Cover, and
cook for about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add basil, dates and coconut, and reduce heat to medium-low.
Cook, uncovered, stirring occasionally, for 5 more minutes. Add the
half-and-half, cover, and cook for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add shrimp to sauce. Cook, covered, until shrimp turns pink,
about 5 minutes. Stir in the cheese, and then the rice, and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
