<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARLOTTE-BOOK-REVIEW     02-23 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLOTTE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHARLOTTE GRAY': LOVE AND SECRETS IN WARTIME FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his new novel, ``Charlotte Gray,'' the hugely talented
British writer Sebastian Faulks continues his exploration of the
mingled themes of love and war. This book is set in wartime England
and France and involves a star-crossed pair of lovers caught up in
the tangled politics, treacheries and heroics of clandestine
actions against the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   So many subjects, so many disparate fates, so much good and evil
is explored here (there is even a subplot involving a sort of
recovered-memory syndrome) that ``Charlotte Gray'' sometimes
threatens to explode into its constituent genres. But there is no
shortage of dramatic tension, excitement or persuasive period
detail, and Faulks, whose last book was the highly praised
``Birdsong,'' certainly does know how to write.
</P>
<P>
   The main character is the eponymous Charlotte Gray, whom we
first encounter on a train from her ancestral Scottish home to
London, where she wants ``to do something to help'' _ namely, work
for a plastic surgeon trying to patch up the British soldiers and
pilots wounded in the first months of World War II. In her train
compartment, Charlotte meets two men who work for some secret
government department. Telephone numbers are exchanged. Once in
London, Charlotte settles into a flat with two partygoing
roommates. She meets a dashing British flier named Peter Gregory,
quits her boring job with the plastic surgeon and calls one of the
men from the train. She is recruited as an agent for G section,
which specializes in helping the nascent French Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, who is a wonderfully intelligent, reflective
creation, falls for Gregory, the pilot. ``Once her feelings for
Peter Gregory had crystallized, she found it hard to picture
herself in a previous epoch, while the days of transition
themselves seemed lacking in self-awareness, almost comically
confused. She loved him. How could she once not have loved him?''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory is then lost when his plane crashes in France. Charlotte
is sent to France on a separate mission (her fluent French
qualifies her for this task), one that is supposed to take 10 days
or so, followed by a pickup by a small plane and a return to
England. But she knows even before she parachutes into the French
countryside _ inside the collaborationist non-occupied half of the
country, ruled over by Marshal Philippe Petain _ that she is going
to stay there and look for Gregory.
</P>
<P>
   She does, and here, still in its early stages, is where Faulk's
novel begins to spread in many different directions. What starts
out as a wartime romantic adventure, Charlotte's perilous search
for her lover, broadens into a portrait of occupied France, with
the themes of collaboration, anti-Semitism, character and tragedy
splashed onto Faulk's vivid canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Among the elements are what might emerge as the stock figures in
a wartime melodrama, except that Faulk invests them all with a
memorable individuality. Two Jewish boys, ages 7 and 4, are being
harbored by villagers after the deportation of their parents. A
member of the Resistance named Julien (code name: Octave) works to
protect the children and, more generally, to preserve something
good in collaborationist France by making provisions for an
eventual uprising.
</P>
<P>
   One of Faulk's more biting figures is an unctuous schoolteacher,
Claude Benech, who is easily persuaded by Petainist propaganda and
joins the pro-Nazi French militia. Another collaborationist is Paul
Pichon, dispatched from Paris by something called the Inquiry and
Control Section, which enthusiastically seeks to fulfill Jewish
deportation quotas approved by the collaborationist government.
</P>
<P>
   Another memorable character is Levade, Julien's father and a
painter of some note who lives hermitlike in an abandoned castle.
He is a Jew turned Catholic, a wounded veteran of World War I and a
kind of ruefully perceptive, acidly disillusioned witness to the
accumulated inhumanities of the century.
</P>
<P>
   But holding the entire, sometimes unwieldy construction together
is Charlotte, whose keen moral sense gives her a sort of layered
awareness. She is worthy of the attention we devote to her in
Faulk's nearly 400 pages, even when his plot slips over the line of
plausibility. Like his other chief characters, both exemplary and
villainous, Charlotte carries her private concerns into her role as
a historic actor. Benech, for example, is a loser, an unhappy,
penny-pinching bachelor. ``The austerity of the new regime brought
out something doughty in him: he was a man of destiny whose fated
hour had come.''
</P>
<P>
   Buried in Charlotte's past is a mysterious family secret,
something to do with her father, whose nightmarish experience of
World War I led him to impose his own psychic burdens on others.
The lesson seems to be that the personal is indeed the political,
or, put differently, that later generations are never free of the
traumas suffered by earlier ones. Charlotte's relationship with
Levade, her love for her Royal Air Force pilot, her determination
to do good, which is less a matter of courage than of inner
necessity, are all related to the unassimilated and yet nameless
wound inflicted by her father.
</P>
<P>
   Do we really want to know this, even about admirable Charlotte?
There is something gratuitous about this psychological history.
``Charlotte Gray'' essentially belongs to the genre of the war
adventure, and it does not have quite the vascular strength to deal
with all the meaning Faulks pumps into it. It is a love story and a
spy story and a story about historical injury as well as a story
about the Holocaust, the politics of Vichy and the particulars of
the infamous camp at Drancy, where French Jews, including children,
were assembled before being deported to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk is a prodigiously talented writer whose literary ambitions
exceed what would seem to be the natural limits of the intrigue he
lays out. Yet thanks to the complex, enchanting vehicle of
Charlotte and Faulk's grasp of political and moral history, he
manages to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CHARLOTTE GRAY'
</P>
<P>
   By Sebastian Faulks
</P>
<P>
   399 pages. Random House. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
