<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Feb. 24, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains and gusty winds will pound the Pacific Northwest
Coast again Wednesday as another in a series of storms moves
ashore. Rainfall amounts of over 2 inches are likely in some areas
while heavy snows bury the Cascade Mountains. The additional
snowfall will exacerbate the already high avalanche threat. Only
scattered showers are expected in eastern Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, tranquil weather will cover the Southwest and
western Plains as high pressure aloft supports sinking air and
abundant sunshine. The sunshine will contribute to unseasonable
warmth from western Kansas to the Southwest deserts.
</P>
<P>
   A band of light to moderate snow will spread into the Upper
Mississippi Valley as low pressure dives southeastward. One to 3
inches of snow will fall from northern Illinois to the upper
Peninsula of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, high pressure will dominate the southern states,
promoting ample sunshine and seasonal afternoon temperatures from
Florida to Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Patchy wet snow and rain will fall over the central Carolinas
and Virginia as a storm system begins to develop over the warm Gulf
Stream waters. The storm will move toward the northeast Wednesday
afternoon, bringing the chance of snow to Long Island and Cape Cod
late Wednesday and Thursday night. The heaviest precipitation,
however, is expected to remain over the open waters of the
Atlantic, as upper level steering winds act to move the storm
offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the interior Northeast will be partly to mostly sunny
and chilly as high pressure moves overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Mounting Snow
</P>
<P>
   The vast, thick ice sheets of Greenland and Antarctica are the
largest of earth's land glaciers, covering over 50,000 square
kilometers. Mountain glaciers are much smaller, but they are not
restricted to polar latitudes. The Cascade Mountains in Washington
and Oregon, for example, house glaciers, largely due to a spate of
winter snowfall and the favorable chill of high elevation. This
month, snow has been falling at prodigious rates in the Cascades,
with nearly 20 feet of snow since February 1 at Mt. Baker in
Oregon. Snow will continue to mount Wednesday as another Pacific
storm comes ashore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
