<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-GRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI, BOEHLERT ANNOUNCE GRANTS FOR NEW YORK WATERSHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York Gov. George Pataki and Rep. Sherwood
Boehlert, R-N.Y., announced Tuesday $5.2 million in federal grants
to help protect the state's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 individual grants range in size from $600,000 for a
program to manage the use of phosphorous that spills into the water
supply in Delaware County to $15,000 for a watershed education
effort in the Town of Somers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These grants will help watershed communities and New York City
pay for much-needed sewage improvements, help communities develop
long-term water quality protection programs and protect the
viability of farms in the watershed while reducing pollution
runoff,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki was in Washington for a four-day National Governors'
Association conference.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert, who obtained the funds through the Federal Water
Resources Development Act, said the money would allow New Yorkers
``to meet the challenges of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert is the chairman of the House water resources and
environment subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's strong leadership and my position in Congress
have made a powerful team for securing funds for the towns and
villages that dot the watershed,'' Boehlert added.
</P>
<P>
   The 8 million residents of New York City and 1 million upstate
New Yorkers receive their drinking water from an area stretching
over eight counties in the Catskill Mountains and along the Hudson
River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   These counties are considered the New York City watershed, which
includes 60 towns and 11 villages.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are aimed at fulfilling an agreement struck in 1995
among New York state and federal officials requiring communities in
the watershed to protect the water supply from sewage discharges
and pollution runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Following are the federal grants announced for the New York
projects.
</P>
<P>
   - Phosphorous management, Delaware County, $600,000;
</P>
<P>
   - Brewster collection system extension, $540,750;
</P>
<P>
   - Comprehensive stream management in the west branch of the
Delaware River, $469,500;
</P>
<P>
   - Croton watershed stormwater conveyance project, Westchester
County, $450,000;
</P>
<P>
   - Evaluating effectiveness of New York City stormwater
management facilities, $410,000;
</P>
<P>
   - Patterson Hamlet sewer project, $385,922;
</P>
<P>
   - Red Falls Stream corridor stabilization, Greene County,
$350,000;
</P>
<P>
   - Development of a pilot sewer district, Town of Bovina,
$330,825;
</P>
<P>
   - Comprehensive stream management in the Chestnut Creek region,
$284,000;
</P>
<P>
   - Comprehensive stream management in Stony Clove Creek region,
$241,500;
</P>
<P>
   - Stormwater monitoring in New York City, $217,500;
</P>
<P>
   - Forestry management across the eight-county watershed,
$215,396;
</P>
<P>
   - Saw Mill River pump station upgrade, Mount Kisco, $196,875;
</P>
<P>
   - Upgraded sewer service, Town of New Castle, $187,500;
</P>
<P>
   - Programs to help farmers reduce agricultural pollution across
the eight-country watershed, $117,750;
</P>
<P>
   - Stormwater bio-filter project, Town of Yorktown, $93,750;
</P>
<P>
   - Putnam County ``non-point'' pollution assessment, $37,050;
</P>
<P>
   - Town of Neversink water quality assessment for farms, $27,461;
</P>
<P>
   - East of Hudson watershed stormwater, erosion and sediment
control training, Westchester County, $19,275;
</P>
<P>
   - Watershed education initiative, Town of Somers, $15,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
