<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-GREENE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NARAS CHIEF WORKS FOR THE GRAMMY GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: ``Tonight'' refers to Wednesday, Feb. 24).  
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Michael Greene is as familiar and sought-after a
figure in the music industry as the small but mighty statuette he
represents _ the Grammy Award.
</P>
<P>
   As president and CEO of the National Academy of Recording Arts
and Sciences (NARAS) _ the professional association for musicians,
songwriters, record producers, engineers, and other creative and
technical music industry personnel _ Greene oversees the entire
Grammy awards process, as well as heading the academy's charitable
arms, MusiCares and the NARAS Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Greene deals with everything from public school music programs
to reaching out to artists using drugs to booking acts for the
annual Grammy telecast, which takes place tonight at the Shrine
Auditorium &UR;  &LR; in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He also sometimes gets caught in the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a nightmare, period,'' he says. ``I mean,
between all the bad press the academy got and Soy Bomb and Ol'
Dirty Bastard rushing the stage during the show, it was a bizarre
year.''
</P>
<P>
   With 925 nominees and just 14 performance slots on the
three-hour program, Greene must say ``no'' more often than he'd
probably like. Tonight's 41st annual Grammy ceremony, hosted by
Rosie O'Donnell, includes a music in film segment; a B.B. King/Eric
Clapton number; a tribute to Duke Ellington featuring Wynton
Marsalis, Herbie Hancock and Natalie Cole; and a performance by
Luciano Pavorotti.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the prestigious best record and best album slots are
dominated by female nominees Lauryn Hill (the first woman to lead
the awards, with 10 nominations), Celine Dion, Madonna, Brandy,
Monica, Sheryl Crow and Shania Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Son of a big-band leader, Greene is ideally suited to his job.
He began his career first as a recording artist and producer and
was president of recording studios, a music publisher, CEO of one
of the nation's first cable TV advertising companies, president of
one of the world's first cable video music channels, general
manager of a major market UHF television station, founder of the
first nationally distributed video music channel launched on direct
broadcast TV. And prior to becoming the first full-time president
and CEO of NARAS in 1988, he headed one of the industry's largest
post-production houses.
</P>
<P>
   It was while earning his BA degree in business that the
Atlanta-bred Greene entered the industry as an artist for Warner
Bros.' Bizarre/Straight label, later recording for GRC and Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Although there's still a touch of Granny in the Grammys, Greene
has made some significant progress since the '80s. Among other
things, after years of hearing that the awards have little to do
with current music trends, the academy developed committees and
secret review panels to determine nominees in important categories.
</P>
<P>
   We met with the affable record academy chief for a wide-ranging
interview in his comfortable office suite at NARAS headquarters in
Santa Monica. Greene, in the midst of fielding urgent calls from
entertainment titans, was having a self-described ``Pavorotti
moment'' as he negotiated with the superstar's agents for a
performance slot on tonight's telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last year's awards suffered through some bad press over the
distribution of funds from the academy's charities, unexpected
guests on stage and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Greene: There's always 10 or 12 journalists gunning for me each
year. When you look at the educational and charitable stuff we do,
the fact that I get up on stage and lambaste Newt Gingrich and go
after the secretary of education and use our podium as an advocacy
platform for music people, I make a lot of people angry.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the 925 nominees all have record companies, and record
company executives are not used to hearing the word ``no'' from
people. It gets very nasty. So when you have a journalist who calls
up any of them and offers anonymity to roast Mike Greene, it
becomes `I'll show him. I'll get him back.' When I'm the focus,
it's bad. It takes the focus off musicians and people that should
be getting the attention. In the end, the board extended my
contract and gave me a raise.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was going through your mind last year when Soy Bomb (an
extra on the show who removed his shirt to reveal the words ``soy
bomb'' written on his bare chest) joined Bob Dylan on stage?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: He got through as one of Dylan's dance troupe. It wasn't
like he came from the side or the front. It seemed like part of the
act at first. My fear in these situations is someone's going to
harm the performer. This year, we're doing a different kind of
screening of the extras. But we don't want the show to feel like a
lockdown. Rosie O'Donnell said during our first production meeting,
`What's going to be our Soy Bomb moment this year?' If there wasn't
a danger element, I woulQ't be worried about it, but we're taking
additional precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can we expect tonight?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: Madonna's opening the show on a beautiful set with
30-foot screens and a Japanese bridge where she'll be revealed in
this gorgeous red dress _ and dancers that look like rocks in
geisha outfits. Plus, we're using an orchestra a lot this year with
Aerosmith, Andrea Bocelli, Celine Dion, Alanis Morissette,
Pavorotti and the music in film segment with James Horner and John
Williams. We're also giving the Latin-pop award on the air, which
we haven't done in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Rosie's a first-time Grammy host. How was she chosen and what
do you look for?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: One of the first things I did when I became chairman in
the late '80s was convince people to move away from music artists
as hosts. This has been a tradition we're very happy with. When we
looked at Rosie, we felt there was a good possibility of doing some
cross-promotion between her show and our show for the month prior
to the ceremony. When we first approached Rosie, we got a no. About
a week after that, I was at an event with her and walked over to
her, got down next to her chair, and for two minutes I just went
with all the reasons why she should do it. I said, ``I don't want a
yes or a no, I'm going to go back and eat my dinner. Call me.'' So,
they go to thinking about it, and she called and said, ``Yeah, I
want to do it.'' And it has worked out great because she's a music
fan, and the public recognizes that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Grammys often get taken to task for gaffes such as Jethro
Tull winning the 1988 hard rock/metal category. How do these things
happen?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: Over some pretty strong objections, that category was
added before we had a voting constituency. It was one of those
I-told-you-so things. Since then, dance is the best example. There
were good reasons to add a dance category earlier than we did, but
until we had the voting constituency in place, we would've had
people voting by name recognition _ Janet Jackson would've won
every time. Now, the only product currently eligible are recordings
created specifically for the dance market. And I think the winners
in that category have been good ones.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of political pressure is the academy under from the
cities of Los Angeles and New York in terms of where the show will
take place each year?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: They both want it, but they're both civil about it. New
York and Los Angeles both have about the same number of academy
members. The real pressure is regarding performances on the show.
It's brutal. During the first years I was here, the Grammy Awards
wasn't a big deal, and we begged to get people on. Now, we beg for
people not to threaten us when we say no.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does the new Staples Center downtown look to the academy?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: I firmly believe this will be the last year we're in a
small venue (like the 6,000-seat Shrine). From now on, we'll either
be at Staples or Madison Square Garden. One of the smart things
Staples did was bring us down there and actually move steel in the
plans for us. As a result, we have a very Grammy-friendly venue
because we participated to a degree in the architectural
renderings. Next year, it'll either be at Staples or the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your annual address normally touches on the year's important
issues. What will you deal with this year?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: I'd like to mention some of the new research on the
connection between music and the mind. But I'll probably skate
through a little education stuff and welcome everybody and then go
straight to the life achievement awards. I generally like to let
sleeping dogs lie in terms of the endowments and the arts
environment in education, which seems a little friendlier this
year, so you won't have to suffer too long with me this year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As a onetime touring musician yourself, how do you feel when
you see how maligned musicality and musical prowess is in some
quarters of the industry?
</P>
<P>
   Greene: I'm afraid we have to remind people there are some great
musicians and singers, and it's OK to sing in tune, and it's OK to
have memorable melodies. There's a whole sludge field of commercial
radio that doesn't care at all about great music, niche music or
indigenous music. There's some great rock music going on. It's not
just Korn and Metallica. We have a responsibility to fight for
musicality. And it is a fight in the light of radio and the fact
that the current voice of rebellion for kids is pretty limited in
terms of musical content.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
