<HEADER>
A6396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-OCALAN24-COX     02-23 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-OCALAN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    TURKEY AGAINST THE WORLD: COUNTRY FEELS ON TRIAL AS KURD LEADER
FACES POSSIBLE DEATH PENALTY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey A soft-spoken and kindly school teacher, Aylin
Atligan becomes downright frightening when the subject is Abdullah
Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Turks, she regards the jailed Kurdish leader as a
ruthless terrorist who deserves the pain his militant Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) dished out for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in the death penalty, but I will not feel
sorry in this case. To hell with what the rest of the world says.
We need to hang this man as soon as possible,'' said Atligan, 27,
as she shopped for groceries Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If Turks were joyous last week at the capture of Ocalan, they
find themselves this week increasingly defensive against what they
regard as a growing international chorus attempting to tell them
how to try and sentence their Public Enemy No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit called outside criticism ``an
unacceptable affront to Turkish justice.''
</P>
<P>
   From Turkey's top leaders to the people on the streets, the
sentiment reflects the rigid emotional and political battle line
drawn long ago over the country's Kurdish minority and their goal
of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan was formally arrested Tuesday on charges of treason in
his first appearance before a judge since he was captured last week
in Kenya. Hated by the Turks but a hero to the minority Kurds,
Ocalan could hang if found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   But it is no simple case of crime and punishment. The case
contains deep undercurrents of Turkish pride and resentment at
Europe's role in protecting the rights of what the Turks view as a
terrorist movement. After a wave of violent Kurdish protests swept
Europe last week, the whole world in watching the Ocalan trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a normal trial, it's a global event,'' said
Huseyin Bagci, a political scientist at Middle East Technical
University in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   International human rights groups and some European governments
have raised concerns about where Ocalan will receive fair
treatment. He has been detained for a week without the ability to
consult with a lawyer, legal under Turkish law, and he will be
tried before a security court, which combines civilian and military
judges, which critics argue cannot render an independent decision.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan's hearing Tuesday took place on the prison island of
Imrali, in the sea of Mamara, and was closed to the media and the
public. How and when Ocalan's trial will proceed has not been
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders have vowed to give Ocalan a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   But weighing heavily, too, is a thirst for revenge against a man
whose guerrilla army is considered responsible for more than 30,000
civilian and military deaths in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey has two options and it is a Hobson's choice: Apply the
death penalty after a quick trial before a security court _ this
would satisfy the desire of the Turkish people's emotions. Or, hold
a fair trial that would satisfy world opinion,'' said Sedat
Aslantas, a lawyer for Turkey's independent Human Rights
Association, a group which is representing Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   While a Turkish lawyer from the group was assigned to Ocalan's
case, he was not allowed to travel to the island for the hearing.
In another sign of deep Turkish public sentiment, protesters
surrounded his car shouting: ``Shame on you!''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights officials in Turkey were frustrated in their
efforts to learn details of the secretive hearing on the island 35
miles southwest of Istanbul. Naval boats have been deployed around
Imrali and military helicopters patrol overhead. Outsiders have
been barred from the nearest coastal town on the Turkish mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Gun Kut, a political analyst at Bosphorus University, said he
believes human rights groups and others are unfairly prejudging
Turkey regarding Ocalan's upcoming trial. He believes authorities
will hold an open trial and perhaps even televise it to demonstrate
to the Turkish public and the world the strong case against Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   He also believes that parliament, which must approve the
execution of a death sentence and hasn't done so in over a decade,
will not vote for it in the case of Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically it won't be advisable and everybody knows that,''
he said. ``Why create a hero? Why create a martyr out of somebody
who the entire Turkish public has already branded as a treacherous
murderer?''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish security courts had already opened several cases against
Ocalan in absentia before his arrest last week. The cases have
proceeded but cannot conclude without his presence. Officials have
said the cases may be combined into one trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan was a brutal and effective guerrilla leader seeking
self-rule for his stateless people. Many Kurds did not endorse his
harsh tactics. Still, he has come to represent their struggle
against Turkey's equally hard treatment of its Kurdish minority of
12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kurds do not share the same minority rights as ethnic Greeks and
Armenians living in Turkey. It is illegal to broadcast or to teach
the Kurdish language. The southeastern mountains, where most of
Turkey's Kurds reside, is governed under authoritative civil
restrictions akin to martial law.
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Greece have asked the European Union to insure a fair
trial for Ocalan, one that would avoid the death penalty he faces
under Turkish law. They would make such procedures a condition for
eventual Turkish membership in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurdish issue has, in part, prevented Turkey from being
considered for membership in the European Union. In a review last
November of Turkey's application for membership, the European
Commission cited ``persistent violations of human rights and
important deficiencies in the treatment of minorities,'' including
the Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
