<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROBESON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL ON ROBESON EXPLORES A COMPLEX MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICAN MASTERS: HERE I STAND 
Directed by: St. Clair Bourne 
Produced by: Chiz Schultz 
Time: PBS, Wednesday 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Paul Robeson died in Philadelphia on Jan. 23, 1976, the
legendary actor, singer, and political activist was hardly
remembered in his own country. Here was an All-American football
player who graduated Phi Beta Kappa from Rutgers University in 1918
and, with honors, from Columbia Law School five years later. He
starred in plays, including Eugene O'Neill's ``The Emperor Jones''
and Jerome Kern's ``Show Boat.'' In 1930, he traveled to London,
where he became the first black man to star in a major production
of ``Othello.'' He entertained the Loyalist troops during the
Spanish Civil War and spent time in the Soviet Union, where he was
lauded as one of the great artists of the 20th century. Yet, when
he died, there were no parades. He just passed on. In some cases,
the obituary of one of the most talented, intelligent, tough
Americans who ever lived was merely a postscript.
</P>
<P>
   This two-hour ``American Masters'' special, ``Here I Stand,''
helps restore the reputation of one of the greatest Renaissance men
in American history. For many Americans, both black and white,
Robeson was simply a Communist _ a traitor to his country and a
Soviet sympathizer who was awarded the Stalin Peace Prize. But Paul
Robeson was never simply anything. He was a complicated man with
complex ideas about everything. And this nonfiction account goes a
long way toward exploring a life that never collapsed under the
awesome weight of racial and political stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   Through vintage footage and interviews conducted with many of
his associates _ including Harry Belafonte, Uta Hagen, Ossie Davis,
and Paul Robeson, Jr. _ Robeson emerges as a man who never betrayed
what his eyes saw and his ears heard and his mind thought. He knew
that his ideas of equality and justice for African-Americans would
be met with hostility and violence yet he never wavered. Even when
he was denied access to concert halls and his passport revoked by
the State Department, he fought back. Even when the media ignored
him and he was unable to make a living as an entertainer, he didn't
cave in. He was that rarest of human beings, a man of principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleased with the way it turned out,'' said Paul
Robeson Jr., referring to the ``American Masters'' special from his
home in Brooklyn. Robeson Jr., who contributed material from his
archives to the program, said that some of the footage, especially
the film and recordings the producers received from the Russians
just a few weeks before air time, has never been seen on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really appreciate about the show is that you really get
a sense of my father's evolution through the epochal changes in the
country,'' he said. ``He was an established worldwide star and the
first American actor of that stature to be so political. What also
made him special is that he challenged the system a full two
decades before the civil rights movement started. Then it was truly
radical. This show places him in historical context.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      02-23 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE SUMMIT SHOWS LINGERING STRAINS FROM IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton huddled Tuesday with
congressional leaders from both parties for the first White House
legislative summit in 19 months, with officials vowing
post-impeachment cooperation to rescue Social Security, cut taxes
and bolster public education.
</P>
<P>
   But partisan maneuvering lurked in the wings as Clinton and
Republican congressional leaders met face-to-face for the first
time since the House impeached the president on Dec. 19 and the
Senate acquitted him of perjury and obstruction of justice charges
on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The year-long struggle over Clinton's sexual dalliance with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky never came up during an
Oval Office meeting that lasted more than an hour, according to
White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the congressional leaders vowed to work together in
the months ahead. Vice President Al Gore also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all took and oath and I think we intend to follow it,''
Clinton said during a photo session at the outset. ``We owe it to
the American people and I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., set the tone for the meeting with a
full-page advertisement in some of the nation's newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time to move on and focus our attention on an
agenda that strengthens the nation,'' the two Republicans said in
an open letter to Americans. ``In the coming months, we look
forward to working with the president, our colleagues in the House
and Senate, and you on these and other issues important to securing
a brighter future for you and your family.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet strains lingered from the impeachment struggle. Lott and
Hastert, emerging from the White House summit, refused to express
trust in the president's leadership in the aftermath of the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert voted to impeach Clinton in the House; Lott voted to
convict and remove Clinton from office in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I trust _ I trust the ability of the
people, here in the Congress, in the government to work together to
do what we need to do for the people,'' Lott said. ``That's where
the real trust should be _ the trust in us doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, referring to the question of trust, said: ``We are
starting to work to put together ideas, and that's the first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans also showed signs of trying to
position their parties for the 2000 presidential election. Clinton,
Lott and House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., outlined
separate litmus tests for future cooperation that raised questions
about whether compromise or confrontation lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Republicans that he will not compromise his State
of the Union proposals to reserve 62 percent of the projected $4.4
trillion budget surplus over the next 15 years to help keep Social
Security solvent and 15 percent of the surplus to protect Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Lott set his own criteria for bipartisanship, telling reporters
that Clinton must lean on Democratic members of the stymied
17-member bipartisan commission on Medicare to shake loose a
compromise rescue plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to get some of his people to participate (in a
deal),'' Lott declared. ``It's very important and this week is
critical and I urge the president to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, leading the House Democrats' efforts to retake control
of the House in 2000, challenged the Republican House speaker to
quickly schedule votes on cherished Democratic priorities _
Clinton's proposal to strengthen patients' rights to sue health
maintenance organizations, Democrats' proposed increase in the
minimum wage and bipartisan legislation to overhaul federal
campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that can happen,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials emphasized that it was too early for real deal-making
on the budget. Congress has until the end of September to consider
the president's fiscal 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certain that down the road, as we get into more specific
issues, we'll be looking at ways we can find common ground,''
Lockhart said. ``I think you're slightly ahead of yourself by
expecting this to be a horse-trading meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said the meeting alone was ``a sign of trust''
developing between political rivals. Republicans ``want to work
with'' Clinton, Gephardt said, adding: ``They realize that if
they're to get the people's business done, they have to work with
the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Lockhart and Gephardt emphasized Clinton's warning to
GOP congressional leaders that the White House will not bargain
away a proposal to extend the solvency of Social Security and
Medicare _ two middle-class entitlement programs imperiled by the
impending retirement in 2011 of the first of 77 million post-World
War II baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Congress will ``have to work through some of
the details,'' but Republican endorsement of the approach remains
``a threshold issue,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt called Clinton's plan ``a threshold decision that we
all have to make'' before considering GOP priorities such as tax
cuts, ending the tax code's penalty on married couples filing joint
tax returns and GOP initiatives on public and private education.
</P>
<P>
   With the Medicare commission facing a March 1 deadline for
delivering recommendations to Congress, the White House did not
rule out that Clinton might intervene as Lott insisted.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's spokesman added: ``We think that it's
important to allow the commission to do its work, report out what
their ideas are, and then we'll take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials agreed on potential benefits from the first
bipartisan White House legislative summit since July 1997 _ six
months before the Lewinsky scandal became public.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton found the gathering ``very constructive,'' Lockhart
said. ``There was a good atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said officials will ``work together, hopefully across the
party lines in the Congress and with the administration, to do what
the American people expect of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said the leaders
ought to get together more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do it in the way we did it this morning is productive, it's
constructive, and hopefully, it will lead to some real action on a
number of these fronts,'' Daschle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
