<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-MIGRATE-ART-2TA     02-23 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MIGRATE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURSUIT OF WORK TURNS CHINA INTO A MOBILE SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CHINA-TRADE) 
(ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Standing on a sidewalk amid a small mountain of
suitcases and gifts, Wu Liuyi mentally girded herself to board the
rickety unheated bus that two and a half days later would deliver
her to her house and pre-teen daughter near the southeastern city
of Wenzhou.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, two tiers of reclining seats were already crammed with
the blankets, coats and food of three dozen other migrants heading
home for Chinese New Year this month. The cramped, dark interior
resembled a communal space capsule.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wu, who owns a small leather workshop in Beijing, seemed ill
suited to the journey in her blue blazer and black heels. But ever
since she and her husband left their farming village for factory
work in Beijing in 1992, this daunting pilgrimage from the place
they live to a distant ``home'' has become a family routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' she said, herding her 7-year-old son to the
bus. ``I have to see my daughter, and I'm taking my son home to
start school this year.''
</P>
<P>
   China is on the move these days, with an estimated 10 percent of
the population now migrating from their official place of
residence, mostly in search of better jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Legions of young Chinese are moving one step up the job chain _
those from tiny villages move to small cities to find work, and
those from small provincial cities move to large cities.
</P>
<P>
   But rural migrants like Ms. Wu remain perpetual outsiders in
China's cities, with little hope of securing the coveted urban
residence permits that would allow them to build an entirely legal
life here.
</P>
<P>
   Registered at birth as residents of rural towns, they remain off
the books in a city like Beijing, ineligible for most good jobs and
housing subsidies, paying a steep price to enroll children in the
few public schools that might admit them, unable even to register a
car or bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   And so every Chinese New Year, most of these estimated 100
million migrants return to their hometowns, producing what Chinese
demographers call the largest seasonal migration in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Significant numbers of Chinese have been leaving their villages
in search of work only since the end of 1984, when the government
eased its rigid system of residency permits, allowing people to
travel for temporary jobs. The trend has snowballed in recent years
for a variety of reasons, including improvements in transportation
and communications, the emergence of privately owned factories and
a growing surplus of rural labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``After many years, reform and openness, fortune-seeking, has
become possible,'' wrote Xie Jinyu, a demographer at Nankai
University who has studied the migrants.
</P>
<P>
   For most rural migrants, the goal is simply to earn money to
take home, in part because they retain strong emotional ties to
their villages and in part because it is nearly impossible to get
an urban residence permit anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rural migrants have become a fixture in China's
cities: ragged men clutching hammers around construction sites and
women selling snacks at street stands. They have provided a vast
new pool of cheap labor that has allowed urban factories to
prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence is transforming urban life, mixing together
China's distinct regional cultures, but also giving rise to a new
rootless urban underclass.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the week Ms. Wu prepared to travel to Wenzhou, in
Zhejiang Province, that city's gleaming new train station was
filled with a ragtag collection of rural migrants who were
themselves heading back to their hometowns for the New Year
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly men from distant dirt-poor villages, they had come to the
small but prosperous coastal city in search of factory or
construction jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make money farming, and it's very hard to find work
in my hometown, so I came here,'' said Zong Jiaohua, 27, who worked
at construction sites in Wenzhou for the last year. Zong, from the
poor inland province of Jiangxi, said he had previously worked in
Jilin Province in the far northeast, and before that in Hainan, the
island province in the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
   But he had little money for all his efforts and said he was not
sure where to go next. ``I had planned to get married when I went
home this time,'' Zong said. ``But without a real job that's not
very realistic, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Zheng Lin, 23, from Shanxi Province in northern China, said he
had spent the last year doing piecework in a shoe factory in
Wenzhou. He said the money was good but the work tenuous and
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can earn $250 a month if you're fast,'' said
Zheng, who was killing time until his midnight train playing cards
on the old duffel bag that held all his earthly possessions. ``But
if the factory has no orders, you may have nothing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these migrants are between 18 and 35 with junior high
school educations, and they tend to work in unskilled low-wage jobs
in the private sector. Their movements have helped fuel China's
economic growth in recent years, as businesses and unskilled
laborers have become increasingly willing and able to follow the
market's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes have made it much easier for us to hire people
from across the country, and that has allowed us to expand our
business,'' said Joseph Chen, the urbane owner of a button factory
in Qiaotou on the outskirts of Wenzhou. ``It has also made it far
easier for us to develop contacts with customers, to have official
sales representatives elsewhere. The old system didn't work very
well for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Job agencies have sprung up to channel the labor across this
vast nation, but word of mouth often guides the flow. Xu Bin, 32,
who works in a badge factory in Wenzhou, said he had gotten his job
through an employment agency in Boyang, his hometown in Jiangxi
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, a few people from my town came and now a lot
more have followed,'' he said. ``Everyone at home knows that this
area has developed quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Luo Lichun, 23, who was tending vats of dye at another button
factory in Qiaotou, said she would be unemployed in her poor
farming town in Sichuan. ``A friend came home and told me there was
good work here, so I came,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But life is not easy for these migrants, even those with good
jobs, who often live at the fringes of the local society. Their
lack of an official urban residence permit constitutes a major
disadvantage in cities like Beijing, where housing, education and
other social benefits are still mostly state-controlled. The
government allows relatively few Chinese to change their official
residence each year, and most of these are well-educated people
moving for government jobs or marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In the cities, the migrants often do piece work in small
factories, working more than 12 hours a day. They live together, in
the backs of workshops, in small private apartments or spare dorms.
One study of a migrant community in Beijing estimated the average
living space at less than 2 1/2 square yards per person.
</P>
<P>
   On the grounds of a former state tire factory on Beijing's south
side, low barracks-style buildings now house hundreds of small,
unheated, one-room clothing workshops, each with a tangle of sewing
machines and cutting tables in front and a jumble of beds in back.
All are owned and staffed by migrants, mostly from around Wenzhou.
</P>
<P>
   In workshop No. C1027 recently, a half-dozen migrant workers
were toiling over fur-trimmed leather coats, while a few others
took breaks in the ``living area'' _ four bunk beds somehow crammed
in a corner behind a curtain made of old blankets. A row of
chickens and pig trotters hanging from the rafters and a
coal-burning stove on a back stoop completed the accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Many migrants said that living conditions were far better at
home. But what they were looking for was something else: money, job
experience, a bit of adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work seven days a week,'' said Li Fenglian, 21, from
Sichuan, as she prepared to venture out from C1027 into the streets
of Beijing. ``But I came because it was a new opportunity to see
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities like Beijing have had to cope with the massive influx of
generally poor rural immigrants and the social troubles their
presence has supposedly spawned: rising crime rates, beggars on the
street and an explosion of sexually transmitted diseases. The
migrants do not qualify for most local government social
assistance, though some private groups have taken up their cause.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of growing urban unemployment, the Beijing municipal
government last year announced that it would forbid rural migrants
from taking certain types of jobs in the hopes of encouraging some
of the estimated 3 million unofficial migrants to go home; the
city's official population is 12 million. The government has
occasionally bulldozed the unofficial neighborhoods where migrants
from a particular province or ethnic minority have clustered and
opened businesses. But the effect is short lived.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Beijing tried repeatedly to expel the
residents of ``Zhejiang Village,'' a chaotic jumble of sweatshops
and stalls in south Beijing, where most migrants from the Wenzhou
area, including Ms. Wu, live. But each time, within months, the
small leather workshops, the day care centers and the pungent
street markets selling the dried shrimp, yellow wine and other
delicacies popular in Wenzhou popped back up again.
</P>
<P>
   And today, the government has seemingly made a bit of peace with
this city-within-the-city that has become home to a hundred
thousand people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're figuring out ways to administer it rather than
suppress it,'' said Dai Jianzhong, a sociologist at the Beijing
Academy of Social Sciences. ``Through licenses and rent, the area
generates a lot of income for Beijing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
