<HEADER>
A6402 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-INVEST-PA     02-23 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-INVEST-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        ECONOMIC EXERTS SAY 'A NATION OF INVESTORS' WILL DRIVE
POLICY.
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 23 -- The growing number of middle class stock
market investors are fast becoming a powerful force in government,
a panel of economic experts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who invest are the invisible hand in American
politics,'' said economist Lawrence Kudlow. ``We have become a
nation of investors. Now that the impeachment trial is over, their
issues will crystalize in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Kudlow along with stock market executives, securities regulators
and lobbyists, discussed how a ``nation of stockholders'' was
changing politics.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of American families are invested in the market.
That's five times more investors than in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting taxes, privatizing Social Security, and creating a more
competitive health care system, are three issues where investors
are hoping to see progress, Kudlow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that rich people sold stock to a bunch of rich
people, said Patrick Campbell, who is chief operating officer of
the Nasdaq-Amex Market Group. ``But I've met the tow truck driver
who invests and reads Barron's.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from both parties will find it crucial to consider the
interests of investors in the stock market, Kudlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors take a more modern approach these days -- frequently
using the Internet to research decisions. Kudlow said access to the
Internet and television financial news has led to a trend of ``day
trading,'' which is when someone buys and sells stock in the same
day.
</P>
<P>
   The middle class investor class is growing because many are
motivated by a desire to increase the wealth in their 401K and
other retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of optimism and faith in the market,'' Kudlow
said. ``The investment class wants to make sure government can help
them with their retirement goals. The investor class votes and has
made these issues bipartisan issues.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's antenna picked up on the investor class'
desire to see Social Security be somewhat privatized. Clinton wants
to invest a part of the federal budget surplus in the market to
fuel Social Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   But Kudlow said dealing with an on-line investment company takes
away the personal rapport between an investor and his broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``My broker can say 'No,''' Kudlow said. ``But my computer
cannot.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Feigin, executive director of the North American
Securities Administrators Association, warned against on-line
investment scams.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were pulling a scam, and I didn't use the Internet, I
should be sued for fraud malpractice,'' Feigin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1820EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHILI-ART-2TAKES-N     02-23 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ROAD TO REAL CHILI, NEW YORK GRIDLOCK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ill., Mich., Ala., Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(With NY-CHILI-RECIPE) 
(nk) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jane and Michael Stern were skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding great chili in New York is like finding great pastrami
in Des Moines,'' he said warningly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like barbecue in New York,'' she added. ``It's never very
good. We are constantly being shlepped around by people telling us
they've found great barbecue here, and it never is. What Michael
and I have based food searches on for the last 12,000 years is
eating regional food in its region. To me, the great Manhattan meal
is at Katz's or Ratners. We had blintzes there a few days ago, and
the sour cream was  &UR; fabulous &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Sterns have agreed to eat chili at three
different places to see if any can equal those included in their
latest book, ``Chili Nation'' (Broadway Books, 1998). Their
expectations were low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of any really good chili is that the flavor of the
chili pepper itself plays a significant role and that does not
necessarily mean hot,'' Stern said. ``New York City has a low chili
consciousness, even though New Yorkers like to think they know
everything about everything. We don't know why people here don't
think that much about chili. It's like asking why people in
Cleveland don't care that much about pastrami. They just don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sterns have arranged to visit two restaurants with a
southwestern theme, Tapika, and Cowgirl Hall of Fame, along with
one Mexican restaurant, El Parador Cafe, which makes chili con
carne for its staff, but will serve it to customers on request.
After decades of eating chili here, Stern said the only great place
was the long-defunct Alamo Chile House on West 44th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chili Nation'' is the Stern's 25th book. Their specialty _
both on and off the table _ is Americana, including their
best-selling ``Elvis World'' (Knopf, 1987) and two editions of
``Road Food'' (Knopf, 1986), their guide to ``America's best
diners, small-town cafes, BBQ joints and other special eateries
serving great inexpensive regional food,'' which has sold more than
250,000 copies. Coast to coast, they know where to find the
freshest lobster rolls, the fluffiest pancakes, the crispiest
catfish. They write monthly for Gourmet magazine and weekly for
Conde Nast's Epicurious Website.
</P>
<P>
   When Robert Gottlieb edited The New Yorker, they wrote articles
about rodeo, cafeterias, chili peppers and parrots, but after Tina
Brown took over, they never heard from the magazine again. ``We
didn't know any celebrities,'' Stern said laughing. ``We only wrote
about people like the woman who founded the Northeastern Rat and
Mouse Club in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Sterns make light of their accomplishments, it has
been their advocacy of regional cooking, tracking with an almost
anthropological zeal how a community's food reflects its way of
life, that has helped push it into the culinary mainstream over the
last 15 years. They still sense remnants of what Stern calls
``anti-American snobbery in the food world,'' and the couple pride
themselves on never having been to France. ``We like eating swanky
food, but for us the exploration of food is less about what's on
the plate and more about what it expresses of its culture,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember very well when we started in the early '70s, it was
us vs. them, and the enemy was Gourmet magazine,'' he continued.
``All that food snobbery with no respect for what ordinary people
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   It was James Beard, actually, who was one of the first in the
food establishment to appreciate what the Sterns were doing.
Stern's family, he said, was less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we published the first edition of `Road Food,' they took
a look and said, `You go out all around America and write a guide
to  &UR; treyf &LR; ?''' Stern said, using the Yiddish word for nonkosher.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't know the half of it. This is a man who can debate
the finer points of a snout sandwich the way other people
deconstruct a cabernet.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, thankfully, the fare is more pedestrian. At Tapika,
they are served roasted brisket and black bean chili, with a hot
sauce on the side. Mrs. Stern tries hers and wrinkles her nose.
``It tastes a little school lunch to me,'' she says. ``It's
minestrone-like in a weird way.'' She shakes her head at the hot
sauce. Stern tastes it, too, and sighs. ``New York is not our
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   They do like the steak here. Peter Luger and Ben Benson's are
favorites. And they are loyal to the Oyster Bar and Lundy's. But as
far as chili goes, they are ready to move on. Midtown traffic makes
restaurant hopping feel more like crawling. But it's a chance for
Mrs. Stern to show off her new red flamenco shoes. Flamenco dancing
is her latest passion, one that Stern does not share.
</P>
<P>
   After living and working together for 30 years, the couple, who
are both 52, have a remarkable rapport. They don't interrupt each
other as much as share their sentences, and each seems to have an
ample sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working together has been great for our relationship,'' Stern
says. ``We have to keep our egos in check, be respectful of the
other person. Most couples are much meaner to each other than the
people they work with.''
</P>
<P>
   As the car inches along, Stern says: ``We wrote `Chili Nation'
because chili is probably the only single dish that has a
representative example everywhere in this country. And it's so
intrinsically a democratic dish _ it's associated with chain gangs
and diners. The connotations are so of the people. It's food as
folk art vs. the foodies notion of it as high art.''
</P>
<P>
   El Parador Cafe is practically empty. OK, let's get down to
business. The waiter serves the chili.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very authentic Mexican,'' Mrs. Stern says. ``And this
is a helluva better hot sauce than chili No. 1. But it's still not
like anything in our book.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern agrees, and it's back to the car.
</P>
<P>
   Although the couple can eat up to 10 meals a day on the road,
they have learned to pace themselves. Because they frequent what
they call mom-and-pop cafes, they're aware that the owners notice
when they don't clean their plates, so they tend to cart around a
lot of leftovers. ``We once sent some slabs of ribs through the
X-ray machine at O'Hare,'' Mrs. Stern says. ``We were stopped and
searched. They thought we had someone's rib cage in our carry-on
bag.''
</P>
<P>
   As for their writing, Stern says they have no system: ``Whoever
writes the first draft gives it to the other. We take copious notes
while we're eating. Most of the time, the owners don't notice or
care. Or they think we're with the health department.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sterns are not traveling, they live in Connecticut with
two dogs and a parrot, and each keeps a horse at a nearby stable.
They are in love with cowboys and feel right at home at Cowgirl
Hall of Fame. Stern looks at the menu: ``If you get the chili,
would you mind if I get the corn dog? One of my lifelong quests is
to find the best corn dog.''
</P>
<P>
   After ordering, Mrs. Stern puts a thermos on the table. ``I
brought some real Texas red, from the recipe in our book,'' she
says. She spoons some out. It is superb, tasty with a long strong
glow of chili pepper. It is not in the same league as either of the
first two chilies, or unfortunately, Cowgirl's, which Mrs. Stern
proclaims ``bland and watery.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband is happier: ``Not a bad corn dog. Not my epiphany,
but not bad.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Sterns met at Yale in 1968; she was earning her MFA in art,
he was there on a fellowship in art history. Mrs. Stern, who was
born in Manhattan, was the daughter of a shoe designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 5, he moved me and my mother to Nogales with the
idea that he would sell pumps to the Indians,'' she recalls. ``We
spent five years in the desert baking, and when we moved back to
New York, my mother left him, and we went to live with my gay
cousin Wally, who was an opera singer in the village. James Beard
was one of his friends, and when I met him as an adult, he told me,
`You used to sit on my lap when you were living with your mother at
Wally's.' Life is such a weird coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern was born in Chicago and raised in the suburb of Winnetka.
His father worked as a traveling salesman. ``My mother could do
three dozen things with Stouffer's spinach souffle,'' he says
admiringly. He graduated from the University of Michigan, before
arriving at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stern had a job sorting slides. ``I looked up one day, and
there was this really killer-looking guy with shoulder-length hair
and a motorcycle jacket,'' she recalls. ``I couldn't think of what
to say, so I said, `What's your sign?''' She laughed. ``Instant
amour. He invited me to a documentary on Howard Hawks, which I
thought was a bird film.''
</P>
<P>
   They have been together ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Have they thought of expanding their franchise to include Europe
or Asia? They shake their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the food we write about requires knowing its
context,'' he says. ``If we're in a small town in Alabama, we know
the clues and cues. And I already feel a tremendous frustration
about what a big country this is. The more we've done, the more we
find we haven't done. We just spent a week in St. Louis tracking
down gooey butter cake, and two weeks after we got back, someone
sent me a list with places to try, and we hadn't been to one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Mrs. Stern adds, she has no intention of abandoning her
passion for eating in ``ancient Cantonese restaurants.'' Her
favorite is the Pekin Noodle Parlor in Butte, Mont. ``It's
unchanged since 1955,'' she says. ``They serve the Chinese food
with French fries and a lettuce and tomato garnish.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern nods delightedly. ``It's so weird and wonderful,'' he
says. ``Someone else can do the rest of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
