<HEADER>
A6406 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-ECONOMY-HNS     02-23 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SEES STRONG U.S. ECONOMY THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
predicted that the U.S. economy will remain strong for the rest of
the year but that growth will slow and inflation will rise a bit
from last year's levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. economy's performance should remain solid this
year,'' Greenspan told lawmakers on the Senate Banking Committee
Tuesday in delivering the Fed's semiannual review to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned that there are ``several risks'' on the horizon
including continued economic slowdowns in Asia, Latin America and
Europe that could further depress demand for U.S. exports and tip
the U.S. economy into a recession. The U.S. trade deficit was a
record $168.6 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects the underpinnings of the U.S. economic
performance are strong,'' Greenspan said. ``But after eight years
of economic expansion, the economy appears stretched in a number of
dimensions, implying considerable upside and downside risks to the
economic outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   He said another risk to the economy would be a drop in stock
prices that could hurt consumer confidence and spending. He again
suggested that the stock market was ``overvalued,'' a concern he
first raised in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending accounts for about two thirds of gross
domestic product, which is the nation's total output of goods and
services. Greenspan and several other economists have said stock
market gains of the last few years have made consumers feel
comfortable spending money on items they might not normally
purchase in slower economic times.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Fed's report noted that Americans bought record
numbers of computers, cars and houses last year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the economy grew about 4 percent, which is well above
the Federal Reserve's target range of 2 percent to 2.5 percent, and
the inflation rate was 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently it was believed that if the economy grew more
than 2.5 percent, it would spark inflation. But for several years
it has grown faster without doing so.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, the Fed is forecasting U.S. economic growth to
slow to 2.5 percent to 3 percent and inflation, as measured by the
consumer price index, to be between 2 percent and 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have gone so well for so long we cannot explain what's
been happening with conventional economic theory,'' said Sung Won
Sohn, chief economist at Wells Fargo and Co. So far, Sohn and other
economists see no signs of a slowdown and expect growth during the
first quarter of 1999 to remain at about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A report released Tuesday by the Conference Board, a leading
business research organization, also suggested the economy would
continue to run at its current clip for a while. The report showed
that consumer confidence rose for the fourth straight month in
February by 3.2 points to 132.1.
</P>
<P>
   While discussing the risks that could hurt the U.S. economy,
Greenspan said its ``surprising'' robustness could continue to defy
his and other economists' expectations. Even he said he isn't sure
what is allowing the economy to grow so quickly without sparking
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said one-time occurrences such as low oil prices that
kept inflation extremely low in 1998 are unlikely to be repeated,
but he said larger, more permanent forces may be at work to make
the economy ``less inflation-prone than in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the fact that American businesses have held prices of
their products relatively constant for several years partly because
of competition from overseas but also because of changes in
technology that have made some goods less expensive to produce.
Computers, for instance, have allowed U.S. workers to become more
productive, which has helped companies offset the cost of wage
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also said that until recently many workers were
willing to trade wages increases for job security, which helped
keep pay hikes low. Now, Greenspan said, many companies are
``unwilling to raise wages any faster than they can support at
current price levels.''
</P>
<P>
   But if inflation does begin to rise, Greenspan suggested that
the Fed will increase interest rates in order to slow economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   His comments initially sent the Dow Jones industrial average
down 90 points, but it later recovered most of the loss, closing
down 8.26 at 9,544.42. The NASDAQ rose 34.34 points to close at
2,376.35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
