<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-H     02-23 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW COMES UNDER FIRE AS EXPIRATION NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the independent counsel law under attack from
both parties, two key senators on Tuesday predicted that the
statute won't be renewed in its present form when it expires June
30.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee, which begins hearings on Wednesday into whether
to renew or kill the Independent Counsel Act, told a news
conference that ``this law won't be renewed as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he worried that the intense media spotlight placed
on independent counsels ``pressured'' them to produce results,
regardless of the merits of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dangerous situation,'' he said. ``The independent
counsel is tempted to show his salt, to prove he is up to the task,
and the longer it goes, the more pressure there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his doubts about the law, Thompson promised to give the
statute a fair review. ``We're not going to stack the deck against
the law by only calling in witnesses that are against it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the witness list would include Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr and Attorney General Janet Reno, as well as former
special prosecutors and attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is coming out of the woodwork over this law, but I
still believe that the onus is on the people who want to keep the
statute around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One those people is Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., the top
Democrat on the Government Affairs Committee. Standing by
Thompson's side, he said no senators wanted to keep the law in its
present form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without changes to the law, there is almost no chance it will
survive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he wants an independent counsel law, but with
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans opposed the law when it was passed in the wake
of the Watergate scandal after President Richard M. Nixon ordered
the attorney general to dismiss special Watergate prosecutor
Archibald Cox after Cox refused to drop a subpoena for Nixon's
incriminating White House tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Under Presidents Reagan and Bush, congressional Republicans
complained that the statute permitted independent counsels to
conduct politically-inspired investigations. Independent Counsel
Lawrence Walsh's probe into the Iran-Contra arms-for-hostages deal
was the GOP's chief example.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans, upset over the six years and $48 million
Walsh spent investigating the Reagan and Bush administrations,
almost didn't renew the act in 1993. But a newly-elected President
Clinton lobbied for the law and won.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when a three-judge federal court panel appointed
Kenneth Starr to investigate Clinton, Democrats have repeated many
of the criticisms of the independent counsel voiced earlier by
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one issue on which the Republicans were right, and we
were wrong,'' Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., said earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law requires the attorney general to
seek the appointment of an independent counsel when there is
substantial and credible evidence of a crime by any one of 49 top
federal officials, including the president. A panel of three
federal judges then picks an attorney for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor has an unlimited budget to hire aides and
investigate _ a frequent point of criticism. Starr has spent nearly
$50 million on his investigation of allegations against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With approval from the attorney general and the appointing
judges, the independent counsel can broaden investigations far
beyond the original mandate, another target of the law's critics.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's mandate, for example, began with inquiries into
Clinton's land deals and widened repeatedly, finally to the Monica
Lewinsky scandal that led to his impeachment and trial. The Senate
acquitted Clinton Feb. 12, on the two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he and other senators were wary of continuing to
give prosecutors such broad powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent counsel has unlimited money and unlimited
time, and operates without any of the checks placed on a normal
prosecutor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said that although Starr's investigation of the
president has generated much of the recent criticisms against the
independent counsel statute, his committee's hearing will not be a
``referendum'' on Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be the Kenneth Starr show, nor is it
going to be the Lawrence Walsh show,'' he said. ``It's going to be
about the law and what to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, only one member of Congress has formally offered
suggestions on how the law could be changed. Last month, Rep. Jay
Dickey, R-Ark., introduced a bill that would continue the
independent counsel law but with restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey's bill would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Give the attorney general more power to investigate
allegations before requesting an independent counsel;
</P>
<P>
   _ Require that the scope of the investigation be narrowly set;
</P>
<P>
   _ Require special prosecutors to have their budgets approved
after two years;
</P>
<P>
   _ Bar independent counsels from practicing law privately while
serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limit the subject matter of an investigation to issues that
arose during the official's tenure in office, not before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue the way we are going with independent counsels,
we risk losing the support of America,'' Dickey said in a letter to
the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There have been at least 20 independent counsels appointed in
the last 20 years (some appointments were made under court seal),
with both Republican and Democratic presidents, cabinet members and
other officials as their targets. Total costs of these
investigations now stand at more than $133 million. Five
independent counsels are currently at work, investigating Clinton
and four present or past members of his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress lets the law lapse, such investigations would be
handled by the Justice Department. The attorney general would
retain authority to turn an investigation over to a special
prosecutor in the manner followed in the Watergate probe of Nixon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
