<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, Feb. 24. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
EXECUTE (Phoenix) - The State Board of Executive Clemency holds a
reprieve and commutation hearing for Karl LaGrand, scheduled to be
executed Wednesday for the 1982 murder of a bank manager. By MARK
SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AF-RECRUIT (Phoenix) - For years, the Air Force has prided itself
on needing little advertisement to attract new recruits. But unable
to meet its recruitment goals for the first time in more than two
decades and faced with unprecedented job growth in the private
sector, that's about to change. The Air Force is launching its
first ever television campaign with a $17 million spot on Feb 27.
That's part of a $76 million ad campaign, largest ever. Other
military branches are experiencing similar losses. By JENNIFER
BARRETT. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AMWEST (Phoenix) - America West's stock dives after the company
says it's not for sale. Story will include analysts' take on the
end of talks with United Airlines, whether it's really over, etc.
By DAWN GILBERTSON and PETER CORBETT. Story will move in the ``F''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDUCATION (Phoenix) - A federal law that gives states and local
school districts $12 billion a year to help poor students is
expiring, and congressional Republicans and Democrats are divided
over how to rework it.
</P>
<P>
   The goals of the 35-year-old education law seem universal:
better schools, smarter spending and more answers for parents whose
children are not learning. But this year marks the first time a
Republican majority has had a shot at rewriting it, and that could
change the way some programs operate. By AMY SVITAK. Story moved in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
ANNE STEPHENSON. Story moved in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
