<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMMY-GREENE-2TAKES-     02-23 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-GREENE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING THE MUSIC AT THE GRAMMYS: ACADEMY EXECUTIVE DOGGED BY
MISHAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the Shrine Auditorium, preparations were under
way for the 41st Grammy Awards ceremony, to be broadcast Wednesday
night on CBS. Drums, banners and giant cinder blocks were carted
hurriedly through the theater as employees in headsets dashed in
all directions; Aerosmith and Celine Dion labored through long
rehearsals with string sections; Bonnie Raitt stopped in for an
online conference, and Brian Wilson took a tour of the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Wandering calmly through the chaos was Michael Greene, casually
dressed in a sweatshirt and baseball cap. His unassuming presence
hardly conveyed that as chief executive of the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, which presents the Grammys, he has
become one of the most controversial figures in the music business.
His supporters hail him as a musical philanthropist who brought the
Grammy Awards up to date; his critics paint him as a self-serving
egomaniac raking in money under the guise of charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of enemies,'' Greene said. ``I've got 925
Grammy nominees and only 14 performance slots on that show. So all
the rest of them are mad at me. We've got over 4,000 people on the
waiting list for tickets to this show _ from Nelson Mandela's niece
to Steven Seagal. I can't get those people in, and they all hate
me. Then you've got the record companies: they all have acts they
want to break and their own ideas about how to program the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, whose father was a big-band leader in Atlanta, is a
saxophonist and composer with two albums to his name. Eleven years
ago, he became president of the academy. Since then, membership in
the organization has grown from 3,500 to 14,000, while the scale of
the production and its television audience have greatly expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Greene also started two charity arms of the academy, which have
had some of their practices questioned. Musicares provides
financial assistance to substance abuse programs for musicians, and
the Naras Foundation focuses on music education.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for example, he announced the construction in Los
Angeles of the first of several planned retirement homes and drug
treatment centers for musicians as well as a new program that will
include classical music CDs in the packages of new mothers leaving
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most rigorous duties of the academy's chief
executive is to take the heat when the organization's 10,000 voting
members grant top awards to albums that are not exactly standard
bearers for a year in music, as in 1995 when Tony Bennett won Album
of the Year for ``MTV Unplugged.'' Greene has usually shared the
consternation of his critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most nervous part of my existence all year is when those
winners are announced,'' he said. ``I'm a rock musician and I love
jazz, but some of the popular music forms leave me just a little
unfulfilled. So I'm in the same boat as everyone else on Grammy
night. There's good stuff that happens, like Ry Cooder winning with
``The Buena Vista Social Club'' last year, but if ``Titanic''
cleans up this year, I'll be having a couple of martinis.''
</P>
<P>
   Nominations and final votes in most categories are open to all
the Grammy's voting members. But three years ago, Greene instituted
a 25-person review board to pick nominations in top categories,
which he said would eliminate fluff pop like ``Macarena'' from the
running. This has quelled some criticism, but musical taste has
been the least of Greene's problems lately.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's recent troubles began in New York last year during a
news conference announcing the nominees for the 1998 awards. When
an aide to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani complained because the mayor was
not allowed to announce any of the nominations (which are typically
read only by musicians), Greene was accused of losing his temper
with her and making threatening statements, behavior he has denied.
As a result of the incident, Giuliani said Greene was out of line
and that the Grammys could return to Los Angeles for all he cared.
(The show usually alternates between Los Angeles and New York.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite Giuliani's condemnation, Greene said that next year the
Grammy Awards could still take place in New York at Madison Square
Garden, which is competing for the show with the new Staples Center
arena in Los Angeles. ``I've got to patch things up with the mayor,
and we will,'' Greene said. Speaking of top record executives, he
continued, ``Tommy Mottola and Doug Morris and everybody there is
saying, `Get the show back to New York now!'''
</P>
<P>
   A comment from Giuliani could not be obtained in time for
publication.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Greene said that everybody but one party
regretted the events surrounding the press conference. ``I wish I'd
never gone in that green room that morning,'' he said.
``Misunderstandings happen, especially when they're communicated by
third parties. Any time I'm the focus of anything like that it is
bad for the music industry, it's bad for our membership, it's bad
for the Grammys. CBS thinks it helped ratings, though. They loved
it. They said, `Aren't you going to get into a fight with
Riordan?''' (Richard Riordan is the mayor of Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   Greene's troubles worsened when The Los Angeles Times published
a series of articles raising questions about his stewardship. Among
other things, the paper reported that Musicares spent only about 10
percent of the money it raised on charitable works; questioned why
the academy charged the Naras Foundation $500,000 for using the
Grammy trademark; said that the $700,000 bonus Greene received in
1997 was the largest ever paid to an executive of a nonprofit
organization, and reported that he tried to interest record labels
in releasing a CD of his own music during Grammy-related meetings,
which could create a conflict of interest because Greene gets to
decide who performs at the Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
