<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMMY-GREENE-2NDTAKE     02-23 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-GREENE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: the Grammys. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Polygram-owned Mercury Records eventually made a deal to
release the CD, though it was dropped when Polygram was sold to
Universal. Mercury was working on a deal to release the album but
abandoned it during the controversy.)
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the articles, Greene defended the payment for the
Grammy trademark, saying it was a ``good business relationship''
that since 1994 has helped increase foundation revenue from less
than $1 million a year to more than $3 million a year, and that his
bonus was appropriate for a business-league trade association. He
added that he received no payment for operating the charities and
contended that 60 percent of Musicare's revenue went to its
programs.
</P>
<P>
   He was unapologetic about trying to release a CD of his music,
and when asked if this request to music companies represented a
conflict of interest, he simply said, ``I'm a musician and there's
not much I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing that happened in that is I didn't get to
finish my record,'' Greene continued, adding that next month he
would travel to Connecticut to mix the record before giving it to
his lawyers to find a label for it, with proceeds earmarked for
music charities.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Greene found himself at the center of another
contretemps. An online music site called MP3.com, one of the
Internet's largest clearinghouses for legally downloadable songs,
tried to place an advertisement in Grammy magazine. But the
magazine would not run the advertisement because, it explained in a
letter, it had limited advertising space and because of MP3.com's
``somewhat controversial nature.'' This letter seemingly put the
Grammys in the same club as the record industry establishment,
which is trying to stop the encroachment of Internet sales on its
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Greene said that he was a passionate supporter of the online
music market, and that the money was rejected because the magazine
was being taken off the newsstand and had stopped accepting
advertisements. The staff member who wrote the letter has since
said that the opinions were his and not those of the Naras.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's Grammy Awards promise to score more favorably,
at least musically, with critics than in previous years, even
though Greene describes 1998 as ``a mediocre year for music.''
Sheryl Crow, Garbage, Madonna, Shania Twain and Madonna have been
nominated for Album of the Year, none of whom would embarrass
Greene as winners.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lauryn Hill, who was nominated for 10 Grammy Awards,
more than any other artist this year, is at the center of a lawsuit
by four musicians called New Ark. They claim that Ms. Hill denied
them proper songwriting and production credits on her album, ``The
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' as well as on a Grammy-nominated
track by Aretha Franklin that Ms. Hill is credited with producing.
Ms. Hill and her lawyers adamantly deny the charges, which are
common in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a person wins a Grammy and it is later adjudicated and the
rights issue is reversed, we very quietly get the Grammy to the
right people,'' Greene said. ``We've done it before without telling
anybody. We try to preserve the dignity of the people involved.
This is something nobody knows, but the Grammy belongs to the
academy in perpetuity. The artists and their direct blood estate
can keep it as long as they want, but if the IRS tries to take it
away, they can't. We've done that with several people, including
Willie Nelson. I remember I once walked into a silent auction and
there was Jascha Heifetz's Grammy for auction, and I picked it
right up and walked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are held in New York or Los Angeles and whether
they are mired in scandal or trouble-free, the Grammy Awards in
2000 will probably not be as interesting as the ceremony in 2001,
when everything is up for grabs. In 2001, not only does CBS's
contract to broadcast the show expire, but so does Greene's
contract with the Naras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get asked twice a day, `So what are you going to do after
this?''' Greene said. ``But as long as we can keep growing and I
can keep dealing with music people, they'll have to throw me out
because I really love what I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
