<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHY DO YOU NEED TWO COPIES OF WINDOWS?
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Why are most consumers who already have a current
Windows license required to buy another copy of the Microsoft
operating system when they upgrade their computer to the latest
model?
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers are likely to raise that issue Wednesday at
the Microsoft antitrust trial when they cross-examine Joachim
Kempin, a Microsoft senior vice president who rides herd over the
software giant's dealings with personal computer makers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In industry jargon, the PC firms are known as ``original
equipment manufacturers'' or ``OEMs.'' While Microsoft supplies
Windows directly to hundreds of OEMs, it deals primarily with the
industry's ``Big Seven'': Acer, Compaq, Dell, Gateway 2000,
Hewlett-Packard, IBM and Packard Bell/NEC.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's defense team has charged Kempin with rebutting a key
facet of the broad case that the Department of Justice has lodged
against Microsoft. It is the charge that Microsoft's contracts with
the OEMs oblige them to favor the Internet Explorer browser, built
into the latest versions of Windows, at the expense of the
Navigator browser developed by a Microsoft rival, Netscape
Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But in his direct testimony released Tuesday, Kempin argues that
the charge is unjustified. ``The government's testimony about this
subject _ which comes from economists, not any OEM witnesses
testifying in open court _ is mostly based on a mistaken (or, at
best, confused) premise,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   The government argues, in effect, that this ``premise'' should
be upheld by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson by finding
that Microsoft sought to illegally misuse its vast Windows market
power to seek control of Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Kempin's 33-page brief does not address the issue of mandatory
Windows pre-loading, a policy which has become the focal point of
several public anti-Microsoft demonstrations in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Computer hardware executives generally cite two reasons behind
for this policy: inhibiting software piracy and limiting the
support costs they would incur after users failed to load the
Windows operating system properly on ``bare'' hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the ``Big Seven'' makers note that most of
the machines they build for business customers can be purchased
with a non-Windows operating system such as Linux, or even with no
system.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the issue of flexibility in the Windows operating
system, Kempin notes in his direct testimony that Microsoft allows
the ``Big Seven'' to modify the Windows 98 startup sequence in two
ways.
</P>
<P>
   They can replace the registration ``wizard'' in the Windows 98
boot sequence with software that offers to sign up the customer
jointly with both the OEM and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they can add their own software to allow computer
buyers to sign up for Internet access with one or more providers
selected by the OEMs. That software can run automatically, prior to
any customer opportunity to use the standard ``Internet Connection
Wizard'' feature of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say these procedures have become a rising
source of revenue for big hardware vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
