   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, Feb. 24. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-COUNSEL (Washington) _ On the eve of Senate hearings
into the law authorizing independent counsels, prominent senators
of both parties predict that the Watergate-era statute will be
heavily revised if renewed at all, becoming a casualty of the
just-ended impeachment struggle. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ In a last-minute
turnaround, the ethnic Albanian delegation at the Kosovo talks
agree in principle to a peace settlement, turning what appeared to
be an almost certain collapse for the Clinton administration's
peace effort into a limited success. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ President Clinton and Republican
leaders of Congress hold their first formal meeting in 19 months, a
businesslike but chilly session that appears to have done little to
pacify the cold war between them. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   ALPS-AVALANCHE (Rome) _ An avalanche crashed through a small
Austrian resort and left at least seven people dead and dozens
missing, in one of the worst Alpine snow disasters in years. Snow
and deadly winds prevented emergency helicopters from flying into
the ski village of Galtuer, near the Swiss border. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   DRAGGING-DEATH (Jasper, Texas) _ With exceptional swiftness, the
jury in the racially motivated dragging death of James Byrd Jr.
declares the white defendant, John William King, guilty of capital
murder. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MIGRATE (Beijing) _ China is on the move these days, with
an estimated 10 percent of the population now migrating from their
official place of residence, mostly in search of better jobs.
Legions of young Chinese are moving one step up the job chain _
those from tiny villages move to small cities to find work, and
those from small provincial cities move to large cities. But rural
migrants remain perpetual outsiders in China's cities, with little
hope of securing the coveted urban residence permits that would
allow them to build an entirely legal life here. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal. With map and photos. 1,700 words. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-EURO (Zurich, Switzerland) _ It isn't one of the 11 euro
nations _ it isn't even a member of the European Union _ but that
hasn't stopped Switzerland from embracing the continent's new
common currency with an enthusiasm that eclipses even the euro
euphoria of some of its large neighbors. By John Tagliabue. 1,800
words.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EURO (London) _ The British prime minister, Tony Blair,
announces his government's plans for adopting the euro. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RITTER (Washington) _ The State Department charges that a
new book by Scott Ritter, a former U.N. weapons inspector who has
alleged that the CIA helped plan arms inspections in Iraq, is
inaccurate, misleading and ``can only serve Saddam Hussein's
propaganda machine.'' By Philip Shenon.
</P>
