<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GROUP TO PROBE MEXICO'S EFFORT AGAINST DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the deadline nears for the Clinton
administration to decide whether to recertify Mexico as a
drug-fighting ally, the Senate wants to know how whether Mexico is
diligently helping the U.S. war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate's Narcotics Control Caucus, Sen.
Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, said many members of Congress are
disappointed with Mexico's drug-control efforts. Grassley will
preside Wednesday over hearings that examine Mexico's efforts to
combat drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus will hear from Raymond W. Kelley, U.S. Customs
Service commissioner; Admiral James Loy, commandant of the U.S.
Coast Guard; Rand Beers, assistant secretary for the Bureau of
International Narcotics in the State Department; and Thomas A.
Constantine, administrator of the Drug Enforcement Administration,
.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said he wants the hearing ``to send a signal that we
aren't totally satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration has until March 1 to decide whether to
certify to Congress that Mexico has fully cooperated in the war
against drugs. Failure to win certification could require a cutoff
of U.S. aid and a U.S. vote against World Bank loans to the
offending countries. The administration also could choose a middle
course, deciding to decertify a country but waive the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton indicated last week when he met with Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo that he will recertify Mexico as a
committed ally in the fight against drugs. Congress then has 30
days to vote to overturn a presidential decision on certification.
</P>
<P>
   One critic of Mexico's drug-control efforts in the past, Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said she will wait until after the
hearing to decide whether to try to block recertification of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top levels of the Mexican government are trying'' to stem
drug trafficking through more infrastructure and technology,
Feinstein said. On the other hand, ``indications of money
laundering, and a lack of arrests and drug seizures don't look
good,'' she said in an interview. ``The cartels are flourishing and
that's of deep concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have complained that Mexico seized less heroin and
cocaine last year than in previous years. They also cite declines
in the number of drug seizures, arrests and investigations in
Mexico last year. There also have been concerns about widespread
corruption in Mexican law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that about 400 tons of cocaine cross the
2,000-mile-long U.S.-Mexican border each year. U.S. officials also
say Mexico is a major producer of marijuana, opium and
amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, who has also criticized
Mexican anti-drug efforts in the past, said she ``has concern about
the certification process,'' adding: ``I think we need another
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in their right mind thinks we are making the progress
we need to make,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., who chairs the Senate
Agriculture Committee, predicted Mexico's certification will be
renewed as it has been 12 times since 1986 when Congress began
requiring the administration to certify annually that
drug-producing countries are cooperating with U.S. anti-drug
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to a pragmatic choice,'' Lugar said. ``I would
guess that when push comes to shove, we would recertify and
continue to work with Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The prior certification have sparked some criticism in Congress
and occasional efforts to cancel the administration's decision to
recertify. Those efforts have been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown University political science professor John Bailey,
who is scheduled to testify at the hearing Wednesday, also
predicted Mexico will be recertified.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't decertify a country you have a 2,000-mile border
with,'' he said. ``The relations are so vast and deep that
decertification isn't a real option.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico ranks as the United States' second-largest trading
partner, having surpassed Japan and its much larger economy. Canada
is the No. 1 U.S. trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, said the United States is partly at
fault for failing to contribute enough money and manpower to help
curb drug production at the source in Mexico and other
drug-producing countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't concentrated on the supply side as much as we could
have,'' Hatch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
