<HEADER>
A6454 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-TAXCUTS-HNS &LR;      02-23 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TAXCUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERS SOFTEN THEIR CALL FOR 10 PERCENT TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Stands for REPUBLICAN-DISUNITY)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Clinton administration opposed to a flat
10 percent tax cut, Republican congressional leaders on Tuesday
struck a more conciliatory posture, saying an across-the-board tax
cut is only one of several ways of returning surplus revenue to
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are for tax cuts,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., told reporters after meeting with Republican governors.
``There are a lot of different ways to do that. They may be a mix,
or they may be across the board, but tax cuts will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., made clear his
preference for a 10 percent across-the-board cut. He cited an
example of a 30-year-old single female taxpayer in Jackson, Miss.,
who would receive $500 back under a 10 percent cut, but nothing
under the proposed marriage penalty tax cut, one of the chief
alternate proposals discussed in the last session of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the marriage penalty would reduce taxes on
joint-income married couples who now pay more taxes than they would
if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lott said ``tax relief'' can be achieved through
``a rate cut and/or some cut like the marriage penalty tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   The willingness to consider tax cuts other than a 10 percent cut
contrasts to previous Republican insistence on an across-the-board
cut.
</P>
<P>
   At a GOP rally in Warren, Mich., last week, Lott stood
underneath a banner saying ``Listen to America _ Tax Cuts for
Everyone,'' and asked the crowd: ``Do you want this surplus spent
by Washington, or do you want it returned to the people?'' The
budget surplus is estimated at $2.56 trillion over the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has opposed the 10 percent cut, arguing it
would favor the wealthy. Clinton prefers what he terms ``targeted''
tax cuts to individuals in need. For instance, Clinton in his
budget plan earlier this month proposed tax credits for individuals
caring for elderly relatives, and credits for work expenses of
disabled workers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Republicans agree on one thing: About 60 percent of
the surplus must be earmarked to save Social Security, which will
not be able to pay full benefits to retirees in 2032 unless
something is done to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
said that considering the size of the budget surplus, the Social
Security system can be shored up and about $900 billion can be
returned to tax payers over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators want a tax cut, but are not overly
particular what form it takes, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Surplus revenues, he said, ``can be used for an across-the-board
type cut or any of the various popular reductions that are musts
for the American people. I don't sense any polaraziation of one
versus the other here.''
</P>
<P>
   One prominent Republican expressed disappointment that
Republican congressional leaders appeared to be backing away from
the 10 percent cut. Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin told reporters
that Republican lawmakers ``should have an identity. It should be
10 percent across-the-board (tax cut)'' that GOP lawmakers should
approve even in the face of a certain White House veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will differentiate between Republicans and Democrats and
show the American public that there is a difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a veteran Republican governor widely credited with
being the moving force behind welfare reform after starting an
early version in Wisconsin in 1987, blasted the GOP congressional
leadership for being ``too tepid. They need to stand up and be
aggressive and develop their own plans, instead of always being on
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson linked the Republican loss of five seats in the House
last November to last year's budget deal with Clinton which gave
the administration significant victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to stand up to Clinton,'' Thompson said.
``And I think as a result of that, Republicans stayed home (on
Election Day) and Democrats came out and we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma, a Republican who is this
year's chairman of the National Governors' Association, said
Republicans shouldn't view Clinton's positions as the sole measure
of the success or failure of the party's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans should not hesitate nor apologize for their value
systems,'' he said. ``We should be able to jointly advance an
agenda for prosperity and growth. I think we're making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if about the view that Republican lawmakers gave away too
much in last year's budget agreement, Keating said ``people's knees
should not knock over Bill Clinton. Bill Clinton was impeached ...
The thing to do is not be afraid to do the right thing (at a time
when) Mr. Clinton happens to be the president.''
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, Keating said with a broad smile on his face, ``I
think he (Clinton) wants what's best for the country, too!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
