<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-PICKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL WIN MUSIC WORLD'S TOP TROPHIES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The girls' night out this evening at the 41st
annual Grammy Awards makes hip-hop diva Lauryn Hill the gal to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   We predict Hill, leading the nominations with 10 nods, will take
home five of the famous trophies shaped as miniature gramophones
when the awards are presented at the Shrine Auditorium and on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's seductive solo debut album, ``The Miseducation of Lauryn
Hill,'' will probably win for album of the year and r&AMP;b album,
while the 23-year-old New Jersey native should get votes for new
artist and producer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Here are our picks for some of the night's biggest honors. The
eligibility period for the Grammys _ the second-most-watched awards
show after the Oscars _ runs from Oct. 1, 1997, through Sept. 30,
1998, with a total of 925 nominees in 95 categories.
</P>
<P>
   RECORD OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Easy _ Celine Dion's ``My Heart Will Go On,'' the ``Titantic''
love theme that sold 26 million copies. Never does a dollars 'n'
cents dud get this award, while movie hits have won in four of the
last six years. &QL; 
ALBUM OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Proven Grammy favorite Sheryl Crow (``The Globe Sessions'') and
the sorely overlooked Madonna (``Ray of Light'') compete with
Shania Twain, Hill and Garbage. Hill's widely praised
``Miseducation'' gets it. &QL; 
SONG OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Five of the past six winners have been movie-related. That's why
Dion's ``My Heart Will Go On'' will win this songwriters' honor for
composer James Horner and lyricist Will Jennings. &QL; 
NEW ARTIST
</P>
<P>
   Often the kiss-of-death category _ Christopher Cross, anyone? _
but this year Hill will probably gather more votes than competitors
Backstreet Boys, Andrea Bocelli, Dixie Chicks and Natalie
Imbruglia. &QL; 
FEMALE POP VOCAL PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Dion again _ her first in this category. &QL; 
MALE POP VOCAL PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   The favorite is Eric Clapton's ``My Father's Eyes,'' although
we'd rather see Eagle-Eye Cherry's ``Save Tonight'' get the nod. &QL; 
POP PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Aerosmith's ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing'' could get it, but
we predict the swing thing will fuel the Brian Setzer Orchestra's
first Grammy win for the ubiquitous ``Jump Jive an' Wail.'' &QL; 
POP COLLABORATION WITH VOCALS
</P>
<P>
   Grammy gets a much-needed shot of credibility by voting odd
couple Elvis Costello and Burt Bacharach into the club for ``I
Still Have That Other Girl.'' &QL; 
DANCE RECORDING
</P>
<P>
   Madonna's adventurous ``Ray of Light.'' An English accent _ real
or faked _ usually helps in this category. &QL; 
POP ALBUM
</P>
<P>
   Madonna wins again for ``Ray of Light.'' &QL; 
TRADITIONAL POP VOCAL PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bennett ordinarily wins here _ but he didn't release an
album during the eligibility period. however, old-time crooner Jack
Jones did _ and it's a tribute to Bennett. Need we say more? &QL; 
FEMALE ROCK VOCAL PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Even though critics' fave Lucinda Williams has a shot at this
trophy for ``Can't Let Go,'' watch Alanis Morissette get the vote
for the radio hit ``Uninvited.'' &QL; 
MALE ROCK VOCAL PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Crazy, man! John Hiatt's ``Have a Little Faith in Me'' was
nominated even though it first came out in 1987. But the late Jeff
Buckley will probably garner the sympathy vote for ``Everybody Here
Wants You.'' &QL; 
ROCK PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP WITH VOCAL
</P>
<P>
   The record academy is probably as intimidated as everyone else
by Courtney Love's raving lunatic act, so Hole's ``Celebrity Skin''
will get the golden gramophone. Watch her break it. &QL; 
HARD ROCK PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the academy makes a surprise left turn _ and votes
for Marilyn Manson's ``The Dope Show.'' &QL; 
METAL PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   As much as we'd like to see those gasoline-powered Nashville
kittens get the nod, we won't be surprised when Metallica wins in
this category for the fourth time. &QL; 
ROCK SONG
</P>
<P>
   Morissette's ``Uninvited'' again, although the more deserving
winners would be Mick Jagger and Keith Richards with Richard
Ashcroft for the Verve's glorious ``Bitter Sweet Symphony.'' &QL; 
ROCK ALBUM
</P>
<P>
   The academy honors studio savvy and votes inducts ``Version
2.0'' by Garbage. &QL; 
ALTERNATIVE MUSIC PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Beastie Boys' ``Hello Nasty'' gets the trophy. &QL; 
SONG WRITTEN FOR A MOTION PICTURE OR TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   A little ditty from ``Titanic'' might have a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
