<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KURDS-COX     02-23 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Louis J. Salome was the Middle East and European correspondent
for Cox Newspapers and The Palm Beach Post for 9 1/2 years. In
1991, he visited a camp operated by the military arm of the
Kurdistan Workers Party. In the wake of recent events in the
region, Salome reflects on that trip in this story.
 &HT;    By Louis J. Salome
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YONTEH, Lebanon _ On the wall of the camp library, next to a
cluster of rifles, was a large photograph of everyman's
revolutionary, Che Guevara. Standing upright on a shelf was a copy,
written in Turkish, of Karl Marx's Das Kapital, which kissed the
cover of an illustrated biography of Nikolai Lenin.
</P>
<P>
   A little dated here, I thought, recalling the fall of the Berlin
Wall almost two years earlier. It was early September 1991, and I
was spending a couple of days at a remote mountain training camp
with some of the most notorious, effective and anachronistic
guerrillas in the Middle East: The military arm of the Kurdistan
Workers Party, known as the PKK and led by Abdullah Ocalan, a
Turkish Kurd who was then the most elusive, if largely unknown,
Kurd in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 7 1/2 years later, Ocalan (pronounced OH-cha-lan) has
become a larger-than-life global figure. He was captured in
mysterious circumstances in Kenya on Feb. 15, and was returned with
great celebration to Turkey for trial. Tuesday, he was formally
charged with treason, and prosecutors are seeking the death
penalty. Kurdish exiles throughout Europe greeted Ocalan's capture
with massive protests, firebombings and kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, the PKK described the rugged, barren mountains of
Yonteh in eastern Lebanon as ``a no man's land,'' which is a
captivating name for a people without a country.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Guevara, Marx and Lenin library was a small
amphitheater, with four rows of wood benches, covered by a canvas
held aloft by thin, buckling saplings. This was where the camp
commander turned library sessions into political indoctrination.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to think that the awed Kurdish recruits from Turkey,
guerrillas in training, believed that the tent remained standing
only because of the will of their all-powerful leader, Ocalan, a
blown-up photograph of whom dominated the amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   All around this guerrilla boot camp were photographs of
``martyrs,'' PKK fighters who trained here and died fighting in
southeastern Turkey for political autonomy and against Turkish
repression. The martyrs represented the blood part of the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the library was the military training ground, where men
and women recruits wearing Nike and Adidas athletic shoes hardened
themselves for attacks inside Turkey by dodging live bullets,
crawling under barbed wire and somersaulting through rings of fire.
</P>
<P>
   This training camp, its only one outside of Turkey, represented
the hard political and military core of the PKK, which since 1984
has caused havoc far beyond its numbers in Turkey. Ocalan is the
Guevara, Marx and Lenin of the PKK, which in ideological terms is
mired somewhere in the mid-Fifties.
</P>
<P>
   From their base in Lebanon, a steady stream of PKK guerrillas _
200 to 300 fresh recruits every three months _ traveled overland to
Turkey. There, they took over Kurdish towns, established PKK cells
and trained more guerrillas for attacks against the Turkish army
and civilians. They also provoked the Turkish army into attacks
that nearly obliterated Kurdish towns _ and in many cases turned
Kurds against the PKK.
</P>
<P>
   As worshipped as he is by the PKK guerrillas, Ocalan is not the
god of the Kurdish people, as many as 25 million of whom are
scattered across the mountains, historically known as Kurdistan, in
Iran, Iraq, Syria, Armenia and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   He is not even the god of the Turkish Kurds, most of whom,
despite poverty and government attempts to suppress their identity,
reject the PKK's violent methods that have killed about 37,000
people in Turkey and brought the devastating force of the Turkish
military crashing down on Kurdish towns in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The violent protests by Kurds across Europe gives the impression
that the protesters must all be members of the PKK or that Ocalan
is a leader to all Kurds. They are not and he is not.
</P>
<P>
   Many are protesting the treacherous manner in which Ocalan, who
is still one of them, was captured and the way he is likely to be
treated by the tough Turkish authorities who believe they can crush
the PKK by erasing Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurds are also protesting the repressive political, social,
economic and military conditions that exist in Turkey and which
continue to smear Turkey's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, the Kurds are also using Ocalan's capture
to inform the world that all 25 million of them remain stateless.
</P>
<P>
   Divided by the states where they live, by tribal and political
allegiances that make them willing and unwilling pawns in regional
and international affairs, the Kurds are as complex as the region
where most of them live.
</P>
<P>
   Most Kurds are secular Muslims who belong to the main Sunni
sect. PKK members are more secular than most, devoted to what they
call ``scientific socialism that can be applied to the reality and
conditions of our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Six miles from Lebanon's border with Syria and not far from the
Bekaa Valley, which was notorious for its Iranian-linked guerrilla
bases, the PKK trained with the permission of Syria, which
controlled Lebanon then and still does.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1991, I watched recruits _ 200 of the 10,000 of whom had
trained at the Lebanon base since it opened in 1984 _ march with
notebooks and rifles into the library for part of the political
indoctrination that gave them as much a reason for existing as
their military training.
</P>
<P>
   I listened to their political lessons that cemented internal
discipline and built esprit de corps. I ate with the recruits,
talked with them and watched their commander, Numan Salman,
distribute green jackets that had three U.S. flags on each label,
which said American Field Jacket, M-65.
</P>
<P>
   I watched the recruits, men and women, carry Soviet-made
Kalashnikov rifles, U.S.-made M-16s, Turkish-made J-3 rifles, and
J-1 rifles, which are used by NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weapons are not a problem for us. The Middle East is full of
weapons,'' Salman said, with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   I also lived for weeks at a time _ in 1991, 1992 and 1996 _ with
Kurds in Syria, Iraq and Turkey. Saddam Hussein drove the Iraqi
Kurds from northern Iraq after the Gulf War in 1991, but that was
not the PKK's war. Only when the Iraq-Turkey border later became a
defenseless zone did the PKK cross the mountains into Iraq and use
the frontier as a staging area for attacks in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish soldiers would kill any Kurds who tried to cross from
Iraq into Turkey. I know, because when I tried to escape from Iraq
in 1991, border guards, thinking I was a Kurd, said they would kill
me if I tried to cross the river.
</P>
<P>
   Until late last year, Ocalan was sheltered in Damascus, Syria,
from which he traveled often to the PKK base in Lebanon. And with
Syria looking the other way, the PKK sometimes launched attacks
across the Syria-Turkey border, until heavy Turkish military
pressure halted the attacks and late last year forced Syria to
expel Ocalan and send him on the futile search for asylum that led
to his capture.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, I located what Syrian Kurds told me was
Ocalan's refuge in Damascus, but I was never able to spot him
there.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 million Kurds live in northeastern Syria near its border
with Turkey and Iraq, but the Kurdish military presence there
centered mainly around Kurds from Iraq, not Turkey. No friend of
Saddam Hussein, Syria opened its border with Iraq in a vain attempt
to help the Iraqi Kurds resist him after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   I have interviewed Jalil Talabani, Massoud Barzani and Sami
Abdul Rahman, the main tribal leaders of the Iraqi Kurds, and
listened to each attempt to delude the world, and probably
themselves, into believing that a victory against Saddam Hussein
was just around the next mountain when a rout awaited them in a
nearby valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurdish fighters in Iraq are called Peshmergas, which means
``men who are facing death.'' Peshmergas are mountain clansmen who
wear baggy tribal clothing with bandoliers of bullets that
crisscross their bodies, broad sashes across their waists and cloth
bands wound around their heads. They look like mountain fighters
from another century.
</P>
<P>
   The Peshmergas are brave but underarmed and anachronistic
mountain fighters compared to the PKK guerrillas, who are backed by
a political ideology that gives them political cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   As outdated as it is, the PKK's Marxist-Leninist philosophy
provided the glue that kept the organization together. The PKK
never wavered in one other respect: Abdullah Ocalan, the man they
call ``Apo,'' gave PKK guerrillas their intellectual and military
reason for being.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan, one recruit said back in 1991, ``is everything for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now his capture gives Ocalan the stature among other Kurds he
never had before. Ironically, the fact that Ocalan is in a Turkish
prison proves he is one Kurd who succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Salome writes for the Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
