<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIITE GUERRILLAS KILL 3 ISRAELI OFFICERS IN SOUTH LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the year's fiercest battle yet in South Lebanon,
three Israeli officers were killed and five soldiers wounded early
on Tuesday by Shiite Muslim guerrillas who attacked them with
grenades and machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   As Israeli radio played mourning music, politicians visited the
wounded and television cameras recorded the funerals, the
casualties set off the latest round of soul-searching here about
the 20-year-long Israeli military presence in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But the soul-searching is cyclical. It arises when coffins force
the question of whether there is any reason for Israel to continue
risking young soldiers' lives inside Lebanon; it dissipates when
the burial images fade. And on Tuesday there was already a
half-hearted quality to the questioning as minor domestic political
events distracted the country's attention.
</P>
<P>
   To Claude Balahsan, however, the anguish of the day could not be
greater. His son, Eitan, a 30-year-old major, who commanded the
special army unit that came under fire, was the first killed. And
Balahsan's faltering voice, choked with emotion, pleaded on Israeli
radio for his loss to serve as a catalyst for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot keep having the troops serve as cannon fodder for
the settlements in the north,'' said Balahsan, who lives on a
settlement in the north. ``I'm turning to the government way up
there to get it together and start thinking. It can't be that every
week or two, a soldier dies, two soldiers die. It can't go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Israelis awoke on Tuesday morning to an eerie but increasingly
familiar black box on the front page of their newspapers. Inside
the box, in white letters, the headlines told of heavy fighting in
South Lebanon. But the typography has grown to be code. Israelis
knew that it meant there had been deaths, but that the army censors
weren't ready to let the news go public.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army and spokesmen for Hezbollah, the Iranian-backed
Shiite guerrilla group, offered different versions of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis said that just after midnight, the elite
paratroopers unit slipped over the invisible border between
Israel's 9-mile-deep security zone in South Lebanon _ which it
occupied in 1985, saying it needed to protect its northern towns _
into South Lebanon proper. They were heading toward Hezbollah bases
when they crossed paths with a group of from three to five
guerrilla fighters who were scouting the area, the army said.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Hezbollah in Beirut said its special
guerrilla force penetrated Israel's security zone, and ambushed the
Israeli soldiers there. Hezbollah said it suffered no casualties,
The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that Hezbollah opened fire, that the clash was
fierce and deadly, and that Israel retaliated with air strikes
early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The incident brought the first casualties of the year. After
Balahsan fell, the others killed were Lt. Liraz Tito, who was to
turn 22 on Tuesday, and Lt. David Granit, 22. The five wounded
soldiers were evacuated to Israeli hospitals during the heavy
gunbattle that followed.
</P>
<P>
   For some Israelis, resolving the conflict on their northern
border is as vital a concern as making peace with the Palestinians.
Every year brings a fresh death toll _ 21 soldiers died last year _
and with every wavelet of deaths, there are renewed calls for a
unilateral troop withdrawal from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Beilin, the 4th-ranking member of the Labor Party, sent a
``Dear Misha'' letter to Defense Minister Moshe Arens on Tuesday,
suggesting that he devote the remainder of his term to Lebanon.
Elections are scheduled for May 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in the short time left in your term, you pull the army out
of Lebanon, you will be remembered as the person who brought the
Israeli movie of folly to an end,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But most military experts here believe that the best, if not the
only, solution to Israel's enmeshed presence in South Lebanon is to
negotiate its withdrawal, preferably with Syria, which effectively
controls Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Arens, in fact, made it bluntly clear in a speech on Monday that
he did not consider Lebanon worth talking to. In unusually frank
language, he called Lebanon a ``puppet state'' controlled by Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all the trappings of an independent country,'' he said
in a speech here to the Conference of Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations. ``It has a president. It has a parliament. It
is a member of the United Nations. It has ambassadors. But it is a
noncountry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the world goes along with the charade, but everyone
knows it is a charade,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said his government was
``weighing alternatives all the time.'' But his opponents in the
race for prime minister _ Ehud Barak, the Labor Party leader, and
Yitzhak Mordechai, the Center Party leader _ say they would
immediately reopen negotiations with Syria over Lebanon and the
Golan Heights.
</P>
</TEXT>
