<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCULPTURE-RETURN-620&AMP;     02-23 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCULPTURE-RETURN-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM RETURNS ONCE-STOLEN SCULPTURE TO INDIA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 15 years ago, the Manhattan's Asia Society
learned that a 1,000-year-old Indian relief sculpture in its
collection had been stolen from a provincial museum in Dhubela, in
central India. The government of Madhya Pradesh state asked for the
return of the piece, which John D. Rockefeller III, the Asia
Society's founder, had donated to the museum in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after many intermittent discussions, the society
worked out the details of the return with Indian officials, joining
the small but growing number of museums that are voluntarily
surrendering items of cultural heritage to their countries of
origin.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles said it
would turn over three important antiquities from its collection to
the Italian government. In October, the Denver Art Museum returned
a carved wooden lintel to Guatemala after discovering that it had
been looted from a Mayan temple there in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   And the Association of Art Museum Directors, facing both an
increase in claims from governments and stepped-up criticism from
some archeologists, decided late last month to revise its code of
ethics. The result may be to clarify what is expected when museums
acquire items that a foreign country considers part of its cultural
patrimony, when the items should be repatriated and when museums
may, in general, reduce their holding through deaccession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next 25 years this issue is going to blow up,'' said
one museum director who insisted on anonymity. ``And our code of
ethics position on buying is not so clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The code, last revised about nine years ago, deems it
unprofessional for a museum director ``to acquire knowingly or
allow to be recommended for acquisition any object that has been
stolen, removed in contravention of treaties and international
conventions to which the United States is a signatory, or illegally
imported into the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   It does not say anything about what questions should be asked
about an item's previous ownership before it is considered for
acquisition. That loophole, combined with the word ``knowingly,''
seems to allow museums to remain in willful ignorance about an
object's past.
</P>
<P>
   The code's language also fails to address acquisitions made
between 1970, when Unesco adopted a convention against illicit
trade in cultural property, and 1983, when the United States joined
the Unesco pact. And it is silent on items that were exported
illegally under the laws of other countries but without violating
American import regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Vishakha N. Desai, the president of the museum directors'
association and the director of the Asia Society's galleries, at
Park avenue and 70th street, declined to predict how the code would
be changed, but said, ``I want this to be done within a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The cultural patrimony issue is thornier than it may appear, and
opinions on the subject vary widely. At one extreme are some
archaeologists who object to the removal of any object from any
excavation site lest it lose its context.
</P>
<P>
   At the other are dealers, collectors and curators of antiquities
who portray themselves as propagators of knowledge and preservers
of cultural objects that might be lost if left to the elements or
in the hands of countries too poor to guard or care for them.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems certain: because of the flourishing trade in
antiquities, the plunder of ancient sites is growing, which
sometimes leaves museum directors in a quandary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something is proven to be stolen, people are happy to
give it back,'' Ms. Desai said. ``But when it's a general claim
that if you have any object from this place, it must be stolen,
that's when it's difficult for institutions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before agreeing to return the 11th-century Indian sculpture, a
mother and child figure hewn from cream sandstone, which
Rockefeller's records show that he purchased from a London dealer,
Ms. Desai asked for proof that it was looted, which became clear
from old museum catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   She also asked for assurances that the sculpture would be well
taken care of and requested some logistical aid. ``We feel he
bought it in good faith,'' she said of Rockefeller, who died in
1978. ``So we asked the Indian government to pay for its return and
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture was on display at the Asia Society only
occasionally. ``It's a very fine piece, but it's not an exceptional
piece,'' said Ms. Desai, who declined to give a precise value but
estimated it would sell today for less than $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that patrimony problems are growing, she said, ``This
issue has not received the kind of attention that it should because
it was not as hot as Holocaust-era art.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the museum association, prompted by growing awareness
that museums may hold art that belonged to victims of World War II
looting, pledged last June to search their collections for such
works. Those searches are now in progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
