</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILED OPPORTUNITY AMID A SEARCH FOR DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France - The partial agreement that Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright dismissed only days ago as unacceptable is
all she left with Tuesday as the Kosovo peace talks here ended.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the nature of high-wire diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Albright's spokesman, James Rubin, told skeptical reporters
that they were missing the big picture. The talks had not ended in
failure, he explained, despite the fact that neither of the warring
parties had signed a settlement. Rather, the talks had ended as a
vindication of democratic values.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovar Albanians, he said, had agreed to the settlement in
principle and wanted to sign it but had waited only because they
wanted to consult with their supporters back in Kosovo. ``They
won't sign until they go through a democratic process,'' Rubin
said. ``Those of us who support democracy have to respect that. We
believe in democracy, as we hope any reporter from a democratic
country would.''
</P>
<P>
   But as any reporter who has visited Kosovo could inform Rubin,
there is no democracy in Kosovo, just as the United States and its
allies could not impose a settlement for Kosovo in Rambouillet
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington view on the talks was generally harsh. ``We don't
have anything,'' said Ivo Daalder, visiting fellow at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington think tank, and a foremr Bosnia
specialists with the National Security Council. ``We don't even
have a piece of paper because there is no signature. All we have is
a promise to negotiate on the implementation of an agreement that
no one has signed yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back to where we were in January, before the massacre --
back to shuttle diplomacy, back to trying to figure which plan will
be acceptable to which side,'' Daalder continued. ``Soon, we could
be back to war in the middle of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Daniel Serwer, senior fellow at the Washington-based US
Institute of Peace, ``The best you can say now is that this is very
odd. No one knows what to say, no one knows who won and who lost.
The one thing the US said going in that was absolutely necessary
was a complete agreement and the ground force to ensure it. They
have neither now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians, said Serwer, ``snatched defeat from the jaws of
victory'' by failing to sign immediately the political agreement
that would have given them leverage over the Serbs. And the Serbs
lost the opportunity to secure their sovereign hold over Kosovo for
at least the next three years and avert the possbility of NATO air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The western alliance, he added, is in disarray and may have lost
its best chance to stop war from breaking out in the heart of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Some were more sanguine about the prospects for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US and NATO got as much as they could have given that
there wasn't even a proper Kosovar delegation before Rambouillet,''
said Joseph V. Montville, director of preventive diplomacy at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies. ``They bought some
time to work out the details, but there is a plausible end to the
fighting now.''
</P>
<P>
   According to international observers and human rights groups,
the Serbs shoulder most of the blame for the suffering in Kosovo.
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic unilaterally ended Kosovo's
autonomy in 1989, suspending local government, dismissing ethnic
Albanians out of state jobs and crushing Albanian culture and
language for those who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   The separatist Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) flourished in that
repressive climate and last year launched a quixotic uprising
against the powerful Serbian security forces, who responded by
crushing the KLA and killing civilians where the KLA was in
control.
</P>
<P>
   The ``democratic consultation process'' to which Albright and
Rubin referred amounts to a group of self-appointed rebels deciding
if they can live with a deal that sidesteps their demand for an
independent Kosovo and calls for them to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   While the KLA undeniably has the support of most ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, it has never consulted ordinary Kosovars in
any meaningful way on its tactics, even though those tactics have
put civilians and their property in the crossfire of the KLA and
Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ethnic Albanians who have had the temerity to speak out
against the KLA have been murdered, or, as the KLA would put it,
summarily executed for collaborating with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But as the White House seeks to put a positive spin on the
desultory news here Tuesday, the fight over Kosovo is now about
democracy. What initially became an attempt to end the latest
bloodletting in the Balkans has become an effort to support the
democratic aspirations of the Kosovar Albanians over the despotic
inclinations of the bad boy of the Balkans, Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Albright conceded that she would have preferred the Kosovar
Albanians take ``a good deal,'' but she said that she respected
their request to consult with their people because it showed a
healthy appreciation for the very democratic values which the US
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Serbs agreed, all they'd have to do is make a phone
call'' to Milosevic, Albright added. But, she argued, the logistics
to gain consensus among the Kosovar Albanians is much more
complicated. As a result, Albright gave them until March 15 to
deliver their verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, under questioning, Rubin acknowledged that there really is
no deadline. The ``democratic consultation process'' is essentially
open-ended. Under questioning, neither Albright nor any other
representative of the six-nation Contact Group on the Balkans could
explain the mechanisms under which the Albanians will consult their
people, or how such a consultation would amount to a democratic
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright contends that the reluctance of the Kosovar
Albanians to sign a deal is understandable, similar reticence by
Milosevic is duplicitous. Milosevic, she said, ``failed to seize
this opportunity for progress. The Serbs moved forward as they saw
the Albanians move close to a yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin dismissed suggestions the Milosevic was laughing at the
Kosovar Albanians, who squandered a chance to keep the pressure on
him. ``President Milosevic may have woken up with a smile on his
face,'' he said, ``but he's going to sleep with a major headache.''
</P>
<P>
   The same, however, could be said for the White House and their
European allies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
