<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE'S TO BLAME BUT THE HOMETOWN HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POZHAREVAC, Yugoslavia - At the smoky Tropicana cafe here in the
hometown of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, brawny men drink
thick Serbian coffee and talk. Most are unemployed. All complain
about the bad economy, the constant threat of a NATO air strike,
and the possibility that they will lose control over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And they all agree who to blame: America. Western media. A
U.S.-led, global conspiracy to destroy the long-suffering Serbs.
Anyone, it seems, but their local hero and national leader,
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is responsible for me not having a normal life,'' said
25-year-old Mirko Lazic, sporting a pistol in the back of his
jeans. ``We love American music, American movies. But when the
first bomb drops, you are going to end up in the cellar'' as a
hostage, he told an American reporter matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens here are ready to defend themselves and their famous
neighbors, the Milosevic family. The Yugoslav president and his
wife have a villa here, and their son, Marko, owns the Madona disco
_ the biggest disco in the Balkans, locals say.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of victimization among Serbs is as deep as their
defiance against the West. Here is a republic whose psyche remains
rooted in a lost battle against the Turks that occurred more than
600 years ago in its souther province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs suffered heavily during both world wars, when, they point
out with hurt looks, they sided with the United States. More
recently, they have lost wars with the previously-aligned republics
of Slovenia, Croatia and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``How come you didn't help us when the Croats were slaughtering
us'' in the Croatian war of independence against Yugoslavia?
demanded Zoran Djordjevic, 30. ``Even then, they were against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's influence and size in the region has shrunk
dramatically and could diminish further if it loses control of
Kosovo. It still faces crippling economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Serbs complain with bafflement and menace, they are
being victimized both by the ethnic Albanian ``terrorists'' who are
trying to wrest Kosovo for themselves and by the United States,
which the Serbs accuse of supporting the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear now that America, from the beginning, was an
advocate of Albanian separatism and terrorism,'' an angry Yugoslav
Deputy Prime Minister Vuk Draskovic said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has portrayed the Serbs as ``animals, guilty
of everything,'' while the Albanian guerrillas have been presented
as ``victims and peaceful,'' he said. ``For the last few years,
Serbs have been punished severely for the program of Greater
Serbia. Now, you are punishing us again for the project of Greater
Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbs here still seem baffled by the international criticism
levied against their government. During the reign of communist
leader Josep Broz ``Tito,'' Yugoslavia enjoyed good relations with
both the communist and capitalist worlds. Now, Yugoslavia has few
friends and many detractors in the world community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the only way Americans can communicate with us, with
Tomahawks?'' asked Dejan Negic, 29. ``Can't they realize we are not
animals?''
</P>
<P>
   Since the conflict with the Kosovar Albanians exploded a year
ago, the Serbs have concluded that they are casualties of a massive
conspiracy against them. They insist that there is a powerful
Albanian lobby in Washington pulling strings at the White House and
the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs in Kosovo have blamed the deaths of Albanians on the
Kosovo Liberation Army, claiming that it is either weeding out
moderate Albanians or are killing its own to gain Western sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, this theory runs squarely into the face of hard
evidence to the contrary. When five Albanians were found in January
riddled with bullets on their tractor, the Serbian Minister of
Health, Labor and Social Services, Miodrag Kovac, described the
incident as a ``traffic accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Atrocities committed against Albanians in Kosovo were
``provoked,'' Draskovic said. He predicted that the Albanians --
given the 20-day rest before peace talks resume -- will
deliberately provoke the Serbs again by committing violence against
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the state forces must react,'' Draskovic added. But
he is convinced that the West will then use this display of force
to justify more anti-Serb rhetoric and perhaps bombing. ``OK, bomb
us then,'' he said, slamming his fist on the table. ``We will
defend ourselves. Probably, we will lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
