<HEADLINE>
SHIFTING FUNDS WILL NOT KEEP SOCIAL SECURITY SOLVENT, BUDGET
EXPERTS WARN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Budget experts warned members of Congress on
Tuesday that President Clinton's plan to save Social Security would
not address the long-term structural problems of the retirement
system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed that over the next 15 years almost
two-thirds of the federal budget surplus be devoted to Social
Security, which is scheduled to fall short of funds by 2032.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration's proposal is not a simple cash infusion
to the retirement fund. Instead it involves a complicated budget
maneuver that would give Social Security more treasury securities,
which could eventually be redeemed to pay obligations to retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Experts testifying before the Senate Budget Committee said that
shifting funds did not address the central problem facing Social
Security _ that the payroll taxes earmarked to pay retirees'
benefits will be insufficient for the bulging baby boom population
as it ages.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller General David Walker told the senators that the
president's plan dodges the ``fundamental changes'' that must be
made to keep Social Security solvent. Those changes are likely to
be more painful than the president has proposed, such as increasing
the payroll taxes or reducing benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no free lunch,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker told the Senate panel that the president's plan also set
a dangerous precedent of using general tax revenues, rather than
the specially earmarked payroll tax, to fund Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes us away from an insurance concept to a welfare
concept,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker praised the part of the administration's plan that would
involve paying down the public debt, which would invigorate the
economy and give the government more ability to borrow in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But he and others noted that the debt reduction would occur
regardless of whether the surplus was earmarked for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., agreed
with budget experts' assessment that the president's plan was
insufficient to address Social Security's long-term needs.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said the president had misled the country when he
boasted that his plan would save Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he has put off reforming Social Security in a
meaningful way,'' Domenici said, noting that he and Texas
Republican Sen. Phil Gramm would soon unveil their own Social
Security plan.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats defended the president's plan as a beginning to extend
the life of the retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed with Clinton's insistence that most of the
surplus be earmarked for Social Security, saying that otherwise
future Congresses would be tempted to use it for tax cuts or
spending increases.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, Rep. Bill
Archer, R-Texas, also endorsed the proposal to set aside the
surplus for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is appropriate to set aside 62 percent of the
surplus until Social Security is saved,'' Archer said at a hearing.
``We have the resources, the economy is strong, and the time is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer also praised the president's proposal to use the stock
market to increase the retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a breakthrough. It is without precedent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Archer said he and the White House disagreed on how those
investments should be made. The Houston Republican opposes the
president's plan to let Social Security system officials invest a
portion of the retirement money in the market, arguing that it
would give the government too much control of private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Archer approves, however, of letting individuals invest their
retirement funds in the market, a concept that is included in the
president's budget. Clinton has proposed the USA accounts, which
would allocate a portion of the surplus for individual retirement
plans that could be invested in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said that ``while the USA plan doesn't in itself do
anything to save Social Security, it represents another potential
building block upon which we should make progress.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
