<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SAYS FED READY TO ADJUST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan told the US Senate
Tuesday that the economy's long-running expansion is at risk,
requiring the central bank to stand ready to move interest rates in
either direction.
</P>
<P>
   Fed watchers who read the tea leaves of Greenspan's twice-yearly
report to the Senate said the chairman would be more inclined to
raise interest rates than to lower them. However, Greenspan
signaled the agency is unlikely to do anything at the next meeting
of the Federal Reserve Open Market Committee on March 30, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the chairman told us very clearly there will be no
change in interest rates one way or another for a good while,''
said Wall Street economist Allen Sinai of Primark Decision
Economics in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The general tenor of Greenspan's report to Congress was
positive, especially given he sees ``no evidence'' of inflation.
Indeed, threats to the economy derive from its strengths _ not
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan cited a tight labor market that may hike wages,
soaring stocks that could deflate, and high and potentially
unsustainable levels of household and corporate debt.
</P>
<P>
   As though to bolster the chairman's implicit concerns about a
``torrid'' rate of economic growth, consumer confidence rose in
February in response to record high levels of optimism about the
current environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, nobody has questioned at all that the dramatic
acceleration that we've seen in some technologies and the marked
increase in productivity and profitability of American businesses
has undoubtedly had a significant impact on underlying prices of
all capital assets, including equities,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he cautioned, ``After eight years of economic expansion,
the economy appears stretched in a number of dimensions, implying
considerable upside and downside risks to the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   If concerns grow, ``monetary policy must be ready to move
quickly in either direction,'' the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the economy expected to continue expanding early this
year, analysts said the Fed is more likely to increase rates to
cool it down. If rates do change, Greenspan ``indicated that odds
are when they do make a move it will be to higher rates,'' Sinai
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the bond market reacted negatively to news of a
firm interest rate policy for the foreseeable future. The yield on
30-year US Treasury bonds rose to 5.43 percent from 5.36 percent
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks ended down 8.26
points, closing at 9544.42.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar came under pressure after Greenspan told the Senate
Banking Committee the US currency could weaken if the US trade
deficit keeps rising. In a question and answer session, Greenspan
said he saw no evidence that foreign investors were less willing to
hold dollars. The trade deficit rose to a record $168.59 billion in
1998, as US demand continues to exceed consumption by sluggish
Asian and overseas economies.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar inched up to 120.95 Japanese yen, from 120.90 yen at
Monday's close, and retreated against the euro, which rose to
$1.1007 from $1.0969 after hitting a new low overnight at $1.0942.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's testimony followed news the economy grew 5.6 percent
in 1998's fourth quarter, and 3.9 percent for the full year. It was
a remarkable finish to a year in which financial crises unfolded
around the globe and threatened to lap at US shores.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan predicted Tuesday the ``economy's performance should
remain solid this year'' amid lower oil prices, and rising
productivity, due to investment in technology.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned oil prices ``are not likely to fall further,'' and
hinted at concerns about inflation, due to a labor shortage in many
markets.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual admission, the Fed chairman indicated that
aggressive rate cuts last fall _ three times in two months _ to
avert crisis may have been overdone.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan's stellar reputation on Wall Street remains
intact. Under his rein, the Fed was praised for acting decisively
last fall when Russia's economy sank and Long-Term Credit Bank ran
into deep trouble due to its wildly leveraged investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Between the end of September and mid-November, the Fed reduced
the rate banks charge each other for overnight loans to 4 3/4
percent, from 5 1/2 percent. For one of those reductions, Greenspan
moved without calling an FOMC meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan may be considering whether he should ``take back one
of those three-quarter-point cuts. That would bring the rate back
to 5 percent,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, who have for the most part given the economy its
kick, have showed no signs of slowing their spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board's consumer confidence index, based on a
survey of 5,000 households, rose 3.2 points in February, closing at
132.1.
</P>
<P>
   One component of the index, which measures consumers' current
mood, climbed from 172.9 in January to a record 178.4 in February.
It was the highest since the board began the survey 32 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
