<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TBS-NEWCHANNEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner South to showcase region on cable
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting today is expected to announce plans for a
new cable TV channel called Turner South, its first new
entertainment channel in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South will be launched this fall and feature 24 hours of
movies, sitcoms, regional news and sports geared toward a Southern
audience. Initially, most of the programming will come from the
vast film and TV library of Turner Broadcasting, now a unit of Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   But the channel also plans to show original programming. It has,
for example, developed a one-hour show in partnership with the
magazine Southern Living.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South is the first new entertainment channel launched by
the Atlanta-based programming giant since its purchase by Time
Warner three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The channel is to be formally announced today at a 10 a.m. news
conference at the company's Techwood campus in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is launching its new channel at a difficult time. New
channels are scrapping to find distribution among cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Turner South will not be announced today with any
distribution deals. Today, most new channels begin life on direct
broadcast satellite services such as DirecTV.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Turner Broadcasting is nothing if not tenacious. Its last
new entertainment channel, Turner Classic Movies, was launched five
years ago and has only recently began to reach a critical mass of
30 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South will feature games by the Atlanta Braves, Hawks and
the new hockey franchise, the Thrashers. All teams are owned by
Turner Broadcasting. Their games are now aired on Turner
Broadcasting cable channels TBS and TNT, as well as on other
channels such as ESPN and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the strategy behind Turner South is to recoup games,
especially for the Braves, that have been lost to other channels
over the years through changing contracts with the leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South would be the first regional entertainment channel,
although there are several regional sports channels. But what the
channel really represents is a new spin on an old idea at its
parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting began more than 25 years ago with the
satellite broadcast of Channel 17 as the TBS SuperStation. It
became one of the first cable TV channels and reached viewers
across the nation but especially in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Ted Turner conceived TBS as a way to bring baseball and
other shows to small towns in the South without a lot of choice in
TV programming.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years TBS has evolved into a channel with broad
appeal and more than 70 million subscribers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting executives began to feel that the regional
market was going unmet. Recent marketing studies by the company
confirmed that there was still a demand for a ``Southern'' channel.
</P>
<P>
   Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
