<HEADER>
A6481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNER-STUDIO-COX     02-23 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-STUDIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner builds new hi-tech studio
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting is more than half done with the
construction of a new production studio on its Techwood campus,
company officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The facility, to be called Turner Studios, is expected to be the
largest all-digital production studio on the East Coast when
completed early next year. Construction on the $37 million building
began about one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said it would take two years to complete and we are right
now on schedule or a little bit ahead,'' said Turner Broadcasting
spokeswoman Terry Cerisoles.
</P>
<P>
   The new facility is adjacent to the home of the company's
entertainment cable TV channels, which include TBS, TNT, Cartoon
Network and Turner Classic Movies. There are three other buildings
on this campus, two of which have been built in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   The 127,000-square-foot studio, the shell of which is nearly
completed, will serve these entertainment channels. It will be
equipped with $15 million in digital recording and editing
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The building will actually house three studios, a four-story
tower and a post-production unit. Its digital facilities will be
largely used to film promos and lead-ins to the company's many
entertainment shows. Most of the company's original content will
continue to be filmed in Los Angeles and on location around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The studio will also enable the company to produce HDTV shows
and translate old shows into this new format, expected to become
the standard in the next decade. HDTV is a digital form of
television that is much sharper than current standards.
</P>
<P>
   Wiring of the building is expected to begin in June or July,
says Cerisoles, with completion due sometime in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
