<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-GENERALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY MAY CANCEL PURCHASE OF SOCIETE GENERALE MANAGEMENT UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Liberty Financial Cos. is considering canceling its
plan to acquire the ailing US mutual fund unit of French bank
Societe Generale SA, sources familiar with the troubled transaction
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The disintegration of the deal, sealed only six months ago,
comes amid a dizzying decline in the unit's assets due to troubled
overseas markets and investor uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is valid to say the company (Liberty) is considering
calling the deal off,'' one person close to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling may prompt legal action from a spurned Societe
Generale, according to a second source close to the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Saying only ``the closing has not gone through,'' Societe
Generale spokesman Justin Lamont declined to elaborate. Liberty
spokesman Hal Thayer also declined to comment, citing
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Liberty's agreement last August to buy New
York-based Societe Generale Asset Management Corp. for $216 million
was supposed to be a match made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, a group of eight financial services firms, would have
gained a marquee money manager in prominent international investor
Jean-Marie Eveillard, who overseas the six Societe Generale mutual
funds, which focus on international stocks and bonds. Eveillard
would have gained marketing muscle and, presumably, new business
for his funds, which at the time of the deal had $5.2 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was viewed as further evidence of the premium that
asset management firms, especially those with a renowned head, can
command in an era of consolidating financial services.
</P>
<P>
   Then Russia collapsed in August, barely a year after Asia's
turmoil began. World markets were roiled.
</P>
<P>
   Returns at Societe Generale funds, once among the highest flyers
around, sank. Panicked investors yanked out cash, helping cut the
funds' total assets nearly in half to $2.8 billion. Hard hit was
the flagship SoGen International fund, which had $4.4 billion in
assets in September 1997, its peak, but has since seen redemptions
of $1.5 billion, including over $800 million last year, according
to Morningstar Inc. Today the fund, which Eveillard has run for two
decades, has only $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The degree of decline has been such that I'm not sure you
could make this deal work,'' one financial source said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty had cautioned last November, when outflows at Societe
Generale accelerated, that it might use its contractual option to
pay less for the firm. The contract requires Societe Generale to
meet certain asset level benchmarks if the deal is to go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what Liberty wanted, but the company had protection
and is choosing to use it,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty declined to assume administrative functions of the
Societe Generale funds last week, signaling that the agreement was
in trouble. Under the terms of the contract, Liberty has until
March 31 to resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Eveillard, 59, for three decades one of the world's best known
investors in undervalued overseas companies, has seen his
often-lucrative investing style suffer in recent years. An
adventurous, go-anywhere investor, he will buy international bonds
or hold cash if he can't find stocks he likes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until two or three years ago, he had done quite well,'' said
Morningstar analyst Hap Ryans. Explaining how an investor whose
funds had double-digit returns in previous years could be punished
for being out of favor with the market, Ryans called the
agreement's unraveling a reflection of ``the what have you done for
me lately school of investing.''
</P>
<P>
   While other asset management deals have been known to collapse _
Nationwide Financial Services's failed bid for Pilgrim Baxter &AMP;
Associates is a recent example _ agreements that are made public
and then flop are relatively rare, according to industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty's step back hurts not just Eveillard, who reportedly
owns around 20 percent of the firm he heads; it is also a
disappointment for Liberty, which wants to expand its fund
offerings at a time when competition is keen for prime fund firms.
Liberty, whose holdings include The Colonial Group Inc. and
Steinroe &AMP; Farnham Inc., derives around two thirds of its business
from its Keyport Life Insurance Co. unit. Liberty oversees $61
billion in assets.
</P>
</TEXT>
