<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BUDGET24-COX     02-23 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH CORDIAL MEETING, CLINTON AND CONGRESS RETURN TO POLICY
 &HT;    460&AMP;adds.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton played host to congressional
Republican and Democratic leaders Tuesday at an Oval Office coffee,
muffling any lingering impeachment rancor with the restorative
rhetoric of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the two parties disagreed over key issues such as tax
cuts and the future of Social Security, though they found the
beginnings of common ground in each area.
</P>
<P>
   The year-long effort to unseat Clinton, however, did not come up
during the businesslike 90-minute meeting _ a testament to the
remarkable recuperative powers of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job here in Washington is to do the people's business, and
that's what we're going to do,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., who voted less than two weeks ago to remove Clinton
from office. ``We're going to work together, hopefully across the
party lines, in the Congress and with the administration, to do
what the American people expect of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoed House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., ''We are starting
to work to put together ideas, and that's the first step'' toward
restoring working relations between the White House and the
Republican majorities in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are committed to do that,'' Hastert said. ``And we are
going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the meeting how he could sit down peaceably and go
to work with those who tried to end his presidency, Clinton said it
was simply part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all took an oath, and I think we intend to follow it,''
Clinton said. ''We owe it to the American people, and I'm looking
forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., agreed that the atmospherics were
encouraging at the session, the first bipartisan leadership meeting
at the White House in 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a good thing to do,'' said Daschle. ``We ought
to do it more frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned repeatedly on the subject of trust, both Lott and
Hastert refused to declare their faith in Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I trust,'' Lott responded at one point. ``I
trust the ability of the people, here in the Congress, in the
government, to work together to do what we need to do for the
people. That's where the real trust should be, the trust in us
doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said, however, that a mixture of trust and necessity
led the Republicans to sit down with Clinton so quickly after his
Senate acquittal to try to map out the legislative future together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the meeting is a sign of trust. I think they want to
work with him,'' Gephardt said. ``They realize that if they're to
get the people's business done, they have to work with the
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's meeting, which also included House Majority Leader
Dick Armey, R-Texas, was not all backslaps and handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Most talk was devoted to Clinton's proposal to set aside 62
percent of the anticipated federal budget surplus over the next 15
years to shore up the Social Security program, and another 15
percent to buttress Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans have expressed some support for Clinton's
Social Security proposal, the party also regards a huge budget
surplus as something to be corrected through tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   While the party is divided over how to structure such a cut,
Republicans are united behind the position that much of the
anticipated surplus _ projected to top $4.4 trillion over 15 years
_ should be returned to the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing is the American taxpayer is overtaxed,'' said
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Lott advocated a 10 percent across-the-board cut in income
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a 30-year-old young person working, with a college
degree, and you make $32,000 a year, a 10 percent tax rate cut
would mean about a $500-a-year
</P>
<P>
   increase in being able to keep the money you earn,'' said Lott.
``I think that's attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he opposed the proposal for two reasons. First, he
said, it would jeopardize Clinton's vision of setting aside the
vast majority of the anticipated surplus to shore up Social
Security and Medicare. Second, he said, 80 percent of the benefits
of such a cut would accrue to the top 20 percent of income tax
payers, the relatively wealthy Americans who least need such
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats prefer targeted tax relief, aimed primarily at
lower-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed, for instance, a half-trillion dollars in
tax relief, over 15 years, in the form of subsidized savings
accounts for low-income and moderate-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Democrats would negotiate with Republicans over
some types of targeted tax relief _ such as a small cut to correct
the ``marriage penalty,'' or the extra taxes a married couple pays
compared to two single people with the came income. In exchange, he
said, Republicans should support a $1-an-hour increase in the
minimum wage, now $5.15 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he saw other opportunities for bipartisan
cooperation as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if the speaker would schedule a patients' bill
of rights, a minimum wage increase, and campaign finance reform in
the next month, we could get all three of those measures passed in
a bipartisan way,'' said Gephardt. ``And I hope that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Privately, aides described the meeting as a mostly formal, but
not awkward, return to business for politicians divided over the
past year about how to respond to a sex-and-deception scandal
relished by few members of either party on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some element of weariness to this,'' said a Democratic
aide. ''We're happy to get back to what we all came here to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And while many Americans find it hard to understand how
politicians could so quickly make peace after such spirited
division, career campaigners insist that burying past grudges is
part of the turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're professionals,'' said the aide, who spoke on
background. ``They're hired to do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
