<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS &LR;      02-23 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-CANCER DRUG APPEARS HEADED FOR HUMAN TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ The most closely watched experimental cancer
drug in decades, endostatin, is being made in large quantities,
appears to have no toxic effects on monkeys, and should enter its
first human tests later this year, a scientist from EntreMed Inc.,
the drug's developer, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to ask the US Food and Drug Administration in
the second half of 1999 for permission to begin initial safety
tests in a few dozen human patients, said B. Kim Lee Sim, an
EntreMed research official who briefed scientists at a meeting
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making the drug in kilogram quantities to supply our
human trials,'' said Sim. The endostatin has been made to proper
specifications and is ready for Phase I clinical tests, which are
designed only to demonstrate safety, not that the drug can combat
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sim said that monkeys given a single injection of a massive dose
of endostatin showed no ill effects. But that doesn't mean that
adverse side effects may not be encountered in humans.
</P>
<P>
   The Phase I tests could take a year or more, said Dr. Joanna C.
Horobin, an EntreMed vice president. Although Phase I trials are
officially only to evaluate safety, researchers look for hints that
a drug may be having some desirable effect.
</P>
<P>
   But Horobin said it may be difficult to tell from early testing
whether endostatin works. Unlike conventional cancer drugs,
endostatin starves tumors by destroying the blood vessels that feed
them. Such drugs, known as angiogenesis inhibitors, may not kill
tumors, but could keep them in check for years. Thus, standard
yardsticks for evaluating cancer drugs may not apply to the new
drugs, say researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if it didn't show any effects in Phase I trials, we still
would probably go on'' to expanded Phase II testing involving many
more patients, said Horobin at the meeting here on angiogenesis
drugs, sponsored by the Institute for International Research.
</P>
<P>
   Although as many as 30 angiogenesis inhibitors are already in
early human testing in the United States and Europe, many cancer
patients and the general public have focused on endostatin and
another blood vessel inhibitor, angiostatin, because they have
demonstrated astonishing potency in mouse tests, shrinking massive
tumors to the vanishing point. No other angiogenesis inhibitors
showed such stunning potency in animal tests.
</P>
<P>
   But leaders in the angiogenesis field said these less-potent
drugs could prove very useful, by slowing a cancer's growth and
lengthening and improving the quality of a patient's life.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike conventional cancer drugs that attack tumor cells with
toxic effects that unavoidably harm normal tissue, angiogenesis
inhibitors are targeted at the tumor's blood vessels, and seem to
have many fewer side-effects than standard drugs, such as nausea,
hair loss and effects on bone marrow. If so, they would likely be
given over long periods to keep cancers under control, probably
with radiation or other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 25 or 30 years we'll be looking at cancer as a chronic
disease, like arthritis,'' said Dr. Peter Polverini, a longtime
angiogenesis researcher from the University of Michigan Dental
School.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin and angiostatin are fragments of larger proteins made
naturally in the body. Discovered in the Boston laboratory of Dr.
Judah Folkman at Children's Hospital, endostatin and angiostatin
are part of an enormously complex group of substances that regulate
the growth of new blood vessels (angiogenenis), which occurs in
early development of the fetus, and in later life in wound healing
and the reproductive functions of the female uterus.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two drugs, endostatin has become the front-runner because
it has proven easier to manufacture. Last week, Bristol Myers
Squibb said it was abandoning work on angiostatin for now because
after spending millions of dollars, the firm has not been able to
make the drug in large quantitites with consistent effects.
</P>
<P>
   But Sim of EntreMed, based in Rockville, Md., said that her
company remains optimistic about angiostatin and is continuing its
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are using a different system'' from that of Bristol Myers,
yielding a smaller form of the angiostatin, and ``it is on a
parallel path'' to endostatin but is not as far along, said Sim.
</P>
</TEXT>
