<HEADER>
A6494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPUBLICANS-H     02-23 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBLICANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, GOP LEADERS VOW TO WORK TOGETHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Republican leaders in
Congress pledged Tuesday to set aside impeachment rancor and work
together on key issues as the two sides met at the White House for
the first time in 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress returned to Washington after a weeklong
break following the Feb. 12 Senate vote to acquit Clinton of House
impeachment charges of perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all took an oath and I think we intend to follow it. We owe
it to the American people, and I'm looking forward to it,'' Clinton
told reporters as congressional leaders from both parties sat on
either side of him.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said later they too wanted to find common
ground for this legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, the
Republican leaders joined Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., and House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., for the
first bipartisan session at the White House since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The breach between the White House and the Republican leadership
began before the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal, back to the budget
battles of 1997. A White House official said the ``problem was not
from our end'' and that Clinton was willing to meet with the
Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job here in Washington is to do the people's business, and
that's what we're going to do. We're going to work together,
hopefully across the party lines in Congress, and with the
administration to do what the American people expect of us,'' Lott
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who voted to convict Clinton and remove him from office,
has been outspoken since the vote in criticizing the president and
expressing his lack of trust in Clinton. But Lott repeatedly
refused to answer a question about whether he now trusts the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I trust. I trust the ability of the people
here in the Congress, in the government, to work together to do
what we need to do for the people. That's where the real trust
should be, the trust in us doing the job,'' Lott told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hastert's first meeting with Clinton as the House
speaker. He assumed the top House role in December after the
resignations by Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and Rep. Bob
Livingston, R-La., both victims of the Lewinsky scandal. Gingrich
resigned following lackluster Republican election results in
November and Livingston stepped aside after acknowledging
extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   During the White House session, which lasted more than an hour,
the president pressed Lott and Hastert to save 62 percent of the
government's expected surplus for Social Security and 15 percent
for Medicare reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders offered no promises but have made clear
they already are rethinking the 10 percent across-the-board tax cut
the party was trumpeting as the centerpiece of its legislative
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 15 House moderates and some conservatives have balked
at an across-the-board tax cut, considering it unlikely to pass or
too expensive. They now favor limited tax cuts targeted to the
marriage penalty or other, more modest areas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans only have an 11-seat majority in the House, making
it more difficult for House leaders to pass legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of types of tax cuts on the menu,'' Hastert said
when asked about the prospect of a 10 percent tax cut. ``Some
people are talking about across-the-board tax cut. There's marriage
penalty. There's reduction for the earnings test on seniors in
Social Security. There's a lot of things we're looking at. And I
think whatever we do, it's going to be part of a mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders said after the meeting that Republicans must
make a ``threshold decision'' to save 77 percent of the surplus for
Social Security and Medicare. They contended that an
across-the-board tax cut would make it impossible to save the
surplus for Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle maintained the Democrats also supported targeted tax
cuts such as those for long-term health care, child care and
Clinton's proposed USA Accounts for a retirement tax credit.
``Those kinds of things are essential and we're going to be
spending a lot of effort and working with our Republican colleagues
to make that happen,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt challenged Hastert to bring up the dormant patient bill
of rights, a minimum wage increase and campaign finance reform all
within the next month. ``We could get all three of those measures
passed in a bipartisan way,'' Gephardt predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Clinton made clear to the Republicans during the
meeting that he hoped they would endorse his ideas for the surplus
in the next few weeks so they could begin work on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   After their White House session, both Republican and Democratic
leaders attended the closing session of the National Governors'
Association meeting. Governors of both parties have asked Congress
to return to some semblance of civility that was missing during the
impeachment debate in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Thomas Carper, D-Del., chairman of the NGA, said he sensed
``a new civility'' since the governors have been in town and noted
the governors demonstrated that their respectful exchanges are
``the way the people of our nation expect us to address our
business and to conduct theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mike Leavitt, R-Utah, said he hoped the governors meeting
``contributed to the momentum to a new period of civility in
Washington. I hope that that continues for at least a period so
that we can get some of the things done that so badly need to be
done before we get into a period of what will undoubtedly be hard
campaigning to dictate our direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
