<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ROBESON-REVIEW-ART     02-23 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROBESON-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBESON: A VOICE AND A PRESENCE THAT ECLIPSE THE CONTRADICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The celebrations of Paul Robeson continue on
Wednesday night on ``American Masters,'' an illuminating if
worshipful two-hour biography of a once contentious figure in
process of rediscovery.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of what has gone before during the year of his
centennial, ``Paul Robeson: Here I Stand'' is meant to do justice
to a man who was treated most unjustly by his own country's
officials even as he was acclaimed around the world for his voice,
his acting and his commitment to what many at the time saw as the
struggle against fascism and on behalf of the so-called common man.
</P>
<P>
   But as in the other tributes, the political part of his career
continues to cast a shadow: his unwavering support of Stalinism is
explained and excused as a reaction to racism and exploitation in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although the anti-communist passions that blasted Robeson's
career in the 1950s have long since subsided and a cadre of
revisionist historians now hold that Stalin was less malicious than
advertised, some viewers may still be left wondering how to square
Robeson's stand for human rights in so many places with his support
for the Soviet state during the era of the gulag.
</P>
<P>
   The program, to be shown on PBS at 9 p.m. in the New York area,
duly records Robeson's athletic and academic accomplishments at
Rutgers University, where he won every available honor.
</P>
<P>
   His successful but complicated movie career is perceptively
scrutinized. Most of his screen roles, adapted to the formulas of
the Hollywood studios of the 1920s and '30s with their Stepin
Fetchit stereotypes, remain embarrassments. Yet we see moments
Wednesday night when the man's physical presence manages to defeat
the demeaning material.
</P>
<P>
   In his popular recordings, particularly of spirituals and folk
songs, Robeson awakened generations to their heritage and
entertained millions more. By the 1930s, he was an international
star. His biographer, Martin Duberman, reports that in 1940,
``Robeson was the most famous black man in America.''
</P>
<P>
   On stage in the early 1940s, his tour de force as Othello _ a
black man making love to and murdering a white woman _ is recalled
by his Desdemona, Uta Hagen. She remembers him less for his ability
as an actor than for their affair, which, in a deliciously
Shakespearean twist, roused the justified suspicions of Jose
Ferrer, her husband and the play's Iago.
</P>
<P>
   Although his Othello was a hit, it was not his acting that
brought Robeson worldwide fame, but his music, which resounds
through these two hours and which he used as a political weapon. By
this account, it was a visit to the Soviet Union that began his
abiding affection for that land as the champion of socialism and
equality.
</P>
<P>
   The reminiscences of old comrades like Howard Fast and Pete
Seeger and younger followers like Harry Belafonte recapture the
enthusiasm he stirred among what his son, Paul Robeson Jr., calls
``progressive'' audiences.
</P>
<P>
   During his Popular Front phase, he toured the Loyalist lines of
Spain's civil war and sold war bonds in America. In an effort to
explain how his father could sympathize with Soviet Jewish
intellectuals after World War II yet utter no criticism of their
top persecutor, Stalin, the younger Robeson says, ``His was a world
of relative evils.''
</P>
<P>
   For the politically like-minded, the voice and the ideology came
powerfully together. When in 1950, during the height _ or depths _
of the nation's anti-communist zeal, Robeson's passport was taken
away, he was demonized by Communist hunters (though he was never
shown to be a party member) and he was acclaimed by elements of the
left as a martyr. The return of his passport in 1958 came too late
to reinvigorate his career or his health, and his final years were
marked by depression and seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Robeson's name may be dimly remembered, if at all, by
many viewers. Except perhaps for those still carrying on the wars
of the 1950s, the arguments over his politics have become a
footnote to a remarkable American odyssey; the politics seem now
less interesting than the man himself, so true to his convictions
yet so blind to reality.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's program, being a birthday party, tries to
avoid the discomfort of Robeson's affinity for a totalitarian
state. It's the sort of occasion at which one celebrant can speak
of the 1948 Progressive Party, that instrument of old-left relics,
as being a broad political coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of the admirers assembled here and the family
members who cooperated with the producers, ``Robeson'' turns the
camera and the soundtrack on its hero's accomplishments as a
performer, his courage in defying authority and what he still means
for those who remember his glory days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
