<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEADERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS TALK ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton met for the first time Tuesday
with House Speaker Dennis Hastert and other Republican leaders who
had sought to remove the president from office, as both sides
attempted to show they can work together despite lingering bruises
from the impeachment fight.
</P>
<P>
   Over coffee and pastries in the Oval Office, Clinton, the GOP
leaders, and their Democratic counterparts, laid out competing
visions for using projected budget surpluses and shoring up Social
Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   While a Clinton aide said impeachment was not discussed during
the hourlong meeting, it is clear the issue has severely damaged
the already tenuous relationship between Clinton and Republicans in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After the Senate voted 11 days ago to acquit Clinton, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott called the president untrustworthy.
Tuesday, while not backing down from that earlier assessment, the
Mississippi Republican skirted the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I trust. I trust the ability of the people,
here in the Congress, in the government, to work together to do
what we need to do for the people,'' Lott told reporters after the
White House meeting. ``That's where the real trust should be, the
trust in us doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, a Republican from Illinois, also avoided answering
whether he trusted Clinton. ``We are starting to work to put
together ideas, and that's the first step,'' he said. After that,
``we can frame the debate, so we can move forward for what the
agenda is for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But White House press secretary Joseph Lockhart said Clinton
considered the bipartisan meeting with congressional leaders, his
first in 19 months, ``constructive,'' and he said the atmosphere
was good. Lockhart said the president thinks the best way to regain
the trust of Capitol Hill is to work with lawmakers on issues
Americans care about.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton said at the start of the meeting, ``We all
took an oath, and I think we intend to follow it. We owe it to the
American people, and I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Lott and Hastert at the White House were House Majority
Leader Richard K. Armey, Senate Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle
and House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   After a 13-month sex scandal that resulted in Clinton's
impeachment by the House but acquittal by the Senate, Gephardt said
it was time to turn to legislative issues. ``We just need to get on
it and get it done, and start making progress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans and the White House share some of the same
priorities _ using part of the budget surplus to shore up Social
Security, finding ways to fix Medicare and improve education _
their approaches differ.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Clinton want to use 77 percent of the budget
surplus to extend the life of Social Security and Medicare, and for
targeted middle-class tax credits, military pay raises and other
new government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, on the other hand, want to return some of the
surplus to taxpayers in an across-the-board tax cut, though some
GOP moderates are beginning to back away from that idea because of
the political risk of supporting a tax cut that Democrats claim
would benefit the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of types of tax cuts on the menu,'' said
Hastert. ``Some people are talking about an across-the-board tax
cut. There's marriage penalty. There's reduction for earnings tests
in seniors and Social Security. There's a lot of things that we're
looking at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
