<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: STRONG NUMBERS FOR NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the usual gloomy talk about fickle television watchers who
incessantly flip to cable channels, February so far has brought at
least some good cheer to each of the six broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's Stephen King mini-series, ``Storm of the Century,'' stood
up to the powerful competition from NBC better than expected on
Thursday, even up against the much advertised episode of NBC's
``ER'' in which George Clooney made his final appearance as Dr.
Ross. Although the 12.0 household rating for ``Storm'' (each rating
points equals 994,000 homes) was modest, it raised ABC to a 10.6
average household rating for the night, its best Thursday rating in
nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
   NBC still clobbered the competition, with above-average numbers
for its entire lineup, topped off by a 23.8 household rating, a 37
share (percentage of sets in use) and more than 35.7 million
viewers for ``ER'' (nearly twice the 19.1 million who watched
``Storm'').
</P>
<P>
   Together, ABC, NBC and Fox, with a special called ``World's Most
Shocking Medical Videos,'' helped increase overall broadcast
viewing by more than 10 share points; 71 percent of all television
sets in use were tuned to broadcast networks, rather than the usual
60 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``ABC deserves credit because they gambled'' in scheduling Part
3 of their King mini-series against ``ER,'' said Marc Berman of
Seltel Inc., a consultant to television stations who follows
ratings patterns closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves that despite all the talk of network erosion, if the
networks are aggressive and find the right programming, people will
watch,'' Berman added. ``They'll watch less cable. They'll come
back to the networks if given the right mix of program choices.''
</P>
<P>
   David Poltrack, executive vice president for research at CBS,
agreed. ``In this new environment of broadcast shares of 60, with
40 percent of the people wandering all over the place,'' he said,
``there is enough noncommitted audience out there to bring you a
significant gain on a given night, regardless of the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Larry Hyams, Poltrack's counterpart at ABC, said that
Thursday's main message to him was that ``Stephen King has a very
loyal audience that tuned in for his mini-series and stayed with it
no matter what the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the mini-networks, WB and UPN, had sweeps success stories.
For UPN, it was a two-hour special episode of ``Star Trek:
Voyager'' on Feb. 17 that pulled the network's best household and
young-adult ratings in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   For WB, it was an early-sweeps event, the Feb. 8 episode of
``Seventh Heaven,'' in which twins are born to the family. It
became the first WB show ever to break into the top 50 for a week
(it was 35th), with a 7.3 rating that was a record for the network.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come in the sweeps: CBS has the Grammy Awards on
Wednesday night with Rosie O'Donnell as host; NBC has its
special-effects-laden new version of ``Alice in Wonderland'' on
Sunday, and ABC has perhaps the most talked-about special event of
all, Barbara Walters' two-hour interview with Monica Lewinsky,
scheduled for next Wednesday night at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Not Choosing Suicide
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, ``60 Minutes'' provoked a hornet's nest of debate by
showing a videotape of Thomas Youk's death from fatal doses of
drugs administered by Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the crusader for
legalizing assisted suicide. This Sunday, ``60 Minutes'' will
present another side of that story: five people who have Lou
Gehrig's disease, or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, as Youk did but
who have chosen to live and cope with it.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hewitt, the executive producer of the CBS magazine program,
said he and Mike Wallace, the correspondent on the report, had been
deluged with calls and mail from friends of people with Lou
Gehrig's disease, urging that those people's stories be broadcast,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Mike and I were on Larry King's show,'' Hewitt said,
referring to the CNN host's talk show, last Nov. 30, about a week
after the Kevorkian report. ``And someone called in and said, `Did
you ever think about finding people who opt to live and not die?'
And we said right then on the air, `That's a very good idea.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is the correspondent on this report, too. Hewitt said he
was not trying to make amends for showing the Kevorkian videotape.
``No, I was listening to our viewers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``Inasmuch as the Kevorkian story caused such a
rumpus, we decided we owed it to them to look at the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Alphabetical Oscars
</P>
<P>
   Turner Classic Movies, eager to show off its extensive
collection of vintage films, always makes March all-Oscar month:
nothing but Academy Award-nominated movies or movies with
Oscar-nominated performers for 31 days, 24 hours a day. Now in its
fifth year, the young cable network is giving the Oscar theme a
twist this time: Oscars from A to Z.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, with ``Above and Beyond'' (1953) at 6 a.m., the
network will schedule its assorted Oscar oddities in alphabetical
order for the rest of the month, ending with the 1969 Costa-Gavras
thriller ``Z,'' of course.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one exception: Turner couldn't find an
Oscar-nominated film whose official title started with the letter
X.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
