<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PLAYERS28-COX     02-23 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PLAYERS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH QUIETLY PREPS FOR PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Feb. 28, 1999.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For weeks now, David Beckwith has felt a lot like a
character in a Samuel Beckett play, his eyes upon Texas, looking
for signs that George W. Bush, the state's governor, possibly the
most popular Republican in the country, had decided to seek the
GOP's 2000 presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot like 'Waiting for Godot','' said Beckwith, who
served in the presidency of the governor's father, George H.W.
Bush. ``So many people have been holding fire, waiting to see what
the governor was going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the main characters in Beckett's play, two vagrants
who never really do anything beyond the trivial, the governor of
Texas has quietly laid the groundwork for a presidential campaign,
even as he has kept so many in the GOP ranks _ like Beckwith _
guessing about his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   While the national media has been focused almost exclusively on
the impeachment trial of President Clinton, Bush has successfully
wooed commitments from an impressive array of campaign ``players,''
from grassroots organizers in such key states as Iowa and New
Hampshire to financial rainmakers on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to the popular perception that Bush is losing ground
to other candidates (by waiting), the hidden story is how
extensively his agents are lining up supporters behind the
scenes,'' said Larry Sabato, an expert on presidential elections at
the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other Republicans also have been recruiting campaign
aides: former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, abortion foe Gary
Bauer, former American Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole, magazine
publisher Steve Forbes, Ohio Congressman John Kasich, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, former Vice President Dan Quayle and Sen. Bob
Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But none has come close to corralling the caliber of campaign
players that are waiting in the wings for Bush. And none has
anything approaching the unprecedented bandwagons of Congress
members, governors and state legislators who have pledged their
support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The only misstep by Bush so far was his failure to sign Steve
Grubbs, an outgoing state party chairman, to organize Iowa. Iowa is
scheduled to host the first voting - in local caucuses - in the
presidential contest next February. Forbes snatched away Grubbs
even as Grubbs and Bush representatives were negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fortunes in Iowa will rest with Thurman Gaskill, a state
senator who is a longtime friend of the governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, which hosts the nation's first presidential
primary, Bush is hoping to win over the state's other senator, Judd
Gregg, and former Gov. Steve Merritt. Both supported the governor's
father in 1988 and 1992, but they both are also close to the
party's 1996 nominee, Bob Dole, and are remaining uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   Fundraising is not one of Bush's weaknesses. He has commitments
from Bush presidential campaign veterans Mel Sembler of Florida,
Wayne Berman of Washington and Heinz Prechter of Michigan to help
raise money. He also has lined up Californians Howard Leach of San
Franciso, Alex Spanos and Gerald Parsky of San Diego, Brad Freeman
of Los Angeles and Tim Draper from Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, his uncle, Jonathan Bush, an investment banker, is
ready to help pull money out of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The one piece that will complete the puzzle is a top-notch
strategist, and many political experts expect former Christian
Coalition executive director Ralph Reed to sign on with the Bush
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signing up Reed will be equivalent to the New York Yankees
acquiring Roger Clemens,'' said Darrell West, a political scientist
at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Kasich, widely regarded as a second tier
candidate, is the one rival who has assembled a campaign
organization that rivals Bush's in credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich has one of the party's best known pollsters, Ed Goeas. He
has a veteran communications director, Ed Gillespie. Among his
fundraisers are Jim Rappaport, chairman of the Massachusetts GOP.
In Iowa, he has Karen Slifka, a rising star in state politics,
organizing the state. And in New Hampshire, he's got Bruce Berke, a
veteran of Reagan, Bush and Dole campaigns, and Rep. John Sununu,
the son of the former governor.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, who runs closest to Bush in the polls, has
surrounded herself with veterans of her husband's campaigns: Robert
Davis, a Washington lawyer; Mari Maring Will, the communications
director for the Dole '96 campaign; consultant Melinda Farris and
Stewart McLaurin, who supervises her office in Washington.
Agribusiness giant Dwayne Andreas, a longtime friend, is expected
to lend a fundraising hand. Dole also is wooing New York consultant
Kieran Mahoney, a longtime adviser to former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who relied on personal wealth and media buys in his 1996
campaign, is paying more attention to the ground game this time
around. In addition to signing Grubbs in Iowa, he has the backing
of Bobbie Gobel, the head of the Iowa Christian Coalition, and
Nancy Streck, Pat Buchanan's organizer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign chairman is former Sen. Warren Rudman of New
Hampshire, a popular figure in the Granite State. He also has a
fundraising whiz, Carla Eudy, and some of the best known
strategists in the GOP: Kenneth Duberstein, Michael Deaver and Vin
Weber.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has the backing of former Gov. Terry Branstad in Iowa.
And his fundraiser is Ted Welch, a prodigious former fundraiser for
the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle and Bauer probably have the closest thing to grassroots
organizations. Quayle's campaign is fueled by the work of Campaign
America, the political action committee formerly run by Bob Dole
and the source of $6 million in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also has an experienced campaign director, Kyle
McSlarrow, who worked in the Senate majority leader's office under
Bob Dole and Trent Lott after running unsuccessfully for Congress
in Virginia. And Quayle has the backing of former New Hampshire
Governor and White House Chief of Staff John Sununu.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer is counting on grassroots anti-abortion voters to power
his campaign. In the last election cycle, his political action
committee raised $7 million, largely on small donations. In
addition, he has raised $15 million for the Family Research
Council, the nonprofit organization he has headed for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
