<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6503 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-TRADESHOW-COX     02-23 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-TRADESHOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Health care and Internet key topics at expo
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Click on health.
</P>
<P>
   The junction of Internet and health care is the crossroads
between the nation's fastest-growing medium and the largest _ and
perhaps most problematic _ sector of America's $6 trillion-a-year
economy.
</P>
<P>
   With health care representing about 14 percent of that economy,
technology is already a major part of the industry. Attesting to
that union are the approximately 17,000 attendees in Atlanta at the
annual health care Information Management Systems Society. On the
exhibit floor are representatives of nearly 500 companies that
apply software, computer and networking to the delivery or
management of health care.
</P>
<P>
   But the hottest trend is the use of the Net. Just ask the folks
at WebMD, perhaps Atlanta's highest-profile, health-related Net
start-up company. Or the folks at McKesson HBOC, which recently
swallowed Atlanta-based HBO &AMP; Co. The company, has Web sites for
its various units and has invested in WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   And on the floor of the HIMSS conference at the Georgia World
Congress Center, the buzz is about the Internet's World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that everybody down there has some sort of Web-based
play or is about to roll one out,'' said William J. Michalak, vice
president of research at Interstate/Johnson Lane. ``There are a
myriad of proposals, depending on the niche. The development of Web
applications is so early stage, anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those jostling for position are older companies that
already have a large presence in hospitals, clinics or physicians'
offices _ companies like McKesson HBOC, IDX Systems Corp. or
Medical Manager Corp. That headstart gives them brand recognition
and could translate into Web power, too. Go to any browser, search
for health or health care or medical information and look at a long
list of offerings _ including some based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But companies that have created themselves specificially for the
brave new Net world may zip past the old ones. Stakes are high for
the transition to a Net-centric economy, and health care is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things that make health information an Internet
sweet spot,'' said Bill Bass, analyst at Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   For example, people who are interested in health information
often have an instatiable appetite for it. Moreover, the Net
permits rapid establishment of ``communities'' around various
diseases or conditions. Sufferers or families who might have been
isolated in years past, now can quickly connect via the Net to
others going through the same thing. Sites and mailings exist for
scores if not hundreds of conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The search for information too can lead in myriad directions _
for caregivers or consumers. To the latest on a disease or on
medications. To lists of providers. To an outlet for griping about
health maintenance organizations. To alternative treatments. To
advice about nutrition or weight loss.
</P>
<P>
   One site trying to tie most of them together is WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   In filing for an initial public offering of stock, WebMD cited a
projection by research company Cyber Dialogue that about 30 million
Americans will surf the Net searching for health and medical
information next year. Those people will spend $150 billion for
health-related products, the researchers concluded.
</P>
<P>
   That's at least partly because viewers of health care sites have
a different attitude about spending money, Bass said. ``You become
price-insensitive when you are worried about your health.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving the interest in health are demographics: millions of
professionals and other affluent Net users are the so-called Baby
Boomers edging deeper into the malady-pocked years of middle-age.
Moreover, they are often coping with aging parents. And the
fastest-growing group on the Net is probably the over-55 crowd.
</P>
<P>
   With all that in mind, companies with very deep pockets are
ready to spend a lot of money to advertise to those users. Jupiter
Communications has estimated that purchases of online advertising
for health and medical companies will surge to $265 million within
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for health care surfers already are already cresting.
General rates for advertising on the Net run about $15 per 1,000
views, Bass said. Yet, health care sites may get more than $100 for
the same number of looks. ``Those are very valuable eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   But how to get in front of those eyes?
</P>
<P>
   Among the many health sites on the Net are many for consumers,
some for doctors. Some that simply compile links, some with
articles, some connecting the user to companies. Atlanta-based
Medirisk offers databases and analytical tools aimed at helping
health care orgnizations be more productive and profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Bass warns against trying to be all things to all users. ``What
I don't see is a site dominating both business-to-business and
consumer. It's just very hard to be good at both.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Net itself, some of the more ambitious Internet
companies see connections as their value.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Atlanta-based ADAM Internet Health Inc. sees itself
as a ``component'' in someone else's Web machine. The nine-year-old
company, which got started making CD-Roms for use in training.
ADAM, never criticized for the quality of its work, has had its
financial ups and down and has recently reshaped itself to focus on
the Net. ADAM has its own Internet site, of course
(http://www.adam.com). But the company's greatest opportunity may
be in licensing its work to other Net companies, said Robert S.
Cramer Jr., co-founder, chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM's illustrations and annotations will become part of another
company's software, an arrangement that is already placing ADAM's
work in front of many more eyes than before, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become the visual component standard of Web health
care. This will begin bearing fruit immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD's connections are right up-front. The company has
alliances with McKesson HBO, CNN, E-Trade, MedQuist, Envoy Corp.,
DuPont and CompuServe _ some of them involving an investment in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these companies are involved in helping health care
evolve,'' said Jay Gilbertson, president and chief operating
officer of WebMD. ``They have found in delivery of data a way to
improve the quality of care as well as the cost of care.''
</P>
<P>
   And like other aggressive Net companies, the shining ambitions
cannot quite reach into the many dark corners of uncertainty.
WebMD's perspectus lists a series of reasons to doubt its promise:
The industry is new, the company's business model is basically
untested, WebMD will likely lose a lot of money for awhile and
can't even begin to predict future revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the Net. The lurking uncertainties that would
strangle a traditional IPO only add to the lure here. What matters
is the hope.
</P>
<P>
   And to be sure, WebMD has a plan. The company last fall started
marketing itself to doctors who pay a monthly fee for a service
that delivers messages, news and health information over the Net.
More than 10,000 doctors have signed up, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   But WebMD is also going after the huge audience of consumers _
the many millions of patients, potential patients and relatives of
patients, who are increasingly going to the Net in search of
information or aid. For them, WebMD offers free access _ but not
the same medical data as for doctors.
</P>
<P>
   That prescription calls for WebMD to mix several business
models.
</P>
<P>
   Money should come from subscriptions _ paid by doctors or,
perhaps, their employers _ and from advertising on the consumer
side.
</P>
<P>
   Net experts tend to be bullish about WebMD, but skeptical about
its business model. After all, the Net continues to evolve and no
single, clear path to profits has yet emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a lot of false starts,'' Michalak said.
``Everyone has to be a lot more patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The Net has already tried and rejected several ideas for making
money. For instance, the ``push'' model in which a user would have
a steady stream of reports or announcements ``pushed'' to his or
her desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   And subscriptions, too, are doomed, said Bass. ``Unless you are
an adult entertainment site or doing some kind of investment tips,
it is all advertising. Subscriptions are not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, online magazine Slate recently abandoned its
pay-for-access policy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some abandoned ideas are recycled in a new guise. For
instance, the notion of delivering data to a user is again being
discussed _ but the data must be customized so that the user really
wants it.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneering that strategy _ with a twist _ is Medcast, a nascent
Atlanta subsidiary of the Greenberg News Network, founded by former
Esquire publisher Alan Greenberg. Medcast customize information for
physicians _ an idea at odds with WebMD's approach, which is a kind
of portal _ Net jargon for a gateway to a range of sites, services
and sources.
</P>
<P>
   And while Medcast has a Web site, the company rejects the tag of
a Web company.
</P>
<P>
   ``WebMD is just a Web page,'' said Wayne Pines, Medcast head of
public affairs. ``This is a comprehensive and specialized news and
information service. And 70 percent of the physicians who see it
sign up on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, the stories are downloaded into doctors' computers,
along with various news and financial channels.
</P>
<P>
   Medcast's 55-member team, which includes a number of former CNN
reporters, analyzes research and articles from medical journals,
then writes its own stories . ``We are the largest medical news
gathering staff in the world,'' Pines said.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
