<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-     02-23 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEETS WITH CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS FOR FIRST TIME IN 19
MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also CONGRESS-COUNSEL) 
(ART ADV: Photos are is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Republican leaders of
Congress held their first formal meeting in 19 months on Tuesday in
a businesslike but chilly session that appears to have done little
to pacify the cold war between them.
</P>
<P>
   The president and those in Congress who tried to remove him
because of the Lewinsky scandal clearly suffer from a deep lack of
trust and remain far apart on major substantive issues, from tax
policy to the federal role in local schools.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his allies, bolstered by polls that show the
president retaining the support of the American people and broad
backing for his substantive agenda, believe they occupy the high
ground of domestic politics. They are inviting the Republicans to
do business with them _ on Democratic terms _ but are prepared to
resume partisan warfare when it suits their purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The chief issue dividing the parties is what to do with
trillions of dollars in projected budget surpluses over the next
decade. Clinton, with solid support from Democrats and the public,
proposes to reserve most of the surplus to shore up Social Security
and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to devote a large proportion of those surpluses
to tax cuts but are feuding among themselves over the specific
contours of tax relief. Some GOPleaders want a 10 percent
across-the-board tax cut; other members prefer limited, targeted
tax credits, like an end to the so-called marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's meeting between Clinton and the bipartisan
congressional leadership _ the first such formal encounter since
July 1997 _ marked the beginning of serious talks about the year's
legislative agenda. Little congressional business has been done
until now because of the extraordinary spectacle of Clinton's
impeachment trial, which consumed the first five weeks of the
congressional calendar.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Senate majority leader, and
the House speaker, Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., met with their
Democratic counterparts and Clinton in the Oval Office to start the
process of disengagement from a trying year of scandal,
investigation and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert fell into pugilistic metaphors to describe his first
face-to-face meeting with the president since Hastert was elected
speaker in January. His ascension came as a result of a separate
allegations of marital infidelity involving the former
speaker-designate, Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert described the meeting as ``an opening round'' in what is
expected to be a months-long bout over policy and political
positioning. ``It was a good first start,'' Hastert said in a brief
interview in the Capitol. ``It was just what I would say, touching
gloves before you got going.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's spokesman said that the speaker and other Republicans
were wary of Clinton's intentions, suspecting that he plans to
offer policies that Republicans are certain to reject and then use
the resulting gridlock as a campaign issue in 2000. It was a
strategy that worked for the White House and congressional
Democrats in 1998, when, against historical precedent, the party
holding the White House picked up seats in Congress in the sixth
year of a presidential term.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we deal with the budget surplus,'' said John Feehery,
Hastert's press secretary, ``we need also to deal with the trust
deficit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hastert and Lott both ducked questions from reporters about
whether they could trust Clinton after his repeated lies about the
Lewinsky affair and the White House campaign of vitriol against
Republicans in Congress who pursued his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate acquitted Clinton on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice 10 days ago, Lott said in an interview that
he could no longer trust the word of the president and did not
answer the question of whether he still respected Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   When asked on Tuesday whether he could trust the president to
keep his word on pledges of bipartisanship, Lott said: ``I'll tell
you what I trust. I trust the ability of the people, here in the
Congress, in the government, to work together to do what we need to
do for the people. That's where the real trust should be, the trust
in us doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and Democratic leaders tried to adopt an
air of magnanimity, promising to lay down their arms and seek
accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered only one brief comment before the meeting,
saying all sides had an interest in working together. ``We all took
an oath, and I think we intend to follow it,'' he said. ``We owe it
to the American people, and I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority leader, said that
Republican leaders had expressed willingness to work with Clinton
on strengthening Social Security, health care, education, campaign
finance and other major policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realize that if they're to get the people's business
done, they have to work with the president of the United States,''
Gephardt said after the Oval Office meeting. ``And by their being
here today and going through what I thought was a positive meeting,
I think there was a lot of good, positive developments to come out
of this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt quickly scratched a line on the ground and dared
Republicans to cross it. He said that the president's plan to
reserve 77 percent of future budget surpluses for Social Security
and Medicare was a ``threshold decision'' that must be accepted by
Republicans. Until they do, Gephardt said, Clinton and the
Democrats will not discuss any specific plans for allocating excess
federal funds, including any possible tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House political adviser said that, for now at
least, Clinton and Democratic leaders are in agreement that
compromise on major spending and social issues is both good
politics and good policy.
</P>
<P>
   Another presidential adviser said that Clinton, despite his
optimistic tone now, did not expect much progress this year on the
ambitious agenda he spelled out in his State of the Union message
in January.
</P>
<P>
   Relations with Republicans will continue to be strained by
bitterness on both sides from the impeachment fight. And the
current Democratic unity could be frayed by the diverging interests
of congressional Democrats, who want to seize control of the House,
and Clinton, whose top priorities are repairing his image and
electing Vice President Al Gore as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   But even without movement on major domestic issues, this adviser
said, Clinton is in position to dominate the public stage on
foreign policy issues, from the Middle East to the Balkans and from
international economic upheaval to the continuing threat of
terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
