<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6511 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAS-SWITCH-COX     02-23 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-SWITCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Customers switching gas marketers
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly one-third of Atlanta Gas Light Co.'s customers have
signed up to purchase natural gas from marketers, and the rest
aren't far behind.
</P>
<P>
   The utility's latest monthly update today is expected to show
about 455,000 of its 1.5 million customers have switched service
four months after the start of deregulation. That's 31 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Public Service Commission is seeking
legislation to ensure all AGL customers are placed with marketers
by next winter. The bill is expected to be introduced in the
General Assembly by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to get the marketers to take over and get AGL into
the pipes business and not selling any gas,'' said the bill's
sponsor, House Majority Whip Jimmy Skipper (D-Americus).
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta Journal-Constitution spot-check Tuesday of what the
average residential customer paid for gas service in February
showed most marketers charging within $3 of one another. The price
comparison includes nine of the 12 marketers now serving former AGL
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Gas Light's price was more than $11 higher than the $60
average price offered by the marketers. The utility's
weather-sensitive rates were pushed upward by balmy temperatures
earlier this month. The current cold snap, however, is lowering
AGL's charges.
</P>
<P>
   Price comparisons are difficult to make, since some marketers
lock in rates for up to three years to ensure against price jumps,
while the rates of others fluctuate monthly and include separate
interstate gas pipeline charges. In addition, the value of
promotional ``free gas'' offers and other giveways also vary.
Marketers also calculate ``base charges'' for delivery of gas
differently.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Service Commission has been debating whether require
marketers to file their rates with regulators to provide more
information to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   PSC Chairman Stan Wise opposes the proposal as ``government
intrusion in the marketplace'' but has urged marketers to ``give
customized quotes to consumers that disclose all charges.''
</P>
<P>
   SCANA Energy has added a ``bill calculator'' to its Internet
site, allowing consumers to figure monthly costs to the penny.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC wants all AGL customers to be assigned to marketers by
Sept. 30. Regulators wants to avoid a repetition of the furor
earlier this year over AGL rates that led to a settlement with
regulators and ordered $14.5 million in customer refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Current law requires that 33 percent of the gas sold in each of
nine separate delivery areas be provided by marketers before the
PSC assigns AGL's remaining customers at random to marketers. The
update due today from AGL is expected to show the Newnan, Augusta
and Macon areas have passed the 33 percent threshhold, and Atlanta
is getting very close.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, however, would give the PSC authority to order
random assignments, regardless of progress made in the nine areas.
Wise said the measure is intended to ensure that areas where
switches are lagging are not left stranded with AGL for another
high-cost heating season.
</P>
<P>
   Wise expects the measure to have the support of top legislative
leaders, including House Speaker Thomas Murphy (D-Bremen), and be
enacted with the signature of Gov. Roy Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   AGL would still, under the legislation, operate as a
distribution company responsible for transporting gas to homes and
businesses, but would no longer sell gas.
</P>
<P>
   Customers would get plenty of written notice before they are
assigned to marketers and be able to switch again without charge if
they don't like their assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is being supported by both AGL, which is anxious
to lay to rest the controversy over its winter rates, and
marketers, who want to simplify their sales efforts and add to
their customer rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine the confusion of trying to explain to
customers in Carrollton and Douglasville why they're (being
assigned) at a different time when they're 15 miles apart,'' said
Deborah Latham, president of Roswell-based Peachtree Natural Gas.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the random assignment, AGL's latest customer count
confirms that the state's deregulation has outpaced any other major
U.S. utility restructuring program.
</P>
<P>
   The random assignment system is what makes Georgia's program
unique and will allocate marketers two customers for every one they
can sign up now.
</P>
<P>
   Wise, in Washington this week to attend the National Association
of Regulatory Utility Commissions annual meeting, said he's getting
lots of questions about the Georgia program. ``They're intrigued by
it,'` Wise said of his colleagues from other states.
</P>
<P>
   With random assignment fast approaching, marketers are retooling
their sales pitches. There's no sign yet of Ginsu knife or toaster
oven giveways yet, but changes are afoot:
</P>
<P>
   Warren Darby, senior vice president of SCANA Energy, said the
South Carolina-based supplier plans to start putting a ``limited
time only'' label on its popular offer of $50 in free gas and
``start winding it down'' in advance of random assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-based Shell Energy and United Gas Management, an affiliate
of a Canadian gas marketer, both plan to add variable monthly rates
to the fixed rates they are currently offering.
</P>
<P>
   Shell is hitting the streets today with a trademark
yellow-and-red mobile van that will visit Shell service stations
and shopping malls to sign up customers.
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree Natural Gas has started basing its separate charges
for interstate pipeline capacity on actual gas usage. Atlanta Gas
Light made the same change as part of its settlement with the PSC.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
