<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO ENLIST ELDERLY IN FIGHT AGAINST MEDICARE FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After six years of fighting Medicare overbilling with teams of
auditors and prosecutors, the federal government is trying to
enlist new soldiers on its fraud squad: The 39 million elderly and
disabled people who receive Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors and other health care providers are objecting that
the campaign _ to be kicked off by rallies Wednesday in Miami,
Dallas, Seattle, Boston, and other cities _ will poison a
relationship that is supposed to be therapeutic and trusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will stigmatize all doctor-patient relationships,'' said
Dr. Jeffrey Modest, medical director of Uphams Corner Health Center
in Boston. ``It's reminiscent of the old `welfare queen' stuff,
when everybody on welfare was stigmatized by focusing on the few
who did commit fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign will attempt to persuade Medicare patients to
scrutinize their bills and call doctors, hospitals, medical
equipment suppliers, and other providers if they see something
suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   If Medicare patients are reluctant to confront health care
providers directly, the government invites them to call a ``fraud
hotline,'' with the enticement of a $1,000 reward if their tips
lead to substantial monetary recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Elder advocates are expecting a big response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found that nine out of 10 people are willing to help
if they knew how to define fraud,'' said Lee Norrgard of the
American Association of Retired Persons. ``They think it's their
personal responsibility and they are willing to participate in the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which boasts 32 million members, is throwing its
weight behind the Clinton administration's campaign against
Medicare ``waste, fraud, and abuse,'' part of a $137.5 million
federal initiative split between the departments of health and
human services and justice.
</P>
<P>
   Although fraud is the focus of the rallies, federal officials
say they don't know how much of Medicare's $210 billion in annual
expenditures is lost to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an estimated 7.1 percent or $12.6 billion of the
program's payouts were ``improper.'' That broad category covers
payment for services or products that were never delivered,
services deemed medically unnecessary, attempts to bill for more
expensive procedures than were actually done, and bills that were
not fully documented or simply erroneous.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.6 billion in improper payments this year represents ``a
dramatic decline'' from $23.2 billion in fiscal 1996, according to
an audit this month by the Inspector General of the Department of
Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, the department excluded more than 5,700 health
care providers from Medicare and other programs because of fraud
and abuse, double that of the previous two-year period. But
officials have decided that further progress will depend on
enlisting Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of 2,000 Americans conducted by AARP, along with
20 focus group interviews, found that most Medicare beneficiaries
said they currently scrutinize their bills for accuracy. The true
figure, Norrgard guessed, may be closer to 30 or 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a lot of folks are already examining their bills,''
he said. ``Most want to call their provider first because they want
to give them the benefit of the doubt, and they recognize that
billing errors are common.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will urge Medicare beneficiaries to use a
three-step process if they find a questionable bill: Check with
their provider to see if it's a billing error; call the Medicare
carrier if they don't get a satisfactory answer; and if they still
suspect fraud, call a toll-free hotline at 1-800-447-TIPS.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association calls the campaign
``lamentable,'' ``irresponsible,'' and ``a public relations
gimmick'' and one official predicted a ``flood'' of patient calls
to physicians' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The massive `phone-in' Medicare fraud campaign. . .sending our
patients out to fight Medicare fraud with little more than a
baseball cap, magnifying glass, and an 800 number, trivializes real
fraud and creates an adversarial tone in every physician-patient
encounter,'' complained AMA President Nancy W. Dickey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
