</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WASHINGTON24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush: Tobacco cash belongs to states, not Washington
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flanked by members of Texas' congressional
delegation, Gov. George W. Bush declared Tuesday that the federal
government should keep its hands off the state's $17.3 billion
tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's general consensus amongst Republican and Democrat and
independent governors as well as members of the Congress _
hopefully, both Republican and Democrat, but clearly Republican _
that this money ought to stay in the states,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government had a chance to join the lawsuit and
chose not to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas and other states sued tobacco companies to recover some of
the Medicaid money they paid out to cover tobacco-related health
problems. But the Clinton administration has argued that because
federal dollars make up a significant portion of state Medicaid
programs (more than 60 percent in Texas), Washington is entitled to
some of the money, or at least a say in how it is spent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the money belongs to the taxpayers and that the states
would spend the money more efficiently and in a way that more
closely reflects the public's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that if the federal government takes some of
the money, it should foot some of the legal bill for the private
lawyers the state hired in the case. Federal arbitrators have
ordered tobacco companies to pay the lawyers $3.3 billion, but the
lawyers have not yet signed off on their right to come after the
state for their paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been in Washington for a four-day conference of the
nation's governors. A dozen of the country's 31 Republican
governors have joined forces to urge Bush to run. Gov. Marc Racicot
of Montana, one of three governors engineering the show of support,
said the National Governor's Association endorsement will be
released ``in a few more days,'' once 15 or 16 colleagues are on
board.
</P>
<P>
   Though speculation about Bush's possible presidential bid
dominated his trip, his meeting Tuesday with the Texas
congressional delegation focused on the tobacco settlement and
other policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison said there is broad congressional
support for her bill to bar the federal government from taking any
of the tobacco money, and that the states should decide how it is
spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president yesterday came out and said he'd let our bill go
as long as the states would agree to spend the money in certain
areas,'' Hutchison said. ``I am absolutely against the federal
government telling the states how to spend the state tobacco
settlement money.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas state Sen. Bill Ratliff (R-Mount Pleasant), chairman of
the Senate's budget-writing committee, said the battle is far from
over. Just in case, he said, state budget writers are preparing
legislation that would cut all programs funded by the tobacco money
by a percentage equal to whatever the federal government takes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
