<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6518 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CRISIS-BOS &LR;      02-23 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CRISIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO TALKS END WITH NO AGREEMENT TO HALT FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France - The Kosovo peace talks ended
inconclusively Tuesday when ethnic Kosovar Albanians and Serbs
refused to sign a settlement that would end the year-long fighting
that has left some 2,000 dead and another 300,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers pronounced the talks a failure because they did
not result in the agreement that the six-nation Contact Group on
the Balkans, including the United States, had tried to impose on
the two sides fighting over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the Contact Group - the US, Britain,
France, Germany, Italy and Russia - claimed that both sides had
agreed to one part of the two-part settlement, and vowed to bring
the two sides together again March 15 in France in a final attempt
to reach a settlement. They also claimed that the Kosovar Albanians
had agreed to the settlement in principle, but needed to consult
with supporters back home before signing it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the claims of a partial settlement, the western powers
admitted that neither side had signed anything, so that nothing
discussed here at this 14th-century castle 35 miles southwest of
Paris is binding.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile fighting continued in Kosovo. Five policemen and a
photographer were wounded in fighting in the snow-covered hills in
the northern part of the province Tuesday just hours before the
deadline in Paris passed.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight day of clashes between guerrillas of
the KLA and Yugoslav security forces west of Vucitrn, an area from
which 4,000 civilians have fled in recent days, according to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   At Rambouillet, the Kosovar Albanians balked at signing the
political part of the agreement because it does not specifically
call for a referendum on independence after three years, a
provision they hold dear. The Serbs, meanwhile, refuse to sign the
military part of the agreement because it calls for 30,000 NATO
troops to police the settlement in Kosovo, their southern province.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who spent the last three
days pleading with the Kosovar Albanians to sign the agreement
despite their misgivings about the absence of a referendum
guarantee, said the ethnic Albanian delegation had accepted the
settlement in principle but insisted they had to consult with
supporters in Kosovo before signing.
</P>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said the talks had
produced ``a consensus on substantial autonomy for Kosovo,
including mechanisms for free and fair elections to democratic
institutions, for the governance of Kosovo, for the protection of
human rights and the rights of members of national communities, and
for the establishment of a fair judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vedrine acknowledged that he had nothing in writing, and
Albright insisted that the Serbs refuse even to discuss the
presence of NATO troops on sovereign Serbian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vedrine and British Foreign Minister Robin Cook, who
together hosted the talks here, said the conference set to
reconvene somewhere in France on March 15 would be used to
implement the agreements in principle that the Contact Group
received from the two sides at Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   But, under questioning by reporters, both men acknowledged that
neither side had formally agreed to anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done a lot here, even if we have not done enough,''
said Cook, stressing that in just four weeks the western powers had
intervened in a conflict that seemed intractable, halted much of
the bloodshed and brought the two combatants to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an agreement from both sides for the self-governing of
Kosovo,'' said Cook. ``Today is not the end of that process, only
the end of the first phase. March 15 is the second phase. It's a
good deal for both sides. They'd be wise to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The KLA remains wary of the provision in the agreement calling
for it to disarm while some of its members in exchange would become
police officers in a newly autonomous Kosovo. Many in the KLA say
they are fighting for independence and anything short of that is
unacceptabale. But most would settle for a referendum on
independence, because the predominance of ethnic Albanians, who
make up 90 percent of the 2 million people in Kosovo, would all but
assure approval.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that she and other leaders of the Contact Group
will spend the next two weeks trying to convince the Kosovar
Albanians ``that it's a good deal.'' Some members of the delegation
could travel to the United States during that time, she said.
Albright is convinced that the only way to persuade the Serbs to
agree to a settlement is first to persuade the ethnic Albanians. If
this is achieved, the Serbs would then be vulnerable to NATO air
strikes should they continue to oppose the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the pattern at Rambouillet, the Europeans were more
conciliatory toward the Serbs than Albright. Cook stressed that
``both sides are to blame for that violence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cook agreed with Albright that any peacekeeping force in
Kosovo must be ``NATO-led and NATO-commanded.'' The Serbs favor a
weaker force, including Russians and other peacekeepers from
countries traditionally sympathetic to Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If other countries wish to take part, we would welcome that,''
Cook said. ``But it would remain NATO-led.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hill, the US envoy to Kosovo who is the chief author
of the proposed settlement, was more candid that many of the
higher-ranking officials here. An exhausted Hill, who trudged back
and forth between the opposing camps during the negotiations, said,
``I don't want to downplay this too much. But we've still got a war
going on out there. It could always spin out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill added, ``A lot more has to be done. We aren't there yet.
Rambouillet was a big step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
