u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUCHANAN-POLITICS-810     02-23 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-POLITICS-810&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSOCIATES SAY BUCHANAN LOOKING TO RUN FOR PRESIDENT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pat Buchanan, who stunned the political
establishment when his low-budget, insurgent campaign triumphed in
the New Hampshire Republican primary in 1996, is preparing a third
bid for the White House in 2000, according to several close
associates.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, CNN President Tom Johnson announced that Buchanan
had been granted a leave as co-host of the program, ``Crossfire,''
beginning Wednesday. ``We wish Pat well in his exploration of a
possible GOP candidacy,'' Johnson said. Some of Buchanan's
associates said he may announce his intentions as early as next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from his appearances as a commentator, he has laid low in
the last three years and not participated in many of the political
forums that are frequented by prospective candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But several associates, most of whom spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said Buchanan told them he has grown bored with his
television role and believes that the early Republican
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, was not as inevitable a
nominee as was Bob Dole, the former senator from Kansas, was four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Given Buchanan's passionate following among cultural
conservatives in states with early contests, his candidacy would
immediately complicate the race. Others who are already fiercely
competing for the support of social conservatives include former
Vice President Dan Quayle; Steve Forbes, the publishing magnate;
Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire; and Gary Bauer, who was head of
the Family Research Council. Like Bush, Elizabeth Dole, the former
American Red Cross president, is undeclared but considered
formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, 60, has long been underestimated as a politician. In
his first bid for public office, he humiliated President George
Bush by drawing more than 37 percent of the vote in the New
Hampshire primary in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Buchanan won the New Hampshire primary with 27
percent of the vote, a point ahead of Dole. And he came close to
defeating Dole in the crucial Iowa caucuses, drawing 23 percent,
compared with 26 percent for Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was also victorious in three other early caucuses,
Alaska, Louisiana and Missouri. He essentially ended the
well-financed campaign of Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas. But Buchanan's
campaign, overpowered and outspent by Dole, fizzled out after New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat is probably going to coalesce his old voters again and
he's going to be a formidable force,'' said Terry Jeffrey, the
editor of Human Events who was Buchanan's campaign manager in 1996.
Arguing that Buchanan's seething appeals to the disaffected and his
attacks on corporate interests had a receptive audience in New
Hampshire, he added, ``If the economy turns down he could be even
more formidable than he was last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican Party, said: ``A
considerable number of people in the party take him seriously,
particularly in the early going. Iowa and New Hampshire are retail
political places _ and he's very good at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation for Buchanan's apparent rethinking about
running in recent months may be that he recognizes there may be a
fresh opening for his populist economic message. Despite the potent
domestic economy, the global economic crisis in recent months has
led to a flood of low cost imports in industries like steel,
leaving both workers and companies feeling vulnerable to unfair
competition. That has been one of Buchanan's central themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's convinced that the global trade issues, particularly the
economic issues, work for him,'' said Bill Press, a Democrat who is
Buchanan's sparring partner on ``Crossfire.''
</P>
<P>
   But a crucial question for Buchanan is whether he can tap into
the reservoir of support he enjoyed last time. Already, most of his
top aides from 1996 have moved on. Jeffrey said he has no intention
of leaving Human Events. Greg Mueller, Buchanan's communications
chief in 1996, is planning to sign up with Forbes. Connie Mackey,
who was a top Buchanan strategist four years ago, is working for
Bauer. Buchanan's sister, Bay Buchanan, a driving force behind his
candidacies, has told associates that she expects to continue as a
commentator on MSNBC. And Peter Robbio, who ran Buchanan's
operation in New Hampshire four years ago, is expected to work for
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Forbes has recruited past Buchanan backers is that he
has readjusted his message with an appeal to many of the social
conservatives who backed Buchanan in 1996. Forbes has the personal
wealth to stay in the race and is therefore generally viewed as
more electable than Buchanan. Quayle also has far greater resources
than Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle McSlarrow, Quayle's campaign chairman, said because of the
crowded field he doubted Buchanan could again win New Hampshire.
``We're fast approaching a situation where we may have more
candidates than people in New Hampshire,'' he said. ``But I never
count Pat Buchanan out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, while Buchanan has been a divisive Republican figure _
he was attacked even in his own party for appearing harsh in
commenting about homosexuals and others at the Republican
convention in 1992 _ he has been a master at capturing press
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat doesn't need a big political machine,'' Mueller said.
``He'll energize his base of supporters who will line up behind his
Lincoln Navigator looking for rides to caucuses and polls.'' But,
he added, ``The endgame is the problem. That's where the niche
conservatives run into a virtually insurmountable firewall.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite early polls showing Buchanan is in the single digits in
Iowa and New Hampshire, Press said Buchanan told him he believes he
can win. ``He is convinced that if Elizabeth Dole stumbles, if G.W.
stumbles, in a field of pygmies, he's the giant,'' he said. ``This
is not just a need for adulation on his part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
