</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-AUDIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDITORS SAY PROBLEMS WERE IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts auditors say internal control problems
have been found in the Treasury every year since 1994, but the
findings were ignored by then-State Treasurer Joseph D. Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We noted numerous repeat issues and findings dealing with ...
weak internal controls,'' Deputy Auditor Robert Powilatis said
Tuesday. The treasurer's office under Malone, Powilatis added,
``had warnings and chose not to take corrective action.''
</P>
<P>
   State Auditor Joseph DeNucci is preparing a report for new
Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien that will specify the recurring
problems found in the department, Powilatis said.
</P>
<P>
   The report will include ``prior recommendations and prior
concerns with internal controls in the collection of cash in the
abandoned property fund,'' including the Unpaid Check Fund, ``back
to '94 and '95,'' Powilatis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't take corrective action, that was obvious,'' added
Powilatis, referring to the alleged attempt to bilk $6.5 million
from the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Powilatis' assertions contradict Malone's claim that the
Treasurer's office passed its audits. When asked to respond to
Malone's contentions, Powilatis said ``That's not true. I don't
know where he can show that.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone has reacted to the financial scandal by vigorously
defending his management of the office, blaming it on ``people, not
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference this week, Malone said, ``I can understand
where, at first blush, they would think, `Gee, there is something
terribly wrong here. How can $5 (million) or $6 million be
potentially walked away with?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when you have auditors _ both public and private ones _
coming in on an annual basis ... you usually end up with controls
and procedures that are appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before last May, the Unpaid Check Fund apparently had no formal
guidelines for approving disbursements, other than the requirement
that two officials authorize payment. Verifying claims was left to
the discretion of John Trischitta, a fund manager who has pleaded
not guilty in the alleged bribery and embezzlement scheme, and one
of Trischitta's supervisors, Treasury officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the informal arrangement for verifying claims was
changed after heir hunters, seeking commissions for putting
claimants together with their money, stepped up pressure through
Freedom of Information requests to gain access to the Unpaid Check
Fund. The Treasury agreed to distribute the list of people owed
money but tightened procedures and required that heir hunters to
present a notarized power of attorney on behalf of the claimant
before receiving money.
</P>
<P>
   Although Malone said this requirement was an effort to limit
access to the fund, O'Brien has countered that the change might
have had the opposite effect. Deputy Treasurer Michael Travaglini
said Tuesday that the written requirement for power of attorney
might have been construed to mean that no other verification was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did DeNucci's office know of past problems within the
Treasuer's operations, but the attorney general's office received
at least two complaints about the operations of Martin Robbins, the
heir finder charged in the current scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas Reilly's office confirmed Tuesday that
two individuals had sent letters to the Attorney general's consumer
protection division last summer complaining about apparent
high-pressure tactics used by Robbins' firm. Both individuals were
sent letters informing them that state law authorized heir finders
to represent individuals who may be due money from the Unpaid
Checks or Abandoned Property Funds.
</P>
<P>
   But they were also told that individuals had the right to seek
those funds on their own without paying a percentage of the funds
to heir finders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Staff writer Stephen Kurkjian contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
