<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-MALONE-BO     02-23 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-MALONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE REFORMS WERE GOOD POLICY, BAD CHOICE, SOME SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the swirl of a breaking scandal, former Treasurer
Joseph D. Malone's decision to rely on heir finders as one of the
primary means of returning unclaimed property to its owners has
been cast in dark hues.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, First Deputy Treasurer Michael Travaglini charged on
Monday, had ``decimated the investigatory staff'' in the office's
Abandoned Property Division.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, the difference between Malone's policy and a more
traditional approach is one of government philosophy, not a clear
choice between good policy or bad. In essence, Malone privatized
some of the job of returning abandoned property, turning to the
private-sector to perform a task the state had once paid public
employees to perform.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Malone's initiatives were hailed as market-driven
reforms on the cutting-edge of reinventing government.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican who came to office in 1991, at a time of severe
recession and deep red ink, Malone had pledged to make the office
run more efficiently after the long tenure of Democratic Treasurer
Robert Q. Crane.
</P>
<P>
   One way he did that was to lay off some of the large staff Crane
had accumulated at the Abandoned Property Division during his 26
years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Malone decided, private heir finders, who earn a
percentage of what they recover, could use the unclaimed property
list the treasurer publishes in area newspapers each year. (State
law has required the prominent publication of that list at least
since the 1950s.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are heir finders fill a role that would have to be
filled by public employees,'' Malone said Monday. ``We would have
to hire dozens of public employees who would go out and find people
who have money coming to them. Here is a way that you can avoid
doing that hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and other measures, helped Malone cut staff and costs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during a time when the number of unclaimed dollars
more than doubled, to $105 million from $41 million, Malone reduced
the Abandoned Property Division to 29 workers, from 46. Even so,
his overall rate of returning unclaimed money was 23 percent to
Crane's 21 percent for a comparable eight-year period. During
Malone's last four years, he returned 28.7 percent to Crane's 16.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Neil Harrington, who now oversees the Abandoned
Property Division, said auditing costs actually increased under
Malone's privatization policies. But even using conservative
figures, Malone did well overall fiscally, inheriting a treasurer's
office budgeted at $13.9 million a year and reducing that amount to
almost half eight years later.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also pushed to limit the fees the private investigators
could collect. Before he came to office, the heir finders could
charge as much as 35 percent, the cap set by the Legislature in
1953.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Malone's initiative, that amount was capped at 10
percent for the Abandoned Property Division. (It's that stricture
that helped direct the heir finders to the more lucrative unpaid
check fund, which was not covered by the 19 pages of statute that
regulate other unclaimed property.)
</P>
<P>
   If O'Brien has cast the measure as one of inadequate controls,
Malone, understandably, sees it more as a matter of personnel
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try your best to find honest people to execute your
policies,'' Malone said. ``But once in a while, whether it is a bad
doctor at a hospital or an employee at a bank . . . you can have
people who end up doing something dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of Malone's earliest and best-publicized moves
may, in a roundabout way, have helped set the stage for this
scandal. When Malone took office, the treasury employed a dozen
tellers who operated a State House bank. All told, expenses topped
half a million dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   Malone replaced those tellers with an ATM machine. That allowed
significant cost-cutting. But it also meant the tellers had to find
other jobs. One of them was John Trischitta, a long-time treasury
employee who eventually ended up working in the treasury's Unpaid
Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   There, Trischitta allegedly played the inside man in a scheme to
defraud the state of $6.5 million from the Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   So will O'Brien move back to a greater reliance on state
employees?
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the new treasurer seemed unsure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to go in and look,'' O'Brien said. ``I certainly think
that heir finders could provide a legitimate function . . . But my
job is to make sure I do the best job to reunite the legitimate
owners of the property or the rightful owners of those checks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian MacQuarrie of the Globe staff contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
