</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$25 MILLION, OWNERS CAN'T BE MATCHED, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' Abandoned Property Division contains
millions of dollars for which the Treasury has no record of
ownership, present and former Treasury officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first sign that the growing financial scandal inside the
Treasury has spread to the Abandoned Property Division, officials
confirmed that as much as $25 million in unclaimed funds cannot now
be matched with their rightful owners because of missing records or
incomplete data.
</P>
<P>
   Tonia Duchano, Assistant Treasurer in charge of abandoned
property for three years before taking a private sector job last
month, said what once appeared to be a computer problem trying to
match unclaimed money with rightful owners could have a more
sinister root. Money from the state's Unpaid Check Fund, which is
supposed to be moved to the Abandoned Property Division after a
year, was transferred last year with no names attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the Unpaid Check Fund money, but never received any
names associated with it, as of today. It's millions,'' Duchano
said in a telephone interview. ``I truly believed at the time it
was a computer glitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Now? ``It just seems very odd,'' Duchano said.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation comes as John Trischitta, head of the Unpaid
Check Fund, is under investigation for bribery associated with the
theft of $6.5 million from the fund last November. Investigators
suspect Trischitta tipped off a so-called ``heir finder'' about the
names of people who were owed money by the state and then conspired
to transfer the sums to their own accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta, who has been placed on leave, was responsible for
moving money from the Unpaid Check Fund after one year into the
Abandoned Property Division. The Unpaid Check Fund holds money the
state owes to taxpayers, vendors and other agencies who have not
cashed the checks, often due to mail problems, company failures or
relocations.
</P>
<P>
   Although each check is supposed to be transferred after one year
to Abandoned Property, treasury employees say the normal practice
was to make large transfers every few months.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta made two large transfers, nearly $10 million in
September and $15.7 million last month, from Unpaid Checks to
Abandoned Property, where annual lists are printed to publicly
notify people that they have money to claim.
</P>
<P>
   But Duchano says the Treasury does not know who the rightful
owners are to as much as $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Robson, spokesman for new Treasurer Shannon O'Brien,
conceded the office is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was often some difficulty in terms of getting computers
to talk to one another and to translate this data,'' Robson said.
``What was once the EDIC became Ecdev. Who knows what Robert Smith
became.''
</P>
<P>
   Robson was referring to the Economic Development Industrial
Corp., an agency now controlled by the Boston Redvelopment
Authority. Martin Robbins, the New Hampshire man who allegedly
stole $6.5 million in EDIC checks, had them made out to ``Ecdev.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to touch off a three-alarm fire there, but there
is some concern about the quality of the data,'' Robson said.
</P>
<P>
   For the average citizen, the lack of documentation could mean,
for example, that some state tax refunds or vendor payments left
uncashed may never get to their rightful owners.
</P>
<P>
   Duchano said she stayed in her job until former Treasurer Joseph
D. Malone left office in January and wrote an exit memo saying the
lack of identification problem was among a list of items that
needed to be addressed in the Abandoned Property Division.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only problem.
</P>
<P>
   Duchano says she had been butting heads for years with
Trischitta's boss, Robert Foley, ever since she replaced him as
manager of Abandoned Property, leaving Foley to oversee Cash
Management and the Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Duchano says then-chief of staff, Beth Myers, called on her to
take over Abandoned Property because Malone felt there were not
enough controls in place.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Duchano took over Abandoned Property, Foley, who
could not be reached for comment, wrote out a check from the
Treasury's general account to ``John Doe'' for $1 million, using
Duchano's signature stamp.
</P>
<P>
   New Deputy Treasurer Michael Travaglini, confirmed that Foley
wrote the bogus check but said he did it to highlight how easy it
was to use another worker's rubber stamp signature to draw funds.
</P>
<P>
   The check was never cashed, according to Duchano, who was so
outraged over the incident she went to Malone with the problem. But
Foley was never fired. His last day, however, is Friday, because
O'Brien plans on replacing him with her own political appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Foley was saying he can't believe there were no controls.
What control is there when the deputy treasurer can write a
million-dollar check as a joke -- when he's in charge of the
controls?'' Duchano asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporter Stephen Kurkjian contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
