u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-PLAN-ART-NYT &LR;      02-23 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-PLAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING SAID TO RAISE CENSUS COST BY $2 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: Fienberg is cq in 3rd-to-last graf) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Census Bureau has calculated that last month's Supreme Court
ruling restricting the use of statistical sampling will force it to
spend about $2 billion more than the $5 billion originally budgeted
for the next decennial headcount, according to a senior Census
Bureau official.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bureau says that, despite the extra money, the 2000
census may not be any more accurate than the 1990 one, which missed
an estimated 8.4 million people and double-counted an additional
4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The increased cost for the 2000 Census was described by an
official on condition that he not be identified. The Bureau plans a
news conference on Wednesday to discuss the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Prewitt, director of the Census Bureau, said that in the
agency's new design, ``we will be running harder to stay in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the characteristics that make the American population hard
to count _ increased mobility, households with two parents working,
people with limited English skills, suspicion of government, lack
of engagement with institutions _ are more present today than they
were in 1990,'' Prewitt said. ``We also believe the design for the
2000 Census is more robust, more innovative, more creative than
it's ever been. But even so, we don't expect to have any marked
improvement over what we had in 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for billions more in spending are a direct challenge to
House Republican leaders who opposed sampling, which many
politicians believe would give the Democrats a political advantage.
The House leaders have said they are willing to pay ``whatever it
takes'' to conduct a traditional census count.
</P>
<P>
   The rural and urban areas where the undercounts were most severe
tend to vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled on Jan. 25 that federal law barred the
use of sampling to help estimate population counts used to
determine how many seats in the House of Representatives each state
will be allocated. But the Clinton administration has interpreted
the ruling as requiring the use of sampling to determine population
figures used in formulas for distributing federal aid to states and
local governments and for use in drawing boundaries for
congressional and state and local legislative districts. As a
result, the Census Bureau's new plans use some sampling, but on a
smaller scale than first conceived.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau had originally planned to count everyone, either by
receiving mail-back census forms or physically visiting their
homes, in 90 percent of the households in each of the country's
60,000 census tracts _ a neighborhood consisting of about roughly
1,700 dwellings. Census takers would then visit a small sample of
the remaining 10 percent and use information from that group to
estimate data about those who were missed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the original plan called for the census takers to
conduct interviews with a nationwide sample of 750,000 households.
The results of this survey would be used to adjust the population
counts of states, cities, neighborhoods, even city blocks.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the high court's ruling, the bureau's new plans
call for an effort to count 100 percent of the households in each
census tract, visiting each dwelling several times and making
numerous telephone calls to try to get the required data.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs just skyrocket as you go after those last
hard-to-count and don't-want-to-cooperate,'' said a senior bureau
official. ``That's what happens when you try to get that last 10
percent and that's what sampling was supposed to take care of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau will still conduct a large post-census survey and use
the results to determine where errors were made during the effort
to count all households and to adjust the population counts
accordingly. But officials said that the size of the sample in this
survey would be scaled back to 300,000 households from 750,000.
</P>
<P>
   Outside experts familiar with the bureau's plans said the agency
needed to reduce the size of its post census survey because it was
being squeezed by the calendar. Trying to count everyone by
traditional means will take much longer than trying to count 90
percent and using sampling to estimate the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they don't get into the field with the
post-enumeration survey until they close the field office for the
traditional enumeration, which is going to be much later if there's
not going to be sampling,'' said Stephen Fienberg, professor of
Statistic and Social Science at Carnegie Mellon University in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's new plans will open another front in the continuing
battle between the administration and House Republicans over the
2000 census. House Republican leaders have insisted that the next
census have only one official number for the nation's population
and that number be derived without using sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's plan will produce, in essence two numbers: one
compiled without using sampling that will be used to apportion
House seats among the states and another that uses sampling that
can be used for everything else, including the politically
sensitive issue of drawing lines for congressional and other
legislative districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
