<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-AUTOINSURAN     02-23 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-AUTOINSURANCE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas lawmakers: Auto insurance deregulation would curb costs
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two lawmakers who want to free auto insurers
from some state regulation said Tuesday that their plan would bring
rates down.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Wentworth and Rep. Harold Dutton have filed bills to
deregulate the price of auto insurance. State officials still would
keep tabs on insurers' financial stability and would root out
illegal discrimination, but individual companies would set their
own rates.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer representatives say many companies now charge the
maximum allowed by state law.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth (R-San Antonio) and Dutton (D-Houston) said companies
that set their rates too high would be run out of business or
forced to lower their prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood is that prices will go down,'' Dutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the Texas Department of Insurance each year
sets benchmark rates in 52 territories around the state. Insurers
subject to rate regulation can set their premiums from 30 percent
above to 30 percent below the benchmark rates.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Schneider, a policy analyst for Consumers Union, warned that
some rate-regulated companies already are testing the limits of the
current system. Several of the state's largest companies, including
Farmers, Allstate and Texas Farm Bureau, have rates about 30
percent above the average state benchmark rate, according to the
insurance department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give them an inch and they will take a mile,'' Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth said information used to set the state rates can be as
much as two years old. He also said the current system forces good
drivers to pay too much and allows bad drivers to pay too little.
That's because drivers are lumped into broad categories, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a deregulated system, Wentworth said, insurers could more
accurately categorize drivers so that insurance for bad drivers
isn't subsidized by good drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most of us pay is determined under an outdated regulatory
system,'' Wentworth said. ``This measure will bring some
long-needed reform to this area and could result in savings up to
$500 million annually for Texas consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth based that figure on the experience of Progressive
County Mutual. The Austin-based company is one of 24 in the state
not subject to rate regulation under Texas law.
</P>
<P>
   County mutual companies were left out of regulation decades ago
because they once were owned by groups of farmers and ranchers who
shared profits among themselves. Though some remain independent,
many county mutuals are aligned with rate-regulated companies.
Jerry Johns, president of Southwestern Insurance Information
Service, an industry group, said deregulating the industry would
encourage companies to do more business in all areas of the state.
That would mean more competition and lower prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have to look at what competition has done to the price
of airline fares and gasoline prices to see how consumers benefit
from a system where market forces dictate costs,'' Johns said.
``The market will take care of any company that abuses this
privilege. They will be driven from the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Newly appointed Insurance Commissioner Jose Montemayor said his
chief concern is that the department retain the authority to reject
rates deemed excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
