<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-CHILDINSURA     02-23 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-CHILDINSURANCE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marking income limit for Texas insurance program tangles
lawmakers
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When it comes to their children's health,
William and Robbie Voges face a stark choice: Should they pay for
food, clothing and housing _ or insure the kids against a medical
catastrophe that might never happen?
</P>
<P>
   William Voges, a heater and air conditioner technician, makes
$27,000 a year and gets full health benefits. But health insurance
for his three children would cost him an additional $280 a month _
money the family doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 200 some-odd dollars a month, and that throws us $200
short on paying our bills,'' Robbie Voges said.
</P>
<P>
   The Voges aren't alone: Many families can't afford private
health insurance for their children but make too much to qualify
for Medicaid, the federal health care program for the poor. So they
forego insurance and hope for the best, skipping the checkups that
could keep their kids healthy and prevent financially disastrous
major illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' soon-to-be-launched Children's Health Insurance Program
would use federal and state money to cover hundreds of thousands of
the Texas children who are in that gap. But Gov. George W. Bush and
state lawmakers are still wrangling over whether the program will
cover people making up to twice the federal poverty level or only
150 percent of it. The federal poverty level for a family of four
is about $16,500.
</P>
<P>
   In public, officials frame the issue as budgetary: Can the state
afford to cover all uninsured families that make as much as $33,000
for a family of four? Privately, some lawmakers and policymakers
question whether the government should be helping to insure
children in families that make that much money.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents, hairdressers and bank tellers in Austin make an
average of close to $24,700, or 150 percent of the federal poverty
level for a family of four. The average salaries of legal
secretaries and mechanics are close to $28,000, or 175 percent of
the poverty level for a four-person family. Austin plumbers and
accountants make an average of about $33,000.
</P>
<P>
   Before the legislative session, an interim committee recommended
the 200 percent income threshold. But under federal rules, the
governor must sign off on the CHIP plan that is sent to Washington
for federal approval, and the Health and Human Services Commission
has drafted a proposal that would cover families making up to 150
percent of the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has delayed sending that plan to Washington, and
discussions between lawmakers and his staff are continuing. He said
Tuesday that a compromise of 185 percent of the poverty level is
being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   About 471,000 of the estimated 1.4 million uninsured Texas
children are in families that make more than the federal Medicaid
limit but less than 200 percent of the federal poverty level.
Overall, nearly a quarter of Texans weren't covered by health
insurance in 1997, according to the U.S. Census Bureau. The state's
24.5 percent uninsured rate was tied with Arizona for worst among
the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the 150 percent threshold say it would be fiscally
irresponsible to go any higher because future federal CHIP
contributions are uncertain, and nobody knows how many people will
enroll in the program. Currently, the federal government puts in
about $3 for every $1 from the state. Privately, some also question
spending money to insure people making as much as twice the federal
poverty level. State Rep. Rob Junell, the House's leading budget
writer, said several lawmakers have expressed such concerns to him.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the 200 percent threshold say advocates of the
lower level are overestimating the number of people who will enroll
in the program. They also note that many other Republican governors
have chosen the higher threshold. Rep. Glen Maxey (D-Austin) has
portrayed the question as a test of Bush's professed
``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the debate about income levels concerns the
approximately 598,000 uninsured Texas children who are eligible for
Medicaid but not enrolled. Many families who have left the rapidly
shrinking welfare rolls mistakenly believe that because they no
longer receive welfare benefits, their children aren't eligible for
Medicaid. Others are daunted by the Medicaid bureaucracy, or
dissuaded by the stigma of getting government help.
</P>
<P>
   Because the state will mount an aggressive outreach program as
part of CHIP, it is likely that many families will discover that
their children are eligible for Medicaid and enroll them.
Proponents of the 150 percent limit note that because no one is
sure how much Medicaid ``spillover'' there will be, the state
should concentrate on serving the poorest group.
</P>
<P>
   Junell (D-San Angelo) suggested that the Legislature look at the
results of the first five months of the program _ it would be
implemented in July 2000 _ and debate the income threshold next
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``This session is not the time to determine where we're
ultimately going to be on a CHIP program,'' Junell said.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the higher level worry that if the governor
submits a plan with the 150 percent threshold, it may be difficult
to change later on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing about the plan going to Washington is that it
needs to stay as flexible as possible and not have us locked into a
poverty level that we can't adjust as the enrollment rises or
falls,'' Maxey said. ``If the money's available and children up to
200 percent of the poverty level need health insurance, there's no
logical reason why we shouldn't cover them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
