<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISS-EURO-ART-2NDTAK     02-23 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-EURO-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ZURICH, Switzerland: Fahrni said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thus, for many Swiss business leaders and economists,
``considerable concern'' exists for the stability of the Swiss
franc and euro exchange rate, said Georg Rich, chief economist at
the Swiss central bank. The flip side is that the reliable franc
helps bolster Switzerland's position as a prime banking nation.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, while Rich said no evidence existed that the Swiss
franc played a meaningful role as a global reserve currency like
the dollar or yen, the replacement by the euro of major European
currencies like the German mark could strengthen the Swiss franc by
increasing its attractiveness for private investors in search of
currency diversification.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss financial companies are approaching the new currency with
gusto. The stock exchange here is ready to trade in both Swiss
francs and euros, said its spokesman, Ettore Candolfi. Last year,
the major Swiss banks opened a clearinghouse in Frankfurt, the
Swiss Euro Clearing Bank, to process euros within Switzerland. The
clearinghouse is 60 percent controlled by the nation's two largest
banks, UBS and Credit Suisse. An electronic bank-payments system,
which handles roughly 480,000 transactions a day worth more than
$140 billion, is thus shielded from competing European banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an outsider, the Swiss took on the euro much more
pro-actively,'' Wellershoff of UBS said. His bank believed that the
euro would have a ``strong impact on the architecture of finance''
by sparking a wave of mergers and acquisitions among both financial
institutions and their industrial clients. Indeed, UBS is the
result of the combination last year of the market leader, Union
Bank of Switzerland, and the No. 3 Swiss Bank Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For Switzerland's private bankers, who add to the nation's
wealth by managing rich people's money for a fee, the euro is most
welcome. ``If it's good for European economies,'' Baer of Bank
Julius Baer said, ``then by implication it's good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, asset managers have been reprogramming computers to
provide euro reporting to clients, if desired, and insure that
securities, whether government bonds or company shares, are
converted to euros. ``If you're an international custodian, you
have to deal with all of this,'' Baer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond markets once fragmented by national currencies are now
unifying, and analysts must learn to assess national risk among
European countries much the way they rank American states' bonds.
Among investment funds, where clients were once advised to
diversify into, say, French francs or German marks, there are now
euros. And where stock choices were once made along national lines,
``we're moving to a sectoral approach,'' Baer said, ``and it's
happening very rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, financial expertise, not location, is increasingly what
will give Switzerland a competitive edge. Citing electronic brokers
like Charles Schwab, Baer said: ``In five or 10 years the client
will never know where a transaction is processed. And I'm not
really sure he cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellershoff said the recent discussion of the Swiss role in Nazi
times could lead to a greater willingness among younger Swiss to
become part of Europe. ``During the Cold War, the Swiss were glad
that they had not many enemies because they were neutral,'' he
said. ``But the whole public debate brought to people's attention
that Switzerland has not many friends in the world, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, say that conservative Swiss politicians opposed
to entry into the European Union and use of the euro will muster
their arguments convincingly, particularly by suggesting that
entering Europe would cost the Swiss dearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decisive problem for the Swiss is, What would it cost?''
said Fredmund Malik, a management professor in St. Gallen, in
eastern Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   As one of Europe's wealthiest nations, Switzerland would be
assessed an immense contribution to the European Union budget, he
said. And if nothing changed, the Swiss, with scant inflation,
would be in the curious situation of having to lift interest rates
so they would be in line with those of the euro countries. Swiss
homeowners _ just one group that would feel the pain _ could expect
to see their mortgage interest rates double.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys, Malik acknowledged, showed a thin majority of
the Swiss now in favor of joining the European Union, which would
almost certainly mean adopting the euro. Yet, he acknowledges, ``it
won't become an urgent matter.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Swiss business, he added, ``those companies that want to
be in Europe are already there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
