<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWERS NO MS. NICE GUY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Oxford University this week,  &UR; Gennifer Flowers &LR; , principled
former mistress of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; , said she disapproved of his
affair with  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   If she had been &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR; , she said, she would have
``scratched his face off'' and told him to leave. All the public
attention to her relationship with Clinton had almost made her
suicidal, said the shrinking violet.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers' remarks were billed as a talk on ``Surviving Sex, Power
and Propaganda,'' said the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE BOSS' TIME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says there are 14 million mainstream Web users in the
country, two-thirds of them using their work computers to average
13 hours a week on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   This means, writes &UR; Bradley Johnson &LR;  of Ad Age, that almost 10
million people are spending major chunks of their workweeks doing
personal chores on their work computers. ``Access to the Web is
almost becoming a benefit,'' said Microsoft's  &UR; Marty Taucher &LR; , and
``enlightened employers'' aren't going to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   Using an office computer is like using an office phone to make a
personal phone call or reading the paper at work. According to
Johnson, ``All work and no play makes Jack go postal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The South Pacific nation Palau has issued a stamp honoring
 &UR; Al Gore &LR;  as an ``environmental hero of the 20th century.'' Another
one of the heroes in the environmental stamp series is rain forest
activist  &UR; Sting &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Harper's Bazaar names  &UR; Dianne Feinstein &LR;  among its top five
picks for the first female president. The others:  &UR; Elizabeth &LR; 
 &UR; Dole &LR; ,  &UR; Christine Todd Whitman &LR; ,  &UR; Hillary Rodham Clinton  &LR; and
General  &UR; Claudia Kennedy &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Anastasia Soare &LR; , tweezer to the stars, told US magazine
about her plans for March 21: ``I always watch the Oscars and
think, God, I did so many brows there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Postcard from Down Under: Driving through rural Australia,
 &UR; David Greenlee &LR;  was puzzled by ``No Tipping'' signs posted on
fences. Research indicated they weren't reminders of reminders of
restaurant etiquette; they prohibited knocking over cows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHOPPING LIST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Falling into step with those consumers annoyed at Christmas
ads that appear months ahead of time, &UR; Frank Moonan  &LR; is shocked at
the nerve of Eppler's Bakery selling hot cross buns a month before
Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Silent Brass, a Yamaha invention described in Discover
magazine, is a plug for the bell of a horn, fitted with a
microphone and attached to a pair of earphones. The user can
practice until the cows come home, but the only one who hears the
sounds is the person who made them. This costs anywhere from $269
to $500.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're out in the wild and looking for an efficient,
compact source of energy, says Sports Afield, a bagel will do you
just as well as an energy bar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIDING OUT IN THE SOFA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So you've had a hard day at the office sounding off on this and
that, and you just want to go home and melt into the furniture?
Cabela's, which bills itself as the ``world's foremost outfitter''
for hunting, fishing and outdoor gear, is offering a complete set
of camouflage furniture.
</P>
<P>
   This set, which includes sofa, love seat, chair, queen sleeper,
rocker and storage ottoman, comes in four ``camo patterns'': Mossy
Oak Breakup, Advantage Wetlands, Realtree X-tra Brown and
Advantage. Customers purchasing matching clothing (and bedding) can
disappear into an environment of their own making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing says, `I'm proud to be a sportsman' better than this
unique camouflage furniture,'' says the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Meanwhile, in the great outdoors, Forbes FYI reports on
llama-training seminars conducted by  &UR; Jim Logan &LR; , a llama breeder
from Chattaroy, Wash. Logan believes in ``operant conditioning,''
in which good llama behavior is rewarded with treats and affection.
He says his llamas can shut doors and turn on lights on command.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in New Hampshire with my family at a pizza place. The
kid working there goes, `Hey, you look like Adam Sandler.' I said,
`Yeah, I know.' He goes, `What's your name?` I go `Adam Sandler.'
And he goes, `Whoa, that's a coincidence.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Adam Sandler  &LR; in Twist magazine. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
