<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-AID-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHWEST EXPORTERS WIN CONTRACTS UNDER RUSSIA AID PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 ((Story moving in both the ``a'' and ``f'' categories.)
 &HT;     By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Northwest exporters have won their first contracts
under an $885 million U.S.-Russia food aid deal, providing 850
metric tons of dried peas and lentils to help alleviate anticipated
shortages this year in the cash-strapped nation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they hope the two contracts awarded this week,
although relatively small, will be the first of several that will
benefit Northwest farmers, exporters and ports that have pioneered
links with the Russian Far East and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not millions, but it's a start,'' said Meg VanSchoorl, an
international trade specialist with the Washington State Department
of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before the Russians had asked for food aid, some of our
exporters called me and ... said we were in a really good position
here to contribute because of the connections we have developed
with Russia over the last four years.''
</P>
<P>
   VanSchoorl and Carol Vipperman, president of the Seattle-based
Foundation for Russian-American Economic Cooperation, said between
30 and 40 percent of the total 3.1 million-ton aid package could go
to the Russian Far East, a market largely pioneered by Northwest
interests.
</P>
<P>
   A consortium of Northwest growers, exporters, port officials,
members of the Washington state congressional delegation and others
have for months been lobbying the U.S. Department of Agriculture
and the Clinton administration on the advantages offered by this
region as a food source as well as shipper.
</P>
<P>
   In a December letter to Vice President Al Gore, all nine members
of the Washington state congressional delegation urged the
administration to ensure that:
</P>
<P>
   _ State commodities and processed foods be included in the food
aid package.
</P>
<P>
   _ Northwest ports be used to ship food aid to the Russian Far
East.
</P>
<P>
   _ Northwest agencies and private voluntary organizations be used
in the delivery and monitoring of the aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic crisis in Russia is having a devastating effect
on the Washington state export community, including agricultural
producers, manufacturers, traders and brokers, warehouse operators,
freight forwarders and service and shipping companies,'' the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacific Northwest ports from the grain and barge terminals on
the Columbia River to container shipping facilities in the Puget
Sound have been hurt by the virtual halt in trade with the Russian
Far East.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still too soon to tell whether those efforts will pay off.
</P>
<P>
   VanSchoorl said half of the wheat specified for the program is
Midwestern hard red rather than the soft white variety grown in the
Northwest. Many of the other commodities are not produced in the
Northwest either, although the state group is trying to convince
the Agriculture Department and the Russians to add Washington
apples, canned pears, dehydrated potatoes and fresh and processed
meats to the aid mix.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, U.S. law requires that at least 75 percent of the
aid be transported on American flag carriers, if available, and
it's uncertain whether any domestic shippers operating in Puget
Sound will submit bids.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture and Russian officials signed the $885 million
food-aid deal in Moscow in early November.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said the huge aid
package _ one of the few bright spots for the U.S. farm sector this
winter _ could be expanded next month when Russian Deputy Prime
Minister Gennady Kulik visits Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume this subject may come up,'' Glickman said when asked
if his department was considering more food aid for Russia. ``If
the needs are there, the United States will try to meet them.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current agreement, the United States will give Russia
1.5 million tons of American wheat and sell another 1.5 million
tons of assorted foodstuffs with the help of long-term,
low-interest loans. The United States also will send 100,000 tons
of food directly to needy Russian regions through voluntary
humanitarian organizations like the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economic crisis, along with dwindling food imports and
the worst grain harvest in at least 40 years, has raised concerns
about possible food shortages this year across the vast nation.
</P>
<P>
   The aid deal also is expected to ease the plight of Northwest
growers, hit by low prices and growing surpluses, as well as ports
that saw tonnages to Russia plummet since the economic crisis began
there last August.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Wilbur, president of Seattle-based Thomas International
Inc., said that one Puget Sound shipping line's cargo to the
Russian Far East plummeted from some 500 containers per voyage last
summer to only 17 shortly after the August devaluation of the
ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Under the U.S. aid package, about $260 million will go for
transportation and distribution costs.
</P>
<P>
   VanSchoorl said the contracts awarded this week were for the
100,000-ton humanitarian program and went to BNP Lentil Co. of
Farmington, Wash., and Maviga of Spokane. The two contracts are
worth a total of $246,000. The peas and lentils will be shipped via
a U.S. port on the Gulf of Mexico to St. Petersburg, in western
Russia, VanSchoorl said.
</P>
<P>
   More contracts could be awarded as early as Wednesday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest exporters are particularly anxious to get details of
the two larger USDA programs _ the 1.5 million-ton wheat donation
as well as the concessional sales that will include 500,000 tons of
corn, 300,000 tons of soybean meal, 200,000 tons of soybeans,
200,000 tons of wheat, 100,000 tons of rice, 120,000 tons of beef,
50,000 tons of pork and 30,000 tons of non-fat dry milk.
</P>
<P>
   Vipperman said the U.S. side can't proceed until the Russians
identify what and how much they want and where it should go,
including port of entry and final destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the wheat, the Russians have to identify which ports they
want to ship it to,'' Vipperman said. ``Some of that wheat is
already stored in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the concessional food loans, it depends on what the
Russians want and where they want it to go. Then tenders will be
put out for the products and well as for the transport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
