<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-OPTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS WEIGH OPTIONS TO INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth W. Starr may be remembered as the attack
dog who went after Bill Clinton and ended up killing the office of
the independent counsel instead.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the independent counsel law indeed appears to be
on the brink of extinction, lawyers and lawmakers have begun to
convey a far more complicated picture of the office _ and of how
members of both parties have come to believe, 21 years after its
creation, that the position designed to address the abuses of
Watergate has essentially failed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans seem more committed than Democrats to seeing the
statute vanish; many Democrats, despite their complaints about
Starr's investigation of President Clinton, say they are willing to
see the law modified rather than killed. Together, their sentiments
raise an enduring mystery of federal government: How can the
president and top government officials be kept in legal check?
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Senate hearings to examine the fate of the
independent counsel, everyone in the Capitol appeared eager to
voice a response. Four pieces of legislation on the independent
counsel are expected to be filed in the House of Representatives
this year; four senators Tuesday appeared at two bipartisan press
conferences, each to express his displeasure with the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone _ even a former independent counsel _ seemed convinced
the problems long predated Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only one who's really been criticized is Starr....I would
say anyone who uses an instrument helps kill it in the end,'' said
Lawrence Walsh, the former independent counsel who spent five years
and more than $35 million investigating Ronald Reagan's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Fred Thompson, whose Governmental Affairs Committee is
holding the hearings, said Starr's tenure in the office should be
examined, ``but this is not the Ken Starr show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really defeated the purposes we were originally
concerned with,'' said Thompson, a Tennessee Republican and a
former counsel for the Senate Watergate Committee. ``I don't know
of anyone who is really locked into the statute exactly as it is
today....as an individual who is placed in a position where he has
all the power and authority of the attorney general without the
checks and balances.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat from Massachusetts, agreed,
saying the 21-year attempt to provide an outside check on the
executive branch was a ``laudable goal, but often unattainable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a widespread feeling in Congress that the abuses
outweigh the benefits, and I share that view,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics make even longtime supporters of the statute
reel. Since its creation in 1978, there have been 21 independent
counsels, at a cost of roughly $160 million, $40 million of which
is the result of Starr. Five independent counsel offices _
including Starr's _ are still up and running, according to Senate
aides familiar with the statute.
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, however, the five-year statute is set to expire,
unless Congress votes to renew it. According to members of both
parties in both houses of Congress, that vote would fail if it were
taken today; serious modifications will be needed for it to gain
enough support to be renewed in any form, members of both parties
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said Tuesday that there are four possible outcomes:
letting the law expire; reauthorizing it in its current form;
amending it; and letting it expire but replacing it with a
scaled-down version later on.
</P>
<P>
   The 1978 law was created out of the concern that the Justice
Department could not objectively investigate the administration for
which it worked. Now, some are willing to take their chances on the
Justice Department, while some cynics think that since the
independent counsel has become politicized over the years, the
government might as well save money by returning control to the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Among critics' chief concerns are the scope of investigations
and the jurisdiction of the attorney general. Starr, who in 1994
began by investigating the Clintons' land deals in Arkansas, ended
up broadening his mission until he believed he had discovered
Clinton lied to a grand jury about his affair with White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton himself who had pushed for the law's
reinstatement: in 1992, after an Iran-Contra investigation that
Republicans viewed as unnecessarily long and vindictive, Congress
allowed the statute to expire. The White House urged its renewal,
and succeeded in getting it passed again in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Attorney General Janet Reno has appointed numerous
independent counsels _ too many, according to Democrats, and not
enough by Republican standards.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, whose efforts failed to get an independent counsel
appointed to investigate questionable campaign fund raising by the
Clinton White House, seems to be leaning toward letting the law
lapse, and ``if it dies, Senator Thompson thinks Janet Reno gets
the blame,'' one Republican aide said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet others believe the positions on both sides are still
being shaped by Watergate. Howard Baker, the former vice chairman
of the Senate Watergate Committee, is among those expected to
testify at Wednesday's hearing. And Senator Carl Levin, a chief
architects of the provision in 1978, said its original purpose
should not be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say at the moment its unlikely to survive in its current
form,'' said Levin, a Democrat of Michigan, ``but the purpose it
serves is an important one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
