<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6571 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-700&AMP;ADD     02-23 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BLAMING STARR RAISES MILLIONS FOR PRESIDENT'S DEFENSE
FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  ( nk ) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's legal defense fund has raised
$4.6 million in the last year, buoyed by a direct-mail campaign
that blamed Kenneth Starr and the congressional impeachment process
for saddling the first family with ``a staggering personal debt''
of nearly $9 million, several supporters said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, the Clinton Legal Expense Trust, has raised $2.4
million since August from 35,000 donors, eclipsing the most
optimistic projections of the president's supporters and the $2.2
million raised in the trust's first six months of operation last
year, according to the supporters who were briefed on the progress.
</P>
<P>
   Small donations _ $10 here, $20 there _ have poured in, the
supporters said, but there have also been $10,000 checks from
corporate executives and Hollywood friends.
</P>
<P>
   Like the president's continued strong showing in public opinion
polls, the trust's windfall is a measure of Clinton's enduring
popularity despite being the first elected president to be
impeached. Several supporters said the trust's success also
reflected the opinion among Clinton's supporters that the inquiry
by Starr, the independent counsel, and the impeachment proceedings
had been inherently unfair and deeply partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direct mail has been off the chart,'' said one supporter
who helped raise the money and spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``The president has never been more popular. And there is a lot of
sympathy for him. We didn't have to ask most people twice for
help.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than half of the Clintons' debts erased in a single
year, supporters said Tuesday that there is a strong chance that
the entire legal bill could be paid by the time the president
leaves office in 23 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``No president, especially a president who has worked as hard
for the American people, should be burdened with this kind of debt
when he leaves office,'' said Terence McAuliffe, one of Clinton's
closest friends, who raised much of the money for the trust.
McAuliffe declined to discuss how much money the trust had raised.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers of the president have said that Clinton's total
legal bills in his two terms could exceed $10 million by 2001.
Erasing those bills is a major concern of the first lady, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who has told her advisers that the debt is a factor
as she decides whether to seek New York state's Senate seat in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first president to accept donations while in
office to help pay his lawyers' fees. Former President Richard
Nixon accepted donations to help defray legal bills after he
resigned from office, but he paid most of his legal bills himself.
</P>
<P>
   The trust's $4.6 million total far outpaces the $1.3 million
that was raised over a three-and-a-half-year period by the
president's original legal defense fund, which was disbanded in
December 1997 after campaign finance controversies and a strict
$1,000 annual limit had severely limited the flow of donations.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers and trustees of the new trust, which is headed by
former Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., plan to release the fund's total
contributions, and a complete list of donors, at a news conference
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters said that many of the 55,000 contributors wrote
checks for modest amounts, like $10 and $20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trust is not being funded by fat cats,'' McAuliffe said.
``These people are committed in insuring that this president, who
has worked so hard on their behalf, does not leave office
bankrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   But the supporters also said that they had received $10,000
checks from scores of corporate executives who are contributors to
the Democratic National Committee, including S. Daniel Abraham,
chairman of the Slim-Fast Foods Co. of West Palm Beach, Fla.;
Ronald Burkle, the California supermarket mogul; Alan J. Patricof,
the New York venture capitalist; and Dirk Ziff, co-chairman of Ziff
Brothers Investments of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the trust has received a windfall from the
president's Hollywood friends, including $10,000 checks from
filmmaker Steven Spielberg, actor Tom Hanks, performer Barbra
Streisand and film executive Harvey Weinstein.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Defending the president at the House impeachment hearings and at
trial in the Senate added at least $2 million to the Clintons'
legal bills, their supporters estimated Tuesday. The Clintons still
owe roughly $3 million to their lawyers, the supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also used the trust's proceeds to pay Robert S.
Bennett, who led his defense in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
lawsuit. The suit was settled in November for $850,000, but that
sum was paid personally by the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the president's battery of lawyers have worked on
defending the Clintons in inquiries related to their Whitewater
real estate transactions and Democratic fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Several supporters said in interviews Tuesday that the fund's
success is owing mostly to the anger and frustration with the
House's impeachment of the president in December.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter, the fund's executive director, Anthony F. Essaye,
asked potential contributors to write a check to the trust if they
were ``disturbed by the way politics is conducted today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's political climate, public service can exact a
disturbing price,'' Essaye wrote. ``There is, perhaps, no better
example than the situation facing president and Mrs. Clinton. The
effort to impeach President Clinton is only the latest in a series
of legal actions that have left the first family with a staggering
personal debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Essaye declined to comment Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
