<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-HNS &LR;      02-23 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SEEK CHANGES TO INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW AS EXPIRATION
NEARS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Long criticized by Republicans and lately lambasted
by Democrats, the law spawning Kenneth Starr's investigation of
President Clinton faces radical changes or certain death in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not convinced (the independent counsel law) has not
outlived its uselessness,'' said Sen. Fred Thompson, whose
Governmental Affairs Committee begins hearings Wednesday on the
statute that grew out of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel statute expires June 30 unless it is
re-enacted by Congress. If it dies, Starr and four other
independent counsels will continue their investigations of the
president, two Cabinet secretaries and two former members of his
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was enacted in 1978, the law has led to 21 executive
branch investigations at a cost of $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The special prosecutors have secured more than 50 criminal
convictions. Thirteen of those resulted from Starr's investigation
of Clinton's business dealings, which subsequently was expanded to
include travel office firings and alleged misuse of FBI files at
the White House, and the death of presidential aide Vincent Foster.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law has been criticized for years, first
by Republicans during the Reagan and Bush administrations, then
during the past year by Democrats. Drawing the Democrats' ire is
Starr's investigation of Clinton, which led to his impeachment,
then acquittal after the first Senate trial of a president in 131
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the law was renewed, ironically at Clinton's behest,
just months after he was targeted for investigation. Two years ago
and three years into Starr's investigation, Clinton complained that
the law's costs had outweighed the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a bipartisan consensus that the independent
counsel statute, as written, needs a very serious look and some
reforms if it's to be reauthorized,'' said White House press
secretary Joe Lockhart. ``We agree with that consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing is the first of four scheduled by Thompson's
committee. A House subcommittee is to conduct its first hearing
into the independent counsel law March 2.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the witnesses scheduled to testify Wednesday have
favored either scrapping the law altogether or narrowing its scope.
Former attorney general Griffin B. Bell and former Senate
Republican leader Howard H. Baker Jr. are scheduled to tell why
they found the statute ``seriously flawed'' in a recent joint
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute as it exists today should not be reauthorized,''
Thompson told reporters, holding out the possibility of radically
revising the law. ``The burden is on those who want to keep it
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the law's problems, the Tennessee Republican said, are the
tendency of prosecutors to deliver a ``rougher justice'' to some
officials and to get ``more involved in the impeachment process''
than is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on whether he was referring to Starr's investigation of
Clinton specifically, Thompson said, ``I would not say the
president was mistreated by Kenneth Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the ranking Democrat on the
Governmental Affairs Committee, argued for revising the independent
counsel law, which was originally passed to restore public trust in
government in the wake of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe abandoning the law would automatically return
civility to our political discourse or raise the public's trust,''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the law was passed to avoid incidents like the
Saturday Night Massacre in 1974, when President Nixon ordered the
firing of Watergate special counsel Archibald Cox, which led to the
resignation of Attorney General Elliot Richardson who refused to
obey Nixon's order, and the firing of Deputy Attorney General
William Ruckleshaus, also for refusing to dismiss Cox.
</P>
<P>
   As written, the law calls for a three-judge panel to appoint an
independent counsel whenever the attorney general finds ``credible
evidence'' of wrongdoing by the president, vice president or by a
Cabinet member or other high administrative official. To give
investigations more credibility, the investigator is independent of
any oversight except when prosecutorial abuse can be proved.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Deputy U.S. Attorney Eric Holder told reporters that
the Justice Department wants Congress to ``tinker'' with the law.
Attorney General Janet Reno has complained about the lack of budget
restraints on the special prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's five-year investigation of Clinton has cost more than
$40 million and is expected to top $50 million this year. The tab
for Lawrence Walsh's six-year Iran-Contra probe of the Reagan and
Bush administrations ran $48.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ways being discussed to revise the law include
requiring independent counsels to have prosecutorial experience,
reducing the number of officials subject to investigation to the
president and a handful of other top officials, and transferring
some of the powers of present independent counsels to a public
integrity chief, confirmed by the Senate, within the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of the uphill struggle the law faces was a joint news
conference called early Tuesday by Sens. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
and Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., to oppose any extension of the
independent counsel statute.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 20 years and $150 million the independent counsel law
has brought down very few high-level officials,'' complained
McConnell, who chairs the Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee.
``Congress has established an elaborate system where we spend a
whole lot of money, build a great big fire, and fry a few small
fish. It's time to let that fire die.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has twice voted
against the law and an aide said he has not change his mind.
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., vowed Tuesday to ``do whatever
I can to terminate it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
