<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURD LEADER CHARGED WITH TREASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ The Kurdish guerrilla leader, Abdullah
Ocalan, who was captured in Kenya last week, was formally charged
on Tuesday with treason, a crime that can carry the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no executions in Turkey since 1984, but popular
sentiment in Turkey appears to favor capital punishment for Ocalan.
For years, he has been portrayed in the press and official
statements as a horrifically evil figure, and the authorities hold
him responsible for the estimated 30,000 deaths that his
14-year-old rebellion has cost.
</P>
<P>
   Under Turkish law, all death sentences are subject to
confirmation by a vote of Parliament. In the present climate, there
seems little doubt that Parliament would vote overwhelmingly to
confirm a death sentence for Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   The court session at which he was charged with treason on
Tuesday was before a single magistrate at the prison island of
Imrali in the Sea of Marmara, southwest of Istanbul. Ocalan has
been held there in isolation since he was returned a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The session was closed to the press and the public, and there
were no reports about what, if anything, Ocalan said in response to
the charge.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the European Union appealed for permission to send
observers to the trial. But Turkey reiterated on Tuesday its
earlier refusal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The EU's idea of sending observers to the trial means to
oppose and encourage interference in the independent judiciary,''
the Foreign Ministry said in a statement. ``This attitude, which is
against the principle of a state of law, is not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement said that observers not connected to organizations
might be admitted and that the presiding judges would decide on
individual cases.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign lawyers for Ocalan have been prevented from entering the
country. Several Turkish lawyers active in human rights groups have
accepted requests from his relatives to form a defense team.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes between army units and Ocalan's guerrillas have
continued since his arrest. A military statement on Tuesday said
that 14 guerrillas had been killed since Sunday. As is customary,
military casualties were not mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish newspapers reported that Ocalan had agreed to tape an
appeal to his followers to lay down their weapons, but no such tape
has appeared. Military officers have said that they are planning to
drop thousands of copies of a photo of Ocalan in handcuffs in front
of a Turkish flag over areas where guerrillas are active.
</P>
<P>
   In a report whose release this week was planned before Ocalan's
arrest, investigators from the Council of Europe said that Turkey
had progressed in its treatment of prisoners, but was still far
from meeting ideal standards.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by the council's Committee for the Prevention
of Torture and Inhumane or Degrading Treatment of Prisoners, said
investigators had found interrogation rooms ``of a highly
intimidating nature'' in some police stations, adding that such
rooms had ``no place in a modern police service.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
