<HEADLINE>
IN REVERSAL, CUBAN EXILES WILL BE TRIED IN PUERTO RICO  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ A federal judge here in the trial of
seven Cuban exiles accused of plotting to kill Fidel Castro has
reversed a ruling he made in January to move the trial to Miami and
instead has ordered the proceedings to continue in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the defendants, six of whom own homes in the Miami
area, said on Tuesday that they regarded the ruling, made on Monday
by U.S. district court Judge Hector M. Laffitte, a setback. Miami
is the bastion of the Cuban exile community, where convictions of
anti-Castro exiles are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities implicated the men in a failed plot to kill Castro
during a Latin American summit meeting in Venezuela. Most of the
defendants are said to have links to the Cuban-American National
Foundation, the powerful Miami-based lobby that opposes normal
relations with Cuba but says it supports only peaceful measures to
oust Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very surprised by his turn-around, and I think he is
making a mistake,'' said Ricardo Pesquera, an Orlando, Fla.,
attorney for Angel Alfonso-Aleman, one of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Pesquera played down concerns that a jury in Puerto Rico would
be more likely to find the men guilty. ``The government may believe
it's easier to get a conviction in Puerto Rico, because they really
scrambled when the case was transferred to Miami,'' he said. ``That
just shows they don't think they have a good case.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judge warned that the case could be moved to Miami if
prosecutors fail to establish Puerto Rico as the proper venue
during the trial itself. He said that the overriding motive for
keeping the case in Puerto Rico for now is that the docket for
criminal cases in Miami is backlogged.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the Coast Guard arrested four
defendants off Puerto Rico in October 1997 after two assault
rifles, nightscopes, military fatigues and a satellite telephone
were found aboard their cabin cruiser. The boat was searched by the
Coast Guard after it reported being in trouble at sea.
</P>
<P>
   The four _ Alfonso-Aleman, Angel Hernandez Rojo, Juan Bautista
Marquez and Francisco Secundino-Cordova _ told the Coast Guard they
were fishing.
</P>
<P>
   They were brought before a U.S. magistrate in San Juan and have
pleaded not guilty to charges of conspiracy, making false
statements and weapons violations. If convicted, they and the other
three defendants _ Jose Antonio Llama, Jose Rodriguez and Alfredo
Domingo Otero _ face life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent defendant is Llama, a member of the
foundation's board and the president of Nautical Sports Inc., a
corporate defendant. The boat involved is registered to the
company, and one of the rifles was traced to Llama, according to
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Marquez and his 26-year-old son, Juan Alberto
Marquez, were arrested on drug-trafficking charges involving almost
4,500 pounds of cocaine. The arrests sparked concern that the elder
Marquez could be turned against his alleged co-conspirators in
exchange for lenient treatment for his son.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a motion filed last month by the U.S. Attorney's
Office here, Laffitte said that ``upon further reflection,'' the
issue of venue for the most serious criminal charge _ conspiring to
assassinate a foreign head of state _ turns on whether the four
defendants arrested at sea deliberately lied ``to conceal a
conspiracy gone awry or to further an ongoing conspiracy.'' If the
conspiracy was ongoing, as prosecutors argue, then the conspiracy
charge could rightly be heard in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Another defense attorney, Howard Srebnick, said that the judge
had ``opened up a door'' that could lead to instant acquittal if
the prosecution is unable to establish that Puerto Rico is the
proper venue.
</P>
<P>
   Laffitte said in his previous ruling that denials by the
defendants that any firearms were aboard the vessel were ``at best
feeble attempts to cover up a conspiracy, not in furtherance of
one'' and that the alleged conspiracy was ``hatched, nurtured and
fledged'' in Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
