<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-RITTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPT. CRITICIZES BOOK BY FORMER U.N. WEAPONS INSPECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department said on Tuesday that a new
book by Scott Ritter, a former U.N. weapons inspector who has
contended that the CIA helped plan arms inspections in Iraq, was
inaccurate, misleading and could ``only serve Saddam Hussein's
propaganda machine.''
</P>
<P>
   The department said statements by Ritter, whose book lends
support to longstanding Iraqi accusations that U.N. inspection
teams were riddled with American spies, were ``consistent only in
their inconsistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter and his book were also denounced by Rolf Ekeus, former
head of the United Nations Special Commission, or UNSCOM, which
conducted the inspections. He said Ritter was engaged in
``destructive fantasizing'' in suggesting such close ties between
the CIA and the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Ekeus also disputed Ritter's speculation of a tie between a U.N.
inspection team that was sent into Iraq in 1996 that according to
the book included CIA officials and what may have been a coup
attempt inspired by the agency. The State Department and Ekeus were
responding to a report on Tuesday about Ritter's book in The New
York Times, which obtained galley proofs of the book, ``Endgame.''
It is to be published in early April by Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Ritter says he worked closely with a senior agency
official to plan ``the largest and most complex inspections''
beginning in 1992. He also says that ``CIA covert paramilitary
operators'' were placed on teams that searched for evidence of
Iraqi chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman, James Foley, did not deny a
central element of Ritter's book _ that the CIA placed employees on
the teams and that they helped plan the inspections. But Foley
suggested that there was nothing surprising or new in the
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made no bones about the fact that we have helped
UNSCOM in its efforts to uncover Iraqi programs of weapons of mass
destruction,'' he said, without noting specifically that the CIA
was among the government agencies that provided assistance. ``The
inspectors we provided to UNSCOM were provided at UNSCOM's
request.''
</P>
<P>
   That point was also made by Ewen Buchanan, a spokesman for the
commission in New York. Although he would not discuss whether
officers from the agency were on the teams, Buchanan said the
commission routinely asked the United States and other governments
to provide them with arms inspectors who had specific technical
skills, some of whom may have come from intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what agency they are from that's important to us,''
Buchanan said. ``It's the skills they bring.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department appeared to speaking for the intelligence
agency, which declined to make a separate comment about Ritter and
his book. The Defense Department, which demanded as recently as
last week that Ritter turn over a copy of the book for a
prepublication security review, also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ekeus, who left the special commission in 1997 and is now the
Swedish ambassador to Washington, said the intelligence agency was
never closely involved in the details of planning inspections.
``UNSCOM plans were never discussed with any of the foreigners,''
he said. ``By that I mean non-UNSCOM people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekeus, too, suggested that there was no surprise over the
presence of CIA employees, because they provided needed expertise.
``We got assistance from many countries and we did not investigate
the people whom the governments provided,'' he said. ``We asked for
the best experts governments could provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contacts with the U.S. government and requests for help
were completely innocent. The people sent were more nerds than a
lot of musclemen, and they had no weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   He discounted Ritter's speculation that the agency may have
coordinated the timing of the coup attempt in 1996 and the presence
of an inspection team that included nine CIA employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been sheer coincidence,'' he said. ``It would
have been odd if there hadn't been a coup attempt at one time or
another _ since there were many of them, apparently _ when UNSCOM
people were in the field inspecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Ritter's motive in making such an allegation, Ekeus said,
``Maybe it's to sell a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter has said he will refuse to provide the Pentagon with a
copy of ``Endgame,'' raising at least the possibility that the
Defense Department could go to court to block further distribution
of the book.
</P>
<P>
   A former Marine intelligence officer, Ritter was under contract
to the Pentagon while he worked for UNSCOM, and the Defense
Department has argued that under his contract, Ritter is required
to submit to the review. He resigned from the United Nations last
year, contending that the United States had tried to hinder the
inspectors' work out of fear of a confrontation with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Matthew L. Lifflander, said in an interview that the
State Department attack was a continuation of the Clinton
administration ``policy of denigrating Scott Ritter because they
are embarrassed by his truthful allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifflander said that nothing in the book compromised American
security and Ritter was not required to submit his book to the
Pentagon, because his Defense Department contract expired last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in there about sources and methods of
intelligence that isn't already in the public domain,'' the lawyer
said. ``Anything he says in there, Saddam Hussein already knows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
