<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CAMPUS-KIDNAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN GANG FREES SOCCER STAR'S FATHER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Kidnappers on Tuesday released Alvaro Campos
Gonzalez, the father of Mexico's most popular soccer star, after
six days, and he returned to his home in Acapulco, authorities and
relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican attorney general's office said in a statement that
Campos Gonzalez, 66, appeared at 8:20 a.m. at a police checkpoint
on a coastal highway 11 miles northwest of Acapulco in Guerrero
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our father is here with us, safe and sound,'' his son, Jorge
Campos Navarrete, the goalkeeper for Mexico's national team, told
reporters hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Campos Navarrete said he ``did not believe'' his family had paid
a ransom, according to radio reports. But Mexican television and
radio reporters who cited police sources said that a ransom of an
undisclosed size had in fact been paid.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the men carrying AK-47 rifles who seized Campos
Gonzalez on Wednesday remained a mystery. No group has assumed
responsibility for the abduction.
</P>
<P>
   But Campos Gonzalez, who made statements on behalf of Mexico's
governing party before disputed Guerrero elections on Feb. 7, told
the police that he was held in a village in an area of the Guerrero
mountains in which leftist guerrillas have been active.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jenkins, an independent Los Angeles-based kidnapping
expert, said that most abductions of prominent people carried out
by professional criminals seeking ransom last longer than six days
because setting up negotiations take time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
