</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-KING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL HOUSE WRITINGS HELP LEAD TO WHITE SUPREMACIST'S CONVICTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See JASPER-TRIAL, which will be filed shortly.) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ John William ``Bill'' King just might have
written himself on to death row.
</P>
<P>
   When jurors found the 24-year-old ex-con and avowed white
supremacist guilty Tuesday of capital murder in the brutal dragging
death of a disabled black man, it was his own writings that helped
earn that conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It killed us,'' said court-appointed attorney C. Haden
``Sonny'' Cribbs of his client's jail house writings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to cost us and I asked him not to do it,''
Cribbs said, slowly shaking his head as he waited for the jury to
come back with its verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The same jury will decide, probably Thursday, if King will be
sent to death row to await execution or if he will be sentenced to
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In prison letters to girlfriends, notes to a co-defendant and
written statements to reporters, King handed prosecutors leads to
evidence they didn't even know about.
</P>
<P>
   In November, King sent a letter to The Dallas Morning News,
claiming that he was with two buddies when one of them picked up
James Byrd Jr. King wrote that one of his friends, co-defendant
Shawn Berry, drove him and Lawrence Russell Brewer to their Jasper
apartment before Berry killed Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter did much more harm than good, Cribbs said.
``Before that letter there was nothing putting him (King) in that
car,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors found King's cigarette lighter at the scene of the
murder, as well as cigarettes with King's DNA on them. ``I could
have tried to do something with those,'' Cribbs said, adding that
he might have been able to convince a jury that those items were in
the truck that dragged Byrd, even though King might not have been
there.
</P>
<P>
   But in the letter King admitted that he was in the truck when he
and his friends picked up Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   The jury was also treated to King's prison manifesto _ a
collection of writings, including letters, applications and even
bylaws of an organization he called ``Texas Rebel Soldiers.'' The
idea for the group, an offshoot of a Ku Klux Klan group, was
conceived while King was in the Beto I prison unit between 1995-97
in Tennessee Colony.
</P>
<P>
   In those writings, which he took with him when he was paroled,
he refers to Aryan pride and makes repeated racist remarks. He even
outlined plans to kidnap a black person, take him to the woods and
kill him. Several times King alluded to something big that would
take place within the organization on July 4, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   By that date, however, he was already in jail, charged with
Byrd's murder.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also saw letters King wrote from prison to a Jasper
teen-age girl he called, ``my Aryan princess.'' The letters
explained that he was a ``peckerwood,'' a white guy in prison, and
again outlined his plans for life on the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   While King sat mainly motionless during the week of testimony,
his biggest reaction came Monday when a letter he wrote in Jasper
County Jail and passed to co-defendant Brewer _ a ``kite'' in
jailhouse lingo _ was read into testimony.
</P>
<P>
   King shifted in his chair and scowled.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many such notes between King and Brewer, who were
held in separate cells. Their messenger was an inmate who worked as
a jail trusty, and who, unknown to King, passed the notes to
sheriff's jailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting these so fast at one point that we didn't even
have time to read them,'' said Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles
of King's jailhouse ``kites.''
</P>
<P>
   In the message King wrote to Brewer he talked of blood on their
clothes. ``I don't think any blood was on my pants or sweatshirt,
but I think my sandals may have had some dark brown substance on
the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they didn't know about the sandals until they
read the jailhouse note. They later found the shoes in a clothes
hamper.
</P>
<P>
   If King had any regret about Byrd's murder, it wasn't evident in
his letter to Brewer. He didn't sound like a man wrongly accused of
capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously though, bro,'' he wrote, ``reguardless (sic) of the
outcome of this, we have made history and shall die proudly
remembered if need be.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Brack Jones said King has long held the idea
that the trial outcome is inevitable. ``He thinks it's a conspiracy
against him,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a half hour before announcing the guilty verdict, the
jury asked to see just one piece of evidence: King's ``kite'' to
Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   His signature with his jailhouse nickname of ``Possum'' _ with
the s's drawn as Nazi storm trooper symbols _ couldn't have helped.
Neither could a symbol of three K's joined to form a triangle,
symbolizing the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   And if that wasn't enough, there was a simple, ``Seig Heil (Hail
Victory).''
</P>
<P>
   But for King, it was hardly victory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
