u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-MEETS-SPI &LR;      02-23 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-MEETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPS OF UPCOMING FILMS WOW DISNEY SHAREHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ More than 1,000 shareholders and other guests of the
Walt Disney Co. packed Seattle's ornate 5th Avenue Theater Tuesday
to listen to dissident sharholder proposals and see Michael Eisner
preview Disney's new Internet service, www.go.com.
</P>
<P>
   What really wowed them were clips of Disney's upcoming animated
features, ``Tarzan,'' ``Toy Story 2,'' ``Dinosaur'' and ``Fantasia
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Disney's original ``Fantasia,'' produced in 1940,
remember a scene of dinosaurs fleeing a blocky, square-jawed
Tyrannosaurus rex. The movie ``Dinosaur,'' to be released on May
31, 2000, has a similar attack. But this T. rex. is a glistening,
lifelike lizard whose realism chews a hole in the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the new ``Fantasia 2000,'' to be introduced at the
turn of the millennium, has a segment reminiscent of the original:
a volcano monster set to Stravinsky's ``Firebird.'' Other segments
include a flamingo with a yo-yo, dancing to Saint-Saens' ``Carnival
of the Animals,'' and the classic tale, ``The Steadfast Tin
Soldier'' interpreted to Shostakovich's Piano Concerto No. 2.
``Fantasia 2000'' has six new segments and three restored ones,
including ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner also showed scenes from ``Toy Story 2'' and ``Tarzan,''
both coming to screens this year.
</P>
<P>
   He also announced that ``A Bug's Life'' has grossed more than
$200 million overseas, and that ``Mulan,'' the animated feature
based on the Chinese legend, opened yesterday in China. ``That
nation only allows the release of 10 non-Chinese films a year,'' he
said. That they chose ``Mulan,'' he said, ``portends well for our
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner also clicked the audience through screens of www.go.com,
the new Internet service developed with Infoseek, a company 40
percent owned by Disney, and with Seattle-based Starwave. ``We are
putting the full power of our company behind Go,'' Eisner said. Go
(which looks a lot like Microsoft's www.msn.com) has a button
called Go Guardian, which filters out material deemed objectionable
to kids.
</P>
<P>
   Disney owns a galaxy of other things, from Disneylands and other
theme parks to the Disney Channel, a Disney cruise line, Club
Disney, the Disney Stores, as well as Touchstone studios (which
produced ``Armageddon,'' last year's No. 1 grossing film) and
Capital Cities/ABC, which includes ESPN. All these things brought
in $23 billion in revenues in the year ended Sept. 30, and produced
a profit of $1.85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers were hardly changed from a year earlier, which the
company said reflected the rising costs of producing films and the
economic downturn in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   A company so large often has controversy. Disney had its share
in three shareholder resolutions, all of them opposed by
management.
</P>
<P>
   The one that came closest to passing was a resolution that the
board not adopt a poison pill without a vote of shareholders. A
poison pill is a measure to dilute a raider's interest and thereby
thwart his bid. Poison pills have been criticized as being
pro-management but not pro-shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which fended off a raid in 1984, long ago adopted a
poison pill that expires June 30. Last year, a shareholder measure
against it got 43 percent of the vote. This year, the company said
it will will let the poison pill expire. But directors wanted to
keep the power to create a new one without consulting shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-poison pill measure failed again, 38 percent yes, 60
percent no. But the spokesman for the measure, James Joyce of the
Communications Workers of America, attracted more applause than the
spokesman for the company, Senior Executive Vice President Sanford
Litvack.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure opposed by management was that wages, working
conditions and union rights at 18,000 foreign factories supplying
Disney be monitored by independent religious and human-rights
groups. Several speakers praised Disney's code of conduct for its
suppliers, but said the montoring needed to be done by people who
were local and independent.
</P>
<P>
   Their resolution said that The Gap, Liz Claiborne, Mattel and
Nike had accepted the principle of independent monitoring, and said
Disney should accept it too.
</P>
<P>
   Global Exchange, a San Francisco advocacy group, said it found
workers at four factories in China earning between 13.5 and 36
cents per hour producing Disney products. Basic survival, the group
said, required a wage of 87 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Litvack said the company has ``no quarrel'' with the
campaigners' goals. He said management is working with independent
groups in certain places. But the company does not want to delegate
the task to them, system-wide.
</P>
<P>
   Disney also objected to the ``living wage'' proposal. The
company's rule is that suppliers pay either the official minimum
wage or the local market rate, whichever is higher. But Litvack
said it is not appropriate ``to attempt to set wage rates at 18,000
sites around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which won 9 percent of the vote in 1997 and 8
percent in 1998, won 8 percent again. It was opposed by 85 percent
of votes cast, the rest abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders also rejected, 6 percent to 92 percent, a proposal
for a special report on the company's efforts to solve the Year
2000 computer problem. Litvack said Disney has 400 employees and
400 consultants working on the problem, and that it expects to
invest $140 million in capital and spend another $120 million to
deal with it. Sending a separate report to shareholders would cost
$1.5 million, he said, which ``would be better spent on the problem
itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
