<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWA-WRECKAGE-ART-1000     02-23 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-WRECKAGE-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERMANENT HOME IS SOUGHT FOR WRECKAGE OF TWA FLIGHT 800 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md., Va., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The crash of TWA Flight 800, already the subject of
the nation's biggest air crash investigation and the world's
largest aircraft reconstruction, has now led to a looming question
as the National Transportation Safety Board tries to wrap up its
inquiry: what to do with the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said when we built it, these things never go away,'' said
Peter Goelz, the board's managing director.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board is seeking a permanent home for the wreckage,
where investigators could go to recheck their conclusions and where
future air safety investigators could be trained in areas ranging
from metallurgy to reconstruction techniques.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the board will issue a request for proposals to build
a hangar to store the reconstruction, which is somewhat less than
half of the Boeing 747's fuselage. Since the crash in July 1996,
the pieces salvaged from the ocean floor have been stored at a
former Grumman hangar at Calverton, N.Y., which has been closely
guarded. But the town of Riverhead, which owns the hangar, would
like to lure some industry there instead. And the board is feeling
the weight of $4.5 million in annual rent and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Already, three parties are interested.
</P>
<P>
   The airport in Hagerstown, Md.; the College of Aeronautics, near
La Guardia International Airport in Queens, N.Y., and the Virginia
campus of George Washington University are all competing to adopt
the wreckage. Each would build a structure large enough for the
reconstruction, which is about 114 feet long including the
scaffolding, 48 feet wide and 30 feet high, and lease it back to
the board.
</P>
<P>
   The College of Aeronautics trains aviation mechanics and
engineers, and George Washington's school of engineering has an
automobile crash test program and would expand into airplane crash
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would save the taxpayers money and would provide a very
important educational tool,'' said James E. Hall, chairman of the
safety board. The board, which intends to issue a final report on
the crash this year and to move the wreckage immediately afterward,
would not give up control over the wreckage nor allow it to be open
for display to the public, but would make it much more widely
available to aviation safety experts and students.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, which was on a flight from Kennedy International
Airport to Paris, exploded off Long Island a few minutes after
takeoff. The safety board believes the reason was a flaw of some
kind in the center fuel tank and has been conducting tests to
determine where in the tank it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever gets the wreckage would also keep it available for use
by the parties in lawsuits. For example, Mitch Baumeister, a
Manhattan lawyer who represents the families of 21 passengers in
suits against TWA, said on Tuesday that he was looking forward to
having juries tour the reconstruction, to prove no missile was
involved in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the families who lost passengers on the plane say they
like the idea of preserving the wreckage, said Aurelie Becker,
president of the Families of TWA Flight 800 Association. Her
19-year-old daughter, Michelle, was on board. She said the families
had previously discussed whether the Smithsonian Institution might
take the wreckage at an annex it is planning near Dulles
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   (FOLLOWING GRAPHS OPTIONAL)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very emotional experience to see this wreckage and know
that there were people inside of it, when you see the devastation
that was caused,'' Ms. Becker, a nurse, said. ``It makes one think
of your humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's grounding, sort of,'' she said in a telephone interview
from her workplace, a nursing home in St. Petersburg, Fla. ``A lot
of people in our day and age need that emotional grounding.'' And,
she said, if more people saw the wreckage, there would be more
public sentiment for better air safety.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hurd, vice president of the organization, said in an
interview, ``They should get some decent use out of it.'' And, he
said, when his grandchildren are old enough, he would like to take
them to see the plane on which their uncle, his son Jamie, died.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Carven, whose sister and nephew died on the plane, said
the wreckage had a magnetic quality for him. Visiting the
reconstruction in the hangar on Long Island, he said, ``You felt
like the people who were on the plane were somehow just present.''
</P>
<P>
   Carven said that his brother and sister-in-law had a baby two
weeks ago. ``I'm sure when he gets to be old enough, my brother
would want to take him and show him what happened to his aunt,''
Carven said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL GRAPHS)
</P>
<P>
   The schools are emphasizing the educational aspects, including
the possibility of a related deal with the safety board, to provide
courses in aircraft technology for safety board investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in just housing this reconstruction,''
said John C. Fitzpatrick, president of the School of Aeronautics,
who said he had been approached by the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were just that, I would not have encouraged them to come
back to talk to us,'' he said. ``The fact is that this was a
tragedy, that they believe they can partner with an educational
institution such as ourselves and develop an aviation safety
accident prevention program, and that interests the college a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The school would build a new building on its six-and-a-half-acre
campus, across the Grand Central Parkway from La Guardia Airport,
if a deal could be struck, he said; it would include classrooms and
possibly laboratories, in addition to the wreckage. He added that
for traveling investigators, the campus was convenient to La
Guardia and within walking distance of hotels.
</P>
<P>
   At George Washington University, Irwin Price, the executive dean
of the university's campus in Ashburn, Va., said, ``We view it as a
research thing rather than as a museum piece.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We have a fairly large program in transportation safety and
automobile safety,'' he said. ``We do some stuff in aviation safety
already, and we would add to work we're already doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The engineering department makes computer models of cars to
predict their crash performance, he said, and would like to do the
same for 747s.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction was designed to separate into three pieces
and would probably move by barge.
</P>
<P>
   Wreckage from major crashes is usually kept for years by an
airline's insurance company; as with a car, when the insurance
company pays the claim, it owns the wreck. But in this crash, TWA
and its insurance company declined to pay for the cost of salvage,
so the federal government did; now the government owns the debris.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
