<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-KLESK024-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hitting, switch to first not troubling Klesko
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Ryan Klesko came into the Braves'
clubhouse to start his spring workouts Tuesday the same as always _
smiling, patting teammates on the back and spouting tales of big
fish and five-foot waves.
</P>
<P>
   He showed no visible signs that he should feel especially
burdened with his recent assignment _ taking over first base for
Andres Galarraga _ or relieved that his name no longer is coupled
with the word trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sid (Bream) was here and I was back up in Richmond, it
was `trade,''' said Klesko, who is in the second year of a
four-year contract worth $20.5 million. ``And then when Fred
(McGriff) was here, it was `trade.' I don't worry about it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I used to think I'd hate to leave. I
worried: `Who am I going to get traded to?' If it happens, it
happens. I've been blessed enough to be in this organization for 10
seasons. If it all ends today, what a great time I've had with the
Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   While the attitude was great, the body was sore. For the past
four days, since Galarraga was diagnosed with lymphoma, Klesko has
been fielding ground balls in North Palm Beach, where he worked out
with some players at the spring training complex of the Expos and
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Soreness is the only problem, Klesko said, because the move from
left field, where he's been most of his major-league career, to
first base, where he played in high school and the minor leagues,
is totally natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The angle of throws is different,'' Klesko said. ``I'm used to
throwing straight over the top. But that's about it. ... I've
always felt comfortable with (first base). I'll be fine. I'll do my
best; that's all I can really do.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Braves have scouted Cincinnati first baseman Hal
Morris and are rumored to be interested in Kansas City first
baseman Jeff King, all moves appear to be on hold. General manager
John Schuerholz wants to see how Klesko does at first before making
any decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Cox liked what he saw Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the first two ground balls Klesko took
Tuesday morning _ one was out of his reach in the hole, and one
bounced up and hit his shin _ Klesko fielded everything cleanly and
got some encouraging cheers from his infield teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll do anything we want him to,'' Cox said. ``He's got a
great attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the Braves want to see a change is in Klesko's offense.
Last year was a disappointment; he started on pace to hit 26 home
runs with 94 RBIs, but finished with 18 home runs and 70 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time he had hit fewer than 20 home runs as a
regular in left field. The RBI total represented the second season
in a row Klesko's numbers have declined, after getting 93 in 1996
and 84 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko's 1998 season took a bad turn when he missed nine games
after having surgery to remove his appendix on June 29. He had only
five home runs and 23 RBIs after the surgery. Klesko was hitting
.382 for the month of June when he had the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start finding my swing again until the last month of
the season,'' Klesko said. ``I probably pushed myself too hard to
come back. I definitely wanted to get my swing back for the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   His finished with a respectable .274 average, cut his strikeouts
by more than half and hit a career-high 29 doubles. But against
left-handers, Klesko hit .213 with no home runs and drove in four
runs. With runners in scoring position, he hit .217 with three home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves hope new hitting coach Don Baylor will improve those
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he won't think too much,'' Cox said. ``Ryan's always
been a natural hitter. I think sometimes you do start thinking too
much. You over-analyze sometimes. Maybe this will be a positive for
his hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko said it's just a matter of good health.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stay healthy, get my at-bats, I can get hits,''
Klesko said. ``No doubt in my mind. ... I'll go out and give it my
best. That's all I've ever done for this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
