<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atwater meeting unlikely
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons have virtually exited the market for free
agent safety Steve Atwater before really getting into it.
</P>
<P>
   Atwater, who was drafted in 1989 by current Atlanta coach Dan
Reeves when he was in Denver, met with the Chiefs Tuesday and will
meet with the Jets today and the Eagles Thursday. The Jets are
especially interested in Atwater, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons officials say they are not likely to meet with the
eight-time Pro Bowl selection, but they are interested in a couple
of Reeves' former players with the Giants. Free agent offensive
guard Greg Bishop is expected to work out for the team today.
Recently released New York receiver Chris Calloway might visit by
the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway met Tuesday with Redskins officials. Peter Schaffer
represents Calloway and Atlanta free agent cornerback Ronnie
Bradford, who is on a vacation cruise. ``I haven't talked to
(Falcons general manager) Harold (Richardson) about (Atwater),''
Schaffer said. ``We're talking mostly about Calloway.''
</P>
<P>
   STRONG CONNECTION
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons hired a new assistant strength and conditioning
coach in Rocky Colburn, who for the past four years has been head
football coach at Bibb County High School in Centreville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn, 35, was Academic All-SEC as a defensive back at Alabama
at the same time that current Falcons strength and conditioning
coach Al Miller was there.
</P>
<P>
   Colburn coached one year at Samford before serving as assistant
strength and conditioning coach at Alabama for five years, then
coaching in high school for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Former assistant strength and conditioning coach Tim Jorgensen
left the Falcons to take the head strength and conditioning job
with the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Schad Freeman, cut by the Falcons last summer as
an undrafted rookie out of Valdosta State, has been allocated to
the World League and will play for Berlin. Freeman, added to the
80-man roster recently, is the only Falcon going to Europe, though
the team might send a couple of future signees there. ... Assistant
public-relations director Frank Kleha is serving as interim
director after Charlie Taylor resigned Monday. The organization
will interview candidates to replace Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
