A6618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TIGER24-COX     02-23 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods on top of the world
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Since he stood eye level to a ballwasher,
Tiger Woods' timing for high drama always has been impressive. But
not since his stunning Masters victory in 1997 has he performed so
appropriately for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it appeared as though everyone from Johnny Miller to
Zell Miller figured that No. 2 David Duval had a rightful claim to
Woods' No. 1 spot in the World Golf Rankings, Woods provided golf's
equivalent of an ``in-your-face'' at the recent Buick Invitational
in San Diego, then followed it a week later with serious contention
at the Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   With his first victory since Atlanta's BellSouth Classic last
May and a tie for second in Los Angeles, Woodsbuffed up his
credentials in the No. 1 discussion.
</P>
<P>
   His two-week performance fuels a Duval-Woods rivalry leading to
the Masters and sets the storyline for the $5 million inaugural
World Match Play Golf Championships, which begins today at the La
Costa resort. Tiger Woods is expected to ignite his game in
individual match play, his specialty, on a familiar course. Woods,
who grew up in Los Angeles, has had many memorable rounds at La
Costa, located north of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Excited by a course-record 62 in the third round at San Diego _
after scrambling to make the Friday cut _ Woods went from ``what
have you done lately?'' to back in control, largely through a
revived putter that has improved his confidence. Had he made a few
more putts in the Nissan at Riviera, Woods would be entering the
Match Play with two victories.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had heard the talk about Duval being the best player in
the world since the fall of 1997, and many golf people think his
game's revival was more than pure coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think Woods didn't notice all the people saying he
didn't deserve to be No. 1 in the World Rankings,'' CBS-TV analyst
Peter Kostis observed in his weekly column for GolfWeb. ``He heard
it, and he didn't like it. But his win (at San Diego), even with
David Duval skiing in Idaho, will only increase the intensity of
their rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, arguably golf's greatest draw, has not been this excited
about the game in a while. Because he plays with such high
standards, his accomplishments often are taken for granted. He tied
for fifth at the Mercedes Championship and tied for third at
Phoenix. He was a stroke from tying Mark O'Meara in the British
Open last July, and he got a victory in the BellSouth in Atlanta,
two seconds and two thirds. It's newsworthy when he is not in
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately for me, I haven't been winning as much as David
has,'' Woods said. ``I haven't been playing as well, either. ...
Hopefully, my game's peaking toward the World Golf. My short game
has improved where I don't mind missing the green as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while match play is where Woods carved his
competitive reputation _ three USGA junior titles followed by three
U.S. Amateurs _ the format is not one of Duval's favorites. But,
then again, maybe that's to be expected from a guy who shot 59 last
month. Such a score could be wasted in match play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the biggest fan of it, no,'' Duval said.``You never
get what you deserve in match play. You don't. You could have
conceivably the No. 1 player in the world shoot 6-under par and get
beat that day, and the No. 2 player in the world might shoot 3-over
and win, and that's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval considers it ``highly likely'' that this week's winner
won't be the player who plays the best golf. One bad day, he said,
``and you're gone _ you're out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as any rivalry with Woods, neither player speaks of one
unless asked, and both admit to playing the field, not a particular
foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great for him and me,'' Woods said, ``but I don't
see that happening, because there are just too many good players
out here. It's not just a handful of guys who can win. ... You
can't just eliminate all of the good ones that have been there so
long and just say Tiger and David are going to carry the torch.
There's probably 50 guys who can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval said, ``I think it's flattering toward me as a player to
try to be anointed the one who is going to try to challenge Tiger
in the future years. However, although I haven't played out here a
long time, I've played out here long enough to realize that there
are many players out here who are just as able as I am or Tiger
Woods is to play and win golf tournaments. So I don't focus on
one-on-one rivalries too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Duval's incredible run might have helped Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, with the way David has performed in the last two
years, some of the expectations are now placed on David, so I think
that takes a little of the burden off Tiger,'' said Mark O'Meara,
Woods' good friend and 1998 player of the year. ``But deep down
inside, I think Tiger likes being No. 1, wants to be No. 1 and
wants to win a lot of golf tournaments. That's my sense of Tiger
Woods. I don't see him backing off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw, the Ryder Cup captain, called Duval immediately
after his 59 at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, asking that he be
careful during a ski trip that followed the record round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't do anything but help golf,'' Crenshaw said about the
Woods-Duval race. ``They're both incredible players, and I think
they're going to push each other to be even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods drives from the gallery on his second shot on the
11th at the Riviera Country Club in Los Angeles during the 1999
Nissan Open Sunday, Feb. 21, 1999. (AP Photo/Michael Caulfield)
</P>
<P>
   David Duval hits his tee shot on the 7th hole at East Lake Golf
Club in Atlanta during final round play in The Tour Championship
Sunday, Nov. 1, 1998. Duval finished the season as the tour's top
money winner. (AP Photo/Erik S. Lesser)
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL CAULFIELD / Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   Perfect match: Tiger Woods is well suited for the World Match
Play Golf Championships at La Costa Resort. Woods won three USGA
junior titles and three U.S. Amateurs in match play and grew up
near La Costa.
</P>
<P>
   ERIK S. LESSER / Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   Not his style: David Duval is not a fan of match play, saying
``you never get what you deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   TOURNAMENT AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   -- Where: La Costa Resort, Carlsbad, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   -- When: Today through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Field: Top 64 players, according to Official World Golf
Rankings.
</P>
<P>
   -- Layout: Par-72, 7,022 yards.
</P>
<P>
   -- Format: Single-elimination match play, beginning with 32
first-round matches today and concluding with 36-hole final Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Purse: $5 million ($25,000 minimum, $1 million to winner).
</P>
<P>
   -- TV: Today 2-6 p.m. ESPN; Thurs. 2-6 p.m. ESPN; Friday 3-7
p.m. ESPN; Sat. 2-6 p.m. ABC; Sun. 2-6 p.m. ABC.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Notes, pairings E3
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
