<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES24-CO     02-23 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan absent from Braves spring training
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Spring training began in earnest on
Tuesday as the rest of the Braves position players _ with the
exception of a few _ arrived to begin the first full-squad
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable absentee was right fielder Brian Jordan, an
offseason free-agent acquisition from St. Louis, who was informed
on Monday night that his mother was sick. Jordan, who had been
working out with the Braves for several days in Orlando, flew to
Baltimore and might not return for several days. Manager Bobby Cox
spoke to him on Tuesday and wasn't sure when he could return.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Gerald Williams did not report to camp, because of
personal problems, Cox said. It's not certain when he will arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Adrian Manzano, a nonroster invitee to camp, is late
arriving from Mexico because of visa problems but is expected to
arrive today. Catcher Eddie Perez was at home Tuesday, still
recovering from surgery as a result of a foul ball in the groin.
</P>
<P>
   HUNTER RETURN
</P>
<P>
   If spring is a time for rebirth and fresh starts, then how
fitting an arrival is this for Brian Hunter?
</P>
<P>
   After Andres Galarraga's cancer news, Hunter signed a
minor-league contract and was invited to Braves camp. He's got an
opportunity to make the team as a backup to Ryan Klesko at first
base.
</P>
<P>
   After going through four teams in the last four years before
getting released by the Cardinals last August, Hunter has returned
to the Braves 20 pounds lighter, five years older and wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so young when I was here the first time,'' said Hunter,
31. ``I got sort of complacent. I thought it was easy. It ended up
blowing up in my face a little bit. I know what I've done; I
corrected it, and I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter played on the Braves World Series teams of 1991 and 1992
before leaving after the 1993 season. Since then he's had only one
season, 1994, where he contributed regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been to the bottom yet, but I know where the bottom
is,'' Hunter said. ``I wasn't at the top (in Atlanta), but I was
one of the players who contributed to helping this team win. That's
what I want to be again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter had to have all four of his wisdom teeth removed on
Friday or he said he would have arrived on Sunday. He's fully
recovered except he has to watch what he eats this week. He can't
chew gum, sunflower seeds or spit _ trouble for any baseball
player.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHART TESTS SHOULDER
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart took his first swings off the pitching machine
Tuesday, another step in his rehabilitation from surgery on his
nonthrowing shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt fine,'' Lockhart said. ``But it's not going to be sore
until tomorrow anyway. . . It was nice to do something different.''
</P>
<P>
   GUILLEN-GALARRAGA CONNECTION
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Ozzie Guillen spent the last two days before reporting
to spring training at Andres Galarraga's house in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   As for his friend's spirits, Guillen said, ``Great.
Unbelievable. I walked in, and I was worried about the way he was
going to act, but he was acting normal. He knows what he has to
face. He's ready for it. He knows he's going to beat it. He knows
he's going to be OK. And that's the most important thing. . . .
Maybe inside it was a big deal, but he didn't show it to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen said Galarraga is en route to Chicago and Baltimore to
search out the best possible treatment and will begin the
chemotherapy not long after.
</P>
<P>
   A. JONES VS. CHICKEN POX
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones had a bout with chicken pox last month, after a
trip to Miami for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even walk the first two weeks,'' Jones said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he has fully recovered and worked himself back into shape by
working out at Turner Field for several weeks, hitting and running.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
