<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADER WARNS CANDIDATES ON ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also REPUBS-TAXES, REPUBS-MODERATES) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a stern lecture to prospective presidential
candidates in 2000, Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican
Party, warned on Tuesday that he would publicly rebuke any
contender who personally attacked another Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not let it become personal or nasty or mean in spirit,''
Nicholson said in a speech in Des Moines, Iowa, the state that
traditionally holds the first presidential caucuses. ``Even in the
heat of the struggle, make sure you don't confuse people about who
the real adversary is. Because if you sow division within
Republican ranks, because if you forget who and what all
Republicans are fighting for and fighting against, you will pay a
price _ I promise you.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a highly unusual statement at a time when most
candidates have not formally declared their intentions, people
close to Nicholson said he was trying to tamp down the sniping at
Gov. George Bush of Texas. Bush has not stated his intentions, but
he is running far ahead in most early polls. Several of his
prospective rivals have already sought to knock him down by
questioning his credentials and his ``compassionate conservative''
slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican advisers said Nicholson timed the warning to
precede the appearance of several presidential prospects _ but not
Bush _ at a gathering of the California Republican Party this
weekend in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, though, Nicholson said such planning
gave him ``too much credit.'' He said some mailings from Republican
candidates were ``tougher than I would have liked,'' but he would
not identify those that bothered him. And he insisted that he did
not believe that any of the criticism of Bush or of other
candidates was thus far out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Several people close to Nicholson said they thought Haley
Barbour, the former party chairman, erred in the 1996 campaign by
not publicly intervening to halt Steve Forbes' multimillion-dollar
advertising attacks on Bob Dole and other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to avoid a bloodbath,'' Nicholson said in the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to Nicholson, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
was even more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concern that's beginning to curdle into unrestrained
terror,'' the adviser said, ``that we're going to have a replay of
'96: Gore raises his $30 million in 90 days, banks it until he goes
on TV _ and blasts our guy. And the Republican nominee emerges
bloody and broke.''
</P>
<P>
   Several campaigns have been frustrated by the outpouring of
support for Bush. At least 13 of the 31 Republican governors, who
are meeting here for a convention of the National Governors'
Association, have said privately or publicly that they intend to
back Bush.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Gov. Marc Racicot of Montana, who has helped rally
support for Bush, said Racicot would in the next several days
announce that more than half the Republican governors were backing
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Such early support from so many governors _ especially for a
politician who is untested nationally _ is a testament to how many
of the chief executives think Bush would be a winning candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted that he did not coordinate the outpouring. ``I
didn't come here and say, `Well, gosh, let's round up a bunch of
governors,''' he told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
