<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PUZZLING OUT TAX-CUT PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (See also REPUBS-MODERATES, REPUBS-NICHOLSON) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans appeared uncertain Tuesday over what
kind of tax-cut policy they would offer the public as House leaders
backed off their earlier support for a 10 percent across-the-board
cut and the Senate began mulling a budget blueprint that could cut
tax rates by as much as 15 percent phased in over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The result was confusion over an important election issue that
demonstrated how difficult it could be for Republican leaders,
particularly in the House, to pass any legislation because they
have a slim majority of just a half-dozen votes.
</P>
<P>
   They had been so eager to pass the eye-catching 10 percent tax
cut that they designated it earlier this year as one of their top
three legislative priorities, along with saving Social Security and
improving education. But a revolt by a dozen moderates, who prefer
smaller tax cuts, and several conservatives, who prefer to spend
any surplus on eliminating the so-called marriage penalty, has
forced leaders to rethink the entire matter.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said in a brief interview
Tuesday: ``There's a lot of ways we need to look at tax cuts. That
may be one of them. But it may be a combination of things as well.
We have the marriage penalty we're talking about, we have the
earnings limit for seniors on Social Security, we have capital
gains, we have a lot of different tax cuts that are out there. I'm
not saying one is absolute.''
</P>
<P>
   Even spokesmen for the Republican who originally proposed the 10
percent cut _ Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, the chairman of the Budget
Committee who is also planning to run for president _ suggested
that it would not fly. ``We're acknowledging reality while at the
same time not giving up our position,'' said Terry Holt, a
spokesman for Kasich.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the tax-writing Ways and
Means Committee, insisted that the party was united in wanting to
cut taxes. He said it was important to return money to taxpayers
because otherwise Washington would spend it. ``If you leave it up
here,'' Archer said, ``it's going to end up being spent on foreign
aid.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Capitol, Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
who is chairman of the Budget Committee, discussed his tentative
budget blueprint privately with his colleagues. He suggested tax
cuts could range between $787 billion and $900 billion over the
next decade but not begin until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Domenici predicted there would be enough money to include
both an across-the-board tax cut and some of the smaller, targeted
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said that
cutting tax rates, not just targeting cuts to certain groups, was
important to expanding the economy. But he put the best face on the
party's puzzle, saying: ``Any time we can have a discussion about
which tax cuts we should put in place, I'm happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
