<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-MARKET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN HINTS OF POSSIBLE INTEREST RATE HIKE LATER IN YEAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After eight years of growth, the U.S. economy is
showing signs of becoming ``stretched,'' with a potentially
``overvalued'' stock market and a labor market tight enough to
spark inflation, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No evidence for a return of inflation has yet surfaced,
Greenspan said. But by voicing his concerns, the nation's central
banker hinted at a possible interest rate hike down the road,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, in his semiannual report to Congress on the state of
the nation's economy, told the Senate Banking Committee,
``Americans can justifiably feel proud of their recent economic
achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   The inflation rate fell to its lowest level in decades last
year. Unemployment dropped to the lowest rate since 1970. And the
economy grew at a robust 4 percent, topping off the year with a 5
1/2 percent growth rate in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan predicted continued healthy growth this year, ``though
likely with a slower pace of economic expansion and a slightly
higher rate of overall inflation than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy-makers are looking for growth of about 2.5 to 3
percent this year, with a modest inflation rate of 2 to 2.5
percent, up from 1.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy has become less inflation prone than in the past,
so that the chances of an inflationary breakout arguably are, at
least for now, less than they would have been under similar
conditions in earlier cycles,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman, however, reiterated concerns about the
astronomical levels of some stock prices, although he carefully
dodged an opportunity to repeat his now-infamous December 1996 line
about investor's ``irrational exuberance.''
</P>
<P>
   And he noted that inflation remained tame last year, in large
part, because of a plunge in oil prices. While devastating to
Houston's energy-dependent economy, the collapse of crude prices
was a boon to many industries struggling to export to a world
largely mired in recession.
</P>
<P>
   That drop in oil prices, Greenspan warned, was a one-time event
unlikely to repeat itself anytime soon: ``These prices are not
likely to fall further, and they could begin to rise as some Asian
economies revive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan obviously remains worried about the tight job market,
calling it a ``critical upside risk to the inflation outlook.'' He
and other economists have been scratching their heads for months
trying to figure out why the dearth of unemployed workers looking
for jobs has not translated into greater pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said Greenspan seemed to suggest the Fed may have
overdone it last fall, when it cut interest rates three times in an
effort to shield the U.S. economy from the effects of economic
crises in Asia, Russia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers were particularly concerned last year about the
economic fallout from financial problems in Brazil _ Latin
America's largest economy _ but the feared economic contagion has
been quite limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Reserve must continue to evaluate ... whether the
full extent of the policy easings undertaken last fall ... remains
appropriate as those disturbances abate,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   That comment ``was kind of a shot across the bow,'' said Paul
Kasriel, chief U.S. economist for Northern Trust in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan wanted to disabuse investors of the notion the Fed is
considering cutting interest rates again anytime soon, and instead,
and get them thinking about a possible increase, Kasriel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's sort of softening the beachhead a little bit, but
it's still very tentative,'' Kasriel said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Greenspan comments, at first blush, might suggest the Fed
could move either way on interest rates: ``Monetary policy must be
ready to move quickly in either direction should we perceive
imbalances and distortions developing that could undermine the
economic expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kasriel noted: ``He didn't mention any reasons to move down
... and warned of certain reasons to move up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasriel does not expect Fed policy-makers to raise interest
rates when they meet again March 30, but he is looking for a
possible move later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The markets seemed unsure exactly how to respond to Greenspan's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year treasury bond fell about 1 4/32 point, or $11.25 per
$1,000 in face value.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged after his comments were
released, then rebounded, wobbled for a time and eventually ended
the day down a mere 8.26 points.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite, meanwhile, thumbed its
nose at Greenspan's concerns about stock prices, rising 34.34.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Brusca, chief economist for Nikko Securities in New York,
said there was such a mixed message in Greenspan's testimony ``it
could have been Julia Child on a cooking show.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also Tuesday reiterated his support for legislation to
modernize the laws governing the banking, insurance and securities
industries, calling the current laws ``outdated, competitively
stifling restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
