<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANALYSTS TAKE DIM VIEW OF POSSIBLE PAY-TV MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Canal Plus of France, Europe's biggest pay-television company,
has had ``conversations'' with Rupert Murdoch's media group, but
industry analysts were overwhelmingly skeptical that the two
companies would merge their pay-TV operations. Shares of Canal Plus
and British Sky Broadcasting jumped on word that Murdoch, whose
News Corporation owns 40 percent of BSkyB, was pushing for a
pan-European merger. But Canal Plus shares then fell amid doubts
that regulators would approve such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END MIXED AS NASDAQ RISES
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed as traders paused after Monday's big
advance and digested comments by Alan Greenspan, the Federal
Reserve chairman, on the economy, inflation and financial markets.
The Dow industrials fell 8.26 points, or almost one-tenth of a
percent, to 9,544.42. The S.&AMP;P. 500-stock index also edged down,
falling 0.96 point, to 1,271.18. The Nasdaq composite index rose
34.34 points, or 1.5 percent, to 2,376.35.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell sharply as traders and investors found a hint
of higher interest rates later this year in Greenspan's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT WITNESS ALTERS TESTIMONY
</P>
<P>
   The government's lead lawyer accused a Microsoft executive of
making up evidence at the software giant's antitrust trial, and the
witness was forced to correct his testimony after he was presented
with his own e-mail contradicting his statements.
</P>
<P>
   BILL WOULD LIMIT YEAR 2000 LIABILITY
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of House members introduced business-backed
legislation that would limit litigation, lawyers' fees and damages
from breakdowns related to the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL DEMONSTRATES PENTIUM III CHIP
</P>
<P>
   Intel demonstrated a version of its new Pentium III
microprocessor that computes more than one billion operations a
second. The chip maker, however, was careful to state that it had
specially cooled the chip to reach the mark and that it did not
expect to begin selling commercial versions of the chip running at
that speed until the end of 2000 or early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM TO CREATE WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   Viacom plans to create what it hopes will be the ultimate
on-line music destination, combining the appeal of both MTV and
VH-1, and it will also start a new children's site.
</P>
<P>
   U S WEST TO SPEND MORE ON NETWORK
</P>
<P>
   U S West said that it would increase spending on its
communications network this year, forgoing near-term profit growth
to prepare for aggressive competition as AT&AMP;T moves into the local
telephone market.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF OLIVETTI SLIDE FURTHER
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Olivetti, the No.2 Italian phone company, weakened for
the second consecutive day, to 2.906 euros, or $3.19, reflecting
increased concern among investors about Olivetti's $60 billion bid
to acquire Italy's largest phone company, Telecom Italia. The bid
met a serious setback on Monday when Italian stock market
regulators ruled it was invalid. Olivetti said it would resubmit
the offer.
</P>
<P>
   THESTREET.COM PLANS OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com, the on-line financial news service, said it would
seek to raise as much as $75 million in an initial public offering
intended to capitalize on investors' vast appetite for stock in
Internet-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   A TV SHOW THAT STILL DELIVERS
</P>
<P>
   The Grammy Awards are music to Madison Avenue's ears, mainly
because the show is one of the few remaining television programs
that can still draw large audiences _ and high ratings _ in an era
of increased viewer fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER CONFIDENCE REMAINS HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Healthy economic growth and a strong job market bolstered
consumer confidence for a fourth consecutive month in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
