<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT HANDS NCAA VICTORY IN CIVIL RIGHTS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., also filed in `w' category) 
(rk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court handed a victory on Tuesday to
the NCAA in a closely watched civil rights suit, ruling unanimously
that the organization is not automatically covered by the
anti-discrimination laws which apply to its member schools.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in Philadelphia had ruled last year that
the NCAA was covered by the federal laws by virtue of its receipt
of dues from its 1,200 member colleges and universities, which are
themselves covered.
</P>
<P>
   Two federal laws prohibit discrimination by educational
institutions that receive federal funds, as essentially all schools
and colleges do: Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972 bars
discrimination on the basis of sex, while Title VI of the Civil
Rights Act of 1964 prohibits race discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The question for the justices, in a sex discrimination suit by a
woman who was refused a waiver by the NCAA to play intercollegiate
volleyball as a graduate student, was whether these prohibitions
extend to the NCAA itself.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleged that the NCAA engaged in sex discrimination
by granting waivers more often to men than to women.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court on Tuesday, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg
said that ``dues payments from recipients of federal funds, we
hold, do not suffice to render the dues recipient subject to Title
IX.'' At most, the NCAA ``indirectly benefits from the federal
assistance afforded its members,'' Ginsburg said, adding that
``this showing, without more, is insufficient to trigger Title IX
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Although race discrimination was not an issue in this case, NCAA
vs. Smith, the court's analysis would also apply to lawsuits
brought under Title VI, which has a similar structure.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling does not spell the end of the three-year-old lawsuit
filed by the graduate student, Renee M. Smith. The court did not
address two other possible grounds for NCAA liability, which Smith,
who graduated from law school last year, is now free to pursue in
the lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   She is arguing that the NCAA itself is a recipient of federal
funds through its separately incorporated National Youth Sports
Program, which receives some $15 million a year from the Department
of Health and Human Services to run sports programs for inner-city
youth. And she is also arguing that the NCAA should be deemed to
share its members' legal obligations because they have effectively
ceded to the NCAA control over their intercollegiate sports
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The organization disputes those alternative theories and will
continue to fight the case in court, its president, Cedric W.
Dempsey, said on Tuesday. ``We have consistently said that the NCAA
should be in compliance with Title IX on a voluntary basis and have
worked to achieve compliance,'' Dempsey said in a prepared
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff's lawyer, Carter G. Phillips, said in an interview
that his client would pursue her case. ``The court went out of its
way to make its ruling extremely narrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith played varsity volleyball at St. Bonaventure University
and graduated in only two and a half years, with two years of
athletic eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But when she sought permission to play while in graduate school
at Hofstra University and law school at the University of
Pittsburgh, she ran up against the NCAA's ``post-baccalaureate
bylaw,'' which limits postgraduate eligibility to the same school
that a student-athlete attended as an undergraduate. Both Hofstra
and Pittsburgh sought waivers for Smith, but the NCAA denied the
requests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6636 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-1STLD-     02-23 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-813&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY QUICKLY FINDS DEFENDANT GUILTY OF MURDER IN TEXAS DRAGGING
DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds.: Subs 10th graf to insert that jury has final decision on
penalty. Adds a sentence to the 13th graf about jury being shown a
videotape of the road the pickup traveled. Adds a phrase in the
20th graf that the KKK drawing was found in King's apartment. Adds
a new 24th graf with reaction from President Clinton.) (fe) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ With exceptional swiftness, a jury on Tuesday
declared John William King, a white man, guilty of capital murder
for dragging a black man to his death behind a pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   The jury began deliberations after less than five days of
testimony and barely an hour of closing arguments, chose its only
black member as foreman and returned two and a half hours later
with the strongest possible verdict. Jurors then quickly began
hearing evidence on whether King should be sentenced to death for
murdering James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice has been served,'' said a tearful Mary Verrette, one
of Byrd's sisters, as she emerged from the 110-year-old Jasper
County Courthouse. ``It was not decided on emotion but on facts,
and that's all we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, slumped slightly as the verdict was read by Judge Joe
Bob Golden of State District Court but showed no other emotion.
Byrd's relatives and others in the packed courtroom burst into
applause as the jury rose to leave the courtroom after the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   King is one of three white men charged with killing Byrd, 49, in
the dark, early hours of June 7, 1998, dragging him on a chain
behind a pickup truck for three miles down rural roads in the pine
woods east of Jasper. Trial dates have yet to be set for the other
defendants, Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, who met King when the two
were in prison, and Shawn Berry, 23, who has known King since high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors argued that King was plotting to form his own white
supremacist gang in Jasper _ the Texas Rebel Soldier Division of
the Confederate Knights of America _ and had hoped to use the
grisly death of a local black man to help recruit members and,
perhaps, to provide a blood initiation into the gang for Berry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any jury in the country would have decided it the same
way,'' said Guy James Gray, the Jasper County district attorney,
who led the prosecution. ``You can't put up with this sort of
stuff. You can't tolerate it. It could've happened anywhere in this
nation, but it fell on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray and others said they were not surprised that it took the
jury so little time to come to a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not surprised that they decided so fast, because the
evidence was overwhelming,'' said Ethel Parks, a black Jasper
resident who came to the courthouse to hear the verdict. ``For
once, they did something right in Jasper.''
</P>
<P>
   After a break of only a few minutes, court reconvened to begin
the punishment phase of the trial, in which both sides will argue
which of the two potential sentences, death by lethal injection or
life imprisonment, should be given to King. Prosecutors said they
expected the jury, whose decision will be final, to begin
deliberating on punishment as early as Thursday, and certainly
before the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which drew international attention and brought back
memories of Southern lynchings from decades past, began with the
discovery of Byrd's body, scattered in pieces along the country
road where he was dragged. He had last been seen alive in the back
of the pickup after hitchhiking home from a late-night party.
Byrd's head and right shoulder were sheared off when the truck sped
around a sharp corner and he slammed into a sharp-edged culvert.
His lower body was found a mile farther down the road, dumped
outside a cemetery and black church.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution called 43 witnesses, some of whom linked King to
the death scene (his cigarette lighter was found there, as was his
DNA on a cigarette butt) and some of whom exposed his racist
attitudes (his arms and torso are covered with Nazi and white
supremacist tattoos and his writings disclosed a deep hatred of
blacks and a yearning for fame).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most compelling testimony came on Monday, when a
pathologist described how Byrd had been alive through much of his
ordeal, probably until his body was cut in two. Prosecutors also
showed a videotape of the road the pickup traveled, illustrating
the length of the trip and showing every inch of what Byrd was
dragged across.
 &UR;  &LR; Also on Monday, prosecutors placed in evidence what they
considered their coup de grace, a letter that King had tried to
smuggle out of his jail cell to Brewer in which he asserted that
``regardless of the outcome of this, we have made history and shall
die proudly remembered if need be.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense offered only three witnesses Monday in a case that
lasted less than an hour. One of them, a prison artist responsible
for some of King's tattoos, testified that King wore them to scare
off fellow prisoners who might try to harm him.
</P>
<P>
   The jury had three choices on Tuesday: to find King not guilty,
to find him guilty of capital murder (which meant that he murdered
Byrd while in the process of committing another crime, in this case
kidnapping) or to find him guilty of a lesser murder charge. King's
lawyers focused much of their attention on refuting the kidnapping
charge, hoping to save their client from a capital murder
conviction and the subsequent possibility of execution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We know that a terrible, terrible, brutal, horrendous murder
was committed,'' said Brack Jones, a lawyer for King. ``No
question. The question is, Was Byrd kidnapped?''
</P>
<P>
   Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs, the chief defense lawyer, asked the
jurors not to let King's repellant views sway them into finding
more guilt than the evidence showed. He acknowledged that his
client was a racist. ``Not that I agree with that,'' he said. ``But
you have a right to be a racist.''
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, Pat Hardy, one of the prosecutors,
asked, ``What makes a person hate so hard to do something like that
to a person they don't even know?'' The answer, he said, could only
be found in the racism that obsessed King.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy directed the jurors' attention to a Ku Klux Klan drawing
that was found in King's apartment and placed in evidence, showing
a trio of horsemen galloping from a fire. ``Robed riders coming
straight out of hell,'' Hardy said. ``And that's exactly what they
were that night. Instead of a rope, they used a chain; instead of
horses, there was a pickup truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray argued that the community needed to rid itself of such
violent racism, almost as an issue of public health. ``It's
something that's a virus,'' he said. ``It's something that's
dangerous. It's something that spreads from one person to
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, on the sun-bright courthouse lawn, a palpable sense of
relief flowed through the small crowd that had gathered to hear the
verdict. While many feared that the trial would draw protests from
both extremes of the racial divide, life carried on much as usual
during the trial and there were no protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very relieved at the moment, but we still have some
healing to do,'' said Mayor R.C. Horn, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict drew responses from leaders across the nation,
including President Clinton, who said that expressions of outrage
over Byrd's death ``demonstrate that an act of evil like this is
not what our country is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   John H. Matthews, a Jasper real estate broker whose office
overlooks the courthouse, came across the road to retrieve his dog,
Domino, who was scampering amid the television crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper is not a bad town,'' Matthews said. ``It's got some
good people in it. I think we're ready for you all to go home
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990223.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-NCAA-NYT &LR;      02-23 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NCAA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT HANDS NCAA VICTORY IN CIVIL RIGHTS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., also filed in `w' category) 
(rk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
