<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury declares main suspect in Jasper killing guilty
 &HT;    By Zach Maxwell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ John William King, pegged as a life-long
criminal and white supremacist, was found guilty Tuesday of capital
murder for the June 7, 1998, slaying of James Byrd Jr., whom he
dragged behind his buddy's truck down three miles of a country
road.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict from the 12-member jury _ who selected the lone
black man as their foreman _ came about 1:45 p.m. Tuesday, two
hours after deliberations began. The trial now moves to the
sentencing phase, with prosecutors expecting the jury to decide
whether King, 24, will live out his years in prison or die for the
murder that shook the soul of this community and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the death penalty is what the government provides for
crimes of this sort, then by all means that's what we want to
happen,'' Byrd's sister Clara Taylor said after the verdict was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's parents also attended Tuesday's emotional proceedings at
the Jasper County Courthouse. ``I saw her smile for the first time
in a long time,'' Taylor said of her mother when State District
Judge Joe Bob Golden read the guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
   King watched the jury, but looked away when his fate was
announced. His father, Ronald King, left the courthouse after
applause broke out. The elder King, who suffers from a number of
ailments, reportedly sought medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Family friend David Luther read a statement from Ronald King,
who did not grant interviews to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you might expect, Mr. King is deeply saddened by the
verdict handed down today,'' Luther said. ``Mr. King is just as
saddened for the James Byrd Jr. family as they have shouldered an
even greater burden these last several months. He prays that no
family should ever experience prejudice of any sort ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   Security was the tightest yet for the trial's outcome, but only
a familiar handful of local residents joined the throngs of media
members on the courthouse lawn. As the courthouse bell tolled the 4
p.m. hour, King was whisked away to jail while a few hecklers
called to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should get the death penalty. Definitely,'' said
Kevin Higginbotham of Houston, who made his first ever trip to
Jasper to witness the day's events. ``Lethal injection is too good
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From day one he's done nothing but smile,'' local resident
Tracey Parks said. ``Now he doesn't have anything to smile about.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys began the day with their closing arguments. Assistant
District Attorney Pat Hardy painted King and two co-defendants as
``three robed riders coming straight out of hell,'' holding up a
drawing of three Klansmen on horseback that was found in King's
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of using a rope, they used a chain,'' he said. ``They
dumped the body in front of a black cemetery to show their defiance
of God, of Christianity and everything most people in this county
stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys failed to convince the jury that kidnapping
was not part of Byrd's horrific murder. Without kidnapping, King
would have faced a lesser charge of murder.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray said he was ``relieved'' about
the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough way to make a living,'' he said. ``This was a
bombshell in our community. It could have happened anywhere in the
country and it fell in our laps.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the mounds of racist writings found in King's
apartment and from jail correspondence as among the most damaging
evidence. King apparently planned to begin a racist hate group
called the Texas Rebel Soldiers in Jasper, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man has done an awful lot of writing,'' he said. ``He's
kind of written himself into this hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs said he was
disappointed but not surprised at the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of your duty as an attorney is to get the client prepared
for the worst,'' he said. ``I don't t
</P>
</TEXT>
