<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6640 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-COX     02-23 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guilty verdict in Jasper dragging death trial
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER _ A white supremacist who sought infamy for his gang was
convicted Tuesday in the dragging death of a black man whose
torturous killing became a wake-up call about racism in America.
</P>
<P>
   The family of murder victim James Byrd Jr. embraced and wiped
tears when the verdict against John William ``Bill'' King was
announced. Spontaneous applause broke out from some spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles, who was guarding King, blew
the Byrd family a kiss. King, 24, showed no reaction, but his
ailing father began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors took just under 2 1/2 hours to decide King was guilty of
kidnapping and dragging Byrd behind a pickup for nearly three miles
until he was decapitated on June 7. The jury, which selected the
only black person on the panel as foreman, now must decide if King
should die for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors heard from probation and police officers who discussed
King's criminal history and his refusal to follow rules while on
probation for burglary. Testimony continues today.
</P>
<P>
   If he receives the death penalty, King would become the first
white person in Texas to be sentenced to lethal injection for
killing a black person since the state resumed capital punishment
in the mid-1970s, state prison records show. Two of King's white
friends also are charged in Byrd's murder and face the death
penalty in upcoming trials. Prosecutors said they won't offer any
plea bargains to Shawn Berry and Lawrence Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and community leaders in Jasper, who have worked
overtime to defend the reputation of this Deep East Texas logging
town in the aftermath of Byrd's murder, were relieved by the guilty
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bombshell in our community,'' said Jasper County
District Attorney Guy James Gray. ``It's something we're unhappy
with. The crime is horrible. The reason is horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It could have happened anyplace in this country and
it fell in our laps. And I don't think we wanted anybody to feel
like we would run from it. We didn't shift it off. It's Jasper's
responsibility and we handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd Sr., who has attended the trial each day since
testimony began Feb. 16, thanked the Jasper community for pulling
together in support of his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't have to do it, but you did and we appreciate it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence in the trial was stacked so heavily against King that
his defense lawyers all but conceded his guilt in the killing. They
have concentrated on trying to win a life sentence for the
ex-convict whose numerous anti-black and Nazi-like tattoos
transformed him into a walking billboard for white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   Court-appointed defense lawyer C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr.
said defending King is ``like climbing Mt. Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   King's conviction came after one-hour of closing arguments,
during which a prosecutor dramatically held up a KKK illustration
from King's collection for the jury. He said King and his two
co-defendants were no different than the ``three robed riders
coming straight out of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of a rope, they used a chain. Instead of horses, they
were using a pickup truck,'' said Pat Hardy, assistant Jasper
County district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they dragged this poor man and tore his body to pieces,
they dropped him right in front of a church and a cemetery to show
their defiance of God, to show their defiance of Christianity and
to show their defiance of everything that most people in this
county stand for and in this state and in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that connected King to Byrd's murder included his
KKK-inscribed cigarette lighter found at the spot where Byrd was
chained to the pickup, a spot of Byrd's blood on the bottom of one
of King's sandals and DNA testing that indicated King had smoked
one of the cigarettes found on the logging road where the dragging
of Byrd began.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the most damning evidence came from King himself,
even though he declined to testify. Scores of his racist writings
were introduced, including a jailhouse note to one of his
co-defendants in which he boasted of having ``made history'' after
Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of written himself into this hole,'' said Gray, the
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that was very damaging and something we
couldn't overcome,'' Cribbs said.
</P>
<P>
   King's hand-written documents show he was trying to form a new
white supremacy group in Jasper called the Texas Rebel Soldiers, an
offshoot of a white state prison gang King joined while serving
time for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers argued that King's prison experience transformed him
into a racist. He joined a white gang and got anti-black tattoos as
a means of protecting himself from black inmates who outnumbered
white inmates and tried to beat or sexually assault small white men
like King, they argued.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, Cribbs suggested that King suffered from
post-traumatic stress syndrome after getting out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question this boy had something
happen to him in the penitentiary,'' he said. ``He became a racist.
He became a hater.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, King's father and Byrd's family have kept
a respectful distance. They have exchanged pleasantries, but have
not visited at length.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was returned and court recessed for 30
minutes, one of Byrd's sisters tried to approach Ronald King to
offer a hug, but the retired lumber worker was surrounded by
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't blame him,'' said Mylinda Washington. ``It was hard
for him as a parent to go through this. We're all losers here.''
</P>
<P>
   Another one of Byrd's sisters, Stella Brumley, said, ``We don't
hold a grudge, and we wanted to let Mr. King know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King, who has emphysema and uses a wheelchair, left the
courtroom to visit a doctor. A family friend, David Luther, later
issued a statement on behalf of the elder King.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you might expect, Mr. King is deeply saddened by the
verdict handed down today,'' the statement said. ``Mr. King is just
as saddened for the James Byrd Jr. family as they have shouldered
an even greater burden these last several months.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. King loves his son as hopefully any father should. He
prays that no family should ever experience prejudice of any sort
ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside on the courthouse lawn, the newly convicted King was
heckled by a few black Jasper residents as he was led in a
bullet-proof vest into a sheriff's pickup for the ride back to
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper served justice,'' said Tracey Parks, a friend of the
murdered man, as she watched King being taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
