</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WARD GIVES AN ASSIST TO A TROUBLING SITUATION
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a cry for help from Brooklyn, a silent cry,
but one with piercing echoes. It was written outside the Jackie
Robinson Intermediate School 320 on McKeever Street in Crown
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   It was written on a deflated basketball that rested between two
crosses in the school garden. Someone had scrawled a plea on the
ball. ``MJ,'' it read, ``Please Explain Love of the Game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a cry for help, for understanding, for trying to bring
perspective where tragedy had struck. The ``MJ,'' unmistakably, was
Michael Jordan. It seemed not so much, in reality, an appeal to
that supreme deity of basketball, as it was a cry in the night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a result of the senseless murder on Jan. 27 across from
the school. After a basketball game between teams of teen-agers in
the Jackie Robinson Center for Physical Culture after-school
program, played at the school, a 14-year-old named Michael Bennett,
the high scorer on the winning team, was chased, beaten and stabbed
to death across from the school.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five teen-agers charged in connection with the slaying,
three were members of the losing team.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward read of the killing, and, though unaware of the
message on the deflated basketball in the school garden, responded,
as most who read of it did, with his heart.
</P>
<P>
   The point guard for the Knicks, who plays home games in Madison
Square Garden, some six miles and a world apart from the Jackie
Robinson school, spoke with Terry Williams, a business associate of
his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie said to me, `I'd like to do something _ I'm not sure
what,''' recalled Williams. ``He is interested in community
affairs. He doesn't make a lot of noise about it. He just does
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams called the school and Ward was invited to speak to
students. Two weeks ago, he did. There was no publicity attendant
to the visit. In fact, I learned about it at the end of a story in
The New York Times' Metropolitan section about the aftermath of the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Ward told the kids that basketball was ``not life and death, but
simply a game.'' He said, ``God didn't give anyone the right to
take someone else's life.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about living with hope _ knowing that some of them,
even at so young an age, were losing hope of a better life beyond
the streets, or had lost the hope. He spoke about everyone having a
talent, and gave an example of a biblical parable about developing
talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at me,'' he said, ``and you are looking at a finished
product. But you don't see all the years of work I had to put in to
get where I have. And you think about the big money basketball
players make. But I'm 28 years old now, and for 20 years I never
made a red cent. I did try to develop my skills. And nothing came
easy. In college, I earned a degree while playing two sports.''
It's no secret, of course, that Ward was quarterback on the Florida
State football team and won the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about trying to reach the masses,'' Ward said,
recalling his visit. ``If I can influence just one person, or two,
to go on to better themselves, that's all I can ask for. Then maybe
those one or two can influence someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward presents himself as a deeply religious man. People
who know him well say he is genuine. He explains the accusations
that he is a less than clean-acting basketball player by saying
that small players _ he is 6 feet 1 inch _ have to be wily to
counteract their larger foes. But that is beside the point in the
larger issue beyond the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   As a citizen _ as a ``brother'' in the black community, as he
referred to himself _ Charlie Ward believes he must try to be part
of the solution. ``Just because I've attained a certain position
doesn't mean I can't look back, and lend a hand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward grew up in Thomasville, Ga. His father was a high school
coach and social science teacher, his mother a librarian. ``I was
fortunate to have a good foundation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of kids grow up in broken homes, but that's no
excuse for not trying to make something of yourself. A lot of
people from broken homes have done well. You have to have faith,
but you have to work hard. You don't realize your dreams if you
have one and not the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's remarks to the students were not earth-shaking. It was
just common-sense talk coming from someone who had achieved, who
had heard a cry, who responded.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the case involving charges against five boys in the
killing will be acted upon by a grand jury. And outside the school,
there remains a small shrine for Michael Bennett. Balloons are tied
to a wrought-iron fence.
</P>
<P>
   There is a picture of him, a boy with a sweet smile, and
underneath is his name and birth date. He would have been 15 years
old on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
