<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SUPREMACIST FOUND GUILTY IN EAST TEXAS DRAGGING DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A 24-year-old white supremacist was found guilty
of capital murder on Tuesday in the dragging death of a black man,
a hate crime that a prosecutor said was reminiscent of 19th century
lynchings by mounted Klansmen.
</P>
<P>
   John William King, 24, sat hunched slightly forward but did not
stir when the jury announced its verdict after deliberating about
85 minutes. The punishment phase of the trial began immediately to
determine if King will be sentenced to death, or to life in prison.
It will continue on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   King is the first of three white men to stand trial in the June
7, 1998, death of James Byrd Jr., 49, who was chained to a pickup
bumper and dragged for three miles along a rural road. The gruesome
nature of the slaying and its apparent racial motivation focused
unwanted international attention on the East Texas community of
8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Several courtroom spectators applauded yesterday's verdict,
drawing a sharp warning from District Judge Joe Bob Golden. Outside
the courtroom, members of Byrd's family said they were ``elated,
relieved,'' and expressed gratitude to the sheriff and district
attorney for mounting a successful case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all should drag him from the truck!'' Tracey Parks, 25, a
neighbor of the victim, shouted as King was escorted to a white
pickup that would shuttle him back to the Jasper County Jail.
``They need to do him like he did to Byrd,'' she said. ``Lethal
injection is too easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the community had been eager to see the case finished
and Jasper's good name restored. No dates have been set for the
trials of the other defendants, Lawrence Russell Brewer and Shawn
Berry.
</P>
<P>
   A family friend read a note on behalf of Ronald King, the
defendant's father, saying he was deeply saddened by the verdict
and just as saddened for the Byrd family ``as they have shouldered
an even greater burden these last several months.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King also urged Jasper ``to continue to show the world by
its example, that during these difficult times, good will overcome
all evil...''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement saying that when Byrd was
killed, ``it was my hope that people would join together across
racial lines to demonstrate that an act of evil like this is not
what our country is all about. That hope was fulfilled over the
past eight months, as citizens across the country expressed their
outrage and grief over this tragedy, and their determination to
ensure that justice be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the verdict rendered today by twelve citizens in
Jasper, Texas, will bring some sense of closure to the family and
friends of Mr. Byrd,'' Clinton said. ``The First Lady and I offer
our prayers for them, and our hope that their memories of Mr.
Byrd's life will sustain them in the difficult time ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, defense and prosecution attorneys said that King's
own writing provided some of the most damaging evidence against
him.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote out by-laws and a constitution for a planned hate group
and sent a newspaper his account of the crime, which the
prosecution used against him.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly harmful to his case was an intercepted jailhouse
note to Brewer. In it, King acknowledged finding a ``brown
substance'' on his sandals that FBI experts determined was Byrd's
blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of the outcome of this, we have made history and
shall die proudly .... SEIG HEIL (HAIL VICTORY),'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs said part of his job
was to prepare King for the worst. ``I am sure he is feeling mixed
emotions,'' Cribbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Cribbs said King's jailhouse note to co-defendant Brewer was
``very damning and something you couldn't keep out'' as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray listed King's writing and DNA
evidence as keys to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of written himself into this hole,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, King's attorneys did not contend that he
was not a participant in a ``brutal, brutal'' killing. But they
insisted that chaining Byrd to a pickup did not amount to
kidnapping and, therefore, King should not be convicted of capital
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tying of the feet and dragging, as we see the case, is the
intentionally killing and not the kidnapping,'' defense attorney
Brack Jones argued.
</P>
<P>
   Cribbs, the lead defense attorney, suggested that King might
have post-traumatic shock syndrome from his two years in a Texas
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In their closing argument, prosecutors summed up the case
against King, linking him to crime by his inscribed cigarette
lighter and his DNA on a cigarette butt found at the scene, and by
a fleck of Byrd's blood found on his sandals at home.
</P>
<P>
   Among racist papers seized at his apartment was an inverted
pentagram behind mounted klansmen with a coil of rope, Assistant
District Attorney Pat Hardy reminded jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was exactly what it was that night,'' said Hardy.
``Instead of a rope, they used a chain. Instead of horses, they
were using a pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, ladies and gentlemen, the satanic part of that comes in
after they dragged that poor man and tore his body to pieces,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dropped him right in front of a church and a cemetery to
show their defiance of God, to show their defiance of Christianity
and to show their defiance of everything that most people in this
county stand for, and in this state and in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
