<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-COLLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: COLLINS HAS SOME OLD HITCHES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kerry Collins arrived in Mobile, Ala., for the 1995 Senior Bowl
fresh from leading Penn State to a 12-0 record and a Rose Bowl
victory over Oregon. He had reached the roses by beating Illinois,
35-31, for the Big Ten title in a struggle in which Penn State
erased a 21-point deficit. Collins directed the winning drive,
connecting on all seven of his passes into a whipping wind. The
drive covered 96 yards. It finished with 57 seconds remaining.
Nebraska would win the mythical national title that year, but
everyone at Penn State was certain that Collins and the Nittany
Lions were better. And they told him so.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the tingling theater of his college career,
Collins was showered with more attention and glory at the Senior
Bowl. Everyone wanted to shake his hand and hear him speak. He
seemed shy, but moved rather easily through the crowds. Shook
hands. Spoke softly. Said the right things to a mosaic of pro
football scouts. But then the news of that Senior Bowl broke. Oh my
gosh! Kerry Collins has a hitch!
</P>
<P>
   It ran like wildfire. Kerry Collins throws with this little
hitch in his passing delivery, a la Randall Cunningham. He sort of
cocks his arm and then throws the football. See? He had been doing
it this way all of his life, but now everyone was noticing and
making this thing big. How will that work in the pro game?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, shockingly, for Kerry Collins, the petals began to
fall off the rose.
</P>
<P>
   Collins immediately started catching them. He tried putting them
back in place. He said he could probably change the hitch. He said
it was not an issue. He could play and excel, all right, throwing
his way, hitch and all.
</P>
<P>
   So, then and certainly now, Kerry Collins comes with a hitch. He
is the Giants' quarterback now and who doubts he has been selected
as their quarterback for the future and most likely even for the
present? Kent Graham hears footsteps. He sees the Giants investing
$16.9 million over four years in Collins and awarding him $5
million up front in a signing bonus. He must know that Collins is
the man to beat at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Today. Tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Collins provides an even bigger hitch _ unless he blows
it.
</P>
<P>
   History says he can.
</P>
<P>
   He blew away the doubt at the Senior Bowl and became the fifth
player selected in the 1995 draft. He became a Carolina Panther and
in his second season took them to the National Football Conference
championship game. The last two seasons, however, Carolina
struggled. So did Collins. Some of his old Panthers coaches and
teammates say he quit on them last year. One of them accused
Collins of racist-like talk. Others said he had a drinking problem.
Collins says it was all a misunderstanding. He was released and
then signed by New Orleans on Oct. 14. On Nov. 2, he was arrested
for driving under the influence of alcohol. Mike Ditka, the Saints'
head coach, had said of Collins and the baggage he might bring when
he signed him: ``I'm not clairvoyant, but I don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Giants say now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have intensely researched his play and his background and
we believe in Dr. Joel Goldberg _ he gave us the green light and I
trust him without reservation,'' Ernie Accorsi, the Giants' general
manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi trusts Goldberg, the Giants' director of career
counseling, without reservation, not Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are always concerned and you are taking a risk in any
football decision you make about a new player, whether it be for
failure on or off the field,'' Accorsi said. ``If we had traded
four draft picks to move up to take one of the young quarterbacks
in the draft, that would have been a risk, too. We felt we made the
best move.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins can take you into the end zone, for sure. He can also
steer you into the ditch.
</P>
<P>
   He was 2-5 as the New Orleans starter and threw 10
interceptions, fumbled eight times and lost four of them in fewer
than 24 quarters. Ditka let Collins go.
</P>
<P>
   How can a quarterback that the downtrodden Saints discarded be
the apple of the Giants' eye?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the Steelers didn't think Johnny Unitas could play,
either,'' Accorsi snapped. ``We trust our own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   True, Collins in four games with a Saints offense that is
horrible is not a true measuring stick of his current talent. But
what is? His Penn State days? His dream season in '96 with
Carolina? His banishing in Carolina and New Orleans? The character
thing? His brush with the law? That's the hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The word is out and the heat is on Kerry Collins. He requires
broad shoulders to stand tall in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants and Collins? They're hitched. The contract says for
four years. History hints maybe not that long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
