<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6646 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     02-23 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ OFFERED DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ It's now up to Ramon Martinez if he wants to
remain with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone said Tuesday the club offered the
right-handed pitcher, who's rehabilitating after surgery to repair
a rotator cuff tear, an incentive-laden guaranteed contract to
remain with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep him. He's a Dodger,'' Malone said. ``Once he's
finished rehabilitating and is healthy, we think he can help us get
to where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he didn't give Martinez a deadline for accepting the
offer. Martinez, who's been with the organization since 1984, is
working out at the Dodgers complex in the Dominican Republic.
Martinez's agents, however, are angling for a bigger contract and
he's not expected to sign with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a low guarantee because I'm not going to pay a guy that
can't perform,'' Malone said. ``We'll pay you to rehabilitate you.
We'll take some of the risks, but we want to share the risk, as far
as financially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that Ramon recognizes his past history with the
medical staff here and the training staff, and he'll recognize how
important it is to continue to be in a relationship with these
people because they can help you. Hopefully, he'll make his
decision off that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Camp in full bloom: The big names _ Eric Karros, Gary
Sheffield, Raul Mondesi and Mark Grudzielanek _ showed up in
Tuesday in anticipation of today's first full workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always exciting coming in that first day, a bunch of
hugs, and how-you-doings,'' Sheffield said. ``Any time you have a
team that has a chance to win, you can't wait to get into spring
training.''
</P>
<P>
   And get a chance to experience Camp Davey.
</P>
<P>
   __ Starters' starts set: Kevin Brown will make his first
appearance of the spring when the Dodgers host the Mets on March 7
in the team's third spring game, Johnson said. Brown and Chan Ho
Park are each scheduled to throw two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said right-hander Ismael Valdes
will start the Grapefruit League opener March 6 against St. Louis.
Dave Mlicki is also expected to pitch in that game. Carlos Perez,
the lone lefty in the rotation, and Darren Dreifort will work March
6 against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said starters will pitch two innings, rest for three
days, pitch again, and then have four days off. He expects them to
work their way up to 90 pitches by their last spring-training
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   __ Slim and trim: Malone and Johnson said players reported in
good shape _ and that includes Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi weighed in at 235 pounds, 15 pounds more than his usual
playing weight, and looking much more fit than recent reports
portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll lose like five, six more pounds,'' Mondesi said. ``I'm
going to be bigger this year but stronger. Not fat. I'm ready to
go. I feel fine, rested.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Galvez surgery: Right-handed minor-league pitcher Randy
Galvez will undergo surgery on a date to be determined after an MRI
revealed a tear in his ulnar collateral ligament. The 20-year-old
was 13-4 with a 3.60 ERA while on loan to the Mexico City Red
Devils of the Mexican League last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
