   (NYT18) BEIJING -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- CHINA-MIGRATE-2, 2-23 --
Riders pack a bus bound for Wenzhou, southeastern China, from
Beijing. These days China is on the move, with an estimated 10
percent of the population now migrating from their official place
of residence mostly in search of better jobs. (Elisabeth
Rosenthal/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BEIJING -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- CHINA-MIGRATE-1, 2-23 -- Wu
Liuyi on a bus taking her home to Wenzhou from Beijing. Ever since
Wu and her husband left their farming village for factory work in
Beijing in 1992, this daunting pilgrimage from the place they live
to a distant ``home'' has become a family routine. These days China
is on the move, with an estimated 10 percent of the population now
migrating from their official place of residence mostly in search
of better jobs. (Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN, 2-23 --
New York Knicks point guard Charlie Ward addresses students in the
auditorium of the Jackie Robinson Intermediate School last week.
Ward, who read about a teenager killed near the school after a
basketball game in January, talked to the children about living
with hope knowing that some of them, even at so young an age, were
losing hope of a better life beyond the streets. (Linda Rosier/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PAWTUCKET, R.I. -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- REPUBS-MODERATES,
2-23 -- Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., left, discusses local issues with
Pawtucket Mayor James Doyle last week. Across the country the
Republican party has become more conservative. Except in New
England where in the most liberal region in the country a
Republican who is not a moderate will simply not get elected.
(Kirsten Elstner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- SUB-NY-HOTEL-BARS-1, 2-23
-- In the early evening, the stage-like King Cole Bar at the St.
Regis Hotel draws a business crowd. Behind the bartenders is
Maxfield Parrish's whimsical mural of life in King Cole's court.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- CHOUCROUTE, 2-23 --
Choucroute garnie, a rustic dish with city ways, at Les Halles.
Choucroute is just French for sauerkraut, or fermented cabbage, but
what makes it so irresistible is the garnish: a variety of
unabashedly heavy meats - some smoked or salted, some not, all
usually pork. The seasonings are often little more than juniper
berries and onion with a little goose or duck fat or lard. (David
Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- NY-HOTEL-BARS-2, 2-23 -- At
the Journeys bar in the Essex House, Joseph Vespa whips up a
``Mystery Cocktail.'' New York City is filled with unappreciated
treasures. But in the world of food and drink, none are so
neglected as hotel bars. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- Feb. 23, 1999 --
ERITREAN-RESTAURANT-2, 2-23 -- Ficre Ghebreyesus, the chef at Cafe
Adulis in New Haven, reinterprets the cuisine of Eritrea. The
restaurant is the creation of three refugee brothers named
Ghebreyesus - Ficre, 36, Gideon, 38, and Sahle, 28 - who escaped
from the chaos in Asmara, the Eritrean capital, and came to New
Haven at the suggestion of their sister, who was in New York.
(George Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- Feb. 23, 1999 --
ERITREAN-RESTAURANT-1, 2-23 -- At Caffe Adulis in New Haven,
Eritrean dishes are combined on one platter, which feeds seven
people. It's been a long time since a restaurant has surprised as
much as Caffe Adulis, a charming little place a long block from the
Yale campus. I guess you would call it an ethnic restaurant,
because it specializes in Eritrean food. (George Ruhe/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- Feb. 23, 1999 --
ERITREAN-RESTAURANT-1, 2-23 -- At Caffe Adulis in New Haven,
Eritrean dishes are combined on one platter, which feeds seven
people. It's been a long time since a restaurant has surprised as
much as Caffe Adulis, a charming little place a long block from the
Yale campus. I guess you would call it an ethnic restaurant,
because it specializes in Eritrean food. (George Ruhe/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- NY-CHILI, 2-23 -- Janet and
Michael Stern at the Cowgirl Hall of Fame in the West Village.
``Finding great chili in New York is like finding great pastrami in
Des Moines,'' says Mr. Stern warningly. Nonetheless, the Sterns
have agreed to eat chili at three different places to see if any
can equal the ones included in their latest book, ``Chili Nation:
The Ultimate Chili Cookbook With Recipes From Every State in the
Nation.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HOUSTON -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- BKW-PERROT-HNS, 02-23 -- Kim
Perrot, a member of the Houston Comets' during their two WNBA
championship seasons, cried frequently Monday as she talked of
being diagnosed with lung and brain cancer. Sitting beside her is
her Comets' coach Van Chancellor. On Friday, she was informed of
that the cancer that began in her lungs had spread to her brain.
(Smiley N. Pool/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS-2, 2-23
-- President Clinton meets with congressional leaders in the Oval
Office on Tuesday. Among those attending the meeting are, from
right: Rep. Richard Gephardt, the House minority leader, and Senate
Majority Leader Sen. Trent Lott. The meeting was the first with
congressional leaders since Clinton's impeachment trial. Vice
President Al Gore is at left. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MONTREAL -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- OLY-POUND, 2-23 -- Richard
Pound, vice president of International Olympic Committee, in his
office during a meeting last week. Pound, an American, has emerged
as the IOC's internal investigator looking into corruption
involving the selection of olympic host cities. (Robert
Galbraith/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- BBN-METS, 2-23
-- New York Mets outfielder Bobby Bonilla, right, gets an early
morning greeting from teammate Rickey Henderson on Tuesday before a
team workout. In his second time around with the Mets, Bobby
Bonilla is trying to present himself as someone who is older, more
thoughtful and more willing to laugh about his past problems with
the Mets. (Gary I.Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS, 2-23 --
President Clinton meets with congressional leaders in the Oval
Office on Tuesday. Among those attending are, from left: Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, House Majority Whip Rep. Dick Armey,
and Speaker of the House Dennis Hastert. Vice President Al Gore is
at far right. The meeting was the first with congressional leaders
since Clinton's impeachment trial. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BUKOS, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FIGHTING-3,
2-23 -- Serb soldiers patrol front line positions during in a lull
in fighting Tuesday near the village of Bukos, some 25 miles north
of Pristina. A fierce bout of fighting in the region raised fears
that a surge of violence could follow the inconclusive end of peace
talks in France. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BUKOS, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FIGHTING-2,
2-23 -- A Serb police officer stands near the scene where his
colleague, Mirko Milosevic, was killed during fighting between
police and members of the Kosovo Liberation Army in Bukos, some 25
miles north of Pristina, on Tuesday. A fierce bout of fighting in
the region raised fears that a surge of violence could follow the
inconclusive end of peace talks in France. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BUKOS, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FIGHTING ,
2-23 -- Dragica Milosevic stands vigil on Tuesday over the body of
her son, Mirko Milosevic, 35, who was killed, allegedly by ethnic
Albanian fighters with the Kosovo Liberation Army, in the village
some 25 miles north of Pristina. A fierce bout of fighting in the
region on Tuesday raised fears that a surge of violence could
follow the inconclusive end of peace talks. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
