<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/23/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- LIVINGSTON-FLOATER, 2-23
-- Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., right, the speaker-designate who
resigned in December on the day the House voted on articles of
impeachment against President Clinton, took a break on Tuesday from
packing up his Capitol Hill office. With him was former Rep. Frank
Cremeans, R-Ohio. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) CALVERTON, N.Y. -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- TWA-WRECKAGE, 2-23
-- The rebuilt wreckage of TWA flight 800 is seen in a hangar in
November 1997. The wreckage is up for grabs, as the National
Transportation Safety Board looks for a way to escape the $4.5
million annual expense of storing it, even before it has finished
its final report on the crash. The College of Aeronautics, near La
Guardia International Airport in Queens, and the Virginia campus of
George Washington University, are competing to adopt the wreckage.
(Vic Delucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-JETER, 2-23 --
New York Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter scoops up the ball during
Tuesday practice. In answering questions about his dream life as
the shortstop who will make $5 million this season for a team that
has snatched two World Series championships in the last three
years, Jeter admitted that he has distressing days, too. One of
them occurred on New Year's Day when Sonny Connors, his beloved
grandfather, died of a heart attack at 68. (Jon Adams/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 28 --
AUTO-REVIEW-BOS, 2-23 -- The 1999 Jeep Wrangler Sport. Jeeps have
been selling for years and they have a personality you at least
have to grudgingly respect. This version is clearly more docile
than its predecessors, but it still yearns to go off roading. (Paul
Drake/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BOSTON -- Feb. 23, 1999 -- AUTHOR-ESTRICH-BOS, 2-23 --
Author Susan Estrich in her hotel room before an appearance to
promote her new book: ``Making the Case for Yourself: A Diet Book
for Smart Women.'' Estrich, the first female president of the
Harvard Law Review, the first woman to run a presidential campaign
(for Michael Dukakis) and the youngest woman to get tenure at
Harvard Law School, is writing about why women do not have more
power. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
