<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Wednesday, Feb. 24, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443 or
Catherine Laidlaw at 415-777-6057.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; VISA  &LR; _ Citigroup's apparent move to jilt Visa in favor of
MasterCard may have pulled the rug out from under the federal
government's far-reaching credit card antitrust case, legal experts
said. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EEOC &LR;  _ Salinas lettuce grower has agreed to pay former
employees more than $1.85 million in the biggest settlement of a
sexual harassment case filed on behalf of farmworkers by the U.S.
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. By Ilana DeBare
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOA &LR;  _ BankAmerica will close its Oakland retail brokerage call
center later this year, eliminating about 100 jobs, a bank
spokeswoman said. The shutdown will come as BankAmerica of North
Carolina merges the operations of the old BofA of San Francisco and
the former NationsBank. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET _  &LR; Do you crave Yahoo shares every time the
search-engine concern splits its stock?
</P>
<P>
   Or do you own shares in companies that display hip billboards
off Highway 101, but you have no earthly idea what they make or do?
</P>
<P>
   Then perhaps you have a problem. You might be a tech-stock
junkie. That's what concerns financial adviser William Urban of
Bingham, Osborn &AMP; Scarborough. By columnist Mark Veverka
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ENTREPRENEUR &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; GROW &LR;  - Question: As the date to file tax returns rapidly
approaches, what tips are CPAs offering their clients this year?
Columnist Peter Sinton has the answer.
</P>
