<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CPA Tips On Filing Tax Returns  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  As the date to file tax returns rapidly approaches, what
tips are CPAs offering their clients this year?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The California Society of Certified Public Accountants
and CPAs Sharon Kreider of Sunnyvale, Craig Malmgren of the Oakland
firm Lautze &AMP; Lautze and Sandy Murray of San Francisco's Burr
Pilger &AMP; Mayer pinpoint important changes in the tax code and
issues to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Schedule C Under Scrutiny: &LR;  Suspicious that many home-based
business owners are merely hobbyists who submit a Schedule C to
deduct hobby-related expenses, the Internal Revenue Service is
becoming more scrupulous and sophisticated in examining these
home-based business filings.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is looking for signs of abuse. For example, a
business that reports losses of less than $10,000 three years in a
row raises a red flag. CPAs caution home-based business owners to
keep careful records, such as maintaining separate bank accounts,
to prove that their expenses are legitimate and relate to a serious
profit-seeking venture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Home Office Deductions:  &LR; Many more people will qualify for
home-office deductions. For your 1998 tax returns, you generally
can deduct expenses related to a home office if it is used
exclusively on a regular basis as your principal place of business
or the place you meet patients, clients or customers. In 1999, the
definition will be eased to include a place of business used by the
taxpayer for the administrative or management activities of the
business.
</P>
<P>
   But consider this: If you claim a home office deduction and
subsequently decide to sell your home, you run the risk of reducing
your $500,000 capital gains tax exclusion by the pro-rata portion
of your home dedicated to your home office. If you expect a big
profit from the sale of your house and plan to sell soon, you might
run through the numbers before electing to take a home office
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Health Insurance Benefit: &LR;  Self-employed individuals can deduct
45 percent of their health insurance premiums for 1998 (compared to
25 percent a year ago), even if they don't claim an itemized
deduction for medical expenses. &UR;  &LR; This deduction, on Page 1 of of
the self-employed taxpayer's Form 1040, will rise to 60 percent of
health insurance premiums in 1999. and by 2003 it will gradually
increase to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deduction is limited to earned income derived by the
business. You can also deduct one-half of your self-employment tax.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Business Expense Deductions:  &LR; Equipment purchased for use in
your business is generally depreciated over its useful life.
However, for 1998, $18,500 of new equipment can be expensed
immediately, instead of being depreciated over a number of years.
This accelerated depreciation will gradually rise to $25,000 by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW24 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  But take note: The 1998 limit for California state tax returns is
only $16,000. For 1999 taxes, the California limit will rise to
$19,000, the same level for deductions on federal tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Business meals and entertainment are still deductible up to 50
percent but complete documentation is required to withstand IRS
scrutiny. That means recording not only time, date and place but
also the business purpose and the specific business that was
discussed over the meal. Club dues are no longer tax deductible,
but dues paid to professional and public service organizations
generally are deductible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dialing for Deductions:  &LR; Cellular phones are considered
personal property. Therefore, cell phone calls are assumed to be
personal, unless you can prove otherwise. Your monthly billing
records are the key.
</P>
<P>
   However, you might have a problem getting an itemized list of
calls if your cellular service contract includes hundreds of free
minutes of usage each month. That makes it nearly impossible to
track _ and, if necessary, to prove _ that your calls were
business-related.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Road Wage: &LR;  The standard mileage rate deduction is changing and
for once is going down, not up. The rate will go from 32.5 cents
per mile in 1998 to 31 cents per mile in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, it gets worse! The rate change doesn't go into effect
until April 1. That's going to create record-keeping headaches for
small-business owners (and tax preparers), who next year will have
to calculate the mileage deduction based on miles accrued before
and after April 1. However, there is good news for those who lease
their cars. Starting in 1998, miles driven in a leased car are
deductible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gifts to Clients:  &LR; Gifts to clients (but not their spouses or
kids) are deductible as a business expense but there's a catch.
Your deduction is limited to $25 per client per year. If you sent
expensive flowers or gift baskets, remember less costly gifts may
be more appropriate. At least from a tax standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Taxing Day Traders:  &LR; The growth of online trading has given
rise to the ``day-trading'' phenomenon, where individual investors
buy and rapidly sell the same stock, usually within 24 hours. Day
traders say they are in it for short-term profit rather than
appreciation. In other words, they consider themselves traders as
opposed to investors.
</P>
<P>
   But they may have a hard time convincing the IRS this activity
is a business pursuit. The IRS would prefer to treat day trading as
an investment activity, which puts considerably greater
restrictions on what you can deduct.
</P>
<P>
   A business can deduct interest and other expenses like research
and computer services and supplies. By contrast, an investor can
only offset interest expenses against interest income. And other
expenses must be itemized and cannot be deducted unless they are in
excess of 2 percent of the individual's adjusted gross income.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of GROW24 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Stay Tuned:  &LR; More tax tips will be offered next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
