A6664 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISA-SFCHRON &LR;      02-23 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Citigroup Shuffle May Weaken Antitrust Case Against Visa  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Citigroup's apparent move to jilt Visa in favor of MasterCard may
have pulled the rug out from under the federal government's
far-reaching credit card antitrust case, legal experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, in a case that could reshape the credit card
industry, the Justice Department's antitrust division filed a
lawsuit challenging what it characterizes as a sweetheart
relationship between Visa and MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   The two credit card networks are run by the same group of big
banks, the lawsuit claims. Visa and MasterCard don't really compete
with each other, but split up the market between themselves and
keep out rivals such as American Express, the Justice Department
maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Now Citigroup's apparent decision to shift most of its business
from Visa to MasterCard highlights a competitive rivalry between
the two networks, antitrust specialists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It runs counter to the idea that the two associations move in
lockstep,'' said William Kovacic, a visiting law professor at
George Washington University in Washington. ``It tends to undercut
the government's concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the No.2 issuer of Visa cards, had been locked in a
dispute with Visa over the association's heavy promotion of the
Visa brand name. Visa's marketing took attention away from
Citigroup's efforts to build its own identity, the bank maintained.
</P>
<P>
   According to Visa officials, the association offered to put the
Visa name on the back of credit cards, leaving the front
exclusively for Citigroup. But, association officials have said,
the bank wanted Visa to sharply cut back its brand-building
activities, such as its well-known ``Everywhere you want to be'' TV
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, two Citigroup directors quit Visa's board
following the breakdown of talks on the branding issue. Visa
officials said they believed that Citigroup had cut a deal with
MasterCard, in which the association would avoid promoting its own
name and focus instead on processing transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reinforces what we have said all along, that this is an
intensely competitive'' marketplace, Visa spokesman Kelly Presta
said.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup and MasterCard both declined comment on their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   If Citigroup has indeed abandoned Visa for MasterCard, that
would address one of the most important issues raised by the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, filed in a New York federal court, the Justice
Department sought an order barring banks that sit on the board of
one association from also governing the other association. By
apparently casting its lot with MasterCard, Citigroup may have done
exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of alignment is what we've been looking for, but
this is just one bank,'' said Justice spokeswoman Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
   The key question is whether other big issuers will follow
Citigroup's example, leading to a wholesale shifting of alliances.
Other major credit card issuers, such as BankAmerica and Chase
Manhattan, worry about brand competition from Visa, though there is
no evidence that they also will shift to MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a handful of others that are thinking about these
issues, but I don't know if any of them are as aggressive'' as
Citigroup, said Anita Boomstein, a New York attorney specializing
in credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Unless other major credit card issuers also break with Visa,
``it's not likely to cause the government to go away,'' said Joe
Sims, an antitrust attorney with the Washington firm Jones, Day,
Reavis &AMP; Pogue.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VISA24 (x1139 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Citigroup-Visa quarrel has no direct bearing on the other
issue raised by Justice _ the associations' rules prohibiting
members from issuing cards other than Visa and MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, even if Justice loses in court, it might have won
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup's move to MasterCard highlights how market forces are
making the two networks more distinct. That undermines Justice's
strategy of casting them as Tweedledum and Tweedledee but reshapes
the credit industry along the lines the department wants.
</P>
<P>
   Visa's marketing juggernaut has overwhelmed MasterCard, which
has about one-quarter of the credit card market compared with
Visa's share of more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, MasterCard may be willing to agree to
Citigroup's demand to give up a strong brand strategy, positioning
itself instead as an efficient transaction processor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds a lot like network competition to me,'' Sims said.
``The government shouldn't care too much how they get to their
objective.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of VISA24 (x1139 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
