<SLUG> BC-EEOC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Record Settlement in Farmworkers' Suit  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Salinas lettuce grower has agreed to pay former employees more
than $1.85 million in the biggest settlement of a sexual harassment
case filed on behalf of farmworkers by the U.S. Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Tanimura &AMP; Antle, the nation's largest lettuce grower, said
yesterday the payment will go to former employee Blanca Alfaro and
other workers who say they faced sexual harassment or retaliation
for complaining about harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The payment is part of a settlement between Tanimura and the
EEOC, which was representing the workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers in the agricultural industry must realize that
sexual harassment and retaliation will not be tolerated,'' said
Susan McDuffie, district director of the EEOC.
</P>
<P>
   Tanimura _ which employs &UR;  &LR; more than 2,200 people each year in
fields and packing plants in Salinas, Oxnard and Arizona _ did not
admit any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But it agreed not to rehire two of the former managers named in
Alfaro's claim and said a third manager had been reprimanded and
sent to sexual harassment counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the $1.8 million payment, the company agreed to
provide sexual harassment training in Spanish and English to all
its workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were never able to substantiate the allegations made
by the EEOC, we feel it is in the best interest of our current and
former employees to resolve this matter by establishing a claim
fund for individuals who may have suffered from sexual harassment
under our employ,'' said Tanimura President Rick Antle.
</P>
<P>
   Farmworker advocates have long complained about sexual
exploitation of women workers by foremen, who have broad power to
hire and fire individual laborers each season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get or keep jobs, it's not uncommon to hear stories of
women having to `put out,''' said Marc Grossman, a spokesman for
the United Farm Workers, which was not involved in the Tanimura
settlement. ``The problem is the corrupt system where workers have
to go hat-in-hand to the foreman for work every season, with no job
security and no seniority.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Tanimura case, Alfaro said the plant manager demanded
sexual favors from her as a condition of employment. She said a
foreman also made verbal advances toward her. When Alfaro
complained, the company retaliated by suspending and then firing
her, according to the EEOC.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of EEOC24 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Elias Aragon, a male Tanimura employee who complained about
Alfaro's treatment, also was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Alfaro and Aragon were the only employees named in the EEOC
complaint. But agency officials said they expect ``a handful'' of
others to come forward during the next few months and share in the
award.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to identify a handful of other women who were
subjected to harassment by the same men we identified in Alfaro's
case,'' said Sanya Hill, a senior trial attorney with the EEOC.
</P>
<P>
   EEOC officials said the Tanimura case is part of a recent
campaign to address the problem of sexual harassment in
agriculture. Last fall, the agency filed a harassment suit against
a Monterey County broccoli grower called Fresh West Harvesting _ a
case that has not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tanimura case, the grower reached a voluntary settlement
with the EEOC before a formal lawsuit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers said the high price tag of the settlement would
serve as a warning to other growers throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call to agricultural employers who are not
already doing things to prevent sexual harassment,'' said Larry
Shapiro, editor of the California Employer Advisor newsletter in
Tiburon.
</P>
<P>
   Before yesterday's settlement, Tanimura had provided sexual
harassment training to its managers. Now, it will provide annual
training to rank-and-file workers, too, at all three of its
locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really puts the agricultural community on notice that
they need to go beyond having a harassment policy and must really
talk to their employees and show them how to use the complaint
process,'' said Carmen Ponce, human resources director at Tanimura.
</P>
<P>
   Tanimura's main crop is lettuce, but it also grows broccoli,
cauliflower and celery.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of EEOC24 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
