<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BofA Will Close Retail Broker Site in Oakland  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BankAmerica will close its Oakland retail brokerage call center
later this year, eliminating about 100 jobs, a bank spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown will come as BankAmerica of North Carolina merges
the operations of the old BofA of San Francisco and the former
NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   In a phaseout expected to be completed by September, the bank
will transfer the work of the Oakland call center to facilities in
Seattle and Charlotte, N.C. Staff at the center, located at 180
Grand Ave. near Lake Merritt, handle investors' questions about the
bank's brokerage business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take some time for this to be implemented,'' said BofA
spokeswoman Ann Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The latest cutback is separate from the bank's announcement in
December that it would eliminate 300 back-office jobs nationwide at
the brokerage unit. Before NationsBank bought BofA, the brokerage
units of the two banks together employed more than 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will offer some Oakland employees jobs in Seattle and
Charlotte, Anderson said. Those who don't want to move will get an
inside track for other bank-job openings or be eligible for
severance packages that include three weeks pay for every year at
BofA.
</P>
<P>
   BofA plans to move other employees into the office space vacated
by the call center, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   BofA has said it expects to shed about 23,000 jobs over the next
few years, more than 10 percent of its workforce. Some of the
cutbacks will come from combining BofA and NationsBank operations,
while others will reflect the bank's drive to become leaner and
more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   While the bank said most job cuts will occur through normal
turnover, it still expects to lay off 5,000 to 8,000 employees as a
result of last year's takeover.
</P>
<P>
   In one Northern California example, BofA has cut almost 200
management jobs in its retail branches since the NationsBank
takeover. Those cuts weren't related to the takeover, but reflected
the bank's move to a ``revised staffing model,'' a spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
