<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Know When Someone You Love Is a Tech-Stock Junkie  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Do you crave Yahoo shares every time the search-engine concern
splits its stock?
</P>
<P>
   Or do you own shares in companies that display hip billboards
off Highway 101, but you have no earthly idea what they make or do?
</P>
<P>
   Then perhaps you have a problem. You might be a tech-stock
junkie. That's what concerns financial adviser William Urban of
Bingham, Osborn &AMP; Scarborough. Urban says too many investors in the
Bay Area have felt the exhilarating high of soaring technology
shares, prompting them to develop a dependency that could be
detrimental to their financial health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that we've seen a number of our clients,
particularly in Silicon Valley, who have a lot of overconfidence in
their expectations of technology stocks,'' says Urban, who heads
the San Francisco firm's Menlo Park office.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when the tech-heavy Nasdaq stock market rises 1.5
percent while both the Dow Jones industrial average and the S&AMP;P 500
tumbles, like they did yesterday, it is easy to understand why
technology stocks are so compelling. The Nasdaq is up 7.8 percent
for the year, compared with 4.2 percent for the Dow and 3.8 percent
for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when individual investors, who essentially are saving for
retirement, have as much as 20 to 25 percent of their total assets
invested in technology stocks, ``the alarms start to go off for
us,'' Urban says.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, investors own way too many shares of their own
employer's stock or too many shares of a tech company of which they
are familiar but don't fundamentally understand.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, Urban says, that the volatility of technology
stocks can wreak havoc on a personal portfolio, causing overall
long-term investment performance to suffer. Hot tech stocks, such
as Internet concerns or newly minted software IPOs, can become huge
winners. But they just as often can be horrible clunkers that
investors tend to block out of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET24 (99185 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Part of the problem is selective memory,'' Urban notes.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Urban's firm preaches a textbook approach to
managing personal portfolios, asking its clients to allocate their
investments over a broad range of stocks, bonds and cash. Thus, too
much of anything _ whether General Motors shares or municipal bonds
_ isn't considered wise either, Urban says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's OK to invest in technology equities once the rest
of your portfolio is in balance. The tech sector often seems to
rise and fall regardless of how the broader market performs. Thus,
the right dose of technology investments is an important
diversification tool, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Urban recommends that investors allocate 5 to 10 percent of
their stock holdings (not total assets!) in technology funds with
historically low expense ratios. Or if investors insist on owning
individual stocks instead of funds, then it's important that those
holdings still remain within the allotment allowed for tech stocks,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for most tech junkies, they own too many shares
in too few companies, and that's where they get burned, Urban says.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of telltale signs. You know that you, or somebody
you love, have a tech-stock dependency problem when the investor:
</P>
<P>
   _is positive that he knows what will be the next big tech-stock
``winner'' (i.e. the next Micrsoft, Intel etc.).
</P>
<P>
   _is confident that he can beat the average investor who plays
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   _is using college funds and retirement savings to buy techs.
</P>
<P>
   _has invested more than a quarter of his portfolio in tech
stocks or funds.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you happen to know anyone who fits the above profile,
direct them to a boring index fund as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RIGHT! &LR; : Hedge fund manager James Cramer could be in for one of the
biggest trades of his career. Yesterday, Cramer's TheStreet.com
filed to go public with the Securities and Exchange Commission. The
filing says that the financial Web site hopes to raise as much as
$75 million by selling 7.5 million shares in an offering
lead-managed by Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   You knew it was bound to happen sooner or later, especially
after the monumental success of the MarketWatch.com public offering
last month. And if that IPO is any indicator, TheStreet.com (which
of course employs the previous occupant of this space, Herb
Greenberg), is poised to perform handsomely. If TheStreet.com's
shares happen to fetch a post-IPO price price similar to that of
MarketWatch's current $65 a share, Cramer's 2.7 million shares
could be worth a cool $175.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELECTRIC SWITCH: &LR;  It's often noteworthy when a large
corporation dumps its accounting firm for another auditor. So
Street Smarts took notice yesterday when PG&AMP;E revealed that it has
replaced Arthur Andersen with Deloitte &AMP; Touche, according to a
filing with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   PGE spokesman Greg Pruett says his company had no dispute with
Andersen but that Deloitte made a good fit because of the firm's
expertise in energy, specifically its previous experience with
deregulation. Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
