<SLUG> BC-JASPER-HATE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKERS RENEW CALL FOR PASSAGE OF HATE CRIMES BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See JASPER-KING and JASPER-TRIAL, which will move shortly.) 
 
By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Moments after a white supremacist was convicted
Tuesday for the violent murder of a black man, state lawmakers said
they hoped the verdict would bolster their efforts to pass a new
hate crimes bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, who wrote the current hate
crimes bill, said the verdict does little to change her opinion
that such a law is needed in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   John William ``Bill'' King was convicted in less than 2 1/2
hours for the murder of James Byrd Jr., 49.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, was the first of three white men to be tried for
Byrd's dragging death last summer in Jasper, a death the hate crime
bill's sponsors say was racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is needed to deter other persons from taking
advantage of others because of hatred they feel,'' Thompson said.
``In Texas, hate crimes are just taken too lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, filed as Senate Bill 275 by Sen. Rodney Ellis,
D-Houston, and House Bill 148 by Thompson, is called the James Byrd
Jr. Act. Previous efforts to clarify the current hate crimes law,
in response to criticism that it's too vague to enforce, failed in
the 1995 and 1997 legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The House version of the bill will be heard by the Judicial
Affairs Committee March 11. The Senate version has been referred to
the Criminal Justice Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Royce West, a Dallas Democrat who co-authored the Senate
version, said he is elated by the guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this lets us all know that we need to do something to
make sure this doesn't happen again, to do whatever we can to make
sure people who commit these types of crimes will receive severe
ramifications,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' current law, passed in 1993 and also written by Ellis,
increased penalties by one level of offense if a crime was proven
to be ``motivated by bias or prejudice.'' For example, a murder
would be prosecuted as a capital murder. But Ellis said it has been
used by few prosecutors because there is concern about a
constitutional challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The new bill would change the definition of a hate crime so that
offenses motivated by race, color, disability, religion, national
origin, ancestry or sexual orientation could be prosecuted as hate
crimes. Ellis said the proposed wording has been upheld by the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Forty states and the District of Columbia have enacted hate
crimes laws.
</P>
<P>
   Besides clarifying the definition of a hate crime, the bill
would provide aid to small counties prosecuting murders considered
to be hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
