<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     02-23 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PRESSES ATTACK ON MICROSOFT'S CREDIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government's lead lawyer accused a Microsoft
executive of making up evidence at the antitrust trial on Tuesday,
and, after presenting the witness with his own e-mail contradicting
his statements, forced him to correct his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom incident focused on a matter of timing: when the
executive, Daniel Rosen, had known that a software rival was making
an Internet browser to run on the Microsoft Windows 95 operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   On its own, it is not a central element in the government's case
against Microsoft Corp. But the episode is part of the government's
persistent effort to undermine the credibility of Microsoft
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft, the credibility issue has become enough of a
problem that U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson joked that
Microsoft's lawyer was embarking on a ``heroic endeavor'' when he
began questioning Rosen on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second day that David Boies, the Justice Department's
lead trial lawyer, and Rosen had clashed concerning the software
giant's intentions and actions at a key meeting with a competitor
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The session is a key chapter in the government case against
Microsoft, and the court's determination of exactly what happened
at the meeting could affect the outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insists that the session with executives of Netscape
Communications Corp. was a routine business meeting intended to
find ``common ground'' on which the two companies could cooperate
concerning Internet software. Rosen was the executive who led the
Microsoft team at that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that Microsoft threatened Netscape at
the meeting and made an illegal offer to divide up the Internet
browser market _ a deal that Netscape says it refused.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have made their arguments in court this week with
piles of e-mail and harsh words. When Rosen was dismissed by the
court at midday, it was clear that executives of Netscape and
Microsoft left the 1995 meeting with very different views of what
had happened.
</P>
<P>
   The real fireworks Tuesday came after Rosen said he did not
regard Netscape as a rival in June 1995 and that one of his goals
was to ``encourage them to write a good browser for Windows 95'' _
the Microsoft operating system introduced in August 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Far from encouraging Netscape, however, the government contends
that Microsoft tried to persuade Netscape to cede the Windows 95
browser market to Microsoft, even though Netscape had long planned
to produce a Windows 95 browser.
</P>
<P>
   Boies asked Rosen when he had first obtained an advance copy of
Netscape's browser for Windows 95. Rosen replied that it was not
until after the June 21 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Boies then presented an e-mail dated May 11, 1995, that Rosen
wrote to another Microsoft executive. It included the notation
``Can i borrow/copy the Netscape Win 95 new client they gave us?''
The ``client'' refers to the new Netscape browser.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosen replied that he never got the test version, which he
said did not work properly.
</P>
<P>
   Boies responded: ``You don't remember that, do you? You're just
making that up right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said, ``No, I remember it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're sure it was May and not April?'' Boies asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen answered, ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Boies introduced an e-mail from Rosen to another
Microsoft executive on April 27 that said: ``Do you remember who
took the Netscape win 95 browser they gave us during our last
meeting? I'd like to get a copy.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with his own e-mail, Rosen paused, then said, ``I
stand corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, on the courthouse steps, Boies said the testimony
raised questions about Rosen's credibility and memory. ``He was
saying that he was trying to encourage Netscape to produce a
browser at the June meeting,'' Boies said. ``In fact, Netscape had
already done it and he had it.''
</P>
<P>
   The government presented notes taken by Marc Andreessen, a
founder of Netscape, at the June 21 meeting, in which he wrote that
Microsoft's proposals added up to a ``threat that Microsoft will
own the Windows 95 client market and that Netscape should stay
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also introduced as evidence an e-mail written on
June 22, 1995, by David Kaiser, an executive at America Online, to
another executive of the online service, recounting a conversation
he had with Andreessen.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser wrote that Andreessen told him that at the meeting the
previous day, Microsoft offered Netscape a deal: Microsoft would
invest in Netscape, take a seat on the board, and Netscape would
agree not to compete with Microsoft head-on.
</P>
<P>
   If Netscape accepted, Kaiser wrote Andreessen had told him, it
would become ``Microsoft's special partner.'' If Netscape rejected
the deal, Kaiser said in the e-mail, ``Microsoft would crush
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft also introduced documents that supported its
version of the June 21 meeting. An e-mail written on June 22 by
Richard Wolf, a Microsoft executive who attended the meeting, said
he did ``not think that they have the intention of competing with
us in defining a platform,'' for underlying Internet software that
Microsoft planned to include in Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wolf added, that ``does not mean they will drop a
broad-based client,'' meaning a browser.
</P>
<P>
   After the testimony, William Neukom, Microsoft's senior vice
president for law and corporate affairs, said: ``The record is
quite clear. There was no effort by Microsoft to dissuade Netscape
from creating a browser for Windows 95. It did and its browser was
quite popular.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
