<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCHPLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN OR GO HOME: GOLF'S ELITE 64 ARE READY FOR A SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Tiger Woods, David Duval and Mark O'Meara
spent Tuesday practicing together, preparing for a tournament that
all three would love to win.
</P>
<P>
   The highly anticipated Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship begins on Wednesday, bringing the world's best golfers
together in a single-elimination format that will be both
entertaining and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   There will be pressure from the opening tee shot. Half of the 64
players at La Costa Resort and Spa will be eliminated by Wednesday
night. Meanwhile, the road to Saturday's final four, followed by a
36-hole championship match on Sunday, will force the champion to
win six matches in five days against some of the world's best
players.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who takes the $1 million first-place check, the first
event in the new World Golf Championships series has already
accomplished one of its main objectives _ to bring the world's best
players together. Looking at the practice tee at La Costa on
Tuesday was like looking at the practice tee during a major, with
Woods, Duval, O'Meara, Davis Love III, Lee Westwood, Colin
Montgomerie, Ernie Els and Vijay Singh among the stars preparing
for the challenge. The atmosphere, and the names, confirmed that
something special was about to happen. And the fact that nobody
knew exactly what to expect only enhanced the anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about playing match play again, something I always
look forward to,'' said Woods, the No. 1-seeded player, who will
face Nick Faldo, the six-time major winner but seeded No. 64, in
perhaps the most anticipated opening-round pairing. ``I love the
thrill of playing one-on-one. It's a chance to put your skills up
against one person, head-to-head. Most sports, that's the way it
works. We don't get that chance very often.''
</P>
<P>
   But in match play, one bad day can mean the end of your
tournament. While Faldo has been struggling for more than a year,
he enters Wednesday's match as the underdog with little to lose. If
Woods jumps to an early lead, the match could be a rout. But if
Faldo stays close until the final few holes, almost anything might
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be some upsets,'' said O'Meara, who will
face Michael Bradley on Wednesday. ``But I don't know how you can
really call it an upset, because the guys in the top 64 are all
good players. Nick has been struggling, but Nick is a tremendous
competitor, and he has a tremendous record. I would think Tiger has
the advantage. But I would never count out Nick Faldo.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other compelling first-round matches include Tom
Watson versus Bob Tway, Els versus Paul Azinger, Steve Elkington
versus Steve Jones and Montgomerie versus Craig Stadler. In
addition, Greg Norman, who missed seven months following shoulder
surgery last year, will be making his first start of the year in
the United States when he faces John Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder is great; I practice every day,'' said Norman,
who has long been a proponent of having a world tour. ``I feel good
about this event, because I can see a lot of the ideas that I had
starting to take place. I think it's good for the game of golf.
There are enough great players now on a global basis that we need
to see them playing against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   While the year's two other world championship events _ the NEC
Invitational (Aug. 26-29) and the American Express Invitational
(Nov. 4-7) _ will also have world-class fields, they will be stroke
play events, not match play, making this week even more special. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
