<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AF-RECRUIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE LAUNCHES 1ST TV RECRUITING CAMPAIGN TO MEET GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ If Robert Kitto was selling Cadillacs, he'd be a rich
man.
</P>
<P>
   But Kitto is selling a four- to six-year commitment _ and he's
not making commission.
</P>
<P>
   The technical sergeant is one of the Phoenix area's top Air
Force recruiters. But, he said, ``I'm only one voice and I can only
talk so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Kitto is exceeding his recruitment goals, many of the
1,000 Air Force recruiters nationwide are not. For the first time
in two decades, the Air Force is falling short of the number of
enlistees needed to fill its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Air Force has prided itself on needing little
advertisement to attract recruits. But faced with unprecedented job
growth in the private sector, that's about to change.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is launching its first television campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For the first spot alone, which will air Feb. 27 during an NCAA
conference championship game, it is paying $17 million _ more than
double the Air Force marketing budget of just a few years ago.
Hoping to capitalize on the thousands of young basketball fans who
will tune in to the tourney, the Air Force has also signed up as a
sponsor for the NCAA Road to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   It also plans to purchase more air time in major cities through
the summer, and beyond. Between future ads and the usual print and
radio ads and promotional brochures, the Air Force marketing blitz
could top $76 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, young men and women look toward television
now,'' said Major Derek Kaufman, U.S. Air Force recruiting
spokesman. ``This isn't going to turn around recruiting overnight
but we're hoping to reach out and show we are a viable option to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the hot economy or the end of the Cold War, budget
cuts or base closures. Whatever the reason, recruiters say more
young people than ever are opting for sizable salaries over
service.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with some of the worst recruiting shortages in two
decades, the U.S. Army has added an extra 1,000 recruiters, boosted
its ad budget to nearly $100 million and offered a few thousand
dollars in additional sign-up bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as of last fall, it is 2,300 short of recruiting
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy fell nearly 7,000 short of its recruiting goals last
year, said spokesman Lt. Blaine McLaughlin. It caught up this year,
after adding more recruiters and more sign-up stations and
increasing its ad budget by $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Marine Corps is the only branch that has not only met,
but exceeded, its recruiting goals. It signed up 40,366 enlistees
last year, said Gunnery Sgt. Cynthia Atwood, public affairs chief
for the Marine Corps Recruiting Command. It spends a fraction of
what other branches do on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines advertising budget for fiscal year 1998 is about
$9.5 million, most on television spots.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is the only branch that has never paid for
television advertising, relying instead on public service ads,
films like ``Top Gun,'' and a reputation for highly regarded
technical training.
</P>
<P>
   This year it needs to recruit 33,800 to meet projections, but
since October the Air Force has fallen behind by more than 6
percent. ``We are seriously struggling,'' Kaufman added.
</P>
<P>
   Even with unprecedented signing bonuses of up to $9,000,
proposed pay raises, and an increase of more than $24,000 in
scholarship money available to those who join in college, the Air
Force has had trouble attracting recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an overheating economy and young people today have
options,'' said Chief Master Sgt. Benken, the highest-ranking
enlisted man in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   It's been tough for ROTC recruiters as well, even at
Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University where many of the 1,500
students are there to learn to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Tri B. Trinh was hoping to recruit a class of 130 ROTC
students this year, but has barely reached half that goal. The Air
Force recently upped the commitment from eight to 10 years which
scared some potential recruits off.
</P>
<P>
   But Trinh said the Air Force last month announced it would
increase scholarship amounts from $9,000 to $15,000 per year plus
provide additional money for books and living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities are just tremendous right now but we're
competing against a booming economy,'' Trinh said. ``You're not
going to get rich in the military. People that join do so because
they want to serve their country.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough of a reason, the Air Force has introduced
unprecedented enlistment bonuses from $1,000 to $9,000 in more than
two-thirds of its specialties, from pararescuers to pharmacists.
Those who sign up for six instead of four years can earn even more.
</P>
<P>
   The incentives have helped increase the number of six-year
enlistees by 30 percent, but the overall number of recruits has
remained below projections. Enlistees dropped by about 20,000
between 1997 and last year. Air Force officer ranks have slimmed as
well.
</P>
<P>
   One problem may be that the Air Force has only 1,200 recruiter
positions, and some are unfilled. Kaufman said filling them has
only recently become a priority.
</P>
<P>
   When recruiter Tech. Sgt. Kitto came to the Phoenix area in late
1997, he was the first full-time recruiter at the
northwest-Phoenix-area office in more than a year. Area school
administrators told him no one from the Air Force had stepped foot
on their campuses for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Kitto has recruited more than 65 Air Force enlistees. But his
recruiting goals for this month have actually increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what recruiting was like before, but now you work
harder than ever, and longer hours, for what you get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kitto has recruited the boy bagging his groceries at the
check-out stand, and another man he met while waiting in line to
pay for dinner at a local Denny's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have your business cards on you,'' he said. ``We're
not afraid to recruit anywhere.'' &QL; 
Jennifer Barrett can be reached at 444-7113 or at
jennifer.barrett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
