<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-SULLIVAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SULLIVAN NAMED FIRST WOMAN DEAN AT STANFORD LAW SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BILL STAGGS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kathleen M. Sullivan, a constitutional lawyer
nationally known for her scholarly sound bites as a frequent guest
on television public affairs and news programs, has been named the
first woman dean of the Stanford University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sullivan _ one of the ``50 Most Influential Women Lawyers in
America,'' according to the National Law Journal last year _
assumes her new job in September. Her predecessor, Paul Brest, is
returning to teaching at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhard Casper, the university's president, announced the
appointment on Monday after a five-month search. The law school has
580 students and 40 faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as Paul Brest pushed the law school in new directions,''
Casper said, ``Kathleen will bring fresh perspective to legal
education, at Stanford and nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sullivan, 43, began teaching law at age 29 at Harvard, where
she had earned her law degree in 1981. In 1993, she was appointed
the first Stanley Morrison Professor of Law at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   An active appellate litigator who has argued numerous First
Amendment cases in federal and state courts, and two in the Supreme
Court, Ms. Sullivan has often been mentioned by national legal and
news magazines as a potential Supreme Court nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt destined for a role in public service, and I
do have an interest in public service some day,'' said Ms. Sullivan
about her future.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sullivan, a Democrat, filed a friend-of-the-court brief in
the Paula Jones case, arguing that it would be unconstitutional to
sue President Clinton while in office. She filed the brief at the
invitation of professors who were addressing the constitutional
issues on behalf of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   She has discussed the complexities of constitutional law on
programs ranging from ``Crossfire'' to ``Nightline'' to ``Lehrer
Newshour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think constitutional law, and public law generally, is
enjoying a surge of new and fresh interest,'' said Ms. Sullivan,
who is co-author of the most recent edition of ``Constitutional
Law,'' a legal textbook, and ``First Amendment Law,'' both written
with Gerhard Gunther, a professor emeritus of Stanford. She also
wrote ``New Federalist Papers: Essays in Defense of the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a silver lining in what some people have called
our recent constitutional crisis,'' she said, ``it's that it has
gotten students' attention about the importance of law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
