<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMWEST STOCK PLUNGES; EVENTUAL SALE NOT RULED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   America West Airlines' stock sank Tuesday as investors hoping
for a big-dollar takeover bailed out after the company said it's
going to fly solo.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe company's shares fell $3.25, to $18.13, a 15 percent
drop. It was one of the biggest losers on the New York Stock
Exchange, where more than 1 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   The decline puts the stock back in the range it was in before
takeover speculation began a month ago. It started after America
West announced that it had been approached by a number of airlines
interested in buying the company or creating a partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Several major airlines were mentioned as possible suitors, but
United is the only one that confirmed its interest and, reportedly,
made a cash offer.
</P>
<P>
   America West Chairman William A. Franke said Monday that the
company has ended talks with other airlines because there were too
many conditions attached to the proposed deals and because there
were regulatory and employee issues to consider.
</P>
<P>
   In a message to employees late Monday, he said America West
hired an investment banking firm, three law firms and other
advisors to help it evaluate the merger proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied that the result that was reached is exactly the
right one for the airline under the circumstances we find ourselves
in,'' he said, calling the talks a ``difficult, time-consuming
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline has to entertain any future offers, of course, but
Franke said the plan is to remain independent and grow
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts and other industry observers say the bidding for
America West might not be over.
</P>
<P>
   The same factors that made it attractive to United and other
suitors _ such as strength in the West and a relatively young fleet
_ remain, as do industry forces such as a slowdown in traffic that
will stunt airlines' growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that a deal will eventually be struck; the
incentives for consolidation are higher and growing,'' Egan-Jones
Ratings Co., a debt rating service, said in a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Schwieterman, a DePaul University economist and former
United Airlines analyst, also thinks America West will be an
eventual target.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the airline's small size _ $2 billion in annual sales
vs. $17 billion for industry leader United _ and the key markets it
serves, which attract vacationers rather than high-fare business
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``America West has a precarious market position and can't afford
to turn a blind eye toward a good offer that comes their way,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Hegeman, who runs the Internet site PlaneBusiness.com and
broke the story about the United and America West talks, was more
cynical about America West's announcement. She suggested that it
might be a ploy to get a better deal from United or another
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do not think that Bill Franke went out tonight and put
the `Do Not Disturb' sign on the door of AWA headquarters,'' she
wrote Monday in her daily column.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of talks was announced, an America West
shareholder filed a lawsuit in Delaware Chauncery Court challenging
Continental Airlines' right of first refusal on any offer for the
controlling stake in America West held by a Texas investment group.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder Odette Muskin, whose holdings weren't disclosed,
argued that the stipulation favors Continental and the investment
group, TPG Partners, at the expense of ordinary shareholders in any
merger transaction. The defendants are America West, its senior
executives and board members and TPG. &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at 444-8617, or at
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Republic writer Peter Corbett contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
