<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-SEAT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Isakson to replace Gingrich in Georgia
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Johnny Isakson surged out of a six-candidate pack
Tuesday to win the race to replace Newt Gingrich in Washington
without a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly two-thirds of the vote counted, the longtime
Marietta legislator and real estate company president had taken 62
percent of the vote to claim the 6th District seat, vacated by
Gingrich last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are overwhelmed with the support Johnny has gotten
throughout the district. ... I think it will set a record in a
special election,'' said Isakson campaign manager Heath Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with nearly $1 million in campaign donations, a fund that
dwarfed his competitors, Isakson surfed on a small but steady
stream of voters in four north metro Atlanta counties.
</P>
<P>
   His nearest competitor, Christina Jeffrey, a 51-year-old
Kennesaw State University professor, was next with 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson could be sworn in by House Speaker Dennis Hastert as
early as Thursday. Chances are, he would move into the same offices
in the Rayburn Building in Washington that Gingrich held before he
was elected House speaker by his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing far behind Isakson and Jeffrey were: Barry Doublestein,
44, a GOP activist from Snellville; Gary Pelphrey, 63, a Marietta
attorney; Leigh Baier, 57, a Vinings attorney; and Marco Longo, a
27-year-old salesman from Duluth. Kelly Brown of Alpharetta was a
write-in candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half a million voters in four counties were eligible to
vote in the special, nonpartisan election to replace Gingrich, and
election officials said they were on target to reach a predicted 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Voting appeared heaviest in Cobb County, which contains nearly
half of the 6th District's registered voters _ and where Isakson
has appeared on the ballot at least 10 times before.
</P>
<P>
   This was Isakson's third try at high political office. He y
candidate who was able to mount a concerted television campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Pocketbook issues were the focus of the campaign, which took
place in the 23rd-richest congressional district out of 435 in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson promised to vote for a 10 percent tax cut in Congress, a
position favored by the national GOP, while Jeffrey tried to use
Isakson's long legislative record against him.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson lost his last statewide election, a Republican primary
race for the U.S. Senate, to Guy Millner. Abortion was a defining
issue in that campaign _ Isakson is against a ban on all abortions.
</P>
<P>
   But that issue was secondary in Tuesday's election, even though
some voters still stayed away from him because of his stand.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Long, a pre-kindergarten teacher, said she voted for
Jeffrey because of her strong position against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that she represented the conservative viewpoint like
Newt had done,'' said J.D. Grant, 33, a full-time student at
Kennesaw University who has taken classes under Jeffrey. ``Isakson
is a Democrat in Republican clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
