<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON SENDS QUIET MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Kings coach Larry Robinson kept the pucks in storage
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After a dismal 5-1 defeat in St. Louis on Monday, Robinson was
hoping to send a message with the puck-free practice, 40 minutes of
silent skating periodically punctuated by Robinson's shrill
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad when it comes to that at this point in the season,''
said Robinson, whose team plays the Detroit Red Wings, the two-time
defending Stanley Cup champs, tonight. ``You've got your regular
workers and then you've got your guys that push just hard enough
that they look like they're working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Insisting he wasn't referring specifically to any of his players
but to the NHL in general, he added, ``We have guys who got a
contract, were happy they got a contract and forgot what working
and playing hard is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   After praising the efforts of players such as winger Russ
Courtnall and defenseman Mattias Norstrom, Robinson said, ``You can
go on right down the line, and then you're going to get to the guys
that can make the difference, and you can pick them. I'm not going
to name names, but you can name the names, and you ask me, `Do they
come to play every night? Do they go hard every shift? Do they
practice hard every day?' I don't know if you can say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson tried a puck-free practice previously, on Jan. 12
following a 4-0 loss in San Jose the night before. In the next
game, the Kings responded with a 3-0 victory over Calgary, but two
nights after that, they lost 5-1 to Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's practice was interesting to watch, if not to
participate in, especially early, when Luc Robitaille ordered Rob
Blake off the ice. Robitaille said Blake has been playing for
several weeks with a sore groin and he was afraid the Kings' most
important player would aggravate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we want is for him to get hurt,'' Robitaille
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said, ``I guess I should give my (coach's) sweatshirt
to Luc then. If it was bothering (Blake), he should have come over
and told me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Pronger (stomach ailment) and Ray Ferraro (bruised toe)
also sat out the practice, as did both goalies.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said Robinson's approach was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know what to do,'' Blake said. ``What can he do?
He's done everything right. It's up to the players. That's why
today was exactly right. You have to skate us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
