<SLUG> BC-STREETCOM-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESTREET.COM PLANS TO RAISE UP TO $75 MILLION IN OFFERING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ TheStreet.com, the online financial news service,
said Tuesday that it would seek to raise as much as $75 million in
an initial public offering of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed offering is intended to capitalize on investors'
vast appetite for stock in Internet-related companies.
TheStreet.com also has the added draw of its co-founder, James J.
Cramer, a hedge-fund manager and financial commentator who appears
on television, in print and in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   If TheStreet.com raises the full proposed amount, it will
outstrip some other recent Internet offerings in size at least. At
$75 million, the offering will almost double the recent offering of
Marketwatch.com, the financial news service that is partly owned by
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Marketwatch.com sold 23 percent of its stock to the
public for $47 million, issuing 2.75 million shares for $17 each.
Those shares vaulted as high as $130 on their first day of trading,
and Tuesday closed at $65.50. TheStreet.com did not disclose in its
filing what part it planned to sell to the public.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, Marketwatch.com had $7 million in total revenue
last year; TheStreet.com had $4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com has grown to about 37,000 subscribers on Feb. 17
from 32,000 at the end of last year. But, like most Internet
start-up companies, it has lost money since its founding in 1996.
Last year, the losses totaled $16.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising accounted for about $2.5 million, or 55 percent of
total revenue last year. By the end of January, TheStreet.com had
already signed contracts for $3.1 million of advertising this year.
</P>
<P>
   One advertiser, which was not identified, accounted for 40
percent of last year's ad revenues, or 22 percent of the total
revenues. About 36 percent of total revenue came from subscription
sales, with the remainder from syndication fees and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing on Tuesday with securities regulators, the company
did not disclose how many shares would be sold or at what price.
But earlier this month TheStreet.com sold shares to The New York
Times Co. for about $11 each and to another, undisclosed investor
for $12 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. said on Monday that it had invested $15 million in
cash and services in exchange for an equity stake in TheStreet.com
equivalent to about 8 percent of the company. Tuesday's filing
showed that the Times Co. received 1.32 million shares of common
stock and 37,728 shares of preferred shares.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of December, before the Times Co.'s investment and
excluding outstanding options on 1.5 million shares, TheStreet.com
had 13.7 million shares outstanding. The Times Co. becomes its
third-largest shareholder, behind the company's co-founders, Cramer
and Martin Peretz, editor in chief and chairman of The New Republic
magazine. Cramer owns about 2.7 million common shares and Peretz
owns about 2.6 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
