<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: RENTING ALL THE ROOMS; CUSTOMER CUSTOMIZATION;
HEALTHFUL HOTEL; AIRLINE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wash., Fla.)   (Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's hotels will not be filled exclusively with
corporate partygoers to welcome in the year 2000, but many hotel
owners would like that to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   The 627-room Millennium Broadway in Times Square is thought to
have started the ball rolling by offering its hotel and staff from
Dec. 31, 1999, through Jan. 2, 2000, for $3 million. Then the
155-room Fitzpatrick Grand Central Hotel made itself and its staff
available those same dates for $1.5 million, followed by the
92-room Fitzpatrick Manhattan, which is available for $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the 100-room Woodmark Hotel in Kirkland, Wash., a suburb of
Seattle, joined the hotel sweepstakes with an asking price of
$199,900. And now the Kimpton Hotel and Restaurant Group in San
Francisco, which operates hotels and restaurants mostly in the
West, is accepting bids for its three hotels in Seattle and their
adjoining restaurants. The asking price for all six properties is
$400,000, or between $120,000 and $200,000 for a combined hotel
(depending on the size) and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was to offer the hotels only to corporations,
but now the public is also invited to bid. Why the change of heart?
Because, said Charlotte Morgan Wayte, a Kimpton hotel spokeswoman,
``We wondered if people are really going to want to celebrate the
millennium with people they work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Room With a View
</P>
<P>
   Many hotel Web sites enable guests to view the rooms,
restaurants and even the landscaping at individual properties. But
Starwood Hotels and Resorts plans to announce Wednesday a Web site
designed by IBM that not only allows frequent guests to make
reservations online but also to customize the Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Most hotel marketing programs are based on profiles developed
from guests' past preferences _ whether they stayed in a
traditional room or suite, smoking or nonsmoking, even whether they
preferred a room facing north, south, east or west. But Starwood
Preferred Guest members can now update that information whenever
their preferences change, and they can redeem their ``Starpoints''
online as well as obtain access to current promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Check In, Checkup
</P>
<P>
   Guests of the Peabody Hotel in Orlando, Fla., can get both a
good night's sleep and a physical checkup that includes cholesterol
screening, cardiac stress test, massage therapy, relaxation and
Yoga. The arrangement is possible because of Peabody's recent
partnership with the Institute for Corporate Wellness, part of a
seven-hospital system in central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Checkups normally cost $1,000 but are available to Peabody
guests for $850. The hotel said it did not receive any money for
the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the health front, guests of the Jalousie Hilton Resort
and Spa in St. Lucia, the West Indies, can now make appointments to
see the island's resident bush doctor, Daniel Cherubin, who
dispenses hands-on healing and concocts natural herbal medicine
from his garden or the island's rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   Airline Update
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, Continental Airlines will begin daily nonstop
service between Newark, N.J., and Amsterdam, Netherlands, subject
to approval by the Netherlands. And effective now, Continental and
Chase Manhattan Bank will offer the first co-branded debit card.
Users of the card, which has a $30 annual fee, will earn one
frequent-flier mile on Continental for every $2 spent on purchases,
compared with one mile earned for $1 spent with the existing
Continental-Chase credit card.
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, US Airways will add one daily nonstop flight between
Philadelphia and each of 10 cities: Atlanta, Baltimore, Chicago,
Cleveland, Denver, Indianapolis, Los Angeles, Minneapolis,
Pittsburgh and Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
