<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS SEASON IS ALREADY 20% FINISHED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was only 13 months ago _ when time ran at a slower
pace _ that the Nets trooped into the big city for the rivalry that
is not all that much of a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, there was room for perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose, we've got 50 left,'' said John Calipari, then and
now the coach of the Team Across the River. ``That's the way I'm
approaching it.''
</P>
<P>
   What lovely, leisurely days they were, days when a marginal team
could put on a stretch run in March and challenge for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In this air ball of a season, there is no time for dawdling.
When the rich tall guys started huffing and puffing down the court,
there were only 50 games left.
</P>
<P>
   For the Knicks and the Nets, there are now only 40 games left.
Time is already a problem for the New Jersey franchise, which was
supposed to be on the rise. But instead, the Nets were 2-8 after
Tuesday night's 82-74 loss to the Knicks, who improved to 7-3. The
Nets have almost no margin for prolonged failure in this short,
strange season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no reason to worry about making the playoffs,'' Jeff
Van Gundy, the coach of the Knicks, said before the game. ``They
have too much talent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he really say that?'' asked Jayson Williams of the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Assured that Van Gundy had indeed said it, Williams laughed and
said, ``Aw, he's just doing that Michael Jordan thing: `Come on out
and I'll buy you a steak.'''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy does not blow smoke, and seemed quite sincere about
praising the Nets. He admits that in this short, strange season
that every game is worth more than a normal game _ something like
1.6 of a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it works both ways,'' Van Gundy said. ``If you win, or if
you lose, a game is worth more.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. In these post-Jordanian times, somebody is going to
take a championship, and it might as well be a sprinter as a
marathoner. Horses for courses, as they say at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Just as some frisky little colts have run off with the
short-short Preakness, couldn't somebody make a burst from the
starting gate, get up some momentum and gallop right toward the
Fourth of July or whenever this mutation of a season will finally
end?
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins this season is going to wear a gigantic asterisk
for eternity, not that the team will mind. The Nets badly needed a
victory over the Knicks in the rivalry that exists only in the most
fevered imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   For the Nets, Madison Square Garden is a bright place across the
river where they play sometimes. For the Knicks, the preoccupation
has been with the Chicago Bulls and the Indiana Pacers, although
Van Gundy said, ``As long as I've been here, they've always played
us tough.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Knicks are 26-15 against the Nets since Van Gundy
joined the organization in 1989, but even beyond the record, there
is just not that much acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   This town is dying for a good rivalry. The best rivalry this
town ever had reached its peak in early September 1951, when the
resurgent New York Giants lounged insolently behind the batting
cage, telling their chums, the Brooklyn Dodgers, that they were
back in the pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, baseball was willing to toss aside its history
of separate leagues to put the Mets and the Yankees in the same
test tube for three games a year. In theory, it's a gimmick but the
town does rock for three days.
</P>
<P>
   The first Jets-Giants exhibition, in New Haven in 1969, when the
Jets annihilated the Giants, now that was a rivalry. The
billingsgate chants from hockey fans in the Garden are just a vague
reminder of what the Islanders-Rangers games felt like a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we're still waiting for the Knicks and the Nets to
generate some heat between them. At the moment, the obsession is
not about some rival across the river, but about time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at my back I always hear
</P>
<P>
   Time's winged chariot hurrying near ...''
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Marvell never imagined he would wind up in a sports
column.)
</P>
<P>
   The worst part of this truncated season is the atrocities
committed upon the good name of hoops. The turnovers. The clangers.
The mental errors. The other night I saw Kendall Gill dribble the
ball off his foot and out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   These folks were not playing solid basketball last year. Since
this lockout they are mostly playing as if they trained on laughing
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty games used to leave time for regrouping. Fifty games is a
season, now one-fifth over, and moving very fast for the Nets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
