</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY FIGHTS THROUGH CHEMOTHERAPY, WORKS FOR SPOT ON YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Darryl Strawberry recovered his breath as he
plopped heavily into his clubhouse chair Tuesday. The rest of his
teammates were outside going through a series of sprints, but
Strawberry was tired and skipped that part of the workout.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry lifted weights, pumped an Exercycle and that was
enough, far more than can be expected from someone recovering from
colon cancer and taking weekly chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good, coming back on such a long road,'' he said. ``Not
an easy road.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, spoke before Tuesday's workout,
the first full-squad gathering of the spring. He presented the team
rules _ punctuality was a primary theme _ and told the Yankees to
concentrate on contending with the rest of the American League, and
not on the records they set in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Torre then watched the pitchers throw and the hitters take
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, limping on his bum left knee, gingerly shagged some
fly balls and took a round of batting practice. His upper body is
strong, carved into thick muscle.
</P>
<P>
   And with Trey Hillman, a Class AAA manager, throwing batting
practice, Strawberry drove several balls beyond the outfield wall,
including a shot over the center field fence that generated a roar
from the small crowd watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, Darryl!'' somebody screamed, and Bernie Williams
raised both arms, as if to signal touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who turns 37 next month, also hit several balls into
the netting at the top of the cage and grimaced in response. His
legs are thinned, undeveloped; the colon surgery and the
chemotherapy that will continue until May have prevented him from
exercising his legs as he did before spring training last year.
</P>
<P>
   He has a long way to go, Torre agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be his own doctor,'' Torre said. ``Everybody is
concerned about his well-being related to the cancer, and he's
building his strength with his daily regimen. But the knee that
causes problems for him, that's like starting over again, because
he hasn't been able to do anything all winter. It's not that he
wouldn't; he couldn't. And that's an area that could cause us some
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   If this were a Hollywood script, Strawberry would take batting
practice immediately after chemotherapy _ and actually, that is not
far removed from what is happening _ and quickly play his way into
shape to become the Yankees' left fielder once more. He would hit a
home run at the Yankees' home opener April 9. The New York fans,
who have booed and cheered him for 17 years, would salute him once
more as he rounded the bases.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood is not real life.
</P>
<P>
   Real life is Strawberry overcome by nausea after chemotherapy.
In simple terms, chemotherapy acts as a poison to fight the cancer,
but the body's instinct is to fight the poison, and the fight
inevitably wears down the body.
</P>
<P>
   Real life is Strawberry limping on a knee that he believes is
arthritic, and losing his breath after taking two dozen swings in
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Real life is the fact that the Yankees have three left fielders
who are younger than Strawberry, more mobile, and none of them is
fighting cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Real life is that Chili Davis is in better shape than he was
last spring and under contract for $4.5 million a season. He will
be given the chance to become the Yankees' everyday designated
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood never accounts for something like the luxury tax,
which may help trap Strawberry into a long rehabilitation. At a
time George Steinbrenner exercised Strawberry's $2.5 million option
for 1999 season _ a gesture of good will, for it is unlikely any
other team would have guaranteed Strawberry that kind of money _ he
asked that the Yankees be granted an exemption of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   So long as Strawberry is not on the 40-man roster, his salary
will not be subject to the 33 percent luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
   If Strawberry were to open the season, the Yankees would have to
pay an additional $833,333 in tax at a time when Steinbrenner wants
General Manager Brian Cashman to cut the payroll, after arbitration
losses to Derek Jeter and Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is deeply religious, a faith developed as he fought
through alcoholism, substance abuse and other personal trouble. He
believes God tested him in the past and that all those troubles
have prepared him for this.
</P>
<P>
   God, Strawberry believes, has asked him to accept the burden of
cancer, because as a public figure, Strawberry is in a position to
educate others about the disease and its pain. Strawberry is
honored that God has chosen him, and when he is tired, he says, he
gleans strength from the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible taught me to accept everything with joy,''
Strawberry said, smiling. ``I have peace within about this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
