<SLUG> BC-INTEL-PENTIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL DEMONSTRATES PENTIUM III MICROPROCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel Corp. demonstrated Tuesday a version of
its new Pentium III microprocessor that computes more than a
billion operations a second, the so-called one-gigahertz mark.
</P>
<P>
   The chip maker, however, was careful to state that it had
specially cooled the chip to reach the mark and that it did not
expect to begin selling commercial versions of the Pentium III
running at that speed until the end of 2000 or early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a technology demonstration,'' said Albert Yu, the
Intel executive in charge of microprocessor business. ``It is not
what I would recommend for people to do in their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Other chip makers have designed experimental microprocessors
that have attained the one-gigahertz mark, but Yu said this was the
first time that a chip designed for general-purpose personal
computers had reached the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which is based in Santa Clara, Calif., said it was
demonstrating the new microprocessor using its 0.25-micron
manufacturing process, but that manufacture of the commercial
gigahertz processors would use an even more advanced process of
either 0.18 or 0.13 micron. The submicron measurement generally
refers to the width of the ultrathin wires that make up chip
components like transistors. By contrast, a human hair is about 75
to 100 microns wide.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has tried to position the Pentium III as a ``next
generation'' microprocessor, but industry analysts have generally
viewed the chip as merely an incremental advance over the company's
450-megahertz Pentium II chips. The first Pentium III chips to be
offered will operate at the speed of 500 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are just running the same old software it doesn't do
much for you,'' said Linley Gwennap, an editor at Microprocessor
Report, an industry publication. ``It's a little faster than the
Pentium II 450.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwennap said the Pentium III had additional instructions that
offered faster processing of three-dimensional graphics for games,
speech recognition processing and video compression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
