<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-POSTSEASON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY INSPIRES HOPE IN FROGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Referee David Hall's whistle dangled between
his lips.
</P>
<P>
   He glared at TCU coach Billy Tubbs, daring him to spew another
stream of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go?'' Hall asked, a second technical waiting if
Tubbs answered wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs and his Horned Frogs were chin deep in a back-and-forth
game with host Nevada-Las Vegas, needing a victory to keep alive
their hope of an NCAA Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   He figured he had little to lose. A loss in Las Vegas would
basically seal TCU's postseason bid to the National Invitation
Tournament, anyway. So he simply shrugged his shoulders, smirked
and began barking again.
</P>
<P>
   His smirk remained long after time had expired on TCU's 76-72
victory over UNLV that ended about 1 a.m. yesterdayCST.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was very emotional for all of us,'' Horned Frogs
guard Vladimir Jaksic said. ``For us, the actual \RWestern Athletic
Conference\S tournament started this game. We don't have a right to
lose anymore if we want to make the \RNCAA\S Tournament and do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   By defeating Mountain Division-leading UNLV, TCU played itself
back into consideration for an at-large NCAA Tournament berth and
back into the running for a possible Mountain Division
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' Tubbs said. ``But I know we're in
better shape now than we were \RMonday\S afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours before the victory, TCU had been sweating
getting a berth in next week's WAC tournament, much less an NCAA
berth.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to hapless Air Force on Saturday had plunged TCU into
sixth in the Mountain Division. Only the top six teams in each
division make the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we lost to Air Force, we had lot to prove,'' said
Marquise Gainous, who sealed TCU's victory by hitting a free throw
with 2.7 seconds remaining. ``We needed this win because it's going
to be tough. We have somebody, Wyoming, trailing behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   With two regular-season games remaining, against third-place
Rice on Thursday and second-place Tulsa on Saturday, TCU has
procured a little distance between itself and other contenders for
the final Mountain Division berth.
</P>
<P>
   TCU (18-8, 6-6 WAC) jumped to fifth, tied with Colorado State
(16-8, 6-6), in the Mountain Division standings by defeating UNLV.
The Frogs hold the tiebreaker over the Rams by virtue of sweeping
their regular-season series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to come in here and win because this was a big
game to win if we wanted to be considered an NCAA Tournament
team,'' said Lee Nailon.
</P>
<P>
   A long inspection list awaits teams like TCU, sweating whether
an NCAA at-large slot will be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   A number of factors play roles, including a team's Ratings
Percentage Index ranking and performance in the final 10 games. RPI
is a computer-generated rankings system that factors in Division I
winning percentage, schedule strength and opponents' schedule
strength.
</P>
<P>
   If the Frogs finish with back-to-back victories and reach the
semifinals of the conference tournament, they will finish with a
22-9 mark, 7-3 over the final 10 games. That, when coupled with
their RPI, is likely to get them in the NCAA Tournament. TCU has a
solid RPI of 28, according to rankings yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   TCU is also likely to be helped because its four-game losing
streak came with Nailon missing all or part of three games. He
didn't play against UNLV or at Tulsa because of an NCAA-mandated
suspension for fighting, and he missed a good chunk of TCU's loss
to SMU with an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes \Rbeating UNLV\S even stronger,'' Jaksic
said. ``We had been struggling since UNLV beat us in \RFort
Worth\S. Then we lost some games we shouldn't. That doesn't mean
we're not a good team. We had to win this game tonight and we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Only afterward were players and coaches willing to admit that it
was a must-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   The only evidence was in the expressions and the emotion of the
players and coaches. The usually nonchalant Frogs were replaced by
players who capped slam dunks with a pump of the fists, who were
banging on the floor to call for a defensive stand, who celebrated
the victory with high-fives instead of the usual shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shannon Long told me: `I guarantee we're going to win this
game,' '' Tubbs said. ``It's one thing for a coach to say that, but
I think when it comes from a player it comes from the heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
