<SLUG> BC-BBN-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGIO, BAGWELL WON'T LET ASTROS FADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Ken Caminiti arrived at the Houston Astros
training camp yesterday riding a Harley-Davidson, gray and black
with lavender trim.
</P>
<P>
   Two autographed baseballs adorned the fenders. Craig Biggio,
riding his own black and silver Harley, escorted him in style. A
large chorus whooped and hollered when they sauntered into the
clubhouse together.
</P>
<P>
   The moment was big for both Caminiti and the Astros, an All-Star
third baseman, former MVP and kindred spirit of Biggio and Jeff
Bagwell, officially rejoining his old team after a four-year exile
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``His presence alone here is huge,'' Biggio said. ``Cammy comes
to play. When he's out there, he expects everybody around him to
play the game hard, play it right and leave everything on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti's arrival yesterday helped lift the spirits of a team
that got an emotional two-by-four whack across the face Monday when
they heard All-Star outfielder Moises Alou will miss most _ if not
all _ of the season with a severe knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge blow,'' Bagwell said. ``You lose a guy like Moises, you
can't replace him. We've got to find a way to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou's loss is the latest in a series of emotional blows that
have buffeted the Astros since they finished the 1998 regular
season with a team-record 102 victories. They were upset by the San
Diego Padres in the playoffs, they failed to re-sign pitcher Randy
Johnson, and they couldn't swing a trade for Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is Alou, and his injury was brought up immediately by
general manager Gerry Hunsicker during a team meeting before the
Astros' first full-squad workout yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't cover up the fact that it was a huge blow to the
ballclub to lose Moises,'' Hunsicker said. ``On the other hand, we
just have to dig a little deeper and work harder to make up for the
loss. I wanted to make sure this team isn't sitting around feeling
sorry for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to recognize we still have a talented ballclub. Not
only are we capable of winning the division, I expect it to win the
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker and manager Larry Dierker also know that a team with
Bagwell and Biggio sitting in the clubhouse isn't going to sit
around feeling sorry about anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Hunsicker said. ``One of the reasons we've been
successful with less resources than some of our competitors is the
character of our ballclub. I've always felt a championship ballclub
starts with the caliber of leadership and we have that with Bagwell
and Biggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell and Biggio make it easy on Dierker, an easygoing manager
with a fondness for cigars, flowered shirts and Jimmy Buffet.
Dierker has very few rules other than be on time and don't
embarrass him. The tacit understanding in the Astros' clubhouse is
if you mess up or cause problems, you answer not to the manager or
coaches, but to Bagwell and Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have to command respect,'' Caminiti said. ``They
get it, just by the way they play and act.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, despite the off-season setbacks, still have
front-line talent. They probably would have won the division last
year even without trading for Johnson, and they have enough
outfield depth to cover for Alou. Carl Everett hit .296 for the
Astros last year, and Richard Hidalgo hit .303 in a half-season.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens or Johnson would have given them a staff ace, but they
still have Shane Reynolds (19-8), Mike Hampton (11-7), Jose Lima
(16-8) and Scott Elarton, the prized young right-hander they
refused to include in any package for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   This is also a well-run franchise that has enjoyed six
consecutive winning seasons, success matched or exceeded only by
the Atlanta Braves and New York Yankees. It's hard to imagine, even
with the loss of Johnson and Alou's injury that this team will fall
off dramatically.
</P>
</TEXT>
