<HEADER>
A6705 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX     02-23 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BETTER OR WORSE, NEW ERA TEES OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bold, new era begins today for the PGA Tour. Call it the
Divided We Thrive Period.
</P>
<P>
   At one venue, the top 64 players in the world rankings will be
competing for a $5 million purse in the kickoff to the World Golf
Championships series, the Match Play Championship.
</P>
<P>
   At another site, one that has hosted a PGA Tour stop for the
past 54 years, organizers of the Tucson Open are selling tickets so
customers can watch Brent Schwarzrock, Rory Sabbatini, Kaname Yokoo
and Tim Loustalot try to earn full-time playing privileges for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   The match-play event in Carlsbad, Calif., has David Duval and
Tiger Woods. The Tucson Open, which Duval won last season, has no
defending champion and no network television exposure. The two
highest-ranked players in its field are David Toms and Per-Ulrick
Johansson.
</P>
<P>
   PGA Tour officials, who added $250,000 to the Tucson purse last
week to stimulate the quality of the field, insist there is enough
golf interest to make both events float in the same week. Common
sense says otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials at the Tucson Open proudly point to a 5
percent increase in advance sales for the 1999 tournament despite a
drop in star quality among competitors, you have to question if
this is a long-term trend or a one-year explosion of civic pride.
Turning a tournament into a permanent Tiger-free zone is no way to
assure its continued financial health and well being.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. I love the idea of the WGC's match-play event.
It's a huge plus for golf and should be a ratings bonanza. But
having it perpetually bump heads with Tucson's dates, as long-range
schedules suggest it will do for three of the next four years, will
make the Tucson Open an interesting test case for how WGC events
will affect traditional tour stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spirit of Tucson is you take every challenge as it comes
and rise to the occasion,'' said tournament spokesman Jennifer
English. ``People here have done that. I can't tell you every other
encumbered event would be this well received in another city.''
</P>
<P>
   The deeper concern about the WGC events is that their emergence
will affect the quality of fields throughout the PGA Tour. With
three additional $5 million purses available in 1999, elite players
figure to cut back on their appearances at nonmajors. Most already
were playing abbreviated schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only going to hurt, from that standpoint,'' said Tom
Watson, the defending champ at the MasterCard Colonial. ``It's
going to hurt all the tours in the numbers of events that players
play.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, Watson said fields at the Colonial and the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic should not feel an impact because they are
positioned far away from any WGC conflicts on the tour calendar.
But a fourth WGC event will be added next year, with the date to be
announced. Long-range plans call for adding more WGC events, if
they prove popular with fans, TV executives and players.
</P>
<P>
   And they will.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, who knows? Phil Thomas, Colonial tournament
chairman, sees the potential for murky waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the proper placement of the \RWGC\S events, I don't think
it will affect us today. But I'm not saying it won't in the
future,'' Thomas said. ``The jury's out on that. It'll take a year
or two to see how things shake out.''
</P>
<P>
   So sit back and enjoy this week's debut of the Divided We Thrive
Period in PGA Tour history, as provided by the WGC series. It's an
enhancement to the tour, but it comes at a cost to events like the
Tucson Open.
</P>
<P>
   And be aware that, as the WGC events gain popularity, the cost
eventually could hit closer to home.
Spotlight on ...
MIRA VISTA CONNECTION WINS BIG AT NISSAN OPEN
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els hoisted the champion's trophy at the Nissan Open in
Los Angeles. But one of the biggest winners Sunday was Mira Vista
Country Club, where three golfers with ties to the course all made
quantum leaps on the PGA Tour season money list.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, Fort Worth residents Mark Brooks, Alan Bratton and
Clark Dennis combined to collect $119,350 in prize money. They also
created a buzz in the locker room during weekend rounds, said Mira
Vista club pro Lindy Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, whose house is adjacent to the course, closed with a 66
and picked up his first top-10 finish at a PGA Tour event since
March 1997. Brooks' ninth-place effort was worth $72,800, boosting
him from 152nd to 68th on the money list ($81,566).
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, who represents Mira Vista on the PGA Tour, began
Saturday one stroke off the lead before finishing 15th. By doing
so, he earned the largest payday of his rookie season ($40,670) to
improve from 103rd to 77th in earnings with $67,476.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, likewise, is a Mira Vista representative. By cashing a
$5,880 check, he improved 11 places on the money list, to No. 150
($12,750).
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday, everyone was talking about Alan being in the
hunt. And Sunday, everyone was gathered around the TV,'' Miller
said. ``It was a really neat deal for Mira Vista. They all played
good, and people here have an extra interest in all three guys.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the three players root for each other. After shooting a
first-round 67 on Riviera Country Club's par-71 layout, Bratton
said his excitement grew after learning that Brooks and Dennis
threw down 68s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the course thinking, `All right. Mira Vista shot
10-under today,' '' Bratton said. ``It was a really good week. The
Fort Worth guys did OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Well enough, in fact, for all three to make double-digit
improvement on the season earnings list.
SHORT PUTTS
SEEKING NEW HORIZONS
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned by organizers of the LPGA Skins Game when sponsorship
dollars dried up during the off-season, Stonebriar Country Club in
Frisco is without a professional golf event for the first time in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean the course, which has hosted a Senior
Tour event (1989-93) and the Skins Game (1990-98), is out of the
professional golf business for good. Monty Becton, club general
manager, said he has begun making inquiries about bringing an LPGA
or Senior Tour event to Stonebriar's new course. Currently under
construction, along with an adjacent resort hotel, the new layout
is scheduled to open next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, said Becton, he'd like to have some
professional event in place for the 2001 or 2002 season.
NO SURRENDER
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard Colonial officials have not given up on landing Tiger
Woods, the world's top-ranked golfer, as a participant in their
1999 event. But they concede the chances are slim in light of a
confirmation by Woods' agent that his client will play in the SAP
Open in Germany during the same week as Colonial (May 20-23).
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger Woods has not officially told us he won't be here. As
far as I'm concerned, we've still got a shot at it,'' said Phil
Thomas, Colonial tournament chairman. ``We certainly want him. But
we understand that you can't expect the top guys to come every
year. They've got other things they need and want to do. In a way,
it gives us something to look forward to next year if he doesn't
play this year. I don't think he can overlook Colonial on a regular
basis, year after year.''
WATSON DISLIKES RULING
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, the defending Colonial champ, is among those who
disagree with a recent ruling that allowed fans to help Tiger Woods
remove a boulder from his shot path during the final round of the
Phoenix Open (Jan. 31). Citing the rules of golf, which allow
players assistance in removing loose impediments, PGA Tour
officials deemed the boulder a loose impediment and decreed that it
could be removed if done so in a timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was dead wrong,'' Watson said during last week's Colonial
kickoff dinner. ``That's not the intent of the rule ... to allow
someone to be able to move a boulder. I think you'll see the USGA
change that rule to read, `If you can't move it yourself or with
the help of a caddie, you can't move it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Watson and Woods may soon have a chance to discuss the matter
personally. If both players win their opening matches in today's
World Golf Championships Match Play Championship, they will meet
tomorrow in the second round.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Under new guidelines adopted this month by the LPGA, criteria
for enshrinement in the LPGA Hall of Fame has shifted from a
win-based formula to a points-based formula (one point per
tournament win, two points per major championship, one point for
Vare Trophy for lowest scoring average, one point for
player-of-the-year award). As a result, Beth Daniel and Amy Alcott
became immediate qualifiers and will be enshrined March 22. Below
is a look at how selected players stand under the new guidelines,
with 27 points needed for enshrinement: Player Points Beth Daniel
39 Amy Alcott 35 Annika Sorenstam 24 Hollis Stacy 22 Laura Davies
22 Juli Inkster 20 Jan Stephenson 19 Sally Little 17 Dottie Pepper
17
</P>
</TEXT>
