<HEADLINE>
TCU WASTES CHANCES IN LOSS TO OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ At the conclusion of a 14-12 loss to
Oklahoma at the TCU Diamond yesterday, Horned Frogs coach Lance
Brown said he felt remarkably refreshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did about 5.1 miles,'' he said, referring to his
stint on an exercise bike beyond the fence down the right-field
line _ his vantage point from the second inning on after being
ejected by plate umpire Kelly Nutt.
</P>
<P>
   Nutt's quick thumb seemed to set the tone for a bizarre
afternoon in which the Sooners (8-4) won despite walking 16 TCU
batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs (6-7) more or less returned the favor by stranding 13
runners and had five more thrown out on the bases _ including two
cut down at the plate in one inning.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma prevailed with a 19-hit attack that included four home
runs and a school-record-tying four triples. TCU, which trailed
10-1 after three innings, fought back by scoring eight runs in the
last three innings _ including four in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Sooners All-America candidate Casey Bookout hit a home run over
the wall in dead center, along with a 400-foot double that bounced
off the top of the wall in the right-center corner, the deepest
part of the park.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's David Wallace tied a school record with four walks. He
also had a single and hit a two-run homer in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played pretty good defense \Rdespite three errors\S, and we
hit the ball really well,'' Oklahoma coach Larry Cochell said. ``We
didn't pitch very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he was not surprised at being tossed by Nutt, who
ejected TCU assistant Donnie Watson from a game here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much the same thing every time certain people show
up,'' Brown said. ``I just mentioned something to him about a
swinging strike call on one of our players who never moved his bat
on the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I figured, what the heck, I might as well get some
exercise. So I rode the bike.''
</P>
<P>
   The game went 3 hours and 13 minutes, and the Sooners spent the
first hour of it roughing up TCU starter Cade Harris. By the end of
the day, the Frogs were pitching their designated hitter and the
Sooners had their left fielder on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   With 14th-ranked Hawaii arriving this weekend for the opening
series in Western Athletic Conference play, Brown saved his
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in a hole today,'' he said. ``The thing I
liked was that instead of quitting, we fought back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
