<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF DYNASTIES, IT'S CAROLINA BLUE OVER 'HUSKERS RED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dynasties typically deal with championships. But a dynasty can
be defined as success over time. And if you want to start a heated
dynasty debate, try this one: North Carolina basketball vs.
Nebraska football.
</P>
<P>
   Last week North Carolina recorded victory No. 20, giving the Tar
Heels 28 consecutive seasons with at least 20 victories. Twenty
times, North Carolina has won at least 25 games. The football
equivalent is winning 10 games, something Nebraska has accomplished
17 times.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three decades, the Tar Heels have won two national
championships while the Cornhuskers have won five. Nebraska's
football winning percentage the past 30 seasons is .839; North
Carolina's basketball winning percentage is .797.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's the argument: North Carolina or Nebraska, which has
the most impressive dynasty? Admittedly, this is a pumpkin
(basketball) vs. watermelon (football) debate.
</P>
<P>
   And this is an argument about excellence. There's little doubt
that when it comes to consistent success _ the most elusive variety
_ North Carolina basketball and Nebraska football are Nos. 1 and
1A.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has competed in bowl games for 31 consecutive seasons,
an NCAA record. North Carolina has participated in 24 consecutive
NCAA Tournaments. The last time the Tar Heels failed to win at
least one game in the NCAA tourney was 1980; they've won at least
one game in the past 18 NCAA tourneys.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina and Nebraska have been on interesting parallel
tracks of late.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of about two months in 1997, both schools' legendary
coaches _ the Tar Heels' Dean Smith and the Cornhuskers' Tom
Osborne _ announced their retirement. Both were replaced by
longtime assistant coaches _ Bill Guthridge at North Carolina and
Frank Solich at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   In his first season, Guthridge guided the Tar Heels to the Final
Four. In Solich's first season, the 'Huskers lost three Big 12
games and lost to Arizona in the Holiday Bowl. The success of these
Legend Substitutes will determine the future of this argument.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to choose between which has the better dynasty, the proof
is in conference play and strength of that conference.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina has finished no lower than third in Atlantic
Coast Conference play for 34 consecutive years. Nebraska has
finished no lower than third in the Big Eight and Big 12
conferences for 21 consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that North Carolina, year in, year out has
faced tougher competition in the ACC than Nebraska has faced in its
conference.
</P>
<P>
   In the ACC, the Tar Heels have had to contend with a national
championship contender in Duke for more than a decade. And the
North Carolina States, Georgia Techs, Marylands, Wake Forests and
Virginias have spent time contending for first place.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past three decades, Nebraska's conference season
came down to one game _ Oklahoma. In their last 27 seasons in the
Big Eight Conference, the Huskers lost 24 conference games _ 14
against the Sooners. It was truly the Big Two and the Little Six.
</P>
<P>
   This is corn vs. tobacco; the flat plains of Nebraska vs. the
tall pines of North Carolina; Midwestern sensibility vs. Southern
hospitality; North vs. South.
</P>
<P>
   The easy way out would be to declare North Carolina the
basketball dynasty and Nebraska the football dynasty. But given the
more competitive nature of ACC basketball, this vote comes down in
favor of the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   Barely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
