<HEADLINE>
RUNNER DEFEATS DISAPPOINTMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the women competitors in last year's Cowtown Marathon had a
hard time keeping up with winner Lori Stich, how will they ever
stay with her this year?
</P>
<P>
   She has barely touched earth since qualifying for the Olympic
Trials two months ago and expects to still be on a high when she
attempts to win her third Cowtown title Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now I get excited just thinking about qualifying, or when
my friends talk about it. It's still hard to believe,'' said Stich,
a 28-year-old lawyer from Stanwood, Mich., who also won Cowtown in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   She qualified at the California International in Sacramento,
Calif., with a personal-best time of 2 hours, 48 minutes, 41
seconds, despite a bout with the flu. What made it sweeter was that
it wiped out a huge disappointment in June. Stich thought she had
qualified then with a 2:50:30 at Grandma's Marathon in Duluth,
Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I just needed to run a 2:50. I was celebrating and
everything, and then someone told me I needed to beat 2:50,'' she
said. ``I crashed. It's not the end of the world to not qualify for
the trials, but when you don't make it because of stupidity, well
...''
</P>
<P>
   She believed she could beat 2:50, and pegged the California
International as her next try. But that became such an ordeal, she
almost didn't go.
</P>
<P>
   The week before, she made the 12-hour drive from Michigan to
Minnesota to be with family and friends for the Thanksgiving
holidays, flew from there to San Antonio to play piano at a
relative's wedding, then flew back to Minnesota. Then she drove
back to Michigan. In midweek, she came down with flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt rotten, and was wondering what the point was of going
out there,'' she said. Then she reasoned that if she didn't run,
she would go sightseeing. ``I had never been to Sacramento,'' said
Stich, who's an avid traveler.
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures in the 40s, race day was perfect for Stich,
who likes to run in the cold. She decided to run, and by the 11th
mile, she liked her decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling great. I know that's still early in the race,
but I was already on pace to break 2:50. When I got to 18, I knew I
could even slow down and make it. It felt fantastic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Stich ran a 3:03:47 to win Cowtown, but a year of
more consistent running has put her in a faster lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I join five people from the building next door at work, and we
run five miles every day at noon,'' said Stich, who ran nine
marathons and two 50-kilometer ultras last year. ``We have runners
of every ability, so it makes it easy to train. I had run 3:03 and
3:02 marathons without training consistently, and I was wondering
what I could do if I did train.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she knows.
</P>
</TEXT>
