<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUYERS IN TOWN TO PICK FILMS FOR EXPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ The year's biggest event for Tinseltown's
major players comes March 21 when Academy Awards are presented; for
everyone else, it's Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For hundreds of Hollywood producers, distributors and buyers,
the nine-day American Film Market is where the rubber truly meets
the road. Headquartered at Loews Santa Monica Beach Hotel, AFM is
the key event to find buyers for movies that deliver American-style
entertainment _ recognizable actors, explosions, starlets and car
chases _ to places like Bolivia, Bulgaria, Singapore and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect there will be about $400 million in deals that get
signed,'' said Jonathan Wolf, managing director of the event.
``It's not a trade show in the traditional sense but a place where
business gets done. People show up with contracts and attorneys and
if they don't sign at the event, they sign a couple of days
later.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19th annual American Film Market, billed as the industry's
biggest single trade event, opens Thursday as the key source for
buyers of movies produced outside the seven major studios. The
other major film-buying markets take place in May at the Cannes
Film Festival in France and in October at MIFED in Milan, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   So Santa Monica will be overrun with pager-laden executives
scrambling to close deals with 7,000 attendees expected from 71
countries, including China for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   What's for sale? More than 1,000 titles fit into the
``debuting'' category, including 330 dramas, 180 comedies, 165
action-adventures, 140 thrillers, 79 romances, 55 adult/erotic
projects, 52 family films and 35 in the horror/sci-fi category.
Several hundred other ``returning'' titles are also up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popular image of an industry awash in cash due to
growth of new sources of revenue such as multiplexes and cable and
satellite systems, AFM participants face daunting obstacles,
including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Asian and Brazilian markets that have slumped and not yet
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   _ A product glut generated by the proliferation of independent
producers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The increasing ability of majors to tap into foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ A tougher market for action product at domestic video stores
and foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ A decreased emphasis on ``pre-sales'' of projects, meaning
distributors often require producers to have a completed film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world market is still very weak,'' asserted George
Shamieh, president of PM Entertainment. ``We have to scramble. The
market's still bad but at least it seems to have stabilized.''
</P>
<P>
   Accredited buyers are charged $495 to attend; everyone else pays
$775. And for the first time, AFM is opening about 70 of its
screenings to the public at the AMC Santa Monica, offering a $95
nine-day pass ($45 for students and trade members).
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to find ``Driving Miss Daisy'' or ``Shakespeare in
Love''; instead, the approach will be breathtakingly direct. Take,
for example, ``Y2K,'' a high-tech thriller with Lou Gossett Jr. and
James Woolvet about a renegade general launching the Apocalypse
from a military base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K,'' produced by PM Entertainment, has a simple tagline _
``Man holds in his mortal hands the power to abolish all forms of
life'' _ because AFM films need to be easily understood by foreign
audiences. Mostly, that means action and adventure, although
comedies, horror films and dramas have a shot, according to
Shamieh.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to do comedy, you have to deliver one that
translates worldwide,'' he said. ``You can't have American slang in
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
