r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ROBESON-SFCHRON &LR;      02-23 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROBESON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PBS, AN EVENHANDED BIOGRAPHY OF ROBESON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Paul Robeson centennial was last year, when the singer,
actor and political activist would have been 100. Now here comes
PBS, chugging across the finish line after the race has ended.
</P>
<P>
   Still, good show.
</P>
<P>
   The ``American Masters'' documentary ``Paul Robeson: Here I
Stand,'' airing Wednesday on PBS, is an eye-opener for anyone who
knows the three presumably essential facts about Robeson and
nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Fact No. 1 is that Robeson was a black American. No. 2 _ and odd
that Wednesday's program airs opposite the Grammys _ is that he had
a big voice and sang ``Old Man River.'' Tote that barge, lift that
bale.
</P>
<P>
   Essential fact No. 3 is that Robeson was a Communist. That one's
in doubt. Robeson, who died in 1976, resented the assumption. His
son, a big presence in Wednesday's program, says Robeson was never
a Communist.
</P>
<P>
   But he was an admirer of the Soviet Union, a fashionable
friendship during the World War II years and pure poison afterward.
Like a locomotive, the entire documentary pushes toward that key
part of Robeson's makeup and its powerful effect on his career.
</P>
<P>
   For most of a decade, beginning in 1949, Robeson was virtually
buried alive in the United States. His passport was lifted. His
music vanished from the radio. Concert stages were off-limits to
him. Old friends joined his enemies in denouncing him.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference in Paris, Robeson had declared that black people
couldn't join in good conscience in a war against the Soviet Union.
He then revisited Russia, apparently turning a blind eye to Josef
Stalin's murderous purges.
</P>
<P>
   The ``American Masters'' production team lets you decide for
yourself what you think about that. Yes, Robeson was victimized by
McCarthy-era hysteria. But one of Robeson's political foes, Herbert
Hill, a former National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People official, is still on hand to insist that Robeson shouldn't
now be lionized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been given a sanitized myth of Paul Robeson,'' Hill
says. ``What we get is the marvelous singer, the great actor, the
man who stood up to the McCarthyites. But what we don't get is the
40-year history of defense and support for a movement based upon
terror and mass murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion in the program is that Robeson clung to his own
priority list of world villains, led by the American right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Without evidence, the documentary also raises the possibility _
Paul Robeson Jr. thinks it may be true _ that the CIA drugged
Robeson and contributed to the physical and mental decline of his
later years.
</P>
<P>
   Robeson was invigorated by his political struggles _ racial
justice, trade unionism, anti-fascism _ but you can't help but
wonder how his life might have been different if he'd been born
several decades later.
</P>
<P>
   He was a Phi Beta Kappa scholar, a linguist, a Columbia Law
School graduate, a grand athlete, a powerful singer and actor, and
a charismatic figure. And yet, in the 1930s, he labored through a
series of disillusioning films that demeaned, exploited and
radicalized him.
</P>
<P>
   What if the young Robeson had sprung upon us today? If you watch
this documentary, you might find it conceivable that he'd be taking
an oath of office somewhere, rather than declining a loyalty oath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
