<SLUG> BC-MONTREAL-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIRMAN OF BANK OF MONTREAL ANNOUNCES RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The failed mergers between Canada's largest banks
appear to have claimed another high-profile victim.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew W. Barrett, the chairman and chief executive officer of
the Bank of Montreal, Canada's third largest national bank,
announced his immediate resignation as chief executive Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the start of the bank's annual shareholder meeting
in Halifax, Nova Scotia, Barrett, 54, also said he would also
retire as chairman in November, the end of the bank's fiscal year.
He was replaced as chief executive officer by F. Anthony Comper,
53, the bank's president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who had led the bank for more than a decade, had been
under pressure from institutional investors and shareholders since
December, when Canada's finance ministry rejected a proposed merger
between his bank and the Royal Bank of Canada, two of Canada's six
national banks.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett had argued that the banks needed to pool resources to
remain internationally competitive following big consolidations in
the United States and in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Montreal owns the Harris Bank of Chicago and is a
major shareholder in Grupo Financiero Bancomer SA in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger with Royal Bank was rejected Dec. 15, the
same day officials rejected a merger between the Canadian Imperial
Bank of Commerce and The Toronto-Dominion Bank. A.L. Flood, the
chairman and chief executive officer of the Imperial Bank, has
since announced his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   After the government shut the door on both mergers, bank stocks
were hit hard, and the Bank of Montreal was hurt more than any
other.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with reporters Tuesday, Barrett tried to distance his
decision to resign from the failure of the merger proposal. ``It is
not related to the merger,'' Barrett said. But he later
acknowledged that the failure of the merger was a personal
disappointment, and that ``had the merger gone through, I actually
would have stayed around longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said the Bank of Montreal had prepared a contingency
plan in case the mergers were not completed. That plan, a sweeping
reorganization outlined Tuesday, will take five to seven years to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said that he believed it was better to have one
executive direct the bank's transformation rather than to begin the
process under one chairman and then have to switch to another in a
few years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Montreal reported net income Tuesday of $362 million
(Canadian) for the first quarter of 1999, which ended Jan. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
