<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIACOM-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIACOM DEVELOPING NEW ONLINE SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viacom Inc. announced a plan Tuesday to create what it hopes
will be the ultimate online music destination, combining the appeal
of both MTV and VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it was starting a new children's site,
``Project Nozzle.''
</P>
<P>
   The music site is being developed separately from Viacom's MTV
and VH-1 Web sites. To assure that its image is not limited to the
more youth-oriented MTV or the more adult-oriented VH-1, the new
enterprise is now using the working title ``The Buggles Project.''
(A video of the song ``Video Killed the Radio Star'' by the musical
group The Buggles was the first video ever shown on MTV.)
</P>
<P>
   The plan also relies on the company's acquisition of Imagine
Radio, an Internet radio service created by Rotem Perelmuter and
Mike Briseno. That radio service has existing channels and offers
listeners the ability to create their own channels with their
favorite performers.
</P>
<P>
   The existing Web sites for MTV and Nickelodeon are primarily
promotional tools for the company's cable programming. But several
industry experts said Tuesday that Viacom recognized that it had to
create more of an online music presence. Julie Gordon, who runs The
Velvet Rope, a music industry insiders' Web site, said she saw the
moves as a positive way for Viacom to capitalize on the MTV and
Nickelodeon brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom said it would dedicate $250 million in advertising time
on its own cable services to promote the new music and children's
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it might spin off 20 percent of the new
venture. The strategy was welcome news on Wall Street. Viacom's
share price rose $1.375 Tuesday to close at $87, a 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom wants to protect its music franchise as rivals like
Wenner Media's Rolling Stone magazine create popular Web sites that
offer similar services. Though Viacom and Rolling Stone's core
businesses are in other technologies, they are now competing side
by side on the Internet. Another competitor is Sonic Net, a
business that offers home pages for every musical group, as well as
bulletin boards to communicate music news. Tele-Communications
Inc., the nation's second-largest cable operator, is a major
investor in Sonic Net.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon already operates a Web site, but Project Nozzle will
be an expanded destination for children with additional content and
features like chat rooms and e-mail. ``We are building a registered
community, that requires registered kids to be in it so that it is
a safer environment,'' a Viacom spokeswoman said. Viacom has
acquired Red Rocket, which sells educational toys online, and will
integrate that company with the existing services. Project Nozzle
has all the features of other general use Internet portals, but its
focus will be on children, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Freston, the head of MTV, said Tuesday that the new music
service was expected to generate revenue from advertising and some
electronic commerce. Though the existing MTV site does direct
consumers to CD Now, an online retailer, the new site may
collaborate more closely with merchandisers and seek deals with
partners such as Ticketmaster to sell tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
