<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL IN THE WORKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The air conditioning went kaput in the team's
administrative offices Tuesday, and the trade winds didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   A rumor has been circulating that accuses the Los Angeles
Clippers and Golden State of working on a trade involving veteran
point guard Pooh Richardson. According to reports, the Clippers
would send Richardson, the former UCLA star, to the Warriors in
exchange for veteran point guard Bimbo Coles and small forward
Duane Ferrell.
</P>
<P>
   But a team source said such a deal would make sense to
Richardson and his agent, Arn Tellem, but not to the teams
allegedly involved.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who is under contract for two more seasons after
this one is history, is making $3 million this season (before
pro-rated lockout deduction), which is close enough to the combined
salaries of Coles and Ferrell to make a deal possible.
</P>
<P>
   Also mentioned were proposed deals with Seattle and Vancouver.
It really is some coincidence that the players the Clippers would
receive from either of those teams in these phantom deals also
happen to be represented to Tellem.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I don't know,'' Richardson said of being dealt.
``And I'm not really thinking about it. The way it is in the league
now, it's difficult to trade people.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's been difficult for the 33-year-old playmaker to adjust
to his role as the third point guard in Coach Chris Ford's
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need for me getting' upset at not playin',''
Richardson said. ``When you bring negativity, it creates a stink.
Let's just get a win first.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Point clicking: &UR; !off! &LR;  With other point guards and rumors of
other point guards in the air, it would seem natural for the
climate to bother current starter Darrick Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about things I can't control,'' Martin said. ``I
just go out there and play, hoping we can get a win. I think we're
getting' there, but we've got to do it for 48 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sense of Closs: &UR; !off! &LR;  In searching for the positives from an
0-8 team, we introduce backup center Keith Closs. The 7-foot-3
southpaw has been cleaning up during garbage time.
</P>
<P>
   Translating his 10-minute totals into an average of 30 minutes
per game, Closs would be averaging 24 points, 12 rebounds and 12
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Clippers also would have to find a way to force
the opposition to play its second unit for 30 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
