<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAMMY SHOW, A THROWBACK, CAN STILL DRAW A BIG AUDIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Mo., Texas)  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Grammy Awards are music to Madison Avenue's ears
_ and not because there's a category honoring the best jingle of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other reasons why advertisers and agencies
have become ardent fans of the awards ceremony. The presentation of
the 41st annual Grammys, administered by the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, is scheduled for broadcast Wednesday
night from 8 to 11 p.m. by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers are paying an average of $450,000 to $500,000 for each
30 seconds of commercial time during the show. Among the sponsors
are blue-chip brands like Bayer, Chevrolet, Compaq, Fidelity,
Intel, Kellogg, Mastercard, Sony and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for the Grammys' appeal is that the show is
one of the few remaining television programs that can still draw
large audiences _ and high ratings _ in an era of increased viewer
fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for big, prime-time events such as the Grammys and the
Academy Awards,'' Bill Ludwig, vice chairman and chief creative
officer at Campbell-Ewald in Warren, Mich., said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell-Ewald, part of the Interpublic Group of Companies, is
the longtime agency for the Chevrolet division of the General
Motors Corp. Chevrolet, a principal Grammys sponsor since 1990, has
bought seven 30-second commercial slots during the broadcast to
promote models like the Cavalier and Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a 60-second brand image commercial that
revives, in a contemporary manner, the famous jingle ``See the
U.S.A. in your Chevrolet,'' associated with singer Dinah Shore. The
upbeat tune, originally written for the metropolitan New York Chevy
dealers, gained national exposure on her popular weekly variety
show from 1951 to 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The new commercial offers a Chevrolet version of 20th-century
American history, from Betty Boop and the Hula-Hoop to Woodstock
and the World Wide Web. As images of celebrities like Charlie
Chaplin, James Dean, Marilyn Monroe and Muhammad Ali appear on
screen, viewers will hear Shawn Colvin _ who won two of the biggest
Grammys last year, for song and record, with ``Sunny Came Home'' _
sing a slower, more soulful version of the ``See the U.S.A.''
jingle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It taps into a musical equity, if you will, from Chevrolet's
past,'' said Jim Jandacek, director for advertising and sales
promotion for Chevrolet passenger cars at the Chevrolet division in
Detroit. ``That makes it even more appropriate to debut this spot
on the Grammys.''
</P>
<P>
   That remark brings up another reason for advertising during the
Grammys: to be associated with music and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is a big part of the culture of our target audience,''
said Larry Flanagan, vice president for U.S. advertising at
Mastercard International in Purchase, N.Y. ``And we like to use
`big programming' like the Grammys and the Super Bowl to showcase
new creative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mastercard commercial features a song called ``E.V.A.'' by
the producer of electronic dance music known as Fatboy Slim. The
spot is part of a campaign carrying the theme ``Priceless'' by
McCann-Erickson New York, part of the McCann-Erickson Worldwide
Advertising unit of McCann-Erickson World Group, which is owned by
Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   Another commercial, for the Advantage brand of flea control
products sold by the Bayer Corp., features a fanciful musical
motif. The spot, by Bernstein-Rein Advertising in Kansas City, Mo.,
uses special effects to make it seem as if pet cats and dogs are
recording a version of the pop tune ``Rockin' Robin''; the lyrics
are rewritten to praise Advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial will start a promotion for Advantage centered on
a search for the ``best singing pet'' in North America.
</P>
<P>
   One big advertiser, the Kellogg Co., is joining forces with
another imaginary musician, this time a human. Christopher Guest,
who played the hapless rocker Nigel Tufnel in the comic cult film
``This is Spinal Tap,'' is the director of new commercials for
Kellogg's Frosted Flakes created by the Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago.
Two of the spots, centered on a obsessive supermarket stock boy,
are to run during the show.
</P>
<P>
   Guest ``has brought a quirky sense of humor to the ads, which we
think will appeal to the hip, younger Grammy audience,'' said Karen
Kafer, communications director for the Kellogg USA unit of Kellogg
in Battle Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Those characteristics of the audience appealed to a first-time
Grammys advertiser, the Compaq Computer Corp., which will introduce
the initial commercial in a television brand campaign created by
the DDB Needham Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group in New York. The
commercial includes such unconventional images as people with
tattoos and an AIDS patient asking ``How are we going to beat this
disease?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The psyche of the Grammy audience seems like an appropriate
fit for our brand personality and essence,'' said Andrew Salzman,
vice president for worldwide advertising and brand strategy at
Compaq in Houston, who characterized Compaq as being ``a younger
company, a company of the Internet age.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers are not the only ones associated with the Grammy
Awards who are pleased with its youthful demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one project we have that's very young and we love
it,'' said Joseph Abruzzese, president for network sales at CBS, a
unit of the CBS Corp. in New York. ``It's one of the highlights of
our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Next on the calendar of television's biggest events: the Academy
Awards on March 21. ABC, a unit of the Walt Disney Co., has sold
out commercial time at a record price for the Oscars, averaging $1
million for each 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, though, there will be a one-time big event: ABC's
broadcast of the Barbara Walters interview with Monica Lewinsky.
That program, planned for next Wednesday, is being scheduled as a
special two-hour presentation of the news magazine ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC has been selling a 30-second spot during the regular
hourlong ``20/20'' on Wednesday nights for an average price of
$160,000. The price being charged for the Walters-Lewinsky show:
$800,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
