u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-GEORGETOWN-RUTGER     02-23 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GEORGETOWN-RUTGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS' COMEBACK FALLS SHORT AGAINST GEORGETOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Geoff Billet and Rob Hodgson were able to
avoid the tears during a farewell ceremony before they took the
floor at the Rutgers Athletic Center for the last time. The two
seniors may have had a tougher time as the final buzzer sounded
Tuesday night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They had spearheaded a revitalization of the Scarlet Knights'
basketball program, guiding Rutgers to its first winning season in
seven years. They also guided Rutgers to the verge of the NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But the dream slipped a little bit further from their reach
Tuesday night as the two were unable to cap the night with the sort
of heroics that would propel them into the tournament as Georgetown
scored a 57-53 victory over Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   After staging a furious comeback, Rutgers had an opportunity to
tie the game and put it in the hands of the two seniors who had
brought them this far. Billet hit a 12-footer at the buzzer against
Georgetown on March 5 last year in the opening round of the Big
East tournament, giving the Scarlet Knights a 61-60 victory and a
place in the national spotlight as his shot was replayed endlessly
on highlight shows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it was Hodgson who got the opportunity this time. Earl
Johnson dribbled down the clock with the two seniors frantically
trying to find an opening on each side. Johnson delivered the ball
to Hodgson, who got a good look from the left corner, but his shot
went in and then spun out with 3 seconds to play. Nat Burton of
Georgetown added a free throw to put the game out of reach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers entered the game having beaten Georgetown three straight
times since Kevin Bannon took over as coach. But this time, they
were facing not only the Hoyas' pressure defense but also the
self-imposed pressure that had reduced their NCAA hopes to a
make-or-break 40 minutes .
</P>
<P>
   A disappointing loss to Seton Hall on Sunday put the Scarlet
Knights into a must-win situation Tuesday night, with the only
remaining regular season game after this coming at Miami on
Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers remained stranded at 17 victories, its record dropping
to 17-10 overall and 9-8 in the Big East with its third straight
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 80 teams in Big East history with at least 18 victories,
74 have made the NCAA tournament. From the Big East, there are
three definites in Connecticut, Miami, and St. John's. Syracuse has
probably wrapped up a spot already, while Rutgers, Villanova and
Providence are still holding out hope. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Against the pressure of the Georgetown defense, the Scarlet
Knights struggled for every basket, or even to get the ball
inbounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by five points with 3 minutes 5 seconds to play,
Rutgers got back into the game with a 3-point field goal by
Johnson. On the play there was a foul inside, sending Rashod Kent,
a 47 percent free-throw shooter, to the line. He missed both, and
the Knights were unable to tie.
</P>
<P>
   But they got another chance when the Hoyas committed a 35-second
violation and Georgetown head coach Craig Esherick was called for a
technical foul, sending Billet, an 84 percent free-throw shooter,
to the line for two. He missed the first before hitting the second,
and the score was 51-50 with 2:29 remaining. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Ruben Boumtje-Boumtje gave the Hoyas a three-point lead on
a follow in the lane, freshman Dahntay Jones finally pulled Rutgers
even with a 3-point field goal with 1:15 to play. Burton hit a pair
from the line after being fouled on a drive to the basket, giving
Georgetown a two-point lead with 54.5 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After another Rutgers turnover with 29 seconds left, Anthony
Perry hit one of two from the line, and the lead was 56-53. Rutgers
called timeout and set up for one final opportunity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Hodgson couldn't hit the shot Rutgers needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
