<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY TO MAKE SUMMER SCHOOL MANDATORY FOR SOME STUDENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying he was ``drawing a line in the sand'' against
``low-performing kids in low-performing schools in low-performing
districts,'' Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew said Tuesday that he
would make summer school mandatory this year for third, sixth and
eighth graders who do poorly on New York's citywide reading and
math tests and in their courses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which Crew is to announce at Wednesday's meeting
of the Board of Education. As many as several thousand students
will have to repeat a grade unless they complete a six-week
remedial course starting in July. It will be the city's broadest
use of mandatory summer school since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Crew's plan adds New York City to a growing list of school
districts around the nation that are turning summertime into just
another semester. As in many of those districts, the aim is to
prepare students for rising academic standards and the impending
end of ``social promotion,'' the policy of advancing students to
the next grade even if they have not mastered the material in the
previous one.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said the summer classes would be a step toward his
oft-stated goal of extending the school year for all students,
which he cannot do without the approval of the state Legislature.
Proposals in the last two years for such a change have gone nowhere
in the Legislature, in large part because of opposition from the
teachers' union.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory summer school is a growing practice. The Council of
the Great City Schools, a Washington-based coalition of the 53
largest school districts in the country, said that 22 of its
members had such policies. About three-quarters of them adopted the
programs in the last three years, said Michael Casserly, the
executive director of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said that next month schools would begin sending letters to
parents of low-performing students warning them that they may be
held back if they do not go to summer school. The aim is not just
to warn parents but to frighten students into shaping up, said Bill
Casey, the administrator who oversees the summer school program.
``It's almost like tough love,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many details remain to be worked out, including the precise
criteria that would lead to summer school and promotion to the next
grade. But school officials said Tuesday that placement would be
based mainly on students' performance on this spring's citywide
reading and math exams (not the statewide reading tests given last
month), as well as course work and the recommendations of teachers
and principals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For now, the officials said, mandatory summer school would be
reserved for the very lowest-performing students, and the summer
classes would be more rigorous than those now offered.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education has set aside about $70 million for the
summer programs, about the same as last year for voluntary summer
school, but children who are required to go will be given priority.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 of New York's 1.1 million public school students
now take summer programs, which have been growing in popularity.
But since the early 1980s, when a mandatory program started by
Chancellor Frank J. Macchiarola was gradually abandoned, summer
classes have been almost entirely voluntary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
