<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PIRRO-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INDICTS HUSBAND OF DISTRICT ATTORNEY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Albert J. Pirro, an influential real estate
lawyer and the husband of Westchester County District Attorney
Jeanine Pirro, was indicted Tuesday on federal charges of hiding
more than $1 million in income by improperly deducting home
furnishings, baby-sitters, family vacations and luxurious cars _
including his wife's Mercedes-Benz _ as business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro, 51, had been the subject of earlier federal
investigations, but the disclosure in the 66-count tax fraud
indictment that several of the improper deductions benefited his
wife raises questions about her political future.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pirro, 47, had been mentioned as a possible candidate for
the U.S. Senate, a prospect that has had the blessing of top
Republicans in the state, including Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, the Pirros appeared side by side in his law
office and, in brief statements, angrily told a news conference
that they were confident that he would be found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an invasive and hostile process for my husband
and for my family,'' an anxious Mrs. Pirro said, placed in the
unusual role of championing a criminal defendant. ``I am convinced
of my husband's innocence and confident that he will be
exonerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Bracken, a personal spokesman for Mrs. Pirro, appeared
to make a point later of putting a firm wall of separation between
the district attorney and her husband, saying Mrs. Pirro ``was not
involved in the professional and business activities of Pirro and
she had no personal knowledge of the matters under investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the indictment announced by U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White,
detailed many benefits to the Pirro family, including limousine
services, clothes, artwork and the salary for a domestic servant.
And it seemed to suggest that Mrs. Pirro did little to question how
her husband was managing the family's finances.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said that from 1988 through 1997 Pirro routinely
declared lavish personal purchases as the expenses of his law firm,
real estate firm or other closely held companies. The salary of his
family's domestic servant was paid for by a Pirro firm, while a
$3,700 awning for the family's marble-clad Italianate mansion in
Harrison, N.Y., was assigned to another Pirro firm.
</P>
<P>
   Other family expenses assigned to his business or not declared
on his joint personal tax returns included: a $123,000 Ferrari
sports car; a leased Mercedes-Benz for his mother-in-law; and
$10,000 worth of furnishings for a vacation home in West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said that Pirro even charged to his law practice
the legal bills for a paternity suit in which Pirro was named by an
Indiana woman as the father of her 15-year-old girl. DNA tests last
year subsequently confirmed his paternity.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on all charges, Pirro faces a maximum of five years
in jail on a conspiracy count, five years in jail on each of four
tax evasion counts, and three years in jail on each of 28 false tax
return counts.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro's tax returns were prepared by his brother, Anthony G.
Pirro, 43, an accountant who was indicted on the same tax fraud
charges and was also charged with witness tampering and accused of
trying to manipulate the grand jury testimony of an unidentified
vendor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
