<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BARON-LADN     02-23 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA POINT GUARD PONDERS JUMP TO NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From Pac-10 standings to NCAA Tournament seedings,
UCLA will have plenty at stake Saturday when it plays
Washington. &UR;  &LR; But looming over the proceedings like a raised gavel _
with UCLA's future underneath _ is a simple question with a
complicated answer:
</P>
<P>
   Is it Baron Davis' last home game?
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a sophomore, is considering a jump to the NBA, and he's
playing like someone with a higher calling than Syracuse,
Washington or the NCAA Tournament. He has averaged 22.8 points in
his past five games and has directed the Bruins with an unwavering
determination. Next month, he'll become UCLA's latest All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis and his sister, Lissa Hodoh, insist they've made
no decision _ ``We've thought about it, but we haven't talked about
it,'' Hodoh said _ NBA executives have no doubt about Davis' plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was done a long time ago,'' said a Western Conference
personnel director who requested anonymity. ``There are 29 teams in
the league assuming he's coming out. He's in everyone's draft
projections.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's high in those projections _ perhaps a top-five pick,
certainly a top-10 selection.
</P>
<P>
   According to several NBA talent evaluators, Davis will be the
second guard taken behind Maryland junior Steve Francis and ahead
of the nation's best seniors, Utah's Andre Miller and Arizona's
Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   NBA scouts love Davis' athleticism and his size. He's nearly
6-foot-3, he weighs 205 pounds, and he's only 19. In addition,
Davis has regained the strength and flexibility in his surgically
repaired left knee, and he has developed a consistent jumper. The
NBA sees a point guard who can both run a team and create his own
offense _ a mix from which all-stars are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The substantive questions that existed after his freshman year
_ his knee and his ability to shoot the ball _ have been erased,''
said Mark Warkentien, the Portland Trail Blazers' assistant general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are aware of Davis' potential _ pending? _ departure
and have scanned L.A. high schools for senior guards. They
recruited Compton's Tito Maddox until his poor academic standing
intervened, and they are watching Verbum Dei's Marlon Parmer
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're monitoring the progress of several players,'' UCLA coach
Steve Lavin said. ``But the staff believes Baron's coming back. In
all of our conversations, he has worked under the presumption that
he'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis will discuss his future with Hodoh and his grandmother,
Lela Nicholson, after the season. Several factors figure to
dominate the discussions:
</P>
<P>
   __ Will he risk another college season on his reconstructed
knee? One bad landing could jeopardize his future and cost him
millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury has definitely changed my thinking and I'm sure it
has changed his,'' Hodoh said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Is Davis emotionally ready to leave his friends behind and
treat basketball as a business? There are no Earl Watsons to laugh
and cry with in the NBA, which has 82-game seasons, trades and
grueling road trips. Is he prepared to live in Detroit or New
Jersey with no friends and family in sight?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love college,'' he said. ``I'd be missing out on the best
years of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is about whether I want to pursue my dream,'' he
continued. ``I think about the NBA all the time, watching games on
TV and reading the papers. It's something I think about every day,
that I'm closer to the dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has always had the talent, but when he arrived in the fall
of 1997 _ fresh from the Blazergate controversy and a brilliant
high school career at Santa Monica Crossroads _ his game was
untamed.
</P>
<P>
   He was often out of control, taking bad shots, forcing passes,
and committing fouls. The presence of seniors Toby Bailey, Kris
Johnson and J.R. Henderson stymied his leadership instincts.
</P>
<P>
   But his career took a dramatic turn March 15 when he landed
wrong against Michigan and tore the anterior cruciate ligament in
his right knee. During a nine-month rehabilitation, he fought his
body and his mind _ and tested his physical therapist's patience.
</P>
<P>
   Davis returned Dec. 2 and slowly regained conditioning and
rhythm. He dunked against Loyola Marymount (Dec. 29) and was in
fabulous form against Arizona a few days later. He made
game-winning shots against Oregon and USC, scored 50 points in the
Bay Area, and, aside from a ragged performance against Syracuse,
has shown patience and control: 32 assists and 13 turnovers this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so good it's unbelievable,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said.
``Put him on any team in the Pac-10 and you have a contender. The
difference this year is, he's smarter. It's like he has gained 10
years in age. It's like a guy who has gone from 19 years old to 29
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has been on his best behavior since a postgame outburst at
Washington drew a public reprimand from the Pac-10. He has become
the dominant locker-room voice, challenging teammates after an
18-point loss at Cal. He is usually the last one off the practice
floor, often shooting jumpers alone while his teammates laugh and
play one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Davis has emerged as UCLA's best player and most
demanding leader since Ed O'Bannon carried the Bruins to the 1995
NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came back (from the knee injury), I was just
trying to fit in,'' Davis said. ``I've gradually assumed a
leadership role. I'm trying to be more of a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   His cerebral approach extends to opponents. Davis no longer
watches games, he studies them. He has always been able to recite
lineups, standings and statistics from across the nation. Now, he
examines a player's style and applies it to his own game.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever possible, Davis studies Arizona's Terry, Maryland's
Francis, North Carolina's Ed Cota and Connecticut's Khalid El-Amin.
From Stanford's Art Lee, he has learned patience and timing. From
Utah's Miller, he has learned defense, rebounding and the
importance of all-around play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, for every big game I'd come in real hyped and
emotional,'' Davis said. ``This year, I'm thinking more. I've
become more of a student. I watch these guys to scout them but also
to pick stuff up.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis then described his style as a mix of Francis' athleticism
and Miller's versatility. As his sophomore season concludes _ and
with it, perhaps his UCLA career _ the NBA seems to agree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
