<P>
   NY-HOTEL-BARS (New York) _ New York City is filled with
unappreciated treasures. But in the world of food and drink none
are so neglected as hotel bars. They have been here for ages,
planted like pillars around the city. Many are elegantly decorated,
like miniatures of the grand hotels that engulf them. And perhaps
it is for that reason that New Yorkers seem to overlook them. But
beyond the barrier of the hotel lobbies lie some of the city's most
secluded oases, where you can relax over a well-mixed drink, be
treated like a king or simply be as anonymous as the bars
themselves. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT12,14) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ERITREAN-RESTAURANT (New Haven, Conn.) _ It's been a long time
since a restaurant has surprised me as much as Caffe Adulis, a
charming little place a long block from the Yale campus. I guess
you would call it an ethnic restaurant, because it specializes in
Eritrean food. Both the decor and the food were pleasant surprises.
It made amends for a lot of culinary nightmares I had during my
year as a correspondent in Africa. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT10,11) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHILI (New York) _ Jane and Michael Stern were skeptical.
``Finding great chili in New York is like finding great pastrami in
Des Moines,'' he said warningly. Nonetheless, the Sterns have
agreed to eat chili at three different places to see if any can
equal the ones included in their latest book, ``Chili Nation: The
Ultimate Chili Cookbook With Recipes From Every State in the
Nation'' By Alex Witchel.
</P>
