<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOOLWORTH-RENOVATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPDATING THE TOWER WOOLWORTH BUILT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For rent: one cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   After 85 years under the same ownership, the glistening Gothic
stalagmite known as the Woolworth Building was sold two months ago
for $126.5 million by the Venator Group, formerly the Woolworth
Corp., which is keeping its headquarters in the 54-story tower but
shrinking to four floors from eight.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the new owners _ the Witkoff Group, Rubin Schron and
other investors _ with the challenge of leasing a tower clad in
medieval frosting to tenants obsessed with the latest technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The Woolworth Building, soaring over City Hall Park, is very
much a public icon, the ``cathedral of commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   And the new owners are discovering that a cathedral designed by
Cass Gilbert comes with a lot of extras.
</P>
<P>
   There is a marble-bordered swimming pool, an office stuffed with
gilt-edged relics of Frank W. Woolworth's reign, a subterranean
storeroom called the bone yard, where hundreds of Gothic ornaments
are stockpiled in case they are needed as replacements on the
exterior. There is a boiler room so titanic it once provided steam
to Con Edison.
</P>
<P>
   But under the copper finials and flying buttresses at the
tiara-like spire are plenty of nooks for telecommunications
equipment. And the mechanical shafts, or ``risers,'' running
through the building are large enough to accommodate new wiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genius of Cass Gilbert is that he leaves behind a lot of
room for us to address the needs of the 21st century,'' said George
M. Stone, senior managing director of the Witkoff Group.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, any work on the lobby or the exterior would be subject
to approval by the Landmarks Preservation Commission. The
renovation architects are Beyer Blinder Belle, whose projects
include Grand Central Terminal and Rockefeller Center. Interior
design is by the Switzer Group.
</P>
<P>
   Witkoff plans to spend about $30 million on the electrical,
mechanical and communications systems in the building, as well as a
cleaning of the terra cotta exterior and the marble- and
mosaic-filled lobby.
</P>
<P>
   To insure a sense of continuity, Witkoff has licensed the name
``Woolworth Building'' from Venator. The corporation once occupied
25 floors but pulled back as it changed its name and nature,
closing its five-and-ten stores to concentrate on footwear and
sporting goods.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the space in the 932,000-square-foot building will
become available this year. Among prospective tenants are music and
film companies, advertising agencies and Internet operators, most
them from mid-Manhattan, said Bradley P. Gerla, managing director
of Insignia/ESG, the leasing agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are companies that have never really looked downtown,''
Gerla said. ``I think Woolworth offers that intrigue.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the Woolworth Building was high-tech from the start.
Its lights were switched on by a telegraph signal from President
Woodrow Wilson in the White House on April 24, 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Built without a mortgage, the 792-foot-1-inch skyscraper at 233
Broadway, between Barclay Street and Park Place, was the tallest
building in the world until it was eclipsed in 1929 by 40 Wall
Street and the Chrysler Building.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 cents, visitors could ascend by express elevator to the
54th floor and board a shuttle elevator worthy of a Jules Verne
fantasy _ encased in a cylindrical glass shaft and encircled by a
spiral stairway _ which pierced the gloomy space inside the
pyramidal summit.
</P>
<P>
   At top was an octagonal outdoor deck, 65 feet around, so loftily
isolated from Manhattan's clamor that the loudest noise was the
wind. The deck has been closed almost 50 years and the elevator no
longer works, but both still exist.
</P>
<P>
   So does the 15-by-55-foot basement swimming pool. Although it is
not in use, it could be filled again. ``Nobody's going to come here
because there's a pool,'' Stone said. ``But if they do come, it's
an amenity they won't get at One Chase Manhattan Plaza or the World
Trade Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Incongruously set in Venator's sleekly modern 24th-floor suite
is Frank Woolworth's office, paneled in green marble, now a lounge
for company executives. It was copied from Napoleon's palace at
Compiegne and was originally adorned with a portrait of the
emperor, later replaced by one of Woolworth himself.
</P>
<P>
   The portraits are in storage, as is Woolworth's claw-footed
chair and his desk, a massive battleship of mahogany, leather and
bronze with a hidden four-button console: ``Sten,'' ``Sec,''
``Elev'' and ``Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolworth's presence is inescapable _ in the W's that ornament
the elevator grilles and doorknob plates and in the gargoyle
greeting visitors to the lobby, a nickel clutched in its hand. As
if the founder were still alive, Ernest A. Conrad of Landmark
Facilities Group, the building systems engineers, refers to him
simply as ``F.W.'' And everyone understands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
