<SLUG> BC-NY-BEATING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICER IS CONVICTED IN RACIALLY TINGED BEATING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOHN T. MCQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ A Suffolk County jury convicted a former New
York City police officer Tuesday of aiding in the bludgeoning of a
young Long Island man in a racially tinged brawl outside a
Westhampton Beach nightclub three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Constantine Chronis, 37, of Hicksville, appeared
stunned as the jury forewoman announced that he had been found
guilty of assault with depraved indifference, official misconduct
and menacing.
</P>
<P>
   The case stemmed from the near-fatal beating of Shane Daniels,
23, of Riverhead, during a fight outside the Marakesh nightclub
early on the morning of May 26, 1996. The jury found Chronis not
guilty of intentional assault.
</P>
<P>
   Chronis had been free on a $200,000 bond that was secured, in
part, by property owned by his relatives. But Judge Joel L.
Lefkowitz increased the bond to $250,000 in cash after the
conviction and ordered that Chronis be taken to jail to await
sentencing on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   The judge granted a motion by a defense lawyer that Chronis be
held in protective custody at the jail. Chronis faces a sentence of
7{ to 15 years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution said Chronis, a former narcotics detective,
pulled his service revolver to hold back a group of Daniels'
friends while a co-defendant in the case, Austin Offen, beat
Daniels as he shouted racial slurs and epithets. Daniels is black
and Chronis and Offen are white. About three months after the
incident, in August 1996, Chronis resigned from the Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Offen, 28, of Queens, pleaded guilty on Jan. 6 to assaulting
Daniels with a metal bar used for locking automobile steering
wheels. He was sentenced Feb. 4 to 10 years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels was in the courtroom for Tuesday's verdict, and he told
reporters afterward that he was relieved that the nearly three-year
ordeal had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over, but it's taken a heavy toll on everyone,''
he said as he left the courtroom with his fiancee, Jen Costa, and
their 20-month-old son, Desmond.
</P>
<P>
   Chronis' brother, Peter, and mother, Helen Chronis, left without
commenting. Like the Daniels family, they had been in court for
much of the seven-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   When Daniels testified as the final prosecution witness last
week, he told the jury that he had no memory of the attack but that
his injuries would be with him the rest of his life. As a result of
the beating, he said, he had a permanent tube embedded under his
skin to drain fluid from his brain, and his peripheral vision was
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Trial evidence showed that Daniels' blood splattered on the
defendant's shoes, and the prosecutor, Stephen L. O'Brien, said the
blood proved that Chronis was nearby when Daniels was beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Chronis' lawyer, Stephen A. Grossman, argued that many of the
people who saw the brawl could have had traces of blood on their
shoes. He denied that Chronis had taken part in the beating. He
said that Chronis was himself a victim during the brawl, that he
had been cut over the right eye and that he was acting in
self-defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
