<HEADLINE>
HE WON'T DANCE, DON'T ASK HIM 
NO TEARS IN HIS BEER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY with C.J. SATTERWHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene: The New York State Theater at Lincoln Center in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The event: A benefit for the School of American Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   The players: Dancers and reluctant dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Robinson, a partner in Highland Asset Management, was
sitting on the sidelines on Monday night when the dancing began.
Asked if he was going to join in, he said, ``Not until I go back to
Miss Quimby's Dance School in New Canaan.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hadn't paid close attention to Miss Quimby when he
was her student. But his wife, Elizabeth Stribling, the real estate
executive, said, ``He's a great dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson suggested that she had metal caps on her dancing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Another husband proved to be a great dancer. Peter Martins, the
chairman of faculty at the School of American Ballet (where his son
was a student) and the ballet master in chief of the New York City
Ballet, danced a few graceful rounds with his wife, ballerina Darci
Kistler, who was wearing high-heeled mules. Martins said she could
dance in those because ``she's a pro.''
</P>
<P>
   To the appreciation of several other women, Martins spread the
talent around. One of his partners, Coco Kopelman, once a student
at the ballet school and a member of its board, said: ``It was
amazing. He made me feel like I weigh 10 pounds.'' (She doesn't
weigh much more than that anyway).
</P>
<P>
   Epilogue: Michael Bloomberg, the financial information
publisher, received the corporate leadership award. The dinner
raised $600,000.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No Tears In His Beer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like the booziest of bar fantasies: write 50 words
about one of your favorite things _ beer _ to win the deed to
another of your favorite things _ a pub _ in one of your favorite
places on earth to drink beer in a pub _ Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   It probably helps if your name is something like Trevor
O'Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, O'Driscoll, now 23, won the contest that is kind of
like Lotto for Irish bar patrons in the United States: the Guinness
``Win Your Own Pub in Ireland'' contest, sponsored by the beer
maker, which each year buys a pub that is up for sale somewhere in
Ireland and then gives it to the contestant who writes the best
essay about why it would be nice to own such a pub.
</P>
<P>
   (The 1999 contest is accepting entries until March 31. The entry
forms are usually available at _ you guessed it _ places where
Guinness is sold.)
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the other winners over the last five years who
decided to sell their prize _ the pubs are generally worth several
hundred thousand dollars _ O'Driscoll, a legal assistant at the law
firm of Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, left his job last
summer to go run his.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction from everybody I knew was like, `Of course that's
what he's going to do,''' said O'Driscoll, who grew up in
Philadelphia and graduated from Brown University. ``I knew I didn't
want to go to law school.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of O'Driscoll's friends dropped what they were doing _
graduate school and a consulting job _ to join him.
</P>
<P>
   And they have made their new home above Finucane's (pronounced
Fih-NU-kins), the cozy pub O'Driscoll won in Listowel, a tiny
village in County Kerry near the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, there was plenty of competition for drinkers
in Listowel: it has 3,000 people and 45 pubs. But O'Driscoll says
he is doing fine. The townspeople like him, and he learned a lot
about running a pub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been on the other side plenty of times, but I never been
behind the bar,'' he said by phone from Listowel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added: ``At the end of the day, it's really not rocket
science. You just have to make sure you have enough beer, and then
you sell the beer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
