<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KAZAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN OSCAR PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Feb. 24:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most striking thing about the decision to give Elia
Kazan an honorary Academy Award at this year's ceremony is the fact
that it was made unanimously. The 39-member board of the Motion
Picture Academy of Arts and Sciences approved the choice of Kazan
``with enthusiasm,'' according to one board member, and without
debate. If so, it is the first time Kazan has failed to provoke
debate since early 1952, when he twice appeared before the House
Un-American Activities Committee, informed against eight friends,
and took out an ad in The Times to explain, with rather incomplete
logic, the reasons for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the news of Kazan's upcoming Oscar, a subdued
protest _ the omission of applause _ has been organized by former
blacklisted writers and their families and friends. The protest is
certainly merited, but so is the award, for Kazan's truly
distinguished work as the director of films like ``A Streetcar
Named Desire'' and ``On the Waterfront.''
</P>
<P>
   The Academy has done what it has not always been able to do _
distinguish clearly between the merit of an artist's work and the
merit of his behavior or convictions. Meanwhile, the protesters
will make the necessary if implicit point that Kazan remains
accountable for a decision he made not as a film maker but as a
human being.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
