<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JAIL-BEATING-380&AMP;A     02-23 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-BEATING-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN TESTIFIES HE WAS BEATEN BY A TOP OFFICIAL IN CORRECTION
OFFICERS' UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mentally retarded man testified Tuesday that guards
at the Nassau County Jail held him while a top official of the
correction officers' union repeatedly beat his head and body with a
pot or a pan in a 1993 attack which left him with broken ribs and
spinal fractures.
</P>
<P>
   The former inmate, Thomas F. Donovan Jr., 39, is suing the union
leader, Salvatore Gemelli, the county and its jail on charges of
violating his civil rights, and is seeking $100 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying in Federal District Court in Brooklyn, Donovan said
that Gemelli assaulted him twice shortly after he arrived at the
jail _ once from behind a desk, with a pot or pan apparently
borrowed from a pantry used by guards, and again a short time later
in a room where inmates are given orange jump suits to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, who has an IQ of 58 and the emotions of a third grader,
appeared nervous as he took the stand, misspelling his first name
as he was sworn in. But he spoke cogently over three hours of
testimony about the beatings and their aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Though he contradicted himself about some details, he recalled
the precise days and dates of many key events in the criminal
investigation of his allegations, which did not lead to a
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan had been charged with child sexual abuse; he later
pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony, before Judge Allyne R. Ross, came amid a widening
federal investigation into possible civil rights violations at the
Nassau jail, where many current and former inmates have described
beatings as an everyday occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry began after the Jan. 13 death of Thomas Pizzuto, 38,
whose family says he was beaten by guards and then left untreated
for days. His death, which was ruled a homicide, is being
investigated by the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the importance with which Donovan's case is being
viewed, the U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of New York,
Zachary W. Carter, listened to much of Donovan's testimony Tuesday
morning from a bench in the rear of the courtroom. Carter, whose
jurisdiction includes Long Island, declined to comment as he left.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are also interviewing witnesses in the
Donovan trial, according to lawyers close to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned Tuesday by his lawyer, Stephen Civardi, Donovan
testified that after the first attack by Gemelli, he was assaulted
again by him and other guards a short time later in the jail's
clothing room. ``The beating started all over again,'' he said.
``They punched me. They kicked me. I fell to the floor. They held
my arms down. I screamed and cried. Then the beating stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said that later that day, he told no one in the jail
that guards had attacked him, and no one asked where he got his
bruises _ not even a jail house doctor who drew blood and took his
blood pressure in a routine examination.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when another doctor had him remove his shirt,
revealing welts as large as 10 inches across, Donovan said he told
the doctor he had fallen at home.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan testified that he believed the correction officers would
retaliate if he told the truth to anyone while in jail. ``I was
scared for my life _ that they were going to kill me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by Gemelli's lawyer, Chris P. Termini,
Donovan admitted giving another conflicting explanation of his
injuries when he was interviewed more than a week later by officers
in Garden City. He told the officers that he had been beaten by
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   His conversation with the officers, during which neither his
parents nor his lawyer was present, was secretly recorded. The tape
is expected to be played later in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you scared of them?'' Termini asked, referring to the
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Donovan replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you surprised to learn that there was a tape recording of
that conversation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Civardi, Donovan believed at the time that he was
about to be sent back to the Nassau jail, on the original charge of
child sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Termini asserted that Donovan was actually beaten by inmates
while walking up a staircase unsupervised by guards. But Donovan
denied that.
</P>
<P>
   Gemelli, a past president of the correction officers' union who
is now its vice president, is expected to testify Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-23-99 2352EST &QL; 
