<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-VENTURE-CAPITALISTS-RESEND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITIES JUMP INTO THE VENTURE GAME  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Boston)   (RESENDING from Feb. 19 for those needing)  
  
 (This 450-word ``separate buy'' article is from TECHNOLOGY REVIEW
magazine.  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444. Ms.
Weydert's e-mail address is:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com.)  
  
 (In Mexico, Central America and South America, contact OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970, or fax her at 310-798-7338.
Ms. Vasquez's e-mail address is: vasquez(at)nytimes.com.)  
  
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to clipping rights
to TECHNOLOGY REVIEW, which is published by the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology eight times a year. Clipping rights allow
you to reprint any of the magazine's articles, which are written by
experts on issues ranging from the environment to the military,
computers to biotechnology, industrial management to the arts.)  
  
 By ANTONIO REGALADO  
 c.1999 Technology Review magazine  
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a symposium at the Boston University (BU) Photonics Center
last fall, the attendees broke for coffee as usual. But something
was amiss.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of professors munching cookies and chatting about the
latest research, men in suits stood facing blank walls, whispering
into cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   They are high-powered investors, but they're not from Silicon
Valley _ they're from the research center's ninth floor.
</P>
<P>
   Better toss out the old stereotypes about academia and get with
the latest rage _ ivory tower goes venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding to spin off more technologies, boost local economies,
and just plain make money, many research institutions and
universities are creating their own venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital has traditionally been the domain of private,
deep-pocketed investors hoping to earn a windfall, often by picking
off promising university research. Most of the action has centered
around big-name schools, such as MIT and Stanford University,
located near East Coast and West Coast hubs of venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   But now an increasing number of universities around the country
want their piece of the pie _ and are willing to do what it takes
to get it.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example is BU's Photonics Venture Partners. The fund
is privately managed, but the university is both an investor and a
manager _ one of the firm's three generals partners is Donald
Fraser, also the Photonics Center's director.
</P>
<P>
   Working cheek-by-jowl with BU researchers studying blue lasers
and quantum communication, the venture capitalists plan to leverage
the center's technical acumen to invest in the rapidly growing
field of photonics.
</P>
<P>
   No two of the university funds turned up by a ``Technology
Review'' survey are exactly alike. Some are wholly-owned
subsidiaries, others are independent firms awarded preferential
rights to an institution's technology.
</P>
<P>
   They also have varying aims. At BU, the strategy is to invest in
any photonics company likely to return a profit.
</P>
<P>
   At Vanderbilt University, on the other hand, administrators have
christened a $10 million fund that will invest in companies built
around the school's technology.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Steranka, Vanderbilt's director of technology licensing,
says the main reason for the do-it-yourself funds ``is that many
promising university inventions are simply too early-stage and too
risky to interest mainstream venture capitalists.''
</P>
<P>
   But based on a study of schools that have previously tried
venture funds, Josh Lerner, a professor at Harvard Business School,
thinks university administrators often have unrealistic
expectations for financial success.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner thinks they also underestimate the challenge of combining
the quick-to-move venture culture with rule-bound academia. ``It's
very hard to marry these organizational forms,'' says Lerner. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _____________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this interesting 450-word TECHNOLOGY REVIEW article, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Ms. Weydert's e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (In Mexico, Central America, South America, contact OLIVIA VASQUEZ
in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970, or fax her at 310-798-7338. Ms.
Vasquez's e-mail address is: vasquez(at)nytimes.com. Se Habla
Espanol.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
