<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-23 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DJ-CANTRELL-NYT &LR;      02-23 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DJ-CANTRELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEJAY'S MISSION: BRING COUNTRY TO THE CITY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)  (nk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a woman whose career _ at least sort of _ is
talking, Laura Cantrell apologizes a lot when she's doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' she said last Saturday afternoon, over a bowl of
beans, ``you can totally just cut me off anytime you want.'' And
later: ``Well this is turning out to be a really long story.'' And
later: ``Am I droning on or what?''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is there are thousands of radio listeners in the New
York area who plan their Saturdays around listening to Ms. Cantrell
do just that (she actually drones very little) and hearing her play
the beaten-up records she carries in the back of her beaten-up
Crown Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   She has the sort of easy Tennessee accent that seems to keep
your coffee warm. Her decidedly uncatchy signature line _ ``Well,
there you have it, folks'' _ has become a lazy weekend mantra for
her fans. And over the last six years, her noon-to-3-p.m. show,
``The Radio Thrift Shop'' on WFMU, the famously eclectic New Jersey
radio station, has made her one of the city's best-known deejays
among music lovers with a country-and-western bent.
</P>
<P>
   After a show last Saturday, Ms. Cantrell, 31, packed up her
records and repaired to the Flamingo diner just down the street
from WFMU in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   There, she explained exactly how it was that a daughter of two
successful Nashville lawyers _ her father sits on the Tennessee
state Court of Appeals _ ended up with an English degree from
Columbia University and parlayed it into a professional performance
life that has never earned her a dime. (The deejays on WFMU, 91.1
FM, are all volunteers. Ms. Cantrell pays the bills by working as
an administrative assistant at a Wall Street brokerage.)
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are very proud of me being up here and that I love
what I do,'' she said. ``But they're still sort of scratching their
heads, like, `What does she do in New York again?'''
</P>
<P>
   She described herself as a ``closet country fan'' while growing
up. But she really fell in love with it when she was 17 and found a
summer job as a tour guide at the Country Music Hall of Fame.
Waiting to hand out tickets, she stood near a jukebox that oozed
history: honky-tonk stars like Webb Pierce and Lefty Frizzell, and
female stars she had never really listened to before, like Kitty
Wells and Loretta Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cantrell moved to New York in 1985, and found her way to
Columbia's campus station, WKCR, 89.9 FM, where she revived a
country show called, appropriately enough, ``The Tennessee
Border.'' During four years at Columbia, it felt almost as if she
were attending two schools, she said. ``Here I was toting around
the most giant Riverside Shakespeare ever and I had two Hank
Williams records in my bag.''
</P>
<P>
   But after college came the quandary: how to do what she loved
and somehow get paid. She worked briefly (``I hung on until the
12th month just so I could say I was there a year'') at the ABC
Radio Network, cracking the whip at affiliate stations to make sure
they played commercials at the right times. Then she tried out
unsuccessfully for a job with Garrison Keillor when he broadcast
from New York in the early 1990s. Without a hint of bitterness, she
says now: ``I think I really was hung up on the idea: `Hey,
shouldn't I get paid for doing this?'
</P>
<P>
   ``When you eventually abandon that idea,'' she adds, laughing,
``it's very liberating.''
</P>
<P>
   At WFMU, she volunteered for more than a year before she got her
own show, and she continues to spend most of her free time pitching
in, as do all the deejays. ``I clean the bathrooms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Two years ago, she also found time to get married. Her husband,
Jeremy Tepper, is one of New York's foremost jukebox experts and
runs a small record label based in Brooklyn. They live in
Williamsburg.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cantrell's rambling, relaxed show is eclectic by any
commercial radio standards. Last Saturday the playlist ranged from
Les Paul to Spade Cooley to Duke Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   But at WFMU, the country's longest-running free-form station,
one with shows named ``Vortex of Chaos'' and ``Inflatable Squirrel
Carcass,'' Ms. Cantrell could be considered almost prim.
</P>
<P>
   She is well aware that many New Yorkers probably see country
music fans as pretty close to the parody in the movie ``The Blues
Brothers.'' (Dan Aykroyd: ``What kind of music do you usually have
here?'' Bartender: ``Oh, we got both kinds. We got country, and
western.'')
</P>
<P>
   And so she has made it her mission to unearth the strange but
numerous connections between country and other genres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live for things like saying, `OK, here was where Jimmie
Rodgers and Louis Armstrong were playing on the same record,''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She also tries to show New Yorkers that early country music
caught on just as easily in tenements as in shotgun shacks.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1930s and 40s, in fact, there were several popular
country music radio shows in the New York area. One old California
vaudevillian, Zeke Manners, whom Ms. Cantrell still interviews on
air from time to time, had a long-running country-folk music show
in the city beginning in the 1930s and also had a popular quartet
here called Pappy, Zeke, Ezra and Elton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was this totally weird hillbilly thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And then added before forging ahead into yet more hillbilly
weirdness, ``Oh geez, I know I'm really going on, but ... ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
